<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE4-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEW FROM THE NOSEBLEED SECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Way up in the nether regions of Staples Center,
where the air is thinner and the beer is just as expensive, the
fans know they're in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie Mendoza from North Hollywood sits at the top row of
section 330, located in a dark corner way above the Los Angeles
Lakers bench and excitedly stands, jumps and bangs her noisemakers
as the Pacers attempt free throws, even though she's too high and
way out of the camera's eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care,'' she said. ``I think they can hear me. Don't
you think so?''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza, 28, is here with her boyfriend, John Urteaga of Los
Angeles. Urteaga bought the pair of $37 tickets from a friend of
his because the friend had to work. The two also attended Game 2
and sat in almost as bad seats across the way in the upper reaches
of section 304.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is complaining, of course. The beer tastes great, people
nearby let them use their binoculars, and they're feeling pretty
festive, Urteaga in his ``Los Angeles Lakers Since 1960'' shirt and
Mendoza in her Kobe Bryant home jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see pretty good,' Urteaga said. ``The best crowd's
always up here. The rich people are mellow. We're glad to see the
Lakers, and we can't afford the expensive tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza can't either, but that doesn't diminish her enthusiasm.
She visited friends in Hawaii while the Lakers played in
Indianapolis and said she was the only one rooting for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody else was for the underdog,'' she said, ``so before I
came tonight, I called them. How can you beat this?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, she could. She was at the Forum that June night in
1988 when the Lakers last won an NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magic Johnson,'' she gushed. ``He was really hot, the way he
played.''
</P>
<P>
   On that night, she sat in a loge-level seat, courtesy of her
father's company. On Monday night, she sat far higher and felt just
as much elation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to be here, come on!'' she screamed above the noise.
``Even if I was outside, I'd be cheering the same way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
