<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREST STILL MUGGY AFTER 12 LONG YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - A dozen years ago this month, on a hot, humid day, they
buried Officer Ken Collings.
</P>
<P>
   I stood with a somber crowd of uniformed cops outside SS. Simon
and Jude Roman Catholic Church and watched the first vehicles of
the funeral motorcade appear to the south on 27th Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The procession of cars and motorcycles passed through heat waves
rising from the pavement as if they were rolling through a
waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   It was less than a week since Collings had been shot during a
robbery at a Valley National Bank branch on - McDowell Road. One of
the two men responsible was still on the loose.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the stickup I talked to a young guy named Jeff
Haines, who was driving on McDowell when the robbers made their
getaway. Haines saw what was happening and, without thinking,
rammed his truck into their car. It didn't stop them.
</P>
<P>
   Other civilians kept track of the suspects, though, helping
police corner one of them at the Syl-Mar Apartments on Camelback
Road.
</P>
<P>
   There was a shootout, leaving one robber, Ismael Conde, wounded
and captured. He later was convicted and sentenced to almost three
centuries in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The other suspect, Rudy Romero, got away, supposedly headed for
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   For the officers who stood outside the church as Collings'
casket was slowly unloaded, the thought of Romero running free was
as unavoidable and as uncomfortable as the heat.
</P>
<P>
   But we're all supposed to feel better, now.
</P>
<P>
   About a week ago, Romero was caught and wounded during a
shootout in southern Mexico. For years, law enforcement officials
have had a pretty good idea where Romero was hiding out. They've
had trouble getting cooperation from Mexican authorities, though.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government won't extradite suspects in cases that
could draw a death sentence, like this one. Besides that, fugitives
have been known to pay off Mexican law enforcement officers to
avoid arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly, Romero visited Phoenix more than once in the 12
years since the murder. But now he's caught, and since Arizona
prosecutors promised not to seek the death penalty, he's expected
to be extradited.
</P>
<P>
   And we're supposed to feel better. Relieved.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Romero finally will face American justice, after
having enjoyed 12 years of freedom. Twelve years to go where he
wanted and do what he wanted. Twelve years of everyday living.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if we're lucky, Arizona taxpayers will get to pay for
Romero's room and board for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Do you feel better?
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but look at it from Romero's perspective. If you
were in his shoes, would you rather spend the rest of your life in
a hellhole of a Mexican prison, or in one of Arizona's?
</P>
<P>
   A few days after Collings was shot I ran into a nephew of his,
Gary Howes, at the apartment complex where Conde was wounded. The
police fired round after round at the guy.
</P>
<P>
   `And the bastard lived, can you believe that?` Howes said. `He
lived after all those shots, and Kenny . . . Kenny gets it with
one. . . . It isn't right. It isn't right.`
</P>
<P>
   No, I told Collings' nephew, it isn't right. It wasn't then.
It's not now. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at &QL; Ed.Montini(at)Arizona &QL; Republic.com or (602)
444-8978. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
