<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SUSPENSION APPEALS SET FOR WEDNESDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In April, the Los Angeles Dodgers began the season
with a three-city road trip that was paramount to a strong start to
ease nerves.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, the Dodgers went on a four-city, 12-game road
trip that wouldn't make their season, but could've possibly
destroyed it.
</P>
<P>
   Hindsight being what is, the importance placed on those road
trips is laughable when measured against what begins today. And it
has nothing to do with playing three games against the Houston
Astros and nothing about the St. Louis Cardinals. Even the possible
return of catcher Todd Hundley is lost.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the shape of a season could be decided in five hours
Wednesday afternoon in a conference room when most of the 16
suspended Dodgers and officials from the players association and
Major League Baseball meet in a mass appeals hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Beeston, chief operating officer of the commissioner's
office, will listen to arguments decrying the severe sanctions
stemming from a May 16 altercation involving many of the Dodgers
and the fans at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have survived injuries to Kevin Brown, Adrian
Beltre, Kevin Elster, who was at the time their starting shortstop
but is now in a platoon, and Hundley. They made it through a month
without closer Jeff Shaw recording a save, mostly because he had a
``dead arm'' and lost velocity on his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Though one can never say it would be the final hurdle for this
organization during Fox's tenure, the next very, very large step
has come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we weathered the storm,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``We have one little other thing in Houston, but
things are setting up pretty good for the second half (of the
season).''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers officials quietly believe a good number of the players'
suspensions, totaling 60 games with fines adding up to $57,000,
will either be wiped out or reduced. But the focal point of the
hearing will be Dodgers catcher Chad Kreuter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of it is there are many facts that aren't in
evidence that we believe were not considered prior to the ruling,''
said Scott Boras, Kreuter's agent. ``That's really what this case
is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter was hit the heaviest among the players, suspended eight
games and fined $5,000. And it's his case that could have a
trickle-down effect. Dodgers players have been instructed not to
talk about the incident, and they've held true to that.
</P>
<P>
   Boras said Kreuter went into the stands only after he was struck
in the back of the head and had his hat stolen by Josh Pulliam, who
works for a subsidiary of the Tribune Company, which owns the
Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter was on his way out of the stands when he was attacked by
other fans, Boras said. An integral part of Kreuter's case is that
he was provoked into putting his hands around the neck of another
fan, Ronald Camacho, and Boras has a series of still-frame photos
that he says proves his case. It will also be brought up that
Camacho, who has filed a civil suit against the Dodgers, Cubs and
each player, has been arrested at least nine times since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The photos, in succession, show Camacho walking toward Kreuter
and spitting on the Dodgers' backup catcher. The argument is that
was provocation for Kreuter.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the commissioner's office, including Sandy
Alderson, executive vice president of baseball operations, and
Frank Robinson, vice president of on-field operations and the man
who levied the suspensions, said players should never go into the
stands, no matter the reason.
</P>
<P>
   Boras, and the players association, is also expected to contest
the severity of the suspensions, and point out that former Dodger
Reggie Smith was suspended five games and fined $5,000 when he went
into the stands after a fan in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the hearings will be Carlos Perez (suspended five
games), F.P. Santangelo (five), Gary Sheffield (five), Mike Fetters
(four), Terry Adams (three), Geronimo Berroa (three), Darren
Dreifort (three), Shawn Green (three), Hundley (three), Eric Karros
(three), Onan Masaoka (three), Antonio Osuna (two) and Chan Ho Park
(three). Alan Mills (three) was traded to Baltimore but is still
appealing the suspension and Eric Gagne (three) was sent to the
minors, though his case will also be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers and players association believes a number of players
with three-game suspensions will have their time dropped or cut
because some suspensions were based solely on a player stepping
over the wall into the stands and turning right back around and
returning to the field.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the case of serving the suspensions. In the
original ruling, because of the number of suspensions, Robinson set
forth the dates on which each player was to begin serving his
suspension. The Dodgers don't agree with that tack, saying that's
managing the team and questioning why Major League Baseball should
decide which player sits against which team.
</P>
<P>
   However, a number of Dodgers officials believe baseball will
still dictate when players serve suspensions if the sanctions
remain.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the three suspended coaches - Glenn Hoffman, Rick Dempsey
and John Shelby - and bullpen catcher Travis Barbary are scheduled
to have their cases heard today. The coaches were each suspended
eight games and Barbary was suspended five games. Each were fined
$5,000. They are being represented by the Dodgers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
