r a BC-KC-TIFF-KAN &LR;      06-20 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-TIFF-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO SHARE BOND THAT ENDS WITH LOVE, TEARS AND MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ He was the biker who calmed her tears. She
was the little girl who made him cry.
</P>
<P>
   What a love story they told.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Hutchison found Tiffany at a hospital. She had suffered
severe brain damage during birth and had cerebral palsy. She
couldn't see or hear. Doctors said she would soon die. Nobody
wanted her.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, a 6-foot-2-inch Harley rider with a ponytail and
tattoos, took her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always be here for you,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   He kept the promise more than 15 years. Tiffany died Monday at
her home in Independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss her already,'' Hutchison said a few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   He stood on the front porch, out of the light rain that fell in
the midafternoon. Hospice workers carried out medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she wanted to hang on through Father's Day,'' he said
in a breaking voice. ``She gave me a watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The gift had been purchased by Hutchison's wife.
</P>
<P>
   Some readers of The Kansas City Star will remember their story.
Hutchison was working as a paramedic that September day in 1984
when Tiffany was born at Truman Medical Center. Her mother, who was
mentally disabled, didn't even know she was pregnant. She gave
birth while sitting in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   The umbilical cord was wrapped around the infant's neck,
shutting off oxygen to her brain.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, who had taken a patient to the hospital, heard about
the baby and went to see her. Her spine was severely curved. Her
hips and shoulders were deformed.
</P>
<P>
   He thought she was beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   A nurse told him the baby was headed to an institution where she
probably would soon die.
</P>
<P>
   After talking with his wife and son, Hutchison took Tiffany
home. She survived that winter and the one after that. Hutchison
and his wife adopted her in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The couple has since divorced, with him prevailing in a custody
fight for Tiffany. Then in 1993, Hutchison's son, Chad, was killed
in a car wreck.
</P>
<P>
   He and Tiffany were on their own. He tended her every need.
</P>
<P>
   A worker with the Missouri Division of Family Services praised
his dedication to Tiffany. His touch often was the only thing that
calmed her.
</P>
<P>
   He took her on dates, letting women know up front they came as a
package.
</P>
<P>
   But he always knew he could lose her. Doctors told him that
Tiffany's heart was working too hard and could give out any time.
</P>
<P>
   So every morning when he left for his job installing lights and
ceiling fans, he kissed her as if the day would be her last.
</P>
<P>
   He promised her that as long as she fought, he would fight for
her.
</P>
<P>
   And he told her that when she got too tired to fight, he would
understand.
</P>
<P>
   That time came Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to let Tiffany go was made last week after doctors
said her body was shutting down and rejecting treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Family and friends gathered at the home. Hutchison knew Sunday
night the time was near.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her little heart just kept getting weaker and weaker and it
finally stopped,'' he said. ``She was a fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany also was a teacher. Just ask those who knew her best.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison has lived a half-century and ridden his bike all over
the country, but says Tiffany taught him about life, love and
family.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Eilene, whom he married last fall, said she was a
little scared of the responsibility of Tiffany's medical care when
she began dating Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she is the sweetest thing in the world, and she taught me
how little we all really need to live and be happy,'' Eilene said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Tiffany died, Hutchison leaned over and kissed her
cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll hurt no more, baby,'' he whispered.
</P>
<P>
   Later, out on the porch, he looked back on 15 years with the
little girl he found by accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wondered whether two parents couldn't have done it
better. But then she'd smile, and I knew nobody could love her more
than me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
