<HEADER>
A9161 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-FOREIGN-POLICY-     06-20 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-FOREIGN-POLICY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT SLAPS DOWN MASSACHUSETTS' BURMA ACT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court dealt a blow Monday to state and
city governments' efforts to levy sanctions against Burma.
</P>
<P>
   The court, in a unanimous decision, struck down a 1996
Massachusetts law barring state agencies, under most circumstances,
from contracting with companies with financial ties to the country
whose military regime has renamed it Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that Massachusetts could not use its economic
muscle to keep companies from doing business with Burma's rogue
regime because the law infringed on the federal government's power
to determine U.S. foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David Souter, writing for the court, said the
Massachusetts law ``is at odds with the president's intended
authority to speak for the United States among the world's nations
in developing a comprehensive, multilateral strategy to bring
democracy to and improve human rights practices and the quality of
life in Burma.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups have long accused Burma of abuses ranging
from the use of slave labor to drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts law barred the state government from awarding
a contract to a company doing business in Burma, unless that
company's bid was 10 percent better than all other competitors'.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decision upheld a federal appeals court in Boston's
ruling a year ago that the law was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   By April 1998, 346 companies _ including 44 U.S. firms _ were on
Massachusetts' list of undesirable contract partners. A number of
other municipal governments, including New York City, Los Angeles
and San Francisco, have passed similar ordinances.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1996, three months after the Massachusetts law went
into effect, Congress imposed sanctions on Burma. And in May 1997,
President Clinton issued an executive order barring new U.S.
investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the federal action, the National Foreign Trade Council,
a Washington-based group representing 550 U.S. firms doing business
overseas, sued Massachusetts in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the court agreed with the trade council's contention
that federal law pre-empted the Massachusetts statute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not merely that the differences between the state and
federal acts in scope and type of sanctions threaten to complicate
discussions; they compromise the very capacity of the president to
speak for the nation with one voice in dealing with other
governments,'' Souter wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Attorney General Tom Reilly, in a prepared
statement, said state officials were disappointed by the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel this law addressed basic human rights and allowed the
state to decide who it did business with,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   The parties were divided over the scope of the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an enormously powerful victory for those of us who
believe that foreign policy is to be made at the national level and
the national level only,'' said Gregory Castanias, an attorney with
Jones, Day, Reavis &AMP; Pogue in Washington who had represented the
council.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Stumberg, an attorney representing 78 lawmakers from
Capitol Hill supporting Massachusetts in the lawsuit, said the
court sidestepped some of the broader questions about state and
local sanctions, limiting the ramifications only to Burma.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts officials had argued in the case that Congress had
failed to forbid state and local governments from enacting
sanctions. County and city sanctions laws were common during the
1980s as a way of non-federal governments underscoring their
opposition to South Africa's practice of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we never ruled on whether state and local sanctions
against South Africa in the 1980s were pre-empted or otherwise
invalid, arguable parallels between the two sets of federal and
state acts do not tell us much about the validity of the latter,''
the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Unocal Corp., Texaco and Houston-based Baker Hughes are among
companies that have done business in Burma in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Unocal is still a partner in an offshore natural gas field and
gas pipeline that transports gas across Burma to the border with
Thailand. Texaco and Baker Hughes have pulled out, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to believe that engagement is the way to bring
about change in countries like Burma, and our record and our
history in Asia shows that is the proper course to follow,'' Unocal
spokesman Barry Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   Lane said none of the state or local sanctions have affected his
company.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Crosby vs. National Foreign Trade Council, 99-474.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STORY ENDS HERE &QL; 
$$$
</P>
