<SLUG> BC-BANROB-SUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK ROBBER'S ATTORNEY DEALS TO AVOID POSSIBLE COUNTERSUIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; An attorney for North Hollywood bank robber Emil
Matasareanu said Monday that he will dismiss a civil rights lawsuit
against two Los Angeles police officers if they agree not to sue
for ``malicious prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley Gage, an attorney for one officer, said John Futrell
intends to sue attorney Stephen Yagman to recover the $300,000 in
lost earnings and attorney fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost to my client has been horrible,'' Gage said after a
hearing in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles. ``He no longer works
for the Los Angeles Police Department. He's a security guard now.
He was falsely accused by Mr. Yagman of being a cold-blooded
murderer, which we know is untrue. That's defamatory.''
</P>
<P>
   Yagman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In March, a federal judge declared a mistrial in the case after
jurors deadlocked 9-3 in favor of the officers, who were accused of
allowing Matasareanu bleed to death after the rolling gunbattle on
streets near a Bank of America branch in North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Brian Lysaght, whom Yagman enlisted to help settle the
case, said he has asked the judge to dismiss the case with
prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to cut off what would become a malicious prosecution
tennis match, we have asked the judge to make it clear in her
dismissal that the police didn't prevail at trial, that there was a
hung jury and that those conditions cut off any possibility of any
frivolous litigation,'' Lysaght said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Christina A. Snyder said she would
send the attorneys to another judge to attempt to mediate the case.
</P>
<P>
   Gage said if the city of Los Angeles agrees to pay the attorney
fees, that would be an ``acceptable'' resolution to the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Assistant City Attorney Thomas C. Hokinson said the city
has no intention to pay Gage's fees.
</P>
<P>
   Yagman and Matasareanu's children decided to seek dismissal of
the case because there is no reason to suspect a second jury would
reach a different verdict, Lysaght said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no new facts, and no new evidence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Snyder dismisses the case without prejudice, that would allow
Futrell to sue the city of Los Angeles or Yagman for his lost
earnings and attorney fees, Gage said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the Los Angeles police have often been unfairly
sued and they have a right to respond,'' Gage said. ``This was the
LAPD's finest hour and now the officers find themselves stuck in a
lawsuit without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant City Attorney Don Vincent, who represented retired
Officer James Vojtecky in the trial, said Vojtecky does not intend
to sue Yagman or the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
