r a BC-HEALTH-INSURANCE-SFCH     06-20 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-INSURANCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE IN FIVE CALIFORNIANS LACKS HEALTH INSURANCE, STUDY FINDS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SACRAMENTO _ Despite a booming economy, and insurance costs
well below national norms, nearly one out of four Californians
lacks health insurance, according to a report released Monday by
the Henry J. Kaiser Family Foundation.
<P>
   The non-insurance rate stands at an even more alarming 40
percent among the state's growing Hispanic population, which helps
explain why Californians of Spanish extraction report the poorest
health of any group in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are part of a comprehensive report that compares
California's health care system with that of the nation. The report
by the Kaiser Foundation, which is not affiliated with Kaiser
Permanente, was assembled from government and private data.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser Foundation health analyst Larry Levitt, who coauthored
the report, said in addition to finding big differences between
California and the nation, the study revealed a health care divide
between rich and poor Californians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like a tale of two states,'' said Levitt, who said
``the dot.com phenomenon'' has simultaneously boosted California's
per capita income ($27,579 here vs. $26,482 in the nation) and left
it with a higher poverty rate (15.4 percent in California vs. 12.7
percent in the U.S.).
</P>
<P>
   The report's most striking finding shows how ethnicity,
immigration status, low insurance rates and poor health status all
converge to the detriment of California's Latino population.
</P>
<P>
   With a lower percentage of whites (50 percent in California vs
71 percent nationwide), a higher percentage of Hispanics (30.3
percent vs 11.7 percent) and more non-citizens (15.8 percent vs 6.1
percent), California lives with several factors that contribute to
its unfavorable health care comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latinos nationwide have the lowest insurance rate of any
ethnic group, and California has nearly three times as many Latinos
as the national average,'' Levitt said. ``That to a large extent
explains the state's challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   But ethnic diversity can't explain other troubling findings in
the report. For instance, California employers pay lower HMO
insurance premiums than their counterparts in other states ($405
per month here versus $445 nationwide). Yet only 48 percent of
California employers offer health insurance benefits, compared to
61 percent of employers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a contradiction we can't explain,'' Levitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance industry lobby Walter Zelman, president of the
California Association of Health Plans, put a positive spin on the
state's low insurance costs. ``If our insurance costs were higher,
the uninsurance problem would be worse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In another finding sure to aggravate the ill feelings between
doctors and insurers, the report found that the average California
physician earns about 14 percent less than M.D.s in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Report coauthor Helen Halpin Schauffler, with the Center for
Health and Public Policy Studies at the University of California at
Berkeley, said this finding marked the first statistical support
for California doctors, who have long complained about falling pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, to our knowledge, is the first data'' to back up the
anecdotal complaints of California doctors, Schauffler said. The
disparity cannot be explained away by a physician glut. Whereas
California did have far more doctors, per capita, than the rest of
the nation in 1975, by 1997, the state and the nation were in a
statistical dead heat, with 278 M.D.s per 100,000 people in
California, versus 276 for every 100,000 people in the rest of the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Schauffler said the lower pay trend affected both primary care
doctors, who earned $140,500 a year in California versus $161,100
nationwide, and specialists, whose annual salaries topped $222,000
in the rest of the U.S. but were $193,800 here.
</P>
<P>
   Such findings help explain why the California Medical
Association recently made a bit of legal history, by filing a
lawsuit that charged the state HMOs with creating a ``racket'' to
restrain insurance costs and doctors' pay.
</P>
<P>
   Schauffler, who stopped short of endorsing that suit, said the
top five health plans in California _ Kaiser, PacifiCare, Health
Net, CaliforniaCare and Blue Shield _ now control 78 percent of all
health insurance in the state. Nationally, the top five health
plans control 68 percent of all insurance, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is increasing cause for concern that the industry in
California and the nation is approaching an oligopoly'' in which a
few insurers dominate health care, she said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for California's lower health insurance costs has
been the fact that large employers here have banded together to
increase their bargaining power vis a vis insurers.
</P>
<P>
   During the mid-90s, these bargaining tactics allowed California
employers to cut their insurance premiums by as much as 9 percent.
But beginning with 1998, insurance rates began to shoot up in the 7
percent to 10 percent range, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt said those rate hikes are yet another warning for
California and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the midst of the most booming economy many of us have ever
seen, insurance coverage has not increased at all,'' he said. ``It
makes you wonder what would happen if we hit a recession.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt said the Kaiser Foundation compiled this comparison
report because California is considered a bellwether for health
trends nationwide. He also said the report was intended as a policy
guide at a time when California's new governor and state
legislature are considering a wide range of health care bills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
