<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9168 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OTTERS-RECOVER-SFCHRO     06-20 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OTTERS-RECOVER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MORE CALIFORNIA OTTERS POP UP IN COASTAL CENSUS  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a tentative but encouraging sign for the
imperiled California sea otter, an annual spring census conducted
by the U.S. Geological Survey has found that their numbers
increased in the past year by 11 percent to 2,317 animals.
</P>
<P>
   The census, which covered 375 miles of coastal habitats from
Half Moon Bay to Santa Barbara, also found that the number of new
pups increased by 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the survey's leaders, James A. Estes and Brian Hatfield,
warned that encouraging results from a single year cannot show a
clearly rising trend. It will take at least two or three more
annual counts before wildlife experts are convinced that the otters
are in fact recovering, they said.
</P>
<P>
   For this year's count, teams of spotters based on shore and
aboard boats and low-flying aircraft used high-powered spotting
scopes and binoculars to tally individual otters and mother-infant
pairs.
</P>
<P>
   The teams did their tedious job between 9 a.m. and about 2 p.m.,
a time when the otters are easier to count as they gather to rest
and feed in close-knit groups, called ``rafts,'' amid floating
kelp, Hatfield said. They spend the rest of the day foraging for a
smorgasbord of clams, mussels, snails, prawns, crabs, abalone, sea
urchins and other seafood.
</P>
<P>
   The cooperative survey included biologists from the Geological
Survey, the California Department of Fish and Game and the Monterey
Bay Aquarium, aided by a corps of volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly extinct by the end of the 19th century after hunters
preyed on them for their water-resistant pelts, the population of
otters along the Northern California coast recovered steadily until
the mid-1970s when growth ceased and the numbers began to decline
again.
</P>
<P>
   They were listed as threatened under the Endangered Species Act
in 1977, and began to recover after emergency California
regulations restricted the use of fixed fishing nets. But their
numbers have declined once more during the past five years _ due to
a combination of disease, parasites, sharks attacks and
entanglement in fishing gear.
</P>
<P>
   The population increase tallied by the latest survey is
``certainly a reason for some optimism,'' Estes said. ``But it will
take another year or two before we can make a meaningful running
average and know whether the population trend is really heading up
and the period of decline is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sea otter populations along coastal areas of the North Pacific
vary widely, Estes said. British Columbia, southeastern Alaska and
Washington state are strongly increasing by rates of 17 percent to
20 percent each year, while the otter population in the Aleutians
has been ``strongly declining'' for several years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The animals also populate Russia's northeast sea coast, but the
data on numbers there are inconclusive and there have been reports
of widespread poaching there since the end of the Soviet Union,
Estes said.
</P>
<P>
   Recent estimates by specialists at the Canadian National
Aquarium in Vancouver, B.C., indicate these current sea otter
populations outside of California: In Washington state, 450; in
British Columbia, more than 2,200; in Russia, 13,000; and in all of
Alaska, 150,000.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
