<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HUMAN ERRORS ... AND SOME OTHERS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Human error has been cited as the cause of that
hard-drive snafu at Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   That brings back memories. I once owned a Hard Drive Snafu, for
my money one of the finest cars ever produced in the Ganges Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it's comforting to know that the nation's most secret
nuclear secrets were misplaced by human error, thus ruling out the
alien-robot-invasion theory.
</P>
<P>
   What probably happened is some office flunky was carrying the
hard drives, he stopped at the copy machine to Xerox his rear end,
he heard the boss coming down the hallway, and he scampered away,
forgetting the X files.
</P>
<P>
   The case of the missing computer files will lead to security
reforms. Currently, secret stuff is classified as ``Secret'' or
``Top Secret,'' but now they're going to add even higher categories
like ``Way Secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Those lab guys might have kept better tabs on the hard drives
had they been classified ``Victoria's Secret.''
</P>
<P>
   HUMAN ERROR was also to blame for the missing excitement at the
U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody let Tiger Woods into the tournament, despite warnings
that his lack of human error was likely to ruin the competition.
</P>
<P>
   After a desperate search Sunday, tournament officials finally
found all the other golfers hiding behind a copy machine in the
press tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' one of the pros explained, ``we don't want any part of
being on the same golf course as Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for them, the tournament was only 72 holes long. It
could have gotten  &UR; really  &LR; embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger won the Masters in '97, then spent a year totally remaking
his swing. I hear he is planning to sue his father, his coaches and
the Stanford Athletic Department for malpractice, for forcing him
to spend the first 21 years of his life burdened with a klunky
swing.
</P>
<P>
   Golf's only hope: Tiger starts playing left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   TV ERROR was to blame for the world hearing Tiger swear. Woods
was miked Saturday, and when he duffed a shot he said a bad word.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lacey reveals, ``Tiger's sponsor, Nike, is considering
changing its slogan to `Just % &LR; f it!' ''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT DO women really want?
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's Examiner &AMP; Chronicle singles want-ads, Bob Perry
spotted this one:
</P>
<P>
   ``Very attractive, intelligent, independent SAPF, 38, seeks
handsome, compassionate, well-manured, sincere, unpretentious SPM.
. .''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking a fertile relationship?
</P>
<P>
   CEASE &AMP; DESIST, that's what the WebVan people are demanding of
the ArtVanSF folks.
</P>
<P>
   ArtVanSF is a whimsical concept of giving away free art from the
back of an old delivery truck, a playful tweak at the city's (some
say) overpriced and pretentious art-gallery scene.
</P>
<P>
   But the ArtVanSF logo looks a bit like the WebVan logo, so
WebVan is flexing its corporate legal muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ArtVanSF`s response? ``We feel violated, angry and uncleaned,
saddened, confused and hungry and slightly chafed.''
</P>
<P>
   Why do I sense a no-win situation for WebVan, launching a battle
against two guys with edgy senses of humor and not a lot of money
who are giving away art?
</P>
<P>
   HANGING IN THERE: It's been seven weeks since he was suspended
for his in-court admission that he was horse-trading favorable ink
for political favors, but his name still tops the Examiner's
editorial-page masthead, right under the proud Hearst eagle:
</P>
<P>
   Timothy O. White, Editor and Publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Shouldn't whoever is actually editing and publishing that paper
get some credit?
</P>
<P>
   HEY, GREAT, we all worked together to coax Steve Young into
retirement seconds before his brain became Jello.
</P>
<P>
   Now all we have to do is work on the several hundred remaining
NFL players who are likely to wind up addle-pated or
severely-gimped by the game.
</P>
<P>
   John Madden, taken slightly out of context here, has the best
description of football: ``Stuff breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   I GET MISTY just thinking about how nice it is that San
Francisco named North Beach Playground after Joe DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   But if we're naming civic treasures after famous local heroes,
says Steve Cannata, why not name something after Johnny Mathis?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a home-grown product and a wonderful singer,'' Cannata
notes, ``and he was a track star at Washington High and at S.F.
State.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis ran hurdles and tried out for the Olympic team in the
high jump.
</P>
<P>
   It might even be a good idea to name a playground after Mathis,
because as Cannata observes, ``His romantic crooning has been
indirectly responsible for a lot of the kids who play on those
playgrounds.''
</P>
<P>
   DEAD WHALES, when did they become the Bay Area's No. 1
sightseeing attraction?
</P>
<P>
   On the TV news, the beached whales attract gawkers like flies.
Or is it vice versa?
</P>
<P>
   But if the authorities decide to dispose of the next rotting
whale carcass by blowing it up with dynamite, save me a spot on the
beach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
