<SLUG> BC-DEM-CONVENTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY COUNCIL TO VOTE ON DNC BAILOUT REQUEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; City Council approval as early as Tuesday of a $4
million taxpayer bailout of the Democratic National Convention
would rid Mayor Richard Riordan of a potential $1 million liability
and free the party from pressing Hollywood contributors for money.
</P>
<P>
   Disclosure of Riordan's conflict of interest over his $1 million
letter of credit to the Convention 2000 Host Committee, and the
lack of a campaign to raise money from celebrities and
entertainment executives who have given heavily to the party, comes
as the council faces an intense lobbying effort.
</P>
<P>
   Only three of the eight votes needed to approve the bailout are
assured Alex Padilla from the Northeast Valley and Nate Holden and
Jackie Goldberg. Council President John Ferraro, the leading
supporter, will not attend Tuesday's meeting because of medical
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Only East Valley Councilman Joel Wachs and West Valley
Councilwoman Laura Chick are firmly opposed and Chick expects to
miss the vote for personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Host Committee officials acknowledged they have no specific
fund-raising plan devoted to the Hollywood community _ even though
Hollywood's wealthy, including Michael Eisner, Steven Spielberg,
Harrison Ford and Nicholas Cage, to name a few, have given
generously to Vice President Al Gore's campaign and to other
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was understood from the start that we would do what we
could to help secure the convention, but that the money to be
raised for it would come elsewhere,'' said Andy Spahn, spokesman
for DreamWorks SKG, the partnership of Spielberg, Jeffrey
Katzenberg and Host Committee co-chairman David Geffen, all of whom
are heavy contributors to Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was to be up to the mayor and Eli Broad and the others to
raise the money while we would be free to concentrate on our
support for the vice president and other Democratic candidates.
There have been some events, but the entertainment industry was
never the primary focus on fund raising for the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Host Committee officials said they have raised all but $2
million of the $35.5 million guaranteed for the convention but that
the demand for more money led to seeking the city's help.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of individuals, the Host Committee relied heavily on 75
mainly corporate donors that include $1 million each from Broad's
SunAmerica, Microsoft, Staples Center, Arco and AT&AMP;T among others
as well as lesser contributions such as the $100,000 each donated
by Times Mirror Co., Amgen, Gibson, Dunn &AMP; Crutcher and Riordan's
Original Pantry restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Committee officials also expect some help from President
Clinton, who is coming to Los Angeles on Saturday for a
weekend-long fund-raising trip on behalf of Sen. Dianne Feinstein
as well as the state and national Democratic parties.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Clinton's events Saturday will be a fund-raiser for
the convention at Riordan's home, attended by numerous business and
civic leaders who have yet to contribute or given only what are
considered modest amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan's conflict on the issue arose because he is among a
group of backers who signed a $1 million letter of credit to be
used by the Host Committee to cover the costs of staging the event.
Others also signed letters of credit that could be protected by the
bailout.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Riordan said he is aware of the perception of a
possible conflict, but insist he has not taken any actions that
would affect that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why all the requests have come from the Host Committee
and the Democrats and he hasn't taken any actions directly,''
spokesman Manuel Valencia said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement with the Host Committee, money would be
drawn against the letter of credit when the committee doesn't have
sufficient cash to pay for services, meaning the city allocation
could relieve the mayor of that liability.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the City Attorney's Office said Riordan did not
request a legal opinion on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of City Council members shows nine members are
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Even Goldberg's support is contingent on two issues: designating
Pershing Square as a safe ground for protesters and creating a
special ad hoc council committee to monitor police activities up to
and during the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Goldberg) has some concerns she would like to see addressed
regarding the protests and make sure they are not ignored,''
spokeswoman Sharon Delugach said.
</P>
<P>
   Wachs complained the city doesn't have enough money to provide
adequate services and should not have to bail out the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convention will go on no matter what,'' Wachs said. ``The
city shouldn't have to bail them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wachs appeared on several radio talk shows Monday calling for
public opposition, prompting a number of people to call in to
council offices.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Rudy Svorinich Jr. is having a tough time justifying
the spending, aide Barry Glickman said, while Councilwoman Cindy
Miscikowski has some misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has some grave doubts about this, but wants to hear the
arguments,'' spokesman Glenn Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Also coming out against the spending was City Controller Rick
Tuttle, who said the arguments in favor of the city making a
contribution were flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we want to set a precedent which will lead those who do
business with the city to believe that if they can just get a
project far enough along, the city will capitulate to any demand?''
Tuttle asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
