<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-MARSH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST DIRECTOR OF MARSHALS SERVICE HAS IMPRESSIVE LINEAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ John W. Marshall embodies two enduring
participants of the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Thurgood Marshall, was a crusading NAACP lawyer and
later a U.S. Supreme Court justice.
</P>
<P>
   And now the younger Marshall is director of the U.S. Marshals
Service, whose deputies once escorted scores of black children in
the often violent struggle for school desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   It is a mantle that Marshall wears lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about it much,'' Marshall said in an interview
in Kansas City on Monday. ``But I take a lot of pride in both.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, who was sworn in to the director's job last fall, is
in Kansas City this week to meet with deputies based here and to
address a national sheriffs convention.
</P>
<P>
   If he seems modest about his heritage, it is because the task of
leading the nation's oldest law enforcement agency into the 21st
century is now first on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Marshals Service was founded by the first Congress in
1789 to enforce federal court orders, make arrests and handle
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   In the country's westward expansion, deputy U.S. marshals
brought law and order to the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Marshall said, the service's primary mission remains
protecting federal judges and the courts, and enforcing their
orders. Deputies also face an array of tasks never imagined by its
founders 211 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Marshals transport nearly 200,000 prisoners a year on its ``Con
Air'' inmate airline as well as administer the federal witness
protection program. They even help guard nuclear warheads and
missiles when the weapons are moved between military facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Marshals Service also is responsible for the daily housing
needs of more than 32,000 federal prisoners awaiting trial or
sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   But solidifying the marshals' most basic police function _
arresting fugitives and putting them in jail _ has Marshall's
attention now. Deputy U.S. marshals make about 55 percent of the
federal felony arrests recorded each year. With additional
deputies, Marshall said, they can do better.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year Marshall submitted an aggressive budget
request, still under consideration in Congress, that would suspend
a hiring freeze and allow him to add 400 officers to the force of
about 4,200 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fugitive apprehension is an area where I'd like to see us
expand,'' Marshall said. ``But we can only do that with additional
people. We don't have enough deputy marshals who come in and work
strictly fugitives. It's all about getting dangerous people off the
streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, 41, comes by his interest in basic police work from
his early days. While a student at Georgetown University he became
friendly with a member of the Virginia State Police, who soon sent
recruiters his direction.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said his career choice, which included stints as a
Virginia State Police motorcycle patrol officer and narcotics
investigator, caught his father by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was very supportive,'' Marshall recalled. ``It helped
him seeing things from the bench as the father of someone in law
enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   In June 1994, President Clinton appointed the younger Marshall
as U.S. marshal for the Eastern District of Virginia. That paved
the way for his appointment as director of the service last year.
</P>
<P>
   Now his weeks are filled trying to convince Washington
policy-makers that the mission of the Marshals Service remains
vital in an era where federal law enforcement might appear
fragmented in a rainbow of FBI-DEA-ATF acronyms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get the word out about the Marshals Service and
educate our political leaders about what it does,'' Marshall said.
``We need to get the attention of Capitol Hill about what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's tenure as director of the Marshals Service barely
touched the 1990s, a decade that was not kind to the public
perceptions of some federal law enforcement agencies, with episodes
at Waco and Ruby Ridge. Marshall, however, said he was determined
to run the service in a manner that honored both its heritage and
the standards for which his father fought.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said law enforcement can be done properly when you don't
cut corners,'' Marshall said. ``He thought it could be one of the
noblest professions in the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
