<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS HOLD OFF PACERS TO WIN NBA TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After 12 years, the Los Angeles Lakers finally
gave Hollywood something to cheer about.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal scored 41 points and Kobe Bryant buried four
late free throws as the Lakers rallied to defeat the Indiana
Pacers, 116-111, to win their first NBA championship since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Embattled Lakers forward Glen Rice made two free throws for a
112-109 lead with 1:16 left. With 32 seconds remaining, Reggie
Miller rushed downcourt and tossed up a wild3-point shot from 28
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant was fouled with 13 seconds to go, and his two free throws
pushed the Lakers' lead to 114-109.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Davis' rebound dunk brought the Pacers to 114-111 with 5.4
seconds left. But Bryant made two free throws with 2.5 seconds
remaining to seal the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, who won the best-of-seven series, 4-2, were so
convinced they were going to wrap up the title Monday night that a
lot of folks around here treated Game 6 as if it were an
afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for a downtown parade, scheduled for Wednesday, were
already mapped out. Some fans were selling championship T-shirts _
two hours before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Flyers to a Lakers championship party hosted by Magic Johnson
were passed out Sunday night to patrons at a swanky Hollywood
nightclub. Johnson is the Lakers' part-owner and vice president,
and the party is scheduled to take place Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Let the party begin.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers used a torrid rally in the fourth quarter to ease
past a Pacers squad that led, 25-24, after the first period, 56-53,
at the half, and, 84-79, after three periods.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was voted the Most Valuable Player of the Finals,
completing the full circle. O'Neal was the regular season MVP,
coming one vote shy of it being unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   For the Lakers, this wasn't Tiger Woods at the U.S. Open. This
was more like Shane Mosley eking out a decision over Oscar De la
Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   But the locals didn't care. All they wanted was the Lakers'
championship banner to be raised into the Staples Center rafters,
and it will be in next season's home opener.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant aided the Lakers' cause with 26 points, and Rice added
16.
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose led the Pacers with 29 points. Miller had 25, Davis
popped in 20 and Austin Croshere added 16. But the Pacers got just
two points on 1-of-8 shooting from center Rik Smits.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers took the lead for good with 9:02 left when O'Neal's
layup gave them a 91-90 lead. It was their first lead since late in
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who also grabbed 12 rebounds, was crying tears of joy
after the game. This was his first championship since he led San
Antonio Cole High School to the 1989 Class 3A state championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to say thank ya'll for being here,'' O'Neal told
the crowd. ``And we're going to get one again next year.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it looked as if there was going to be a Game 7. The
Pacers were controlling the tempo for most of the night and were
beating back every rally the Lakers threw at them.
</P>
<P>
   But back-to-back rebound dunks by O'Neal, a pair of 3-point
field goals by Robert Horry, and some poor shot selection by Rose,
Croshere and Miller were the main reasons the Lakers will be
partying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
