<SLUG> BC-PINK-EXPAND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PDQUICK TAKES NEW NAME NATIONAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMARILLO, Calif. _ Goodbye PinkDot, hello PDQuick.
</P>
<P>
   The home-delivery retailer whose snappy cars have darted around
the streets of Los Angeles and Orange County for more than a decade
is going national.
</P>
<P>
   Under its new name, the company plans to open 30 new locations
and begin doing business in Baltimore, Phoenix, Sacramento, San
Diego, San Francisco, San Jose, and Washington, D.C., by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Now officially known as PDQuick, the Camarillo-based company
operates 12 neighborhood centers that fill orders coming in via
telephone and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with its new identity, PDQuick has a new Internet
address (www.pdquick.com) and a new phone number (888-PDQUICK). For
phones without the letter Q on the keypad, the number is (888)
737-8425.
</P>
<P>
   PDQuick is entering a volatile market segment fraught with eager
competitors that have ambitious expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
   Homegrocer.com and Kozmo.com are among them, and the market
segment has been touched by the early dot-com shakeout, with
Peapod.com folding after 10 years of on-demand service.
</P>
<P>
   PDQuick's specialty is convenience items _ popular grocery
brands and prepared foods such as salads and sandwiches _ delivered
quickly for a moderate service charge.
</P>
<P>
   But the market for home-delivery services, particularly over the
Internet, is a growing one, according to Forrester Research, a
Cambridge, Mass.-based research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester analyst Evie Black Dykema predicts on-demand delivery
firms will grow into a $20 billion market.
</P>
<P>
   PDQuick's expansion includes new locations in Southern
California, including the first location to open under the new name
in Fullerton. Sites in Reseda and Long Beach will follow in short
order, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Slama, manager of the Long Beach store that is set to open
July10, said the location will make deliveries between 6 a.m. and 3
a.m., and will employ 60 to 70 people.
</P>
<P>
   A 24-hour operating schedule is a possibility in the near
future, Slama said.
</P>
<P>
   PDQuick chief executive officer Dan Frederickson said the
company intends to dominate the market with its dual sales strategy
that allows customers to order online or by phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mandate is simple: to redefine the way customers think
about convenience,'' Frederickson said. ``Our goal is equally
simple: to dominate this fast-growing consumer market on a national
basis just as we already do in one of the largest consumer markets
in the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
