u s BC-BKN-PACERS-MILLER-NYT     06-20 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-MILLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER PUTS SCARE INTO LAKERS WITH A TORRID START 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even after he had mimicked his coach, the great
Larry Bird, in three straight games in Indiana, there were
questions. Which Reggie Miller would show up at the Staples Center
on Monday night? The one who had been confounded by the
surroundings and backdrop of Los Angeles's cavernous arena, or the
one who had laid waste to the Lakers' vaunted defense with a flurry
of points that not even Shaquille O'Neal's domination could
overcome?
</P>
<P>
   The glamorous crowd surrounding the court found out almost
immediately. Miller scored 7 points in the first quarter alone, his
final basket of the period coming on a 3-pointer. It was clear from
that point on that the man who had missed 15 of 16 shots in Game 1
was not in the building.
</P>
<P>
   And while Miller was not enough to keep Los Angeles from
winning, 116-111, to claim its first National Basketball
Association championship since 1988, it was enough to put a scare
into the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who averaged 31 points in leading Indiana to two
victories in three games at the Conseco Fieldhouse, continued his
wicked shooting on Monday night in Game 6, finishing with 25 points
to keep the outcome in doubt until the waning moments. Strong all
night, he started a late-game run that nearly foiled the Lakers'
victory.
</P>
<P>
   With 2 minutes 41 seconds remaining, Miller hit a 22-footer from
the left corner to move Indiana within 5 points. The Pacers pulled
within 1 point, but then, with the Lakers ahead by 112-109, Miller,
shooting quickly and perhaps ill-advisedly, missed a 26-footer with
30 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   When Glen Rice grabbed the rebound for Los Angeles, the
celebration began.
</P>
<P>
   Though Miller had been so spectacular of late, shooting 51
percent over all and 55 percent from 3-point range over the last
three games, there was doubt as to whether he could replicate those
performances in Los Angeles. Like the rest of the Pacers, he had
found the Lakers' new arena a tough place to sink baskets. In four
games at the Staples Center, including two regular-season losses to
the Lakers and the woeful Clippers, Miller had shot just 32.8
percent from the floor. From behind the 3-point line, where he is
one of the best ever, he was only 2 for 18.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation abounded as to why Miller and the Pacers, who shot
39.5 percent in their three previous road games against the Lakers,
had struggled so in Staples. The Pacers said they got the same
shots in Los Angeles that they did in Indiana, so it wasn't
necessarily the Lakers' defense.
</P>
<P>
   Bird mentioned that the background of the baskets in the
cavernous arena might have been responsible. Miller, who scored
just 28 points on 8-of-32 shooting in Games 1 and 2, made no
excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it feels any different,'' Miller said before the
game. ``It's just missed shots. They're making shots, so there
can't be anything wrong with the arena.''
</P>
<P>
   The rims and their background were no issue on Monday night. The
Pacers shot 50 percent in each of the first two quarters. Along
with Jalen Rose who scored 12 points in the first half, Miller was
the dynamo.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's performance in the finals, in which he averaged a
team-best 24.2 points over the first five games, added to a
tremendous postseason for Miller, a 34-year-old soon-to-be free
agent. After failing to lead Indiana in regular-season scoring for
the first time since 1990, Miller took back the team's top role in
the playoffs, averaging 23.9 points.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he put on some outstanding performances and, not
surprisingly, was at his best in the most crucial times. With the
Pacers facing the possibility of a first-round elimination against
Milwaukee, Miller scored 41 points, his postseason career high, in
Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   In the next game, he set the tone for the series against
Philadelphia by recording 40 points, 21 of them on 3-pointers. And,
of course, against the New York Knicks, he scored at will over
Allan Houston, Latrell Sprewell and Chris Childs in posting 17 of
his 34 points in the fourth quarter of the deciding Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   Though he clearly feeds off of pressure, Miller claimed to be
playing stress-free against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pressure on us,'' he said after Game 5. ``From the
get-go, they were supposed to beat us, to sweep us.''
</P>
<P>
   From the get-go, observers should have known that Miller would
not let that happen. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
