<HEADLINE>
EX-CARDINAL FACES RETURN TO CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JUDI VILLA AND KENT SOMERS  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Luis Sharpe hasn't lived in Cuba for 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   His five children are in Phoenix with his ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   Brothers and sisters settled in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   But the former Arizona Cardinals lineman could be sent back to
Cuba, deported after serving time for his most recent drug charge.
Sharpe remains detained in Florence, while INS officials decide his
fate.
</P>
<P>
   `He has very little, if any, connection to Cuba,` said Marc
Budoff, Sharpe's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Ahr, special assistant to the INS director, said he
couldn't comment on Sharpe's case. However, he did say that people
who are not U.S. citizens can be deported if they break state or
immigration laws.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe never became a U.S. citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, immigration judges remove as many as 9,000 people
from the Phoenix District. They are barred from returning for five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Ahr said judges don't consider how long a person has been away
from his home country. And statistics aren't kept on the number of
years deportees have been away.
</P>
<P>
   Since retiring in 1994, the former Pro Bowl player has struggled
with drugs. From November to January, he was arrested twice for
drug-related charges. He was sent to prison in March.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his release, Budoff said, Sharpe had planned to enter a
rehabilitation program. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
