<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-NYT     06-20 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS PRODUCE A TITILE FOR TINSELTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kobe Bryant and Shaquille O'Neal spent much of the
last four years trying to meet high expectations, and deal with
heartache and the perception that they were simply too young and
immature to seize a world championship. Hurdle after hurdle, their
Los Angeles Lakers team leapt over everyone this season _ until
only Reggie Miller and the resilient Indiana Pacers remained.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, before a screaming crowd at the Staples Center,
the Lakers sailed to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   With Coach Phil Jackson folding his arms in serene contentment,
having won his seventh title in the last nine seasons, the Lakers
won their first National Basketball Association championship under
his guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Delivering down the stretch, coming from behind for three
quarters, O'Neal, Bryant and Los Angeles finally caught the Pacers,
winning by 116-111 in Game 6 and securing the franchise's first
title of the post-Magic Johnson era.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal completed a majestic triple-crown season _ he had won the
scoring title and the league's most valuable player award _ by
scoring 41 points and grabbing 12 rebounds, and being named MVP of
the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Few shots were bigger than the running floater he hit on the
right side with just over nine minutes remaining. Hit by Derrick
McKey and Austin Croshere, O'Neal somehow converted the layup that
gave the Lakers their first lead since the last second of the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   When Rick Fox put in a soft 3-pointer from the left wing with
less than nine minutes left to give the Lakers a 4-point lead, the
Lakers had scored on their last nine possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who ended with 26 points, 10 rebounds and 4 assists,
dropped in a 22-footer from the right wing with 3 minutes 28
seconds remaining that gave the Lakers a 109-103 lead.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal also closed the Pacers out. Hitting a pretty turnaround
from the left baseline about 15 feet away, he gave the Lakers a
4-point lead when Indiana was drawing close.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, he was dunking in missed putbacks, bringing the fans
to their feet and the Pacers to their knees. The Lakers won the
series, four games to two, and won all three games they played at
their home arena.
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose led the Pacers with 29 points and Miller added 25.
</P>
<P>
   It was not easy. Down by 7 points in the fourth quarter, the
Pacers roared back. Rose tied the game with a 3-pointer from the
right baseline with 5:04 remaining that forced the Lakers to call a
timeout.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry, Ron Harper and the stingy Lakers defense also
played an important role in the Lakers' first title since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers were trying to become the seventh team in National
Basketball Association history to recover from a 3-1 deficit in a
seven-game series and the first team to accomplish the feat in the
finals.
</P>
<P>
   For more than three quarters, they looked determined to force a
Game 7. Moving the ball around the perimeter, getting clutch
shooting from Miller and Rose and inspired play off the bench from
Croshere and Sam Perkins, Indiana was in command.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow the Lakers found the missing element from their
fairy-tale season, the one thing they needed to erase the
perception that they lacked a killer instinct: the hammer, a
fourth-quarter performance so dominating that nothing could be left
to chance in a deciding game on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They found it, and that is why the streamers and confetti
descended from the rafters, the embroidered championship hats and
T-shirts were distributed and O'Neal, having scored more than 40
points in three of the six games, grinned wide and proud and hugged
Bryant, his 21-year-old teammate, as the buzzer sounded and the
party began.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers misfired on many opportunities through three
quarters. As Los Angeles recovered from 7- and 8-point deficits in
the third, Bryant missed a short pull-up shot in the lane when the
Lakers were trailing by 1. Rice then missed two free throws on the
next possession.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were within a point several times at the end of the
quarter, only to be repelled from taking the lead. When Rose put in
a difficult jumper over O'Neal at the third-quarter buzzer, giving
him 18 points in the game, the Pacers took a 5-point lead into the
final period.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers possessed two of the league's top five players,
the Pacers have shown they have a better team from Miller through
their 12th man. Never was this more apparent than during a flawless
possession with less than nine minutes left in the third quarter,
when all five Pacers touched the ball before the score.
</P>
<P>
   Rose threw an entry pass to Dale Davis on the left block. Davis,
with nowhere to go, found a cutting Mark Jackson in the lane. With
the defense collapsing, Jackson flipped it to Rik Smits on the
right baseline, who unselfishly gave it Miller behind the 3-point
line on the right wing. The shot was good, the exclamation point to
a ball-movement clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, an ordained minister, threw up a prayer from a few feet
inside midcourt to end the first quarter. It hit only nylon,
sending the Pacers in front by 26-24.
</P>
<P>
   But down by as many as 12 points in the quarter, the Lakers
bailed themselves out before intermission. With Bryant harassing
Jackson in the backcourt and O'Neal cleaning up the offensive
glass, they went on a 6-0 run in the final two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Outplayed for much of 24 minutes, the Lakers went to the locker
room trailing by only 3 points, 56-53. They looked reinvigorated,
capable of putting the Pacers away early in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing is as it seems with this Lakers team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
