<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9185 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE6-BIRD-L     06-20 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE6-BIRD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD'S SWAN SONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL A. ANASTASI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was a sickly, strangely exciting feeling Larry
Bird felt Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The same feeling he has before every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm nervous; I'm scared,'' he said. ``And it's great.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no apprehension in his voice, no emotion. His anxiety
was buried somewhere deep inside his gut, and he needed no rhetoric
- no Norman Dale ``Maybe we don't belong here!'' that Gene Hackman
performed for us so beautifully in ``Hoosiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird was nervous and scared, but he felt no fear.
</P>
<P>
   He knew his team belonged here, and so did his players. Which is
why they played with the kind of heart that forced a series against
a clearly superior team to reach six games, and nearly seven.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird coached his final game for the Indiana Pacers on
Monday, a 116-111 loss. He approached it as he did his first, and
he flatly stood by his word that his tenure would last three years
and no more.
</P>
<P>
   He achieved what he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a great basketball player, he was denied the finish because
of injuries,'' said Pacers assistant coach Mel Daniels, a man who
coached Bird at Indiana State and has known him for as long as
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think right now maybe he thinks he has carried this
program as far as he could carry it and it's time to step back,''
Daniels said. ``So it's a statement of how good he really is. I
think getting to the Finals is the culmination of his entire career
in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Those three years brought two trips to the Finals, a
regular-season record of 147-67 - his .686 winning percentage the
best for that time span in Pacers history. He won consecutive
Central Division titles and the NBA named him its Coach of the Year
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As long as his players play hard, Bird fears nothing - win or
lose. What he does fear, what terrifies him, really, is
underachieving. Austin Croshere, the Santa Monica native who grew
up idolizing Magic Johnson at a time when Bird, too, was an idol,
hardly spoke to Bird his first two seasons with the Pacers. Bird
knew Croshere was too soft, too eager to sit out with a minor
injury, too wide-eyed at the talent that now surrounded him in the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   For a year now, beginning in summer league, Bird has ridden
Croshere softly but mercilessly. ``Don't be a sissy,'' Bird told
him. And often.
</P>
<P>
   ``Constantly,'' Croshere said. ``Just walking by me. ... Without
eye contact, or even stopping.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, no one who watched these Finals would consider saying that
about Croshere, the Pacers' most consistent player throughout - at
least not without risking Bird's wrath.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a time when the in thing may be to yell and scream, act
crazy and draw attention, here's a coach that simply coaches the
game, prepares his team, believes in us,'' Indiana guard Mark
Jackson said. ``He has faith in us and trust in us and allows us to
go out and play the game and never panics.''
</P>
<P>
   Panic is for those who are desperate, those who fear the future.
Bird embraces the future as few former professional athletes can.
Bird was desperate in the final moments of Monday's game, but only
for the men who again brought him to this stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``After going three years with these guys and knowing that some
of them have come to the end of their careers, knowing that they
work very hard for me, they've had an opportunity to win a
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for them. I'm happy they're here. If we'd won the
whole thing, I'd be more happy for the players than I would for
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Meaning, himself.
</P>
<P>
   Bird the coach will never be remembered for his tactical genius.
He has relied on two veteran assistants - Rick Carlisle and Dick
Harter - for that, especially in the first season. He knows a
coach, foremost, must make his players fulfill their potential, a
philosophy likewise mastered by Phil Jackson and painfully lost on
Del Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come a long way,'' Bird said. ``I've been very fortunate
to pick a team of guys that play hard for me. That's the key in
this league. If your guys play hard, you'll win a lot of games. If
you got talent, you'll have an opportunity to play for the world
championship. And that's what these guys have done.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what Bird did for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing is, it doesn't just happen,'' said Chris Mullin,
who has been around long enough to know. ``The same things that
made him a great player make him a great coach - dedication, hard
work, being consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   The same things ensure Bird will be successful no matter what
follows. His team played hard; he succeeded. He succeeded simply by
bringing the series back to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jack Nicholson had to shake Bird's hand when the buzzer
sounded Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Daniels put it, ``It's time to do something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird will return to his home in Florida, and he does not yet
know what that something else is.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's been a great ride,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   You knew, with Larry Bird, there is no other kind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 0118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-20 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AUERBACH WON'T JOIN THE BANDWAGON 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Phil Jackson won his seventh championship in nine
seasons on Monday night. When the Los Angeles Lakers found a way to
get past the Indiana Pacers, 116-111, their coach had won a title
without the greatest player in the history of the National
Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   So, irrespective of what his supporters and detractors think, he
can do it without Michael. People are talking about his genius _
his ability to get his players to perform at their highest levels _
in the same vein they once talked about Red Auerbach, whose Boston
Celtics won 11 titles in 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder what Red thinks.
</P>
<P>
   From his home outside Washington, the former Celtics patriarch
has been watching the NBA finals. He still enjoys the games. But he
doesn't understand the fuss over Jackson, the need to anoint him
the greatest coach of his era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any place he's gone, he's had the team given to him,'' the
82-year-old Auerbach said before Monday night's game. ``I had to go
make my team and put it together. I had to draft the players
myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry West gives him a team, and Jerry Krause gives him a
team. And he goes ahead, and he wins with those teams. He's a good
coach, but let's not get carried away.''
</P>
<P>
   Either out of spite or wounded pride, Auerbach went on:
</P>
<P>
   ``He got blown out three times in the playoffs. He was supposed
to run the table with these guys. He was lucky in that Portland
game. They just fell apart at the end; that's why they won.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Auerbach refusing to give another successful coach his
due. Arrogant in his day, despised by many in his profession, he
would light up victory cigars with games in hand, celebrating as
much he was rubbing it in.
</P>
<P>
   Phil may not want to admit it, but he has a lot of Red in him.
The condescension aimed at the other team and its crowd, the
inability to give effusive praise to another team's staff, the
idea, deep down, that he's Phil Jackson and you're not.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much trouble his team appears in, Jackson has
never given the impression that he or his players have panicked and
nearly thrown a series away. Tested severely against Sacramento and
Portland and then Indiana, Jackson still had this serene demeanor
about him, as if he knew how it would end with Shaquille O'Neal
just as he knew how it would end with Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   During the Sacramento series, to make sure his players were
paying attention to the game film, Jackson had look-alikes for
Kings Coach Rick Adelman and Jason Williams spliced into the
videotape. For Adelman, he used Adolf Hitler. For Williams, he had
edited in a clip of Edward Norton's skinhead character in
``American History X.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the times, the harder you try, the harder it is not
to,'' Jackson said when asked if he has alienated some of his NBA
peers. ``I don't know. I just let it slide. You just have to let
that kind of stuff slide in this profession.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the comparisons to Auerbach, he said humbly, ``When
you retire, 10, 15 years down the road _ God willing you're still
alive _ you think about those things at a later date.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Auerbach was also not singing Larry Bird's
praises. Bird, who planned to retire after the season, after taking
the Pacers to two Eastern Conference finals and one NBA finals in
three years, was drafted by Auerbach in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry, he also took a ready-made ball club,'' Auerbach said.
``He doesn't want to go through the process of rebuilding, which is
a smart move. He doesn't really want to coach. He's so wealthy, why
is he going to kill himself? But, basically, he did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   As old school as you can possibly get, Auerbach was asked about
Jackson's coaching philosophy, which includes a lot of new-age
teachings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't follow that routine,'' he said. ``When you win, you
can all of a sudden worship the moon. When you lose and you say
it's Zen or zip, or whatever they call it, they laugh at you.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said they got no ballplayers outside their two stars.
What is Rice? Chopped liver? What about Robert Horry. Rick Fox, I
know a lot of ball clubs who would want him on their team. He's not
doing it with mirrors, so why doesn't he come out and say, `I got a
good ball club'?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is these days. Coaches have a tendency in
all sports to downgrade their ball club. So when they win, they're
heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person who gets coach of the year now is a guy that
finishes second that was supposed to be fourth. I like Doc Rivers,
but why did he win? What can you do more than win? Isn't that the
job?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach was not all gloom and doom, saying O'Neal belongs in a
category with Russell and Chamberlain. But he saved his choicest
comments for Jackson, the Renaissance man who many feel has
eclipsed Pat Riley as the best coach in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you can do it the way he's doing it, it's easy,''
Auerbach said. ``You walk right into a ball club. He didn't make
any moves. He didn't do anything. They'll say the other coaches
that were there didn't win. Maybe they weren't given enough time to
mature with that team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether he had to do anything with their immaturity, I don't
know. But when you're older, things start to fall in place. You
tell yourself: `Last year we lost. Why did we lose? Let's play
together.' That's what's happened to those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach has never been incredibly complimentary regarding his
peers, just as Jackson has not exactly endeared himself to his
generation of coaches. They won't ever admit it, but they're more
like each other than they both realize.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 0141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9194 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-20 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, A CHANCE TO CELEBRATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They had waited 12 years and six NBA Finals games
and four excruciating quarters to be NBA champions. The Lakers
could wait another 2.5 seconds to party.
</P>
<P>
   And so the celebration on the court started modestly after Kobe
Bryant's free throws set the 116-111 final score with only those
two ticks left on the clock. During the Indiana Pacers' final
timeout, Lakers players exchanged perfunctory high-fives near their
bench, and veteran guards Ron Harper and Brian Shaw hugged.
</P>
<P>
   That would be it for Lakers celebration - until the timeout
ended, Reggie Miller's last desperate shot bounced away, and the
Staples Center exploded around them.
</P>
<P>
   Delayed gratification turned out to be the best kind.
</P>
<P>
   It was 9:05 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Public address announcer Lawrence Tanter rumbled, ``The Los
Angeles Lakers are world champions!'' and could barely be heard
above the jet-engine roar of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Gold streamers and purple and gold confetti rained from the
rafters.
</P>
<P>
   The dozen Lakers players bounded around the court, trading what
must have been 132 hugs.
</P>
<P>
   Someone waved a sign reading, ``It's in the Fridge!''
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson bear-hugged Shaquille O'Neal and planted a kiss on
the center's cheek.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal fairly swam through the crowd of well-wishers to embrace
his mother near the celebrity seats.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's grin filled the message-board video screen and the
crowd erupted in a deep-throated cheer.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, now wearing a championship cap, appeared on the screen,
and the fans launched one more chant of ``MVP! MVP! MVP!''
</P>
<P>
   Workers erected a small stage at center court, and within six
minutes of the final buzzer, players, coaches and Lakers owner
Jerry Buss were accepting their prize from commissioner David
Stern, who exclaimed about the Lakers' and Pacers' ``six
heartstopping games'' having exhibited ``the best of the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   The players thrust ``No. 1'' fingers into the cloud of confetti.
</P>
<P>
   Buss took the trophy from the commissioner and handed it to
Harper, who passed it around to his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Queen's ``We are the Champions'' blared through the arena, as it
probably blared through the Forum in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first of many (championships), just like before!''
Buss shouted into an NBC camera.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal accepted the finals MVP trophy and said that Phil Jackson
was the real MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna get one next year, too!'' O'Neal promised - and
you remembered how Pat Riley promised a repeat after the Lakers'
1987 title and they got it in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the Champions'' gave way to Randy Newman's ``I Love
L.A.,'' another sensory sensation from the old days.
</P>
<P>
   It was all enough to make you forget that the Lakers were being
labeled disappointments by many for struggling through four playoff
rounds as teams with 67 regular-season victories aren't supposed
to, that their postseason foibles had diminished them in many eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 teams that won 65 or more regular-season games and the
NBA title, the Lakers are the first to lose eight playoff games,
first to lose any games in the first round, first to need seven
games in the conference finals, first to fail six times in
elimination games, first to lose five times by double digits, and
first since Philadelphia in 1967 to fail to sweep a series.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the most egregious of the double-digit losses -- by
29 to Portland and by 33 to Indiana - the Lakers managed to give up
more points than they scored in both their conference finals and
NBA Finals series.
</P>
<P>
   None of that mattered now.
</P>
<P>
   In the minutes after the Lakers wrapped up their 4-2 victory
over Indiana, after trailing by as many as 12 points in the first
half, not a man or woman in the Staples Center was sitting, and it
seemed that nobody was standing on the floor, instead climbing on
their chairs, the better to take in the entire scene.
</P>
<P>
   In the stands, the celebration had threatened to begin eight
minutes prematurely, after the Rick Fox 3-pointer that followed the
tumbling O'Neal hook shot that gave the Lakers the lead at 91-90.
</P>
<P>
   The unofficial card section in the southeast corner of the
Staples Center that had been spelling out ``ON A MISSION'' switched
to ``WORLD CHAMPS.'' The arena was positively pulsating - the fans
indoors incited by the message-board images of the rollicking crowd
watching the game on a giant screen on 11th Street.
</P>
<P>
   It was at that point that beefy men wearing earpieces began to
unwrap the yellow rope they would use - (begin ital)mostly(end
ital) with success - to keep fans off the court after the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers players would resist the temptation to begin the
party then.
</P>
<P>
   Only after letting the Indiana Pacers catch up, and after
regaining control of the sensational game, and after Bryant's free
throws in the final seconds rendered their lead insurmountable, did
the home team begin to acknowledge the title they'd waited so much
longer than expected to make official.
</P>
<P>
   Gratification delayed was that much sweeter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
