<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9202 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-LAD     06-20 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS WIN NBA CHAMPIONSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One more sputter for suspense. One more pause for
dramatic effect. One more blistering, dazzling, stubborn charge up
the hill, one big grasp for the crown.
</P>
<P>
   One more banner for the rafters.
</P>
<P>
   One long drought ended, wiped out by a cloudburst of confetti
and multiple champagne showers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, title-less since Showtime faded out more than a
decade ago, are NBA champions once more.
</P>
<P>
   Their 116-111 victory over the Indiana Pacers on Monday night
clinched the Finals, four games to two, and set off a thunderous
celebration on the Staples Center floor, with 18,997 of the Laker
faithful joining in.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, brought together four years
ago to bring about this renewal, embraced at midcourt after the
final buzzer, the Lakers having at last restored a feeling not felt
since their last title in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea,'' said Bryant, ``that champagne burned so much
when it gets in your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old star quickly got used to the feeling. Everything
else he felt, he could hardly describe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't, man. I just feel so numb,'' said Bryant, his fiancee
Vanessa Laine at his side, and his mother Pam standing nearby. ``I
just feel numb. I put the championship T-shirt on, put the hat on,
celebrated with my family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory will bring a seventh championship banner to Staples
Center. It comes in just the first season for coach Phil Jackson,
who brought the magic touch and the steady hand to L.A. that won
him six titles with the Chicago Bulls. It's Jackson's seventh title
in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first title for his young proteges, Bryant and O'Neal,
who figure to add several more before they are through here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through ups and downs, but the most important thing is
that we believed in one another,'' said Bryant, who scored 26
points - including the last four - in the victory, ``and we
believed in the system. We believed in sitting in a room, and
meditating and Phil lighting incense in the room and doing all
kinds of crazy stuff. But we believed in it and we believed in one
another and this championship shows it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, whose 41 points, 12 rebounds and four blocked shots led
the Lakers on Monday, was the unanimous choice for Finals MVP,
adding the trophy to his regular-season MVP award.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned a lot. We've been able to grow together,'' said
Glen Rice, who scored 16 points. ``I'm just, I'm so happy for the
team right now. I really am. That's what it's all about. I mean, we
really worked hard, we fought together and to be able to raise that
trophy up out there is an unbelievable feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers showed their Hollywood side, scripting an appropriate
final chapter:
</P>
<P>
   The imperfect championship game, for the imperfect championship
team.
</P>
<P>
   It took multiple tries to win every round of the playoffs. But
the fits and starts and the hiccups only intensified the suspense,
added to the anticipation and made the crowning moment that much
sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 was simply a repeat of everything the Lakers have done to
date. From the iffy start to the late deficit to the dramatic
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   They lost every quarter until the fourth - trailing by two
points after the first, three points at halftime and by five
heading into the final period.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal's hook off the glass with 9:02 left gave the Lakers a
91-90 lead, their first since the first quarter, and the boost they
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Fox followed with a 3-pointer over Austin Croshere, and
Staples Center erupted as the Pacers called a timeout and Fox
bumped chests with Rice at the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Then a Robert Horry 3-pointer, then a pair of O'Neal putback
jams, and the tide seemed to have turned for good, the Lakers
leading 101-94.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pacers, who provided a stiffer challenge throughout the
series than many anticipated, scrapped back, and the Lakers - as
they have done all postseason, gave one more scare.
</P>
<P>
   With a 9-2 run, and seven points from Jalen Rose, the Pacers
tied the game at 103, capped by a Rose 3-pointer over Bryant. The
building went nearly silent.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Lakers, who have made a habit of comebacks, launched
their final surge.
</P>
<P>
   Horry hit a running jumper. Ron Harper picked off a Mark Jackson
pass. O'Neal swished a turnaround from the baseline, then blocked a
Rose layup. Bryant hit a turnaround 21-footer over Rose, and the
Lakers had a 109-103 lead with 3:28 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers briefly resorted to Hack-a-Shaq, but even as he
missed three of four free throws, the Lakers held the lead.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Croshere free throws provided the final chill, cutting
the lead to 110-109 with 1:32 to go, but Rice made a pair of free
throws with 1:16 left, then Bryant provided the final four points
from the line. After his final two, with 2.5 seconds left, Bryant
walked toward the bench, looked to the stands and pointed at his
ring finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``After those two free throws, I knew we had it,'' Bryant said.
``I didn't think there was a way mathematically for them to get
back in the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room afterward, it was all champagne and cigar
smoke. O'Neal tackled Fox in the center of the room. John Salley
kissed the Larry O'Brien Trophy. Teammates chased A.C. Green, not
yet doused with champagne.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just feels like I'm dreaming right now, like you guys
aren't even here,'' Bryant said. ``I swear, man. I must be trapped
in `the Matrix.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After trailing by as many as 12 points in the first half, the
Lakers looked anything but ready to claim a championship. But they
stayed within striking range throughout and Bryant hit a 3-pointer
with 2.3 seconds left to cut the deficit to 56-53 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The shot capped off a 10-3 Lakers run that started with a Rice
jumper and was aided by a pair of Pacer turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had 21 points by halftime, hitting 10 of 19 shots, and
Bryant, despite some shaky moments, scored 12 points on 4-of-12
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the change of venue, from Conseco Fieldhouse to
Staples, the Pacers kept their hot shooting touch, making 21 of 42
field-goal attempts in the half. Jalen Rose scored 12 points,
Reggie Miller added 11 and Dale Davis got nine points to go with
eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Early momentum belonged to the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   They struggled to hold off the Lakers in a seesaw first quarter
but ended the period with an answered prayer - Jackson's
buzzer-beating shot-put over Bryant, on an inbounds pass from just
past midcourt, gave Indiana a 26-24 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
