<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE5-VETERANS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERANS GET TASTE OF THE TOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ron Harper caught a glimpse of general manager
Mitch Kupchak in the chaos of the Los Angeles Lakers locker room
Monday night and stopped puffing on his cigar just long enough to
bellow, ``Hey Mitch, I quit! I quit!''
</P>
<P>
   Harper, obviously joking, couldn't stifle a laugh at his own
comment, but the serious question is, will Harper, now 36 years
old, and a handful of other Lakers, be there for a repeat run?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it's up to Phil and all them,'' Harper said. ``We've got
a deal. If Phil calls me and says he still needs me, I'll be back.
If he thinks he has all the guys to get it done without me, that's
just fine too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had 14 years in this league, and I wouldn't trade those
14 years for these bad knees for anything. I wouldn't trade these
last six, seven, eight years for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the excitement of the moment, but all three of the
Lakers' elder statesmen didn't sound ready for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets sweeter every time,'' said 36-year-old backup center
John Salley, who won a championship with his third team. ``It's
like wine, and I don't think there's any better feeling than
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward A.C. Green, 36, who started for most of the season but
deferred to Robert Horry for the important minutes of each game,
said he would be ready for training camp this fall, ``without a
doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to keep the good times rolling,'' Green said.
``We're going to savor this right now and for the next few weeks,
and pretty soon it will be time to get back to business.''
</P>
<P>
   The status of other Lakers is less certain. Trade rumors have
circulated around Glen Rice practically since his arrival in Los
Angeles, and Brian Shaw was signed primarily as a fill-in when Kobe
Bryant broke a bone in his hand in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said he would ``love to return, if the situation is
right,'' but was content to celebrate the first NBA title of his
10-year career. Fellow veterans Shaw (10 years) and Rick Fox (eight
years) also had their first taste of championship champagne Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still experiencing it right now,'' Fox said as he
videotaped the locker-room scene. ``There's a lot of good feelings
right now, everything from elation to just breaking down and
crying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
