<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9207 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     06-20 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CITY CAN SMILE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They staged a wild party Monday evening inside and
outside the Staples Center where thousands of people shrieked,
screamed, yelled, pleaded and cheered maniacally for the Los
Angeles Lakers in their climactic match against the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the first time in 12 years, the beleaguered city that
has endured earthquakes, civil riots, police scandals and the
disappearance of its NFL franchise during that bleak period,
finally can smile.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since October of 1988 when the Dodgers
shocked the sporting orbit by beating the Oakland A's in the World
Series, L.A. finally has something to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, finally, after bitter stretch of frustrations throughout
the 1990s when all the local professional entries---the Lakers,
Clippers, Dodgers, Angels, Kings, Mighty Ducks, the dearly departed
Rams and Raiders---took turns taking pratfalls, L.A. can rejoice
heartily over becoming Titletown, U.S.A again as it was so often in
the long ago past.
</P>
<P>
   And it can extend a stirring gratitude of thanks to the athletic
franchise, the Lakers, that has delivered the most world
championships to the Southern California basin across the seasons,
with the seventh one coming Monday night when Shaquille O'Neal and
his teammates managed to hold off the Pacers, 116-111, in a match
in which the reverberating crowd of 18,997 might have played as
vital a role in the outcome as O'Neal's dominate work.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening tipoff of a game in which the Pacers led
throughout until the tide turned dramatically in the late stages,
the L.A. fans, supposedly so blase and so cool, never stopped
rooting lustily for their heroes, who finally responded to their
pleadings with a 37-point fourth period eruption that caused the
entire city to erupt into a banner-waving, horn-blaring,
bonfire-setting paroxysm of ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to get it done when they showed on the scoreboard video
our fans outside the building cheering for us,'' Shaquille O' Neal
would say afterward. ``We just couldn't let them down.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't let them down, although a segment of their youthful
followers, alas, lost its senses afterwards, turning the Staples
Center area in downtown L.A. into a riot zone of burning police
cars and rampaging youths.
</P>
<P>
   It got so bad for a while that those still inside Staples
Centers were not allowed outside until police---many on
horseback---finally were able to bring the chaos under control.
</P>
<P>
   As desperately as the L.A. patrons wanted a championship to
savor, no one wanted one more than Shaquille O'Neal, the 7-foot-1,
340-pound Laker center who had achieved everything in his life
---movie appearances, rap songs, untold riches, staggering
fame---except a world title.
</P>
<P>
   And, after the final horn sounded, after he had poured in 41
points against the Packers including 13 in that decisive final
period, after he had assured himself of the MVP trophy for the NBA
finals after earning one for the regular season, Shaquille O'Neal
warmly embraced the team's other big star, Kobe Bryant, and began
weeping.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure a lot of people in L.A. did likewise at this poignant
sight in the wake of an emotional victory against a resilient
opponent that refused to fold despite the relentless attack of
O'Neal and ear-splitting noise of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, this Laker team that took six games to eliminate the
heavily underdog Pacers won't rate among the best in the
franchise's history.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Lakers did win 67 games during the regular season,
they struggled mightily throughout the playoffs, being extended to
the full five games against Sacramento, needing to dispense an
implausible fourth quarter, Game 7 rally to survive against
Portland and getting beaten by an embarrassing 33 points in Game 5
against the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   But what brought them to the pinnacle of their sport was that
they possessed the game's most overwhelming performer in O'Neal, a
21-year-old player of extraordinary athletic skills in Bryant, a
slew of resourceful, tough role players in Robert Horry, A.C.
Green, Rick Fox, Ron Harper and Brian Shaw, and a stubborn resolve
that was always displayed at their most critical moments.
</P>
<P>
   And they also reacted well to the guidance of Phil Jackson, who
won six championships with the Michael Jordan Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Jackson is one remarkable coach who was able
to turn the Lakers from being perennial underachievers---they were
swept the past two post-seasons by the Utah Jazz and San Antonio
Spurs---into being overachievers and was able to prove convincingly
that he doesn't need Michael Jordan to win world championships.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it helps to have a Shaquille O'Neal, who might not be
able to shoot free throws---he was a typical 3 for 12 at the foul
line Monday night---but does enough other good things to now rate
favorable comparisons with the Wilt Chamberlains and Kareem
Abdul-Jabbars and Bill Russells.
</P>
<P>
   But, as awesome as O'Neal was in Game 6---and he took over the
proceedings in that fourth period when he sank all six of his
shots, blocked three shots and grabbed four rebounds---the frenzied
crowd was just as awesome.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't surprising to see people like Mel Gibson, Jack
Nicholson, Helen Hunt, Dyan Cannon, Pamela Anderson, Dustin Hoffman
clapping their hands and rooting passionately for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But even an international corporate type like Rupert Murdoch was
seen getting excited, not to mention wealthy gentlemen like Steven
Spielberg and Michael Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
   This was a glorious night for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But even a more glorious one for L.A., which has been in a long
slump in so many areas but broke out if it in a flourish on the
broad shoulders of Shaquille O'Neal and his teammates, with
unrelenting encouragement from what may well have been the loudest
crowd in L.A. sports history.
</P>
<P>
   It's unfortunate that some individuals whose brains haven't
quite made it up to their heads decided afterward to tarnish this
bright L.A. moment with the kind of behavior commonplace among the
English soccer hooligans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
