<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-NBA-LAKERS-FANS-1stld     06-20 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-LAKERS-FANS-1stld-writethru-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNRULY FANS TARNISH CHAMPIONSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: updating with further police action) 
By JASON KANDEL 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; L.A. came back Monday night with the Lakers
winning the NBA championship, but delirium over victory soon turned
to anarchy as dozens of fans outside Staples Center rioted and set
vehicles on fire as police stood passive.
</P>
<P>
   Joyous scenes of fans dancing merrily around harmless bonfires
celebrating the end of a 12-year drought without a championship
turned ugly with a television equipment van looted and smashed and
an SUV battered and set afire by dozens of vandals without an LAPD
officer in sight. Two empty police cars were then attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Police moved in about 20 minutes after scenes of disturbance
were broadcast nationally and dispersed the heavily drinking crowd,
which continued to attack vehicles, set new fires and loot a
computer store in advance of the several hundred officers assigned
to crowd control.
</P>
<P>
   A tactical alert of police citywide was declared more than an
hour after the game ended.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said there were several minor injuries and the
destruction was contained to vehicles, but some officers at the
scene said they were embarrassed at being ordered to hold their
positions in the face of the disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying our best to disperse the crowd, but you don't go
up to 2,000 people with just 30 people,'' said LAPD spokesman Jason
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go out there, you'll just get attacked. This should be a
time for celebration in the city of L.A. The Lakers fans are
supposed to be celebrating, not committing crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   For a city long troubled by riots, economic collapse and
devastating earthquakes, the disturbance tarnished the joy shared
by the vast majority of Lakers fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers struggled to a sixth-game victory, 116-111, led by
triple MVP Shaquille O'Neal's 41 points and 21-year-old superstar
Kobe Bryant's on-court leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for L.A.! What a way to start a millennium!'' said
coach Phil Jackson, the Lakers' first-year coach who won two titles
as player, six as coach of the Chicago Bulls and now his first as a
Laker.
</P>
<P>
   Fans outside waved banners, threw water balloons and climbed up
light posts in celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is L.A. all day, all night!'' exulted Vic Camarillo, 19,
of San Fernando.
</P>
<P>
   His friend Jason Addcox predicted a dynasty: ``The Lakers are
the champs!''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment of victory inside Staples Center, shouts rang out,
purple and gold confetti filled the air, and people jumped up and
down and embraced each other throughout the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Jack Nicholson, the Lakers' No. 1 fan, reached out and
shook hands with Indiana coach Larry Bird for the valiant effort
his Pacers team put up.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers' legend Magic Johnson, a team vice president, hugged
O'Neal and Bryant, praising the players for their season-long drive
to a title that had eluded the city since 1988, when the Magic-led
Lakers and the Kirk Gibson-led Dodgers last won world titles for
the city.
</P>
<P>
   City officials declared Wednesday as Laker Day and said the
victory parade through downtown will start at 11a.m. with a
ceremony at the Department of Water and Power Building on Hope
Street and work its way along Figueroa Street to the Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Players in double-deck buses or other vehicles will start on
First Street, go down a ramp to Figueroa Street and down to Staples
Center at 11th Street and Figueroa, where the big celebration will
be held outside the arena in parking Lots 2 and 3, which can
accommodate 90,000 people. Jumbotrons also will be set up.
</P>
<P>
   Police added bike patrols, mounted units, and set up a command
post near Staples Center early Monday in case anything went awry,
but police officials said they didn't expect anything but
good-natured celebrations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Staples Center, as police clashed with dozens of unruly
fans outside, it was the fans that Lakers owner Jerry Buss and the
players themselves praised.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Buchanan, 27, from Los Angeles, clad in a Lakers jersey and
hat, was hugging everyone in sight outside the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lakers victory is the whole wide world to me,'' he said.
``I thought they would take the last game, but they didn't and it
broke my heart. But they mended it tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting 12 years for this,'' said Alredo
Tardencilla, 21, of Los Angeles. ``The Lakers are the best
</P>
<P>
   in the new millennium. We won and we are going to keep going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
