<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9210 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-20 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPARED TO WILT, SHAQ DOESN'T WILT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal is no Wilt Chamberlain, that much
was obvious Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   That beatific expression O'Neal wore after the Los Angeles
Lakers closed out Indiana 116-111 to win the NBA title, all those
tears mixing with his sweat as he hugged Kobe Bryant and Glen Rice
and his mother, Lucille Harrison? Wilt would have sooner broken
bread with Bill Russell than broken down in public like that.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain was too cool a cat to cry. After his Philadelphia
team turned back San Francisco in six games in 1967, the seven
footer to whom O'Neal long has been compared - sometimes
ignominiously - celebrated his first NBA title by keeping his
emotions corked even as the champagne flowed around him.
</P>
<P>
   To show joy or relief, the late Chamberlain explained years
later, would have been to reveal just how much he needed an NBA
championship to complete him. In his crowning moment Chamberlain
was too proud to acknowledge that falling short of the summit, as
he had his first seven years in the league, had made the climb
every year seem a little steeper, a little more back-breaking.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that Chamberlain sat stoically, alone with his
thoughts in the middle of his teammates' celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Not O'Neal. The center of attention wouldn't dream of shrinking
from the spotlight. He took the microphone upon being named the NBA
Finals Most Valuable Player - completing a divine double-double for
the 7-foot-1 center, who was a near-unanimous choice for league MVP
- and, with tears welling in his eyes, thanked Lakers first-year
coach Phil Jackson, expressed his love for the Lakers' fans and his
teammates and all but guaranteed plenty more titles from whence
this one came.
</P>
<P>
   That's O'Neal, who always has related more to Superman than
Clark Kent. The only thing muted about the man is his voice.
</P>
<P>
   It was only right that the Lakers' revelry revolved around
O'Neal. After all, he was their ringleader.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal averaged 29.7 points, 13.6 rebounds, 3.8 assists and 3.0
blocked shots during the regular season. On Monday he collected 13
of his 41 points in the fourth quarter and pulled down four of his
12 rebounds in that span to bring the Lakers back from an 84-79
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth quarter unfolded like one of the television scripts
of David E. Kelley, who was sitting courtside at Staples Center.
The drama was cliffhanger kind of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal gave the Lakers their first lead of the second half, at
91-90, on a layup off a flip pass from Bryant. He drew a foul from
Derrick McKey but flubbed the free throw (O'Neal was 3 for 12 from
the free-throw line and some will say that was a more fitting
reminder of Chamberlain than the black band the Lakers wore on
their jerseys in his honor).
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' lead was two points when O'Neal jammed home a Bryant
shot that fell short. Thirty seconds later he put back a Brian Shaw
miss to give the Lakers a seven-point lead (101-94) that seemed to
give his team a second wind.
</P>
<P>
   They'd need it to weather the perimeter shooting of the
persistent Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate how far O'Neal has come this year, it's
instructive to note he was at the center of the storm in 1998 when
Utah blew out the Lakers in the Western Conference finals and again
in 1999 when a squall in the form of the San Antonio Spurs doused
the Lakers' championship aspirations in the Western Conference
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake; O'Neal's fingerprints were all over the
guillotine that dropped on Del Harris early in last year's
lockout-shortened season. The verbose Harris wasted his breath
preaching defense to O'Neal who, for whatever reason (immaturity?
petulance?) wasn't sufficiently motivated to listen.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, 28, was a conspicuous no-show for the final team meeting
of the 1999 season, conduct most unbecoming of a team captain. His
absence, after a decidedly narcissistic series against the Spurs
(he mustered only two assists in four games), precluded the air
from being cleared along with the players' lockers.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Lakers were O'Neal's team, all right, and for that the
rest of the West breathed a little easier. As former standout
center Bill Walton, now a television commentator, noted, ``A year
ago the Lakers represented all that was wrong with pro sports.''
And this year? ``They represent everything that is right,'' Walton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson generally is credited with the makeover.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as Chamberlain himself once noted, the coach isn't the
one on the floor fighting for rebounds and rising to block shots.
O'Neal deserves his due for remaking himself into the player that
Jackson (and Harris before him) figured he could be and the rest of
the league feared he one day might become.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999-2000 Lakers were O'Neal's team, all right, and this
time they were in good hands. His 30.3-point average in the
playoffs carried the team on the court and his playfulness off it
kept the Lakers' locker room from becoming as suffocating as a
sauna.
</P>
<P>
   We'd say there is a movie of O'Neal's life waiting to happen,
but it already has been made. That would be ``Big'' with Tom Hanks
playing the big kid that O'Neal in real life is.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, O'Neal's boyishness was what you noticed, not his
determination to be The Boss. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq has become the greatest defensive force in basketball,''
said Walton, who can be stingy with his verbal bouquets. ``He has
become the best passing center in basketball. He's got newfound
levels of toughness but also newfound levels of patience and
tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to this year, you would never have a conversation about
who the greatest center was,'' Walton added. ``It would have begun
and ended with Wilt Chamberlain. After this season, you've got to
start talking about Shaquille O'Neal in the same class.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight months after Chamberlain died, O'Neal honored him in the
most felicitous way imaginable. Hollywood couldn't have scripted it
any better. In winning his first NBA title in his eighth season,
same as Chamberlain, O'Neal earned his best nickname yet. He
henceforth shall be called, ``The Big Dipper Deux.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
