<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE3-KOBE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE WINNING TITLES COULD BECOME HABIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kobe Bryant sat on a table in the trainer's room
Monday after the Los Angeles Lakers' 116-111 victory over Indiana
to capture the 200 NBA championship. Dripping with champagne and
sweat, his beautiful fiancee to his left and Magic Johnson to his
right, Bryant looked very much like a young man with the world at
his fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   But inside, he was still just a typical 21-year old kid trying
to figure out what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what I felt,'' Bryant said as he described the
first moments of being a champion. ``When I got up to the podium I
looked at (Phil Jackson) and said, `OK, what do we do now? Where do
we go next? I don't know what to do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant might be a bit unsure how to act now, but chances are
good he'll have plenty of opportunities to get it straight over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the start,'' Bryant said. ``It depends on how
long we stay together, but right now we're king of the hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson can relate. After carrying the Lakers to the NBA title
in 1980, someone asked the then 20-year old rookie how many more he
hoped to win before retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, without hesitating, smiled and said, ``I don't know,
20.''
</P>
<P>
   Supreme confidence notwithstanding, Magic fell considerably
short of his goal, winning five over his brilliant career.
</P>
<P>
   Time ran out on Johnson, but it could be on the side of another
brash, young Lakers' guard. Bryant, who had 26 points Monday, might
not get 20 rings, but he's clearly on pace to match, even surpass,
the greats of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see a (big) run for him,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Russell is the league standard, winning 11 titles after
getting his first when he was 23, two years older than the 21-year
old Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Like Johnson, Russell captured a championship as a rookie, and
both won NCAA titles in college the year before that.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan won six titles, but he was 28 when the Bulls won
their first championship, making it impossible to seriously
consider catching Russell. Jordan also hurt himself by sitting out
nearly two years after retiring in 1993 to play baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant might want to be like Mike, but he's never said anything
about home runs and split-fingered fastballs. Besides, he's already
thinking about getting rings for more than just his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got toes, too,'' he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Of the other true legends of the game, Bryant compares
favorably.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, who got his first with Milwaukee in 1971,
finished with six titles and Larry Bird had three, the first coming
at 24. Wilt Chamberlain won two titles.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of factors working in Bryant's favor. He's got
youth, scintillating talent and enough confidence to carry out his
plan, which he considers his destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant also has Shaquille O'Neal, likely for the next six or
seven years, an owner and team president determined to maintain
championship-level teams and the ideal coach to lead them.
</P>
<P>
   The trifecta of Jerry Buss, Jerry West and Phil Jackson pretty
much insures the Lakers will have the leadership and personnel to
stay competitive, and there's no team in the league with the
one-two punch of O'Neal and Bryant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 0233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
