<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALAMA, MARINERS ABSORB A RAYS RAZING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As homecomings go, it wasn't as bad as the time Bluto
and the Delta boys ravaged Faber College, but it was right up
there.
</P>
<P>
   After rising to a season-best eight games above .500 with their
best road trip of the season, the Mariners returned to Seattle
Monday night and opened a 10-game homestand with an 10-3 loss to
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays in Safeco Field. Starter John Halama
didn't get out of the fifth inning, Seattle stranded 11 baserunners
and Mariners pitchers walked five batters, hit another and allowed
a run in every inning but the second, third and ninth.
</P>
<P>
   So it was one of those nights for the Mariners, who had been
playing well. Monday night marked the first time Seattle allowed 10
runs in a game since the infamous Jose Mesa-John Mabry game against
Tampa Bay at the end of May. Halama and the bullpen kept Mabry off
the mound but accomplished little else.
</P>
<P>
   Halama was a most pleasant surprise for the Mariners when he won
his first six decisions, including an 87-pitch shutout over the
Twins last month. He has struggled in recent weeks though, losing
his past three decisions. He is 0-3 with a 7.71 ERA in four starts
this month. He hasn't made it through the sixth inning in his past
three starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's struggled the last few times out and we have to figure
out how to get him straightened out,'' manager Lou Piniella said.
``You can talk to the pitching coach about his mechanics, all I
know is the last few times out he hasn't been as sharp as he was
earlier in the year and we need to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's mental. He's getting behind hitters and not
locating his pitches well. And Johnny is not the type of pitcher
who can afford to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama struggled from the opening batter, allowing a double to
center fielder Randy Winn to open the game. Winn wound up scoring
to give Tampa Bay a 1-0 lead and its first of five runs against the
left-hander. Halama, who depends on his control to be effective,
allowed five runs on seven hits and walked three batters in
four-plus innings. He threw 91 pitches, 54 for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You fall behind and put guys on base and then you have to make
better pitches,'' Halama said. ``I haven't jumped ahead of guys
like I did before and I have to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you want me to say about it? It just hasn't been going
my way. Before, it was. Now it isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle came back with a run in the second and another in the
third on Alex Rodriguez's 20th home run to take a brief 2-1 lead.
It was all Tampa Bay after that. The Devil Rays scored three in the
fourth inning and two more in the fifth while chasing Halama.
</P>
<P>
   Frankie Rodriguez took over from Halama and was unable to stop
the scoring. He did slow it somewhat, allowing one run the fifth,
one in the sixth and another in the seventh. Robert Ramsay relieved
him in the eighth inning and quickly allowed two runs on Fred
McGriff's home run to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay is in last place in the American League East but the
Devil Rays have been pitching well recently. They entered June
ranked 29th in ERA but have had the league's lowest ERA this month.
Starter Albie Lopez, who is the only American League pitcher with a
complete game and a save this season, continued the strong showing.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez allowed six hits and walked four batters, but held the
Mariners to two runs _ one earned _ in six innings. Seattle
stranded two runners in the first, two in the second, two in the
third and two in the sixth against Lopez, then stranded three in
the seventh against Tampa Bay's bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We left a lot of people out there,'' Piniella said. ``We had
some chances early and didn't capitalize. And even late, we had
some chances. But the story tonight was they hit the ball well and
we didn't pitch well.''
</P>
<P>
   With the loss and Oakland's win, the Mariners dropped two games
behind the AL West-leading Athletics, the farthest they've been out
of first this season.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
