<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9213 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     06-20 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ SHOWS HIS SENSITIVE SIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ His arms opened wide as Kobe Bryant came rushing
toward him, a cacophany of cheers and screams and music from the
Staples Center surrounding him in this wildly public yet deeply
intimate moment.
</P>
<P>
   As Bryant landed in his large limbs and thrust an arm into the
air, a resounding, defiant exclamation point on the end of a team's
and a city's 12-year pro title drought, Shaquille O'Neal dug his
chin into the chest of Bryant and cried like a newborn.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Champion? Yes, very much so after the Los Angeles
Lakers' 116-111 Game 6 win over Indiana gave them the 2000 NBA
title. But he is also The Big Teardrop.
</P>
<P>
   When you are 7-1 and 315, people don't wonder whether or not a
sensitive heart beats inside, whether he yearns for something. A
man big enough to seemingly take whatever he wants doesn't
encourage much empathy. As it was once said about another great
Lakers center, Wilt Chamberlain, no one roots for Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal has yearned for this. Since he came into the league
as its biggest prodigy ever, people have undercut whatever personal
success he had by noting the lack of his team's success, with an
emphasis on the way he and his teams have been swept aside. Whether
or not the critiques were fair, they hurt.
</P>
<P>
   So the tears were a release. It's actually a wonder that O'Neal
was as composed as he was after the tears on the court and the wild
champagne celebration in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've held my emotions for 11 years now, three years in college
and eight in the pros,'' said O'Neal. ``I always wanted to win.
They (the tears) just came up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a great moment. I watched Magic Johnson and Larry
Bird celebrate their titles as a kid. I'm just happy, very happy.
I'm happy for Kobe, for my teammates, Phil (Jackson), and the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   And the city is happy for Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of reasons why the Lakers won the title Monday.
Credit owner Jerry Buss for providing the wherewithall, and Jerry
West for his foresight to obtain Shaq and Kobe, and Kobe for being
the superb team player he has become, and Jackson for finding a way
to turn a team with embarrassing playoff exits the last three years
into a champion.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal carried this team. He never flinched at the double
teams and triple teams and the intentional fouls, or let his free
throw Kryptonite overcome him.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter Monday, while his teammates were
floundering in the face of inspired and smart play by the Pacers --
Larry Bird shouldn't be allowed to retire after just three seasons
-- O'Neal scored more than half (15) of the Lakers' 29 points. If
he doesn't stay strong, the Pacers extend their lead just like they
did in Game 5, and maybe we're preparing for Game 7 instead of a
parade.
</P>
<P>
   In the final quarter, when the Lakers finally pulled away for
the first time since the end of the first quarter, he was perfect
everywhere except the free throw line -- six field goals in as many
shots, four rebounds, three blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the quarter, as three Pacers surrounded him, O'Neal
grabbed a rebound, spun away and back and dropped a double pump
eight-footer into the basket. Next possession, he dunks off a
beautiful Bryant pass.
</P>
<P>
   Two trips later, he soars from a steep angle to take a Brian
Shaw pass off the glass to score and give the Lakers the lead and
fill the Pacers with doubt.
</P>
<P>
   He would score seven more points, but the rest of his big plays
were defensive -- stepping up to challenge a Mark Jackson shot from
the baseeline, and the next trip down coming out on Jalen Rose, who
was absolutely otherworldly in this game and the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the ugliest 41 points I ever had,'' said O'Neal. ``We
took the game to them in the fourth quarter. We made a couple of
stops.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq was very dominant,'' said Bird, the Celtic great who
imbued the Pacers with a lot of the same characterists his Boston
teams had. ``We had problems with him most of the series. We used
Dale Davis, we used Rik Smits. He was just too much for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing is never easy to take. We're all hurt by it. But the
Lakers were a better team. We played as well as we could the first
three quarters. They just had too much going down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever personal joy O'Neal felt, he shared it with everyone
near him. The sight of he and Bryant together was counterpoint to
the supposed rift between them in previous years. When asked about
his contributions Monday, he made a point to single out all of the
big shots and big plays from his teammates in the fourth quarter --
three-pointers by Derek Fisher, Robert Horry and Rick Fox.
</P>
<P>
   He saved his kindest words for Jackson, who won six titles with
Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great motivator,'' he said. ``I think we needed Phil
because of his resume. He was a no-nonsense coach. He wouldn't
accept any of the nonsense that we had in the past, when guys would
goof in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the kind of discipline I was used to, from my father,
from (former LSU coach) Dale Brown. It was what we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaq Monday got what he needed -- a title to go with his big
shoulders, his big heart, and his Big Tears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 0243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
