<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9214 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-20 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS SHOW SOMETHING TO ADMIRE IN A CHAMPION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As much as nobody likes Goliath, nobody loves
dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   But if it is possible to like, just a little bit, a big-market
champion with a mammoth in the middle and a future that glistens,
the 2000 Los Angeles Lakers just might pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, if sports fans can accept pleasantly the New York Yankees
as baseball champions, the Lakers at least deserve the air kiss
popular in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   In beating the Indiana Pacers, 116-111, Monday night for the NBA
championship, they outsmarted and outworked a team that had been
increasing its edge in both departments as the series went along.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Lakers had Shaquille O'Neal, but he scored just one
point in the final 3:28 when the game was in the balance. The
Lakers got scores on 17 of their final 22 possessions by weaving
together scoring from six different players and multiple key stops
from a team defense that had been mostly missing for the past three
games.
</P>
<P>
   Team ball at its finest _ beating a good team playing its best
and a legendary sports figure coaching his last.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's L.A. It's easier to like gravel underwear than L.A.
And Phil Jackson? The man wins six championships with the game's
greatest player, then wins a seventh with the next greatest player.
Do it in Vancouver, Phil.
</P>
<P>
   But those are superficial matters, having nothing to do with the
basketball at hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were superb at times, but often demonstrated a
vulnerability, not only this game, but in this series and
throughout the season, leaving open the possibility that a 67-win
team could be had at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the teams of the Chicago Bulls dynasty, or even of the
two championship teams in Detroit, the Lakers were youngish,
mistake-prone and just too rubbery to be ranked with the greats.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't play the greats. They played in the NBA of 2000.
They were good enough to overcome everyone as well as their own
weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   As O'Neal demonstrated in the moments after the title was won,
they were also endearingly human. As the big man wandered from hug
to hug on the floor of the party-time Staples Center, his face was
locked in teary immobility.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal has been packing around his potential for most of his 28
years, never having had a championship as a collegian or a pro.
Finally, the burden was lifted, making for considerable eye
moisture.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, a composed O'Neal explained himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've held my emotions for about 11 years now,'' he said.
``Three in college and eight here. I've always wanted to win a
championship. It just came out.''
</P>
<P>
   Given his embarrassments of previous seasons, the big man was
entitled. A year ago, the Lakers were swept out of the playoffs by
San Antonio. Two years ago, they were given the O-fer by Utah. And
in the 1995 Finals, O'Neal's coming out party as a pro when he
played in Orlando, he was shut out by the Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the bad days. The good days started Monday night when
O'Neal helped the franchise reconnect with its rich history.
</P>
<P>
   Including its time in Minneapolis, the Lakers have been in 25
Finals. Monday night was the 12th championship, but the first since
1988 _ the fifth title during the time of Magic Johnson, when the
Lakers were Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   After coach Pat Riley left in 1990 and Johnson retired in 1991,
Showtime was dead and a royal franchise had fallen. The Lakers went
through six coaches in the next nine years _ producing just 23
playoff-game victories, compared to the maximum 15 this season _
before connecting the best player with the best coach, Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The triumph was plain even to their chief tormentor over the
past two weeks, Indiana's Reggie Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil came here and really gave Shaq a boost of confidence,''
said Miller, who scored 25 points. ``From day one, when Phil sat
down and told him whose team it really was _ I know there was some
tension between him and Kobe Bryant _ everything ran through Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe's a great complementary player. That's no shame on Kobe.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Shaq is Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   He was all that Monday night, scoring 41 points to give him a
38-point average for the series, fourth-highest in Finals history.
Despite his free-throw troubles and a massive swarm of defenders,
O'Neal was the pillar when the rest of the Lakers shook from the
pressure of doing the expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's improved immensely,'' said Larry Bird, the outgoing
Pacers coach. ``He's just so dominating that they have an
opportunity to do something great here for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The point was brought home at the podium afterward. After team
owner Dr. Jerry Buss finished answering questions, O'Neal sat down
next to him.
</P>
<P>
   Beaming, and referring to his contract, O'Neal looked at his
boss and said, ``Extension ... extension.''
</P>
<P>
   Buss smiled back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything you want, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a pleasant prospect for non-Lakers fans. But for one night
anyway, it was possible for almost anyone to be a Lakers admirer
because they beat a good team in a good team way, and did it with
team people.
</P>
<P>
   In a sport that has often lost its identity as a team game, a
sticky night in Southern California turned refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
