<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9215 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-FINALS-SPI &LR;      06-20 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN TO GLORY: SHAQ REIGNS, TEARS FLOW AS LAKERS TRIUMPH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In Hollywood, where just about everything is done
on a large scale, they finally figured out how to make the Big Man
cry.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's biggest trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal, overcome with
emotion _ as opposed to anything the Indiana Pacers threw at him _
fought back tears Monday night after leading his team to a 116-111
Game 6 victory that wrapped up the NBA Finals in Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the 7-foot-1, 315-pound O'Neal allowed tears that
could create puddles to roll down his face as he hugged teammates
and accepted the series MVP trophy.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first title for O'Neal, and the first championship
for the Lakers since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an emotional game, and the ugliest 41 points I've ever
had,'' said O'Neal, who added 12 rebounds and four blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles won the best-of-seven series 4-2, completing a
coronation that many had counted on since the Lakers took a 3-1
series lead. Even though the Pacers claimed all week they were
playing a few Game 7s, O'Neal and Lakers didn't want any part of
one.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers used an explosive fourth quarter, outscoring the
Pacers 37-27, to ignite a celebration in the streets of Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The victory preserved Lakers coach Phil Jackson's record in Game
6 of the Finals. Dating back to his six championships with the
Chicago Bulls, Jackson's teams had never faced a Game 7 in the
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is now 6-0 in those situations after winning his seventh
championship as coach, in addition to a ring in 1973 as a member of
the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed Phil to do it,'' said O'Neal, who earlier called
Jackson the league's ``real'' Coach of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Several Lakers finally stepped up to help O'Neal down the
stretch. Kobe Bryant, who finished with 26 points despite 8-for-27
shooting, made four free throws in the final 13 seconds to seal the
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just determination,'' Bryant said. ``And P.J. (Phil
Jackson) did an excellent job. Shaq was marvelous and out bench was
great. We just pulled it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana played well enough to win, but fell apart in crucial
moments. Despite shooting 46 percent and having five players reach
double figures in scoring, the Pacers gave up 21 points off just
nine turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did an excellent job for three quarters,'' said Pacers
coach Larry Bird, whose three-year coaching career ended with the
loss. ``When it came to the end of the game, we couldn't get the
stops that we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose led Indiana with 29 points and Reggie Miller added
25, but neither player scored a significant field goal in the final
three minutes. Rose's jumper with 1.9 seconds left was too little,
too late. After erasing a seven-point deficit in the fourth
quarter, the Pacers trailed 112-109 when Miller missed a chance to
tie the game, attempting a 30-foot 3-pointer that bounced off the
back iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give L.A. credit,'' Miller said. ``Every time we
made a run, they found a way to get back into the ballgame. They
always found an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for questioning whether the Lakers had a killer
instinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a way to start a millennium,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles was clinging to a 110-109 advantage when Glen Rice
hit a pair of free throws with 1:16 left.
</P>
<P>
   Down 110-103 with 2:20 remaining, the Pacers fouled O'Neal every
time he touched the ball. The strategy worked. O'Neal missed three
of four free throws while the Pacers scored six straight points.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers forward Robert Horry broke a 103-103 tie, hitting a
hanging floater in the lane. O'Neal followed with a fadeaway bank
shot before Bryant's 20-foot jumper demoralized the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana missed four straight shots during the Lakers' run.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, who had led for nearly three quarters, found
themselves down 97-92 with seven minutes left in the game. Horry's
3-pointer capped an 11-2 run that revived the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Until that surge, the Lakers' offense consisted mostly of O'Neal
staking out deep post position, converting layups and dunks, and
getting fouled in the process.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal missed several free throws that would have put the Lakers
ahead. It wasn't until he finally scored on a running hook shot
with 8:58 left that the Lakers went in front. O'Neal's basket put
the Lakers ahead 91-90 _ their first lead since a 24-23 edge in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were on target from beyond the arc. Los Angeles made
10 of 17 3-pointers _ six in the fourth quarter. Indiana made 12 of
25 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well enough to win,'' said Indiana's Dale Davis, who
had 20 points and 14 rebounds. ``We didn't execute down the stretch
like we normally do. We made some mental mistakes, we got some bad
breaks and the ball bounced their way.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the Pacers exorcised the shooting demons they
encountered in four previous visits to Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Every Pacer except center Rik Smits (1-for-7) played with a
sharp shooting eye in the first half. Indiana took mostly jump
shots and made 50 percent of them in the first two quarters.
</P>
<P>
   But Indiana could not maintain _ a problem the Pacers endured
throughout the series.
</P>
<P>
   In a tale of two halves, the Pacers began to wither while O'Neal
stayed strong, scoring 13 of his 20 second-half points in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who has several nicknames, all of which carry the prefix
``Big,'' was just that in closing out the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Champion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
