<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE1-BUSS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNER BUSS GLAD HE SPLURGED TO BRING JACKSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Lakers owner Jerry Buss was about to
leave the postgame press conference when center Shaquille O'Neal,
next up for the media, sat down at the podium.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had one word for Buss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extension,'' O'Neal said. ``Extension.''
</P>
<P>
   Buss, who hadn't been in this celebratory situation for 12
years, was in no mood to quibble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you want, baby,'' Buss said. ``Whatever you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Buss was in a giving mood Monday, after the Lakers had defeated
the Indiana Pacers 116-111 to capture the NBA title in six games.
</P>
<P>
   He had set the stage for the championship a year ago, when he
finally went against his history and shelled out a hefty salary for
Phil Jackson to coach the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt confident that it would be a big improvement,'' Buss
said. ``But to think that he could take us all the way to the
championship - I couldn't even imagine that.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing left to the imagination by the time Game 6 had
come to an end. The Lakers had their 12th title in franchise
history, Buss his sixth as owner of the Lakers and Jackson his
seventh overall - six coming while leading the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Buss said he doubted anyone else could have pulled off this
championship but Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some great coaches, but I think this took a very
special combination of talents,'' Buss said. ``You know, Pat Riley,
a long time ago, was able to knit together a bunch of superstars
and make them into a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil has been able to do that with this team. And at least in
my mind, I'd have to doubt that anyone else could have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   The team, of course, was led by O'Neal, both the MVP of the
regular season and the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's noticed this fantastic improvement,'' Buss said.
``The way he passes, the fact that he can shoot so much better.
He's developed a lot of shots that I hadn't seen until this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I think it's a question of confidence. He just seems
to feel that he is the best player, and he set out to demonstrate
it and certainly did so, I think, to everyone's satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   In Buss' office window overlooking the court at the team's new
practice facility in El Segundo, there are five NBA championship
trophies looking down. Every day at practice, the Lakers have been
able to look up and see what their goal looked like.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite a three-point lead and the ball with 5.4 seconds to
play, Buss said he still wasn't confident he'd add a sixth trophy
to his window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relax?'' he said. ``Well, at 5.4 seconds, I was still nervous.
But they gave Kobe (Bryant) three seconds to dribble (before
fouling), and I figured that was the end of the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
