<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON'S SPOT IN HISTORY? NOT NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds details) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even as he closed within one victory of the
championship, coach Phil Jackson said he was too focused on the
present to think about his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   The championship the Los Angeles Lakers won Monday night made
Jackson the second coach ever to win championships with two teams,
joining Alex Hannum.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked whether he would put himself in a class with
legends such as Red Auerbach, Jackson declined the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that's not important,'' he said. ``To look at it when
you're in the midst of something, you do what you have to do. When
you retire 10, 15 years down the road - God willing, you're still
alive - you think about those things at a later date.''
</P>
<P>
   Missing: The Lakers were dismissive of a news report Monday that
executive vice president Jerry West would retire at season's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the annual `Jerry West is going to retire' rumor,''
Lakers spokesman John Black said. ``And that's all it is.''
</P>
<P>
   West was unavailable for comment and did not attend Monday
night's game.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he did not attend a single game, home or away, in the
last two playoff series. West has described watching the games as
too stressful and said he prefers to avoid the media swarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry's too nervous,'' Lakers owner Jerry Buss said. ``He has
the hyper-anxiety problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Three more years: As Buss addressed the media, Shaquille O'Neal
playfully interrupted - ``Extension. Extension.'' - referring to
the contract extension he's eligible for this offseason.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, under contract through 2003, can sign for up to three
more years, for a maximum total of $83.5 million. Lakers sources
say it's unlikely they will pay the max, because it would trigger
the NBA's new luxury tax, which Buss has vowed not to pay.
</P>
<P>
   But amidst Monday's championship celebration, Buss could only
say to O'Neal, ``Whatever you want, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Rewarded: Three years ago, Rick Fox turned down millions more
elsewhere to sign a short-term deal with the Lakers, in hopes of
reaching a night like Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, man, the money isn't even an issue right now. You
know, you look at it, I'd play for free to have this feeling,'' Fox
said. ``We've had so many chances to make it happen this year, and
we've fallen on our faces. But the bottom line is we're still
champions, and we got it done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just settling in,'' he said of the feeling. ``But I
thought of my dad, and I ran to him. I thought of all the years of
trying to get to this point and the joy, then tears, and joy, then
tears, and champagne in the nose. And then a takedown by Shaquille
(who tackled him in the locker room). There's a lot of things I'm
feeling right now, and I'm just enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubious honor: As it turns out, the Lakers set an NBA record
with Friday's Game 5 loss at Indiana. The defeat was their sixth in
an elimination game - the most ever for a single postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's great,'' Jackson said sarcastically, offering two
thumbs up and a grin. ``It doesn't say a thing. It says something
about this team a little bit, but that's not the story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
