<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 03:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9218 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-REW     06-20 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS WIN NBA CHAMPIONSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One more sputter for suspense. One more pause for
dramatic effect. One more blistering, dazzling, stubborn charge up
the hill, one big grasp for the crown.
</P>
<P>
   One more banner for the rafters.
</P>
<P>
   One long drought ended, wiped out by a cloudburst of confetti
and a downpour of champagne.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers, title-less since Showtime faded out more
than a decade ago, are NBA champions once more.
</P>
<P>
   Their 116-111 victory over the Indiana Pacers on Monday night
clinched the Finals, four games to two, and set off a thunderous
celebration on the Staples Center floor, with 18,997 of the Lakers
faithful joining in.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, brought together four years
ago to bring about this renewal, embraced at midcourt after the
final buzzer - the Lakers having finally restored the glory that
has lain dormant since the last title in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea,'' said Bryant, ``that champagne burned so much
when it gets in your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old star quickly got used to the feeling. Everything
else he felt, he could hardly describe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't, man. I just feel so numb,'' said Bryant, his fiance,
Vanessa Laine, at his side, and his mother, Pam, standing nearby.
``I just feel numb. I put the championship T-shirt on, put the hat
on, celebrated with my family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory will bring a seventh championship banner to Staples
Center. It comes in just the first season for coach Phil Jackson,
who brought the magic touch and the steady hand to L.A. that won
him six titles with the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for L.A.!'' Jackson shouted to the packed house as
players passed around the Lawrence O'Brien Trophy. ``What a way to
start the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Jackson's seventh title in nine years, and first without
Michael Jordan, cementing his status as the era's greatest coach.
But it's the first title for his young proteges, Bryant and O'Neal,
who figure to add several more before they are through here.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson got the pair of superstars to work together, producing a
67-win season and now the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very proud of our team for holding up under a lot of
pressure, a lot of criticism,'' Jackson said. ``Their confidence
oozed out. They remained confident. They took a lot of hits, had
resiliency and kept coming back. For that part, I was grateful for
these guys. The spirit was just wonderful with this team.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, whose 41 points, 12 rebounds and four blocked shots led
the Lakers on Monday, was the unanimous choice for Finals MVP,
adding the trophy to his regular-season and All-Star Game MVP
awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like about Phil when he was coaching for the Bulls it's
not what he did with Michael and Scottie (Pippen), but how he got
the other guys to play,'' O'Neal said. ``When he came here he put
it down on a piece of paper. He said this is how it's gonna go,
this is what were gonna do. And he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant scored 26 points - including the final four - in the
victory, but it took contributions all the way down the bench to
finish the championship run: 16 points from Glen Rice, the
sometimes-disenchanted third wheel; a combined 21 points from
Robert Horry, Rick Fox and Derek Fisher, all former starters who
willingly went to the bench; six points from Ron Harper, a
three-time champion in Chicago; and six from A.C. Green, the lone
link to the Showtime era, who was here for the last celebration a
dozen years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through ups and downs, but the most important thing is
that we believed in one another,'' said Bryant, ``and we believed
in the system. We believed in sitting in a room and meditating and
Phil lighting incense in the room and doing all kinds of crazy
stuff. But we believed in it and we believed in one another and
this championship shows it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rice, ``We learned a lot. We've been able to grow together.
... I mean, we really worked hard, we fought together and to be
able to raise that trophy up out there is an unbelievable
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe, too, that they would pull it off after so many
missed chances.
</P>
<P>
   It took multiple tries to win every round of the playoffs. But
the fits and starts and the hiccups only intensified the suspense,
added to the anticipation and made the crowning moment that much
sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 appropriately symbolized the entire run. An early
12-point deficit. Trailing continuously until the fourth quarter. A
lead, then a tie. Then another lead. And finally, the fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   The imperfect championship game, for the imperfect championship
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to happen that way,'' Fisher said, ``because if it
happens too easy, you don't appreciate it, and I think now we
respect that team, we respect the fact that in order to win a
championship, you have to keep working hard all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers lost every quarter and trailed continuously until the
fourth. But O'Neal's hook off the glass with 9:02 left gave the
Lakers a 91-90 lead and the run for the rings was on.
</P>
<P>
   Fox followed with a 3-pointer over Austin Croshere, Staples
Center erupted, and Fox bumped chests with Rice at the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Then an Horry 3-pointer, a pair of O'Neal putback jams, and the
Lakers led 101-94. But the Pacers, who provided a stiffer challenge
throughout the series than many anticipated, scrapped back. Jalen
Rose scored seven quick points, capped by a 3-pointer over Bryant,
and the Pacers tied the game at 103. The building went nearly
silent.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Lakers, who have made a habit of comebacks, launched
their final surge, taking a a 109-103 lead with 3:28 left. A pair
of Austin Croshere free throws provided the final chill, cutting
the lead to 110-109 with 1:32 to go, but Rice made a pair of free
throws with 1:16 left, then Bryant provided the final four points
from the line.
</P>
<P>
   After his final two, with 2.5 seconds left, Bryant walked toward
the bench, looked to the stands and pointed at his ring finger.
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room afterward, it was all champagne and cigar
smoke. O'Neal tackled Fox in the center of the room. John Salley
kissed the O'Brien Trophy. Teammates chased Green, not yet doused
with champagne.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just feels like I'm dreaming right now, like you guys
aren't even here,'' Bryant said. ``I swear, man. I must be trapped
in `the Matrix.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
