<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9360 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0621-CO     06-20 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0621-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Squirrel dynamics featuring Fats and Sheena
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ A feisty new squirrel has moved into my yard
_ and she's a she. At least I'm pretty sure. We haven't talked, nor
have I done any impertinent snooping but I've named her ``Sheena,
Queena Madison Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheena isn't much to look at. Her tail isn't the bushiest, and
she has that most unattractive Rodentia overbite, but what she
lacks in beauty, she makes up for in dynamics. In short order, she
has taken over. Even ``Madison Fats,'' the dominant male of the
side yard gets all silly acting now when Sheena comes shimmying
across the mulch.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, when Sheena first showed up, Fats tried chasing her
away from his sunflower seed saucer. Apparently shocked by his
ungentlemanly behavior, Sheena backed off a couple of feet, sat up
on her haunches, and gave poor old Fats what for. Naturally, I
couldn't tell what she was calling him in squirrel chatter, but it
worked. Fats doesn't mess with Sheena any more _ hardly.
</P>
<P>
   The other afternoon as I watched from the kitchen window, Sheena
zoomed down the side of the big pine and skidded to a rather
ungraceful halt right at the rim of the saucer where Fats was
enjoying a lengthy petit dejeuner. He dropped a fat seed he'd been
turning over in his paws and stared at the pushy young lady who'd
had the nerve to come between him and his chow.
</P>
<P>
   Fats feinted a move toward her. Sheena stared at him, but didn't
flinch. Instead, she stuck her head out as far as it would go on
her furry neck and told him a thing or two. Now it was Fats's turn
to stare. What with their beady little eyes and all, it was tough
to tell who blinked first.
</P>
<P>
   Sheena quickly tired of this inactivity and moved on. Fats and I
watched as she headed for the new bird feeder that hangs from a
tree limb, six feet from the ground and three feet from the trunk.
We weren't worried because neither Fats nor any member of his clan
had been able to master this huge, three-barreled, squirrel-proof
beauty. Sheena gave it a once-over from the ground, scooted up the
tree, ran out on the limb, and leaped onto the roof, hind paws
scratching for purchase, fingers wrapped around the chain.
</P>
<P>
   One foot at a time, she tried grabbing onto something, anything,
but there was nothing. She skidded first one way and then another,
arching her body to shift the weight so she could ride out the
feeder's wild gyrations. Fats and I gawked.
</P>
<P>
   Shewas that when it comes to off-road driving, one should never
expect to exceed 5 mph.
</P>
<P>
   And we wondered why all those SUVs seem to go belly up when
trying to negotiate bad on-road weather conditions at 70 mph. ``You
will want to left-foot brake. You will also want to be very gentle
on both the brake and the accelerator pedal. Never do anything
abruptly or unexpectedly.''
</P>
<P>
   With the basics tucked neatly in mind, it was time to go. We
slowly meandered our way among the West Virginia hardwoods and
conifers, up and down the hills. And then we got to the edge. There
I sat with the Discovery's front bumper extended over heaven only
knew what. Green instructed me to set the hill descent control, a
clever little feature that maintains an almost crawl mode in the
vehicle. ``Let's go, and whatever you do, don't touch the brakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't touch the brake? The ground is disappearing below me as
I'm about to dive off into an abyss, and she is telling me not to
touch the brake. But you have to trust your instructor, there to
take care of you and the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   So in spite of what every muscle in my body wanted to do, I
didn't touch the brake. Once the vehicle pivoted over the edge, I
could at least see where we were headed and it wasn't quite so bad.
It looked like we were driving down a muddy version of an Olympic
ski jump.
</P>
<P>
   Physics told me Green was right. When you touch the brake, you
transfer weight to the front of the vehicle. With the Discovery
already in what seemed like a vertical drop, the last thing you
wanted to do was to take weight off the tail. Gravity might take
over, and we would tumble down the hill.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we splashed through the stream at the bottom. Anything
else was going to be easy. It's an adrenaline rush at 4 mph.
</P>
<P>
   My reward for a job well done was to move to the larger Range
Rover.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really want me to drive this $70,000 vehicle through that
river?''
</P>
<P>
   That was exactly what I was being instructed to do. Water was up
to the middle of the grill, but there was not a drop on my green
waders or the carpet of the Range Rover.
</P>
<P>
   If I had any misconception of a cushier course for the cushier
upscale Range Rover, those notions were quickly erased. It was
pretty much the second chorus of the same song, except for that
ski-jumplike decline.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
