<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9364 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-SCHOOLPRAYER-C     06-20 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-SCHOOLPRAYER-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MOST POWERFUL PRAYERS ARE SILENT ONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, June 20, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great thing about prayer is you don't need a church or a
temple or a mosque to do it right.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is a rabbi or a priest or a holy blessed sanctioned
uniformed official of any kind absolutely essential to your
mission.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need any structure or any person or anybody's
permission if you want to pray.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't matter who you are, either. Beggars and death row
prisoners have the same freedom to talk to God as do kings and
billionaires.
</P>
<P>
   In saying that, I mean no disrespect to any houses of worships
or individuals who are heeding a higher calling. Lord knows we live
in times when organized religion can be a great source of strength
and comfort to those whose beliefs conform to a particular brand.
</P>
<P>
   But that's all that stuff is _ brand name worship. Wrap yourself
in your religion and quote scripture or condemn my soul all you
want for saying that, but if you tell me you're 100 percent sure
that your religion is the only right path, the only one with a
direct pipeline to the only one true all-powerful God, I'm going to
tell you I think you're going to have some interesting
conversations in the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several days I've had two major reasons to pray _
the baptism of a child and the serious illness of a friend. One
involved attendance at a 125-year-old church and taking communion
and reciting sacred vows as the godfather; the other involved
informal appeals and hopes. Nobody's going to tell me one set of
prayers was more effective than another. I don't believe in that
kind of God.
</P>
<P>
   What you can't dispute is this: If anyone on this planet wants
to talk to God or Buddha or the clouds in the sky, if anyone wants
to give all glory and praise to a higher being, if anyone wants to
appeal to the spirits or a statue or a vision or a burning bush,
nobody can stop them.
</P>
<P>
   That's because prayer can be silent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact private prayer may be the best mode of all. Once you
start shouting from the mountain top and preaching to the perceived
heathens and arguing with people whose beliefs and rituals differ
from yours, hatred and war are sure to follow.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Establishment Clause of the First Amendment is
one of the most important provisions in the Constitution, as it
proclaims the government will not allow the establishment of any
single religion. You may think separation of church and state is a
terrible thing, but let me ask you this: What if the official
national religion wasn't the same as yours?
</P>
<P>
   Now all of a sudden you're talking revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court made a wise and fair ruling Monday with its
6-3 vote declaring prayer in public schools must be private.
</P>
<P>
   Note that the court didn't ban school prayer. It simply agreed
with other rulings on this subject that have been made over the
last four decades.
</P>
<P>
   What frightens me is that three justices voted the other way,
and that many Republicans, including presidential hopeful and Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, disagreed with the ruling. The same party
that's always talking about making sure the government doesn't
stick its nose in our business wants government to sanction laws
pushing prayers onto everyone, believers and nonbelievers alike.
</P>
<P>
   What a convenient shift in philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of this latest controversy is one Marian Ward, a
student at Santa Fe High School in Texas, who uttered the words
``Lord'' and ``Jesus'' over the public address system before
several thousand fans prior to a football game on the night of
Sept. 3, 1999, thus defying an earlier Supreme Court ruling against
the Santa Fe Independent School District, which had been sued by
the American Civil Liberties Union after a series of incidents in
which Christianity was promoted in the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question was if Santa Fe was violating the First
Amendment by allowing student-led prayer at high school football
games.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Christian you might shout: Hell (or Heck) no! But
what if the Buddhists, the Muslims, the Mormons and the Jews wanted
equal time? That OK with you? Start lining up all the religions and
the football game will never kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   (Not that the above groups are exactly well represented in the
Santa Fe school district, which is why it's easier to trample their
rights.)
</P>
<P>
   My favorite respondent to Ward's crusade was her classmate,
Amanda Bruce, whose constitutionally correct campaign included the
wearing of a button reading WWJD, for ``What Would Jefferson Do?''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, I believe in the rights of players,
cheerleaders, coaches and fans to pray before, during and after
football games. You can thank God in the postgame interview or
curse Him if you fumbled away the game, even though I seriously
doubt He cares.
</P>
<P>
   Just keep it to yourselves.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
