<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9405 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-AIRLINE-CONFID     06-20 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AIRLINE-CONFIDENCE-$ADV25-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMISES IN THE SKIES: SO FAR TRAVELERS ARE LARGELY UNIMPRESSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One year ago this month, the nation's major airlines announced
that they would make travel more pleasant by improving customer
service. Fearing that Congress was about to pass a bill of rights
for passengers in response to the increasing chorus of consumer
complaints, airline executives pre-empted the government's plans by
coming up with their own list of a dozen promises. They vowed to
give travelers information about low fares and flight delays. They
said they would make a ``reasonable effort'' to feed people who
were waiting on runways for hours at a time. They promised to
explain frequent-flier rules clearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers have just about had it,'' Leo Mullin, the chief
executive of Delta Air Lines, said in a speech last year to the
Wings Club, an aviation group in New York. It was time, he said, to
``restore public confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is what has happened since then:
</P>
<P>
   Consumer complaints to the Department of Transportation have
almost doubled. Virtually every independent measure of customer
satisfaction has declined. Lines at airports seem to be longer, and
many travelers say the airlines are not living up to at least some
of their promises.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome, travelers, to the year of restored public confidence.
We hope you have enjoyed the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The unfortunate truth is that flying on an airplane today, while
the safest way to travel long distances, is as unpleasant for many
passengers as it has ever been. The strong economy has sent more
planes into the air and kept them nearly full, but airport space,
the air-traffic control system and the size of airline staffs have
all failed to keep pace.
</P>
<P>
   Following the set of promises, the industry has improved in a
number of areas, travel experts say. Airlines respond more quickly
to complaints and seem to keep passengers better informed about
delays. But the promises have not caused enough improvement to make
up for the problems that remain. And because many travelers can
cite at least one instance in which the airlines have not followed
their own new rules, the industry has managed to raise expectations
above the level of service they are providing.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general of the Department of Transportation,
Kenneth M. Mead, is now studying how well the airlines are living
up their promises and plans to release a final report in December.
</P>
<P>
   But this much is clear: the airlines vowed to improve service,
and few travelers think they have. ``People who travel frequently
think it's pretty tough out there,'' said Rustin Carpenter, vice
president and general manager in Boston at American Express
Consulting Services, which advises corporations on managing their
travel.
</P>
<P>
   In the American Customer Satisfaction Index produced by the
University of Michigan Business School between January and March
using telephone interviews, the airlines received lower customer
satisfaction scores than any other industry. Their cumulative grade
has declined since 1994, the survey's first year. It held steady
this year mainly because Northwest Airlines saw its score rebound
after it had been hampered by a blizzard last year and a strike in
1998. The scores of most carriers declined.
</P>
<P>
   Other surveys offer similarly grim news. Since 1998, for
example, the percentage of Americans who think the airlines do a
good job serving their customers has fallen from 78 to 66,
according to Harris Interactive, which conducted a telephone survey
of 1,024 adults in April. Travelers' frustration has reached the
point that on the day last month that biztravel.com announced an
offer to give its customers partial or full refunds when a flight
on selected airlines arrives late, its Web site received so many
visits that it crashed.
</P>
<P>
   A major part of the problem, industry executives and analysts
agree, is an overburdened air-traffic system. The number of
passengers on domestic carriers grew 40 percent from 1989 to 1999,
according to the Air Transport Association, the major carriers'
trade group. The traffic has increased delays, especially in the
most crowded regions like the Northeast. Meanwhile, tighter
security rules force people to spend more time in line as travelers
in front of them show identification and answer questions about
their bags' contents. ``The whole airport process is much worse
than it was five years ago,'' said Michael Boyd, president of the
Boyd Group, an Evergreen, Colo., aviation consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   Congress recently voted to increase the FAA's funding by 30
percent, which should help the agency improve air-traffic control
technology and alleviate some delays. And the carriers are
installing devices in airports that allow passengers who are not
checking baggage to print their own boarding passes. Over all,
though, few experts expect the crowds and delays to get much better
anytime soon. The airlines are unlikely to spend the millions of
dollars to enlarge their staffs. And current efforts by government
officials and executives to build new runways and airports face the
usual resistance from nearby communities.
</P>
<P>
   None of that is new, however. The promises are new, and the crux
of them is a commitment to give passengers better information about
everything from fares to delays to frequent-flier rewards. Airline
executives say they are doing just that. ``Delta has absolutely
lived up to its promise,'' Mullin, the carrier's chief executive,
said in a recent interview. The airline, for instance, now responds
to consumer complaints in eight days on average, versus about a
month last year, according to a spokesman for the airline, John
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Some travelers say they see a difference as well. ``I've noticed
instances where they're saying things clearly and precisely that
I'm surprised by and that I don't think I would have heard a couple
years ago,'' said Carpenter, who flies at least once a week. He
added, however, that ``I don't think it's moved the needle
substantially'' from most travelers' perspective. In fact, some of
the promises represented little change for the airlines. Two of the
plan's 12 parts _ making provisions for passengers with special
needs and treating travelers bumped from a flight fairly _ already
existed in the airlines' written ticket contracts, and another four
represented only a small change, according to an audit by the
General Accounting Office, a government agency.
</P>
<P>
   A number of other promises are vague enough to leave the
carriers room for fudging. The airlines say they will strive to
return lost bags within 24 hours. They also talk of providing
``timely and complete information'' about frequent-flier
restrictions and other details, without saying whether the
information will appear in the footnotes of a little-read document
or more prominently in a monthly mailing, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The holes in the plans have left the industry's critics and more
than a few frequent fliers skeptical that the promises mean much.
``Thus far it's a pretty flimsy showing _ lots of public relations
and not much substance,'' said Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., who has
pushed for a law that would fine the airlines for breaking their
own rules. ``The airlines are in denial,'' he said. ``They refuse
to acknowledge the seriousness of the problem and the breadth of
the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Most damaging of all, many travelers say they can readily cite a
recent instance or two in which the airlines have broken one of
their promises. That has aggravated the industry's credibility
problem and is one reason that complaints to the Department of
Transportation have increased so rapidly, travel experts say.
(Another is the newfound ease with which travelers can register
their complaints, via the Internet or a toll-free phone number.)
``I wouldn't assume airlines are any worse than last year,'' said
Terry Trippler, the airline expert for a travel Web site,
onetravel.com, speaking of the spike in complaints. ``Passengers
are just more fed up.''
</P>
<P>
   They often have good reason. In late April, Continental
Airlines' Flight 1031 was scheduled to leave Newark for Fort
Lauderdale at 12:15. With storms over New Jersey, the flight was
delayed. First it sat on the runway for about two hours, said
William Friedman, a Fair Lawn, N.J., resident who was on the plane
with five family members. Then it returned to the gate, and the
passengers got off the plane and sat in the area around the gate
for about an hour. After another unsuccessful boarding and more
hours of sitting on the runway, the plane finally took off at 9
p.m. and arrived in Florida about 13 hours after the passengers had
originally boarded.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout the ordeal, Friedman said, Continental fed the
passengers only the sandwich it had planned to serve on the flight.
The uncertainty of when the plane might depart and the lines in the
airport made it impossible for passengers to get food during the
brief times they were waiting in the gate area, Friedman said.
Recognizing this, a flight attendant asked for more food to be
brought on the plane, but a ground supervisor refused, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not arguing they should have flown the plane in that
weather,'' Friedman said. ``But we went from 11:30 a.m. to midnight
with a cheese sandwich. I just felt it was inhumane.'' It also
seems to violate one of Continental's 12 promises, which is to make
``every reasonable effort'' to provide food to passengers stuck on
planes for long periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the policy applies to planes that are stuck on a
runway, not those that return to the gate for a time, according to
David Messing, an airline spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   When Friedman returned home and sent an e-mail to the airline,
the response addressed only the delay, not the lack of food. ``They
either misunderstood the point or purposely evaded what the real
issue was,'' he said. Continental did offer him a $25 voucher, but
Friedman refused it on principle, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of travelers' biggest frustrations is the quality
of information they get from airlines, in spite of the industry's
promises. A Wednesday-night flight last month on American Eagle, a
partner of American Airlines, from Ronald Reagan National Airport
in Washington to Kennedy Airport, is an example. It was scheduled
to arrive at 9:45 p.m. at Gate 40. By 10 p.m., it had not landed,
but airport computer screens still showed it as a 9:45 arrival.
Agents at Gate 40, working with travelers who were supposed to be
on another late flight, said they did not have time to find updated
information for the people who had come to meet the plane. American
Airlines employees at a nearby gate said they could not help either
because American Eagle, and not their airline, operated the flight.
Finally, the plane pulled up to the gate at 10:07 _ without the
computer screen ever showing it as delayed.
</P>
<P>
   A J.D. Power &AMP; Associates survey suggests such anecdotes are
more than just the rare exception. The research firm asked
travelers in its most recent annual study of the airlines to rate
the accuracy of information given at the gate, and the survey found
virtually no improvement in the category over last year. Of the
airlines rated the top three in communicating with passengers _
Continental, Southwest and TWA _ only Continental did better, said
Michael Taylor, J.D. Power's director of travel services.
</P>
<P>
   The gate isn't the only problem area, either. The airlines
continue to exaggerate the benefits of some of their travel
programs by omitting key information from the documents fliers are
most likely to read. Delta's misleading frequent-flier rules are
typical. In the main section of its membership guide, Delta says
passengers flying economy class on Aeromexico receive Delta miles.
There are no asterisks next to the statement. But 20 pages later,
the footnotes reveal that passengers flying in fare classes G (for
groups) and L (which are specially negotiated) in fact receive no
miles. ``How does the ordinary person know what that is?'' asks
Milton Klein, a retired history professor at the University of
Tennessee who said he was surprised to return home from a vacation
and not be credited for part of the trip. ``Apparently, truth in
advertising does not apply.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar problem crops up on the mileage statement Delta sends
each month to 27 million passengers. It neglects to mention that
one of the most popular awards _ a trip to Europe _ cannot be used
during the summer on the very days most people would want to use
it: Fridays, Saturdays or Sundays. Asked about the problems, Kevin
Pinto, system manager of SkyMiles, said the company would fix them.
It is worth noting, though, that Klein's complaint led Delta to
send him a copy of its rules but not to change them.
</P>
<P>
   The overarching problem is that one year after making their
promises, the airlines still seem to lack a fundamental
understanding of how to treat passengers, travel consultants say.
The carriers often reply to passengers' letters by restating a
policy rather than responding to a specific complaint, for example.
Or they install baggage templates halfway between the ticket
counter and the gate, forcing travelers whose bags are too big to
retrace their steps. As Boyd, the Colorado aviation consultant,
said, ``Airlines still want to make passengers do business their
way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
