<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9411 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-AGENTS-WEBSITE     06-20 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AGENTS-WEBSITES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN TRAVEL AGENTS FEAR AIRLINE WEB SITES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Taking a cue from the travel industry in the United
States, European airlines and hotel companies have begun setting up
their own Web sites, where customers can shop for flights and
rooms. And as in the United States, the action is angering travel
agents who fear the sites will cut them off from some of the more
tempting offerings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In May, 11 European airlines _ led by British Airways, Lufthansa
and Air France _ announced plans for a Web site where consumers can
shop for fares and order tickets. The site has yet to be named, but
it will be managed by the McKinsey Consulting Group. The airlines _
which also include Alitalia, Austrian Airlines, British Midland,
Finnair, Iberia of Spain, KLM of the Netherlands, Aer Lingus and
Scandinavian Airlines Systems (SAS) _ hope to have it operational
by the end of the year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, three of Europe's largest hotel groups, Hilton
International and the Forte Hotel Group of Britain, and Accor of
France, agreed to set up a similar Web site for hotel
accommodations. The hotel site is also expected to be up by year's
end.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, a similar booking system called T2 was
announced in January by Continental, Delta, Northwest and United
Airlines, to allow consumers to shop for inexpensive air fares on
participating airlines, and one day perhaps, on all others as well.
The site, which has since been joined by at least 23 other
airlines, is due to start up later this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, as in North America, the goals of the airlines and
hotels are twofold: first, to wean some customers from travel
agents, who charge the airlines commissions. But more important,
airline and hotel executives concede, they are trying to seize back
the initiative from the array of Internet companies that offer
inexpensive flights and hotel accommodations on the Web. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the clicks versus the bricks, unless we did
something,'' said David Michels, chief executive of Hilton
International. ``We have a right to sell our own product direct to
the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rod Eddington, chief executive of British Airways, said, ``All
our research shows that customers want to be able to compare and
buy offers from a wide range of airlines by visiting just one
site.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hilton executives say the plan is not aimed against travel
agents and that they will continue to use agents. Instead, they
say, it is aimed at middlemen, often working through Web sites, who
buy up low-fare plane tickets or vacant hotel rooms and pass them
on to the customer, usually pocketing a thin margin. And indeed,
travel agents themselves will be able to use the hotel site, Hilton
says.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As in the United States, the plans by the airlines and hotels
are also a reaction to a wave of startup online travel agencies.
The Boston Consulting Group, which is managing the airlines' Web
site in the United States, estimates that total online travel
transactions in Europe was about $930 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   That is less than 1 percent of the $116.3 billion Europeans
spent on travel, but growth at British-based companies like
ebookers.com and lastminute.com, as well as dozens of other sites
in Europe, has been dramatic. From 1998 to 1999, European online
travel booking, though admittedly starting at very low levels, grew
280 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet the travel agents, who are far better organized than the
online companies, have reacted strongly. In the United States, the
American Society of Travel Agents has asked the Justice Department
to decide whether the plans by the American and European airlines
violate antitrust laws. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Organizations of travel agents in several European countries,
including Britain, Spain and Germany, want to take similar action
in Europe. In May, the two largest Spanish organizations
representing travel agencies wrote to the chairman of the Spanish
carrier Iberia, which supports the European airline plan,
threatening to appeal to antitrust regulators, and accusing the
airlines of ``not trying to improve sales or customer service, but
to begin operating themselves as travel agencies.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keith Betton, director of corporate affairs at the Association
of British Travel Agents, said travel agent organizations
throughout the 15-nation European Union were considering an appeal
to antitrust regulators. ``Obviously, airlines and others are
perfectly free to set up Web sites, but they mustn't be
anticompetitive,'' he said. ``We would be very upset if there were
offers online which were not available to travel agents.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, it appears unlikely that the pressure on the traditional
travel agents will diminish any time soon. Some European airlines,
including Lufthansa and Finnair, already enable customers using
cell phones with limited access to the Internet to check for flight
delays or to change reservations. Within two to three years, they
expect customers to be able to use their phones to book flights and
buy tickets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Moran, chief executive of the Irish Travel Agents
Association, recently described the use of the Web for reservations
as just another form of distribution to which travel agents would
have to adapt. To remain competitive, he said, travel agents would
have to stress other kinds of services, like providing advice and
information.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
