<HEADER>
A9414 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-AIRLINE-FOOD-$     06-20 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AIRLINE-FOOD-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIGESTIBLE FLYING OBJECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traveling makes me hungry. I want comfort food when I'm bored
and lonely, and exhaustion and enforced waiting combine to make me
ravenous; only huge quantities of protein will do the trick.
Anxiety brings a craving for calming carbohydrates. So the one good
thing about sitting in a plane, where I'm almost always bored,
lonely, exhausted and anxious, is that the fierce demands of my
stomach keep me from worrying whether the mechanics remembered to
check the flaps.
</P>
<P>
   Although I have learned, to my relief, that the airlines get me
where I want to go, I have also learned, to my chagrin, that I
cannot count on them to feed me. This holds true even in the
relatively luxurious confines of business class, where we are all
either traveling on someone else's dollar or cashing in on tens of
thousands of miles of past suffering. Here, the galley might
conceivably prepare a piece of beef that is both rare and hot
(you'll never see that in economy), but it still won't be appealing
_ not by a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   And in coach, where almost everyone travels all the time, people
rarely get sick from eating airplane food, but horror stories
abound: pasta cooked to death, half-frozen salads, indescribable
flavors, unidentifiable vegetables, leathery meat, leathery
chicken, mushy fish, undercooked food, overcooked food (the norm),
even uncooked food (one of my daughters was once served raw rice),
and now overly ambitious ingredients. What gave the airlines the
idea they should start messing around with croissants when they
have yet to serve a decent piece of bread?
</P>
<P>
   But one must eat. And for the hungry traveler, nothing describes
the situation better than the old joke about the hotel in the
Catskills: Not only is the food bad but the portions are also too
small. Every road warrior has had an experience like this one:
Start a meeting at 11 a.m., preferably in an earlier-than-usual
time zone, so you're hungry already. Sprint for a two-hour flight,
with no time to grab anything, and be handed a ``bistro meal'' on
your way onto the plane, or be informed that you will be served ``a
light snack.''
</P>
<P>
   At times like these you'll eat anything. When you're begging for
a second bag of peanuts (the flight attendants will generally take
pity, and even allow three or four), even the thought of smoked
turkey and American cheese on a soggy croissant with yellow mustard
and wilted lettuce (served with a box of raisins the size of a
priority-mail stamp and a brownie so sweet your teeth hurt can make
your mouth water. And the reality of one of those sandwiches is
enough to make you really believe that your heart and stomach long
for nothing more than baked tortellini with cheese sauce or steak
in wine sauce (known in high school as Salisbury steak, and little
changed since then).
</P>
<P>
   Some airlines hire chef consultants. They correctly perceive the
situation as a public relations problem, but incorrectly believe
that by attaching a chef's name to a bad meal it will magically
become a good one. Although chefs can provide ingenious recipes,
they cannot compensate for third-rate ingredients, precooking in
stages, freezing and thawing, microwaving and reheating, and
cafeteria- and battlefieldlike conditions. Substitutions and
shortcuts are fine, but you still cannot make roast chicken without
a chicken and an oven.
</P>
<P>
   The concept should be straightforward: Simple food is best.
After all there is nothing inherently wrong with a sandwich. But
whether airline food is simple or complicated, it's executed
miserably. It simply isn't worth the money for airlines to serve
good food.
</P>
<P>
   It might be argued, and not entirely without logic, that the
airlines believe that Americans don't care about food, that we view
it strictly as fuel _ fill 'er up, who cares about the brand, and
there's always more where that came from. But the
I-can't-believe-they're-serving-this phenomenon is not limited to
domestic airlines or flights; United States-based companies may set
the pace, but the pattern holds true around the world, and some of
the guiltiest airlines are those originating in the countries whose
cuisines are, theoretically at least, superior.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the theory is that we travelers somehow lose our ability
to tell the difference between marginally appealing food with some
flavor and that which could only be considered when the alternative
is crankiness or worse. But even fast food has punch, and recent
years have seen a move away from blandness and toward bigger
flavors, not only in top restaurants but everywhere. No one in his
right mind prefers a soggy whole wheat croissant with off-colored
meat and warm American cheese to, say, a good bag of Doritos and a
can of jalapeno dip, or a few Chicken McNuggets.
</P>
<P>
   And proof that travelers remain conscious of what they eat is as
obvious as the permanent lines at food courts in some of the
busiest and most recently remodeled airports, like those of
Pittsburgh and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the cheap, relatively flavorful, and popular food of
normal daily life is sold by the ton. Happily coexisting, at prices
significantly higher than those two miles down the road, are
McDonald's, Burger King, Wendy's, Pizza Hut and more. These places
are almost always crowded, and the people crowding them are either
(a) about to get on a plane, knowing that this common fare will be
far superior to the food served on board; or (b) just got off a
plane and don't even have the strength to pick up their bags
without fortifying themselves after the enforced starvation of the
flight.
</P>
<P>
   In my nontravel life, I no more eat voluntarily at these places
than I drive to the airport and try to buy flight food. Yet I'm on
those lines at the food courts whenever I have the time, and
whenever I think a Whopper will save me from eating the plane's
cheese tortellini.
</P>
<P>
   Nor am I alone. Increasingly, my fellow travelers board planes
with McDonald's sack in hand, merrily (or at least hungrily) tuck
into their Quarter Pounder while the plane is still at the gate,
and happily work or sleep through the meal service. Others carry
snacks along with their laptops. Some make do with an apple, or
just skip lunch or dinner. And no one I've spoken with feels happy
about the situation.
</P>
<P>
   It's about money. The airlines' food budgets are set, and the
small portions of bad food must be delivered quickly and their
detritus removed just as fast.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that instant meals mean smaller galleys _
which in turn mean more seats _ and in many instances may require
one attendant less.
</P>
<P>
   Yet having established a tradition of feeding us, the airlines
should make an attempt to do it with the same amount of class and
elan with which they do everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, now I get it. Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
