<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PROMOTIONS-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOINING THE MILLION-MILE CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By JOSEPH SIANO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intentionally or not, airline frequent-flier programs have moved
the target for mileage trophy hunters: it's now a million free
miles. One of the latest examples is courtesy of LatinPass, a
frequent-flier consortium representing 10 Latin American airlines.
</P>
<P>
   In January, LatinPass offered a million-mile bonus to anyone
flying at least one international leg on each of nine of its
members: Aces, Aeropostal, Avianca, Copa Airlines, Aviateca, Lacsa,
Nica, Taca and Taca Peru. (Saeta, an Ecuadorean airline that is
also a LatinPass carrier, cannot fly internationally and is not in
the million-mile bonus program.) Participants also have to take
three flights on partner carriers, stay three nights in partner
hotels and rent a car for five days from a partner car-rental
company. All of this must be done by July 1. There are also
intermediate awards of 500,000 and 100,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Those requirements may seem restrictive, but on March 20,
LatinPass officials shut off enrollment in the bonus plan. Guy
Booth, program director for LatinPass, estimated earlier this month
that more than 50 pass holders would probably qualify for the
million-mile bonus, with a similar number earning 500,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't envisioned as such a popular program, Booth said, but
LatinPass officials apparently failed to grasp the reach of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We initially promoted it in a newsletter to our frequent
fliers, but our good friend Randy Petersen got hold of it and
posted it on his Web site,'' he said, referring to
www.flyertalk.com, Petersen's chat room for frequent-flier
fanatics. Petersen also publishes InsideFlyer magazine, designed to
help frequent fliers make each mile go as far as possible. ``It did
catch us a little bit by surprise in not knowing these Web sites
existed and that the mileage hunters were out there,'' Booth said.
</P>
<P>
   Word was also spread by the beneficiary of another mileage-bonus
promotion, David Phillips, a civil engineer from Davis, Calif.,
known as Pudding Guy. He earned the nickname (and 1.25 million
miles on four carriers) in a promotion that offered miles in
exchange for buying Healthy Choice foods. Phillips determined that
by buying some $3,400 worth of products, mostly pudding cups, he
could redeem the lids for 1.25 million miles. He says he has
already used part of his bonus to take his family on a trip to
Europe. Amid the news media attention that seems to be another
bonus accompanying such feats nowadays, Phillips said that he had
also qualified for the LatinPass million miles.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how a million miles in the LatinPass program are
redeemed, Booth said, the bonus could wind up costing the program's
operators anywhere from $5,000 to $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The LatinPass airlines are among the leaders in the region,
although not as large as major European and American carriers. The
carriers joined forces to form LatinPass in 1995 for extra
leverage. ``On their own, it's difficult for them to have a
frequent-flier participation program with a major hotel chain or
credit-card company,'' Booth said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
