<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9425 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-MOM-MOBILE-HNS &LR;      06-20 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-MOM-MOBILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOR BUSY SOCCER MOMS, FORD DEVELOPS A HOME AWAY FROM HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a vehicle for the Martha Stewart in all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Minivans have been known as mom-mobiles for some time now, but a
new version of the Ford Windstar seems to be taking that theme to
extremes.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Maytag have joined forces to create the Windstar
Solutions minivan concept, complete with a built-in clothes washer
and dryer, as well as a microwave oven, trash compactor,
refrigerator and vacuum cleaner. Ford says the concept evolved from
research the company commissioned in its efforts to market cars to
women.
</P>
<P>
   But, gee, this seems to be taking the mom-mobile to extremes.
Did I say that already?
</P>
<P>
   Built into the back end, where the tailgate lifts up, is the
nifty little combination washer/dryer, which Ford says can wash and
dry a soiled soccer uniform or party dress in 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   So now, after mom picks up the kids at the end of the soccer
match, she can go ahead and launder their soiled uniforms while
feeding them dinner in the minivan. The refrigerator can hold a
variety of cold foods, such as luncheon meat and juice boxes, and
the accompanying microwave can heat up soup, hot chocolate or
popcorn. That, alone, might be worth the money _ popping your own
corn at a sporting event instead of buying the expensive stuff from
vendors.
</P>
<P>
   And if you go grocery shopping, there is no need to rush home
with the cold stuff, Ford says. You can continue running errands
after storing the cold stuff in the refrigerator. Besides the
fridge in the rear cargo area, called a ``food drawer,'' there is a
second refrigerated compartment in the rear passenger area, as well
as cup holders designed to keep drinks either cold or hot.
</P>
<P>
   After a day at the beach, or a picnic by a group of toddlers in
the back seat, mom (or even dad or one of the bigger kids) can
vacuum up the sand or dropped food by using the built-in Hoover
wet-dry vacuum cleaner. (Hoover is a subsidiary of Maytag).
</P>
<P>
   But wait _ there is more.
</P>
<P>
   The minivan is equipped with a voice-activated ``home
connection'' device that allows mom or dad to turn on the oven and
other appliances back at home by remote control. You would have to
buy Maytag appliances that are capable of being operated by remote
control, and this technology is still under development. But it's a
technology that will be commercially available soon. Imagine having
your entire house networked with a computer in your minivan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listening to and observing the consumer led to the development
of the Windstar Solutions concept vehicle,'' said Jim Schroer,
Ford's vice president for global marketing. ``It is Ford Motor
Co.'s goal to be responsive to our consumers by creating solutions
which improve their quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no word yet as to whether a vehicle with all of these
options will ever find its way to market. If it does, it could be
of help to some moms _ or dads _ who have to spend an inordinate
amount of time in their vehicles, shuttling kids to event after
event all over town.
</P>
<P>
   But a possible backlash could occur: the vehicle just might
steer an even larger number of mothers from minivans to sport
utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Booming SUV sales have been fueled in part by women who have
chosen to trade their minivans for vehicles that aren't quite as
domestic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here, from a Ford news release, is a complete list of the
special Suzy Homemaker features in the Windstar Solutions minivan,
which is being displayed at various home shows across the nation:
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerator: Maytag's ClimateZone technology food drawer is
featured in the cargo compartment. Consumers will be able to set
the proper temperature for certain foods, especially meat, fruit
and vegetables. There is also a refrigerated compartment in the
rear passenger area. These built-in units provide convenient
storage of perishable items purchased at the grocery store,
allowing for customers to continue their errands without stopping
at home.
</P>
<P>
   Microwave: Placed in the left rear, it's perfect to heat up a
baby bottle, hot chocolate, tea, soup and even popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler: Located behind the driver and front passenger seats, the
cooler stores easily accessible items such as bottled water, sodas
and juice boxes. It is also removable for use at a park or a
football game.
</P>
<P>
   Hot/cold cup holders: Located between the passenger and driver,
these cup holders keep milk cold and coffee hot.
</P>
<P>
   Trash compactor: Windstar Solutions has a trash compactor
located between the front seats and a trash bin in the vehicle
cargo area. The mechanical compactor can crush everything from
apple cores to aluminum cans. Both trash units have a washable
liner, which can be removed for easy cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Wet/dry utility vacuum: The Hoover wet/dry utility vacuum is
placed in the side panel adjacent to the second-row passenger
seating. It can pick up cracker crumbs, beach sand and spilled
juice.
</P>
<P>
   Washer/dryer: Spills on clothing are common, especially with
children in the vehicle. A miniature Maytag combination
washer/dryer is built into the rear cargo area.
</P>
<P>
   Tray tables: Tray tables fold down from the seat backs of the
front captain's chairs, providing children and adults a great place
to eat a snack, complete a crossword puzzle, read or do homework.
</P>
<P>
   Home Connection: Home Connection, a conceptual idea, adds a
unique twist to Ford Motor Co.'s Telematics system. Telematics
brings voice activation and automatic emergency notification into
the Lincoln LS and Jaguar brands. The Home Connection concept could
enable consumers to remain connected to their homes. Customers in
the future could preheat the oven, check home food inventories, and
monitor home security and fire systems while driving, using
voice-activation technology. With the vehicle parked, consumers
could use a touch screen to operate the system.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment package: Family members and friends can experience
hours of entertainment. Individuals can choose between viewing
movies or playing CD-ROM interactive electronic games. Game
controllers and CD storage are built into the rear passenger area.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
