<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9426 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-INTERNET-POLITICS-HNS     06-20 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLITICAL PARTIES HOPING TO LURE VOTERS TO LOG ON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KIM COBB  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If an Internet service provider furnishes a door to the World
Wide Web, the doorkeeper also has the opportunity to influence the
opinions of those who travel through it.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the national committees for the Democratic
and Republican parties are trying to attract Web surfers to
Internet portals that launch computer users onto the Web through a
kind of partisan filter _ Web pages tailored to deliver party
messages wrapped around the usual links to news, sports and chat
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   When the Democrats unveiled www.freeDEM.com June 8, party
officials stressed that their Internet access and e-mail services
would be free to anyone, regardless of party affiliation
(advertising on the site pays for the service). The Democrats
crowed that freeDEM would help bridge the so-called ``digital
divide'' between those who can afford to get on line and those who
can't.
</P>
<P>
   But the party's primary goal is to reach out to uncommitted
voters, to expose people to the Democratic message who might not
otherwise seek it.
</P>
<P>
   Log on to freeDEM, and the message at the top of its red, white
and blue page is, ``brought to you by the Democratic National
Committee.'' Links to the Democratic National Committee, the Gore
presidential campaign and other Democratic sites are featured
prominently.
</P>
<P>
   But the lion's share of the site is nonpolitical _ the links to
general interest news, shopping, weather, sports and finance that
the average computer user demands.
</P>
<P>
   The comparable Republican site looks similar, but users of
www.GOPnet.com pay a monthly fee for its Internet access service.
GOP officials say the GOPnet site is designed to serve as an
on-line community for the party faithful, not as a recruitment
tool.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, GOPnet is more overtly partisan, its content chosen
to spotlight Republican issues. The GOP site features commentaries
by Republican congressional leaders and even takes jabs at the
opposition through links like ``Gore Gaffes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some theorize the advent of such sites could be a powerful tool
in connecting voters to candidates, like television did in the
1960s. But the trick is generating interest in politics when
Internet browsers have so many other trails they can follow.
</P>
<P>
   Users of both sites can ``customize'' certain selections to
reflect their personal interests, but a certain percentage of
political ``spin'' will be delivered or offered as links to every
user. And users of both sites get the same promise: no political
mail and no solicitations for funds, unless the user requests it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between the Republicans and us is they're not
trying to get as many people on line as possible, they're trying to
raise as much money as possible,'' said Democratic National
Committee Chairman Joe Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   The RNC is not trying to ``wire'' everyone in the United States,
countered RNC deputy chief of staff Larry Purpuro, because the
private sector is doing a pretty good job of it. And a majority of
Republicans are already on line, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We launched GOPnet in Silicon Valley in January,'' said
Purpuro. ``The Democrats are only seven or eight months behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew countered that the Web sites should not be judged as
competing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always want to make it look like a horse race _ who's got
the best site, who was there first,'' Andrew said. ``What's
important is: Are you reaching the audience you want?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party officials are also investigating the use of a
similar political portal to reach their audience but won't make a
decision until after their national convention in Long Beach,
Calif., in August, a party spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The companies providing the Internet connections to subscribers
at freeDEM and GOPnet are what's known as ``affinity'' providers,
who design portals aimed at specific slices of the Internet
population. Instead of building a subscriber list from the ground
up (the competition is already pretty fierce), affinity providers
approach existing organizations and associations and build portals
designed to appeal to their members.
</P>
<P>
   For example, iBelong, the Internet service provider for freeDEM,
also provides similar portals for the AFL-CIO and National
Federation of Women.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first presidential election in the Internet age,''
said Bob Viney, who supervises the freeDEM page for iBelong. ``As
Joe Andrew said: Think back to the '60s when Kennedy first used
television. We're really at the same kind of transformation of the
election process. It will forever be different ...because of the
power of the Internet to connect voters and candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   But it would be difficult for either freeDEM or GOPnet to make
major inroads in molding public opinion because of the vast number
of choices people have in a diverse communications marketplace,
said Tom Patterson, professor at Harvard University's JFK School of
Government.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson has been conducting surveys on Internet use and
election politics during the current campaign cycle. He finds that
while large numbers of Americans are on line, few are using the Web
to keep abreast of politics.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone survey of 1,000 adults conducted May 3-7, 75
percent who described themselves as Republicans said they had
Internet access either at home or at work. Sixty-four percent of
independents reported having access, compared with 57 percent of
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But only 9 percent of Republicans said they had acquired
information about the presidential campaign from the Internet in
the 24 hours preceding the May survey. Seven percent of Democrats
said they'd used the Web to research the presidential campaign, as
did 4 percent of Independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's underestimated about the Internet is if you're not
interested in public affairs and politics ... you may take a quick
glance (at a site) but you don't stay,'' Patterson said. ``And I
think that's the real challenge that faces people on the Internet.
Not providing access, but building interest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
