<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-INVESTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BROKERAGE TO OFFER UPGRADED INTERNET SEARCH ENGINE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In what may be the closest thing yet to a
computer engaging in intelligent thought to answer a user's
question, a new technology will help Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. customers
collect investment data on the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   One step beyond search sites such as Ask Jeeves, which take a
user's question and respond with a list of Web sites that may
provide an answer, the technology, developed by iPhrase
Technologies Inc. of Cambridge, Mass., allows users to type in a
question and receive a tailored answer based on the system's
interpretation of the phrasing and a search of relevant databases.
</P>
<P>
   When Bob Sofman, a senior vice president of Schwab's electronic
brokerage, tried the system out, he typed: ``Compare the P-to-E
ratios for the top five chip manufacturers and biotech firms.'' The
answer, in seconds, was a table created by the program comparing
both fields, ranked in order of largest ratio to least.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it had done was create a dynamic table in response to my
inquiry,'' Sofman said. ``It was remarkable, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   The same question typed into askjeeves.com offered results
varying from U.S. Census statistics and information on business, to
Britannica.com's entry on biotechnology, places to learn about the
math topic ``ratio and proportion,'' as well as this unlikely
result: ``Where can I buy snacks from an on-line store?''
</P>
<P>
   The service will be free to schwab.com users when it becomes
available in the fall. Sofman said Schwab had interviewed 20 to 25
companies before settling on iPhrase, home to several former
scientists at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. Terms of
the contract were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   IPhrase, which also has an office in San Mateo, has attracted
$11 million from venture capitalists, including Sequoia Capital,
Greylock Management and Charles River Ventures. The company says
its goal is to provide more acutely tailored search engine
capabilities, rather than the throwing-darts results that sometimes
prevail on the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9437 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-SPEER-$ADV24-     06-20 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-SPEER-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW PLAY EXAMINES THE TWO FACES OF NAZI ARCHITECT, SPEER
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., June 24 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ How can an apparently honorable man take part in an
unspeakable evil and then find a way to live with himself?
</P>
<P>
   This is the central question of ``Albert Speer,'' a new play in
London that pursues its unsettling answers through a 3 1/2-hour
examination of the confessions and equivocations of Nazi leader
Adolph Hitler's pet architect and armaments minister.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Trevor Nunn, the play is based on the successful
1995 biography by Gitta Sereny, ``Albert Speer: His Battle with
Truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sereny, an Austrian-born Briton, wrote the 720-page book nearly
20 years after a three-week interview she had with Speer, who died
in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his high position in the Nazi regime and his
willingness to write about his experiences, Speer long has been an
important figure in the effort to understand the inner workings of
the Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the confessional and analytical nature of his books,
he has been widely regarded as ``the good Nazi.'' He maintained to
his death that he was unaware of the Holocaust until after the war.
</P>
<P>
   However, this assertion has come under attack in recent years by
Sereny and other writers who doubt that Speer could have been so
comfortably ignorant.
</P>
<P>
   This perspective is embraced by playwright David Edgar, best
known to Americans for his adaptation of Dickens' ``Nicholas
Nickleby'' in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar explores the Speer story in two acts. The first represents
Speer's version, a portrayal that is faithful to his books,
``Inside the Third Reich'' and ``Spandau Diaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene opens with Speer's reporting to Spandau prison in
Berlin to begin the 20-year sentence handed down during the
Nuremberg trials. In the background of the scene are Nazi war
</P>
<P>
   criminals dangling by their necks _ a fate escaped by Speer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an intelligent rendering of Speer by Alex Jennings, the
first act is stolen by Roger Allam's mesmerizing Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Allam plays the Fuehrer as an intensely charming prophet with a
grand vision of a strong, pure Germany that will need _ and here's
where the young architect Speer comes in _ a spectacular new
capital on the magnitude of ancient Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Hitler comes across as an engaging, good listener with Old World
manners and a gift for flattery. He casts a Faustian spell over the
ambitious young Speer and elevates him to be the second most
powerful man in the Reich.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Speer tries to explain how Hitler's charismatic
appeal worked on intelligent, stable Germans _ such as Speer:
``Eighty million people didn't follow him because he was evil but
</P>
<P>
   because they thought he was extremely good!''
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Sereny describes an emotional even ``erotic''
relationship between the two men. Hitler saw the handsome young
Speer as the Aryan of his warped dreams. To Speer, Hitler was the
father-figure he never had. In the play, Speer's own father regards
his son's role in the Reich with icy contempt.
</P>
<P>
   This theme unfolds as a dark love story that only begins to
unravel in the horror of the last years of the war when Hitler's
loathsome insanity becomes obvious even to Speer.
</P>
<P>
   The moment of revelation comes during one of the play's most
memorable moments. Hitler _ now clearly disjointed and drained _
sits slumped against Speer's white model of the majestic dome that
he designed as centerpiece of the imperial Reich capital that never
was.
</P>
<P>
   Hitler rages at the cowards and inferiors who failed him in his
quest to rid the world of the ``Jewish-Bolshevik conspiracy.''
Speer, at last recognizing Hitler for what he was, bravely resists
the Fuehrer's final demand that he destroy Germany to deprive the
weaklings left behind with any means to recover from the war.
</P>
<P>
   Act 1 closes with a chilling 1943 speech made by Heinrich
Himmler, the Nazi SS leader who directed the program of mass
killing. Himmler reveals the full horror of the ``Final Solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The second act, which shows Speer after his release, shifts from
Speer's account of what happened and begins to chip away at his
story.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the play, Speer is portrayed not as sinner
seeking redemption but as a man seeking comfort in denial.
</P>
<P>
   Described by one character as a ``rent-a-penitent,'' Speer makes
the university and bookstore circuit dogged always by questions
about his role in the Reich. The questions in time overcome his
comfortable and practiced responses.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he is forced to confront himself and the ghost of
Hitler in dreams that allow him no escape from his reality.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he confesses that he must have known _ even though
he could never bring himself to acknowledge what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sensed, and turned away from what I sensed,'' Speer says
with horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albert Speer'' is scheduled to run through July 8. For
tickets, call 011-44-207-452-3000
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s e-mail address is BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nt-online.org,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.londontown.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
