<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9439 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-WILLIAM-0621-     06-20 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-WILLIAM-0621-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TURNING 18, BRITAIN'S PRINCE WILLIAM BEGINS NEW RELATIONSHIP
WITH THE MEDIA
 &HT;    (700&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain's hunk and future king Wednesday(6/21) is
expected to begin his long and maddening battle against a likely
lifelong nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   The press.
</P>
<P>
   For Wednesday, it is Prince William's fate to turn 18. Now that
he is officially an adult _ and blessed (or is it burdened?) with
the title ``His Royal Highness'' _ the contest can commence in
earnest.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of shame over the circumstances of the death of
his mother, Princess Diana, and maybe even out of respect for his
youth, the British press has been amazingly mannerly in its
</P>
<P>
   coverage of the prince during his years of schooling at Eton.
</P>
<P>
   But this polite arrangement _ an unnatural state for the
generally frantic British celebrity press _ is likely to come to an
abrupt halt.
</P>
<P>
   Already, even as William studies for his final exams, the rules
seem to be changing.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the News of the World, Britain's biggest-selling
tabloid newspaper, ran photos of William next to a story about his
apparent choice of university _ St. Andrews in Scotland _ which it
described as ``St. Randy's'' because of the college's reputation as
a party school.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Sunday Mirror tabloid reported that a friend of
William's at Eton had been expelled after being caught with drugs
during his exams.
</P>
<P>
   Even the more restrained Guardian wasn't above it all. Last
week, the respectable broadsheet carried a spread on the prince's
``ladies in waiting,'' a list of 10 women considered fitting dating
</P>
<P>
   material. The list included Sarah Gore, Vice President Al Gore's
21-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   In the mounting pre-birthday frenzy, a number of newspapers have
been taking the pulse of the public on the William issue. They have
tried to determine where the people stand on the prince's
</P>
<P>
   choice of university and career.
</P>
<P>
   William will need something to do, as he has a few decades to
kill waiting for his father to relinquish the crown _ which, for
the record, still is worn by Queen Elizabeth II.
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting that there still will be a throne for William in 30
or 40 years, a poll in the Daily Telegraph found that only 11
percent of the British people want to dump the monarchy in favor of
a republic.
</P>
<P>
   While the public may want to keep the monarchy, polls show
they're not particularly nuts about their current monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles for one, has never found his way into British
hearts, probably because of his longtime romance with decidedly
unpopular Camilla Parker Bowles. The beloved Princess Di blamed the
widely known affair for the demise of her marriage to the prince.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday Express dared ask readers if William shouldn't go
ahead and become king instead of Charles _ the readers were split
on that one.
</P>
<P>
   The polls also showed popular support for allowing William to
have as normal a life as possible before assuming his royal duties.
He'll apparently have plenty of time because his father has decided
that he won't have any royal duties, like opening hospital or
sponsoring charities.
</P>
<P>
   No public celebration of William's birthday is planned, but a
fancy private family affair is scheduled for Windsor Palace.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to William's milestone, the party will mark the
100th birthday of Queen Mother Elizabeth (on Aug. 4), 50th birthday
of Princess Anne (on Aug. 15), 40th birthday of Prince Andrew (in
February) and 70th birthday of Princess Margaret (on Aug. 21).
</P>
<P>
   The press will not be allowed in the palace, but a flashing,
shouting mob is expected to press against the gates. William is not
expected to attend the party, officially to study for exams. (But
it has been widely speculated that he is having a royal tiff with
his father over not being allowed to have his birthday party at a
London nightclub.)
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for William, he has all the wrong attributes for a
hermit.
</P>
<P>
   He has his mother's grace and good looks molded into a 6-foot-2
man's frame. He is athletic, as demonstrated by new officially
approved photos of him playing water polo and soccer. He is said to
be personable, even it he didn't show it in an officially approved
interview in which he refused to be pinned down on, well, anything.
</P>
<P>
   And to make matters worse, he seems determined to have his
privacy _ making him all the more tantalizing to the paparazzi and
royal writers.
</P>
<P>
   In his interview _ actually a series of insipid written
responses to insipid written questions _William made it clear that
he intended to be anything but an open book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to keep my private life private,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   He seemed particularly snippy when it came to questions about
his love life, even though he was proclaimed the most eligible
bachelor in Britain while still in high school.
</P>
<P>
   He and has family have demonstrated considerable displeasure
with press reports of his exchange of e-mails with American pop
star Britney Spears and the suggesting that there was more than
electronic pulses between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of nonsense put about by PR companies,'' he
responded. ``I don't like being exploited in this way, but as I get
older it's increasingly hard to prevent.''
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles, who has had his own scraps with the press over
the decades, has complained bitterly when even innocuous reports
about his son surface.
</P>
<P>
   In the build-up to William's birthday, Charles last week
expressed his sense that a gloomy future awaits his heir.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scrutiny and interference is just beyond description and I
personally don't envy him at all,'' Charles told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.ukroyals.co.uk
</P>
<P>
   www.guardianunlimited.co.uk/monarchy
</P>
<P>
   www.royalreport.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
