<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, June 21.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL  &LR;  (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-CHINA (Taipei) _ Emboldened by last week's summit meeting
between the leaders of North and South Korea, Taiwan's new
president, Chen Shui-bian, on Tuesday invited his Chinese
counterpart, Jiang Zemin, to take part in a similar peace-making
effort. China immediately rejected the overture. By Mark Landler.
(An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ The linchpin Shas political party
quit Prime Minister Ehud Barak's governing coalition Tuesday,
throwing the Israeli political system into even greater frenzy. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-BBC-DEATH (Jerusalem) _ The British Broadcasting Corp.
wants to prosecute Israel for the killing of a BBC employee in
Lebanon during the troop withdrawal. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-IMMIG-DEATHS (London) _ Developments in the
investigation of the deaths of 58 illegal immigrants from Asia. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MEDIA (Moscow) _ Vladimir Gusinsky, who owns several
major media organizations, will appear on TV Tuesday night to
discuss his arrest last week. (Byline to come)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-HITLER (Berlin) _ The presentation of a major German
prize to a historian who says Hitler was merely responding to
Bolshevism has created furor. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-HEALTH-CARE (Undated) _ In its first analysis of health
care systems around the world, the World Health Care Organization
has found that France provides the best overall care, followed by
Italy, Spain, Oman, Austria and Japan. By Philip J. Hilts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL  &LR;  (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PARDON-BOARD (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas board of pardons
and parole will vote this week on whether or not to give a reprieve
to convicted killer Gary Graham. Sara Rimer profiles the board,
which is unlike any other body in the country. They are all
appointees of Gov. George W. Bush and receive $80,000 a year. They
never meet in person but only talk on the phone. They are perhaps
the governor's biggest imprint on executions in Texas. By Sara
Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Lawyers for Juan Miguel Gonzalez, the
father of Elian Gonzalez, have until Tuesday to reply to a request
from the boy's Miami relatives that all 12 judges of the federal
appeals court based in Atlanta reverse a decision that would allow
him to take his son Elian home to Cuba. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   WACO-LAWSUIT (Waco, Texas) _ Opening statements in the wrongful
death lawsuit against the U.S. government over the 1993 Branch
Davidian raid.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CHILD-KILLERS (Miami) _ Why would a child kill? Because he
IS a child and doesn't consider the consequences of his actions,
says the mother of 13-year-old Nathaniel Brazzill, accused of
shooting his teacher to death. The state of Florida has no middle
ground in such cases: A child like Nathaniel, accused of a felony,
is tried as an adult. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HARLEM-CANCER (New York) _ Ralph Lauren has donated $5
million to open an early detection and treatment center in Harlem
for breast, prostrate and colon cancer. Researchers have said that
death rates in Harlem due to cancer are worse than in undeveloped
nations. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
