<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Life in the Oklahoma Oil Patch,
1938.
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Dortha Dunkel
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   They were just crepe paper flowers on a tin can base.
</P>
<P>
   Daddy cut the cans, and mama made the flowers to sell for extra
money. Times were hard in the Oklahoma oil patch in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   Daddy was working part time for Magnolia Oil Co. (ole Aunt
Maggie, as he called the company) in Oilton, Okla. The hope was he
could get on full time, but prospects weren't bright. The oil field
there was almost depleted.
</P>
<P>
   Our big weekly outing was driving to Tulsa with mama to hear Bob
Wills and His Texas Playboys in their studio at KVOO radio. Of
course, we took along flowers to sell.
</P>
<P>
   One Saturday, I became fascinated by a large baby doll in a
store window.
</P>
<P>
   When mama told me to come on and get in the car, that we needed
to start home, I lingered.
</P>
<P>
   Then mama took three bunches of flowers from the back seat and
went into the store.
</P>
<P>
   We hadn't sold any flowers that day. I was hoping she would find
some buyers in the store and stay awhile, and I could feast my eyes
on the doll.
</P>
<P>
   A sales lady came and took the doll from the window. I thought
how great it would be for the little girl who got it.
</P>
<P>
   Then the impossible happened. Mama came out of the store with
the doll. She had traded her flowers for it.
</P>
<P>
   My head swam as she handed me the doll, and I held it tightly
all the way back.
</P>
<P>
   When we got home, daddy had good news. There was full-time work
with Magnolia Oil in Salem, Ill., and we were going there to see if
he could get a job.
</P>
<P>
   What a great day! A new doll! Maybe a new job!
</P>
<P>
   In the days to follow, I hugged my doll through the selling of
our house and furniture. I held it to ease the pain of things
familiar which would be gone. I held it close as my voice echoed in
rooms empty of furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   Even mama's pride and joy, her mahogany dining room suit and
eight chairs, were sold. Through it all, that was the only time
mama cried.
</P>
<P>
   Our few worldly goods were reduced to a large Oxydol box of
linens and dishes which was placed in the back seat of our black
1936 Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   With tears in my eyes, I looked out the car's back window as we
drove off.
</P>
<P>
   Silently I said goodbye to the four-room unpainted oilfield
house and the sheet metal barn behind it. That's where the kids of
the neighborhood put on amateur shows, sang and danced and used
mama's good clothes, unknown to her, for costumes.
</P>
<P>
   Everything grew smaller, then disappeared. The past was gone,
but the future looked bright.
</P>
<P>
   I turned, hugged my doll and began to vie for my share of the
back seat with the Oxydol box and my sister.
</P>
<P>
   I wondered if there was always snow on the ground in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   (Dortha Dunkel lives in Avinger, Texas.)
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(at)txucom.net. If your article
is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville stories, visit
http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
