<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9454 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SAVING-YIDDISH-BOS &LR;      06-20 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVING-YIDDISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ISRAEL, JEWS STRUGGLE TO SAVE YIDDISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ If Yiddish is a dying language, perhaps it is best
not to tell Rivka Basman-Ben-Haim, a poet who believes she can only
express herself in Yiddish, the language she spoke as a child in
her hometown in Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, after the Holocaust, the town she knew is no more,
and Basman-Ben-Haim herself is 75 years old, but she has no doubt
that Yiddish is alive and well. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see more of an interest among young people in Yiddish, but
of course, the life here is in Hebrew, and we Yiddish writers are
like an island, a small island in the Hebrew sea, trying to save
the treasures of Yiddish,'' said Basman-Ben-Haim.
</P>
<P>
   Oy vey, as a Yiddish speaker might say. In Israel, home to
nearly 6 million Jews, Yiddish daily newspapers are no more, the
Yiddish radio hour runs for 25 minutes, and the new chairman of the
World Council for Yiddish Culture does not speak Yiddish.
</P>
<P>
   The once-prestigious Yiddish Writers and Journalists Club in Tel
Aviv has more plaques memorializing the dead than members still
living. High schools prefer to offer French over Yiddish. And the
youngest Yiddish writer of renown is 52 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have good writers, good poets, good books being published,
but the question is for whom are we writing?'' said poet Moshe
Sacher, 72, sipping red wine at one of the weekly gatherings of the
Yiddish writers club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to buy our writings and when they are in the
bookstores, it seems the books are always put in the anthropology
section under `dead cultures,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is an issue that rankles those who love and live the
language, whose usage has declined throughout the world after
Hitler's extermination of 6 million Jews and the assimilation of
Yiddish-speaking Jewish immigrants into American life.
</P>
<P>
   But pain over the declining use of Yiddish _ some say its death
_ may be even sharper in Israel, the state that was formed to
protect and nurture Jews and their culture.
</P>
<P>
   Yiddish experts complain that the language was ignored _ if not
actively suppressed _ by the founders of the Jewish state and the
Zionist movements that helped shape the new society.
</P>
<P>
   One Zionist language association would stop Yiddish speakers on
the street and give them cards that asked them to speak Hebrew
instead. A more radical youth group burned down a kiosk in Tel Aviv
that sold Yiddish publications.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Israel was founded, there was an anti-Yiddish campaign
because they felt they couldn't give Yiddish equal rights, that it
might become the language of the land,'' said Gershon Winer, 76, a
former chairman of the Yiddish department at Bar-Ilan University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now after 40 to 50 years, Hebrew is so rooted that there is no
danger to Hebrew, but there is the danger that after Hitler and
Stalin, Yiddish will be eradicated,'' said Winer.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's first prime minister, David Ben-Gurion, maintained that
Jews needed to shake off the mentality and lifestyle of the shtetl,
or Eastern European village, and remake themselves into an
independent people with their own homeland and own language.
</P>
<P>
   Yiddish, a Germanic-based language that evolved between the
ninth and 12th centuries, represented the old way of life in
Eastern Europe, while Hebrew, revived by Zionists and picked to be
the national language of Israel, represented the new.
</P>
<P>
   But because the common language of many of the new immigrants
was Yiddish, its use had to be dissuaded to ensure that Hebrew took
root. There was also a practical matter. Hundreds of thousands of
immigrants coming from Arabic-speaking countries did not know
Yiddish, and it was essential that a common language be created for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, Israel did have an active Yiddish cultural life
through the late 1970s. The hundreds of thousands of people who
arrived from Europe after the Holocaust learned Hebrew, but they
maintained Yiddish, publishing daily newspapers and magazines, and
creating Yiddish theater.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, when the Soviet Union began to allow some Jews to
leave, Yiddish life here got another boost because it was still the
mother tongue of many of these new immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   But similar to the United States, where the children of the
Yiddish-speaking immigrants often learned very little Yiddish, the
children of immigrants to Israel were encouraged by schools and
youth groups to learn Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israeli attitude doesn't make sense,'' said Mendy Cahan,
36, a Yiddish speaker from Belgium who established the Yung Yidish
cultural association in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say that the Bible is the soul of the Jewish people,
then Yiddish is the representation of Jewish civilization,'' he
said. ``It represents 1,000 years of culture, of history, 1,000
years of looking for a home.''
</P>
<P>
   Yiddish, which gave the world such words as schlemiel (the guy
who always spills the soup), shlemazel (the man on whom the soup
always falls) and shmatte (the old dress used to wipe up the soup),
was once spoken by 11 million Jews, nearly three-quarters of world
Jewry.
</P>
<P>
   Most prevalent in Eastern Europe, it was also the common
language of Jews in such far-flung places as Buenos Aires, New York
and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yiddish represented a great culture. There wasn't a writer in
the world who was not translated into Yiddish, from Shakespeare to
Walt Whitman,'' said Lev Berinski, 61, a poet and director of the
Tel Aviv-based Leivik House, a cultural center named after Yiddish
poet H. Leivik.
</P>
<P>
   There are still pockets of Yiddish spoken _ among some Russian
Jews, elderly Eastern European Jews and within certain
ultra-Orthodox communities _ but for many people, Yiddish is more
about nostalgia than about speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take more than money to make Yiddish culture bloom
again, because there's the biological truth that most Yiddish
speakers are old and nothing can change this,'' said Berinski.
</P>
<P>
   Some Yiddish mavens argue that while the use of the language may
wither, Yiddish will never die, and the important thing is to
search for new ways to encourage interest.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by nostalgia, a summer Yiddish language program in
Lithuania is doing well, as are the Yiddish cabarets, readings and
language classes sponsored by Cahan's Yung Yidish.
</P>
<P>
   ``A language can be alive in many ways and while it may not be
alive like it was in Warsaw, it is still alive,'' said Cahan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
