<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM, HARD LUCK JOIN ALONG THE THAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Do you suppose it's time they just stopped using the
word ``millennium'' around here?
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everything the British attach the word to ends in
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   First it was the Millennium Wheel, the biggest observation wheel
in the world, which was supposed to be the premier place to watch
the fireworks over the River Thames on New Year's Eve, but which
didn't pass safety tests and so couldn't start carrying passengers
until a couple months after the event.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the Millennium Dome, the $1 billion exhibition
hall a little farther downstream that opened on New Year's and has
become Britain's biggest white elephant. The dome's promoters
breathlessly predicted 12 million visitors would help defray the
construction costs by paying about $35 a head to get in before it
closes Dec. 31. But most visitors and critics have panned it. The
promoters have cut their attendance predictions in half, and many
think even that is overly optimistic. The government, meanwhile,
has to keep sinking cash into what has become Money-Pit-on-Thames.
</P>
<P>
   And now, just three days after it opened, the $28 million
Millennium Bridge that spans the Thames had to be shut down
indefinitely because it was swaying too much. The 1,050-foot
pedestrian bridge, which spans the river between the famous dome of
St. Paul's Cathedral and the new Tate Modern Art Gallery, linked
London's past and present, both figuratively and literally. But
last week it became just the latest victim of the Millennium Curse.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the river's cursed, or maybe the river god Thames, whose
statue adorns a park in Richmond, simply doesn't like all this
construction, which is intended to make the river a more central
part of one of the world's greatest cities. After all, the river
had not had an expanse built across it in London since Tower Bridge
opened in 1894.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe, as the Conservative opposition bleats on about, this
is all about Tony Blair's Cool Britannia being nothing but smoke
and mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   There is, as the outpouring of vitriol prompted by these
disasters along the Thames provides testimony to, a new Battle of
Britain being waged, one pitting the hip reformers led by Blair
against the traditionalists of the Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Tories had the idea for the Millennium Dome,
Blair's Labor Party government made sure the thing got built.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the dome is boring and not worth anything near its
price tag, not to mention the infusions of cash it needs so it
won't go belly up.
</P>
<P>
   For all the pessimism, not all is hopeless. After months of
problems in literally getting off the ground, the Millennium Wheel
has spun without trouble since its belated opening. It dominates
the central London skyline and is well on its way to becoming the
institution that its sponsors, British Airways, hope it becomes.
</P>
<P>
   The song ``Millennium,'' by Britain's top-selling pop singer,
Robbie Williams, was actually very good and continues to get
airplay.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, meanwhile, enjoy the swaying Millennium Bridge and
are disappointed by the pledges of engineers to fix it by tinkering
with its design.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Emery, who lives in Devon in the southwest of England, came
up to London to walk across the new bridge. While some have
complained of feeling seasick, Emery thought it was one of the best
attractions in the city.
</P>
<P>
   After England's collapse in the European championships last
Monday against Portugal, losing 3-2 after being up 2-0, perhaps
it's time to start calling the national soccer squad the Millennium
Team.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe if this country is as ambitious as Blair claims, some
of the money that's being thrown down the pit known as the
Millennium Dome could be used to persuade soccer star Ronaldo and a
few other Brazilians to move here and apply for citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be that much of a stretch, apparently. Ronaldo,
Brazilian friends insist, is mad about flat beer and rain. If
that's true, he'd love it here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen is chief of The Boston Globe London bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
