<HEADER>
A9458 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-PAIN-SYNDROME-HNS &LR;      06-20 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAIN-SYNDROME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PAIN SYNDROME STUMPS PHYSICIANS, SUFFERERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SYLVIA WOOD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Jessi-Ann Rosenbaum hurt her pinky finger three
years ago and hasn't been the same since.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a fall on the ice and everything is taken away
from you,'' said Rosenbaum, 41. ``I want my life back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum, who lives in Monticello, N.Y., had no idea that a
sprained pinky would end up disabling her to the point where she
can no longer work, or even clean house. But then, she had never
heard about reflex sympathetic dystrophy, or RSD, until a doctor
diagnosed her with the condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something as minor as a sprained ankle can set it off,'' said
Dr. Eugene Lucier, a pain management specialist at the Albany
Medical Center. ``We don't know why it happens. Men and women get
it, old people get it, young people get it. It can happen to
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   What occurs is somewhat of a neurological mystery. The syndrome
is thought to be the result of damage to the sympathetic nervous
system, that part of the nervous system responsible for much of the
body's routine work _ from relaying messages necessary to keep
organs functioning to controlling the diameter of blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Institutes of Health, these damaged
nerves ``send inappropriate signals to the brain, interfering with
normal information about sensations, temperature and blood flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucier likens the problem to putting the nervous system into
``overdrive.'' The result can be devastating. Even a slight breeze
on the skin can trigger intense pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people don't want to even put shoes on because it hurts
too much,'' Lucier said.
</P>
<P>
   No one is certain how many people suffer from RSD, also known as
complex regional pain syndrome, but the estimates are as high as 7
million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guaranteed way to diagnose the condition. ``There's
no definitive standard that rules you in and rules you out,'' said
James Broatch, director of the Reflex Sympathetic Dystrophy
Syndrome Association of America in New Jersey
(http://www.rsds.org). ``One day you can have all the telltale
symptoms and the next day nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The one standard used by many physicians is ``pain way out of
proportion to the injury,'' Lucier said. There are also some other
signs, including color changes in the skin of the affected area,
swelling and excessive sweating.
</P>
<P>
   In Rosenbaum's case, the RSD spread from her finger into her
other limbs, and has become a chronic condition.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cure.
</P>
<P>
   Some cases of RSD have been known to go into remission but the
key is catching the condition early and starting treatment, ideally
within three months of the first symptoms. But in 50 percent of RSD
cases, pain persists longer than six months and sometimes for
years. When that happens, the bones, joints and muscles around the
affected area can become stiff and start to break down, making any
movement difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In treating her RSD, Rosenbaum has tried a variety of drugs,
including a morphine pump. Some of the drugs most often used
include corticosteroids, vasodilators and injections of local
anesthetics, such as lidocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You usually pull out the entire arsenal when you try to treat
someone,'' Lucier said. ``It's very hard to treat and very
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest frustration for victims of RSD is getting others to
understand their condition. Rosenbaum acknowledges that if she
didn't have firsthand experience with RSD, she would be a skeptic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be honest, if this happened to someone my age, I'd turn
around and say, `Get a life,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after suffering from RSD for three years, and with no end
to her pain in sight, Rosenbaum wonders about her future. She and
her 11-year-old daughter live on disability in a rent-subsidized
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   To help pass the time, she has started an on-line support group
at http://www.angelfire.com/me2/rsdpainpals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wash three dishes today and three dishes tomorrow, that's
a good day,'' Rosenbaum said. ``I just want a normal day.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
