<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9459 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-UNIFIED-BOS &LR;      06-20 1853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-UNIFIED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIFIED MESSAGING PROMISES FREEDOM BY WIRELESS PHONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; With the arrival of summer, thousands of people will be
``working from home'' _ read, ``Down the Cape at the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   But for many white-collar workers, leaving the office can mean
big headaches keeping up with two or three voice mailboxes (work,
home, and wireless), multiple e-mail accounts, and the faxes and
snail mail piling up on the office desk.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are signs of relief, and the promise of less worry and
more efficiency _ and if you don't mind an electronic tether to the
office, a version of the relative freedom summer brought before the
technology explosion.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest emerging telecommunications services aimed at
helping the mobile white-collar worker is called ``unified
messaging,'' or ways to get access to all of your communication
through one device.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, the technology is still very much in its
infancy. But more than a half-dozen companies are developing
products and systems that allow you to consolidate all of your
voice mail and e-mail in one system you can reach from a wireless
or landline phone or a computer desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Some early users of the systems rave about them. ``I have fallen
in love,'' said Ted Tye, a partner at National Development in
Newton, Mass., which manages more than 7 million square feet of
office space in the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Tye began using a system developed by a Seattle
company that lets him get all his messages in a computer desktop or
from his cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really has made my life so much easier,'' said Tye, who is
frequently on the road overseeing projects while trying to shuffle
40 or more incoming e-mails a day plus dozens of voice-mail
messages.
</P>
<P>
   At work, Tye can get all his voice mail and e-mail in one
desktop computer, playing the voice mail out of his computer
speakers and storing them in files like e-mail. On the road, Tye
can call in and hear e-mails read by a speech synthesizer, and
dictate answers _ sent back to recipients as ``wave files'' they
open and play on their computer _ hours sooner than he would be
able to if he had to get back to his office or home computer to
write to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a couple of days of getting used to,'' Tye said, but
people who get spoken e-mails from him in his voice ``will write me
back messages like, `How do you do this? Where did you get this
voodoo magic?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tye's Active Voice system is typical of several that allow users
to log on to a computer screen and see all messages listed, with
little symbols next to them showing whether it's an e-mail, a
digitally converted voice mail, or a fax that can be viewed on the
screen or retransmitted to another machine nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Related services let you ring your office calls to several other
numbers simultaneously _ the phone in your seaside cottage, or a
wireless phone _ and call in to hear a synthesized robotic voice
read you the contents of your e-mail and dictate responses.
</P>
<P>
   Hard figures on how many people now actually use some version of
unified messaging, and realistic estimates of how many might in the
future, are hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is definitely a very dynamic and interesting area,'' said
Dana Gardner, Internet infrastructure research director with The
Aberdeen Group in Boston. ``Unified messaging is likely to ramp up
the way e-mail did.''
</P>
<P>
   WGBH-TV in Boston, for example, is in the process of installing
a Lucent Technologies system for its 1,200 employees _ some of whom
may be on the road making documentaries in Mongolia or Bimini _ to
be able to check voice mail, e-mail and faxes with one phone call.
</P>
<P>
   Some data suggest a huge market potential. The Gartner Group has
predicted that by 2002, up to 40 percent of voice mails could be
delivered through unified messaging systems. The total global
market for companies that provide those systems could reach $5.5
billion by 2003, according to IDC in Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   IDC estimates the number of US business e-mailboxes will grow
13.5 percent a year to 166 million by 2003, while daily e-mail
traffic will soar from 5.3 billion messages last year to 14.9
billion by the end of 2002. By 2003, 47 million US workers are
expected to be mobile, IDC predicts.
</P>
<P>
   Combine those numbers with projections of several hundred
million wireless data users globally within three to five years,
and there seems to be a big potential market of people who want
access to their voice mails and e-mails from anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The etiquette issues of some of these new services _ in
particular spoken responses to e-mails _ could take a little
getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   While Tye has found most recipients of his dicated responses to
e-mail are impressed, analysts note some people might find such a
response somehow arrogant, or a technological headache to deal
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically for when you're stuck in a taxi or something,
so it's great that you even got back to them before you got on the
plane,'' said Rami Safadi, president of UltiVerse Technologies in
Waltham, Mass., a start-up selling services allowing people to use
their wireless phones to get access to Microsoft Exchange e-mail,
calendars, and contact lists.
</P>
<P>
   But given that people have gotten used to getting an e-mail
response to a voice mail, Safadi expects people in time will find
it no big deal to click and hear a spoken response to an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   In a related vein, some people wonder how much time people
really want to spend hearing a synthetic, sometimes choppy voice
reading them their e-mail, unless it is a situation where they are
stuck in traffic with no other way of checking their office mail
than the cell phone. An e-mail that can take five seconds to scan
and discard can easily take a minute to hear read aloud before a
listener determines it is useless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people lose patience with text-to-speech
technology and, don't forget, you're paying for air time the whole
time'' you have some piece of spam read to you, said analyst Amanda
McCarthy of Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the local action involves companies developing products
for Bell Atlantic or other phone carriers to resell to customers.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, iBasis, a Burlington, Mass. company known mainly
for carrying international phone calls over the Internet, has also
developed a Cisco Systems-powered unified messaging service for
telephone companies to resell to customers, at a wholesale price of
$3 to $8 per voice/fax/e-mail mailbox per month.
</P>
<P>
   Also developing systems aimed at phone companies to resell to
homeowners and businesses are Unisphere Solutions in Chelmsford,
Mass., IPeria in Burlington, and hardware maker Comverse Network
Services in Wakefield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Lernout &AMP; Hauspie, a Belgium-based giant in text-to-speech
systems whose main US offices are in Burlington, provides the key
software that powers the iBasis system as well as the free service
offered by Shoutmail.com of Chestnut Hill to hear e-mail read aloud
over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more distinctive offerings comes from CanBox USA of
Woburn, Mass., a subsidiary of a German telecom company. Since last
June, CanBox has sold a service that includes all the digital types
of unified messaging as well as a way to have regular mail sent to
your computer: You get a CanBox postal box where clerks scan in
your incoming mail and send it to you as a picture in an e-mail
that you can print out.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end, CanBox will take a letter you have prepared to
mail to hundreds or thousands of people around the world and have
it printed and mailed from the location closest to recipients to
save time and postage.
</P>
<P>
   Ultiverse in Waltham, Mass., whose roots date to a 1997
business-plan-of-the-year winner at Harvard Business School, is
perfecting a system that allows people who have Wireless
Application Protocol cell phones to get and send e-mail from the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   They can also use the phone to get voice-powered access to
calendars and personal phone directories they store on their office
computer, so they can say ``Call Joe Smith in accounting'' from the
phone without having to look up Joe's number.
</P>
<P>
   Start-up NowSpeed Inc. of Framingham, Mass. is rolling out a
similar product enabling companies to get access to e-mail through
wireless phones, digital pagers, and devices such as wireless Palm
Pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Companies would pay $8 per device per month _ or a maximum of
$20 for multiple devices for each subscriber _ to offer wireless
access to the corporate e-mail account, which could be Lotus Notes,
Microsoft Exchange, or several other systems. A version aimed at
individual subscribers is planned later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to announce this week a promotion offering a
year's free service to the first 5,000 people who sign up, and
25-percent-off rates for people signing up before Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   NowSpeed chief executive David Reske said his company has souped
up the service with some special features, including the power to
convert nine types of document attachments into a format that can
be read aloud over the phone or viewed on the cell phone screen.
Currently most wireless e-mail offerings can not show the contents
of attached documents.
</P>
<P>
   It also keeps your office e-mail ``synched up,'' so when you use
the phone to delete an e-mail, move it to a folder, or forward it,
your e-mail account reflects those changes the next time you log in
from the office computer.
</P>
<P>
   On the phone-only side, Linx Communications of Newton, Mass.
offers a service _ now resold by Bell Atlantic locally _ providing
customers a new local or toll-free number that simultaneously rings
three numbers (say, office, home and mobile). You pay $50 a month
for 400 minutes of incoming and outgoing calls or $100 a month for
1,000 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, it is a less expensive, simpler version of
the Wildfire ``virtual personal assistant'' offered by Wildfire
Communications of Lexington, Mass., which responds to spoken
commands. The promise is you can get one Linx number to put on your
business card that rings to wherever you might be.
</P>
<P>
   People calling your Linx number have to state who they are
before the call goes through, so you can shunt calls to voice mail
or have them transferred to a colleague. Likewise, faxes sent to
the Linx number can be stored for printing out on whatever machine
you can find where you are.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the promise of unified messaging, some analysts
wonder how many people really want to be reachable everywhere by
every mode all the time _ and whether this really signifies
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The core problem is that we are all over-messaged,'' said
McCarthy, the Forrester analyst. ``Unified messaging can't solve
that problem for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is ``assessing the practicality of it, rather than
the `Gee whiz, you can actually do this,' aspect,'' McCarthy said.
``I would bet only 5 percent of companies really need this and
would have IT guys who would shell out for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
