A9460 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-DESTROYER-MUSEUM-HNS &LR;      06-20 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESTROYER-MUSEUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WARTIME DESTROYER DRAWS TOURISTS, VETERANS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ What once was a vessel of war is now a siren for
a singular group of tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The USS Slater , a World War II destroyer escort, has attracted
33 groups sponsoring military reunions this season. While the ship
is open to the public as a museum, the military veterans constitute
an additional niche market.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipated 2,238 reunion guests will spend more than $1.55
million in Albany County _ dollars the area wouldn't have attracted
otherwise, according to an estimate from the Albany County
Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe every Destroyer Escort Group left will eventually
come to the Slater, I really do,'' said Raymond Crumley, a World
War II veteran from Georgia helping to plan a September reunion for
people who served on the USS Savage.
</P>
<P>
   While the Slater isn't the Savage, it is the only one of 565
original destroyer escorts still afloat, and one of only four
surviving. It was opened for reunions in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 and 1999 combined, it attracted 30 groups, said
marketing director Deborah Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Word of mouth _ or word of e-mail among veterans _ has spread,
and people appear happy to travel during summer months for their
reunions to Albany's Snow Dock, where the Slater now is tied up. It
is cared for and owned by the privately run Destroyer Escort
Historical Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Crumley is anticipating the Slater will generate
higher-than-usual attendance at his upcoming reunion, which usually
draws about 50 people, counting spouses.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the ship, it stirs attention and brings back memories,
Crumley said: ``A DE sailor is a DE sailor.''
</P>
<P>
   Destroyer escorts were developed in World War II to respond to
the threat posed by submarines. The escort was a smaller, more
maneuverable vessel than the larger ships serving as troop convoys.
The escort's job was to sail along with the troop convoys and try
to detect and deflect attacks from enemy submarines.
</P>
<P>
   Destroyer escorts often took torpedoes before convoys.
Sometimes, the escorts traveled in small groups around a convoy for
even better defense.
</P>
<P>
   Some vessels went on into later service. The Savage, for
instance, saw duty in both the Korean and Vietnam wars, Crumley
said, so he is hoping this reunion attracts some Vietnam veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Christos J. Saffaras, a Navy veteran of World War II from
Latham, N.Y., will be at the Slater again in September for the
reunion of his ship, the DE 104. Saffaras, 75, thinks this may be
one of the last reunions of World War II veterans, because of their
advancing age, and said he is glad the Slater is available for use
as a backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Crumley and some friends even will help refurbish the vessel, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said the Slater also has attracted a larger group, members
of the Destroyer Escort Association. That meeting should attract
about 800 people to Albany from Sept. 10 to 15, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
