<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9461 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-AIDS-OUTBREAKS-BOS &LR;      06-20 1754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-OUTBREAKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH AIDS DRUGS, MANY GAY MEN SEE LESS DANGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It all looked distressingly familiar: a men's sex club,
unprotected intercourse, an outbreak of syphilis.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been a more common combination 20 years ago,
before AIDS devastated gay communities, prompting a nationwide
crusade for ``safe sex.'' But this syphilis outbreak hit late last
year. Local health workers found that a cluster of men, 11 by last
count, had contracted the disease, and had traced the infections to
the Safari Club, a Boston gay men's spot that had been closed by
the city last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Those events, followed by similar ones in other cities, have
health officials worried. Although total syphilis cases reported in
Massachusetts have remained steady, the gay men's share of those
cases has now jumped to 34 percent. This is high enough to concern
Department of Public Health officials, who met with gay activists
on June 16 to address fears of an increase in unprotected sex.
</P>
<P>
   The state officials' vigilance might be premature: The number of
HIV cases in Massachusetts has not increased, although symptoms are
found months after exposure, and diagnosis can be made months after
that.
</P>
<P>
   But a survey of AIDS activists has found that they, too, are
concerned that with a sense of crisis abating, as new drugs
significantly extend the lives of HIV-positive people, many gay men
are relaxing their attitude toward unprotected sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say whether it's a significant minority or a
small minority of vocal individuals,'' said Brian Byrnes of the
AIDS Action Committee in Boston. ``But we're definitely hearing
that there are individuals who are making what many of them believe
is an informed choice to have unprotected . . . intercourse with
sex partners.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are numerous, according to AIDS prevention
specialists: Some men may choose unprotected sex because they and
their partners are already HIV-positive, and they hear that the
likelihood of contracting more virulent strains is slim.
</P>
<P>
   Some may find that unsafe intercourse has become a preference, a
calculated risk in the interest of greater pleasure. And others may
see unprotected sex as a kind of surrender: After years of anxiety
about the disease, some gay men are too fatigued to remain
vigilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay communities have been living in a kind of emergency for
two decades now about this, and there's a point at which it gets
normalized,'' said a Berkeley psychologist, Walt Odets. ``It's easy
to forget that for gay men, this is like being in London during the
Second World War, and after a while one becomes numb and
desensitized to the extremity of the situation. One way to deny the
emergency is to go out and pretend it doesn't exist. It's like
going to an outdoor cafe during the blitz.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue is more common among older men, psychologists said. For
younger men, with only dim memories of lesion-racked 30-year-olds
leaning on canes, a preference for unprotected sex has arisen
largely as the result of new drug therapies.
</P>
<P>
   For longtime AIDS activists, the situation is disheartening: The
dramatic shift in sexual practices in the 1980s has been a point of
pride among older activists, who note that safe sex took root among
gays more quickly than among straight people.
</P>
<P>
   Gay men, ``in the midst of the epidemic, took responsibility for
each other,'' said Marshall Forstein, medical director of mental
health and addiction services at Fenway Community Health Center and
assistant professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School. ``The
AIDS epidemic crystallized a political and social movement.''
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, the message was simple: a condom every time,
no matter what. Vigilance was a matter of life or death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've changed gay male behavior phenomenally, more than any of
us ever thought they could,'' Forstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Because HIV infections can be difficult to trace, transmission
of syphilis has always been a marker of sexual responsibility. In
the early 1980s, gay men accounted for half of all syphilis cases
in Massachusetts. Ten years later, safe-sex messages had been so
effective that gay men accounted for less than 1 percent, according
to state figures. And that small percentage has remained steady for
almost 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   That was why the outbreak at the Safari Club was so alarming,
officials said. At the club, three men had been infected, then had
transmitted the disease to at least eight more men. Half of the men
infected, including the first three, are HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not young kids,'' Michael Whelan, deputy director of
sexually transmitted diseases for the Massachusetts Department of
Public Health, said of the syphilis cases that were reported this
year. ``You can maybe understand someone who's missed the whole
AIDS epidemic and they're 18 and just coming out, but that's not
what we're seeing. It's people who have been around, and are aware,
and have just chosen to take the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fenway Community Health Center reported a doubling of
gonorrhea cases this year. And over the past two years, sexually
transmitted diseases among gay men have spiked in other cities, Los
Angeles, San Francisco, and Newark among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly an indicator of things to come,'' said Whelan.
``If you increase the pool of infected people, you increase the
number of people at risk, and the cost of taking care of the
problem is clearly greater.''
</P>
<P>
   And for each documented instance of unprotected sex, health
officials know there are many more. They say they see anecdotal
evidence that attitudes are shifting, at least among those who
frequent bars and clubs and the Internet. A preference for
unprotected intercourse has even entered the ``hanky code,'' the
lexicon of signals by which some men indicate their sexual
preferences in bars, said researcher Michael Scarce, who is writing
a book on the subject. Its sign is a navy blue kerchief with white
spots.
</P>
<P>
   Scarce, who has talked to scores of gay men for his book, said
that new AIDS drugs have changed the equation. Younger men assume
that if they contract the disease at 30, Scarce said, it will take
10 years before they become symptomatic, and another 15 until the
drug therapies stop working. They might be 55 or 60 before they get
really sick, they figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a fool. I don't think HIV has gone away. But life is a
series of risks. It's an issue of quality of life versus quantity
of life,'' said David, a man in his 30s who no longer uses condoms
and spoke on condition his name be changed. ``How many years will
not eating ice cream actually buy me? Smokers go through this all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists who treat gay men emphasize that a desire for
unprotected sex is understandable. It was, after all, perfectly
normal to have sex without condoms before AIDS struck. And they see
many men who engage in unsafe sex at least some of the time:
National surveys have found that at least one-third of gay men
admit to having had unprotected sex with multiple partners in any
six-month period, and that substantial numbers of those men did not
know their partners' HIV status.
</P>
<P>
   At first, specialists had thought that HIV prevention was a war
against ignorance. But now they are increasingly aware that
psychology is just as potent an enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many men feel it's not a matter of if, but when,'' said Miguel
Rivera, who runs a Manhattan discussion group for men who avoid
condoms. ``They're tired of worrying. Some have buried lovers and
friends, and have this prevailing sense that HIV will catch up with
them at one point.''
</P>
<P>
   Forstein added that in many ways, unprotected sex ``is the most
life-affirming event some men can imagine. How do you keep the
devil at bay? Go head-to-head with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists who treat gay patients say early safe sex
messages, successful as they were, had alienated some men because
they did not take account of the complexities of their sex lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the '80s, we lied to people,'' Forstein said. ``We
said that safe sex was better sex, telling them it was just as much
fun to do it with a condom as it was to do it without.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Web sites for those who prefer unprotected sex are full of
references to AIDS prevention organizations as ``condom Nazis,''
accusing them of demonizing men who have risky sex the same way
some have demonized homosexuality itself.
</P>
<P>
   Such rejection of safe sex, unthinkable a few years ago, is
largely traced to protease inhibitors, AIDS-fighting drugs that
have dramatically slowed the progress of the disease, making it
less fearsome.
</P>
<P>
   Donations to organizations like AIDS Action have been slipping.
Advertising for this year's AIDS Walk hammered home an idea: ``AIDS
is still a crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest statistics in Boston and elsewhere suggest that
slogan may be more than just rhetoric. In Los Angeles County, for
instance, 93 cases of syphilis among gay men have been reported
since March 22. Usually, Los Angeles sees 100 cases of syphilis in
an entire year. Half of the men whose infections were reported this
year are HIV-positive. Having syphilis makes the other men far more
likely to contract HIV from unprotected sex, which worries health
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be very surprised if we didn't have an increase in HIV
transmission and other STD diseases,'' said Dr. Jonathan Fielding,
director of public health for Los Angeles County. ``Syphilis is
treatable. We know we don't have a cure for HIV, and treatment is
arduous. The overall toll is so substantial, so I'm very
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Some organizations, AIDS Action and Fenway Community Health
among them, are adjusting to the environment, replacing an
insistence on safe sex at all times with the concepts of safer sex
and harm reduction.
</P>
<P>
   These groups acknowledge that men might not always use condoms
during sex, and they offer them ways to at least reduce the risks.
They are also trying to treat the epidemic as a mental health, not
just an education, problem, recognizing that some men do not insist
on condoms because of low self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   There is now a support group for HIV-negative men at Fenway, and
the health center is part of a national study called Project
Explore, which tracks thousands of HIV-negative men over several
years to determine what kinds of one-on-one counseling best equip
them to negotiate sexual relations as the disease endures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9462 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-GAYS-RELIGION-HNS &LR;      06-20 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-RELIGION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SHUNNED BY MAINSTREAM CHURCHES, GAYS WELCOMED AT SOME HOUSES OF
WORSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN GUTIERREZ-MUIR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Prayers were offered and hymns were sung.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of fellowship as mothers, fathers, children and
couples filled the pews of Rainbow Cathedral on a recent Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beloved, God truly does love you,'' the Rev. John Nicholas,
pastor of the 200-member church, told his congregation.
</P>
<P>
   The service was like many throughout San Antonio on any given
Sunday. There was one big difference: the majority of those in the
pews were gay or lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   Being gay while being faithful is something that, when noticed
in other churches, has caused controversy and consternation. Entire
denominations that regard homosexual inclinations or behavior as a
sin are arguing over what role, if any, openly gay churchgoers can
have in religious life.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Stotts, president emeritus of the Austin Presbyterian
Theological Seminary, said Christianity has grappled with the
homosexual question since its earliest days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church has struggled over the centuries to develop
perspectives on pressing issues,'' Stotts said. ``Racial equality
was one issue. Women being ordained or serving in leadership
positions is another. People take different positions. It's the
same way with the homosexual question.''
</P>
<P>
   Presbyterian theology does not prohibit people from being
members or holding office because of their sexual orientation,
Stotts said, but gay Presbyterians are required to remain celibate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexual orientation itself is not a sin. But the behavior that
comes with it is,'' Stotts said.
</P>
<P>
   Few pastors in mainstream denominations in San Antonio or Austin
perform same-sex marriages, but one who does said his congregation
has been enriched by not only accepting but embracing as equals
gays and lesbians who enter a committed relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Art Severance, pastor of First Unitarian Universalist
Church in San Antonio, said he has performed about two dozen union
ceremonies for lesbians and two for gay men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religiously, it's a wedding,'' Severance said. ``Legally, it's
not _ yet. I liken it to the civil rights era when a white would
never marry a black or a minister would be divorced.''
</P>
<P>
   Such unions, and the ordination of gay clergy, have become
topics of open debate at leadership gatherings of Protestant
denominations, and Stotts said it would be foolish to assume gays
and lesbians are not already part of most Christian churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just don't flaunt it. They're not out of the closet, so
to speak,'' Stotts said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas, the openly gay pastor of the Rainbow Cathedral, an
affiliate of the Universal Fellowship of Metropolitan Community
Churches, said that is precisely why the fellowship of churches was
established in Los Angeles in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is welcome at our church, including heterosexuals,''
said Nicholas, a Navy veteran and pastor of one of a half-dozen
congregations in San Antonio that openly accept gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Coinciding with an emerging gay and lesbian movement in the
1960s, the establishment of the Metropolitan Community Churches
offered church services for those whose sexual orientation made
them unwelcome, or made them feel that way, in the denominations
they grew up in.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, a network called Dignity/USA was formed
to provide Masses for gay Catholics. The Catholic Church has never
officially sanctioned the group, but even in conservative South
Texas, a handful of sympathetic priests celebrate Mass each Sunday.
One of the priests, the Rev. Eddie Bernal, said it's considered an
``outreach ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gays and lesbians have been told a lot of lies and have been
made to feel horrible about themselves,'' Bernal said. ``Many times
people in religion have scapegoated on gays and lesbians, pointing
their finger at them and causing them to suffer from unnecessary
low self esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Dignity they find solidarity, support and love. They find
what every Christian church should offer them: love.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jim Cottone, a retired professor of infectious diseases at
the University of Texas Health Science Center in San Antonio, being
forced to give up either his sexuality or his religion is out of
the question. He has been attending Dignity services since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dignity completes me,'' Cottone said. ``It makes me realize
that my upbringing as a Catholic is still part of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dignity congregants are reluctant to reveal where they hold
services. Nickie Valdez, who has been a member of the group since
1983, remembers a Sunday in 1987 when members got in their vehicles
after Mass and drove off.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't get far. The lug nuts on their wheels had been
removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly a message,'' Valdez said. ``Luckily no one
was hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the Presbyterian Church (USA) and the Episcopal
Church will debate sanctioning same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, United Methodist Church leaders voted to uphold
their doctrine that homosexual behavior is incompatible with
Christian teaching. It also adopted a policy requiring clergy to be
faithful in heterosexual marriage or celibate otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, messengers at the Southern Baptist Convention in
Orlando, Fla., voted to revise the Baptist Faith and Message
Statement to oppose homosexuality, along with what they called
``all manner of deviant and pagan sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Although each Baptist congregation is autonomous, the statement
is viewed as the closest thing the denomination has to an official
creed.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Central Conference of American Rabbis, which
represents 1,800 Reform rabbis serving more than 1.5 million Reform
Jews, approved a measure allowing them to perform same-sex
commitment ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Lasalle R. Vaughn, pastor of New Life Christian
Center, a nondenominational Christian church in San Antonio, said
the growing lesbian and gay movement and increasing public
acceptance of same-sex unions is blasphemous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the Bible says homosexuality is a perverted
lifestyle,'' Vaughn said. ``Just like all of those having sex
outside of marriage. That's perversion.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he is offended by the notion that those opposed to
the gay lifestyle are bigots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm African-American and being homosexual does not make you a
minority,'' Vaughn said. ``We're not going to accept it in this
church.''
</P>
<P>
   Wes Giles, who attends services at Rainbow Cathedral, said
anti-gay sermons from fundamentalist pulpits breed hatred and
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about hell and damnation, fire and brimstone,
especially if you're gay,'' said Giles, a volunteer coordinator for
the San Antonio Gay and Lesbian Community Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I run across that hate, my response is John 3:16. Jesus
Christ died for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact John Gutierrez-Muir by e-mail at
jgmier(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
