u a BC-SCI-CLIMATE-BOS &LR;      06-20 1675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CLIMATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL WARMING COULD ALTER NEW ENGLAND DRAMATICALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No colorful foliage in the fall to lure carloads of leaf
peepers, and no sugarhouses for brunch in early spring. Hardly any
skiing in the winter. Dwindling potato fields in the Maine
countryside. And a coastline pounded and eaten away by violent
storms.
</P>
<P>
   That could be the New England of 2100, according to an
unprecedented White House report on the impacts of climate change.
The draft review, issued last week for a 60-day period of public
comment, paints a picture of dramatic change in New England as well
as in the rest of the nation, drawing attention as never before to
the wide variety of effects that could be triggered by the global
warming scientists expect to accelerate over the next century. And,
they emphasize, there could be big surprises as well.
</P>
<P>
   The report marks a significant new phase in attempts to quantify
the results of the greenhouse effect, which causes the planet to
warm up when certain gases _ many of them produced by human
activity _ accumulate in the atmosphere. While previous efforts
have concentrated on global effects, the new report, called
``Climate Change Impacts on the United States,'' attempts to detail
what the results would be in our own backyards. While the effects
are a mixed bag _ agricultural yields nationwide are expected to
increase, but so are both droughts and floods _ the overall picture
is sobering.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it turns out that a great deal of local variation
has been masked in the global summaries, but shows up in detail in
this localized analysis. For example, a small increase in average
temperatures for the whole planet could produce killer heat waves
in some regions, as well as some places that actually get colder.
</P>
<P>
   What that means, said William Moomaw, professor of international
environmental policy at Tufts University, is that ``there are going
to be some losers, even if some areas are better off. Some places
will be much worse off.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States as a whole is expected to experience about
double the globally averaged temperature rise, according to both of
the computer models studied. While the amount of that increase
remains uncertain, the United Nations-backed International Panel on
Climate Change has predicted that the planet's temperature will
rise 1.8 to 6.3 degrees Fahrenheit by 2100. In the United States,
however, the new report says the projected increase is 5 to 10
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics last week seemed to misunderstand the distinction
between the global and US forecasts, citing the difference as if it
were a discrepancy between the two reports. In fact, said Peter
Raven, an ecologist who heads the goverment panel that evaluated
the report and made suggestions for revisions on early drafts, the
US forecast ``is not only consistent, it's drawn from the same
model'' as the global forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the US effects are more severe than the global ones, the
White House report says, ``Regional and local level impacts are
much more pronounced than those at the national level.''
</P>
<P>
   That difference between regional and global effects is not just
based on projections; it is also reflected in what has already
happened. For example, while temperatures worldwide have increased
about 1 degree Fahrenheit over the last century, Alaska has already
undergone a 4-degree warming during that same period.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting the climate on a regional level is even more
difficult, however, than forecasting the planet's temperature, a
task that has required the most sophisticated computer models ever
developed for environmental problems. As a result, the White House
study is the first comprehensive regional climate forecast for the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   By identifying these local effects, the report ``really brings
this global problem down to Earth,'' said Susan Moser, a staff
scientist with the Union of Concerned Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the report goes out for a 60-day comment period during
which Anthony Janetos, a scientist with the World Resources
Institute and cochairman of the panel that prepared the report,
hopes for a broad public debate on global warming and its possible
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the report has become part of the larger Washington
debate on global warming, in which the White House has pushed for
actions to reduce US emissions of carbon dioxide and other
so-called ``greenhouse gases'' while many members of Congress have
questioned whether climate change is a real fear. They say the real
issue is the damage to the oil, coal and other industries that
would result from limiting US emissions.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate floor last Friday, speakers complained that the
two different climate models cited in the report often give
different projections _ and, in a few isolated cases, even opposite
ones (for example, one model predicts Southwestern forests will be
replaced by grasslands, while in the other, trees flourish).
</P>
<P>
   ``These complicated models . . . are still not accurate enough
to provide reliable forecasts on how the climate may change,'' said
Sen. Chuck Hagel, Republican of Nebraska. ``The several models
often yield contradictory results.''
</P>
<P>
   But such criticisms are ``a bad misreading of the results and of
how science is done,'' said Tufts' Moomaw. Scientists ``do come at
this in different ways, using different tools. Rather than average
(the two models' results), it is better to have all these concerns
reflected _ it at least raises the possibility of what might
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   During Senate debate, however, study cochairman Janetos conceded
that ``we're not making a specific prediction about what the future
will be like. It would be farcical to try to do that.'' Rather, the
intent was to provide ``what-if'' scenarios based on certain
assumptions, including that no aggressive steps are taken to try to
curb emissions.
</P>
<P>
   In many areas, the models actually agree:For example, both show
that, under the expected amount of warming, maples will virtually
disappear from the United States, including all of New England, and
will remain only in Canada. But where the models do disagree, Moser
said, there should be further analysis and research.
</P>
<P>
   And study cochairman Janetos warned that people shouldn't
automatically assume that the less-severe prediction is the one
that is more likely to be accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any reason to suspect that one is more likely than
another,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Moomaw said the 1980s debate over the hole in the Earth's
protective ozone layer should be a sobering reminder that the
reality ``can be worse than we anticipated, instead of better.''
The giant hole in the ozone layer that has emerged over the South
Pole had not been forecast by any model.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that is very hard to predict is the way both
agriculture and natural ecosystems will adapt to climate change.
The report says that, in general, agricultural yields will increase
because of the fertilizing effect of higher carbon-dioxide levels,
and because of longer growing seasons in some places. (One of the
few exceptions is potatoes, whose yields could decline by more than
20 percent under one model).
</P>
<P>
   But, because the changed climate will alter the optimum growing
regions for different kinds of plants, such increased yields will
only occur if farmers are able to adapt by changing the crops they
grow in a given place. But that is not always easy.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, shifting crops is more than a matter of
temperatures and rainfall. There also can be significant costs to
farmers for different seeds, fertilizers and machinery, and these
could present real strains in places where farmers are already
working on razor-thin margins. And, while the climate may shift the
growing zone for a given crop northward, that doesn't necessarily
mean that suitable soils will be available there.
</P>
<P>
   As for natural ecosystems, the report warns that, in some cases,
especially in small, isolated zones or where there are boundaries
imposed by urban sprawl, it will simply be impossible for an
ecosystem to shift to a new location. For example, alpine meadows
in the rockies and coral reefs off Florida and Hawaii could suffer
irreversible damage, the report concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Many such systems already face problems because of unrelated
pressures, such as air or water pollution or urbanization. ``One
has to consider climate change in the context of a lot of the other
environmental stresses people are concerned about,'' said Janetos
of the World Resources Institute. Assessing the interactions among
all the factors that will affect land, air, water and living things
is ``extremely difficult to do. We've made a first step.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The environmental system is so complex, there will be
surprises,'' Moser said. ``We should take that as seriously as any
of the other findings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the science is a cautionary tale,'' Moomaw said,
``particularly if the consequences are highly damaging and
irreversible. Then, we ought to use the precautionary principle,
rather than use uncertainty as an excuse for inaction.''
</P>
<P>
   On one thing at least both the report and its critics
wholeheartedly agree _ the need for far more research to try to
reduce the uncertainties. ``Science must drive policy and not vice
versa,'' said Sen. Larry Craig, Republican of Idaho. ``We owe to
our constituents and to future generations to seek answers and not
hide from whatever turns up.''
</P>
<P>
   Janetos, who cochaired the White House study, feels that the US
political response so far, while decidedly mixed, is moving in the
right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are now a lot of people around the country who are
taking a step back from the ideology and saying this is an
important issue, we need to understand it and understand what the
adaptation options are. I hope it will be an ongoing process.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The full draft report can be viewed on the Internet at the
following address: www.usgcrp.gov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
