<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURSE FILLED WITH ANIMATED OBSTACLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABERDARE NATIONAL PARK, Kenya _ Tiger Woods will never be called
on for this shot. But a wandering Texan named Bill Evans is
undaunted by the high-and-mightily-mobile hazard in front of the
green at the fourth hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``What club would you like to clear that giraffe, sir?'' asks
Evans's caddy _ me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the 10-iron will do it just fine,'' Bill says.
</P>
<P>
   Since club selection is fairly limited (three instruments: 10
and 5-irons, plus putter, on rental from the pro shop), I briskly
hand him the 10. The rubbernecking giraffe, sensing our approach,
just as briskly glides off into a woods no tiger will inhabit. But
possibly a lion or two. We saw one down the road a couple of hours
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, saying the 10-iron will serve as well as a wedge, lofts
his ball onto the green. Beautiful _ except that the ball stays
where it lands, as though encountering emerald molasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect the only rolls are at lunch,'' he muses correctly
after 3-putting from 12 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Piga mzuri, bwana!'' shouts guide Kim Edmonds. ``That means
good shot, sir, in Swahili, the local tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the Aberdare Country Club in the East African wilds, a
lush course where you may move a ball 6 inches without penalty if
it has alighted in an animal hoofprint on the green. Or in a stack
of elephant doo-doo anywhere. Whenever an elephant hollers, it may
not sound like ``Fore!'' but it's probably wise to get out of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free drop given if a baboon takes the ball,'' advises the
scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   A 40-minute flight from Nairobi, past snowy Mount Kenya and then
a jaunting bus ride, the ACC is a zoo without bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not your every-day round,'' says Bill, who has golfed across
the world.
</P>
<P>
   But there are nine holes, and a 19th hole overflowing with
Tusker beer and tales _ preferred lies? _ you won't hear at The
Country Club in Brookline, Mass. Such as bodily holes-in-one by
poor souls tumbling into aardvark tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   Guide Edmonds, says, ``In an earlier time if you asked somebody,
`What did you shoot today?' the reply might be, `Three over _ and a
buffalo and a couple of water bucks on the sixth.' But hunting is
no longer permitted in Kenya.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but,'' wonders Bill, ``does it go both ways? Are the
resident beasts prohibited from hunting us?''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Magondu and Francis Ojul, a couple of groundskeepers
toiling at the tri-level, steeply uphill seventh, are reassuring.
``I don't think any player has been trampled by an elephant or
eaten by a lion,'' Ojul says. ``But if a baboon wants your ball let
him keep it. They can be foul-tempered.''
</P>
<P>
   Although you can't carry a gun, maybe a fixed bayonet on your
putter would be prudent.
</P>
<P>
   A Kenyan named Phil West says he once tried the course, but
thought better about playing through a rhinoceros snorting around
the second green. The twin horns looked like a double-bogey to
West, and ``I decided to retire to the bar where I'd rather take my
chances with pink elephants than a black rhino.''
</P>
<P>
   A lovely layout with adventurously lumpy greens, tilting
fairways and sawdust bunkers, the course is decorated by plenty of
handsome trees: fig, olive, acacia, pink-flowering chestnut, and
euphorbia (built like a green candelabra). Mount Kenya looms as the
backdrop. Congregations of vividly-hued birds, like red-feathered
fire finches and yellow-and-black weavers, provide the sound track.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever we putt, black-winged creatures called go-way birds
utter hoarse laughs, sounding, ``Gway! Gway!'' Among other
chittering kibbitzers are leaping, long-tailed colobus monkeys.
Black with white faces, they bear a bearded and hooded resemblance
to Ayatollah Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
   The constant up and down plodding is good exercise. ``Too many
hills and gullies ever to have carts here,'' says Bill. ``You'd
have a wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   A mixture of pars 3 and 4 add up to 33, none of them longer than
297 yard No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Rate it sportily different. ``Much of the sport lies in watching
out where you're walking _ dodging and avoiding you-know-what,''
says Bill, a nimble hop-scotcher. ``This is the best fertilized
course I've ever seen. Can you tell who or what's been here, Kim?''
</P>
<P>
   Any good guide is an expert excrementologist, Edmonds no
exception. ``Zebra and dik-dik _ a tiny antelope _ here,'' she
points. ``There's giraffe, warthog, peacock. Some eland and water
buck. You ought to be carrying a pooper-scooper club.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the short length, three blind greens and sharp dog legs
make the round a little tricky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around here call them hog legs,'' says Edmonds. As if on cue,
a family of five tusked warthogs scoots down the fairway, waddling
but quick.
</P>
<P>
   Bill likes the fifth hole, especially because a maintenance road
curls near the green. ``The local road hole. Reminds me of the
famed Road Hole at St. Andrew's in Scotland. Except that Jack
Nicklaus never chipped a ball into a giraffe footprint there. I'm
one-up on him in that respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The stone clubhouse behind the ninth green dates back to 1932,
colonial days when the ruling Brits installed golf here. Cascading
bougainvillea and poinsettia trees enhance the finish line. Tall
hedges and a bright flower garden near the building preserve a
British air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' says Bill. ``Nothing like this in Dallas. But I
sure couldn't read those greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they were in Swahili.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9466 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-PSYCHOLOGY-TODAY21-CO     06-20 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHOLOGY-TODAY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Use of placebos can help in healing
 &HT;    By Hap LeCrone
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the back of his wooden wagon he learned forward toward the
crowd. In one hand he held up a brown bottle, hailing its potent,
curative powers. His other hand mesmerized the audience by twisting
his lengthy handlebar mustache around his long graceful fingers.
Was he a snake oil salesman or a purveyor of alternative medicine,
a century before his time? In either case, the success of his
magical remedies was largely dependent on the power of the placebo
effect.
</P>
<P>
   The placebo's history dates back to medieval times when
mistranslations of the 116th psalm in the Hebrew Bible resulted in
the Latin phrase ``I shall please.'' In the middle ages,
professional mourners were hired to sing vespers (placebos) for the
dead. By the early 19th century, placebo referred to a medicinal
treatment given more to please than to benefit the patient. Medical
problems where the patient's self-report is used to measure
intensity such as migraine headache, back pain, post surgical pain,
rheumatoid arthritis, angina and depression often respond well to a
placebo. Other more objectively measured problems such as blood
pressure, some skin conditions such as warts, and heart rate can
also respond significantly to placebos.
</P>
<P>
   Placebos are also used in experimental medicine. The
experimental (active substance or treatment) is given to one group
of patients and an inert (inactive substance or treatment), a
placebo, is given to a control group. At the end of the study the
two groups are compared in order to assess whether any changes that
take place are due to the experimental treatment or to
psychological factors. Some medical researchers have concluded that
between 30 and 70 percent of any treated group will respond to a
placebo. In fact, some studies have shown the placebo effect to
exceed those attributed to the active drug.
</P>
<P>
   There are several explanations for the placebo effect. Perhaps
the most widely accepted is that the placebo effect appears as an
involuntary conditioned reflex of the patient's body. People who
have experienced relief in medical settings or from ingesting a
pill are ``primed,'' like Pavlov's dogs, to do the same again. The
placebo effect then is a result of the patient's expectation of an
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Current medical thinking encourages health-care providers to
make use of the powerful self-healing forces of the mind-body
connection. The savvy health-care provider introduces treatment
with enthusiasm and optimism rather than simply suggesting that the
treatment may or may not be of assistance to the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Dear readers: I receive a lot of mail from readers suggesting
material for this column. Recently, I received a humorous piece
titled ``16 Things It Takes Years to Learn.'' I published this in
my column in the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald May 21, with the
notice that the author was unknown. I have since found that this
material was originally published in Dave Barry's book Dave Barry
Turns 50.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hap LeCrone is a clinical psychologist. If you have
questions or topics you would like Dr. LeCrone to discuss, write
him 4555 Lake Shore Drive, Waco, Texas 76710 or e-mail him at
hlecrone(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9467 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-GROUP-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     06-20 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-GROUP-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... would see?  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unplanned as ever, I decided to try a group tour and to let
someone else do the heavy lifting and thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Several days before its nine-day, seven-night trip to Sicily was
to leave, the Richard Durgan Travel Service of Stoneham informed me
that there was a space for me in a group of 38, most of whom were
friends, relatives, or neighbors who had traveled together before.
</P>
<P>
   Once committed, I began to worry. What if no one talks to me or
wants to eat with me? Can I spend hours on tour buses with total
strangers? Can they do the same with me?
</P>
<P>
   There was no need to worry. At Logan Airport, I was met by a
friendly, smiling woman named Mary, the tour leader, who had
already brought our tickets to the Alitalia counter.
</P>
<P>
   Seven hours later at Milan's Malpensa Airport, Mary saw to it
that we all went to the right gate on time for the 1 1/2-hour
flight to Catania Airport in Sicily. Under her watchful eye, our
luggage arrived the same time we did.
</P>
<P>
   At Catania, we were met by Rosa Rizza, one of the local guides
engaged by Durgan Travel and one of the finest. Rosa went to Sicily
23 years ago from her home in Plainville, Conn., to attend
university. She married a Sicilian and now has two teenage boys.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa saw to it that we and our luggage all got on the same bus
for the hour's ride to the Hotel Ariston in Taormina, a resort high
on the slopes of Mount Tauro overlooking Sicily's Ionian coast.
</P>
<P>
   It was a relief for me not to have to run around trying to find
a room.
</P>
<P>
   The three-star Ariston is a charming Mediterranean-style hotel
constructed of white cement, with a red-tiled roof and wrought-iron
balconies draped with wisteria and tropical flowers. After some of
the hotels I had stayed at in my travels, it was paradise.
</P>
<P>
   For seven days, we were able to eat three scrumptious meals a
day from a buffet table laden with in-season vegetables, local
fish, meat, poultry, and homemade breads, including panetonne.
</P>
<P>
   In my lone travels, most of my meals have been of mysterious
content from street stalls, usually eaten standing on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Ariston's chef, Carmelo Catania, told me he prepares
eggplant, my favorite food, 23 ways. I hoped to sample them all.
</P>
<P>
   For seven days, Rosa, Mary, and several other tour guides made
life easy for us. I could always trust that Mary would sit with me
at meals, just as she was there for the others in the group. When
one of us felt nauseous on the bus, Mary was there with the
wastebasket. When another was buffeted by winds walking to a
historic ``duomo'' (church) on a cliff, Mary commandeered a private
car to take her down to the bus.
</P>
<P>
   When I had to change dollars to lira, Mary took me to a bank,
told me how to check my camera in a cubicle outside, as required,
and then pass, one at a time, through a glass enclosure as a guard
watched our movements.
</P>
<P>
   Our seven days in Sicily were filled with activity. When we
weren't riding along spectacular mountain roads with hairpin turns
in Mercedes buses navigated by drivers named Angelo, Giovanni,
Mauricio, and Dino _ all with nerves of steel _ we were walking up
cobbled streets and steps for another breathtaking site.
</P>
<P>
   We walked a lot, mostly uphill, but what we found was always
worth it. Being a mountain goat would have helped; but, I never saw
an overweight Sicilian.
</P>
<P>
   One day, I went on my own on an optional bus tour to Agrigento
to see the stunning Greek ruins at the Valley of the Temples and I
missed my regular tour buddies. The strangers I had met the week
before at Logan Airport had become friends.
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, we said our goodbyes when Mary and the group
went to Rome and I headed for five days in Malta, a 25-minute
flight from Catania. I had thought there was a ferry running
between Sicily and Malta but I would have had to go far south to
Pozzallo to catch one and that depended on the weather.
</P>
<P>
   I began to feel lonely as I watched my group leave. I can't wait
to see the photo the men took of us women out front of the church
at Forza d'Agro where some of the scenes in ``The Godfather'' had
been shot.
</P>
<P>
   As I waved goodby to Mary, I suddenly felt like a child who had
lost its mother in a department store.
</P>
<P>
   Malta, I told myself, would prove that I could still travel on
my own. It did, but it wasn't so much fun.
</P>
<P>
   I began to feel back in my ``loner'' groove on Air Malta's
flight back to Catania to connect to Milan and, then, home.
</P>
<P>
   I passed up Air Malta's 4 a.m. flight to Catania. Maltese use it
for a day's shopping trip. I opted for the 5:25 p.m. flight, happy
it would get me back to Catania, a city I didn't know, before
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, we were still on the ground in Malta. The plane
was waiting for in-transit baggage from Casablanca; the owners of
the baggage were already on board.
</P>
<P>
   A reservation had been made for me at a hotel in Catania. ``A
three-star,'' I had been told, unaware how varied that rating can
be.
</P>
<P>
   Finally off the ground in Malta, it was 9 p.m. before I finally
cleared customs in Catania, too late, I decided, to be driven
through the streets of a big, strange city only to have to return
the next morning for the flight to Milan.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I made up my mind to stay awake at the airport all
night and read. Looking around for someone who spoke English so I
could ask where the comfortable seats were, one young man
responded.
</P>
<P>
   When I found his only English was, ``Hi, baby,'' I decided
staying at the airport was not a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   A Mr. Alloni, a kindly Alitalia employee at the airport who did
speak English, convinced me of that. The ``polizia'' would evict
me, he said.
</P>
<P>
   By now, exhaustion had shattered my broken Italian. Mr. Alloni
told the cab driver the hotel I wanted and asked the fare: 35,000
lira, or about $18.
</P>
<P>
   The ride through Catania to the outskirts seemed a lot longer
than the 15 minutes I was told to expect. The hotel was dismal. It
reminded me of the places I stayed in my pre-tour days.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's feisty proprietess and I did not hit it off. The
room with breakfast was priced at 170,000 lira, or $97, she told
me. ``Big bed, big bed,'' she said, touting its double bed.
</P>
<P>
   Too tired to quibble, I took the rickety elevator to the
fourth-floor room to find the ``big bed'' was two cots pushed
together, a phone that didn't work, and a hand-held shower.
</P>
<P>
   I put my coat on over my pajamas, my shoes on bare feet and went
to the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   `'This is a dump,'' I said, trying to imitate the line made
famous by Bette Davis in the 1949 film, ``Beyond the Forest.''
``Not worth $97.''
</P>
<P>
   (Right now, the easiest way to convert lira to dollars is to
halve the amount, so 170,000 was closer to $85. What Miss Davis
actually said was, ``What a dump!'').
</P>
<P>
   The proprietess stood firm. ``I am going to report you to the
polizia,'' said I. A paper and pencil appeared on the counter.
``120,000 lira'' was written down, now $60 instead of $97. I left
for the airport at dawn the next morning, arriving four hours
early. I skipped the ``breakfast included'' at the hotel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
