<P>
   DAYTON HEARTLAND POLITICAL PROJECT
</P>
<P>
   Part 4 of 5 parts
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-PA _ Before we begin, will Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge
be Gov. George W. Bush's running mate? If the answer is yes, and it
might be, then move Pennsylvania into the GOP column and go on to
the next topic. Even Democrats in the Keystone State concede that
putting the popular governor on the ticket would guarantee Bush a
victory. ``I think he's a solid leader with a great, sparkling
resume,'' a Democratic member of the Pennsylvania General Assembly
said. ``Now, if Ridge is on the ticket it would make things more
difficult for me....''Perhaps more than any other state,
Pennsylvania is a vexing jumble of political identities. Anchored
by major urban centers Pittsburgh and Philadelphia on opposing
corners, vast miles of the state are rural farm and hunting land.
Last week the state mourned the death of a beloved former
Democratic governor who gained national fame as a rare opponent of
abortion in his party. Ridge, the popular Republican of today,
favors abortion rights. The winner in Pennsylvania will have to
avoid offending Catholics, who outnumber all other regligious
groups in the state, appease one of the largest retiree populations
in America, deal with pockets of deep union support, and thread the
needle on gun control between rural gun advocates and suburban
voters hypersensitive to the dangers of firearms and children.
(Montgomery, Dayton Daily News). 50-60.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-PABAR _ From most any downtown angle, the renaissance
is hard to see. A warren of one-way streets surrounds the main
drag, which is ruled by faintly traveled dime stores and the odd
tattoo parlor. On successive blocks off this road, called Hamilton
Mall, worn row houses still project the image of a working class in
decay. The Allentown of the Billy Joel song back in 1982. A place
still best defined by the absence of something, which in this case
would be the absence of Big Steel.But what a few dismal vistas fail
to reveal is that a sense of optimism now beams through Allentown
and neighboring Bethlehem, twin anchors in a two-county region
known as the Lehigh Valley. This cradle of industrial innovation
and might, where plans were drawn and steel was forged to build the
Golden Gate Bridge and large chunks of the New York skyline, is in
the midst of a rebirth. The Lehigh Valley of the 21st Century is
pulling itself up with bootstraps sewn not from leather, but from
fiber optic cable. In a state where political identity feels
transitory, few places are more in transition than the Lehigh
Valley. The fate of Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic nominee
for president, and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican
nominee, seems likely to rest here on the direction to which
cross-party voters flow. (Montgomery, Dayton Daily News). 20.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
