<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DO YOU NEED SO MUCH WATER EVERY DAY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q.Health guidelines indicate that eight glasses of water should
be consumed every day. I can understand why caffeinated beverages
cannot be substituted, but why not herb tea? Does it really have to
be straight water?
</P>
<P>
   L.P., Lexington, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You lose water all day long through a combination of
perspiration and other bodily processes, and you obviously have to
replace it or you'll die. The eight glasses you cite are a sort of
nominal guess for what might make sense, but, of course, you have
to modify it according to your personal needs. Clearly you'll need
more on a hot day or when you're exercising.
</P>
<P>
   Your body will get the water it needs from any food or drink
containing water, so there's no real reason not to go for juice or
tea (herb or otherwise). One thing to watch out for is that if you
drink beverages that contains diuretics (caffeinated or alcoholic
ones, for example, or so-called medicinal teas that contain other
diuretics), you may stimulate your body to excrete water and have
to take in even more to compensate. You may also want to watch for
the calories that you take in with drinks that contain sugar or
alcohol; pure water is calorie free. Finally, you may find that you
absorb water better when it has some salts and electrolytes in it,
such as sports drinks or fruit juices.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, common sense is a good guide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
