<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9471 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-SQUID-ART-BOS &LR;      06-20 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SQUID-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 FOR THE LOWLY SQUID, IT'S CURE VS. CUISINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODS HOLE, Mass. _ They come to the shores of Cape Cod every
year for a summer mating festival, and they make biologists very,
very happy. The slim, translucent squid give scientists insight
into everything from the roots of Alzheimer's disease to the
mechanics of vision, and they're ripe for the picking in the waters
around Woods Hole.
</P>
<P>
   But they're also valuable deep-fried and dipped in tartar sauce.
</P>
<P>
   That has Woods Hole scientists worried: As demand increases and
fish populations decline, there's ever more pressure on the squid _
what the scientists call ``Loligo pealei'' and the rest of us call
calamari.
</P>
<P>
   It's a conflict that reflects the precarious balance of ocean
life, and the state of commercial fishing around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Because of increased demand, more efficient gear, and years of
fishing with few limits, many ocean species have been overfished,
so much that some biologists fear they're in danger of extinction.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, the biggest troubles have hit the traditional
staples, haddock and cod. As stocks have decreased and restrictions
have increased, many fishermen have turned to other species, said
Roger Hanlon, director of the Marine Resources Center at the Woods
Hole Marine Biological Laboratory. Over the last three or four
years, he said, more and more of them have been catching squid.
</P>
<P>
   And the prospect of losing the squid carries an even greater
risk. If scientists lose their research tools, we could be eating
our way out of a cure for Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the squid has become the third most valuable
fishery in the Northeast, accounting for $33 million in annual
sales, Hanlon said. The market, for now, is mostly overseas, but
it's growing everywhere _ as evidenced by its popularity on local
menus.
</P>
<P>
   Calamari is served at nearly every Woods Hole cafe, to
decreasingly squeamish patrons. Mark Roscoe, assistant chef at the
Landfall Restaurant, said interest in the dish is on the rise, as
long as there are no tentacles on the plate. While many Cape chefs
buy frozen squid in bags, demand for fresh and frozen catch across
the region is clearly increasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is greater than ever before,'' Hanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   The sort of squid that fishermen catch along the East Coast is
what biologists have nicknamed the ``Woods Hole squid,'' which has
a life span of one year. The squid spends winters out at sea near
the Continental Shelf, but comes to coastal waters every summer to
spawn. It has eight tentacles called ``arms,'' a pair of uncannily
human eyes, and a large central nerve known as an axon.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies much of the squid's special value: The axon is 100
times wider than a human neuron, capable of being seen by the human
eye and studied in-depth with a powerful microscope. (It also has
the ability to live and function for six to eight hours after being
removed from the squid.)
</P>
<P>
   Discovered in the 1930s, the axon's research potential draws
hundreds of scientists to Woods Hole every summer, largely to study
the way nerve cells transmit chemicals and information. George
Langford, a biology professor at Dartmouth College, has been
studying the squid at Woods Hole since 1972. In three decades, he
said, he has seen the understanding of nerve functions grow
exponentially, particularly as scientists learn more about the
makeup of DNA.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Langford and his students are studying the way
chemicals travel along the nerve, research he hopes will soon yield
information that will eventually help Alzheimer's patients and
people with spinal cord injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But the squid isn't only good for its nerve. Hanlon has been
studying the squid's behavioral patterns, which he says give
insight into how birds and mammals choose their mates.
</P>
<P>
   Sex, for a squid, is a complex thing, Hanlon said. The squid
change their coloring dozens of ways to attract and repel each
other. Males alter their tactics for moving in on females,
depending on the size and strength of the competition. Females
narrow down the field of partners by waiting for males in
hard-to-reach places.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with DNA fingerprinting, Hanlon and other researchers can
measure the results of the squid pickup scene better than ever,
determining exactly which males have fertilized which eggs, and
learning which tactics are most successful _ for squid and for
other species.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in evolutionary terms, there's a lot of benefit to
looking at different animals,'' Hanlon said. ``The commonalities
just stare at you after awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this research demands a lot of squid. Langford said his
laboratory group, one of 25 that study the squid every summer,
dissects about 200 of the creatures every week. Overall, the Marine
Biological Laboratory goes through about 10,000 squid _ each of
which weighs less than a pound _ every season, Hanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing compared with the 15 million pounds of squid that
will be caught in Massachusetts waters this year, but it's an
important cache, Langford said. Scientists haven't yet perfected a
way to raise squid in a lab, he said, so Woods Hole researchers
depend on the wild variety, pulled from the water in nets and
stored in huge, cylindrical tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about it a lot,'' Langford said of the squid fishing
crunch. ``If we cannot get animals for our research, then we are in
very, very big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanlon has been busy promoting squid conservation in recent
years, working with state and federal fisheries managers and
independent groups of fishermen to study populations and assess the
health of the stocks. The inshore summer fishery isn't his only
concern, he said; a 5-year-old winter fishery, farther out in the
North Atlantic, takes in three times as many squid each year. And
because cod and haddock like to eat squid, he said, an ample
population is key to restoring the stock of those fish.
</P>
<P>
   But the dangers to the squid probably have decreased in recent
years, because of new state and federal restrictions, said Dan
McKiernan, a biologist at the Massachusetts Division of Marine
Fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for the first time, he said, the federal government
limited by half the amount of squid the offshore fleet could catch,
``a big, big thing'' by squid fishing standards.
</P>
<P>
   And about a decade ago _ sensing the kind of pressure Hanlon
fears _ the state set limits on inshore squid fishing as well.
While squid were once fair game all summer, McKiernan said, now
they can only be caught near the shore for about six weeks a year,
at the start of the spawning season.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Hanlon and his colleagues aren't proposing a
moratorium on squid-eating. ``I love calamari,'' Hanlon said, and
he has strong opinions on the best way to cook it (for maximum
tenderness, he says, cut the tube lengthwise instead of in rings.)
</P>
<P>
   And posted in Langford's laboratory is a former student's recipe
for ``squid fantastic'' _ breaded and served with a special dip
made of mayonnaise, pickles, and roasted red peppers. It's tasty
enough to make biologists put aside their worries at their picnic
each summer, Langford said.
</P>
</TEXT>
