<SLUG> BC-MARC-ANTHONY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTHONY LIGHTS IT UP
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Latin-pop sensation Marc Anthony didn't need the Lakers victory on
Monday to kick the crowd's excitement level up a notch at the Greek
Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   But when hooting erupted between songs and someone handed
Anthony a tiny TV on stage, he couldn't help but make the post-game
announcement that drew cheers: ``Reggie Miller's crying, so it
looks good.''
</P>
<P>
   It was icing on the cake during a perfect evening that saw the
salsa star bring a tropical heat wave to the packed outdoor venue.
Often lumped with Ricky Martin and Enrique Iglesias, the razor-thin
Anthony seems more driven by music than media.
</P>
<P>
   A tasty orchestra, which included 17 elegantly attired musicians
and backup singers, offered a propulsive, percussion-fueled romp
through old and new material sung in English and Spanish, along
with ``stuff I probably have no business doing,'' Anthony joked
early in the set.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony, born in New York's Spanish Harlem to Puerto Rican
parents, showed there were few songs he had no business doing. A
consumate showman, the singer and actor, who cut his teeth singing
backup for teen group Menudo and later performed in Bronx and
Manhattan dance clubs, was in constant motion throughout the first
of two nights at the Greek, running across the stage, leading the
band with king-fu kicks and greeting a steady procession of women
bearing roses and lingering smooches.
</P>
<P>
   However, the recently married Anthony, 31, seemed to lack a
great deal of natural charisma, even while commanding attention
with heartfelt readings of such smoldering ballads as ``Don't Let
Me Leave'' and ``De La Vuelta,'' from his self-titled second mostly
English-language album.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps he prefered to let his music speak for him, which it
did with eloquence on the moving Top 10 hit ``I Need to Know,''
which Anthony performed on the Grammys telecast earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the best moments during the warm set came when Anthony
returned to his salsa roots and allowed his superb band to work out
on extended tunes like ``De La Vuelta,'' which started slowly but
morphed into an uptempo dance number.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK to stand up,'' Anthony told the heavily female crowd,
which didn't need to be prompted.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Anthony, who played a dreadlocked homeless psycho in
Martin Scorsese's ``Bringing Out the Dead,'' created a frenzy just
by walking out on stage.
</P>
<P>
   But when he interjected at one point, ``The Lakers won, folks,''
an exceptionally hot night got that much hotter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
