u a BC-AIDS-CHASERS-BOS &LR;      06-20 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-CHASERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW INTENTIONALLY SEEK OUT HIV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They compose a tiny minority, and inhabit the fringe of the gay
community, but many of the health professionals who work with gay
men and HIV have seen or heard of a few of them.
</P>
<P>
   They are men who have moved beyond embracing unprotected
intercourse as a sexual preference to embrace HIV itself.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a generation after it was first reported, some men have
turned the virus that causes AIDS on its head, seeing in it
appealing qualities like community and kinship.
</P>
<P>
   In the parlance of the burgeoning chat rooms and Web sites
devoted to the subject, they are called ``bug chasers,'' men who
deliberately try to convert their HIV status from negative to
positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another whole level of distress people are carrying
around,'' said Marshall Forstein, medical director of mental health
and addiction services at Fenway Community Health Center in Boston.
``These are people who don't feel entitled to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Forstein knows of one man who was 65, and shunned by his family
after coming out late in life. Also isolated from the gay
community, the man fantasized about getting HIV, Forstein said,
``because suddenly, he'd have a whole world of people around him,
delivering meals to him, paying attention to him.''
</P>
<P>
   That is partly because of the role HIV has played in gay
communities since AIDS was first reported in 1981. Then, gay men
mobilized more effectively than ever before, taking charge of
prevention, and solidifying ties to each other. That brought them a
respect from the mainstream that had hitherto eluded them, from
people as diverse as President Ronald Reagan and red ribbon-wearing
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``HIV allowed gay men a public presence and a demonstration of
intelligence and competence and management skills that they hadn't
had an opportunity to express publicly,'' said a Berkeley
psychologist, Walt Odets. ``The other more uncomfortable thing is
that gay men have gained a lot of acceptance by being sick and by
being chaste.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Valenzuela, a California activist who stopped using condoms
and eventually contracted the disease, said, ``AIDS was a great
war, and there's a great amount of courage and respect and
romanticism that surrounds soldiers in war. When I was entering the
gay community at the height (of the epidemic), I felt like I'd
joined a war. And that somehow transformed HIV into this rite of
passage as opposed to something to be reviled and avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   In postings by men who want to get, and give, HIV, the virus has
also become a means of kinship. Some Web sites and chat groups
advertise ``conversion parties'' at which an HIV negative man has
unprotected sex with several HIV positive men to ensure he
contracts the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In the chat groups, the virus is framed in the language of
birth, not death: here is HIV infection as genealogy. The HIV
positive man who infects another man with the virus _ called ``the
gift'' _ is a ``father.'' Men infected by the same HIV positive man
are ``brothers.'' The moment of infection is spoken of like
impregnation: one chat group devoted solely to conversion stories
is called ``Knocked Up.''
</P>
<P>
   Infection creates ``a death to the old life and a rebirth to the
new one,'' wrote a frequent contributor to one chat group, who
calls himself GiftGiverSF, and identifies himself as an HIV
positive. ``The new life includes gaining a new Dad, many brothers,
whose genealogy will be traced and given to all who want it, an
intense bonding for life, and for death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9476 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS &LR;      06-20 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CELL PHONE, NO SUV, NO E-TRADE . . . SURVIVE THAT! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fat and happy with the runaway success of its mid-season hit,
``Survivor,'' CBS announced last week that next season's
installment will plop a new group of 16 contestants in the
Australian outback, where they will spend 39 days whining,
conniving, and generally showing humankind at its double-crossing
best.
</P>
<P>
   Reports say the show's producers also considered the African
wilderness and the Peruvian Andes as follow-ups to the current
jaunt on an island off Borneo. There, contestants who are supposed
to work together inevitably turn on each other like mad dogs, then
vote one member off the island each week. The ``survivor'' will
pocket $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, episode three drew 23 million viewers. After
thoroughly tattooing Regis Philbin's monochromatic hide during its
first two weeks, ABC moved its once-unbeatable ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire.'' With such enviable ratings (which have increased
each week), it's a sure bet the other networks are scrambling to
concoct their own hokey, and _ they hope _ deliciously addictive
``Lord of the Flies'' knockoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they'll have to tweak the formula a bit. See, while
there's something to be said about watching city folk stumbling and
bumbling about on a deserted island, killing and eating rats for
dinner (much to the chagrin of People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals), or slurping down beetle larvae in yet another round of
Stupid Survivor Tricks, producers need not traipse half a world
away to find a setting for their show.
</P>
<P>
   We now have a sense of what it's like trying to inhabit a
deserted island. But it would be even more interesting watching
people trying to survive in their familiar surroundings with all
their amenities and creature comforts taken away.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine it: Sixteen people in the big city with no credit cards,
cell phones, pagers, CD players, or computers. No access to bank
accounts. No tony apartments or houses like on MTV's ``The Real
World.''
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, make folks abandon their current jobs and work for
minumum wage _ that's $5.15 an hour. If you think people behave
badly when they have limited fresh water on an island, think of a
40-year-old investment banker stripped of his Palm Pilot and Range
Rover, reduced to donning a paper hat and name tag while trying to
survive the lunchtime crunch at the local fast food joint. Then we
could watch him waiting forever at one of those awful 24-hour
check-cashing places whose fees would eat up way too much of his
measly pay.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's entertainment!
</P>
<P>
   The show could be set in just about any sizable American city.
Contestants would have to work together in such things as dealing
with difficult landlords, and buying groceries at overpriced
convenience stores since, on minimum wage, no one could afford to
live in a neighborhood with a decent supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, each show would be tailored to fit the particular
peccadilloes of each locale.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, contestants would be allowed to earn no more than
$15,000 a year. In a city where the monthly damage for a
one-bedroom apartment averages $1,600, participants could vie for a
$600 a month domicile by trying to be the first to make it from
Greenwich Village to the Bronx on a Saturday night when station
after station is closed for never-ending construction. And there
would be a special reward for anyone who survives reaching for
their wallet when surrounded by police in the foyer of their
apartment building. (This seems like the sort of thing that Fox,
after years of airing ``Cops'' and ``World's Scariest Police
Chases,'' could really pull off.)
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, contestants would have to get around the City of
Angels without cars _ an impossible task _ relying instead on the
world's most inept mass transit system. On the upside, the LA
participants wouldn't even need apartments since they would spend
all their time waiting for buses that never arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Boston, of course, contestants would have to endure just
the opposite _ they would have to drive every single day without
benefit of a street atlas. They would have to suffer the constant
slings and arrows of cranky, ticket-happy meter maids,
mind-boggling rotaries where no one ever yields, and parking
problems that grow more unwieldly each week.
</P>
<P>
   As in New York, yearly salaries could not exceed $15,000 which,
these days, couldn't even secure a park bench on the Common. In the
Big Dig portion of the competition, there could be tribal games to
see who could make the quickest trip between Ashmont and North
Station during morning rush hour with the fewest instances of horn
honking, cursing, or obscene gestures.
</P>
<P>
   If you thought watching people eat a rat last week was tough,
imagine being trapped in a car with Rudy, that annoying retired
Navy Seal, on the Central Artery. Now that would be something to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
