<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9480 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-TRAVEL-BOS &LR;      06-20 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TRAVEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE TRAVEL FIRMS GAIN GROUND BUT BUMPS REMAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A longtime Internet shopper, Kathy Keating deftly maneuvers
through the Web's music and book stores. But her recent attempts
online to plan a six-week trip to Europe may send her running back
to her trusty travel guides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a jungle out there,'' said Keating, 32, a public
relations director. ``I'm just trying to book a regular vacation
and I'm like, this is a headache.''
</P>
<P>
   As the summer travel season heats up, customers have been racing
to the Web in record numbers to bid on airline tickets, book hotel
rooms, and to rent automobiles. But shoppers are quickly
discovering that planning an entire vacation online is far more
complex and frustrating than purchasing a novel on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Keating, for instance, says she has been unable to find a
comprehensive Web site that offers her the lowest airfares, the
best hotels, and detailed maps. In recent weeks, she has grown
irritated by the number of sites that require passwords, which she
sometimes forgets.
</P>
<P>
   She likes the idea of booking unique lodging online, but she
doesn't quite trust Web sites to weed out hotels and inns with
leaky roofs, seedy neighborhoods, and ill-tempered innkeepers.
``I'm like, `Who are these people?' ''
</P>
<P>
   There is little question that Web travel sites have made great
strides in recent years. Indeed, Internet agencies have grabbed
enough customers to hurt some traditional travel agents. By 2004,
online leisure travel purchases are expected to balloon to $32
billion, or 12 percent of the industry, from $7.8 billion last
year, according to Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the giants, Expedia.com and Travelocity.com, are molding
themselves into powerful, full-service travel agencies, offering
consumers an array of tools to compare airfares, hotel prices, and
car rentals.
</P>
<P>
   At Expedia.com, customers can book a castle in Umbria, Italy,
for $6,000 a week. Like Priceline.com, another popular site,
Expedia.com allows its customers to bid on airline tickets.
Travelocity.com's strengths are in its hotel offerings, which
include maps, a bed-and-breakfast directory, and a place where
customers can rant and rave about hotels (and they do).
</P>
<P>
   But consumers and industry observers say the online travel
business still has a long way to go before it lives up to promises
of providing busy vacation planners with the lowest prices, the
best customer service, and a one-stop shopping experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have bits and pieces right now,'' said Terry Trippler, a
consumer advocate who writes for 1Travel.com. ``They have to prove
themselves. Next summer is the time that you'd better have your act
together _ or you're going to be left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, most travel consumers on the Web are browsers, not
buyers. Less than 5 percent of new visitors to travel sites end up
booking a trip or flight. By comparison, Internet retailers like
Amazon.com, Pets.com and Sears.com bring more than 10 percent of
surfers to the cash registers, according to May figures from PC
Data, a technology research firm in Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Travel site executives say the gap is natural and reflects the
graduation of consumers from simple purchases of books and compact
disks to more complicated and expensive transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has taken a while to really have a meaningful percentage of
people (buying travel online),'' said Richard Barton, chief
executive of Expedia Inc. ``People had to get comfortable with
using the service before hitting the buy button. They had to
believe the service was capable and reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   Susana Lopez, an advertising consultant in Brookline, has become
a convert. She has used the Web to help book trips to New Orleans
and London with her husband and two children. She's now perusing
travel sites to plan a family skiing trip to Chile in August.
</P>
<P>
   The sites give her the freedom to research smaller towns and
make arrangements from her desk in the wee hours. Travel agents,
she said, can't help her unless they specialize in the kind of
off-the-beaten-track travel she prefers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (travel sites) have made great advances in five
years,'' Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Ed Boudrot, a product manager for an Internet firm,
decided to book a last-minute and much-needed trip to Bermuda from
Travelocity.com. He said he and his wife had been under enormous
stress and had not had the time to plan a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a lot of confidence in it, to tell you the
truth,'' Boudrot said. ``At that point, it was like rolling the
dice. I kind of put my trust in the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, he said, was mediocre. And he said he probably could
have found a better vacation package if he had had the time to do
extensive research. But in the end, Boudrot said he was pleased.
``Overall, it solved our problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other customers aren't as pleased with the state of online
travel sites. Numerous sites have sprung up, offering cluttered and
sometimes glitchy Web pages. Shoppers also complain about Internet
sites that refuse to answer e-mails or pick up their phones _ even
during emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites have tried to win customers' trust by offering
ratings and reviews of lodging and restaurants. But some consumers
aren't convinced that Web sites are as diligent as travel guides
such as Fodor's and Frommer's.
</P>
<P>
   Those suspicions aren't far off the mark. Expedia.com, for
instance, ``screens'' customer reviews of hotels listed on its
Vacationspot.com site. Although it claims to edit only the comments
that don't appear credible, you'll have to search long and hard
before you find any reviews that don't contain words like
``fabulous,'' ``beautiful,'' and ``wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrating experiences online have a few customers racing back
to the bookstores for travel books. Still other online shoppers are
knocking on the doors of their old travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kutrubes Travel Agency in downtown Boston, owner Kathy
Kutrubes says a woman recently called for help after a Web site
refused to refund her airline ticket. ``She said she would never do
it again,'' said Kutrubes.
</P>
<P>
   A desperate family called Village Tours &AMP; Travel after
discovering that they had booked a flight for the wrong month,
thanks to an online typo. They had showed up at the airport, but
had no ride. ``It was ugly,'' said Deb Carr, owner of Village
Tours.
</P>
<P>
   Carr says that online travel sites don't always provide the
lowest airfares or best lodging. An experienced travel agent, she
said, knows when the airlines are cutting prices _ and how to sniff
out reliable and unique hotels around the world. That's why she
doesn't mind when her clients flirt with the e-travel sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some go to e-commerce,'' Carr said. ``But they end up coming
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
