<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9481 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-VENTURE-RISK-ART     06-20 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VENTURE-RISK-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURE CAPITAL RUSH CARRYING HEAVY RISKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seventy percent.
</P>
<P>
   If history is a guide, that's how many start-up companies,
fueled by the technology-investing fervor of the late 1990s, are
likely to fail. And when they do fail, they could leave a costly
trail of wreckage behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Behind those young companies are billions of dollars in venture
capital. This once-mysterious realm has become as pervasive as real
estate speculation in the 1980s, and its failures will be felt
across a broad swath of the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer volume of dollars pouring into venture poses risks
that economists are only beginning to ponder. And the Federal
Reserve is taking notice, proposing tighter limits on how much
banks can bet on the sector.
</P>
<P>
   Banks are just one stream in the raging river of cash out there.
Among those inking deals and fattening the coffers of venture firms
are corporations, pension funds, insurers, mutual funds, and
wealthy individuals _ all of them hungry for big returns, few of
them experienced in this highly risky corner of the investment
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the invisible hand of capitalism at work,'' said
Oliver Curme, a general partner with Battery Ventures in Wellesley,
Mass. ``That's the drunken hand of capitalism wasting money. And
it's wasting money on a scale comparable to the S&AMP;L crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists injected $48.34 billion into 3,649 companies
from Boston to Silicon Valley last year, a 152 percent jump from
1998, according to Venture Economics in Boston. Meanwhile, firms
raked in new venture money at the same clip, reaping a record
$46.55 billion from investors eager to join the party. That's 67
percent more than they raised in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Curme, a former banker, and other seasoned venture capitalists
worry that too much money in the hands of inexperienced investors
will translate to scores of bad deals. With every collapsed Web
company will come layoffs, broken leases, and a string of lawyers,
advertising firms, and other service firms left in the lurch,
sometimes holding worthless stock options they accepted instead of
fees.
</P>
<P>
   The collapses have already started to come in e-commerce, and
industry watchers expect scores more. Historically, only three in
10 start-ups has made it, and no one from Wall Street to the Web
research houses expects the new economy to change that.
</P>
<P>
   The question is how much damage a slew of failures could inflict
on the broader economy.
</P>
<P>
   There's about $100 billion in venture money sloshing around the
market, half of that waiting to be invested. That's a lot of cash
to wash over the economy in a brief period. Mark Zandi, chief
economist at RFA/Dismal Sciences of West Chester, Pa., calls the
phenomenon ``quite dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   In relative terms, it's far less than, say, the $5.2 trillion
market value of the stocks listed on Nasdaq, or the $1 trillion
managed by mutual fund giant Fidelity Investments. But it's in the
ballpark with the big run-up in commercial lending by thrifts from
1982 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Zandi said, venture firms don't carry the kind of
central role in the economy that thrifts did. But the venture shops
clearly have played a huge role in propelling the new economy, he
said. Any mass failure of companies they've backed could cause
ripple effects in the economy _ especially in New England, where
there's a heavy concentration of venture firms and the high-tech
companies they finance.
</P>
<P>
   Consider an example of how venture has worked its way into the
fabric of the economy. In one of the last patches of decay in
Boston's South End, a developer is turning old mills into chic
rental space. There's exposed brick, original wood beams, high
ceilings, and sunlight streaming through sparkling new windows.
</P>
<P>
   Digs that only artists and students would have called home a
decade ago are being wired for work stations and Internet
connections. Young entrepreneurs are clamoring for such space. And
in a recent bidding war for 25,000 square feet in this emerging
high-tech SoWa district, the winner was TechSpace, a venture
capital-backed real estate firm that caters to Web start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   TechSpace's business _ which started in New York and is
expanding to other cities _ depends on the continued health of the
venture business. The same is true for the start-ups that move into
the building _ and for GTI Properties, the developer.
</P>
<P>
   People enmeshed in the tech world remain optimistic. Said Read
Coughlin, a former real estate broker who's building up TechSpace
in Boston: ``I can see the real estate market slowing down. I can
see the stock market slowing down. But I don't see technology
slowing down.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither do evangelists like Howard Anderson, a founder of
Battery Ventures, the Yankee Group, and the YankeeTek Incubator.
But even the true believers see excess in this market. Anderson
predicted recently: ``You're going to see some abject failures in
venture capital.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve is clearly waking up to the venture frenzy
and zeroing in on the banks it regulates. The Fed is proposing that
banks set aside 50 cents of reserves for every dollar of venture
capital they invest, vs. a modest 4 cents today. The idea is to
create a bigger cushion against losses.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank also wants to impose a cap of $6 billion on
private equity activities by banks, or 30 percent of a bank's Tier
1 Capital, whichever is less. For FleetBoston Financial Corp.'s
venture group, the nation's number two bank-owned venture group,
behind Chase Manhattan, that would mean a cap of about $4 billion _
not far above the size of its current $3.3 billion portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers are objecting strenuously to the limits.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before a US Senate panel Tuesday, Rick Fritz, chief
of Fleet's main venture group, BancBoston Capital, said the unit
had been profitable in all of its 41 years of business. Some
investments have been losers, Fritz said, but the portfolio as a
whole has always made money.
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston vice chairman and chief financial officer Eugene
McQuade said in an interview that there should be leeway for
longtime players like BancBoston. To let bigger but less
sophisticated groups amass bigger portfolios, he said: ``We think,
from a risk standpoint, doesn't make any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Fed governor Laurence Meyer, testifying before Congress last
week, praised venture capitalists for helping propel the new
economy. But he warned that the easy gains made in taking companies
public in recent years could dry up.
</P>
<P>
   The bull stock market has delivered more ``home runs'' on IPOs
in recent years than is typical, Meyer said, making up for any
losing bets in spades. In a less hospitable market, he said,
``Small declines in asset values would eliminate large proportions
of (banks') small equity base.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet has $187 billion of assets, and Tier 1 capital of about
$13 billion, so even a total wipeout in its venture activities
would take no more than a 15 percent bite out of its capital base,
McQuade said.
</P>
<P>
   Banks account for only a sliver of all venture deals. What
economists don't know _ and won't for some time _ is what havoc
venture investors are wreaking far away from the Fed's watchful
eye.
</P>
<P>
   Battery's Curme offers a grim forecast. ``Most of what's been
funded over the past three years will go belly-up, or it will get
merged,'' he said. ``It'll be very, very ugly. But people won't see
it for another 18 months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
