<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ROUNDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL WARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Travel agents can barely conceal their contempt for online
travel sites, which continue to swipe more of their sales. And even
among the virtual travel players, few pleasantries are traded.
</P>
<P>
   But both online and offline travel firms have united now that
they've discovered a common and more formidable foe in their back
yard.
</P>
<P>
   The new enemy is Orbitz.com, an upcoming online site backed by
five major US airlines. Debuting later this summer with $100
million in funding, it is expected to be a dominant force, offering
Web shoppers everything from airline tickets to cruises.
</P>
<P>
   The looming threat has travel agents and their online
counterparts complaining to politicians and federal regulators.
Last week, an Internet travel trade organization that includes
Travelocity.com and Expedia.com accused the airlines of creating an
``Internet travel cartel.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtual and traditional travel agents fear the airlines will use
Orbitz.com to offer steep discounts to consumers, only to raise
rates once the competition has been clobbered. If this sounds
familiar, it's because American Airlines was sued last year by the
Department of Justice for allegedly battering discount carriers
with predatory pricing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a concerted effort to change what e-commerce is all
about: openness, freedom, and competition,'' said Ed Rothschild,
spokesman for the Interactive Travel Services Association, which
represents the dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   Orbitz.com officials have defended the site, saying it will
behave without bias. But the Department of Justice is now reviewing
the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time federal watchdogs have taken note of
giant industry alliances on the Web. The Federal Trade Commission
has been looking into a new Internet marketplace developed by the
Big Three automakers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Web retailers could forfeit up to $19 billion in revenue this
year if they fail to improve the online shopping experience,
according to a recently released report.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, some sites have become less customer
friendly, said Phil Terry, chief executive of Creative Good, a New
York consulting firm that published the report.
</P>
<P>
   The problems? E-commerce sites have gotten carried away with
fancy features, failed to adequately staff call centers, and, in
some cases, lost their focus by rushing into new markets, Terry
said.
</P>
<P>
   Terry remains confounded by the number of e-commerce sites that
appear to pay more attention to their investors than their
shoppers. As evidence, he cites the increasing number of e-commerce
sites that require customers to remember passwords to enter their
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Although Web sites claim passwords help them protect and better
serve customers, Terry says the requirements may backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine going to a store and having a security guard stop you,
saying, `Before you pay, you have to say the secret word,' '' he
said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, customers surveyed by Gomez Advisors said they
had the most confidence in eToys Inc., compared to other online toy
stores. Their next-best picks were other Internet-only retailers
such as SmarterKids.com and Toysmart.com.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing behind the virtual stores were toysrus.com,
wal-mart.com, and other sites backed by traditional retailers. Last
Christmas, these sites angered customers with poor inventory
controls and late deliveries, among other problems.
</P>
<P>
   But virtual retailers that pride themselves on well-designed
sites and reliable deliveries are learning a harsh lesson: Deep
pockets are just as important as good customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com collapsed last month after its major investor, Walt
Disney Co., pulled its support. Shares of SmarterKids.com, a
publicly held company known for in-depth educational offerings,
have taken a nosedive. Even eToys, once a rising e-commerce star,
is hurting.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, eToys announced that it had raised $100 million from
a group of investors led by Promethean Asset Management. But it
turns out that the terms of this deal were less favorable than
previous financings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
