<SLUG> BC-TECH-VENTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT A DIFFERENCE A YEAR MAKES FOR E-COMMERCE STARTUPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About a year ago, at the height of the b-to-c craze,
JuniorNet.com _ an online service for kids _ was reveling in its
good fortune. The Boston-based start-up had just landed $70 million
in venture financing, in the biggest early-stage deal Boston has
seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   Founder Alan Rothenberg told the Globe then that he'd left piles
of money on the table. He only wanted $20 million, he said, but he
got offers as high as $130 million.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the days.
</P>
<P>
   JuniorNet.com has fallen on hard times since then. The company's
lead investor, RCN Corp., the Princeton, N.J., telecom and cable
giant, has installed two new executives to run the company.
Rothenberg has been ushered to a nonexecutive board seat. A slew of
top executives has left the company, and money is tight.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard Yetming, one of the new co-CEOs at JuniorNet.com, says:
``Whenever there's a shift in strategy, you're going to have some
fallout.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift is significant. JuniorNet.com started as an ad-free
access point to games, educational tools, and interactive stories
from the likes of ``Ranger Rick'' and ``Bear in the Big Blue
House.'' It touted itself as a kind of America Online for kids. And
it charged a $9.95 monthly subscription fee.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a warning against Peter Lynch-style investing when it
comes to venture capital. RCN president David McCourt said he
decided to invest when he couldn't drag his 8-year-old son away
from the Junior.net service. Three other venture firms
participated, including Boston Capital Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Yetming says the company is now retooling itself as a ``new
media'' play. RCN appears to be trying to ride the convergence
wave, where television and Web services meet.
</P>
<P>
   JuniorNet.com owns a TV production company, Lancit Media, which
it bought from RCN for $25 million as part of last year's deal.
Lancit has developed two PBS television series for children
(``Reading Rainbow'' and ``The Puzzle Place'') and RCN wants to see
more money spent to develop TV programs with links to the Web
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to spend a lot of money developing our own
television show, JuniorNet TV,'' Yetming says.
</P>
<P>
   The company's blind spot may be that it fancies itself different
from the others out there vying for kiddie viewing time, because of
its education bent. But there's Disney, Nickelodeon and FoxKids.com
to contend with, just for starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``JuniorNet provides enlightenment,'' suggests Cecily Truett,
co-president of Lancit. But, she concedes, ``We know, as realists,
we compete with folks like Disney.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other consumer Web companies, JuniorNet.com will be more
carefully watching its money, Yetming says. He's scrapped a costly
and ineffective direct mail campaign, he says. And a search is
afoot for additional financing. Last August, Rothenberg told the
Globe he was looking for another $50 million, and he planned to
spend heavily on advertising. There has been no formal round of
financing to date, only bridge loans.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the only sob story in Web land, of course. A Wayne,
Pa., Internet media company, put out a press release this week that
blared, ``4Anything.com secures $11 million in funding, reduces
workforce by 33 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the turmoil continues at beleaguered Furniture.com in
Framingham, Mass. On Monday, employees received a rare note of
encouragement from the boss, chief executive Andrew Brooks, urging
them to hang in there.
</P>
<P>
   But by week's end, more senior execs had marched out the door of
the online furniture seller. The departures included Mike Sudik,
senior vice president of operations, as well as the company's vice
president of engineering and its chief of human resources.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Morale is, well, not exactly sunny at the company, which had
filed plans to go public in January but canceled them after Nasdaq
cratered in March. The company fired about 30 people in a
mind-numbingly nasty way (go to your desks and wait for the phone
to ring) and has since seen a parade of guys in suits stopping by.
For one recent visit by financial types, a source says, managers
had customer service people sit in the tech quarters, to beef up
the thinning ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com's early investors, CMGI's (at)Ventures and
Bessemer Venture Partners, reportedly took a pass in the ``cram
down,'' or declined the chance to dump more money into the company.
</P>
<P>
   While rumors swirled Friday that the company's financial
situation was dire, people familiar with the efforts to raise money
said Furniture.com had managed to land about $20 million _ half the
amount it was seeking _ part of which will go toward a new venture.
</P>
<P>
   These are ugly days for e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beth Healy is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
