<P>
   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, June 21:
</P>
<P>
   (Coded d)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-WORCESTERSHIRE (Worcester, England) _ In
English-speaking countries and many others, Lea &AMP; Perrins
Worcestershire Sauce is as ubiquitous as taxes. Lea &AMP; Perrins
Worcestershire was first formulated in 1835, and it has been
manufactured since 1897 in a handsome red-brick Victorian factory
on Midland Road in Worcester, a mile from the city's fine medieval
cathedral and 125 miles northwest of London. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (With NYT photos 2-5.)
</P>
<P>
   EATING-WELL-ORGANIC (Undated) _ When it comes to sales of
organic food, the British are leaving the Americans in the dust. By
Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   SCALLOPS (New Bedford, Mass.) _ With the reopening of the
Georges Bank to scalloping for the first time in five years,
supplies this summer will be bigger and better; with recipes. A
report from New Bedford, Mass. By John Willoughby and Chris
Schlesinger.
</P>
<P>
   CAFE-NICHOLSON (New York) _ In a New York restaurant scene
defined by cozy neighborhood joints and imposing temples of haute
cuisine, Cafe Nicholson stood alone and apart, a theme restaurant
whose only theme was its owner's peculiar sensibility. By William
Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   HARRIOTT-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Tackling the recipes in
``Ainsley Harriott's Meals in Minutes'' (Dorling Kindersley,
$19.95) calls for energy, concentration and dexterity. It often
means doing two, three or even four things at the same time.
Harriott, who has one television program in Britain and another
filmed in New York and shown in the United States, is a chef in
high gear, enlisting audience and celebrity assistants to work on
salads, whip up a marinade, sear chicken and somehow assemble a
dish while keeping up a steady, energetic patter. By Florence
Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   SEA-BEANS (Undated) )_ They go by so many names they would seem
to be as common as corn: sea beans, sea asparagus, samphire,
salicornia, pousse-pied, glasswort. Until recently, though, these
salty little vegetables were just an oddity turning up once a year
or so between the pea shoots and the cipolline onions in high-end
produce markets. Now, thanks to new farming techniques, fresh sea
beans are becoming more abundant and available. And they are more
than a novelty. By Melissa Clark.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (New York) _ Debut of Michel Richard of Citronelle
in Washington: strawberry-rhubarb `salad' that's really an ice
cream dessert; with recipe. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ Cold potato soup with green garlic;
with recipe. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
