<HEADLINE>
`FAST EDDIE,' THE MAN WHO LIT A FIRE UNDER SUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SANTA CLARA, CALIF. _ THEY CALL HIM fast Eddie.
</P>
<P>
   Edward J. Zander, president of Sun Microsystems Inc., thinks
it's because he's from Brooklyn, even though he spent a big chunk
of his life in the Boston area working for Raytheon Corp., Data
General Corp., and Apollo Computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife says I sleep fast,'' Zander said in an interview last
week. ``I'm from New York, so I'm New York fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of Greek and Polish immigrants, Zander has the hustle of
a street kid spoiling for a good fight. Last week, he took aim at
EMC Corp., the reigning heavyweight champion of the computer
storage industry, by rolling out products to compete head-to-head
with the Hopkinton company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition is here,'' Zander said, and with a mischievous
smile added: ``So don't upgrade your houses in Hopkinton yet.''
</P>
<P>
   It was vintage Zander. Feisty, fast, and no-nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Those qualities led Sun's chief executive, Scott McNealy, to
spend six years recruiting Zander from Apollo, a competitor to Sun
during the 1980s. (Apollo was sold to Hewlett-Packard Co. in 1989.)
In 1987, Zander relented and moved to join what he then called the
``West Coast crazies.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a good move, for both Zander and Sun, which became the
dominant supplier of workstations and computer servers. Since 1995,
Sun's market valuation zoomed from $9 billion to $146 billion last
week. Executives within Sun and company watchers credit Zander for
much of that success.
</P>
<P>
   Zander, 53, thinks Sun's ability to thrive is related to its
willingness to reinvent itself at times when the company was at the
top of its game. When Sun's workstation business boomed, the
company went after the server market. Now that Sun servers are the
industry standard, it's going after the Internet and preparing to
push out an array of products and services for e-commerce
companies, from storage devices to Web consulting. It was Zander
who came up with the slogan: ``We're the dot in dot-com.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big project to rip up the guts of Sun and `dot-com'
our company.'' Zander said. ``Usually you look at the height of
success for the birth of a new paradigm.''
</P>
<P>
   Resting on laurels is something Zander learned to avoid while in
Boston. After graduating with a bachelor's in engineering from
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in New York, Zander moved to
Massachusetts to work as an engineer for Raytheon. In 1972, he went
to Data General and earned his master's in business administration
from Boston University. It was then that Zander discovered he had a
talent for marketing. After witnessing the decline of the
minicomputer, he joined Apollo in 1982 as head of marketing, and
left Boston in 1987 to join Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Zander, a sports fanatic, still has a fondness for Boston, where
he met his wife, Mona, and where his two sons were born. ``The
trouble out here,'' Zander continued, ``is that these San Francisco
people always win. Then they go out and have their white wine and
tofu, and they go surf. They don't deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zander comes back to Boston frequently now because Sun has
designated Massachusetts and Colorado as its hubs outside of the
company's headquarters in Palo Alto. The company has 2,000
employees in Burlington and Chelmsford, Mass. In May, Sun embarked
on a project to add 300,000 square feet of office space to its
existing 540,000 square feet in Burlington.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that Silicon Valley was seen as the center of the
technology universe, but the Internet has changed that, Zander
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has had a leveling effect on business culture,''
Zander said. ``It's become so homogeneous that you can start an
Internet company anywhere now. Sure, Silicon Valley has more
service providers, more incubators, more venture capital, more
entrepreneurs. But I just think Boston is back, back big time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can
be reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
