<HEADLINE>
NCR IS TAKING ATMS TO THE NEXT LEVEL OF SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all of the blessings of life in America today, it seems
almost a churlish complaint. But many people would agree it's a
hassle to have to fill out and seal an envelope when you want to
deposit a check in an automated teller machine.
</P>
<P>
   In what may become the wave of the future for ATMs, however,
financial giant Fidelity Investments has begun rolling out new
machines at seven US sites that let you put an endorsed check
straight into a slot.
</P>
<P>
   Out pops a receipt with a little picture of the check you
deposited, something to give you a little peace of mind (and proof
of deposit) when you entrust your holiday bonus check to a faceless
machine.
</P>
<P>
   While the no-envelope deposit system and image-containing
receipts have attracted some enthusiasm, it is only one of dozens
of possibilities for the machine, which is made by NCR Corp. of
Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Fidelity representatives hope to use the machine's
personal computer-based, Internet-connected system to allow people
to do walk-in stock trades and get a printed receipt, or have
research reports printed out, or move money around in their
accounts by using the screen and keyboard, or check stock quotes.
</P>
<P>
   By slipping in a module, Fidelity eventually could use the
machine to dispense cash, ski lift tickets, or stamps as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really just a huge amount of intelligence in here that
you won't find in a bank machine,'' said J. Peter Benzie,
Fidelity's executive vice president for ``high net worth''
customers. ``And the machine is really only now doing 10 percent of
what it could do.''
</P>
<P>
   The unit is a money-saver for Fidelity, which according to NCR
is the first US company using the machines in daily customer
service. And it frees representatives from the drudge work of
processing paper transactions to advise people on buying mutual
funds or opening a brokerage account.
</P>
<P>
   What takes 12 steps to do manually _ take an endorsed check,
time-stamp the receipt, and send the check on its way to the bank
clearinghouse _ takes only six steps with the machine.
</P>
<P>
   If only 20 percent of people coming to a branch to deposit a
check use it, a target that has been easily exceeded in some
branches, the machines should cover their low-five-figure cost in
10 months.
</P>
<P>
   While Fidelity executives rave about the machine, however, a
spokesman for Massachusetts' biggest bank, FleetBoston Financial,
said officials there are a little more skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have talked to NCR about this technology, but we have felt
that it's not quite up to par as far as our banking needs and it is
still developing,'' said Fleet spokesman Bruce Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   The main drawback Fleet officials see is that people depositing
several checks at once would have to enter separate information for
each one and feed them in one at a time, a big hassle for, say, a
store owner or landlord depositing 20 checks on a Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Adapting the system to handle envelopes as well as individual
checks, or a stack of checks without an envelope, however, appears
to be little more than a matter of adding a different module and
tweaked software to the box. If NCR can accommodate people with
multiple checks, Spitzer said, ``We will consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter J. Howe is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at howe(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1409EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
