<HEADER>
A9494 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-APPRECIATE-MARCHAND-B     06-20 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPRECIATE-MARCHAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM MRS. PYNCHON TO LIVIA SOPRANO, A WEALTH OF THESPIAN RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nancy Marchand, whose acting range spanned both the regal Mrs.
Pynchon on ``Lou Grant'' and the seething, scheming Livia Soprano
on ``The Sopranos,'' died of lung cancer at her home in Stratford,
Conn., on Sunday night, one day before her 72d birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Highly respected by fellow actors, Ms. Marchand enjoyed a
significant career on the stage and fairly steady film work. Her
performance on Broadway in ``White Liars and Black Comedy'' won her
a Tony nomination, and when she ventured off-Broadway, she brought
home Obie Awards for ``The Cocktail Hour'' and ``The Balcony.'' Ms.
Marchand also turned up in supporting parts in movies as various as
``Naked Gun'' and the 1995 remake of ``Sabrina.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was best-known for two TV roles that were nearly two
decades _ and light years _ apart.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Lou Grant'' (1977-1982), a newspaper drama starring Edward
Asner as a curmudgeonly city editor of the Los Angeles Tribune, she
won four consecutive Emmy Awards for her portrayal of publisher
Margaret Pynchon. In that role, the elegantly coiffed Ms. Marchand
epitomized aristocratic grace and rock-ribbed integrity. When the
chips were down and a journalistic principle was at stake, editor
Lou Grant could always count on Mrs. Pynchon to do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Livia Soprano was another matter altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who saw Ms. Marchand's performance as Livia, the mother
of New Jersey mob boss Tony Soprano in HBO's ``The Sopranos,''
found it hard to forget. Her hair flattened against her head, her
eyes wild and her voice grating, Livia was an unsettling mixture of
whining self-pity and feral fury. Livia's weird and wicked ways
were at the root of Tony's need to visit a psychiatrist every week,
which put him in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   Livia also did her part to put him there. Angry at Tony (James
Gandolfini) for depositing her in a nursing home (``I gave my life
to my children on a silver platter,'' she wails, unconvincingly),
Livia coerces Junior Soprano, her brother-in-law, into a murder
attempt on her son.
</P>
<P>
   Or did Livia even know what she was doing? Did she slip Junior
damaging information about Tony out of senility rather than malice?
Was her subsequent stroke real or fake? Such was Ms. Marchand's
skill as an actress that the viewer was left wondering.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Livia originally had been scheduled to die at the end
of the first season of HBO's ``The Sopranos.'' But Ms. Marchand's
performance was so compelling that the producers decided to keep
Livia alive for a second season. Ms. Marchand helped make ``The
Sopranos,'' which premiered in January 1999, one of the most
acclaimed dramas in television history.
</P>
<P>
   HBO had no information Monday on how ``Sopranos'' producer David
Chase would handle Ms. Marchand's death within the show's story
line. During the second season, Livia was seen less frequently,
although Junior kept imploring Tony to ``make peace'' with her.
Filming for a third season of the show is slated to begin this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Marchand enjoyed a major career rebirth with ``The
Sopranos,'' some of her fellow actors viewed it as just desserts.
In an interview with the Globe last year, Tyne Daly of ``Judging
Amy'' offered lavish praise for Ms. Marchand as the consummate
professional, and spoke of how gratifying it was to see the actress
recognized for her gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Buffalo, Ms. Marchand had a career that spanned most of
TV history. She appeared in the 1953 Philco Television Playhouse
production of ``Marty,'' playing the girlfriend of the title
character, and did guest stints on ``Naked City'' in the late
1950s. She also experienced television's down side: In the
mid-1970s, she was in the cast for ``Beacon Hill,'' an attempt to
put an American accent on ``Upstairs Downstairs.'' It flopped
miserably.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two decades, in addition to ``Lou Grant'' and ``The
Sopranos,'' Ms. Marchand appeared on such TV shows as ``Homicide:
Life on the Street,'' ``Cheers,'' ``Coach,'' and ``Night Court.''
On film, Ms. Marchand appeared in ``Regarding Henry'' with Harrison
Ford, ``The Bostonians,'' ``The Hospital,'' ``Tell Me That You Love
Me, Junie Moon,'' and ``Dear God.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marchand leaves her three children, Kathryn, Rachel and
David. Last November, Ms. Marchand's husband of 47 years, Paul
Sparer, died, also of cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
