<HEADLINE>
OLD STURBRIDGE BRINGS 4TH CLOSE TO HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was time for the annual reading of the Declaration of
Independence. The speaker, sporting a blue morning coat and bright
red vest, soon had his audience stirred up as he outlined the evils
perpetrated against the colonies by King George III:
</P>
<P>
   (itals)``He has obstructed the administration of
justice.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   The crowd roared in outrage.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)``He has . . . sent hither swarms of officers to harass
our people.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   The crowd roared louder.
</P>
<P>
   (iteals)``He has plundered our seas, ravaged our coasts, burnt
our towns, and destroyed the lives of our people.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   The crowd roared loudest of all.
</P>
<P>
   And then the speaker, a prominent citizen of Old Sturbridge
Village, reeled off the names of the signers of the Declaration and
where they were from. Hearing their states mentioned, audience
members from Maine to Virginia cheered wildly.
</P>
<P>
   Every July 4, people from those states and others appear happy
to be at Old Sturbridge, a re-created New England village of the
1830s in Sturbridge. After all, they are celebrating Independence
Day in a unique way by returning to the time a little more than a
half-century after the Declaration was signed _ a time when the
holiday was one of the premier events of the year and meant a rare
day off from hard work.
</P>
<P>
   The day is faithfully recaptured at the 200-acre village,
beginning with fife and drum music, a flag raising, and musket and
cannon fire. In the afternoon, a parade is held. But this parade
features no drum majorettes in spangled costumes or tuba players
oom-pahing down the street. Instead, it's a straw-hatted procession
of citizens _ farmers, carpenters, blacksmiths, and others _
carrying the tools of their trades and sometimes accompanied by
beasts of burden such as oxen. The reading of the Declaration,
complete with a musket salute, follows. Throughout the day, there
are toy hot-air balloon flights, 19th-century dancing,
early-American games such as hoop rolling, and boat rides on the
Quinebaug River.
</P>
<P>
   Old Sturbridge Village will do it all again this July 4, and
hold Family Fun Days July 1-3. The fun days include demonstrations,
activities, and family entertainment, including more balloon
flights, cow milking, children's garden tours, gossip tours,
19th-century puppets, and storytelling. For more information and
prices, call 800-SEE-1830 (TTY: 508-347-5383) or visit www.osv.org.
For information about a variety of red-white-and-blue events
through July 9 that the town of Sturbridge calls the Americana
Experience, call 800-628-8379 or visit www.sturbridge.org. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of Independence Day: On July 2, beautiful Belcourt
Castle in Newport, R.I., will be the scene of an old-fashioned
Fourth of July barbecue. The benefit event, from 7 p.m. to
midnight, will feature a lavish barbecue (until 10 p.m.) with items
such as seafood appetizers, black angus burgers, hot dogs, wings,
ribs, corn, beans, and a lot more. In addition, there will be
lively music by The Ravers. Tickets for the event, which is limited
to those 21 and over, are $60 before June 26 and $70 afterward.
Call 401-846-0669, ext. 2. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking some more of Independence Day: The annual Fourth of
July ``Turtle Independence Day'' celebration at Mauna Lani Resort
on Hawaii's Big Island is indeed a day of freedom for young
``honu'' (turtles), who are tagged and released into the ocean
after being nurtured in a program to protect Hawaii's dwindling
turtle population. Last year more than 1,000 gathered at water's
edge to cheer the turtles to freedom. Free and open to the public,
the event draws spectators in turtle-themed clothes, swimsuits, and
snorkeling gear, who form a human path to independence. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Where is the world's largest McDonald's restaurant?
(Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: London's Canary Wharf is so named because it originally
handled ships full of bananas from the Canary Islands. (This
fascinating fact is from ``Kids' London'' (DK Publishing, $7.95). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: In Portland, Maine, shoelaces must be tied while
walking down the street. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Money back: Biztravel.com is guaranteeing the on-time performance
of five airlines _ American, Continental, US Airways, British
Airways, and Air France _ or the Web company will give its
customers the following refunds: Any flight arriving at the gate
more than 30 minutes late, $100; more than an hour, $200; more than
two hours, a full refund. There are also refunds for flight
cancellations, seat assignments that are not honored, requested
meals that are not available, and lost baggage. For details, rules,
and information on still other refunds, visit www.biztravel.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
Event to remember: The remote outback town of Boulia in Queensland,
Australia, will host the fourth annual Boulia Desert Sands camel
races July 14-16. The feature event will be a 1.2-mile race with a
prize purse of $20,000 US. For more information on Australia, where
bookmaking is legal, visit www.australia.com or call 800-333 0262.
For more information on the races, visit www.camelraces.asn.au or
email hump(at)ultra.net.au. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Worthy of honor: A small shrine in Dublin honors America's Choctaw
Indians, and for good reason. In 1847, hearing of Ireland's famine,
the tribe sent money and food. They were the only such people in
the world to do so. The Choctaws, after all, knew what starvation
was like, having experienced it on the Trail of Tears from
1829-1843. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Orlando, Fla. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Compiled from wire service reports, news releases, books,
magazines, Web sites, and the deepest recesses of the author's
mind. Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpenter(at)globe.com. Include
your name and community.)
</P>
</TEXT>
