<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN WITH GAS PRICE HIKES, YOU CAN SAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With gasoline prices averaging more than $1.60 a gallon for
regular nationwide, some travelers are getting cold feet.
</P>
<P>
   A recent USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll found 48 percent of those
surveyed said rising gas prices were making them change their
vacation plans.
</P>
<P>
   While no one likes what is happening at the pumps, there's
really no need to change plans although, yes, driving is going to
cost you more. Let's say you have a vehicle that averages 20 miles
a gallon. On a 600-mile roundtrip, fuel would cost $47.70 based on
a AAA average price of $1.578.
</P>
<P>
   If it were still available in those wonderful days of
$1-a-gallon prices, the same trip would have cost $30. Now, is a
$17.70 increase worth canceling your plans?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you are one of the macho types who only drives the
huge sport utility vehicles, then you're going to pay more, but
still not enough really to keep you home.
</P>
<P>
   When making vacation plans the first thing to do is set
priorities. If you plan, you can find savings just about anywhere
you are traveling _ and on any aspect of the trip. For example, you
can prearrange for accommodations at your price, not at what the
traffic will bear.
</P>
<P>
   Consider joining a club. If you're not a member, check out AAA
since they do a lot more than just provide towing service and maps.
Included in the membership are excellent guides for use throughout
the country to find hotels and restaurants. Your membership card
also provides discounts at dining spots, shops, and attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Look for hotel deals. The recently renovated Marriott Bay Point
Resort Village in Panama City Beach, Fla., is offering a Round Trip
Reward from now through Sept. 30, which provides vacationers
staying five days with a rebate of 32.5 cents per mile traveled to
reach the resort. The resort has everything for golf and family
vacations; the gasoline rebate makes it even more of a deal. For
information on rates and the rebate (a limit of 1,000 miles), call
800-874-7105.
</P>
<P>
   Omni Hotels is offering Phenomenal Fridays for weekend stays
with rates beginning at $69 through Sept. 3. And other chains are
offering low summer rates also to those who call ahead. Many are
also offering extras for the kids, like Comfort Inn and Comfort
Suite hotels, which give the children a free Pokemon the Movie 2000
Activity Book.
</P>
<P>
   Since you really should have the car checked before hitting the
road, why not take advantage of this? Jiffy Lube is offering travel
discounts valued at $1,000 to those having a Signature Service in
June. With the service, drivers receive a Drive America brochure
and savings card with a pin number to access the deals wherever you
go. For information, call 800-344-6933.
</P>
<P>
   Make plans for somewhere where the dollar goes far _ Canada.
With the US dollar worth up to $1.50 in Canada, a vacation up north
becomes a real bargain. The Four Seasons Hotel Toronto just did a
comparison of staying there and at The Plaza Hotel New York, both
world-class hotels. The results were amazing: A $1,498 vacation in
New York would cost just $703 in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend stay included (Plaza/Four Seasons prices):
accommodations $960, $410; meal $72, $52; wine $65, $44; dessert
$20, $11; coffee $5, $5; show $260, $123; baseball game $110, $53;
and transportation $6, $5.
</P>
<P>
   Should you head to Toronto, the Four Seasons has lots of
packages beginning from $230 (800-332-3442). And if you go for
shopping, Liloo Alim, chef concierge, says locally produced
fashions, shoes, leather goods, and cigars are Americans' top
items. He'll also assist you with more entertainment tips, tax
refunds, and shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing what that dollar can do with a little planning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Pisa to reopen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The leaning tower of Pisa will reopen on July 17, 2001,
according to the Italian Tourist Office in New York. For more than
a decade work has been under way to stabilize the 12th-century
landmark. When it does open, visitors will only be able to go to
the second circle, not the top. The reopening coincides with Pisa's
celebration of its patron St. Ranieri. That evening, lighted
candles are floated down the Arno River.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy Fest &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key West's Fantasy Fest 2000 is expected to be its biggest party
ever. This year's fest is set for Oct. 20-29, but the time to plan
and book is now.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best places to catch the action is at Ocean Key
resort, which overlooks the famed Sunset Pier and the action in
Mallory Square and Duval Street. The resort's Come As You Aren't
four-night package offers lots of amenities and VIP seating on
Sunset Pier. The package begins at $2,919 for up to four people.
For details, call 800-328-9815 or visit www.oceankey.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
London luxury &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ritz, one of the top addresses in London right on Piccadilly
and overlooking Green Park, is featuring one of the newest wonders
of the world, the British Airways London Eye on weekend packages.
From July 7 to Sept. 8, guests can enjoy two nights'
accommodations, full breakfasts, and a dinner, along with a ride in
the hotel's reserved capsule on the observation wheel. The package
is $1280 for two. Since its opening in 1906, this grand hotel has
been a favorite with royalty and celebrities. The hotel was
recently restored to its original grandeur along with all the
latest amenities. For information, call The Ritz at 020-7493-8181
or visit wwww.enquire. . .theritzhotel.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Newport walks &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Newport can now take a three-hour walking tour of
Bellevue Avenue or see the inner workings of a grand Gilded Age
mansion. The Preservation Society of Newport County Victorian
Cottages Walking Tour is offered daily at 10 a.m. ($25, $9 for
children 6-17). Behind the Scenes at the Elms: The House That Ran
by Magic is offered four times daily ($12, $4 for children 6-17).
For information and reservations, call 401-847-1000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Icy stay &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How would you like to stay in a hotel built of ice? Until now
the only place in the world to do so was Sweden. Now the concept is
coming to Quebec City. Planned to open in January 2001, the second
ice hotel will offer a cinema, art galleries, a chapel, sleeping
accommodations for 100, and a bar where vodka will be served on the
rocks _ naturally.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel is planned to be open for three months each year and
then rebuilt the next winter. Accommodations are expected to be
about $100 a night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
House tour &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two of the loveliest towns in the Litchfield Hills of
Connecticut will have open house tours in July. On July 1, the
Great Sharon Water Wonders tour will feature six homes with
outstanding pools, ponds, and water gardens. The self-guided tour
is $30 and benefits the Sharon Historical Society. Box lunches are
also available. For reservations, call 860-364-5688.
</P>
<P>
   The 53d annual Litchfield Open House Day will be July 8 with
five homes spanning eras from 1765 to 1937. For more information on
tours and travel in the Litchfield Hills, call 860-567-4506 or
visit www.litchfieldhills.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Montreal jazz &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Montreal becomes soul heaven from June 29 through July 9 when
music lovers flock to the 21st Montreal International Jazz
Festival. City streets become the world's largest stage for 400
concerts, 300 of which are free.
</P>
<P>
   Among the performers will be Sting, Ray Charles, Manhattan
Transfer, Herbie Hancock, and Patti Smith. This year's edition pays
tribute to the legacy of Louis Armstrong on the 100th anniversary
of his birth. For information on packages, hotel rates, and more,
call the Info-Jazz Bell line at 888-515-0515 or visit
www.montrealjazzfest.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
