<HEADER>
A9512 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-CRUISE-BOS &LR;      06-20 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CRUISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE IT YOUR WAY ON THIS SHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cruising the way you want it. That's the newest idea to hit the
seas.
</P>
<P>
   A common complaint among those who avoid vacations at sea is
that cruising is too regimented. That is, you have to dine when the
line says so, rather than when you want to. That complaint is
usually accompanied by others, such as ``You have to dress up some
nights,'' and ''Cruising is too confining.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Mr. or Miss No Cruise, have we got news for you. Your
excuses have all been washed out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Cruise Line is introducing ``Freestyle Cruising'' to
provide passengers with a ``more relaxed, resort-style cruise
product with complete flexibility and non-intrusive service of the
highest standard,'' said Colin Veitch, president of NCL. ``The
implementation of Freestyle Cruising marks a tremendous milestone
for NCL and a return to innovative cruise vacations.``
</P>
<P>
   Freestyle Cruising is up and running aboard the line's Norwegian
Sky in Alaska, and will be available on Caribbean cruises this
fall, and throughout the fleet by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Sky passengers now have complete flexibility as to when and with
whom they want to dine. From 5:30 p.m. to midnight, passengers can
choose which of the ship's three dining rooms or alternative
restaurants they wish to dine in and when. Passengers also have the
option of choosing their dinner companions and requesting tables of
two to 10 each evening rather than being assigned to a specific
table for the length of the cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Formal nights are also out on the Sky. Typically, these occur
twice on a cruise, but on the Sky, the dress code calls for
``resort casual'' attire. But should you still like to dress up,
the Sky will have one optional formal night and reserve a dining
room and lounge for those in formal wear.
</P>
<P>
   Tipping has also been simplified. Instead of passengers having
to distribute tipping envelopes to waitstaff and cabin stewards,
the line is automatically adding to each guest's onboard account
the recommended gratuity to those staff members. Passengers have
the option of leaving an additional tip for great service, and
should they feel the service did not meet their expectations, they
may remove the charge from their final bill.
</P>
<P>
   The line is also increasing staff aboard the Sky by about 100 to
bring its crew-to-guest ratioto the level found at shoreside
resorts.
</P>
<P>
   While this is good news for many who have hesitated to board a
ship, a visit with a travel agent who specializes in cruises will
reveal that features such as those mentioned can be found on other
lines. For example, Princess and Carnival have 24-hour dining
aboard some of their vessels (allowing not only dining when you
want, but also providing a way to avoid the formal night); some
lines lines have a completely casual code. Holland America has long
been known for its no-tipping-required policy. Silverseas includes
some shore excursions in its price.
</P>
<P>
   And if your no-go cruise companion still insists that cruises
are too confining, book passage aboard Royal Caribbean's Voyager of
the Seas. This 142,000-ton vessel is the largest at sea and is the
equivalent of a land-based resort with all the usual cruise
amenities plus such features as an indoor ice skating rink,
climbing wall, miniature golf course, and inline skating track.
</P>
<P>
   So now what's your excuse for not cruising? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   World cruise is out &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many have dreamed of taking a world cruise, but the cost
prevented the dream from becoming reality. So it was good news when
the World Cruise Co. was formed last year to provide a of more than
100 days for around $10,000 a person _ $5,000-$10,000 less than the
lowest price of other line's world cruises. But the news was not so
good for passengers aboard the cruise ship Riviera on May 23 when
they were informed the line was shutting down.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sam Blyth, president of the company, said the line was
not filing for bankruptcy and that passengers aboard that cruise
would be compensated, many had to scramble to find rooms at their
unexpected final port of call in Tahiti and pay for flights home.
Blyth blamed the shutdown on fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the passengers were more fortunate. They had booked the
cruise through Grand Circle Travel, a Boston-based firm that
specializes in travel for those 50 and older. Hearing rumors of the
shutdown, Grand Circle obtained rooms and flights home for their 56
clients, as well as full refunds at a cost to Grand Circle that
could exceed $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   One lesson from the line's failure is the importance of having
the ``right'' travel insurance. Those booking through Grand Circle
had solid protection, those booking independently might be out
financially. According to a story in the Los Angeles Times, the
Toronto-based insurance firm that sold travel insurance to
passengers said those policies were not intended to protect
passengers if the World Cruise Co. failed. Before obtaining travel
insurance, check to see what it does and does not cover.
</P>
<P>
   Blyth, who is also president of Marine Expeditions and a new
line that will offer cruises to Cuba, said those operations are not
affected by the World Cruise shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Circle said the reason it booked passengers on the World
Cruise Co. was the positive experiences its clients had on Marine
Expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New cruises &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seven- and 14-day cruises up the Hudson River or through the
southern New England islands and along the coast of Maine are the
newest travel opportunities from American Cruise Lines. Its brand
new American Eagle will offer Hudson River cruises beginning July
1, then on July 8 seven days of cruising from Block Island to
Nantucket, and on July 15, a grand New England cruise among the
Tall Ships. The American Eagle carries just 49 passengers and many
cruises depart from Haddam, Conn. On Oct. 7 the ship sails to
Baltimore to begin a series of Chesapeake Bay and Williamsburg
cruises. For information, call 800-814-6880 or visit
www.americancruiselines.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sail and save &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Windstar Cruises is offering those who plan and book ahead
savings of up to 50 percent off holiday cruises this winter. These
luxurious sailing vessels will be sailing to Caribbean ports unseen
by those on larger vessels. For example, the 312-passenger Wind
Surf's Dec. 17 Caribbean sailing of 10 days costs $3,073, half the
brochure fare of $5,870. For information, call 800-258-7245 or
visit www.windstarcruises.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
