<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9516 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-QUEBEC-BOS &LR;      06-20 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-QUEBEC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHERN SCENERY WITH SOUTHERN CHARM AND FRENCH CUISINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH HATLEY, Quebec _ Two countries, languages, and cultures
meet and mingle here in the Eastern Townships. As one local
resident boasts, ``We've got French cuisine, English gardens, and
Vermont scenery.''
</P>
<P>
   This rural region about an hour southeast of Montreal parallels
the border between the Province of Quebec and the State of Vermont.
The townships have always been a place apart and distinct from
neighbors in both countries.
</P>
<P>
   Politically the townships belong to Quebec but geologically the
hilly and lake-dotted landcape _ ideal for hiking, biking, and
boating in summer and downhill and cross-country skiing in winter _
is an extension of the Green Mountains of Vermont. The Eastern
Townships resemble Vermont in other ways, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Township villages, with their white clapboard houses and
churches, tidy town commons, and old covered bridges, look more
up-country Yankee than Quebecois. They are also as rewarding to
explore as those in Vermont's so-called Northeast Kingdom, just
over the border.
</P>
<P>
   The province of Quebec is proudly (and officially)
French-speaking, and the townships are also known as
Cantons-de-L'Est. But many township communities have such
unmistakably Anglo names as Sherbrooke, Knowlton, Granby, Ayer's
Cliff, and Hatley. In most cases these are the surnames of
prominent British Empire loyalists (the Tories of American history
books) from the New England states who settled the region after the
American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   North Hatley, however, owes its distinctive character to another
group of Americans who arrived after another conflict. In the years
following the Civil War, well-to-do Americans from the Deep South
no longer felt welcome in New England resorts like Bar Harbor,
Maine, and Burlington, Vt., where they once went to escape the
summer heat. So the ex-Confederates founded a colony in North
Hadley. Some of the spacious summer homes they built on the shore
of Lake Massawippi are reminiscent of the pillared plantation
houses of the Old South.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the first language of most townships residents is French,
but North Hatley (population 750) has an Anglophone majority, and
English is the language of most summer visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The village center, at the northern end of Massawippi, is a
charming resort community, with antiques shops, art galleries, and
several lakeside restaurants. One popular spot, the Pilsen
Restaurant and Pub, has a long terrace at water level that is
delightful on sunny summer days _ but liable to flood on wet ones.
Notable among the art galleries is Galerie Blais, which displays
the work of folk artists from Quebec, the United States, Eastern
Europe, and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Massawippi is 10 miles long and circled by a bicycle path that
in winter is used for cross-country skiing. The path is relatively
flat and has lake views all the way, making it popular with
cyclists of all levels.
</P>
<P>
   The townships have more than 200 inns and bed and breakfasts,
but three boutique inns on Massawippi _ Auberge Hatley, Hovey
Manor, and Ripplecove Inn _ rank among the best in the province for
both accommodations and cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-room Auberge Hatley, a member of the prestigious Relais
et Chateaux association, was built in 1903 as a grand summer
estate. It still has the feel of a country home. Rooms are bright
and cheerful, furnished with antiques and decorated with paintings
by Quebec artists. The dining room overlooks the lake, and the
menu, happily, is more French than Anglo-Saxon. The wine list is
awesome, offering a choice of nearly 1,000 different wines from a
cellar that contains some 10,000 bottles.
</P>
<P>
   In American dollars (worth about a third more than Canadian)
Auberge Hatley's per-person room rates, which include breakfast and
dinner, are roughly $82 to $163 a night. Like other area inns, the
Auberge requires a minimum stay of two nights on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Hovey Manor, also in North Hatley, has 39 rooms. It was built at
the turn of the century for a Georgia industrialist who modeled his
``cottage'' after Mount Vernon, George Washington's home. The manor
is impressive but not intimidating, with homey rooms, most with
lake views. Rates, with two meals (modified American plan), are
approximately US $78-$150.
</P>
<P>
   Ripplecove Cove Inn in Ayer's Cliff, at the southern end of the
lake, was built about 50 years ago in the style of the old Lake
Massawippi homes. The common rooms are decorated accordingly. There
are 26 rooms and suites. The cuisine served in the elegant dining
room is continental with local touches (the smoked salmon served is
cured on the premises) and the wine cellar is award-winning. Per
person MAP rates are US $90-$185.
</P>
<P>
   Two other area lakes, Lake Brome and Lake Memphremagog, the
southern tip of which is in Vermont, offer a range of recreational
activities and are popular weekend getaway spots for Montrealers.
</P>
<P>
   Knowlton, on Lake Brome, is an attractive village noted for its
many antiques shops.
</P>
<P>
   One of the sights _ not to mention sounds and tastes _ of Lake
Memphremagog is St. Benoit du Lac (St. Benedict of the Lake).
Dramatically sited on a point of land thrusting out into the lake,
St. Benoit is a large Benedictine monastery known for the beautiful
chanting of its choir. It is equally famous for the well-aged
cheeses and apple wines sold in its gift shop, both popular
souvenirs of an Eastern Townships visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
