<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MISSILE' HAS HAD A STEALTHY LAUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While most of the attention was focused on the Triple Crown,
Golden Missile quietly cruised to the top of the handicap ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-year-old son of A.P. Indy went wire to wire to win the
$750,000 Stephen Foster Handicap at Churchill Downs Saturday in an
impressive display. That followed a tally in the Pimlico Special
May 13, and when combined with a second place in the Donn Handicap
at Gulfstream Feb. 5, he has done more than Behrens, who was
clinging to the division lead.
</P>
<P>
   Off at 5-2 over a sloppy track, Golden Missile sprung to the
front under Kent Desormeaux, and held Ecton Park, a noted
mud-runner and the 3-2 choice, safe at the wire to score by nearly
3 lengths. Pat Day had Ecton Park on the rail all the way but he
could not gain on the winner. The final time for the 1 1/8 miles
was 1:49 2/5.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Missile is owned by Frank Stronach and trained by Joe
Orseno, the same connections as outstanding 3-year-old Red Bullet.
Just as Red Bullet, who took the Preakness, must defeat Kentucky
Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus to rule the sophomore division,
Golden Missile must beat Behrens to become the undisputed boss of
the older horses.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens finished behind Golden Missile in the Donn, captured the
Gulfstream Park Handicap, and ran second in the $6 million Dubai
World Cup. He has not raced since March, having suffered a foot
bruise that held him out of the Massachusetts Handicap and the
Foster. Golden Missile, who has earned more than $2 million with a
career record of 20-7-6-3, had one poor race this year, a fifth in
the New Orleans Handicap at Fair Grounds March 5.
</P>
<P>
   So the title's on the line, and Orseno figures the big showdown
will come in the Whitney Handicap at Saratoga Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kent knows this horse,'' said Orseno. ``When he wants to run,
you can't fight him. He's at the head of the class right now. We're
the only horse in the country that has shown up in all of these
races. He's at the head of the class, at least until he runs in the
Whitney.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rock field shapes up
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Super Red, who led all the way while winning the Connaught Cup
at Woodbine May 27, Monday was assigned 117 pounds for the $200,000
New Hampshire Sweepstakes at Rockingham Park Saturday. He is
considered a ``possible'' starter for the 1 1/8-mile turf event,
and was given the highest weight of those who may be entered.
Others whose connections are taking the race seriously include
Where's Taylor, at 114 pounds; Brawny, 112; The Kaiser, 112; Johnny
Dollar, 111; Mi Sierra, 111, and Makeyourselfathome, 110.
Christophe Clemente, who commands a powerful stable of grass
runners in New York, also is expected to be represented. He will
choose from among four nominees: Inexplicable, at 112 pounds;
Forbidden Apple, 111; Tiger Shark, 111; and Halcyon, 110. The
official highweight, Haami, listed at 118 pounds, is not expected
for the race. The field for the Sweeps will be drawn Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lukas charge yields
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   High Yield, a son of Storm Cat who was considered trainer D.
Wayne Lukas's best 3-year-old before Commendable took the Belmont
Stakes, suffered a fractured left front sesamoid in a workout at
Santa Anita June 12 and probably will be retired. ``The owners will
make a decision, but more than likely he'll go to stud,'' said
Lukas Saturday. ``I think he'll be a popular sire.'' High Yield was
a $1,050,000 yearling, and he won the Blue Grass at Keeneland.
However, he was overmatched in the Derby (15th) and Preakness
(seventh) . . . On a brighter note for Lukas, Exchange Rate, his
third outstanding 3-year-old, captured the $100,000 Northern Dancer
Handicap at Churchill Downs Saturday. Exchange Rate, a son of
Danzig, scored in the 7-furlong test despite a rough trip, blasting
past the opposition in deep stretch. It was Exchange Rate's first
start since he finished 12th in the Derby . . . It has long been
known, but it was officially announced Friday that Belmont Park
will host the 2001 Breeders' Cup Oct. 27. The 18th running will
mark the third time the Cup has come to Belmont (previously 1990
and '95), and the fourth time to New York (Aqueduct hosted in
1985). The eight-race Breeders' Cup card is worth $13 million, and
is anchored by the $4 million Classic. It is expected that the Cup
will head to California in 2002. Which track will host is
uncertain, but Hollywood Park has the early edge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Silic is 1 for 1
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Silic, who had not raced since winning last year's Breeders' Cup
Mile at Gulfstream, made a successful seasonal bow by seizing the
$400,000 Shoemaker Mile at Hollywood Sunday. Ridden by Corey
Nakatani, Silic held off fast-closing stablemate Ladies Din to
prevail by a half-length in the time of 1:33 1/5 for a mile over
the lawn. The powerful entry was held at 3-5 ($3.40 to win). ``Our
trip was just great,'' said Nakatani. ``He was going nice and
relaxed, and was into the bridle. When I called on him, he was
there. I got the right trip with the right horse.'' ``This horse is
very special,'' said Julio Canani, who trains the French-bred
(career record 15-8-2-0, earnings $1.4 million). ``He's a great
horse, an unbelievable horse.'' . . . Beautiful Pleasure, last
year's champion handicap female, breezed 6 furlongs in 1:13 1/5 at
Belmont over the weekend as she prepares for Saturday's Hempstead
Handicap. Beautiful Pleasure won the Shuvee at Belmont by nearly 7
lengths May 20. ``She came out of the work just fine,'' said
trainer John Ward. ``It was more like an open gallop. She's really
on her game.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was used
to prepare this report.
</P>
