<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-NASDAQ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ JAPAN GETS OFF TO A SMOOTH START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHARON MOSHAVI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ With his casual, all-black clothes, narrow black-framed
glasses, and thick crop of black hair, you know immediately who
Shinichi Nishikubo is: the owner of a fledgling Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, he has one more credential: His stock now trades
on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   After months of hype, Nasdaq Japan finally launched, trading
just eight companies, including Nishikubo's Masternet, an Internet
mail service provider.
</P>
<P>
   Nishikubo had managed to take his fledgling company public 2 1/2
years ago, on the Japanese over-the-counter market. When some
investors urged him to be one of the trial stocks on Nasdaq Japan,
he says he jumped at the chance. ``Companies in Nasdaq tend to be
highly valued,'' Nishikubo said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, despite the recent downward spiral of
Nasdaq-listed stocks in the United States, to many in Japan and
Asia, the market still is equated with making money.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Japan wants to attract others like Masternet. The market,
half owned by the Japanese technology giant Softbank Corp. and
affiliated with the Osaka Stock Exchange, is looking to add about
10 companies a month. Executives expect it will take about three
years before the market is ``robust.''
</P>
<P>
   The first day of trading was unexceptional. Most of the shares
performed moderately. The listed companies seemed pleased that the
launch went off without a hitch. ``I am relieved, that's all,''
said Seiji Yoshikawa, president of asset management systems company
XNET Corp., whose shares rose 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sugi Pharmacy Co. was the most active of the eight companies
listed on the exchange, with 651,000 shares worth $5.4 billion yen
($51 million) being traded. The drugstore chain operator rose 29
percent to 9,000 yen, from its initial price of 7,000 yen.
</P>
<P>
   Masternet didn't fare as well. Its stock fell 300,000 yen, or 15
percent, to 1.65 million _ or $15,570.44 a share. One of the
difficulties facing start-up companies in Japan is that government
regulations base stock price on a multiple of net assets, pushing
prices too high for most investors. Just 18 of Masternet's 17,000
shares changed hands Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Market executives expect US companies to list on Nasdaq Japan
later this year. Ultimately, the market's goal is to create a
global 24-hour exchange, in combination with Nasdaq markets in the
United States and Europe. ``The result is that companies all over
the world will be able to raise capital outside their home country,
that investors will be able to invest in companies outside their
home country,'' predicted Nasdaq chairman Frank Zarb.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq had never thought of Japan, with its maze of stifling
regulations, as a place to open a stock market geared toward young
companies. But during a March 1999 dinner in Tokyo between Zarb and
Softbank chief Masayoshi Son, the idea was born.
</P>
<P>
   They thought they could take advantage of the rapid changes
Japan's once hermetically sealed financial system was undergoing.
In the last few years, the country has embarked on extensive
financial deregulation, known as the Japanese version of the ``Big
Bang.''
</P>
<P>
   That finally has started to shake up Japan's entrenched
corporate system, which gave little opportunity to individual
investors, kept funding out of the hands of start-ups, and
prevented companies from going public until they been around a
decade or two.
</P>
<P>
   The last year has seen the most visible change. High-tech
entrepreneurs are flooding Japan (Tokyo has its own ``Bit Valley'')
and venture capitalists started setting up shop and writing checks.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq executives think the impending arrival of their market
helped propel the venture-funding boom. Investors ``knew there
would be a market where they could cash out. Our announcement gave
them hope,'' said John DeSaix, chief market strategist for Nasdaq
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Japan, says Luigi Limenpani, an equities analyst at
Solomon Smith Barney in Tokyo, ``could be the first real capital
market in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock markets have never had quite the impact on Japan's economy
that they have in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell the entire story of Japan's post-war economic
bubble without mentioning the stock market. It's been totally
irrelevant,'' said Alexander Kinmont, Japan equities strategist for
Morgan Stanley in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Many hope Nasdaq helps companies change their attitude toward
the stock markets and brings in new investors. Japanese companies
are notoriously averse to disclosing information. Catering to
shareholders has never been a top priority, since most of the
owners are financial institutions or other corporations; as a
result, Japanese stocks don't hold much interest for individual
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Masternet has started handing out a slick presentation kit, with
brightly colored charts and graphs showing revenue, profits, and
future potential. Entrepreneur Nishikubo says he designed it to
ready his company for its new Nasdaq era.
</P>
<P>
   Nishikubo is even doing something unheard of in Japan: He's
taking on a director to his board who comes from outside the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Japan's listing requirements for publicly traded
companies are the same as in the United States, though it will take
some time for disclosure regulations to catch up and companies to
begin filing quarterly financial statements. Compared with Japanese
companies traded on the Tokyo board and five other regional
exchanges, Nasdaq-listed firms will offer far more information on
company performance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many remain wary about Nasdaq Japan's prospects. A main
concern is its relationship with Softbank. Analysts and potential
investors are worried that the market could be used as a personal
vehicle for Softbank to take public its many group companies,
including some that may not be worthy of being listed on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real concern and they have to be very careful to
separate their interests. The risks of running into conflicts of
interest are real,'' said Limenpani.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference to announce the launch, Nasdaq chairman
Zarb bristled at any criticism that Nasdaq would not be transparent
and fair. ``It's illogical, has no substance, no merit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq says its listing requirements will remain firm.
Executives also say that they want in time to reduce Softbank's
share and bring in other investors.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Japan is not the first market for fledgling companies to
launch in Japan. In November last year, the Tokyo Stock Exchange
launched the Mothers market. With 10 companies trading _ seven
below their IPO price _ it hasn't engendered much positive
response. Listing standards are widely considered too loose, shares
are highly illiquid, and some of the companies a bit suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Many argue that Mothers' problems are actually bad for its
competitor Nasdaq Japan, because it has made investors wary about
new markets and new companies. If any of the companies listed on
Mothers actually fail, that could create more fear about investing
in any IPOs, on any market.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts believe it could take months, if not years, for
Nasdaq Japan to earn the trust of Japanese as well as foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts would like to see Nasdaq Japan attempting to
attract spin-offs of large Japanese companies. Not only would that
strengthen the nascent market, it would help the Japanese economy,
they say. That's because many Japanese companies are bloated with
subsidiaries that have little to do with their core businesses.
Economists believe that such restructuring could help Japan lift
from its current malaise.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of vibrant stock markets and companies trying to
please shareholders would be good for Japan, said Morgan Stanley's
Kinmont. ``It would turn Japan into something that looks more like
a capitalist country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
