<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, June 25,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Moving in `e' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FISCHINGER-FILMS (Undated) _ Decades before computer graphics,
before music videos, even before ``Fantasia'' (the 1940 version),
there were the abstract animated films of Oskar Fischinger
(1900-1967), master of ``absolute'' or nonobjective filmmaking.
Each film is a personal expression that reflects Fischinger's
mystical spirituality, a confluence of Hinduism and Buddhism. By
John Canemaker.
</P>
<P>
   CLOONEY-FILM (Burbank, Calif.) _ The story of George Clooney's
rocky though successful rise from television bit player to NBC's
smash hit ``E.R.,'' and, most recently, to movie stardom, reveals
an actor who can be as confrontational as he is affable, as tough
as he is thin-skinned, who often really did do it his way. By Dana
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-SUMMER-THEATER (London) _ Americans still patriotically
smarting at the number of British prizewinners in this year's Tony
Awards need only visit the British capital itself to find a salve
for sore pride. If the New York theater sometimes looks a bit like
Shaftesbury-Avenue-by-the-Hudson, there are parts of London this
summer that might be Broadway-on-the-Thames or even
Hollywood-Near-the-Atlantic. By Benedict Nightingale.
</P>
<P>
   JITNEY-THEATER (New York) _ On the surface, the play deals with
the social and economic troubles of the time through the impending
forced closing of the car service business, which will put the
drivers out of jobs. But as with all meaningful plays, ``Jitney''
operates on deeper levels as well. In the end, it is a play about
the meaning of love. By Wilborn Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH-COMIC-ALI (London) _ Clad in his bright yellow athletic
warm-up suit, Tommy Hilfiger skull cap, sunglasses and dangling
gold chains, the British cult comic character Ali G brings a new
look to the complex racial mix of London nightlife entertainment.
By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BACH-MUSIC (Undated) _ On an anniversary or in any other year,
there can be few musicological questions more pressing than that of
how Bach's music sounded when it was being performed for the first
time, week after week, under the composer's direction in St.
Thomas' Church in Leipzig. Light on this subject is now being shed
by one of the leading practitioners of early music, Andrew Parrott,
in performances, recordings and a book: ``The Essential Bach
Choir'' (University of Rochester Press). By Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   GILBERTO-LATIN-MUSIC (Undated) _ What Latin America struggles to
achieve in its civic life it produces effortlessly in its musical
art. That art is carried to its delicate conclusion in the music of
Joao Gilberto. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY-MUSIC-NATIVE (Undated) _ For those in the cities of the
north who like country music, it is music they like, not music they
live or grew up to. And it's definitely not the country music real
Southerners listen to. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY-MUSIC-CONVERT (Undated) _ New York Times reporter Peter
Applebome says that when it comes to music these days, for him it's
close to all country all the time. A country music convert tries to
explain how things worked out this way. By Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BALLETS-RUSSES (New Orleans) _ Everyone kissed everyone else and
the kisses were wonderful to behold. People kissed on lecture
platforms, in a hotel lobby, at an art gallery, at receptions.
There were delighted cries of, ``My dear, I haven't seen you for 50
years!'' And the remark was not hyperbole. Happy tears flowed like
Champagne. Champagne also flowed. All this happened at the Ballets
Russes celebration, an extraordinary event that took place here
June 1-4. It honored the three great companies with Ballets Russes
in their names: Sergei Diaghilev's pioneering Ballets Russes and
the successor troupes of Col. W. de Basil and Sergei Denham. By
Jack Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SIDEKICK-TV (Undated) _ It is the day after his last appearance
on ``Late Night With Conan O'Brien'' _ a day that a more
predictable type would probably describe as ``the first day of the
rest of my life.'' Nothing so shopworn comes from Andy Richter. He
takes stock in his own way, doing a kind of ``In the Year 2000''
routine about where he is and where he is going. James Barron
examines the death of the late-night sidekick.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WILKERSON-ANTIQUES (Undated) _ John Wilkerson was 7 when he dug
up a shiny stone arrowhead at a water hole near the family's small
ranch in Elko, Nev. Collecting arrowheads remained a passion
throughout his youth, spent among the children of ranchers and
Shoshone Indians, and much later, when he returned from college to
work summers as a cowboy and do research on the economics of
raising cattle in the West. Yet he never dreamed that in finding
that arrowhead at the water hole he had taken his first step toward
becoming, 50 years later, the president of the Museum of American
Folk Art in New York. By Rita Reif.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART/ARCHITECTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE-GLOBAL (Undated) _ The Surrealist critique remains
the most useful method we have for revealing the values at work in
environments constructed in the name of civilization: a Tahitian
village in Tunisia, a Cambodian temple in Paris, or a freeze-dried
street festival at our feet. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Coded `t')
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AGENTS-WEBSITES (Undated) _ Correspondent's report:
European airlines and hotels are taking on Web discounters, but
travel agents don't like it. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Lead item: Cities go whole hog for
animal art and a couple of famous spuds. By Joseph Siano.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AIRLINES-CONFIDENCE (Undated) _ A year ago, the airlines
vowed to ``restore public confidence.'' So, how have they done? By
David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EXPECTATIONS (Undated) _ Air travel is safe, and cheap.
Isn't that enough? By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AIRLINE-FOOD (Undated) _ Indigestible flying objects:
Good food, like good wine, doesn't travel well. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ All it takes to cancel a flight
is an ill wind. Understanding and dealing with flight
cancellations. By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AIRLINES-SLEEPING (Undated) _ Crossing the Atlantic in a
bed (take your own pajamas). By Peter H. Lewis.
</P>
