<P>
   KOREA-ANNIVERSARY: Fifty years after North Korea invaded the
South, triggering a war that left nearly 37,000 American soldiers
dead, the border dividing the Korean Peninsula into Communist North
and Capitalist South remains the world's last Cold War fault line,
a place where U.S., South Korean and North Korean troops face off
across the most heavily militarized border anywhere in the world.
Now, North and South Korea stand at the brink of a historic detente
that could usher in the reunification of the divided peninsula,
shifting, yet again, the geostrategic stakes for the United States.
The costs and the benefits of half a century of U.S. involvement in
Korea, pegged to 50th anniversary, on June 25, of the outbreak of
the Korean War.
</P>
