<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9539 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-390&AMP;ADD-     06-20 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT OF TAIWAN INVITES CHINA TO COPY SUMMIT MEETING OF TWO
KOREAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Emboldened by last week's remarkably warm
summit meeting between the leaders of the two Koreas, Taiwan's new
president, Chen Shui-bian, on Tuesday invited his Chinese
counterpart, Jiang Zemin, to take part in a similar peace-making
effort across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
   ``If North and South Korea can, why can't the two sides of the
strait?'' Chen said at his first news conference since taking
office last month. ``The Koreans have made a historic stride
forward. We can also make changes and create history.''
</P>
<P>
   But China predictably rebuffed Chen's overture, as it has
several other gestures he made since being elected the first leader
of Taiwan from outside the Nationalist Party in more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Chinese government said: ``The one-China
principle is the basis and precondition for peaceful reunification.
On this major, black-and-white question, we won't make any
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen's proposal, while shrewdly timed and boldly phrased, was
not accompanied by any concessions on the key issue that has kept
Taiwan and China apart. He reiterated that Taipei would not accept
Beijing's pre-condition for negotiations: that Taiwan acknowledge
there is only one China, of which it is a part.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he challenged both sides to show ``wisdom'' and
``creativity'' in crafting a new definition of ``one China''
acceptable to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   By seizing on the Korea summit meeting, however, Chen seemed to
be trying to shift the terms of the debate over cross-strait
relations. Rather than a standoff between a sovereign China and a
renegade Taiwan province, as Beijing contends, Chen painted a
portrait of two long-lost brothers linking hands.
</P>
<P>
   The progress between the Koreas underscores the paralysis in the
relationship between Taiwan and China. Although Chen's election did
not provoke military action from China, as Beijing had repeatedly
threatened, the two countries seem to be hunkering down for a
protracted stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten stuck,'' said Yung Wei, a longtime adviser to the
Taiwan government on cross-strait relations. ``The mainland Chinese
are being rigid. And Chen is not in a position to make an offer. He
wants to leave some room for a rapprochement without yielding a
basic point.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For all the familiar posturing on both sides, Chen seemed
genuinely inspired by the Korean meeting. He said it was a symbol
of how bitter adversaries could put aside their differences in a
historic bid for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Chen said he had put a photograph in his study of the two
leaders, Kim Jong Il of North Korea and Kim Dae-jung of South
Korea, shaking hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sincerely invite the leader of China, Mr. Jiang Zemin, to
join hands and work to create a moment like the handshake between
North and South Korea,'' Chen said Tuesday, smiling under a
sweltering midday sun.
</P>
<P>
   He also encouraged the United States to do more to bridge the
gulf between China and Taiwan. Chen said he expected the Clinton
administration to adhere to Washington's long-standing policy of
refusing to mediate between the countries. But he praised President
Clinton for reminding Beijing that Chen could not change Taiwan's
policy without the support of its people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the United States is willing, it can play a more active
role,'' he said. ``Keeping peace between the two sides of the
strait is not just in Taiwan's interest, it is also in the United
States' interest.''
</P>
<P>
   In dwelling on Korea, political analysts said Chen has more than
symbolism in mind. Several noted that Korea offers Taiwan a far
more appealing model for reunification than Beijing's preferred
example, Hong Kong. When China regained sovereignty over Hong Kong
in 1997, it guaranteed the former British colony some autonomy but
otherwise politically subsumed its separate identity.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan officials said such an arrangement would not satisfy
people in this country, which has developed a vibrant political
culture and, with Chen's election, marked its first democratic
transfer of power since the defeated Nationalist forces fled to
Taiwan from China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   The two Koreas, by contrast, recognize each other in
international organizations like the United Nations. When Kim
Dae-jung traveled to Pyongyang, he was greeted by Kim Jung Il as a
head of state. Beijing does not use Chen's name in official
statements, let alone recognize his status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taiwan always used to talk about the German model for
reunification,'' said Antonio Chiang, editor and publisher of the
Taipei Times, an English-language newspaper. ``Perhaps now we're
going to start talking about the Korean model, which involves two
countries on a equal footing.''
</P>
<P>
   Like North and South Korea, Taiwan and China share a common
language and cultural heritage. But Chiang noted that the
Taiwan-China relationship differs in one respect. While Korea was
divided by war, Taiwan was ruled by the Japanese prior to the
arrival of the Nationalists. This colonial heritage makes people
here suspicious of foreign rulers, even if they are Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   And while there has been little contact between the two Koreas,
China and Taiwan have not needed formal ties to develop a bustling
trade in goods and people. Relatives visit each other, fishing
boats from Taiwan moor in Chinese ports and 40,000 Taiwanese
companies operate on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Wei said the breakthrough in Korea carried risks for Chen. If
North and South Korea can ease the tension in their corner of Asia,
he said, other countries might press Taiwan and China for a similar
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Korean summit is going to have a major impact on
Taiwan,'' Wei said. ``The more the Koreans interact, the more
pressure it will put on Taiwan to agree to a framework with
China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
