<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9577 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SMALL-SCHOOLS-0621-CO     06-20 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-SCHOOLS-0621-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPORTS SAY SMALL SCHOOLS WITHIN SCHOOLS WORK WELL
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dividing a big public school into smaller schools _
sometimes in the same building _ improves the performance of
students and teachers, according to a set of five reports released
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The results from a two-year study of small schools in Chicago by
outside researchers should help strengthen support for smaller
schools in several other big cities, said the main report's chief
researcher, Patricia A. Wasley, dean of the graduate school at Bank
Street College of Education in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York, Boston, Philadelphia, Atlanta and Los Angeles have
small school initiatives under way,'' she said as she prepared to
brief advisors to members of Congress and presidential candidates.
``Oakland is preparing to move in that direction as well.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who obtained $45 million for small school
programs last year, has asked Congress to approve $120 million to
encourage the creation of smaller schools within 700 big schools in
low-income, low-performing districts next year. Final budget
negotiations this fall will decide the fate of his request.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 high schools (grades 9-12) and 33 elementary schools
(kindergarten through 8th grade) studied in Chicago each had no
more than 400 students and had been formed between 1990 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A handful are freestanding, but most keep down expenses by being
located within the same building as other small schools or a larger
``host'' school. They may or may not have fewer students per class.
</P>
<P>
   The small schools had roughly the same mix of students as other
Chicago schools that are neither magnet schools nor disciplinary
schools. ``Children in the schools are mostly from poor and working
class families and are predominantly young people of color,'' said
Linda C. Powell of Columbia University's Teachers College.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers compared the small schools' performance between
1997 and 1999 with that of their host schools and other Chicago
schools.
</P>
<P>
   They concluded that the smaller schools had:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fewer students who failed the promotion tests given in Chicago
in 3rd, 6th and 8th grade; more students who got high grades from
their teachers, and more students who improved their high school
scores in reading (though not in math).
</P>
<P>
   _ Lower dropout rates and higher attendance rates in high
school.
</P>
<P>
   _ Passing rates in required high school courses that matched the
city average and were much higher than those in their host schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Teachers who were less likely to use race or ethnicity in
generalizing about their students' performance, and who reported
greater job satisfaction, safer student behavior, more
collaboration with colleagues, and more efforts to improve the
curriculum and their own skills.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the small schools' average scores on annual
standardized tests didn't improve as much as the scores in other
Chicago schools. The researchers said smaller schools might have
lagged because their weaker students were less likely to drop out,
skip school on test day or be diagnosed as special education
students exempt from the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been at this long enough to know there are no silver
bullets in education policy,'' said August Souza Kappner, president
of Bank Street College, which published ``Small Schools: Great
Strides'' and its four supplemental studies.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   ``School size does not necessarily lead to good instruction,''
the researchers cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for the size of the school to have an impact on
student learning, it has to influence and facilitate greater
instructional variation, class size, the quality of the task, and
the clarity of the skills and knowledge teachers wish to
inculcate,'' they concluded, after visiting several schools several
times. ``The work that students do needs to be rigorous and
focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Several studies of school size over the last decade have shown
that in most cases, ``smaller is better'' for low-income children,
but ``bigger is better'' for children from high-income families.
Bigger public schools can be cheaper per pupil, but nearly as
expensive per graduate, since the big schools usually have more
dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   But those studies were based on the traditional model of one
school per building or campus, and cannot be compared directly with
the new study, which concentrated on smaller schools that shared a
principal, building or campus with other schools.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Bank Street College of Education: www. bankstreet.edu
</P>
<P>
   Smaller Learning Communities Program:
www.ed.gov/offices/OESE/SLCP/overview.html
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
