<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEWURZTRAMINER: GIVE LOVE A CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom has it that people either love
gewurztraminer or hate it. I disagree. Most people have no idea
whether they love it or hate it, because they've never tried it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe people are scared off by the daunting name (pronounced
guh-VERTS-trah-meen-er), or the wine's reputation for exotic
flavors: gewurztraminer is usually described as tasting like
litchis, rose petals and grapefruit.
</P>
<P>
   I happen to love this extravagantly fragrant white wine, but in
small doses, because I find many gewurztraminers to be not very
flexible with food. Their potent flavor tends to overpower most
foods, although they are a fine accompaniment to choucroute garni,
the Alsatian sauerkraut and pork extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   The solution to the food issue is paradoxical. Gewurztraminers
range from dry and fairly simple to unctuously powerful, complex
and sweet. Not surprisingly, the complex wines are more expensive,
costing $50 or $60 a bottle, and generally do very well in wine
ratings. But the simpler bottles, which balance the more exotic
elements with a breezy dryness and citrus flavors, are better with
food.
</P>
<P>
   Gewurztraminer is mostly identified with Alsace, where it
flourishes in the region's cool climate, but it also does well in
parts of Germany, particularly the Pfalz, and in some cooler areas
of California, like the Anderson Valley in Mendocino County.
Another dose of conventional wisdom has it that California can't
produce good gewurztraminers, but examples from both Navarro
Vineyards and Handley Cellars are just the sort of dry
gewurztraminers that work with food.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to deride the richer examples. They are by all
means great wines, and can be enjoyed as aperitifs or for dessert.
But with dinner, stick with simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   ALBERT MANN, ALSACE 1998 $25
</P>
<P>
   Aromas of flowers, honey and melon; dry with a lively, spicy
edge.
</P>
<P>
   HUGEL, ALSACE 1998 $15
</P>
<P>
   Spicy citrus aromas, dry and straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   NAVARRO VINEYARDS, ANDERSON VALLEY, MENDOCINO COUNTY 1998 $14
</P>
<P>
   Citrus, lemon and grapefruit aromas, nice and refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   J.B. ADAM, ALSACE, RESERVE 1998 $14
</P>
<P>
   Aromas of roses and honey, a little sweetness with a long
finish.
</P>
<P>
   HANDLEY, ANDERSON VALLEY, MENDOCINO COUNTY 1998 $16
</P>
<P>
   Classic aromas, lemon and grapefruit flavors, dry and
refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   DOMAINE PAUL BLANCK, ALSACE 1998 $16
</P>
<P>
   Aromas of honey, flowers and spices, clean and fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Listed in order of preference. Prices are those paid in various
Manhattan wine shops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
