 Eds.: The Globe's Tuesday technology package is now being moved
under a separate budget; see TECH-BUDGET (f).  
 ART ADV.: A photo with SCI-SQUID is being transmitted to NYT Photo
Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-COMMUNISM (Tokyo) _ There is no shame in joining Japan's
second biggest party, the Communist Party, which is establishing
itself as a legitimate and articulate voice of opposition. By
Sharon Moshavi. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-SUITS (Tokyo) _ Japanese are suddenly doing something
normally frowned upon: They are suing their doctors. What's more,
small patients' advocacy groups have sprung up and are questioning
the country's medical system. by Sharon Moshavi. 1600 words.
</P>
<P>
   SAVING-YIDDISH (Tel Aviv) _ Pain over the declining use of
Yiddish is sharp in Israel, the state that was formed to protect
and nurture Jews and their culture. By Aliza Marcus. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-JOURNAL (London) _ Do you suppose it's time they just
stopped using the word ``millennium'' around here? Anything the
British attach the word millennium to ends in disaster. By Kevin
Cullen. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
