<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9590 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES     06-20 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE A FUN, FAST-PACED RIDE IN `HOT SIX' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Janet Evanovich's hilarious sixth mystery again features the
very likable, yet inept, New Jersey bounty hunter Stephanie Cross,
who amazingly always gets her man, in ``Hot Six'' (St. Martin's
Press, $24.95, 294 pages).
</P>
<P>
   After talking her friend Carol out of jumping off a bridge,
Stephanie heads for the office of her Uncle Vinnie, a bail
bondsman, hoping he has some wayward bondees who need picking up.
Right now Stephanie's bank account is as nonexistent as her love
life. And does Vinnie have a job for her. Ranger _ a really good
bounty hunter, a former soldier of fortune with a strong stock
portfolio and Stephanie's mentor and sometimes lover _ has failed
to appear on charges of carrying a concealed weapon. And now,
Ranger is considered a prime suspect in the murder of the son of
Alexander Ramos, an international black-market arms dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Stephanie refuses to take the case. So Vinnie gives
her three lowlife AWOLS to detain: Morris Munson, who ran over his
wife, ``beat her with a tire iron, raped her and tried to set her
on fire''; Walter ``Moon Man'' Dunphy, wanted for drunk and
disorderly conduct; and Lenny Dale, charged with domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Another old lover, Trenton Vice Cop Joe Morelli, asks Stephanie
to let him know if she hears from Ranger. Saying yes to Morelli,
Stephanie heads off for the home of Dale, who is having a big fight
with his wife. Before Stephanie can cuff him, Dale dies of a
massive heart attack. Next she stops at Moon Man's place; he
invites her in for lunch so he can watch the end of a ``Rocky and
Bullwinkle'' retrospective.
</P>
<P>
   Saying she has a lunch date with her mom, Stephanie says she'll
come and get him later. As soon as she gets out the door, two thugs
in a black Lincoln pull over and tell her to get in. No way is
Stephanie going to get into a ``mob staff car with two strange men,
one of whom is a Pakistani with a .38 tucked into his Sans-A-Belt
pants, partially hidden by the soft roll of his belly, and the
other is a guy who looks like Hulk Hogan with a buzz cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Habib, the Pakistani, and Mitchell, the buzz cut, are after
Ranger and tell her they are going to tail her because they figure
Ranger will eventually contact her.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch, she picks up Moon Man and takes him to the Trenton
Police Station to get him a new bond. She leaves him with the
docket lieutenant and heads upstairs to check in with Brian Simon,
who arrested Carol. He agrees to drop the charges, but tells
Stephanie she owes him big time. When she gets back downstairs,
Vinnie is there, but not Moon Man. He is out in the parking lot
watching Stephanie's car burn _ seems he dropped a lighted reefer
and the car caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie thought the day couldn't get any worse until her
grandmother shows up at the door with a suitcase and says she is
moving in until she finds her own apartment.
</P>
<P>
   We're at page 36 in this wildly funny and amazingly fast-paced
look at the wacky life of a dysfunctional bounty hunter, whose
trials and tribulations have only just begun. Crisp and sassy
writing fuels the funny world of Stephanie Cross, which is peppered
with characters who would fit in nicely in Quentin Tarentino's
``Pulp Fiction.'' As always, Evanovich has a sure-fire summer hit.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Controlled Insanity.'' By Randy Cruts. Black Forest Press.
$14.95. 418 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Cruts' second thriller featuring Navy SEAL Lt. Nick Cutter
is a fast-paced joy ride into the world of international terrorism
and drug-dealing.
</P>
<P>
   Cutter heads a covert counter-terrorism team that is sent to
Bosnia to assassinate two of its leaders. After a very difficult
high-altitude jump, Cutter's team lands in Bosnia and heads for a
hunting lodge where the two Bosnians are scheduled to meet.
However, before they can accomplish their assignment, another
assassin kills not only the two Bosnian leaders, but also their
entire entourages.
</P>
<P>
   Airlifted out, the team returns to base and is immediately sent
to the Caribbean to kill the computer whiz of a giant drug cartel.
The target, Shane Kearny, tells them that he no longer works for
the Mauricio Moncada drug cartel because the cartel is funding the
Islamic Ibn Allah terrorist group. Cutter decides to spare Kearny's
life and take him back to the United States for a debriefing.
</P>
<P>
   Cutter, his team and his girlfriend become targets of the
cartel. It's a fight of good vs. evil as the action mounts. Cruts
gets carried away with technical jargon in some sections, but cut
that out and you have a perfect book to take to the beach or keep
you occupied on your next plane ride.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep South.'' By Nevada Barr. G.P. Putnam's Sons. $23.95. 340
pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep South'' finds National Park Service Ranger Anna Pigeon
moving from her beloved Colorado mountains to Mississippi to become
district ranger for the Port Gibson District of the Natchez Trace
Parkway. After 22 hours of driving, she sees a sign that says
``REPENT,'' then a bullet-riddled sign with the words ``REPENT.
FINAL WARNING.'' Next thing she knows, she skids and the car and
U-haul are off the road. Some local fisherman help her get the car
and U-haul back on the road and in the right direction. Turns out
one of the rangers she'll be supervising gave her wrong directions.
</P>
<P>
   This is just the beginning of the problems she will encounter on
her new assignment. On her first night, she is awakened in the
middle of the night by a camper complaining of some joy-riding
kids. Pigeon trails them to a nearby church and cemetery. The boys
flee but before returning to her house near Rocky Springs
Campground, Pigeon hears crying and discovers a drunken teenage
girl in the cemetery. Pigeon takes the teen back to her place and
puts her to bed. After the girl's parents pick her up the next
morning, Sheriff Paul Davidson stops by to say a teen is missing.
Pigeon says Heather is safe, but Davidson says he is looking for
Danielle.
</P>
<P>
   Pigeon returns to the cemetery and begins to search the area and
eventually finds Danielle's body with a sheet over her head and
noose around her neck. As Pigeon begins her investigation, she
encounters resentment from her co-workers and eventually becomes a
victim of some very dangerous practical jokes. ``Deep South'' has a
well-crafted plot, strong characters and realistic dialogue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
