<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9592 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     06-20 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMARILLO BUSINESSMAN SEES PROFIT POTENTIAL IN A LIQUID, AND IT'S
NOT OIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Edna Ferber's ``Giant'' were updated to reflect the New Age
wildcatters of Texas, the epic drama could have a decidedly
different look.
</P>
<P>
   James Dean's character, Jett Rink, would not stand on the porch
of the Benedict family mansion, dripping oil from all over his
body. In the new version, Rink would drip, but he would be clean as
a whistle.
</P>
<P>
   Water might soon be the state's newest liquid gold. Oil
continues to lubricate the wheels of commerce in West Texas, but
with a growing population sucking up the state's groundwater, new
pipelines are needed to move crystal-clear, life-giving H2O across
the state.
</P>
<P>
   It seems inconceivable at the moment. With city streets still
damp from recent rains, water doesn't appear such a valuable
commodity. In a state that just weeks ago was crying about a
suffocating drought, the most recent headlines bemoan record
downpours.
</P>
<P>
   In Waco, this year's rainfall is 6 inches above normal. The
Concho Valley, in the San Angelo area, saw flash floods this
weekend. Lubbock has the highest June rainfall total ever.
</P>
<P>
   But the drought will return; it always has. And entrepreneurs
are stationing themselves to reap the benefits of waterless cities
and barren fields.
</P>
<P>
   Amarillo oilman T. Boone Pickens has been buying up water rights
in the Texas Panhandle, and he intends to pipe the water to needy
cities such as San Antonio, El Paso and perhaps Abilene, Dallas and
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Sweetwater has used its right of eminent domain to condemn 705
acres southwest of the city to develop wells that could deliver a
million gallons of water per day to the community.
</P>
<P>
   That has prompted a lawsuit involving a Fort Worth company. Duer
Wagner and Co., a petroleum producer, owned the property, and when
Sweetwater took possession, the company tried to negotiate a
selling price with the city.
</P>
<P>
   Duer Wagner recognized that the city was buying the land not for
its surface but for its underground resources. In Texas, water will
continue to be a valuable resource, and that's what Sweetwater was
after.
</P>
<P>
   The company asked more than $6,500 an acre. The city offered
$300 an acre, the land's appraisal value.
</P>
<P>
   The case went to court, and the city won. But that was only the
first round. An appeal is pending, and all of West Texas, along
with a bunch of ``water wildcatters,'' is watching.
</P>
<P>
   It seems improbable that parched, cactus-filled West Texas land
could go for thousands of dollars an acre or that a network of
pipelines will spill out of the high plains to supply cities far to
the south.
</P>
<P>
   But even the lawyers who won the initial Sweetwater case
understand that the issue is far from closed. They admit that there
is little or no precedent for this kind of case.
</P>
<P>
   And cities such as San Antonio that have seen their own water
sources dwindle to alarmingly low levels have shown interest in
Pickens' Panhandle pipelines. Pickens says he has bought up 100,000
acres of water rights and is looking for another 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The hotter the summer, the higher the interest.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
