<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9594 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-20 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCEEDING THE CLOTHING-CARE INSTRUCTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICAN FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was in elementary school, my father took me to see the
Jackson 5. Michael Jackson was my age then; now, for some reason,
he's younger than I am.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, there were four of us at the concert: me, my dad, my
friend Cynthia and her father. It was my first concert, and I was
so excited. As I recall, it was held at the Tarrant County
Convention Center and we had floor seats.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't too alarmed when the Jacksons came out and everyone
stood up to cheer. However, imagine my dismay when it became
apparent that those evil, tall people in front of me were not going
to sit down. I couldn't have been much over 4 feet tall, so even
when I stood on my chair, I could only make out the several
bouncing, black mushrooms, which I assume were the tops of their
Afros.
</P>
<P>
   Noticing my consternation, my father gallantly hoisted me to his
shoulders and there I remained until the end of the concert. Now I
could see Michael and those other guys. (I was so in love with
Michael!!!)
</P>
<P>
   But even better, Michael could see me in my white dress with the
red patent leather vest stitched onto the front of it. I loved that
dress almost as much as I loved Michael. It was my favorite piece
of clothing. I would still have it if my mother hadn't thrown it
out when I moved away from home.
</P>
<P>
   Sigh, sigh.
</P>
<P>
   When we bought that dress, it fell below my knees, but by the
time I was banned from wearing it, it was a mini.
</P>
<P>
   So you see, I do understand that people have their favorite
attire. However, I do not understand why my boys love certain
clothes so much that they wear them until they fade while other
things remain in the drawer undisturbed until they're too small.
Don't they want a little variety? How many times can you wear a
shirt that says, ``Here's a dollar. Buy yourself some game.''?
</P>
<P>
   Surely, your friends would notice after a while.
</P>
<P>
   My oldest son will bypass clean clothes and try to dig that
awful shirt out of the dirty laundry if he's going somewhere
special. Why does he think that I won't notice? Even if his friends
don't care, I care.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have a lot of clothes, because he's growing so fast,
but he does have enough T-shirts to get through the week. I'm not
even going to go into his one pair of size 16 athletic shoes that
we have to special order.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, baby brother has a potpourri of clothes. He
gets hand-me-downs and new stuff so there is no reason for him to
keep wearing that same pair of too-big shorts that hang off his
little, narrow hips. I am sick of those shorts. Last week, he
plucked that single pair of shorts out of his overflowing bag of
dirty laundry and washed them. He wasted all that water on one pair
of shorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Mom, I didn't want to wear those other clothes,'' he
explained, when I admonished him. ``Look at my brother. He's
wearing that dirty T-shirt again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What's a girl to do? When my youngest got ready to go to camp,
he was practically in tears because he didn't have enough cool
clothes to take with him. I dug through the faded items at the top
of his drawer and found two brand new T-shirts buried underneath.
My sister bought him those for Christmas but every time he washes,
he puts the favorites back on top of everything else in the drawer
and then he wears the same clothes again.
</P>
<P>
   When I gave him the shirts, he said, ``Oh yeah, I forgot about
those. Where were they?''
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's all I have to say about that because it's obvious
they aren't going to change any more than I did when I was their
age. However, did you know that I was a major influence on Michael
Jackson's wardrobe? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   When we went to that concert, I was wearing white socks with my
white patent leather shoes. A few years later, guess who started
wearing white socks everywhere he went?
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence? I think not.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
