<HEADER>
A9597 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-20 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANCERRE, THE ULTIMATE SUMMER WINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   America has one great white wine, chardonnay. There are, of
course, a host of runners-up: sauvignon blanc, chenin blanc, pinot
blanc, pinot gris, viognier, riesling and a few hardly worth
mentioning, like trebbiano.
</P>
<P>
   France, on the other hand, has an abundance of great white
wines. They start with Burgundy and its superstars like
Batard-Montrachet and Corton-Charlemagne. A few miles up the road
toward Paris is Chablis, whose steely, green-gold wines have never
met a crustacean they couldn't ennoble. Alsace offers its elegant
rieslings. To some connoisseurs, wines like Trimbach's Clos
Ste.-Hune and Zind-Humbrecht's Clos St.-Urbain are the finest of
all white wines.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Sancerre. Is it equal to the others in breed
and finesse? Perhaps not, but it is beloved in France and in much
of Europe as the ultimate summer wine, a wine for picnics (dejeuner
sur l'herbe, as they say over there) and for parties. It may be
France's friendliest white wine.
</P>
<P>
   Sancerre is a place, not a grape. It's in the beautiful Loire
Valley about 120 miles south of Paris. The grape is the sauvignon
blanc, which shows up in many Loire Valley wines, including Quincy,
which almost rhymes with ``can't see'' and is the name of another
town, and Pouilly-Fume, which is named for Pouilly-sur-Loire,
across the Loire River and a few miles south of the village of
Sancerre. The wine has lots of acidity and a pronounced herbaceous
taste. At its best, Sancerre is fresh and lively and should be
drunk young.
</P>
<P>
   (Don't confuse Pouilly-Fume and Pouilly Fuisse. Pouilly Fuisse
comes from southern Burgundy and is made from the chardonnay
grape.)
</P>
<P>
   The name Sancerre comes from castrum sancti satyri, which is
Latin for ``stronghold of the holy satyrs.'' The name also lingers
in a neighboring village called St.-Satur. What went on in those
parts in Roman times is anyone's guess, but today it is wine
country.
</P>
<P>
   For almost half a century, Sancerre has been the white wine of
choice in Paris bistros. In the 1950s, production amounted to about
50,000 cases a year. Today, it's close to a million.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Friedrich, in her book ``A Wine and Food Guide to the
Loire'' (Henry Holt &AMP; Co., 1996), traces Sancerre's popularity back
to 1946, when Edward Alphonse Mellot, a Sancerre producer, opened a
wine bar on the Avenue Rapp in Paris. Its name? Le Sancerre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artists, writers and gastronomes _ from Jean Cocteau to Jean
Marais to Curnonsky _ regarded Sancerre as the little white they
drank with shellfish platters,'' she wrote. ``Then Chablis prices
skyrocketed after a killer frost in 1956. And autoroutes took
Parisians past Sancerre on their way to the ocean. Its success has
not yet peaked.''
</P>
<P>
   The best Sancerre doesn't come from Sancerre. It is to be found
in neighboring towns like Bue, Chavignol and Verdigny. The best
wines are sold under the names of locations within those towns like
La Perriere in Verdigny and La Poussie in Bue. Some of the best
producers include the Domaines Alphonse Mellot and Roger Neveu,
Cotat Freres, and Pascal Joliver.
</P>
<P>
   The Mellots, who are led, according to Friedrich, by the 18th
Alphonse, are one of the best known families in the region because
their wines are good and because they run a highly visible
restaurant, Mellot, in the village of Sancerre, along with a
tasting room and wine shop. Their best wine, Cuvee Edmond, is made
from vines up to 60 years old and is partly vinified in oak
barrels.
</P>
<P>
   The most talked-about wine in the Sancerre region at the moment
is made across the river in the village of St.-Andelain, near
Pouilly; it is Didier Dagueneau's Pouilly-Fume. Dagueneau is a
highly vocal champion of low yields in the vineyards, and like many
crusaders he does not hesitate to denounce competitors who he
contends make thin, characterless wines.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his most sought-after wines are Pur Sang _ thoroughbred _
and Silex. Most Sancerres and Pouilly-Fumes sell in the $15 to $20
range. These two can sell for $50 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my favorite wines from this region come from Quincy,
about 25 miles west of Sancerre. The wines occasionally lack the
raciness of the best Sancerres, but the best of them can be sharp
and refreshing. Quincy is an appellation that nearly died out in
the 1960s and 1970s but has been growing and improving since then,
thanks to the big demand for white sauvignon wines in Paris and
across northern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Reuilly, a few miles from Quincy, has much the same history, and
some observers, Friedrich among them, believe that eventually it
will emerge as a closer competitor to Sancerre.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Sancerre rouge _ red Sancerre _ became popular as
the wine to go with nouvelle cuisine. Most Loire reds are made from
the cabernet franc grape. Sancerre rouge is made from pinot noir
grapes. But any resemblance to the pinot noirs of Burgundy or
America's West Coast are accidental. Their popularity has declined
with that of nouvelle cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   A few producers take their reds seriously, and the result is a
full-bodied wine worth sampling as a curiosity. But the best place
to drink Sancerre rouge is in the restaurants around Sancerre when
the wines are fresh and young. There is also a pleasant rose. Come
to think of it, aren't all roses pleasant?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1606EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
