<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEMEPARKS-COST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMUSEMENT PARK PRICES ON UPSWING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN WOOD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The average cost of going to a U.S. theme
park shot up this year after a year of falling prices, according to
an annual survey taken by Amusement Business.
</P>
<P>
   The average cost for a family of four to spend the day at a
theme park increased more than 7 percent, or $10.12, to $151.44,
compared with the previous year. That's a record high, according to
Amusement Business, an industry publication that surveys prices at
25 parks representing a variety of geographic areas, facility sizes
and price ranges.
</P>
<P>
   The average cost for a family of four to go to Six Flags Over
Texas increased 13.97 percent, or $22.50, to $183.50, thanks
largely to an increase in the cost of a souvenir T-shirt. A child's
souvenir T-shirt costs $14 this year, compared with $5 last year,
according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Six Flags Over Texas and Premier Parks did not
return telephone calls seeking comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices at Six Flags fell 75 cents for adults and 25 cents
for children compared with prices in last year's survey. Six Flags
was the only one of the nine parks on the survey owned by Premier
Parks, which owns 35 parks, that didn't increase ticket prices this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Premier Parks, based in Oklahoma City, led the
decrease in Amusement Business' family-price index by setting
children's ticket prices at half of adult prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a decrease last year,'' said Gloria Radeff, an
analyst covering Premier Parks for Lehman Brothers in New York. ``I
guess last year it was a big year in terms of them getting more
traffic through the parks in terms of pricing. I think they're
still working on driving attendance with season passes, group sales
and combination tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that higher ticket prices at most Premier parks
surveyed could be an incentive for guests to opt for season passes.
</P>
<P>
   The Premier parks with the largest increases in ticket prices
also had some of the biggest changes and capital improvements
during the off-season. They include Six Flags New England _
Riverside Park until last year _ which got eight new rides. Adult
admission there went up $7. At Six Flags Magic Mountain in
Valencia, Calif., which added a new roller coaster, adult admission
went up $4.
</P>
<P>
   This year's average increase, $10.12, is the largest in the
history of the survey, according to the magazine. Last year's
figure, a $1.58 decrease, was the first drop ever. In 1998,
Amusement Business' survey found an average increase of $9.32; in
1997, the average increased $8.88.
</P>
<P>
   The survey is based on admission prices for two adults and two
children, parking for one car and purchase of two hot dogs, two
hamburgers, four orders of fries, four small soft drinks and two
children's T-shirts. The survey does not take into account
discounted admissions, which most consumers use.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
