<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9628 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-GAYS-RELIGION-1STLD-W     06-20 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-RELIGION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUNNED BY MAINSTREAM CHURCHES, GAYS WELCOMED AT SOME HOUSES OF
WORSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS to correct byline)  
 (Eds: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN GUTIERREZ-MIER  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Prayers were offered and hymns were sung.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of fellowship as mothers, fathers, children and
couples filled the pews of Rainbow Cathedral on a recent Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beloved, God truly does love you,'' the Rev. John Nicholas,
pastor of the 200-member church, told his congregation.
</P>
<P>
   The service was like many throughout San Antonio on any given
Sunday. There was one big difference: the majority of those in the
pews were gay or lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   Being gay while being faithful is something that, when noticed
in other churches, has caused controversy and consternation. Entire
denominations that regard homosexual inclinations or behavior as a
sin are arguing over what role, if any, openly gay churchgoers can
have in religious life.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Stotts, president emeritus of the Austin Presbyterian
Theological Seminary, said Christianity has grappled with the
homosexual question since its earliest days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church has struggled over the centuries to develop
perspectives on pressing issues,'' Stotts said. ``Racial equality
was one issue. Women being ordained or serving in leadership
positions is another. People take different positions. It's the
same way with the homosexual question.''
</P>
<P>
   Presbyterian theology does not prohibit people from being
members or holding office because of their sexual orientation,
Stotts said, but gay Presbyterians are required to remain celibate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexual orientation itself is not a sin. But the behavior that
comes with it is,'' Stotts said.
</P>
<P>
   Few pastors in mainstream denominations in San Antonio or Austin
perform same-sex marriages, but one who does said his congregation
has been enriched by not only accepting but embracing as equals
gays and lesbians who enter a committed relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Art Severance, pastor of First Unitarian Universalist
Church in San Antonio, said he has performed about two dozen union
ceremonies for lesbians and two for gay men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religiously, it's a wedding,'' Severance said. ``Legally, it's
not _ yet. I liken it to the civil rights era when a white would
never marry a black or a minister would be divorced.''
</P>
<P>
   Such unions, and the ordination of gay clergy, have become
topics of open debate at leadership gatherings of Protestant
denominations, and Stotts said it would be foolish to assume gays
and lesbians are not already part of most Christian churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just don't flaunt it. They're not out of the closet, so
to speak,'' Stotts said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas, the openly gay pastor of the Rainbow Cathedral, an
affiliate of the Universal Fellowship of Metropolitan Community
Churches, said that is precisely why the fellowship of churches was
established in Los Angeles in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is welcome at our church, including heterosexuals,''
said Nicholas, a Navy veteran and pastor of one of a half-dozen
congregations in San Antonio that openly accept gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Coinciding with an emerging gay and lesbian movement in the
1960s, the establishment of the Metropolitan Community Churches
offered church services for those whose sexual orientation made
them unwelcome, or made them feel that way, in the denominations
they grew up in.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, a network called Dignity/USA was formed
to provide Masses for gay Catholics. The Catholic Church has never
officially sanctioned the group, but even in conservative South
Texas, a handful of sympathetic priests celebrate Mass each Sunday.
One of the priests, the Rev. Eddie Bernal, said it's considered an
``outreach ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gays and lesbians have been told a lot of lies and have been
made to feel horrible about themselves,'' Bernal said. ``Many times
people in religion have scapegoated on gays and lesbians, pointing
their finger at them and causing them to suffer from unnecessary
low self esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Dignity they find solidarity, support and love. They find
what every Christian church should offer them: love.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jim Cottone, a retired professor of infectious diseases at
the University of Texas Health Science Center in San Antonio, being
forced to give up either his sexuality or his religion is out of
the question. He has been attending Dignity services since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dignity completes me,'' Cottone said. ``It makes me realize
that my upbringing as a Catholic is still part of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dignity congregants are reluctant to reveal where they hold
services. Nickie Valdez, who has been a member of the group since
1983, remembers a Sunday in 1987 when members got in their vehicles
after Mass and drove off.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't get far. The lug nuts on their wheels had been
removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly a message,'' Valdez said. ``Luckily no one
was hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the Presbyterian Church (USA) and the Episcopal
Church will debate sanctioning same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, United Methodist Church leaders voted to uphold
their doctrine that homosexual behavior is incompatible with
Christian teaching. It also adopted a policy requiring clergy to be
faithful in heterosexual marriage or celibate otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, messengers at the Southern Baptist Convention in
Orlando, Fla., voted to revise the Baptist Faith and Message
Statement to oppose homosexuality, along with what they called
``all manner of deviant and pagan sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Although each Baptist congregation is autonomous, the statement
is viewed as the closest thing the denomination has to an official
creed.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Central Conference of American Rabbis, which
represents 1,800 Reform rabbis serving more than 1.5 million Reform
Jews, approved a measure allowing them to perform same-sex
commitment ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Lasalle R. Vaughn, pastor of New Life Christian
Center, a nondenominational Christian church in San Antonio, said
the growing lesbian and gay movement and increasing public
acceptance of same-sex unions is blasphemous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the Bible says homosexuality is a perverted
lifestyle,'' Vaughn said. ``Just like all of those having sex
outside of marriage. That's perversion.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he is offended by the notion that those opposed to
the gay lifestyle are bigots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm African-American and being homosexual does not make you a
minority,'' Vaughn said. ``We're not going to accept it in this
church.''
</P>
<P>
   Wes Giles, who attends services at Rainbow Cathedral, said
anti-gay sermons from fundamentalist pulpits breed hatred and
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about hell and damnation, fire and brimstone,
especially if you're gay,'' said Giles, a volunteer coordinator for
the San Antonio Gay and Lesbian Community Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I run across that hate, my response is John 3:16. Jesus
Christ died for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact John Gutierrez-Mier by e-mail at
jgmier(at)express-news.net)
</P>
