<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FERMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBJECTIONS TO `41 SHOTS' ADD UP TO VERY LITTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amazing what one song can do.
</P>
<P>
   I refer to the flap raised the past several days over ``American
Skin (41 Shots),'' the new, unrecorded and unreleased Bruce
Springsteen song that the Boss first performed last week in
Atlanta. He sang it again on Monday during the first of 10 sold-out
shows he's doing at Madison Square Garden to cap a long reunion
tour with the E Street Band.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skin'' is a pointed reference to the fatal shooting of Amadou
Diallo on Feb. 4, 1999, by four New York City police officers as
the unarmed 22-year-old West African immigrant stood in the
vestibule of his apartment building. Forty-one shots were fired; 19
hit him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it a gun? Is it a knife? Is it a wallet? This is your
life/It ain't no secret/It ain't no secret/Ain't no secret my
friend: You can get killed just for living in your American skin''
is the chorus.
</P>
<P>
   For having the temerity to sing this song, Springsteen has been
vilified by the New York City Patrolmen's Benevolent Association.
PBA President Pat Lynch accused Bruce of ``trying to fatten his
wallet'' with the song and urged cops working security at the
Garden to boycott the shows.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bob Lucente, president of the New York state chapter of the
Fraternal Order of Police weighed in, calling Springsteen a
``dirtbag'' and worse.
</P>
<P>
   I won't descend to their level of name-calling in responding.
</P>
<P>
   First, a reminder: There's a crazy little thing we call freedom
of speech in this country, which does, in fact, extend to rock 'n'
roll singers who write and perform a song about a brutal and
controversial shooting, even though a racially mixed jury acquitted
the four plainclothes cops on all counts.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the part about Bruce trying to fatten his wallet,
which is patently ridiculous. He's been a multimillionaire for
years, the song isn't officially available for purchase, and the
shows were sold out many weeks ago. So that record won't spin,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the knee-slapper from Lynch about ``Skin'' coming
at a time when the ``police officers and community members are in a
healing period.''
</P>
<P>
   This is politically correct nonsense-speak we can translate as:
Some of our cops shot an unarmed black man ``NINETEEN TIMES'' and
got the world's attention, and we would very much like everyone to
just go away and act like it never happened. Because it was
embarrassing for us.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, Diallo's mom and dad, Kadiatou and Saikou Diallo,
support Springsteen and met with him backstage before Monday's
show. So does Police Lt. Eric Adams of 100 Blacks in Law
Enforcement Who Care. And so does the Rev. Al Sharpton, who invited
Springsteen to march in Washington against police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   So which ``community'' is ``Skin'' stopping from healing, Pat?
</P>
<P>
   ``American Skin'' does not vilify all police officers. It does
not say all police officers are bad people. It does not say all
police officers are prone to shooting an unarmed black man 19
times.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in the second verse, a mother gets her son Charlie
ready for school and reminds him that if he's stopped by a police
officer, to be polite, not run away ``and promise mama you'll keep
your hands in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Do we really think that black mothers haven't said this or
something very similar to their children (especially their young
men) in the days and weeks after the Diallo shooting?
</P>
<P>
   I would wager they have, hundreds of times, and still do,
because the song is the truth: Here in the United States you still
can die for being black and in the wrong place at the wrong time.
And no amount of name-calling by a couple of cops can change that.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at Dave Ferman, (817) 390-7839, or
e-mail: dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
