<HEADLINE>
HEY, POPS, HAVE YOU GOT A LIGHT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm having my father's old cigarette lighter repaired. It needs
a new flint. The wick is shot. And I've managed to lose the little
screw normally visible at the bottom when you slide the insert out
of the metal case.
</P>
<P>
   I don't smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The lighter is a Zippo manufactured in 1950. I checked the
patent number on the case through a computer Web site maintained by
people who collect Zippo lighters. I don't collect Zippo lighters.
</P>
<P>
   I have this one lighter. The silver patina is worn at the top
and around the edges. It has a few dents in it. The phrase ``safety
pays'' is engraved where the top flips open, and the words ``J&AMP;L
STEEL'' are in a box on the lower right-hand corner.
</P>
<P>
   It probably was given to my dad the year it was made, a gift
from the steel mill he'd returned to after the war. He was about 30
years old then, still running on the war's adrenaline. Happy,
strong.
</P>
<P>
   He first let me hold the lighter when its 2- by 1{-inch body was
too large for me to pinch between my middle finger and thumb, the
way he did, twirling it round and round with his index finger.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't allowed to open it or to light it.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, when he was adding fluid, he'd let me hold the can as
it dripped into the container.
</P>
<P>
   My father quit smoking about 35 years ago, and I doubt the
lighter has had fluid added to it since. But even now, if you hold
it close to your nose, you can smell it. And the oily scent lingers
on your fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   He used to hold the lighter sometimes just to open it and close
it, oblivious to the metallic click-clop, click-clop, click-clop,
until my mother would ask him to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Something in him required that his life have a rhythm to it. A
beat. This was it.
</P>
<P>
   The real skill, though, was in lighting a cigarette. With one
hand, my father could open the lighter, roll his thumb over the
flint wheel, light a cigarette and close the lighter in half the
time it took you to read this sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, when he worked the midnight-to-8 a.m. shift, sleeping
during the day, I'd sneak into my parents' bedroom and take the
lighter from the nightstand next to where my father slept.
</P>
<P>
   Already, my friends and I were lifting Luckys and Camels from
our parents' cigarette packs and lighting up under the Plan 12
bridge, trying to act tough.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking didn't interest me much, though. It was that slick move
with the lighter I wanted to perfect, that open-light-close
happening so fast you might not notice the flame. I never mastered
it.
</P>
<P>
   Not enough practice, I guess. Or not enough of the post-World
War II optimism that ran like lighter fluid through my father's
veins.
</P>
<P>
   The cigarette lighter sat in a junk drawer in my parents' house
for decades, unwanted, unnoticed, unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   It's necessary now.
</P>
<P>
   After my mother and father died, the lighter was moved from
their junk drawer to a shelf in my house, to my desk at work, to my
pocket, to my hand. I was happy for a while just to carry it
around.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm having it repaired. The Zippo company does such work
for free. And though I'll never develop my old man's speed and
grace, I want to be able to strike a flame. I don't smoke
cigarettes. There's nothing I need to light. Except, occasionally,
my way. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
