<HEADER>
A9662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SEA-BEANS-NYT &LR;      06-20 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEA-BEANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRINY BEAN WITH PLENTY OF SNAP 
</HEADLINE>
   By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They go by so many names they would seem to be as
common as corn: sea beans, sea asparagus, samphire, salicornia,
pousse-pied, glasswort. Until recently, though, these salty little
vegetables were just an oddity turning up once a year or so between
the pea shoots and the cipolline onions in high-end produce
markets. Now, thanks to new farming techniques, fresh sea beans are
becoming more abundant and available.
</P>
<P>
   They are more than a novelty. These little stalks of crunchy sea
vegetation _ actually a fleshy flowering plant _ have a subtly
salty flavor and a fascinating crispness that suits them to salads
and other dishes. They can even be deep-fried to make the
equivalent of French fries of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   The sea bean (Salicornia europaea), a member of the beet family,
has long been considered a delicacy in France and Great Britain.
The beans grow wild there along the shores of salt marshes and are
gathered by hand when still young and tender, usually from mid-May
through June.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, sea beans are traditionally pickled and served with
roasted meats, while in France they are often blanched and coated
with butter or hollandaise or tossed raw into salads.
</P>
<P>
   Sea beans also grow in rocky coastal areas in the United States,
particularly in Oregon and Maine, but have never been in much
demand here. Now they are being cultivated, mainly in Mexico; these
beans are more consistently tender than wild beans, which can be
fibrous and woody at maturity. They are planted in sandy estuaries
and harvested every six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs are taking to sea beans, and several markets carry them.
At Balducci's, 155A West 66th Street and 424 Avenue of the Americas
(Ninth Street), they are $14.99 a pound, and at Dean &AMP; DeLuca, 560
Broadway (Prince Street), $12 a pound. Three 12-ounce packages are
$30 at Melissa's Gourmet, (800) 588-0151.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Pasternack, the chef of Esca in the theater district, was
introduced to sea beans more than a decade ago by a French chef.
``They've got an intense, briny taste that couples really well with
fish and seafood,'' he said, adding that the less you do to them,
the better. Blanching took away all the flavor, he said, ``so I
either use them raw, pickle them in vinegar or give them a quick
stir-fry.''
</P>
<P>
   With guaranteed supplies, sea beans have become a fixture on the
Esca menu, served over translucent slivers of raw fluke sprinkled
with herbs and olive oil. In one special, Pasternack mixes sea
beans with the thinnest of green beans in a crunchy salad as a bed
for a square of wild salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Mina Newman, the chef at Dylan Prime in TriBeCa, heard about sea
beans from a supplier and was taken with the saltiness. ``They
reminded me of capers, so I paired them with steak tartare,'' she
said. The effect is similar to that of capers, but cleaner and
fresher, without the vinegary tang.
</P>
<P>
   Most chefs capitalize on the beans' affinity for seafood. Rick
Moonen of Oceana in Midtown adds them to a lobster salad; at Jack's
Fifth in Midtown, the co-chefs, Matthew Herzog and Marc Van Steyn,
match them with roasted tautog, a meaty, white-fleshed fish, and
smoked trout. At Thalia in the theater district, Michael Otsuka
pickles them to serve beneath baby monkfish tails.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Rodriguez at Chicama in the Flatiron district takes a
slightly different tack: instead of serving sea beans with seafood,
he uses them instead of it in his seaweed ceviche. Although the
citrus-marinated seaweeds served in the martini glass are
delicious, the real standout is the garnish: nutty, deep-fried sea
beans.
</P>
<P>
   If you buy carefully, sea beans require much preparation. Choose
the greenest, firmest beans for the best crunch and flavor. Discard
any that are discolored or shriveled. A short soak should dislodge
any sand, and they're ready to eat or cook.
</P>
<P>
   DEEP-FRIED SEA BEANS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Chicama
</P>
<P>
   Time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   { cup plus 2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon ground turmeric
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil for deep-frying
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces sea beans (about 1 cup), trimmed.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place { cup of the flour in a small bowl. In another small
bowl, whisk together the remaining flour, cornstarch, turmeric and
salt. Stir in enough water, about 3 tablespoons, to create a thin,
runny batter.
</P>
<P>
   2. In medium saucepan, heat 2 inches of oil to 365 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   3. Dredge sea beans in the plain flour, then in the batter,
shaking off excess. Deep-fry in batches until beans are golden
brown, 3 to 4 minutes. Use a slotted spoon to transfer the fried
beans to a plate lined with paper towels to drain before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   PICKLED SEA BEANS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Jane Grigson's Vegetable Book'' (Penguin Books,
1978)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes, plus cooling and chilling time
</P>
<P>
   } cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   } cup dry apple cider
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon prepared white horseradish
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces sea beans (about 2 cups), trimmed.
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, bring the vinegar, cider, horseradish and
peppercorns to a simmer. Add the sea beans, and turn off the heat.
Let the beans cool in the liquid. Transfer the beans and liquid to
a jar. Cover them, and refrigerate for at least 4 hours before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 pint.
</P>
<P>
   WILD SALMON WITH SEA BEANS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Esca
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes, plus chilling time
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced shallot
</P>
<P>
   Sea salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   7 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces haricots verts (about 1\ cups), trimmed
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces sea beans (about 2/3 cup), trimmed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   4 6-ounce fillets wild salmon, skin on.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small bowl, combine the vinegar and shallots with a
pinch of salt and pepper. Slowly whisk in 6 tablespoons of the oil.
Season with more salt and pepper if necessary. Refrigerate
vinaigrette for at least 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. Fill a bowl with ice water, and set aside. Bring a small pot
of salted water to a boil, and add the haricots verts. Cook until
tender, about 2 minutes. Drain well, and immediately plunge into
the ice water to stop the cooking. Drain again. Toss the haricots
verts with the sea beans, vinaigrette and parsley, and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   3. Season the salmon on both sides with salt and pepper. Heat a
large skillet, preferably nonstick, over high heat. Add the
remaining oil and then the salmon, skin side down. Cook until the
skin is well browned and crisp, about 5 minutes. Carefully flip the
salmon, and cook until medium rare, 3 to 4 minutes. Divide sea bean
mixture among 4 serving plates. Lay 1 fillet on top of each bed,
skin side up, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
