   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TRAVEL (Washington) _ The common wisdom about Congress,
repeated in news reports and accepted as truth in foreign embassies
in Washington, is that few lawmakers travel abroad, only half hold
a passport, most do not speak a foreign language and a majority are
uninterested in worlds beyond their next election. This portrait of
Congress, especially the House, as an inward-looking institution
grew largely out of the Republican revolution of 1994 led by Newt
Gingrich. The House Republican Class of '94 proudly adopted the
defiant slogan, ``America first.'' But a New York Times survey
challenges each and every one of these common wisdoms. By Eric
Schmitt and Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HATE-CRIMES (Washington) _ The Senate is expected to
vote to make hate attacks on homosexuals a federal offense. While
the Senate passed a similar measure last year by unanimous consent,
Tuesday's vote was the first time either House of Congress backed
protection of gays or lesbians on a rollcall vote that would have
political consequences. By Adam Clymer.
