<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-LABOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS GROUP SEEKS SAFEGUARDS FOR YOUNG FARM WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN GUTIERREZ-MIER  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ An international human rights organization charged
Tuesday that U.S. labor laws are doing little to safeguard young
farm workers, many of whom are Hispanics, and should be revised and
better enforced.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Rights Watch, a nonprofit group that monitors human
rights in about 70 countries, found children often work 12 to 14
hours a day on U.S. farms and are exposed to dangerous pesticides.
Only about 55 percent graduate from high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we hope to do is make the U.S. government aware of the
fact that kids who work in agriculture usually get less pay, are
exposed to pesticides and work long hours,'' said Lois Whitman,
director of the children's division of the New York-based
organization, which released a report on farm labor Tuesday. ``We'd
also like to see an increase in enforcement by the Occupational
Safety and Health Administration and the Environmental Protection
Agency when it comes to safety issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The group is calling on Congress to amend the Fair Labor
Standards Act. The act, passed in 1938, sets the minimum wage and
the length of the standard workweek for most employees in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The law, however, exempts young farm workers from minimum age
and maximum hour requirements that protect other children.
</P>
<P>
   In other occupations it prohibits the hiring of children under
14 and limits those under 16 to three hours of work a day when
school is in session.
</P>
<P>
   The act also allows 16- and 17-year-olds to work under hazardous
conditions in agriculture. The minimum age for all other
occupations is 18.
</P>
<P>
   Juanita Valdez-Cox, director of the United Farmworkers Union in
San Juan in the Rio Grande valley, applauded the report and said it
was long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farm work is only second to mining when it comes to dangerous
work for adults,'' she said. ``One can only imagine how dangerous
it is when it comes to children.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said if the law is changed, it may present a hardship
for many migrant families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason they're taking their children out there to
work is because they're not making enough money,'' Valdez-Cox said.
``Over the years, it seems like we've gotten a lot of paper
victories, but they're just that. If the law is changed, Congress
has to make sure enough money goes to OSHA and the EPA. And they,
of course, have to follow through.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Pringle, legislative director for the Texas Farm Bureau
in Waco, questioned the validity of the report and stressed that
the original law was designed for rural families and should not be
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rural children are used to working on the farm from the ages
of about 12 and 13,'' said Pringle, whose organization represents
farmers in Texas. ``It's not uncommon for children as young as 12
to be driving a tractor to haul hay. For those reasons, we support
the current exemptions and would fight any changes proposed in
Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Human Rights Watch report, titled ``Fingers to
the Bone: United States Failure to Protect Child Farmworkers,''
young farm workers often earn less than minimum wage. They also
account for 8 percent of all working minors, but account for 40
percent of work-related fatalities among children.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch also is proposing that every state raise or
set its minimum age for farm work at 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
