<SLUG> BC-TRUCK-SAFETY-0621-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SAFETY GROUP SLAMS PROPOSED NEW TRUCK RULES
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Highway safety activists charged Tuesday that a
Clinton Administration proposal would put more tired truck drivers
on the road and increase risks to other motorists.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration ``is proposing
to degrade safety by increasing the amount of time that truck
drivers can remain behind the wheel from 10 to 12 hours a day,''
said Joan Claybrook, president of Public Citizen, a consumer
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Daphne Izer, whose 17-year-old son, Jeff, and three of his
friends were killed in Maine in a 1993 collision with a driver who
had fallen asleep at the wheel of a big rig, said she is
``stunned'' at the plan announced last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Administration's attempt to justify more driving hours is
unfounded,'' she said. ``No load of toilet paper or Wheaties is
worth your life or that of your loved ones.''
</P>
<P>
   An arm of the Department of Transportation, the Federal Motor
Carrier Safety Administration was created by Congress last year to
improve highway safety and reduce fatalities involving trucks and
buses. This spring, the agency proposed new work rules for
commercial truck drivers. One regulation would lengthen the maximum
hours of consecutive driving from 10 to 12, but then increase the
mandatory rest time from 8 to 12 hours for long-haul drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The current rule requires that drivers take at least 8 hours of
rest after a maximum of 10 hours driving and thus could permit
driving 16 hours of a 24-hour day. Transportation Secretary Rodney
Slater said the proposed rules are based on scientific studies of
sleep cycles and would limit driving to no more than 12 hours
within a 24-hour day.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed changes in the ``hours of service'' had already
been attacked by the motor carriers for economic reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proposal could mean a 50 percent increase in the number
of refrigerated and dry van trucks on our already crowded
highways,'' said Walter McCormick, president of the American
Trucking Association. ``DOT's proposal would force today's
sophisticated e-commerce, point-and-click, just-in-time delivery
system back into old economy inefficiencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Now highway safety advocates have added their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Driver fatigue is a major factor in up to 40 percent of all
heavy truck crashes,'' said Claybrook. ``We strongly urge the
government not to tack two more long hours onto truckers' already
lengthy days.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Claybrook conceded that her movement is in a
``complicated position'' because it doesn't want to thwart needed
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The safety advocates support DOT proposals for the additional
rest periods and to require on-board electronic recorders that
would ensure that long-haul drivers are abiding by the hours of
service rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``On-board recorders to replace the manual logbooks or 'comic
books' as they are referred to by everyone are long overdue,'' said
Izer, founder of a safety group called ``Parents Against Tired
Truckers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland, R-Ga., was among 14 senators who wrote to
Slater expressing concern about the proposed changes in driving
hours. Cleland spoke Tuesday at a press conference held by the
safety advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious that we have a problem,'' he said. ``Georgia is
one of the top five states in terms of truck traffic.'' The danger
is increased around Atlanta because ``commuter traffic is mixed
with truck traffic on The Perimeter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving in the wrong direction'' in proposing longer
hours that truckers can spend on the road,'' said Sen. Barbara
Boxer, D-Ca.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Senate voted 99-0 in favor of an
appropriations bill that denies funds for implementing the new
rules for at least a year. The House bill did not contain this
restriction, however, so the issue will go before a conference
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Slater said he would extend the public comment period
on the proposed changes for 90 days, with the new conclusion set
for Oct. 30.
</P>
<P>
   For online information:
</P>
<P>
   www.dot.gov
</P>
<P>
   www.patt.org
</P>
<P>
   www.truckline.com
</P>
<P>
   www.citizen.org
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
