<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION CANDIDATE BRINGS BLUNTNESS TO MEXICAN CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Vicente Fox Quesada, the leading contender to
dethrone the party that has ruled Mexico for seven decades, is
running an aggressive, irreverent campaign that would be right at
home north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, the presidential candidate for the center-right National
Action Party, or PAN, has become the John McCain of Mexican
politics, a sweet-and-sour powder keg of indignation, good cheer
and shocking bluntness.
</P>
<P>
   And Fox, a rancher and former president of the Coca-Cola Co. for
Mexico and Central America, is running neck and neck or better with
Francisco Labastida Ochoa, the candidate of the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Fox calls the PRI ``a party dictatorship'' that has wrought
corruption and fraud for most of the 20th century. Only a political
change, he says, can bring Mexico out of its economic and social
inequity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result at the end of the century is deplorable,'' he said
recently. ``A country with 40 million poor people can't be called a
successful country. ... Mexico could have a place in the top 10 or
15 nations in the world, and only democracy, an alternative in
power, will guarantee us that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox refers to his PRI opponent, a reserved economist and veteran
public servant, as ``this little man,'' or ``shorty'' or the
``wimp,'' and to the PRI as the ``PRI-tanic,'' as in the sinking
Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   Such irreverence has not always gone over well with the public,
but the boastful Fox has fired up the imagination of many Mexicans
with his strong rhetoric, deep voice and 6-foot-5 frame made even
taller by his trademark black cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   He will be 58 on July 2, the day Mexicans will vote in what
pollsters are calling the closest presidential race in Mexico's
history.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is running even with Labastida, who is backed by a powerful
party machine that can reach into all corners of Mexico with its
social programs and party favors.
</P>
<P>
   In Levi jeans _ 34 inches at the waist, 38 along the seam, held
up by a silver buckle emblazoned with ``Fox'' _ the former governor
of Guanajuato cuts a striking figure.
</P>
<P>
   A divorced father of four children, Fox is literally at home on
the range, in the saddle and wearing a cowboy hat, a rugged, modern
vaquero who appeals to the Mexican image of independence.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his appearance and his rugged demeanor, he has been
described _ sometimes derisively by the media _ as the ``Marlboro
Man,'' a Mexican John Wayne with a Jesuit education, a Harvard
degree and a passion for politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a businessman, but I am also a human being. I learned at
the ranch from living with the poor. They are my friends, but they
are still poor,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jesuit philosophy tells you that a person finds happiness
helping others. It is the antithesis of egoism.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps so, but ego does get in the way at times, as it did in
May when Fox refused to abide by the strict rules of a televised
debate with Labastida and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the candidate for
the leftist Democratic Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<P>
   The media called it Fox's ``Black Tuesday,'' after he first said
he didn't want to debate and then changed his mind, shouting on
national television he wanted to debate ``Today! Today! Today!''
</P>
<P>
   The ``today'' exclamation became a campaign slogan for both Fox,
who used it as in ``change parties today,'' and Labastida, who used
it to make Fox look like a lunatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell him to take some transcendental meditation
courses. I would tell him to listen to a little Mozart ... to count
to 10 until opening his mouth,'' Reforma newspaper columnist
Guadalupe Loaeza wrote.
</P>
<P>
   One of five children, Fox embodies an immigrant family who came
to Mexico and made a life and money in cattle and agriculture in
much the same way European migrants thronged to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   His mother was born in Spain, and his Irish grandfather landed
in Ohio, finally settling in Mexico in 1913 at the height of the
Mexican Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a man of the country, as all my family has been for four
generations,'' he wrote in an autobiographical campaign book, ``Fox
to Los Pinos,'' as the official presidential residence is called.
</P>
<P>
   ``My origins are like that of many families in Mexico, product
of a union of cultures and different ways of thinking, but rooted
in this land,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He studied at the private Lux Institute and attended the elite
Universidad Iberoamericana, where Fox said he was the only one to
wear jeans and where he played on the soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, short of finishing a thesis for a business
administration degree (which he finally completed in 1999), Fox
became a Coca-Cola salesman.
</P>
<P>
   Coke sent him to Harvard, where he received a degree in
management. From 1974 until 1979, he was president of Coca-Cola for
Mexico and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am accused of wanting to run the country as if it was
Coca-Cola,'' he wrote. ``It's not about that, but about rescuing
principles and philosophies that work well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, in politics there is more than management and
production; you have to put a human face to the economy,'' he
added. ``The ultimate result in politics ... has to be having happy
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   An ardent believer of free trade, Fox foresees a time when the
United States, Mexico and Canada will have no borders, when goods
and people can travel freely.
</P>
<P>
   He also envisions a North American common market, and wants to
link the ``four great economic machines of Latin America _ Mexico,
Brazil, Chile and Argentina _ to detonate an era of growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Labastida, who wants to maintain Mexico's 5 percent
annual growth, Fox thinks it's possible to have a 7 percent growth
rate and 1.3 million new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   He's landed in political hot water several times, once telling a
reporter he wanted to privatize Pemex, the oil monopoly
nationalized in 1938 and one of the country's sacred cows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to privatize Pemex, because I want to be
president,'' Fox told foreign correspondents recently, indicating
the sale could not be a political reality.
</P>
<P>
   He also was ridiculed for quipping that he could solve in ``15
minutes'' a lingering 1994 standoff in Chiapas, where Zapatista
rebels are demanding greater economic and political independence
for the southeastern state's indigenous population and where the
armed forces remain on alert.
</P>
<P>
   Fox later said he would withdraw the army presence and abide by
accords with the Zapatistas that never have gone into effect.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he owes his political awakening to mentor Manuel J.
Clouthier, the PAN presidential candidate and party founder killed
before the 1988 national election in a car accident many Mexicans
still call suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was elected to the national congress, and became governor of
Guanajuato in 1995, four years after fraud allegedly robbed him of
the governorship.
</P>
<P>
   He is the only bachelor in the presidential race. Divorced from
his wife, Lillian, they have four adopted children and remain good
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I started my struggle to get (elected), people always
ask me what I am going to do about a first lady, and they even
invent romances,'' he wrote. ``But I am completely committed to my
four children and to politics. ... What I vehemently reject is that
you have to be married to be president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
