r e BC-VIDEOGAME-REVIEW-TEX     06-20 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOGAME-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPCOM KEEPS CASHING IN ON SUCCESS OF `STREET FIGHTER'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's two reasons why Capcom's ``Street Fighter'' series has
done so well: Kids dig it 'cuz of the cool animation, and parents
dig it because there's no blood.
</P>
<P>
   And year after year, Capcom keeps cashing in on ``Street
Fighter's'' success, releasing sequel after sequel. Some of these
are completely worthless, others build on the ``SF'' genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Street Fighter Alpha 3'' (Capcom for Sega Dreamcast) falls
into the latter category. The first ``SF'' game for the Dreamcast,
``Alpha 3'' is loaded with new enhancements and features that
aren't even in the arcade version. That's one cool thing you can
say about the hit-and-miss Sega: They always throw in stuff you're
not gonna get elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Here, that would include the skill-building World Tour Mode and
three-player battle, both of which are very cool pluses to an
already great game.
</P>
<P>
   In now-typical ``Street Fighter'' fashion, the animated graphics
are superb, beautifully colored and textured. They look like they
were torn from the pages of a comic book, they're so well-detailed.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 30 fighters from the ``Street Fighter'' gang
to choose from _ and, supposedly, a few hidden ones. I can't
unearth them, though, 'cuz I keep getting beat by the really big
guy with the beard and mohawk, the dude who looks like Mr. T.
You're on your own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Channel 5'' (Sega for Dreamcast) is sort of a cross
between the local newspaper and Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   Players take on the role of Ulala, a Space Age reporter who,
when she's not trying to scoop a story and save the universe
(because, of course, that is the same thing, you know), dances and
grooves to techno music. Yeah, it's pretty stupid.
</P>
<P>
   The object of the game is to teach aliens how to dance and stop
the world from blowing up. Oh, I get it: If the aliens learn how to
dance, they'll befriend Spacey Spice and help her save whatever it
is she's supposed to be saving. Man, Sega, what a fine idea! I'm
thinking game of the year!
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   The latest old game to be dug out of its grave is ``1942''
(Capcom for Game Boy), an airplane shooter that was a popular
arcade game back when I was a kid, you know, just a coupla years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   This thing is still way cool: It's an overhead-view game in
which you control a plane that _ whoa, this is ``so'' hard _ blasts
away at other planes. Sometimes the simplest games are the coolest.
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713, or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
