<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9679 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-MATERNITY-FASHION-100     06-20 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATERNITY-FASHION-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CLOTHING LINES FOR EXPECTANT MOTHERS EMERGE AS SOPHISTICATED,
STREAMLINED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAVONNA MAY-MONS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Move over, mumus.
</P>
<P>
   The days when moms-to-be were relegated to bow-covered tents
masquerading as fashion are officially over. Going, going, thank
goodness they're gone.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a convergence of forces _ among them, perhaps,
Hollywood starlets with swelling bellies, Madonna with child No.
two, La Nina, and Alan Greenspan's ever-expanding economy _
pregnancy is trendy. It's cool. And as it tends to do, form has
followed function once again. And fashion has followed burgeoning
forms.
</P>
<P>
   With approximately 4 million American women giving birth each
year, it was only a matter of time until savvy manufacturers and
designers would capitalize on the booming market, moving beyond
selective (and often high-priced) maternity boutiques _ where
fashion first showed a hint of its lovely face about 10 years ago _
into hip, casual, very wearable clothes for the style-conscious
consumer.
</P>
<P>
   The surest sign that maternity has made it into the mainstream
collective fashion conscience is Gap.com's new line of basics,
still in its infancy after a March debut.
</P>
<P>
   Why the decision to give birth to the new line? Brooke Baldwin,
spokeswoman for the San Francisco-based Gap, says it was simple.
``We found out customers would be trying to make our regular line
of clothes into maternity clothes. So why not give them what they
are looking for and have it actually fit?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. The retailers's 16-item maternity line gives Gap-aholics
their favorite basics with a twist. Separates include a classic
cotton cardigan, sleeveless cotton shell, cotton/spandex stretch
capris and supersoft T-shirts, at price points between $24 and $84.
The items are only available online at gap.com, but they may be
returned at branch stores.
</P>
<P>
   Other mass market stores such as Macy's, Lord &AMP; Taylor and
Target are following suit, delivering new, expanded maternity
sections due to large demands. Target stores now house nine
clothing racks of maternity wear compared with about half that just
10 years ago. Target's maternity line offers what their regular
line offers _ a mix of classic and trendy styles at affordable
prices, with a focus on solid-colored coordinates and shorts sets.
This summer, Target will offer its line of maternity items online.
</P>
<P>
   Designers such as Nicole Miller, Anna Sui and Vivienne Tam have
jumped on the maternity bandwagon in the last few years, creating
versions of their popular lines for A Pea in the Pod stores
nationwide. For the ultimate in pregnancy chic, Barneys New York
opened maternity departments last December in its flagship New York
store and its Beverly Hills and Chicago outposts. The store sells
items under its own label _ Barneys New York Procreation _ as well
as offerings from Tocca and other designers.
</P>
<P>
   Today's thoroughly modern maternity clothes are making their
mark in clingy, form-fitting fabrics like Lycra. The most
fashion-forward of the new maternity lines includes that of former
``Vogue'' editor Liz Lange, whose bold and often outright sexy
designs include halter tops, tube tops and short, stretchy skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Lange, who has been publicly credited with almost
single-handedly bringing fashion firmly to maternity wear when her
line came out about two years ago, says pregnant women should
expect her clothing to offer the latest fashions without
sacrificing comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that my friends and myself just wanted to wear the same
things everyone was wearing,'' she says. ``With some exceptions, of
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Pregnant with her first son, Lange, who is now 33, was surprised
at the lack of variety in maternity clothes. Most shirts were
shapeless and baggy, while pants had uncomfortable (and
unfashionable) maternity panels. Lange's line includes high-end
treats such as a $500 dupione evening gown and a $110 pair of
stretch cotton sateen shorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maternity clothes didn't seem to follow the same fashion
sensibility as nonmaternity, and I thought, `that's crazy,' '' she
says. ``You're pregnant for nine months _ anything you feel like
wearing on a given fall or given spring, (when) not pregnant should
be available (when) pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   For 4 million women, the good news is, now, it is.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
