<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-BAYLOR-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE CUBS AND SOSA, THE SEASON BECOMES A TRADE SAGA 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 10th inning of a tie game with the Arizona Diamondbacks
this month, two Chicago Cubs outfielders brushed against each other
while trying to catch a fly ball with two outs. The ball fell to
the ground and the Diamondbacks went on to score two runs.
</P>
<P>
   The official scorer charged center fielder Damon Buford with an
error but later changed the ruling and assigned the error to the
right fielder: Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, after the Cubs had rallied for three runs and a
4-3 victory, the right fielder asked a member of the Cubs'
front-office staff to talk to Manager Don Baylor about the ruling.
If Baylor felt it was Buford's error, Sosa thought, maybe he could
get the official scorer to change his call back to Buford. The
manager, though, believed the right ruling had been made because
Buford had called for the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Sosa, in effect, declared war on Baylor, telling
reporters that the manager had not treated him ``the way I'm
supposed to be treated.'' Baylor, he added, ``has got no class.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa did not tell the reporters how he had wanted Baylor to get
involved in the error call. His unusually sharp comments were
attributed to statements Baylor had previously made about Sosa's
deteriorating defense, among other facets of his game, that Baylor
saw as coming up short.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the schism between the new manager and his
superstar had been created and would add fuel to the Sosa situation
that has exploded on the North Side of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The betting around baseball is that Sosa's name will be added to
the list of glamour players who have been traded since the end of
last season, a group that includes Ken Griffey Jr., Juan Gonzalez
and Shawn Green. If so, it will be one of the more intriguing
developments of recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is the No. 1 player in a city where he wants to stay,
certainly one of the most popular in Chicago's checkered baseball
history. He is a premier slugger, having hit 129 home runs the
previous two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But other factors are at work, and not just Sosa's clash with
Baylor. The Cubs' real star anyway is Wrigley Field, a baseball
anomaly that the team may feel will fill up even without Sosa.
Also, the Tribune Co., the team's owner, would not want to pay
upward of $15 million a year to keep Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   In that way, Sosa will join a growing list of superstars who are
being traded before they can become free agents. In the other
instances, the players were traded a year before they could become
free agents because their teams concluded that they could not sign
them or did not want to pay what it would cost to keep them.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey went from Seattle to Cincinnati, Gonzalez from Texas to
Detroit, Green from Toronto to Los Angeles. Mike Hampton went from
Houston to the Mets, Carl Everett from Houston to Boston and Jim
Edmonds from Anaheim to St. Louis. These players, in effect, were
premature free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who because of his scintillating home run race with Mark
McGwire in 1998 has grown perhaps even bigger than Griffey in
stature, would be in that position this winter, but he may be even
more premature than last winter's group.
</P>
<P>
   Just as his trade value is probably at its highest now, so is
his ability to get a monster of a contract. The combination of
value to the Cubs and value to Sosa is the reason this entire
situation has blossomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say there are three different things that could
happen,'' Andy MacPhail, the Cubs' president, said the other day.
``Reach agreement on a contract extension. Trade him. Not do
anything since we're fortunate to have the player signed through
2001. I can't assign a probability to any one of those.''
</P>
<P>
   No one outside the Cubs has expressed the opinion that they will
sign Sosa to a contract extension. The Tribune Co. is one of the
most hard-line owners in Major League Baseball, ranks 13th among
the 30 clubs with a $60.5 million payroll this season and has shown
no inclination to spend in the lofty stratosphere where salaries of
elite players is headed, $15 million to $20 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, there is the sense in and out of Chicago that the
Cubs don't have to spend top dollar to try to win because the
Wrigley Field experience attracts fans, win or lose. The Cubs, who
have not won a World Series since 1908 or played in one since 1945,
have long been known as the most lovable losers in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing view among baseball officials is that the Cubs
will trade Sosa sometime before the July 31 deadline for making
trades without needing waivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't let it go this far if you're not going to make a
deal,'' one veteran official said. ``They've let it go on too long.
Their responses have been vague. If you're going to keep a guy, you
don't do this. I think Sammy wants out. I didn't think so a week
ago; I think that today. Their leverage is the greatest right now,
the next week or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet MacPhail and General Manager Ed Lynch have not acknowledged
their intentions to trade Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't make that assumption,'' MacPhail said. ``It's not
something you can generate a lot of excitement from the chair I'm
sitting in. But you have a responsibility that if something is
going to make you better, you have to review it. But it's not a
foregone conclusion from my point of view.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE; OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   This is Sosa's ninth season with the Cubs. As he himself has
said, he has become an icon in Chicago. Because he loves the city
and its people and the whole Wrigley experience, he would prefer to
be with the Cubs the rest of his career. Not, however, without an
appropriate contract.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Katz, who with Tom Reich represents Sosa, has met with
MacPhail but said that he made no demands and that he doesn't know
what the Cubs will do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've discussed our desire to have them decide what they want
to do,'' Katz said. ``We all agree it's time to decide. If they
want to sign Sammy and keep him, then my bet is they could pull
that off quickly. If they want to trade him, we'll be cooperative.
My desire is to be collaborative and cooperative. I don't want to
press them. I think it's still possible for both sides to get what
they want. Whether that's together or apart, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that the Cubs will trade Sosa has become the
premier story of the season. Newspapers and radio and television
air time in Chicago, New York and Boston have been filled with Sosa
stories. Will he or won't he, and where?
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs have fueled the speculation by sending scouts to
scrutinize major and minor league players of the teams they think
are most seriously interested. The Yankees and the Red Sox are the
two clubs with the hottest interest, officials of other clubs said.
The Mets' interest, some say, has been overrated. The Diamondbacks,
they also say, have some interest, though not as much at this point
as the Yankees and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees expect to hear from the Cubs by the end of this week
on what players the Cubs would want for Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   From Sosa's standpoint, he has the collective bargaining right
to veto a trade, which means the team that makes a trade with the
Cubs has to be prepared to sign Sosa to a new contract or face his
veto. Under baseball rules, the Cubs would make a contingency trade
with a team, then give that team 72 hours in which to negotiate
with Sosa's agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever he approves a trade to,'' Reich said, ``he's going to
be inclined to want to finish his career there rather than bounce
around through free agency or go through this again.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides a torrent of speculative news media reports, the Sosa
situation has generated a rush of analyses and columns urging the
Yankees not to trade for the outfielder on the grounds that he
wouldn't fit in with the low-key, star-free environment that is
their clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   One criticism of Sosa has been that he has fallen in love with
his image as a megastar and has changed in the last two years. Katz
said the assessment is nonsense, but others point to specific
examples.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's entourage, for one. After emerging from the 1998 season
as a world-class hero, Sosa gathered a group of about 10 to 12
people around him who were steady visitors to the clubhouse last
season. Baylor has curtailed the entourage this season, perhaps
another reason Sosa has soured on him.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the visiting parking list at Pacific Bell Park
when the Cubs played in San Francisco last month. Baylor, as
manager, was on the list with one other member of the team: Sosa.
MacPhail, the club's president, was on the trip but not on the
parking list.
</P>
<P>
   But it is disclosure of stories like these along with the
suggestion that Sosa has become a one-dimensional player that
prompts the Sosa camp to believe the Cubs have orchestrated a
campaign to reduce the player in stature in the eyes of the fans.
If the Wrigley regulars come to think less of Sosa, the thinking
goes, they will be less bothered if and when he is traded.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the fans and a handful of eager teams wait to find
out if he will be traded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
