<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9685 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CHICKEN-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      06-20 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE NOT TRYING TO RUFFLE FEATHERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Aardman animators Nick Park and Peter Lord met DreamWorks
executive Jeffrey Katzenberg for dinner to pitch their idea about a
prisoner-of-war movie with chickens, they weren't sure how it would
go over _ particularly after Katzenberg told them about the
specialty of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Everything's good here, but you must order the roast
chicken,''' Lord says. ``So we did as we were told and, in between
bites, we told him about our heroic chickens.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg swallowed the idea whole, not a surprise since he had
been chasing Aardman _ the British company responsible for the
wildly popular, Oscar-winning claymation man-dog duo of ``Wallace &AMP;
Gromit'' _ for a decade, dating back to his tenure at Disney. The
result, four-plus years in the making, is ``Chicken Run,'' a
delightful claymation retelling of ``The Great Escape'' from a
bird's-eye view.
</P>
<P>
   Lord co-founded Aardman in 1972; Park joined the company in 1985
and has won three Oscars for his animated short films (two for
``Wallace &AMP; Gromit,'' one for ``Creature Comforts''). The two men
are about as low-key as they come, unfailingly polite Englishmen
who cherish tea, creative control and sitting in the afternoon
California sun.
</P>
<P>
   Here, they talk about hatching ``Chicken Run,'' why they ran
away from Disney and the future of ``Wallace &AMP; Gromit.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why chickens?
</P>
<P>
   Lord: We often asked that question ourselves. They're great
subjects to make a movie around, but not great subjects for
animated figures. We had to work really hard. They're not like
conventional cartoon characters, but they're always funny, and that
was the joy of it. Whether they're standing around looking rather
dippy ...
</P>
<P>
   Park: And they're very good at that ...
</P>
<P>
   Lord: Or flying into a panic and running and screaming, they're
funny just because they're chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Park: We got the idea from a drawing I did of a chicken digging
a hole with a spoon. And that evolved into this prisoner-of-war
film with chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Lord: We spent nine months developing the idea and we came up
with this absurdly elaborate story full of action and events and
set pieces based on way too many things that I'm sure would have
run for four hours had we ever made it. And it probably would have
taken five years to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And that's because of the phenomenal amount of time it takes
to create an Aardman movie. With 24 frames per second of film time,
you can have 24 different poses for your characters for just one
second of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Park: Nick and I were directing on 15 sets each every day. We
had 30 animators working at once. And a good day would produce 10
seconds of film.
</P>
<P>
   Lord: It's more work than we ever anticipated. We always thought
it would be two or three times a short film in terms of work, but
it's so much more complicated because it's a much bigger world.
</P>
<P>
   Park: We often said that it was 20 to 30 times the amount of
work just in terms of mental effort.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was it hard to create so many different chicken
personalities?
</P>
<P>
   Lord: The supporting characters, the broad types like the ditsy
Babs or the gruff Fowler were easy.
</P>
<P>
   Park: It was the romantic leads that were difficult. In animated
movies, they are often the most boring characters. We wanted our
romantic leads to be interesting. I mean, we couldn't make them
good-looking as chickens, but we wanted them to have presence since
this is the first time chickens have ever been stars. So that was a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did having Mel Gibson do the voice of the rooster help a
little?
</P>
<P>
   Lord: His improv was terrific. He'd always come up with these
terrible, terrible word puns, just tossing out every kind of wing
and drumstick gag you can imagine, accompanied by a very good Sean
Connery impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   Park: To be honest, we weren't quite sure why he was doing our
movie. When he turned up on the first day of recording, I was
thinking, ``He must have better offers this year than playing a
chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: The screenwriter, Karey Kirkpatrick, says you beat every
ounce of sentimentality out of his script.
</P>
<P>
   Lord: We did. I think it is quite British not to say your
message very emphatically. I think the British way is to
communicate your message, but you don't need to actually SAY it to
communicate it. You can act it, you can imply it, you can show it
without directly saying it. And that's where a lot of our
discussions came from.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Katzenberg had a deal with you back when he was with Disney,
but you never signed on the dotted line. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Lord: We were afraid that Disney would swallow our company both
economically and also culturally.
</P>
<P>
   Park: Several studios threw ideas at us, but I think we would
have always felt that we were making a movie for them and not for
us. It was important to have an idea of our own that we believed
in. And with this we had something to take to Jeffrey. And he knew
by then that we were interested in creative freedom above all and
he seemed to respect that an awful lot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But Katzenberg is a famous meddler. How much did he talk to
you?
</P>
<P>
   Park: Jeffrey is very verbal and upfront. But you can disagree
with him and he likes that.
</P>
<P>
   Lord: We also have the advantage of having the Atlantic between
us. (Laughs)
</P>
<P>
   Q: Nick, have you given any thought to ``Wallace &AMP; Gromit''
lately?
</P>
<P>
   Park: I think about them all the time. Every time I'm on the
phone, I'm doodling pictures of them. That's the next movie I'm
going to start work on.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do you think people love those characters so much?
</P>
<P>
   Park: It's really hard to know why, but you put it right. The
love element is so high with them. And you can't plan that or
design something with that in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Lord: I think they are honest as creations. And getting back to
that sentimentality stuff, I think they are unsentimental
creations. But at the same time, they're fundamentally good-hearted
so the films leave you feeling good about life. No one has preached
you a lesson like they do in so many movies, and yet you've learned
something.
</P>
<P>
   And the nice thing about Wallace is that he's such a terrible
fellow in so many ways. He's so insensitive to Gromit's feelings.
But if we changed his character and all of a sudden he became all
soppy and caring, it would lose its charm. He feels like a real
person; that's how people's relationships are. They make mistakes,
but they still love each other.
</P>
<P>
   Park: I'm just concerned about keeping the freshness and not get
too wise really in terms of Hollywood. We can't be influenced by
any marketing-think. But ``Wallace &AMP; Gromit'' is an institution in
Britain. It's not something anyone can change. They have their own
life and they'll write their own story and it will be funny.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After making this movie, can you look at a chicken sandwich
the same way?
</P>
<P>
   Lord: If anything, I relish eating chicken even more. We became
a little desensitized after spending four years of our lives with
them.
</P>
<P>
   Park: But somehow I think we're doing something for
chicken-kind. We're making them stars. They've never really been
stars before, apart from Foghorn Leghorn. You know, they've always
been extras, flapping out of the way of vehicles. So I think we've
advanced their cause a great deal with this movie. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
