<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9689 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SURVIVOR21-COX     06-20 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Survivor' crew goes from rats to rain
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our national security forces can't keep atomic secrets on a Los
Alamos computer hard drive, but the one mystery that millions want
to know has yet to leak: Who will be the last ``Survivor,'' the one
to win $1 million?
</P>
<P>
   In an age of saturation media, there has been much speculation
as to the winner of CBS' summertime hit, but not a single nugget of
hard fact. The 16 participants, who videotaped the show in March
and have been back in the United States for several weeks, have
kept mum.
</P>
<P>
   That's partly because all 16 signed extensive contracts that
Executive Producer Mark Burnett says are as thick as ``War and
Peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Although CBS hasn't publicized it, every ``Survivor''
participant will get some money. Sonja Christopher, the first to be
exiled by her peers, will get $2,500, and the payments go up from
there, with the second-place finisher getting $100,000. But no one
will be paid until after the series concludes Aug. 23 _ and the
castaways' silence has held up, Burnett says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the contracts call for financial penalties against
the participants if they divulge information. Burnett confirms the
penalty clause but will not give specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's less about the contract and more about loyalty,'' Burnett
says. ``There's been some serious bonding within themselves and
with me. People don't screw over their friends.''
</P>
<P>
   But will that bond hold if the tabloids or others start offering
serious money to loosen some lips? Maybe not, but at least one tab
editor says his organization isn't pursuing the winner's name that
aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at it but we're not doing anything with it,'' says
Charlie Montgomery, senior editor of the National Enquirer. ``I
don't know if people want to know. You get sucked into watching it,
and it's a good guessing game.''
</P>
<P>
   And has America ever been sucked into it. The nation is
wallowing in CBS' quasi-reality show the way the castaways
themselves frolicked in a tropical mud hole last week.
</P>
<P>
   No one at CBS, or even Burnett, thought ``Survivor'' would take
off the way it has. It premiered May 31 with a strong audience of
almost 16 million, beat ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
head to head in its second week and, by last week's third episode,
had more than 23 million viewers, up 49 percent from Day One.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's episode was the third-most-watched program in the
nation (behind the Tuesday and Sunday editions of ``Millionaire'')
and the top show among advertiser-coveted viewers ages 18 through
49. CBS' Web site crashed repeatedly as millions of people tried to
find out more (www.cbs.com and follow the prompts).
</P>
<P>
   On tonight's fourth episode, it will be rain, rain, go away.
Viewers saw the start of the monsoon at the end of last week's
show. The downpour, which lasted several days during filming, was
so intense that the makeshift shelters leaked badly and the
island's rats were driven inside with the cranky campers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on CBS
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
