<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9695 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UAL-USAIR-ART-980(2TA     06-20 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UAL-USAIR-ART-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMERS SEE UAL-USAIR MERGER IN A HARSH LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James E. Goodwin, the chief executive of the UAL Corp., the
parent of United Airlines, describes his proposed $4.3 billion
purchase of US Airways as a ``win-win for consumers'' that will
usher in a glorious new era of global air service.
</P>
<P>
   But many passengers see the proposed merger rather differently.
For them, air travel is already a grim reality of high fares,
interminable check-in lines, overcrowded planes, endless delays and
in-flight meals that are stingy when they are offered at all. ``I
look at fares now, especially for business trips, and they are
outrageous,'' said Linda Kurz, an executive assistant in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Those two visions are on a collision course in Washington, where
Goodwin and Stephen M. Wolf, the chairman of US Airways, have
already faced a hostile Congress at three separate hearings. At
issue is whether the airline industry, a generation after the 1978
deregulation law prompted a wave of industry consolidation, will
best serve consumers if it is allowed to become even more
concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   The United-US Airways deal, if approved by regulators, would
create a winged giant that would carry one quarter of the nation's
air traffic. The proposal has sparked a frenzy of merger talks that
many are convinced could reduce the country's six largest carriers
to three mega-airlines. That prospect alarms consumer advocates and
lawmakers who already complain that there is too little
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no loss of competition if this merger goes
through,'' Rep. Leonard L. Boswell, D-Iowa, said with more than a
touch of irony, ``because there is no competition now.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill., was even more disturbed. ``I think the
flying public is in for some real, real horror stories, worse than
they have ever experienced,'' he said, adding that Congress does
not have the power to stop the merger.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department will decide whether the combination
hinders competition. But opponents and backers of the deal agree
that it may rise and fall on public opinion and election-year
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Several lawmakers have written to the Justice Department urging
it to look at the effect of the merger on the structure of the
industry. A group of senators led by Ron Wyden, D-Ore., asked the
Department of Transportation's inspector general to investigate the
degree to which airline mergers adversely affect customer service.
And attorneys general from 20 states have joined forces to oppose
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, UAL, already the nation's largest airline, has
enlisted a small army of lobbyists to make its case. Goodwin is now
devoting nearly all his time to talking to anyone in Washington who
will listen.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, this is a terrible moment to propose an airline
merger. The major carriers have faced a growing chorus of critics
and government challenges over the last six years. As business
fares rose to record highs in the mid-1990's, many cities and
states came to resent the way large airlines dominated major
metropolitan airports.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that fares are much higher at such hubs than at
airports with more carriers. In Minneapolis, for example, where
Northwest Airlines is the biggest airline by far, fares on average
were 49 percent higher than at comparable airports with greater
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The major airlines were also accused of preying on new, low-fare
competitors. The Justice Department sued American Airlines in May
1999, accusing it of illegally driving a small competitor out of
its Dallas-Ft. Worth hub and then raising prices. American denies
any wrongdoing and is fighting the government in court.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Justice filed suit in 1998 to force Northwest to sell
its controlling stake in Continental Airlines. It charged that the
deal would lead to higher ticket prices and diminished service for
millions of passengers. That case is scheduled to go to trial later
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints about airlines rose to such a crescendo last year
that Congress came close to passing legislation mandating specific
levels of service. The industry headed that off by submitting a
voluntary set of standards, promising, among other things, to
respond to complaints within 60 days and to allow consumers to hold
reservations for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, complaints are at an all-time high, rising over
130 percent in the 12 months ending in April.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both United and US Airways score at or near the bottom in
industry measures of service compiled by the Department of
Transportation. United was ranked seventh and US Airways eighth in
on-time arrivals for the 12 months ending in April, according to
the latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``How they could come forward with this deal in an environment
like this leaves you scratching your head,'' said Kevin P.
Mitchell, chairman of the Business Travel Coalition, which
represents corporate airline customers.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation is that airline executives live in a world of
statistics while passengers tend to remember individual flights.
United flew 89 million passengers last year so it is not surprising
to Goodwin that some had problems. He acknowledged in an interview
that United needs to improve its service but he said that according
to data compiled by the industry for internal use, United ranks at
the top.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin and other airline executives point out that passengers
nearly tripled to 635 million last year from 240 million in 1977,
before the industry was deregulated, but average fares, adjusted
for inflation, declined 40 percent over the same period. Still, the
complex way the industry sets fares, which seem to change by the
minute, has fueled broad resentment among consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the airline industry,'' said Leo F. Mullin,
the chief executive of Delta Air Lines, ``is that it gets killed by
anecdotes.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Most airline executives and industry analysts on Wall Street
believe that consolidation is inevitable. Industry profit margins,
even in the best years, are about 5 percent compared with an
average at least twice that for the companies included in the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index.
</P>
<P>
   United argues that combining with US Airways will give it a
strong presence along the East Coast, where it is weak. That will
be a boon for consumers, the airline said, because the new United
would be able to offer service on 560 city-to-city routes, like
Sacramento to Erie, Penn., and Fargo, N.D., to Panama City, Fla.,
that neither it nor US Airways currently serve. Together with its
international partners, United said it would also be able to offer
``seamless'' service to numerous destinations in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the deal will only force United's rivals to get
bigger, too. Within days of United's announcement, the AMR Corp.,
the parent of American Airlines, the country's second-largest
airline, entered into merger discussions with both Northwest and
Delta Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe that AMR will ultimately seek to merge
with No. 4 Northwest, while No. 3 Delta will attempt to combine
with No. 5 Continental Airlines. That would create three giants
carrying 80 percent of all passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Some airline executives argue that having three truly national
carriers competing head to head in every city would be an
improvement on the situation today in which the six airlines have
hegemony over so-called fortress hubs at major metropolitan
airports.
</P>
<P>
   But Samuel Buttrick, a airline analyst with Paine Webber in New
York, called the notion that three big carriers would offer more
competition than six independent airlines ``borderline lunacy.'' He
said that ``more competitors means more supply, means more choice
at better prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Many consumers agree. ``Right now all the airlines have to
compete for the same dollar,'' said Wally Thompson, a salesman in
Manhattan. ``Once they don't have to compete, prices will go up.''
</P>
<P>
   To mute criticism, United has pledged not to lay off any of US
Airways' 40,000 employees and has also vowed not to increase fares
for two years after the deal is consummated. In addition, because a
combined United-US Airways would dominate air travel in the
Washington D.C. area, US Airways has agreed to sell most of its
operations at Ronald Reagan National Airport to Robert L. Johnson,
the founder of Black Entertainment Television and a US Airways
director.
</P>
<P>
   But many executives and analysts believe the fare freeze is
meaningless because United has said it reserves the right to raise
prices in response to inflation and fuel costs. Executives at rival
airlines also said that United will ultimately be forced to abandon
some of US Airways' hub airports to justify the expense of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   DC Air, Johnson's new airline, has also been heavily criticized
as a ploy to keep valuable assets at National Airport out of the
hands of United's strongest competitors. There are also concerns
that DC Air, which will depend on United for all its services from
ticketing to maintenance, will not be a truly independent
competitor. And even if it is, United would still be the clearly
dominant airline in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And bigger is not necessarily better for frequent flyers,
including some in Congress. ``I'm a 2 million mile customer of
United,'' Rep. Peter A. DeFazio, D-Ore., told Goodwin. ``I want a
reasonable price and I want better service. I am not so concerned
about the seamlessness of my international and national travel.
That's what travel agents are for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
