<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-HARRIOTT-BOOK-REVIEW-     06-20 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRIOTT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CULINARY SPRINT TO THE FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: A recipe for Quick Peking Duck appears at end of
story.)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tackling the recipes in ``Ainsley Harriott's Meals in Minutes''
(Dorling Kindersley, $19.95) calls for energy, concentration and
dexterity. It often means doing two, three or even four things at
the same time. I am highly organized in the kitchen, but this book
put me to the test.
</P>
<P>
   Harriott, who has one television program in Britain and another
filmed in New York and shown in the United States, is a chef in
high gear, enlisting audience and celebrity assistants to work on
salads, whip up a marinade, sear chicken and somehow assemble a
dish while keeping up a steady, energetic patter. The big surprise
is that this culinary sprint is mostly worth it. Occasionally, a
recipe like spicy Indian ground lamb skewers takes 10 to 15 minutes
longer than Harriott's ETA. On the other hand, I made his pan-fried
pizza in 30 minutes, not 40, as the recipe stated.
</P>
<P>
   That pizza is made with a simple dough of flour, water and
baking powder, which is rolled out in a circle and put in a big
oiled skillet over medium heat. While the underside browns, the
toppings are arranged on it. The whole thing is then run under the
broiler. I've never made a pizza like that, and it was terrific.
</P>
<P>
   Spicy wine-steamed mussels, fish in a Thai curry sauce, broiled
cod on couscous and even an oddly appealing onion ``tarte Tatin''
to cut in wedges all worked. Chicken in a spicy cream and yogurt
sauce needed more chicken or less sauce, but it was tasty and easy.
</P>
<P>
   Noodle dishes, quick casseroles and stir-fries, some of which
would be good with leftovers, dominate. Aside from some worthwhile
crumbles and an apricot rice pudding, the dessert chapter is weak.
What I found admirable is how seldom Harriott uses canned or
packaged convenience foods. The purist could go further, as I did
for the pizza, using a tablespoon of tomato paste from a tube
instead of ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   There is no mistaking Harriott's English tastes: ``mash,'' as
mashed potatoes are called, reigns; so does cod. There are also
clever Asian, Mexican and Cajun touches. He gives a good tip:
freeze chunks of peeled ginger for easy grating.
</P>
<P>
   A 20-minute Peking duck was that fast and excellent. But there
was no crispy skin, so I fried strips of duck skin to tuck into the
pancakes. It added less than five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK PEKING DUCK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Ainsley Harriott's Meals in Minutes'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces skinless, boneless duck breast
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dark soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Chinese five-spice powder
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon coarse black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon toasted sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons plum jam or hoisin sauce
</P>
<P>
   Pinch dried chili flakes
</P>
<P>
   8 Chinese wheat-flour pancakes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sunflower or peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   4 scallions, trimmed and slivered
</P>
<P>
   { cucumber, peeled, seeded and cut in matchsticks
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh cilantro leaves plus sprigs for garnish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Halve duck breast horizontally. Then cut with the grain in
thin slivers. Mix 1 tablespoon soy sauce with honey, five-spice
powder and pepper, toss with duck, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat sesame oil in small saucepan, add garlic, cook briefly,
then stir in vinegar, jam, chili flakes and remaining soy sauce.
Cook 2 minutes over medium heat to blend, then strain through a
sieve, mashing the garlic. Set sauce aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place pancakes on a heat-proof plate. Cover with foil. Set
them on top of pan of simmering water to warm.
</P>
<P>
   4. Heat sunflower or peanut oil in wok or skillet. Drain duck in
sieve to remove excess marinade, add to wok, and stir-fry over high
heat 2 to 3 minutes, until browned. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   5. Spread warm pancakes with sauce mixture. Top with strips of
duck, scallion and cucumber, sprinkle with cilantro, and roll up.
Garnish with cilantro sprigs, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 to 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
