<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9702 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-WILKERSON-ANTIQUES-$A     06-20 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILKERSON-ANTIQUES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PASSION FOR ANTIQUES THAT BEGAN AT THE WATER HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Nev., Mass.)   (For release Sunday, June 25)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ L. John Wilkerson was 7 when he dug up a shiny stone
arrowhead at a water hole near the family's small ranch in Elko,
Nev. Collecting arrowheads remained a passion throughout his youth,
spent among the children of ranchers and Shoshone Indians, and much
later, when he returned from college to work summers as a cowboy
and do research on the economics of raising cattle in the West. Yet
he never dreamed that in finding that arrowhead at the water hole
he had taken his first step toward becoming, 50 years later, the
president of the Museum of American Folk Art in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Wilkerson is a venture capitalist specializing in medical
technology at Galen Associates, a New York firm of which he was a
founding partner in 1995. (He had just sold the Wilkerson Group, a
consulting firm on medical industry technology that he had started
20 years earlier, to IBM.) But he still owns the 60 stone
arrowheads he amassed decades ago. ``The real jewels _ maybe 10 _
are long and skinny, shaped to travel the farthest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   These days, he and his wife, Barbara, are avid collectors with
broader interests. Color-splashed barber poles, carousel carvings
and apothecary chests enliven his office in Rockefeller Center.
Boldly patterned aboriginal spirit paintings add graphic intensity
to the interiors of their country home in Pennsylvania.
Late-20th-century abstract sculpture fills the gardens of their
home in New Jersey, while American folk art reigns supreme indoors.
</P>
<P>
   As the Wilkersons acquired folk art, they met other collectors
at, among other places, the Museum of American Folk Art. Wilkerson
became a trustee in 1994, became treasurer in 1996 and late last
year was elected board president, replacing Ralph Esmerian, a
pre-eminent collector of American folk art, who had been president
since 1979. (He remains as board chairman.) Esmerian had helped
Robert Bishop, then the director, guide the institution through
turbulent times. Under their leadership, it grew from a one-room
museum with a collection of 184 objects, and deeply in debt, to a
formidable institution with many masterpieces among its 4,000
objects. It organizes exhibitions that travel throughout the world,
and, under its current director, Gerard C. Wertkin, it is building
a $22 million museum on West 53rd Street, due to open late next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson hopes to build on the success of his predecessors,
placing even more emphasis on the business aspects of the museum.
``For the last 20 years, the leadership at the museum had focused
75 percent on its collections and curatorial activities and 25
percent on its business management,'' he said. ``Today with
everything we have on our plate _ the building going up and an
endowment being planned for major acquisitions _ it is a more
balanced equation, 50-50.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wilkersons are already involved in the museum in other ways,
lending pieces for exhibitions. Their 9-foot-long ``Angel Gabriel''
weathervane was hard to miss in the museum's show marking the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Their other weathervanes _ in the shape of horses, cows, angels
and American Indians _ hang floor to ceiling in the entrance hall
of their home. Pennsylvania German cabbage cutters, embellished
with cutouts of hearts and hands, cover a wall in the kitchen.
Painted furniture, shop signs, trade figures and watercolors are
spread throughout the rest of the house.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   In this crowded environment, you have to look closely to see the
complexity in the haunted Munchlike expression in a woman's face in
a gouache by Bill Traylor.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wilkerson had a head start on her husband as a folk-art
collector: she bought her first piece _ an 1880s cherry end table _
when she was 14. But he proved a fast learner, succumbing quickly
to the easy charm, optimism and diversity of folk art. They began
collecting after they were married 33 years ago, and furnished
their first home on a tight budget with painted chests, tables and
a desk, paying less than $100 for most pieces. By the 1970s, they
were buying decorative objects and weathervanes.
</P>
<P>
   The first vane they bought was by J. Howard &AMP; Co. of West
Bridgewater, Mass. ``We knew he was our guy; his vanes were the
most striking,'' Wilkerson said. ``In the 1980s, we decided that we
would develop the most comprehensive collection of weathervanes by
Howard. We've probably done just that _ nobody else would be so
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 57 vanes they own, 27 are by Howard, a competitor in the
1860s of the better-known manufacturers A.W. Jewell of Waltham,
Mass., and J.W. Fiske of New York. Howard specialized in using zinc
and copper to achieve a better balance in his vanes. He made
stepping horses of exceptional grace, while Jewell strove for more
dynamic movement in his all-copper horses. This characteristic is
seen in a Wilkerson treasure, a patinated flying horse by Jewell,
its tail and mane borne high by the wind.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilkersons also realize that their involvement in the museum
is having an impact on their collecting: they are trying to upgrade
what they buy and to better document the pieces that they own.
Their biggest problem as collectors, they say, is that they have
never sold or given away anything from their collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't seem to say goodbye,'' he said. ``We have a lot to
learn from the curators at the museum on how to fashion and
continuously refine a collection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
