<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9703 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-20 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CONSTITUTION PREVAILS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court isn't perfect, but once again it
has demonstrated its indispensability as the guardian of last
resort of our constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   By ruling that school-sanctioned prayer at football games
violates the principle of separation of church and state, the high
bench protected religious diversity from yet another political
demand for conformity in organized worship.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was 6-3, as thumping a majority as is ever likely
on this deeply ideologically divided court. Writing for the
majority, Justice John Paul Stevens ruled that a prayer delivered
by a student at a school-controlled sports event ``has the improper
effect of coercing those present to participate in an act of
religious worship.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens ruled that a football game is not a public forum for
free expression. ``These invocations are authorized by a government
policy and take place on government property at a
government-sponsored school related event,'' he wrote, adding that
the circumstances mean the audience would view the student prayer
as stamped with the school's ``seal of approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist, in a strangely irrational
dissent, fumed that the majority opinion ``bristles with hostility
to all things religious in public life.'' Actually, it did nothing
of the sort.
</P>
<P>
   The opinion did not encompass ``all things religious,'' and it
specifically noted that public school children are free to pray
voluntarily by themselves any time before, after or during the
school day or at extra-curricular Bible classes.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be surprising, however, if the majority felt
unfriendly toward the Santa Fe, Texas, Independent School
District's sneaky attempt to make an end-run around the court's
well-known position that school prayer violates the First
Amendment's establishment clause.
</P>
<P>
   The justices declined to be conned by the transparent device of
electing a student to deliver the prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens noted that school officials controlled the stadium
loudspeaker, supervised the vote on picking the student to hold
prayers, sponsored the game itself and generally did not have the
``hands-off'' approach it claimed.
</P>
<P>
   The school policy, Stevens wrote, ``involves both perceived and
actual endorsement of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians like Texas Gov. George W. Bush who pander to the
religious right predictably attacked the decision as picking on
devout pupils who merely wish to openly express their piety.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who as governor filed a brief supporting pre-game prayers,
said the opinion was ``disappointing.'' In case the Christian right
felt that he was insufficiently outraged, he also backed the right
of all students ``to express their faith freely and participate in
voluntary, student-led prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential candidate was pulling a typical
political stunt, creating a straw-man to knock down. He did not
address what the high court opinion said at all. Bush was being
disingenuous at best and dangerously incendiary at worst.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was not whether students are free to pray or talk
about their religious faith. Private acts of devotion are
protected. The issue was whether students had the right to impose
their views on others at a big social event, abetted and sponsored
by a state taxpayer-funded school authority orchestrating one set
of beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The school district had defended its policy by claiming it to be
``content-neutral,'' a slender legal reed that Rehnquist grasped.
He argued that the policy had a secular rather than religious
purpose: ``to solemnize the event, to promote good sportsmanship
and student safety and to establish the appropriate environment for
the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure. How does prayer do anything but provide a religious
tone for what is essentially a power struggle between two teams of
bulky boys assigned to maul one another over possession of a ball?
The purpose is to win, and as a practical matter the Lord does not
take sides.
</P>
<P>
   If an `appropriate'' environment is a bowed head instead of
cheering and rooting for the home team, that's a religious rather
than secular notion. If the rowdy game of football needs to be
``solemnized,'' that's a religious rather than secular goal.
Otherwise, cops could be sent in to keep order. And as for
sportsmanship, that's up to the coach more than to heavenly
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Church groups and their political allies who have a majority in
many localities continually press to insert their own biblical
interpretations into the public schools despite competing minority
religious interests. But the Founding Fathers erected a
constitutional wall between church and state to prevent people of
one religion from establishing control over those of different
views. This issue is particularly sensitive in the public schools,
where impressionable youngsters are vulnerable to adult doctrines.
</P>
<P>
   The wall has worked well. But some public school officials still
ignore the message. For nearly four decades bullies on the
religious right have tried various dodges to get around the Supreme
Court's 1962 ruling that organized prayer is unconstitutional in
public schools. One by one, the high bench has struck them down.
</P>
<P>
   This is only the latest test. It will not be the end of the
struggle between the religious zealots and the Constitution. The
next president _ Bush or Gore _ may get to pick at least two
justices who could make the difference in the diligence with which
the court has protected this constitutional right. Think about it
when you vote.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
