<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHICKEN-SPI </SLUG>
  
 DREAMwORKS HATCHES A WINNER IN `CHICKEN RUN'  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: A-  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Up to now, DreamWorks studio's much-ballyhooed challenge to the
Disney animation monopoly has amounted to a trio of duds _
``Antz,'' ``Prince of Egypt'' and ``Road to El Dorado'' _ while
Disney has cranked out four of its all-time greatest hits: ``A
Bug's Life,'' ``Tarzan,'' ``Toy Story 2'' and ``Dinosaur.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, just as Hollywood has all but given up on DreamWorks
animation and its guru, (ex-Disney honcho) Jeffrey Katzenberg, the
studio has come up with what could be one of the big movies of the
summer of '00: ``Chicken Run'' _ the first feature film from
England's Oscar-winning ``Claymation'' studio, Aardman Animation.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it will catch on with an audience large enough to give
it blockbuster status is by no means assured _ Claymation remains a
cult attraction and barnyard chickens will be a harder sell to kids
than dinosaurs and cute humanoid toys. But the film is clever,
funny and thoroughly entertaining from beginning to end.
</P>
<P>
   It's set in the postwar '50s on a chicken farm in the Yorkshire
countryside that's run like a German POW camp by a tyrannical and
ax-happy matriarch (voice of Miranda Richardson) and her cowering
husband (Tony Haygarth) _ complete with watchtowers, guard dogs and
barbed-wire fences.
</P>
<P>
   Life is so hard and precarious that the colorful flock of
overweight chickens longs to escape. Their situation becomes even
more dire when the nasty owner tires of her low-profit egg
business, and decides to bring in a ton of automated machinery and
turn the place into an ultrastreamlined chicken pot-pie factory.
</P>
<P>
   But hope comes for the doomed chickens in the form of a runaway
circus rooster named Rocky (Mel Gibson), who seems to have mastered
the unchickenlike art of flying and is convinced by Ginger (Julia
Sawalha), the primary chicken protagonist and henhouse ringleader,
to stick around and teach the others how to fly the coop.
</P>
<P>
   The big joke, of course, is that the film plays off World War II
POW movies in general and John Sturges' 1963 classic, ``The Great
Escape,'' in particular. It apes several of that film's plot
points, its music mimics Elmer Bernstein's famous score, and
there's even a character who methodically bounces a baseball
against a wall Steve McQueen-style.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, however, co-directors Peter Lord and Nick Park do not
belabor this premise, and use it mostly as an extended gag off
which they play their cast of delightfully surreal puppet creations
_ a gaggle of cowardly chickens, a pair of mercenary rats, one
horrific human villainess _ in a string of hilariously Aardmanesque
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Aardman's cult of fans should especially enjoy the movie. Even
with its G rating, it retains the characteristic Aardman hard edge,
it never seems to compromise itself to appeal to a mass audience,
and it constantly works into its rich visual fabric the various
eccentric motifs and devices of the studio's short films _ so it
almost becomes a tribute to Aardman's past.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Chicken Run'' also should work for an audience that has no
identification with the studio's Claymation masterpieces. The story
is compelling, the characters are endearing and the atmosphere is
magical. Above all, it represents something refreshingly different
from the hand-drawn and computer-generated Disney-style animation
that currently rules the multiplexes.
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Run. Directed by Peter Lord &AMP; Nick Park. Screenplay by
Karey Kirkpatrick. Voices: Mel Gibson, Julia Sawalha, Miranda
Richardson, Jane Horrocks, Benjamin Whitrow. DreamWorks. 85
minutes. Rated G, suitable for all audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
