u w BC-AFRICA-AIDS-0621-COX     06-20 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-AIDS-0621-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RELIEF GROUPS STEP UP PLEAS FOR INCREASED FUNDING FROM U.S. TO
FIGHT AIDS
 &HT;    By LISA MICHALS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the epidemic spread of AIDS devastates the
populations of sub-Saharan African countries, international relief
groups Tuesday escalated their pleas for an additional $275 million
in U.S. aid to fight the dreaded disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we hear about all the debates on Capitol Hill wanting to
reduce . . . assistance, most of us working in the field don't
comprehend what is going on,'' said Elizabeth Lule, with Pathfinder
International aid group. ``And we would like to request that as
demand is increasing, and since you invested in increasing that
demand, don't stop now.''
</P>
<P>
   Pathfinder, and the other groups _ 126 in all _ have thrown
their considerable weight behind New York Democrat Joseph Crowley's
Global Health Act of 2000, which seeks to double the current $1
billion the United States spends on worldwide health issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disease knows no boundaries,'' said Crowley, taking a cue from
President Clinton's statement last month that HIV-AIDS has become a
threat to U.S. national security.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley's bill boasts several Democratic co-sponsors, including:
Texas Reps. Martin Frost, Sheila Jackson Lee, Charles Gonzalez,
Nick Lampson and Ruben Hinojosa; Ohio Reps. Tony Hall, Stephanie
Tubbs Jones and Sherrod Brown; Florida Reps. Carrie Meek and Robert
Wexler; and Georgia Rep. Cynthia McKinney.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the bill, which is currently in the House Foreign
Operations subcommittee, is expected on the House floor in the next
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a responsibility as the richest nation in the world to
do what we can to help,'' Crowley said Tuesday during a forum
addressing the HIV-AIDS crisis in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   He said HIV-AIDS epidemic, which has resulted in more than 16
million people dying since the 1980s, has ``reached catastrophic
dimensions in developing nations.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that sub-Saharan African countries _ now struggling
with millions of children orphaned by parents killed by HIV-AIDS _
are hit the hardest. In Zimbabwe, there are as many as 800,000 AIDS
orphans. In one rural school, 24 percent of its 946 students have
lost their parents to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS experts and relief officials at Tuesday's forum discussed
the benefits of family planning in preventing HIV-AIDS and appealed
for continued funding from the United States, stating that American
dollars save lives.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the urgency of their request, South Africa on
Monday announced its five-year $291 million strategy to combat all
diseases, including HIV-AIDS. But despite an 80 percent discount
from multinational drug firms, limited resources forced the country
to exclude funding for anti-retroviral drugs, such as AZT, which
help prevent the transmission of HIV from mother to child during
pregnancy, according to South African health officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a responsibility as the richest nation in the world to
do what we can to help,'' Crowley said, who in April, traveled to
Malawi to observe the effects of HIV-AIDS and work being done by
international relief organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
