<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN _ ATLANTA _ The federal government and the father of Elian
Gonzalez are urging a federal appeals court in Atlanta to allow the
boy to go home to Cuba. The two parties filed responses this
morning to Elian's Miami relatives. Earlier this month a
three-judge appeal panel upheld the Immigration and Naturalization
Service's decision not to allow Elian to file for asylum in the
United States. The Miami relatives appealed that decision. Today's
filing by the boy's father says the full appeals court should
``immediately'' reject the Miami relatives' appeal and let Elian go
home. The federal government agrees in its filing. There is no word
on when the full appeals court might decide whether to hear the
Miami relatives' appeal. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
8-10.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIAN-TRIAL21 _ WACO, Texas _ Opening statements begin in the
Davidian civil lawsuit trial. Plaintiffs attorney Mike Caddell
posts photographs of many of the children who died at Mount Carmel,
``children who never owned a gun, who never fired a gun.''
Government co-counsel Michael Bradford told jurors that Davidians
set the fires that destroyed compound. He also denied that the FBI
had started dismantling Mount Carmel. Caddell called two witnesses:
Rita Riddle and Jaynessa Wendell, who was 8 years old during the
ATF raid. She said her mother, Jaydean, was doing her hair. Her
mother put her into the hallway and went back into the bedroom,
where she was shot and killed. (England, Waco Tribune-Herald).
</P>
<P>
   SMALL-SCHOOLS _ WASHINGTON _ Students in Chicago's new small
public schools are less likely to skip classes or drop out, and may
perform better academically, says a multi-year academic study to be
released and discussed here Tuesday. The findings support Education
Secretary Richard Riley's call to ``stop building high schools the
size of large shopping malls.'' But cost-conscious skeptics remain
unconvinced. Pros and cons of the dispute over how to handle the
upcoming increase of 1.3 million in high school enrollments in this
decade. (Mollison, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DATA-SMALL -SCHOOLS on size of U.S. elementary and secondary
schools. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   HITECH-RR-XINGS _ BLUE RIDGE, Ga. _ We watch Tuesday as the
federal Department of Transportation and Georgia Tech researchers
field test a possible high-tech solution to railroad crossing
collisions. A transmitter aboard a Georgia Northeastern Railroad
Co. locomotive will beam a signal to antennaes near railroad
crossings that will then relay it to transmitters that can be
carried on vehicles - including school buses - to warn a train is
approaching. Such a device might have prevented the tragic
train-bus collision in Tennga, Tenn., this spring. (Ledford,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-SAFETY _ WASHINGTON _ Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., holds a
news conference to discuss a Department of Transportation proposal
that would increase maximum driving time for interstate truck and
bus drivers from 10 hours a day to 12. (Dart, Cox News Service).
18.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Attlanta, category National, subcategory
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-HACKER _ WASHINGTON _ The debate over gun control is getting
uglier, even on the Internet. A pro-gun hacker this week erased an
entire Web site run by a well-known gun-control group. The hacker
replaced it with a page featuring a skull and crossbones, profanity
and a link to the National Rifle Association. (Moscoso, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WAN category National, subcategory Social Issues
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON HEARTLAND POLITICAL PROJECT
</P>
<P>
   Part 4 of 5 parts
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-PA _ Before we begin, will Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge
be Gov. George W. Bush's running mate? If the answer is yes, and it
might be, then move Pennsylvania into the GOP column and go on to
the next topic. Even Democrats in the Keystone State concede that
putting the popular governor on the ticket would guarantee Bush a
victory. ``I think he's a solid leader with a great, sparkling
resume,'' a Democratic member of the Pennsylvania General Assembly
said. ``Now, if Ridge is on the ticket it would make things more
difficult for me....''Perhaps more than any other state,
Pennsylvania is a vexing jumble of political identities. Anchored
by major urban centers Pittsburgh and Philadelphia on opposing
corners, vast miles of the state are rural farm and hunting land.
Last week the state mourned the death of a beloved former
Democratic governor who gained national fame as a rare opponent of
abortion in his party. Ridge, the popular Republican of today,
favors abortion rights. The winner in Pennsylvania will have to
avoid offending Catholics, who outnumber all other regligious
groups in the state, appease one of the largest retiree populations
in America, deal with pockets of deep union support, and thread the
needle on gun control between rural gun advocates and suburban
voters hypersensitive to the dangers of firearms and children.
(Montgomery, Dayton Daily News). 50-60.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-PABAR _ From most any downtown angle, the renaissance
is hard to see. A warren of one-way streets surrounds the main
drag, which is ruled by faintly traveled dime stores and the odd
tattoo parlor. On successive blocks off this road, called Hamilton
Mall, worn row houses still project the image of a working class in
decay. The Allentown of the Billy Joel song back in 1982. A place
still best defined by the absence of something, which in this case
would be the absence of Big Steel.But what a few dismal vistas fail
to reveal is that a sense of optimism now beams through Allentown
and neighboring Bethlehem, twin anchors in a two-county region
known as the Lehigh Valley. This cradle of industrial innovation
and might, where plans were drawn and steel was forged to build the
Golden Gate Bridge and large chunks of the New York skyline, is in
the midst of a rebirth. The Lehigh Valley of the 21st Century is
pulling itself up with bootstraps sewn not from leather, but from
fiber optic cable. In a state where political identity feels
transitory, few places are more in transition than the Lehigh
Valley. The fate of Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic nominee
for president, and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican
nominee, seems likely to rest here on the direction to which
cross-party voters flow. (Montgomery, Dayton Daily News). 20.
</P>
