r s BC-ELECTRIC-FOOTBALL-HNS     06-20 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRIC-FOOTBALL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW-TECH FOOTBALL GAME ELECTRIFIES NEW GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROY BRAGG  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The years pass. The images fade. But there will
always be that distinctive electric sound.
</P>
<P>
   Bzzzzzzzzt.
</P>
<P>
   Like an razor racing over the top of a young boy's head or a
broken vacuum tube television, it is the sound of nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Bzzzzzzzt. Childhood afternoons spent in grudge match
camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   Bzzzzzzzt. Rainy days and seldom-used toys.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sound of Electric Football _ yes, that football game
with the board and the little men _ a decidedly low-tech throwback
to another era.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in this year of computer viruses and billion dollar sports
broadcast deals, the game of Every Kid is buzzing, shaking and
vibrating its way back into popular consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, there is the Alamo City Electronic Football
League, which played its championship game last Saturday. In the
final game, Jerry McGhee's Dallas Cowboys routed Barry Stephenson's
Chicago Bears 34-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was picking him apart (with the passing game) like the U.S.
Air Force in Desert Storm,'' McGhee said.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of Electronic Football leagues, comprised
primarily of adults, in the nation. A Web site, which plays the
game's signature ``buzz'' when it is called up, links the faithful
around the world. And a national convention, including its own
Super Bowl, draws thousands yearly.
</P>
<P>
   Here in South Texas, league play takes place in after-hours
elementary school classrooms or in dens and carports. Competitors,
such as McGhee and Hilton Chretien, pony up $25 to compete in a
10-game seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturer Miggle Toys of Chicago says the game is more
popular now, in the high-tech, Pentium III, full-motion video game
world of 2000, than it has ever been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in America grew up playing this game, before there
was the Internet and video games,'' said Miggle President Michael
Landsman. ``Those games have proven to be anti-social. You sit in
the corner and you play by yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, these kids don't have imagination because it's shown to
them,'' he said. ``When you play this, you can see plays unfold.
They strategize our plays like a chess game. You play an opponent.
You see it. You imagine it.''
</P>
<P>
   For league coaches, it's both hobby and obsession.
</P>
<P>
   They spend their off-hours painting their diminutive plastic
warriors, faithfully recreating their favorite pro or college
teams. They get to know the tiny, green plastic bases that each
player stands on. They juice their players' performance with a bag
full of performance-enhancing tricks.
</P>
<P>
   And then, in after-hours classrooms or the still air of
carports, they go to war. Coach on coach. Play after play.
</P>
<P>
   Take a recent practice game in Jerry McGhee's carport.
</P>
<P>
   McGhee, 34, Alamo City league commissioner and his nephew Ryan
McGhee, 16, were supposedly scrimmaging to demonstrate how the game
is played.
</P>
<P>
   There were hand-painted, inch-tall players. It was a
custom-built field. There were talking clocks to keep track of the
time between plays. On one end, the elder McGhee had put a boom box
to play music loudly, in hopes of distracting his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The switch was hit, the field buzzed, and players took off in
all directions like scattering roaches.
</P>
<P>
   While others vibrated and danced higgledy-piggledy, Ryan's
defensive end broke through the line and bumped up against Jerry's
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sack. But Jerry went on with the demonstration, using
the tiny quarterback's bendable arm to accurately drill the
pea-sized felt football to the open receiver located 13 scale yards
away. Had this been a game, it would've been a first down.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, Ryan reminded him. The quarterback had already been
sacked.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Jerry explained, it was just a demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Ryan said, it was still a sack.
</P>
<P>
   That, McGhee says, shows the competitive nature of the game.
Others say they got into and learned about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of those who looked far beyond the simple toy and I
saw it was a learning tool,'' says Reginald Rutledge, who runs the
Dallas-Fort Worth area league. ``It really helped me to understand
strategy. I'd spent long hours working on players to understand
them and all and that kind of stuff. With that understanding, it
actually helped me as an athlete as I grew up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I put Electric Football in the category of playing checkers
and chess,'' Chretien said. ``It takes a lot of thought and
concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   The history of electric football, Landsman said, goes back to
1947 when Norman Sas, founder of Tudor Metal Products, stumbled
upon an electric horse-racing game while on a trip to Europe.
Movement was provided by a small electric motor, attached to the
bottom of the board, that made the whole thing vibrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sas) said, 'If I can adapt that to other things, such as
football, it might be a good idea,''' Landsman said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the very first electric football game _
complete with metal men playing on a 35-inch-by-19-inch sheet
playing field _ hit American toy store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   It was a huge success. By the late 1960s and early 1970s, the
game's heyday, it was a million-seller, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
   But it died in the 1980s, unable to compete with technology,
Landsman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Handheld computer games came out and everyone wanted to have
the newest and latest,'' Landsman said. ``All of the other games _
Monopoly, Clue, ours _ stopped selling.''
</P>
<P>
   Electric Football games soon disappeared from shelves. The
company stopped production in the late 1980s. And in 1988, Tudor
Toys was sold to Miggle.
</P>
<P>
   Electric Football, it seemed, vanished from the American scene,
going the way of trading stamps, full-service gas stations and
8-track tape players.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not. In the dens and playrooms of Middle America, there
was an underground scene of guys who never stopped playing the
game.
</P>
<P>
   A league in Toledo, Ohio, had been going strong with weekly
contests since 1975, but didn't know that anyone else played the
game, Landsman said.
</P>
<P>
   When Miggle re-introduced the game in the early 1990s, the
company held a tournament at Michael Jordan's Chicago restaurant,
expecting a little bit of publicity, which Landsman hoped would
boost sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 300 people show up,'' Landsman said, laughing.
``Everybody looked at everybody else and said 'You play this
too?'''
</P>
<P>
   That began a Renaissance of interest in the game. More leagues
began forming. A semi-annual newsletter was created. The game had
rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Roy Bragg by e-mail at rbragg(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
