<SLUG> BC-GLF-TIGER-BRITISH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS' EYE IS ON THE BRITISH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN FORNOFF  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rest assured, the eye of the Tiger already has turned to bigger
and better things.
</P>
<P>
   What's bigger than the U.S. Open championship, you ask? What's
better than a 15-shot blowout on perhaps the most beautiful of the
Open venues, Pebble Beach?
</P>
<P>
   Try a career Grand Slam at age 24 _ and achieved at the most
famous golf course in the world, St. Andrews, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods has a month to get ready for a quest that got his
attention even as he gazed adoringly at his new trinket, the U.S.
Open championship cup, after his remarkable victory Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that I would love to have happen, and there's
no better site to have it occur than at the home of golf,'' Woods
said. ``That's where it all started. If I could somehow be
fortunate enough to play well and at the right time, and get that
Claret Jug, it would be a good feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came close in '98 (finishing third behind his friend Mark
O'Meara). And if I made a few putts on the weekend last year
(seventh place, four shots behind Paul Lawrie) it may have been a
different story. I have to put myself in a position to win and
hopefully I can get that jug.''
</P>
<P>
   With the British Open July 20-23, Woods between now and then is
expected to play only in the Western Open, July 6-9. He usually
takes off for a couple of weeks after a major, and two or three
weeks before one.
</P>
<P>
   Woods played his first British Open at St. Andrews as an amateur
in 1995, and came out tied for 68th place. He's been back to the
Old Course once since then for the Dunhill Cup in 1998, firing 66,
66, 68 and then 72 in his final match, a loss to Santiago Luna.
</P>
<P>
   That is a score total that is 10 shots better than the 282 that
won for John Daly in 1995. And Woods will be practicing away,
trying to get even better as he tries to add the 2000 British to
the three major victories he already has, the Masters in a 1997
runaway, the PGA Championship in a 1999 dogfight, and now the U.S.
Open in a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a 9-, 10-shot lead every time, every single time,''
Woods said. ``Now I realize why most of the golfers out here are
balding and gray.''
</P>
<P>
   They are probably balding and gray trying to keep up with Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to work on my game quite a lot, just to get close to
him nowadays,'' said Ernie Els, who tied Miguel Angel Jimenez for
Sunday's B flight championship. ``And, who knows, I'm looking
forward to the British Open. I know St. Andrews pretty well, like
Tiger knows (Pebble Beach). But I have to play out of my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' worldwide competitors are already out of their minds
contemplating his five official victories in 11 events this season,
and the way he left them in the rye grass from the first day of
this U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   The scary thing about it all is that they have already raised
their games to try to compete. Players are hitting the ball farther
and scoring lower, all with shrinking waistlines and broader
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like everybody worked out harder this offseason,
practiced harder and came out more determined,'' said Lee Janzen.
``But he's on a level that nobody can catch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
