<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9741 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-cox-stroke-0621     06-20 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-cox-stroke-0621 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOSPITAL STROKE CENTERS SEEN SAVING LIVES
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although more than 700,000 Americans will suffer
``brain attacks'' _ or strokes _ this year, most will be taken to
hospitals that have not implemented relatively inexpensive
procedures and facilities that could save their lives.
</P>
<P>
   To correct that, all hospitals should establish stroke centers
to quickly evaluate and treat stroke victims, a committee of
experts said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although strokes are often painless and seldom as dramatic as
heart attacks, they can result in devastating or fatal brain
damage. An estimated 160,000 Americans die of stroke each year.
</P>
<P>
   One of the deadliest aspects is the fact that a victim's
associates often don't realize what is happening.
</P>
<P>
   But a committee of the national Brain Attack Coalition said
Tuesday the story does not end there. Even when stroke victims
reach a hospital, the dire circumstances surrounding their
condition may not be fully understood.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys show that as many as two-thirds of all American
hospitals do not have established procedures for dealing with
stroke victims and as many as 82 percent do not have the ability to
rapidly identify patients experiencing a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primary stroke centers'' could be organized around the trauma
center model and operated in community and even rural hospitals at
costs ranging from as little as $8,000 to as much as $250,000 a
year, the committee says in an article being published Wednesday in
the Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The recommended centers would include an acute stroke team led
by a physician experienced in diagnosing stroke, a set of written
treatment protocols, special training for ambulance and emergency
room staff and an established procedure for getting the patient to
a brain surgeon within two hours if necessary. Brain imaging
facilities such as CT scans should be available 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Some primary stroke centers would include stroke units, somewhat
like intensive care units, for the continued care of victims. The
committee said smaller hospitals could choose to have an
established procedure for transferring victims to larger centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our recommendations are similar to those guiding trauma
centers _ getting patients to facilities where the specialists and
infrastructure are in place to evaluate them and treat them
quickly,'' said Mark J. Alberts, director of stroke care at Duke
University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Alberts suggested that the ``stroke belt'' _ Indiana, Kentucky,
Tennessee, Arkansas, Louisiana, Virginia, North Carolina, South
Carolina, Georgia, Florida, Alabama, Mississippi and Washington,
D.C. _ would be ``an ideal area'' to start establishing the primary
stroke centers. The region has significantly more strokes than any
other part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing the recommendations Tuesday, Alberts and other
authors of the article avoided estimating the number of lives that
could be saved.
</P>
<P>
   But they noted that the chances that a stroke victim who is
treated in a stroke unit will not die or be permanently disabled
are 25 percent better than those of a victim treated in a general
hospital ward.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 83 percent of all strokes are characterized as
``ischemic'' events, meaning a clot or other obstruction has
blocked blood flow to an area of the brain. Because of the brain's
voracious appetite for substances carried by the blood _ primarily
oxygen and glucose _ permanent damage can occur if the blood flow
is not re-established.
</P>
<P>
   If given soon enough, a new family of ``clot-busting'' drugs can
reopen obstructed blood vessels and prevent the damage.
</P>
<P>
   However, the remaining 17 percent of stroke victims suffer what
is known as ``hemorrhagic'' strokes, meaning a blood vessel has
burst and is bleeding into the brain. If a clot-dissolving drug is
given to the victim of this kind of stroke, the bleeding will
worsen.
</P>
<P>
   A primary stroke center would have the ability and established
procedures for determining whether clot-dissolving drugs are
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marc R. Mayberg, a neurosurgeon at the Cleveland Clinic,
said a recent survey in the Cleveland area showed that only 1.8
percent of victims of ischemic stroke received clot-dissolving
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   And in half of those cases, physicians administering the drug
departed from accepted protocols for using it, he said. One-fifth
of the patients had brain hemorrhages after receiving the drug, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Brain Attack Coalition is a group of professional, volunteer
and government organizations concerned with stroke treatment and
prevention.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet: http://www.stroke.org;
http://www.ninds.nih.gov/patients/Disorder/STROKE/strokehp.htm
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e.mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
