<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9745 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RELIGION-WORKPLACE-2T     06-20 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-WORKPLACE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE NAME OF PEACE AT THE OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one at the Earth Justice Legal Defense Fund, an environmental
law firm in San Francisco, expected December 1998 to be the
cruelest month. The holiday season is supposed to be about peace,
not tribal warfare. But war is what broke out, over Yuletide
decorations.
</P>
<P>
   The fracas began when Christian employees decided to celebrate
and the manager told them to decorate the office however they saw
fit. But the firm's non-Christian employees, including Jews,
Buddhists and Muslims, felt slighted, so the boss told them all to
decorate their personal areas rather than one centralized location.
That did not fly, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``People went all out, and it became almost obscene with the
excess,'' said Tracy Salkowitz, the executive director of the
Northern Pacific region for the American Jewish Congress in San
Francisco, who was brought in along with an outside lawyer to help
negotiate a truce. ``They were angry and bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   In a half-day workshop that about 30 employees attended, the two
arbitrators explained the law on religion in the workplace. Then
Salkowitz asked people to describe what the holiday season meant to
them. ``They said December was a dreary month; they wanted to keep
it festive and celebrate the earth,'' Salkowitz recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot was that employees created a festival committee in
charge of seasonal decor, dressed up the lobby and other common
spaces with greenery and tributes to the earth, organized a food
drive and abolished the company party in favor of community
service.
</P>
<P>
   Earth Justice's brush with religious discord is hardly a
workplace anomaly. With the nation undergoing something of a
spiritual revival, more companies are seeking to accommodate
employees' religious needs by initiatives like letting people swap
religious holidays, organizing prayer breakfasts or spiritual
retreats, setting aside prayer rooms and even hiring on-site
corporate chaplains. The Fellowship of Companies for Christ
International, a Christian group, estimates that 10,000 Bible-study
and prayer groups meet in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to an employer's benefit to accommodate employees'
religious needs,'' said the Rev. Diana Dale, the executive director
of the National Institute of Business and Industrial Chaplains, in
Houston. ``It's a core part of people's grounding, and it makes
them more productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, that means simply letting people take prayer breaks.
At mondus.com, a shopping site for businesses in Manhattan, Farid
Senzai, 30, a Muslim who is the company's director of business
development, unrolls his prayer rug every afternoon and becomes
unavailable for meetings.
</P>
<P>
   His co-workers, who include Christians, Jews and even a believer
in the Hindu religion Jain, ``are understanding,'' Senzai said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't bother me if my door is shut, and they'll go out of
their way not to eat food in front of me during Ramadan,'' the
Muslim month of fasting.
</P>
<P>
   The epicenter of American capitalism, the New York Stock
Exchange, has also become a bit of a religious center lately. Jay
Knopf, senior vice president of the brokerage firm Spear, Leeds &AMP;
Kellog, has organized a mincha minyan, or afternoon prayer of
Orthodox Jews, in a computer room at the exchange for four days a
week. (Agudath Israel, a Jewish advocacy group, says there are 99
workplace minyans in Manhattan alone.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't cost the company a penny,'' Knopf said, ``and the
employee has better job satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Prayer at the exchange is not just for Jews, either. On Friday
mornings, a Christian group gathers in a corner room.
</P>
<P>
   Such activities reflect the norms of a deeply religious society.
In a recent Gallup poll, 95 percent of those surveyed said they
believed in God, and 48 percent reported talking about their
religious faith at work that day.
</P>
<P>
   Employers have taken note. The Society for Human Resource
Management in Alexandria, Va., says 68 percent of 743
human-resource professionals at American corporations who were
polled in 1997 said they offered flexible schedules for religious
observances and 15 percent said they provided space or time for
religious observances.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing God and the office is not to everyone's liking, of
course, and it can be legally tricky. Complaints to the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission about religious discrimination
rose to 1,811 in 1999 from 1,584 three years earlier, though they
still paled in comparison with 24,454 accusations of sexual
discrimination in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires ``reasonable accommodation'' of religious
practice in the workplace. Guidelines issued by the Clinton
administration in 1997 say employees have the right to express
their beliefs, for example by keeping copies of the Bible or the
Koran on their desks, so long as they do not interfere with the
rights of others.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that ``employers don't know what their
obligations and rights are,'' said Marc Stern, a lawyer with the
American Jewish Congress in New York, who helped draft the
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the employer is a devout Christian and he's running prayer
breakfast, can he make everyone come?'' Stern asked. ``Are
Christmas trees offensive to others in the same way a nude pinup is
offensive to someone? Many firms have been operating under the bad
advice to treat religion the way you treat sex, which is to ban it
from the workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the issue at Sandia National Laboratories, the federal
nuclear research center in New Mexico. The lab allowed an employee
gay-rights group to meet on its property but turned down a
Christian group's request for company recognition. The Christian
group sued in May of last year, and its lawyer denounced Sandia's
policy as ``an insult not only to believers in God, but to
believers in freedom everywhere.'' Sandia declined to comment on
that accusation. But John German, a spokesman for the lab, said the
two sides reached an agreement in principle last Friday to allow
the Christian group to meet on its premises.
</P>
<P>
   Some questions may not have satisfactory answers. Which holds
precedence, Stern asked, a man's right to follow a religious
stricture against working with women or a woman's right to equal
employment opportunities? ``The secular-religion divide is too
great,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some people want to build bridges. Salkowitz, the
American Jewish Congress official in San Francisco, started a
project this month aimed at getting people to air their religious
differences openly. ``You'd be amazed at the problems that arise,''
Salkowtiz said. ``But it's in a company's best interest to work it
through. They did it at Earth Justice. You wouldn't even recognize
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1807EDT &QL; 
