<HEADER>
A9747 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-CLAYMATION-SPI &LR;      06-20 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CLAYMATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHICKEN RUN' MAKERS PRAY CLAYMATION FILM DOESN'T LAY AN EGG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD   
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a mere $50 million price tag, DreamWorks' first stop-motion
animated feature, ``Chicken Run,'' would seem to be _ by current
industry standards _ a relatively low-budget offering. But
Wednesday's midweek unveiling of the film is still being widely
regarded as Hollywood's biggest dice roll of the summer, because:
</P>
<P>
   _Despite huge investment costs, neither of the two previous
major stop-motion animated films of the past decade, ``Nightmare
Before Christmas'' and ``James and the Giant Peach,'' was a
blockbuster hit, and their producer _ Disney _ has since abandoned
the process.
</P>
<P>
   _Claymation is the most stylized and esoteric form of
stop-motion animation, and every previous attempt at a Claymation
feature _ such as Will Vinton's 1985 ``Adventures of Mark Twain'' _
has failed miserably with critics and audiences alike.
</P>
<P>
   _The filmmakers at Aardman Animation have a following and have
won three Oscars for their animated shorts, but their popularity is
still very much a cult phenomenon, and the film pointedly does not
feature their most recognizable characters, Wallace and Gromit.
</P>
<P>
   _The film's stars _ chickens _ do not evoke the same kind of
instant affection that other, more cuddly animals do, yet
DreamWorks is going all out with chicken toy merchandising, and a
tie-in with a fast-food chain that sells chicken sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   _Even though the film has a slightly hard edge and is geared to
play to adults as well as children, Aardman and DreamWorks have
gone for a G rating, which is regarded as a handicap in today's
movie market because it tends to chase away the core teen audience.
</P>
<P>
   So, not surprisingly, when the film's two British directors,
Peter Lord and Nick Park, rolled into Seattle last week midway
though a grueling nationwide press tour, they seemed more than a
little apprehensive about how well their film _ the product of many
years of work _ will do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' Lord admitted, ``we're nervous. This is all new to us,
and the process of a large (make-or-break) opening is totally
nerve-racking. The truth is that we haven't even seen the film with
an audience yet. ... The only thing that keeps us sane is that
people who have seen it seem to be crazy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The two directing partners make a bit of an odd couple. Lord,
the older of the pair, has long, graying hair, a quick wit and a
confident, almost professorial manner. Park is much more shy, and
has a natural sweetness and slight awkwardness that makes him often
seem like one of his gentler Claymation creations.
</P>
<P>
   Lord said he first ``discovered'' clay animation as a high
school student and began to make short films for BBC television
programs while still in his teens. He founded Aardman (the name
comes from a superhero character of one of their early shorts) in
1972, and moved to the company's Bristol studio in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Park began making films in his parents' attic at age 13, sold
his first 8 mm short to the BBC in 1975 and joined Lord _ his
``boyhood hero'' _ in 1985. In 1990, he turned out both the
Oscar-nominated ``A Grand Day Out,'' introducing Wallace &AMP; Gromit,
and ``Creature Comforts'' _ the first of his three Oscar-winning
shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the company has turned out a succession of
shorts, commercials and music videos with an ironic tone and
distinctive visual style that critics have called ``Aardmanesque.''
Despite limited exposure in the States, Lord said the size of their
following here ``constantly surprises us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, when we decided to go for an international
superstar for the voice of Rocky (the film's lead character), we
sent it to Mel Gibson and discovered both he and his children were
huge fans of Wallace &AMP; Gromit. Far from being resistant, he
literally jumped at the chance to become involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Lord said the idea of a feature has been in the back of their
minds from the earliest days, and Hollywood _ including Disney _
had been courting them since their first Oscar. ``People would keep
coming to us with their ideas, but somehow we never seemed to like
them. We just seem to work better with our own story ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, they got more serious about the idea and allied
themselves with noted producer Jake Eberts (``The Killing Fields'')
who, after several years of shopping, eventually made a
coproduction deal for them with DreamWorks and French company
Pathe. ``Chicken Run'' was announced in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Why chickens? With a bemused smile, Lord said he finds them
``stupid and ridiculous.'' Park _ who worked in a chicken-packing
plant for two summers as a student _ said, ``Since I was a child,
I've always liked to draw birds. I like the way they behave and
I've always found chickens to be particularly funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I came across a sketch I'd made earlier of a chicken
trying to dig its way under a fence, and the idea suddenly occurred
to me, `Why not make a World War II-style prisoner-of-war movie
like ``The Great Escape'' with chickens as the prisoner
characters.' And everyone seemed to just love the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the pair have hardly been ``up for air.'' Park said,
``We discovered that making a feature film is many times harder in
every way than making even a 30-minute short. If we knew what we
were getting into, I'm sure we would have turned back. But, of
course, it was too late by the time we realized this.''
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Aardman's Bristol studio was transformed from a
small, familylike company into a state-of-the-art animation
facility that now employs more than 400 people. ``It's sad in a
way,'' Lord said, ``because now we don't even know the names of
many of our employees. But you can't stand still or you die.''
</P>
<P>
   Lord said their relationship with DreamWorks ``could not be
better.'' ``They were quite happy to have us remain in our Bristol
digs _ out of sight _ and (top executive Jeffrey) Katzenberg said
from the beginning we only had to answer to him, promising there'd
be no Hollywood bureaucracy to frustrate us.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept his word on that score, and was otherwise enormously
helpful all along the line. And far from being (a compromising
influence), he always urged us to be more daring. When we thought
the scene where (a character) has his head chopped off might be too
much for kids, Jeffrey said, `Think of Bambi's mother.'''
</P>
<P>
   Park said Aardman hopes to continue making features. The company
has a deal for five more films with DreamWorks, and it already is
working on its second feature, ``The Tortoise and the Hare.''
``Yes,'' Park smiled, ``I realize it violates our rule of working
only with our own stories. What can I say? We just like it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the DreamWorks deal is dependent on the success of ``Chicken
Run'' and, if it stiffs at the box office, what then? ``Then,''
Lord said, ``we can always go back to making shorts, commercials
and music videos. In fact, if we had any sense, that's where we
should have stayed in the first place _ because the money is so
much better and the risk is almost non-existent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
