<HEADLINE>
SHAS QUITS ISRAELI GOVERNMENT, THREATENING BARAK'S COALITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to update and add background: 4th graf to update time
element; 7th graf, bgng `But their gambit...' to clarify; adds new
grafs 8,9 to update with Barak press conference; adds to last graf
of orig. text and adds 8 grafs of background to end of original
text.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Throwing Israeli politics into an even greater
frenzy than usual, the linchpin Shas political party on Tuesday
quit Prime Minister Ehud Barak's governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   But Shas' resignation does not take effect for 48 hours, which
leaves plenty of time for political bargaining before Barak loses
his parliamentary majority.
</P>
<P>
   If the strictly religious Shas party does leave, it will not
only reduce Barak to a minority government but also jeopardize his
plans for making peace with the Palestinians. The prime minister
would need the support of Shas to get a peace deal approved
smoothly by a sizeable majority of the parliament and by Israelis
in a popular referendum.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak said Tuesday night that after a week of intensive,
sometimes round-the-clock negotiations, he and Shas had worked out
the major part of an agreement. And Shas politicians made clear
that if an effort was made to address their remaining concerns,
their resignations could well be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely an escalation,'' Eli Suissa, one of four
Shas members in Cabinet, said after submitting his resignation as
infrastructure minister Tuesday. ``But the ball is now in the prime
minister's court.''
</P>
<P>
   Exercising their raw power at a time when Barak considers a
peace agreement to be his singular goal, Shas' leaders are playing
a very public game of hardball in their quest to be treated with
respect and compensated for their indispensable support. They have
chiefly been demanding debt relief and tax forgiveness for their
religious school system as well as the legalization of their pirate
radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   But their gambit could backfire. Barak's associates said Tuesday
that the prime minister was fed up and contemplating the advantages
of reshaping his government without Shas. While such statements are
meant to pressure Shas, they probably do reflect Barak's thinking,
too.
</P>
<P>
   In a press conference Tuesday evening, Barak called the
situation a ``crisis that tests the norms of government and Israeli
democracy.'' It also, he suggested, tested his patience, but he
repeated his commitment to a broad government including Shas, which
he called an ``important party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My associates and I made a paramount effort to keep Shas in
the coalition,'' Barak said. ``Ninety percent of the problems have
been solved. We would like to see Shas stay, but we will respect
its decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Shas' latest political maneuver comes at a sensitive time in the
Israeli-Palestinian relationship, when both sides are maneuvering
toward what would be the endgame of their seven years of peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have viewed the chaos in the Israeli government
partly with suspicion and partly with concern. On the one hand,
they suspect that Barak is using his political problems as an
excuse to delay meeting their demands. On the other, they worry
that they no longer have a partner strong enough to make a good
deal and sell it to his public.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they have displayed a willingness to step back. Senior
Palestinian officials said Tuesday that they would not press the
Israelis to stick to a June 23 deadline for their next withdrawal
from the West Bank. In the midst of Barak's political troubles, the
implementation of the transfer of land this week would have proven
all but impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians said their leader, Yasser Arafat, was acceding
to a request that President Clinton presented in Washington last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed to postpone the implementation for two weeks to
examine the possibility of reaching a final agreement,'' Ahmed
Qurei, speaker of the Palestinian legislature and the senior
Palestinian negotiator, told Voice of Palestine Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to push things forward speedily, the Israeli government is
putting on its own full court press to convince the Americans to
convene a retreat-style, Israeli-Palestinian peace summit meeting
in the United States in early July. They have proposed July 5, in
fact. U.S. officials said it is unlikely a decision would be made
before Secretary of State Madeleine Albright returns to the region
next week.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the political crisis is likely to have been
resolved.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It has been an intense week of bartering. Barak and his
political negotiators have largely met Shas' demands for money.
They have also promised that the recovery plan for its school
system would be overseen directly by the prime minister's office
and not by the leftist education minister, Yossi Sarid, who is the
Shas party's nemesis. Sarid has volunteered to resign his post, if
need be, but remain in the government to support the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   Nissim Dahan, a Shas lawmaker and the deputy finance minister,
complained that in return for what Barak was offering, he was
demanding Shas support in advance for every future peacemaking move
by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are extorting us in the diplomatic, political sphere,''
he said. ``Even if he wants to transfer Tel Aviv to the
Palestinians, we would have to vote yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Shas' leaders have been upset that they have been portrayed as
extortionists and that so many political analysts have predicted
that Shas would never be able to give up the perquisites of power.
Eli Yishai, the leader of Shas, suggested on Tuesday that the
resignation letters were meant to prove wrong those who doubted
their resolve. ``Our reasons are not personal ones,'' he said.
``Everyone always said give them money, they're incapable of
leaving the coalition, they're bound to the money, to the power, to
the Volvo,'' the car that every minister gets.
</P>
<P>
   An ultra-Orthodox party that doubles as a kind of ethnic pride
movement for Jews of Middle Eastern and North African descent, Shas
is by self-definition an anti-establishment outsiders' party. Even
it were to remain inside the government, it would likely continue
to be a difficult partner.
</P>
<P>
   In building a broad coalition government last year, Barak
considered Shas a critical, if temperamental, partner for his
peacemaking plans.
</P>
<P>
   Shas' rabbinical leaders are believed to be more dovish than
their party's working-class constituents, supposedly making them
critical allies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Shas has shown a reluctance to support Barak's peace moves,
and in citing its incentives for quitting the government last week,
it referred to plans to ``forsake'' the West Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
