<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, June 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled weather will return to portions of the East on
Wednesday as a jet stream disturbance crosses the Great Lakes.
Scattered showers and isolated thunderstorms will develop from New
York to northern Maryland while farther east, sunshine fades behind
thickening clouds across New England.
</P>
<P>
   A broken band of potent storms will erupt late Wednesday
afternoon from Lake Erie to Kentucky as sultry air is lifted by an
approaching cold front. A few of the storms will be severe, with
hail and damaging winds. Heavy showers and thunderstorms will bring
flooding to northeast Texas and Arkansas where the cold front slows
its southward progress.
</P>
<P>
   Partial sunshine will cover the Southeast. As the potent summer
sun heats the humid air, ascending currents of air will cause
clouds and spotty thunderstorms. Elsewhere, the West will stay
mainly dry, with ample sun, though isolated storms will form near
the Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: THUNDERSTRUCK
</P>
<P>
   Many long-time residents of Barrow, Alaska, paused in
astonishment on Monday when the weather did something they had not
seen before. The first thunderstorm in the recorded history of the
nation's northernmost weather station added unfamiliar illumination
to the land of the midnight sun. Although very rare, thunderstorms
have occurred in the past over extreme northern Alaska, but never
at the official reporting site. Weather records at Barrow began in
1901.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
