<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, June 21, 2000. The NYT frontpage advisory, with
layout description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News
Service Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HATE-CRIMES (Washington) _ Senate approves by a vote of
57-42 a bill that makes hate attacks on homosexuals a federal
offense. While the Senate passed a similar measure last year by
unanimous consent, Tuesday's vote was the first time either House
of Congress backed protection of gays or lesbians on a rollcall
vote that would have political consequences. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT (Washington) _ The trial judge in the Microsoft
antitrust case Tuesday stayed all the restrictions he had imposed
on the company until the Supreme Court decides whether or not to
hear the appeal. Although he had been expected to ask the high
court to consider a direct review, the stay was unexpected. It
apparently reflected his previously stated view that he felt
uncomfortable imposing remedies in the case without a quick review
by a higher court. The move may buy Microsoft several months at
least, since the Supreme Court may not decide whether to take the
case until fall. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-COLLEGE (Cambridge, Mass.) _ An in-depth look at Al Gore's
years at Harvard, which were far more politically volatile than
those of George W. Bush's at Yale. By Melissa Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   With NYT photos 13,14,15,16,17
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PARDON-BOARD (San Antonio, Texas) _ The Texas board of
pardons and parole will vote this week on whether or not to give a
reprieve to convicted killer Gary Graham. Sara Rimer profiles the
board, which is unlike any other body in the country. They are all
appointees of Gov. George W. Bush and receive $80,000 a year. They
never meet in person but only talk on the phone. They are perhaps
the governor's biggest imprint on executions in Texas. By Sara
Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   With NYT photos 18-19.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-CHINA (Taipei, Taiwan) _ Emboldened by last week's summit
meeting between the leaders of North and South Korea, Taiwan's new
president, Chen Shui-bian, on Tuesday invited his Chinese
counterpart, Jiang Zemin, to take part in a similar peace-making
effort. China immediately rejected the overture. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (Early version has moved)
</P>
<P>
   LUNG-CANCER-SCREENING (Undated) _ When word got out recently
that two radiology centers in Portland, Ore., were offering a new
screening test for the early detection of lung cancer, the response
was overwhelming. Smokers and former smokers jammed the centers'
phones, demanding the simple, painless test that can find lung
cancers so tiny that they can be snipped out and, doctors hope, the
patients cured. It is a scene that is being repeated throughout the
country as more and more radiologists begin advertising that they
can carry out the lung cancer screening test. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PARENTS (Undated) _ In the world of Internet startups,
where a typical chief executive is 30 and a labor shortage
continues even as some dot-coms fail, dot-commers in more than a
few cases are recruiting their own parents. These thirtysomethings
belong to a generation that came of age comfortable with both
technology and the risks that come with entrepreneurship. Most of
their parents are still in the work force, many of them still years
from retirement. By Katie Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   With NYT photos 20,21.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
