</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9776 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MICROSOFT21-COX     06-20 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUDGE SHUNTS MICROSOFT CASE TO SUPREME COURT
 &HT;    420&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The judge who ordered Microsoft Corp. to be broken
up Tuesday sent the company's appeal of his historic antitrust
ruling directly to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's highest tribunal, nearing the end of current term,
can now either accept the landmark case or else turn it back to the
U.S. Court of Appeals for further review.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson acted under a rarely
invoked law that allows the Supreme Court to decide antitrust cases
of major national importance without a prior review by a federal
appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Jackson brushed aside Microsoft's legal objections
and upheld the view of the Justice Department and 19 states that
short-circuiting the normal appellate process ensures ``the most
prompt and efficient resolution'' of the widely watched case.
</P>
<P>
   In the same 120-word order, Jackson granted Microsoft a reprieve
by freezing, while the appeals process moves forward, the strict
curbs he had imposed on the way the software giant can do business.
</P>
<P>
   Those so-called conduct-based remedies, which were due to go
into effect Sept. 9, would ban Microsoft from punishing computer
makers who support rival products and force the company to license
its popular Windows operating systems on non-discriminatory terms.
They also would allow the manufacturers to modify Windows before
shipping their machines.
</P>
<P>
   Concurring with government briefs that cited the vital role
technology
</P>
<P>
   has come to play in the U.S. economy, Jackson said a direct
review of his sweeping June 7 ruling by the full Supreme Court was
of ``general public importance in the administration of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   While, at one point or another, the nine-member high tribunal is
virtually certain to accept an antitrust case of such paramount
importance, it first must decide whether to do so on the fast track
laid down Tuesday or on the regular track that requires an initial
decision by the Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   That intermediate body, which sits in same courthouse as
Jackson, has shown its clear interest in taking case by declaring
that all seven eligible members, rather than the customary
three-judge panel, would weigh the appeal if it were to first come
before them.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court could decide on its course of action before
the conclusion of its current term, only days or weeks from winding
up, or it could wait until the start of its next term, which begins
in the first week of October.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Legal scholars believed Jackson had stayed his conduct remedies
to leave the Supreme Court the option to set its own timetable
without being overrun by his own. His decision also waives the
possibility that the Court of Appeals, were it to win jurisdiction,
would have stayed these remedies pending the outcome of a full
appeal _ a decision which would have handed Microsoft a tactical
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the justices expedite their handling of the case,
Microsoft will have until Aug. 12 to file an appeal of Jackson's
fast-track ruling. The government then would have 30 days to
respond and explain why they think the case should not be initially
heard by the appellate judges.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department immediately hailed Jackson's move, while
noting that his stay of the temporary steps he imposed made it all
the more important for the Supreme Court to hear the appeal
directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased with the court's decision to place the
appeal directly in the Supreme Court,'' the department said in a
statement. ``This decision affirms the department's position that a
quick and effective remedy is necessary to resolve this significant
case.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate reaction from Microsoft. The company is
counting on the justices to shun the daunting prospect of reviewing
the entire 13,466-page trial transcript and as well as some 2,700
trial exhibits in favor of reading the appellate summaries.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.usdoj.gov/atr/cases/msindex.htm
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
