<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-COMMISSION-0621-     06-20 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-COMMISSION-0621-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE REJECTS CUBA COMMISSION
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate rejected a proposal Tuesday to create a
commission designed to improve U.S. relations with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense to me that we can have a normal
relationship with China and Vietnam, and lift sanctions on North
Korea, but it is not possible to even form a commission to just
look into the Cuba issue,'' said. Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,
the amendment's author shortly before the 59-41 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., called the proposal a ``pointless
political exercise that attempts to set foreign policy through a
partisan commission, rather than the normal conduct of foreign
policy by the president and Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are big differences between China and Cuba,'' Mack said.
``China began policy changes and economic reforms as early as 1978,
and today they continue to open their economy, while Cuba does not
permit trade independent from the state, or freedom in economic
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said the bill comes at the wrong time
because of the upcoming presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Policy in Cuba shouldn't be decided by a commission appointed
by a lame-duck administration,'' Graham said. ``It should be
decided by the American people in the next election for
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The amendment would have created a commission to Cuba made up of
twelve members. Six of the members would have been appointed by the
President, and six by Congress _ of the latter, two would be
Republicans and one a Democrat from both the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Mack said that was arrangement was blatantly political because
eight of the members would be Democrats and four would be
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd said that he hoped the commission would help establish a
better relationship with Cuba, and especially lay the groundwork
for the future relations in the post-Castro era.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a step backwards in foreign policy,'' Dodd said. ``I
am stunned that my colleagues are willing to squander a
relationship with a post-Castro Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   (Rob O'Dell's e-mail address is robo(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
