<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9789 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-HNS &LR;      06-20 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON REDEFINES SUCCESS OF MISSILE DEFENSE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jacques Gansler, the Pentagon's top weapons
official, signaled Tuesday that the Defense Department is allowing
itself more wiggle-room on the question of whether a proposed
missile defense system will work.
</P>
<P>
   Gansler said that even if a crucial July 7 test flight is a
failure, Pentagon officials might still urge Defense Secretary
William Cohen to recommend to President Clinton that he approve the
construction of the complicated network of interceptors, computers,
satellites and sensors.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Pentagon officials said they wouldn't recommend that
Cohen give the go-ahead until the missile defense system had scored
two successful test intercepts. The officials had said they would
require two successful tests in order to be assured that the
technical hurdles associated with knocking a speeding
intercontinental ballistic missile out of the sky with another
missile can be overcome.
</P>
<P>
   The system scored a direct hit last October but missed in a
January test. The July 7 test was then scheduled to allow the
Pentagon another chance to achieve its second successful test in
time to meet a deadline for Cohen to make a recommendation to
Clinton by August.
</P>
<P>
   The target is a modified Minuteman II missile that will be
launched from Vandenberg Air Force Base in California. The
interceptor rocket _ fired from Kwajalein Island in the Pacific _
will be directed near the target by radar and then commanded to
deploy a 130-pound ``kill vehicle'' designed to ram into the
warhead some 100 miles above the ocean at 4.6 miles per second.
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked about possible outcomes of the July 7 test,
Gansler indicated to reporters Tuesday that the definition of
``success'' had some elastic in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending upon the types of failures, we may still be able to
say it's technically feasible,'' Gansler, the undersecretary of
defense for acquisition, said.
</P>
<P>
   Gansler said that if ``everything (on the intercepting missile)
worked fine but the target didn't work or something,'' the test
still might be classified as a success even if the interceptor
rocket didn't hit the target.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly a high-risk overall program,'' Gansler said.
``And it's not a high probability of being able to precisely get
everything to work on this flight'' in July.
</P>
<P>
   A successful test on July 7 had been considered essential in
order to meet a deadline of fielding the weapon by 2005, the date
when U.S. intelligence officials believe North Korea might possess
a missile capable of striking the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The program is on a tight deadline. By August, Cohen is
scheduled to make a recommendation to Clinton about whether the
weapon is ready to be transitioned from the laboratory to the
battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton in turn must give his approval no later than November or
December if the Pentagon is to meet the 2005 deployment deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule is compounded by the need to build a new radar on a
remote Alaskan island in the Aleutians. Contracts must be signed in
November so that the radar can be completed to meet the 2005 date.
If contracts are not signed in time, it will delay the program for
a year, said Air Force Lt. Gen. Ronald Kadish, who manages National
Missile Defense for the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   According to current Pentagon plans, the $36 billion-plus
program will be constructed in several phases, if Clinton gives the
green light. At first the anti-missile system will use 20
interceptors based in Alaska. But by 2007, the Pentagon plans to
begin adding another 80 interceptor missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has already approved the plan, if it can be proven
technically feasible.
</P>
<P>
   National Missile Defense is being designed to provide protection
for U.S. cities against a ballistic missile attack from so-called
``rogue'' countries such as North Korea or Iran, which are
developing long-range weapons. The system also is being designed to
provide protection against an accidental nuclear missile launch in
Russia, sparked by decaying Soviet-era equipment or a weapon that
falls into the hands of a terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail:
eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
