<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-HEARTLAND-PA21-COX     06-20 1865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARTLAND-PA21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keystone State seen as key to victory in November
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRYN MAWR, Pa. _ Pennsylvania's Route 30 runs west out of
Philadelphia as fast as it can, crossing out of neediness and into
affluence, changing its name to the Main Line and leaving behind
the dull grays of the city for the bright greens of the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Main Line is the name for a short stretch of Pennsylvania 30
where it runs through Montgomery County, Pa. Just a few miles where
Jaguar and Range Rover have dealerships, where Democrats give way
to Republicans and where a presidential hopeful for the GOP must
stem the predictably Democratic tide of inner-city ballots and
start winning precincts if he wants Pennsylvania's 23 electoral
votes.
</P>
<P>
   There are streets just like it coming out of Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania is one of four industrial states across the
heartland where the election will be won or lost. Like Ohio,
Illinois and Michigan, Pennsylvania is a swing state populated by
voters unafraid to cross party lines to cast their ballots and with
a knack for choosing a winner. The last time Pennsylvania supported
a losing candidate was 1968: Hubert Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   The race for president in Pennsylvania can be seen as a simple
mathematical equation in which the heavy concentrations of
Democratic votes in Philadelphia and Pittsburgh _ still dominated
by minorities and labor unions _ weigh against the increasingly
conservative voters found farther from those cities.
</P>
<P>
   James Carville, the colorful political strategist who gained
fame helping President Clinton get elected, cut his teeth on major
campaigns in Pennsylvania and summarized the state this way: You've
got Pittsburgh on one end, Philadelphia on the other and Alabama in
between.
</P>
<P>
   That means many issues of significance in the state split
geographically. The cities still vote along liberal lines on social
issues, and the outlaying parts of the state vote bedrock
conservative, even if their voter registration card says Democrat.
But the state's unusually high number of retirees _ who stay put
after their careers because of the state's generous benefits to
seniors _ means some issues, such as Social Security, split
generationally.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the Main Line remains predominantly Republican, but
Clinton won these suburbs in 1992 and 1996, and political
strategists in Pennsylvania say the statewide winner in 2000 is
going to have to win them, too.
</P>
<P>
   But winning the suburbs can be costly elsewhere in the state. Go
too conservative and you risk firing up the inner-city Democrats in
Philly and Pittsburgh who, with a hefty turnout, still can sink a
statewide candidate. Go too liberal and, plain and simple, the
suburbs won't vote for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pennsylvania right now is more of a Republican state than a
Democratic state,'' said Terry Madonna, who teaches political
science at Millersville University in the Lancaster region of the
state. ``(But) In the suburbs are voters that the Democrats have
been able to woo away in elections.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Main Line Starbucks, a pair of 30-something mothers
police the wreckage where the coffee cake met the toddlers. One is
a Republican, the other a Democrat. They are educated and
interested and listening to Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But so far neither one loves what she's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel 100 percent, or even 70 percent for either one,''
said Laura Harrington, the Republican, a mother of two. ``I'm
having a hard time. I liked McCain but now I don't know what I'm
going to do. They're both doing so much hedging.''
</P>
<P>
   Physician Dr. Allison Oler, the Democrat, is favoring Gore, but
if Bush proposed funding for medical research through the National
Institutes of Health, which has been cut in recent years, he'd have
a good shot at winning her vote. She also might be swayed by
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beyond elementary and high school, it's also about the
affordability of college,'' said Oler, a mother of two. ``I hope
(one of the candidates) seizes on education as a whole and proposes
something comprehensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington still winces at the thought that Oler voted for
Clinton twice (``I don't care about his personal life, he's done
well by us''), but they are unified in their belief that abortion
should remain legal, and that tougher gun control laws only make
sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``A waiting period?'' Harrington said. ``Why would that be a
problem for anyone?''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with Pennsylvania is its size and political
diversity. Harrington and Oler want gun control _ even if Oler
wants more than Harrington does _ and that would be warmly received
in the cities. But much beyond the reputable suburbs that branch
north and south of the Main Line and Pennsylvania turns into
hunting country, dotted with towns that close local schools for the
first day of deer season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who has ever run a gun-control campaign in
Pennsylvania has lost,'' said William J. Green, a public relations
executive in Pittsburgh who worked on the staff of former
Republican governor Richard Thornburgh.
</P>
<P>
   This also is where abortion plays a role. Pennsylvania was the
first state to pass a law requiring parental notification and a
24-hour counseling period before abortions are performed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a pro-life vote here that has made a difference in
campaigns,'' said Neil Oxman, a Democratic Party consultant in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the anti-abortion vote, Pennsylvania has twice
elected an abortion rights Republican for governor. Tom Ridge, who
like 40 percent of the state's voters is Catholic, was attacked on
the abortion issue in his first race in 1994 when an independent
anti-abortion candidate managed to draw 13 percent of the vote.
Ridge won the governorship with 45 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, Ridge hasn't been seriously challenged and won
re-election in 1998 with 57 percent, even as the bishop in his home
diocese in Erie announced that Ridge is not welcome at church
events.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ridge, who won a Bronze star during combat in Vietnam, is
an oft-mentioned possibility to join Bush on the GOP ticket as the
candidate for vice president. Even Democrats in Pennsylvania say
the move would hobble Gore's chances of winning the Keystone State.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush rat.
</P>
<P>
   But not all Democrats are so enthusiastic about Ridge, and not
all of them are ready to concede the state to Republicans if Ridge
joins Bush. The die-hards, in Pittsburgh and Philadelphia, say
Ridge hasn't cracked the inner-city Democratic base, even if he has
done OK with union voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Ridge lost Philadelphia both times he ran, this is a city
with a deep Democratic heritage,'' said Ken Snyder, a Democratic
consultant in the city. ``There's a Democratic Party infrastructure
that still counts.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Pittsburgh, the president of the Allegheny County Council
that represents the bulk of the city, still believes that Ridge or
no Ridge, Gore is well positioned win there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Al Gore is going to carry Allegheny County,'' said
John DeFazio, a Democrat who also is the district director for the
United Steel Workers. ``You look at all the good things that have
happened, it's pretty tough to go with the other guy.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore faces serious questions about the loyalty of union
voters in places such as Michigan, some in Pennsylvania say he
doesn't face the same challenge here. Pennsylvania's blue-collar
unions haven't been thrilled with Gore's position in favor of
opening trade with China and other countries _ a stance he shares
with Bush _ but as industrial trade groups they've benefited from
the increase in construction in the good economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore didn't go my way on a few things,'' DeFazio said. ``But
the proof is in the pudding. Things are pretty decent.''
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania has participated in the economic boom of the last
several years, but not to the same extent as other states. Steel
and coal continue to contribute heavily to the state's economy, and
although pockets of the state have economies with surging high-tech
markets, Pennsylvania is not a growth state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't produce jobs the way we should. We're a net exporter
of college students and we're migrating people,'' said Madonna of
Millersville University, which conducts that state's widely cited
Keystone Poll on politics. ``Should the economy catch a cold, we'll
get pneumonia.''
</P>
<P>
   The `decent' state of things is a mixed bag, both for Gore and
for Bush. Union members argue that if the economy continues to grow
through November, it will improve Gore's chances of winning the
state. But Republicans counter that Gore isn't likely to get much
credit for the recent prosperity, which they say is as much the
result of a Republican congress as a Democratic president.
</P>
<P>
   And, they argue, Gore is more likely to suffer the consequences
of having a more contented, less energized political base.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy has kept a lot of people working,'' agreed Pat
Meehan, a district attorney in suburban Philadelphia who previously
worked on statewide campaigns for both of Pennsylvania's Republican
senators. ``For the first time, issues like schools and education
and taxes can come first. But those kinds of things tend not to
generate turnout the way unemployment and economic uncertainty
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Back on the Main Line, Nelson Azeff's issues are health care and
Social Security. At 61 he's a retired executive whose life long
membership in the Republican Party may be in jeopardy now that he's
considering voting Democrat for president for the third time in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   A back injury forced Azeff into early retirement so now he
spends his days reading up on politics, and wiling away afternoons
in the cigar shop owned by a friend. With a library of $6 and $7
cigars rising up behind him, Azeff said he's not been impressed
with Bush, though he has questions about Gore, too.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of Pennsylvania's large retiree population, Azeff
and others like him could be a decisive force in the election if
they move en masse on an issue. Pennsylvania offers senior citizens
a variety of benefits, from rebates on local telephone to free bus
passes, depending on their income level, which has enticed many
retirees to stay put rather than move south.
</P>
<P>
   But Pennsylvania's retirees come from a cross section of its
wider population. Some are blue-collar, some are white-collar. Some
are Catholic or Protestant, Irish, Italian and on and on. Statewide
strategists say the retirees in Pennsylvania may just vote as
members of those groups rather than as seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Unless they sense a threat to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Azeff does. He opposes Bush's plan to let people invest portions
of their own Social Security benefit in individual accounts. The
issue may not be decisive, but it's helping him lean toward Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people should touch that money. I think the
government has to control Social Security,'' he said. ``There are
some things that our government has to be involved in, right up to
the neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
