<HEADER>
A9794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRAZIL-CRIME-530&AMP;ADD-     06-20 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-CRIME-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL BANS GUN SALES AFTER PUBLIC OUTCRY OVER CRIME WAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Faced with growing public alarm over a
wave of crime, the Brazilian government decreed an immediate ban
Tuesday on the sale of firearms. The move came as as part of a
broader $1.7 billion national security plan intended to reduce
urban violence and reform the police over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   The weapons restrictions will remain in effect until the end of
this year, Justice Minister Jose Gregori announced at a news
conference in Brasilia. By then, the government hopes to have won
congressional approval of a more restrictive bill that would
virtually ban the possession of firearms by any Brazilian citizen
who is not a member of the armed forces, a police officer or an
employee of a private security company.
</P>
<P>
   The government estimates that Brazilians now own more than 8
million guns, about three-quarters of which are unregistered, and
that guns are used in nearly 90 percent of the killings committed
in this country, a much higher figure than in the United States.
Under the proposed legislation, gun owners would have one year to
turn in their weapons to the government.
</P>
<P>
   The security package, which President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
announced in a nationally televised speech Tuesday, also includes
$185 million to be spent this year alone on improved training and
equipment for state and city police. Local police forces throughout
this country of 175 million are widely viewed as trigger-happy,
corrupt and incompetent, with many officers barely literate and
earning salaries of $300 a month or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first plan in the history of Brazil to attack the
issue of public security in a comprehensive way,'' Gregori said.
</P>
<P>
   With the public clamoring for more security in advance of
municipal elections scheduled for October, the government has been
under mounting pressure to act to curb rising crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso rejected, however, a much-discussed plan that would have
used the military in crime-fighting activities.
</P>
<P>
   That step had been urged on him by some of the parties making up
his governing coalition, but is highly controversial in a country
that retains bitter memories of a 21-year military dictatorship
that ended in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The new security measures were announced a week after a gunman
who appeared to be under the influence of drugs hijacked a city bus
here and held six passengers hostage for four and a half hours. The
episode, which was broadcast live on national television and has
dominated news coverage ever since, ended when the hijacker, using
one of his captives as a shield, stepped off the bus and was
immediately fired upon by the police.
</P>
<P>
   The hostage, a 20-year-old schoolteacher, was struck by a police
bullet and died in the ensuing exchange of gunfire. The hijacker
survived, but the police who accompanied him in an ambulance
strangled him on the way to the hospital and, according to official
accounts, threatened violence against the doctors who insisted on
listing asphyxiation as the cause of his death.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a sharp outburst of anger and disgust, both
with rising crime rates and the brutality and ineptness of the
police.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cardoso has led the attacks, saying the way the police handled
the hijacking was ``totally unacceptable.'' The governor of the
state of Rio de Janeiro, Anthony Garotinho, fired the commander of
the military police and ordered that the policemen involved in the
strangulation be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The case took on added symbolism and importance when it emerged
that the hijacker of the bus, Sandro do Nascimento, 21, was a
survivor of the notorious ``Candelaria massacre'' here, a 1993
incident in which military policemen sprayed gunfire at 72
abandoned street children who were sleeping on the sidewalk in
front of the city's most famous church.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of concerns about public safety were demonstrated by
a poll published Sunday in the newspaper O Globo, indicating that
81 percent of families here have at least one member who has been
the victim of a crime. But 72 percent of those surveyed also said
they have no confidence in the police as an institution, and 59
percent described the performance of the police as ``bad or
dreadful.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the government plan announced Tuesday also calls
for the hiring of 2,000 new federal police officers. That step is
necessary, Cardoso said in his speech, because ``society is
demanding a quicker response from all of us'' to combat crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
