<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-HEARTLAND-PABAR21-COX     06-20 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARTLAND-PABAR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Votes up for grabs in the optimistic Lehigh Valley
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALLENTOWN, Pa. _ On successive blocks off Hamilton Mall Road,
worn row houses still project the image of a working class
neighborhood in decay. The Allentown of the Billy Joel song back in
1982. A place still best defined by the absence of something, which
in this case would be the absence of Big Steel.
</P>
<P>
   But what a few dismal vistas fail to reveal is that a sense of
optimism now beams through Allentown and neighboring Bethlehem,
twin anchors in a two-county region northwest of Philadelphia known
as the Lehigh Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In Lehigh and Northampton counties, unemployment is baseboard
low, and job growth is ahead of the state average. Incomes have
risen. Education levels are climbing. This cradle of industrial
innovation and might, where steel was forged to build the Golden
Gate Bridge and great chunks of the New York skyline, is in the
midst of a rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are definitely seeing the glass as half full now,''
said John G. Englesson, a Bethlehem businessman. ``Our best times
are ahead of us, absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   But presidential politics in the new prosperity lack that kind
of barging certainty. Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George
W. Bush will vie for voters here, but no one is sure who'll win.
Gore the Democrat may or may not get credit for the rosy economy
that has propelled the Lehigh Valley's revival, and Bush the
Republican may or may not benefit from the political weakening of
labor unions whose industrial jobs have waned.
</P>
<P>
   In a state composed of so many potent political fragments, the
Lehigh Valley, particularly in its current state of economic
transition, represents the obstacle course of Keystone State
politics as well as any region possibly could.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lehigh Valley isn't significantly influenced by any one
thing, it's a real swing area,'' said Pat Meehan a district
attorney in a Philadelphia suburb who worked on statewide campaigns
for both Republican Senators Rick Santorum and Arlen Spector.
``Everything we have in Pennsylvania, you'll find in the Lehigh
Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   What you find today, first and foremost, is the sense that life
here is good. And getting better. After decades of watching its
industrial economy shrink, the Lehigh Valley of the 21st Century is
pulling itself up with bootstraps sewn not from leather, but from
fiber optic cable. The result is a work force shifting from
blue-collar to white, changing local views on things, such as free
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when votes for NAFTA and normal trade
relations with China might not have gone well for you here,'' said
Pennsylvania State Sen. Charles W. Dent, ``but today there's no
substantial penalty for that.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, too, when Bethlehem Steel Corp., was a primary
employer. Today, the leading manufacturer in the region is
high-tech giant Lucent Technologies, Inc., whose 5,300 workers in
Allentown produce electronic communication devices and circuits.
Lucent, and the many smaller high-tech start-ups in the Valley,
don't fret over export quotas, they thirst for overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sandy McNamara, 47, whose husband recently was laid off
from his job as a warehouse manager, feels confident he won't be
out of work long. That wasn't the case five years ago, when the
McNamaras and their two teen-age daughters moved to nearby
Coopersburg following a layoff in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so different from where we were,'' she said. ``Homes are
being built on every piece of flat land they can find around here.
And sometimes, the not flat land. We're hopeful for work because
there's just so much here.''
</P>
<P>
   But McNamara is undecided in the presidential race, which she
hasn't spent much time thinking about yet. If there's an issue on
her mind, it's guns. She worries about the safety of her school-age
children, who now are required to use see-through book bags. But
new gun laws aren't the answer for McNamara. She'd rather see a
change in social climate that helps children understand human
values, she just doesn't know which candidate is best suited to the
task.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to vote today,'' she said, ``I really don't know what
I'd do.''
</P>
<P>
   As is true in Pennsylvania as a whole, Democrats outnumber
Republicans in the Lehigh Valley. But crossover voting is common
and, often, decisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's up for grabs here. Times are good in our
valley,'' said Frank Colon, a professor of political science at
Lehigh University. ``Lehigh Valley has put its emphasis on becoming
another Silicon Valley and it's moving in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Today in the Lehigh Valley, a significant part of labor's
sustaining force resides in its retirees. With Pennsylvania's
generous senior citizen benefits, which are funded through the
state lottery and include free public transportation and subsidized
telephone service, many blue-collar workers have stayed long after
their jobs disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The steelworkers and the truck drivers just stayed here, they
didn't go to Florida,'' Colon said. ``They create a force, but in a
way they're kind of a single-issue force.''
</P>
<P>
   That issue has little to do with the color of the collar.
Retirees in the Lehigh Valley are focused primarily on the
condition and the future of Social Security, Colon said.
</P>
<P>
   That's what worries Gil Robertson, who at 70 is retired from a
career with a utility company where he worked as a mechanical
engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't settled on what they're going to do with Social
Security,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson and his wife, Agnes, have lived in the Lehigh Valley
for 24 years. Both are Republicans. But Gil Robertson is the type
of Republican who thinks ``the rich are rich enough,'' Bush should
forget about allowing people to invest their own Social Security
funds and the budget surplus should be used to pay off the national
debt.
</P>
<P>
   But the Robertsons don't know where that leaves them in the
choice between Bush and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult because I don't see myself voting for
Gore,'' Mrs. Robertson said, ``but on the other hand Bush hasn't
impressed me too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
