<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9797 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-BIO-COLLEGE-ART-     06-20 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BIO-COLLEGE-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S COLLEGE MEMORIES SEARED BY THE ANGUISH OF VIETNAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: An abridged version is also moving; for a repeat of GORE-BIO,
which moved May 21, phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT13-17 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore arrived at Harvard in the fall of 1965 so sure of
himself and his place in the world that he hadn't even bothered
applying anywhere else. ``I had the idea it was the best,'' he said
simply, in one of several interviews about his college years. ``I
knew President Kennedy had gone there.''
</P>
<P>
   By his second day on campus, the 17-year-old Gore was out
knocking on doors, starting a successful campaign to become
president of the freshman council. In those days, coats and ties
were required at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Yet all of this genteel tradition, and much of what Gore had in
mind when he signed up for Jack Kennedy's Harvard, was on the way
out even then. Vietnam was not a world away any more; American
involvement in the war was escalating constantly.
</P>
<P>
   In Al Gore's sophomore year, Defense Secretary Robert McNamara
visited the university to give a speech and was mobbed by screaming
students who climbed atop his car and rocked it while he sat
inside. During Gore's junior year, protesters organized by the
Students for a Democratic Society held a recruiter for Dow, the
maker of napalm, in a classroom for five hours. And in his last
semester, demonstrators took over the school's main administration
building, University Hall, only to be forced out at dawn the next
day by local and state police swinging clubs and wearing riot
helmets.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly four years after he had first arrived, the recently
graduated, recently enlisted Private Gore returned to campus in
short hair and an Army uniform _ an inherently provocative act in
militantly anti-military Cambridge in September 1969. Students in
Harvard Yard jeered at the sight of him.
</P>
<P>
   That moment, the moment he truly left Harvard behind, remains
alive for the vice president across the decades: ``It was an
amazing experience, a Ralph Ellison experience in that I was the
same person inside but my physical appearance conveyed a message
that completely overwhelmed the message of my humanity. It was just
an emotional field of negativity and disapproval and piercing
glances that shot arrows of what certainly felt like real hatred,
and I was astonished. I mean, it was no big deal in the sense that
I didn't suffer as a result of it at all, but it was really
educational. Really educational.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, both the snapshot of that kid in uniform, looking
more surprised than he probably should have been, and the vice
president's take on it, more than 30 years later, explain a few
things about Al Gore. There he was, going off to fight in a war he
hated and didn't believe in, after a solid year of agonizing, which
everyone who knew him then believes could only have ended exactly
as it did.
</P>
<P>
   He had said a lot of conflicting, conflicted things to his
friends, as 21-year-olds do. Sometimes, he muttered about Canada
and how different things might be if his father were not a U.S.
senator. But the conclusion, obvious to others long before he
reconciled himself to going to the war, was that he could never
seem to stop thinking about the boys his age back in Tennessee,
where he was registered for the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The kids he had spent summers with did not have the options that
he and his Harvard friends had. The guys who had worked alongside
him cutting tobacco on the family farm weren't thinking, Hmm, body
bag or divinity school? And he kept coming back to that. ``He said
that if he found a fancy way of not going, someone else would have
to go in his place,'' remembered his college pal, the actor Tommy
Lee Jones.
</P>
<P>
   This rings especially true in light of Gore's rigorous
upbringing, a childhood in which adult notions of responsibility
were constantly reinforced by his hard-working parents. It seems
unlikely that their ultra-dependable only son, who carried their
hopes and was made so responsible for their happiness, would ever
have let someone else go to war in his place.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it in him to disappoint his parents, who apparently
expected him to serve despite their own anti-war feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's senior thesis adviser at Harvard, the presidential
scholar Richard Neustadt, is pretty sure he told young Al that
serving would preserve the possibility of a career in politics.
That's certainly the career both his mother and father wanted for
him.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore told friends then that it was, perversely, in going to
war that he could probably best support the anti-war movement _ by
helping his father, Sen. Albert Gore, of Tennessee, get re-elected.
The senator's stand against the war was wildly unpopular in the
Volunteer State, and if his son had stayed home, he would have
handed a campaign issue to his father's opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Gore seems to have believed all along that his
father would lose in 1970 - and he did lose. Nonetheless, the young
man felt obligated to do whatever he could to help, and as he
marched off to join the service seemed to feel he was sacrificing
himself to two lost causes, in Vietnam and in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the final decision appears to have hinged more on Gore's
sense of himself as a Tennesseean _ and as the moral man his
parents had constantly prodded him to be. In the end, he was one of
only about a dozen of his classmates who served in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember so clearly him saying he was going to have to do it
the way his fathers' constituents did it, as an enlisted man,''
said Neustadt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd spent enough time in Tennessee to understand morality as
it applied locally, and it was a moral, not a political judgment
that if the regular folk have to enlist, I do, too. Certainly no
other Harvard kid I knew who thought he might want to get into
politics did that. All the ones that talked to me came to the
conclusion that they had to serve, but they were quite happy to
serve as officers.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When Gore returned to campus in his uniform, to say good-bye to
some professors, he never dreamed that others would fail to see
this, and would somehow miss that he was really one of them in
disguise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't'' see the negative reaction coming, he said in
a recent interview. ``That did not occur to me. It's one of those
things that's hard to see from the inside. It was just, `I am
myself and here I come. I know this place well.'''
</P>
<P>
   And there is much that is instantly recognizable in that picture
of Al Gore at the end of his college days. He is a man who in the
end probably chose the harder of two hard roads. But someone who
also seems to have made that road harder than it had to be.
</P>
<P>
   As Jones put it, ``It wasn't any fun to have the war in Vietnam
weighing heavily on one's mind, but fun was possible, and it's fun
to be 21 if you've got any brains at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, Gore put the earnest student government work of
planning mixers and lodging official protests about room cleaning
behind him. He and the friends he made in Mower B, his dorm in the
North Yard, pooled their record collections and listened to a lot
of Dylan, Motown, the Beatles, Buffalo Springfield. He played
poker, house football, and took up handball because his group
considered squash ``too Harvard.''
</P>
<P>
   He mostly warmed the bench for Harvard's basketball team that
year, too, averaging just under 3 points a game. And he was forever
challenging friends to all kinds of other competitions _ push-ups,
swimming the Charles River, beer chugging. Both Gore and Jones, who
grew up in Texas and lives there still, recall nearly killing an
elm tree near where they lived in a monthlong knife-throwing
contest, ``testing our ability in that backwoods skill,'' the vice
president said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that his father was a senator was not a big deal on
campus. ``One thing about that university is almost everybody has a
father'' of prominence or power, said Neustadt. ``They recede into
the distance. At another university it might have made more of a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   While others might have been running from their roots, Gore was
busy living through his, wearing bib overalls and subscribing to
the Carthage Courier, the paper from the small town in Tennessee
where his family had their farm.
</P>
<P>
   He hoped it might provide inspiration for the novel he was
trying to write, set back there, and populated with folks he had
known. ``It meandered like the Caney Fork River,'' Gore said
recently, spoofing his former literary aspirations. He spent hours
at the typewriter, not always productively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the day push-button phones came to Harvard,'' Jones
recalled. ``There he sat in his bib overalls and a gold ball cap _
Golden Acre Seeds, Carthage. There sat Li'l Abner. And what he'd
done is taught himself to play Dixie on the phone. Of course we
took it right away from him.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of their freshman year, Gore, Jones and a couple of
other friends got together a musical revue that they actually took
on the road _ for one performance, at a Wellesley coffeehouse. ``It
was kind of like the Little Rascals: `Let's put on a show!''' said
Michael Kapetan, now a sculptor at the University of Michigan, who
remembers writing the handbill for the performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here at last, no longer coming soon,'' it said, ``the Old-Time
Country Panorama, featuring those old-time country musicians of
note, Tommy Lee Jones and the Ben Hill County Boys.''''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the stand-up comic,'' Gore said, ``if you can believe
that.'' And sure enough, there he is, billed as ``the highly
respected professor of animal husbandry and the curative sciences,
Doctor Albert A. Gore'' who ``has promised to favor us with
readings from the society pages of the Carthage Courier, including
news on Wilber Gridley's recent trip to Bristol.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore does not remember the show as an unqualified success: ``The
women of Wellesley were in between puzzled and amused,'' he said.
``Not quite the reaction we were shooting for.''
</P>
<P>
   He rode a motorcycle back to school from Washington in the rain
that same year, and gave friends high-speed rides around Boston.
``I didn't like to ride on his bike,'' said one of his friends,
John Tyson, now an international business consultant in Washington.
``He'd try to scare you, popping gears, going 65, 70 and
laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   One time, Gore, his future wife Tipper Aitcheson, Kapetan and
Kapetan's date were all riding on the motorcycle. Gore described it
as ``a modern day version of how many people can you fit in the
phone booth, ``with Tipper mainly on the handlebars and Michael
mainly on the tailpipe.'' When they noticed a police car behind
them, they sped into an alley, ditched the bike, and as Gore
remembers it, ``walked around with innocent looks on our faces.''
</P>
<P>
   As the world knows, he also smoked pot on occasion. But the only
time he has drawn the line at any question during a number of
interviews about his life was when prodded to tell an anecdote
about getting high. ``I hate to make light of it, I don't want to
encourage it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Friends do remember that he liked ``magic brownies'' and crashed
a few times on a couch in the basement of Dunster House, where a
group of his friends moved after their freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   He started out as an English major _ until, he says, Chaucer
nearly killed him _ and along with his novel, which he never
finished, he enjoyed writing poetry.
</P>
<P>
   He was always a reader, and Harvard nurtured the part of him
that is in love with the world of ideas _ promiscuously taken, in
fact, with scientific theories, mathematical concepts, great and
maybe not so great literature. Buckminster Fuller and Marshall
McLuhan turned his head in college. Later, he was enchanted by
chaos theory. These days, it's the debate about whether we're part
of a multiverse _ one of many universes competing in a Darwinian
struggle to reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   Also in college, he became a fan of ``Star Trek,'' adored the
movie ``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' and showed great enthusiasm for
astronomy, as he still does. ``It's one of the things he loves
about living at the Observatory,'' said his oldest daughter,
Karenna Gore Schiff, referring to Gore's official residence at the
U.S. Naval Observatory. ``At dinner parties, there's always a march
to the telescope, and it always seems like he's having the most
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His studies did not really engage Gore until his junior year at
Harvard, when he took Neustadt's course about presidential decision
making. When the class re-enacted President Kennedy's decisions
during the Cuban missile crisis, he took the lead role. He got his
first A's that year, after a string of C's - and even a D in
biology as a sophomore, which prompted one friend to joke that
having failed evolution, he was all set for a career in Tennessee
politics.
</P>
<P>
   But when energized, Gore did have quite a ride academically.
After taking Neustadt's course, he switched his major to government
and nagged his professor into giving him a private reading course,
as well as into overseeing his senior thesis on how TV was changing
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   From what he saw in class, Neustadt said, Gore ``is not afraid
of decisions, but not precipitous about it, either, like the early
Harry Truman saying, `How many decisions did I make today?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of the originality of his mind, I would probably have
called him a good group two student, not a group one student.'' But
Neustadt made clear that he was not one of the easiest graders on
campus: ``The brightest people I've seen in the White House were in
different ways Kennedy and Johnson, and neither of them was group
one, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as a throwaway, he added that ``as intelligences go''
among U.S. presidents of the last century, only ``Teddy Roosevelt
might have stood higher'' than Gore _ who, by the way, received an
A-minus in Neustadt's Government 154.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the challenge for George W. Bush is to prove his smarts,
Gore's is precisely the opposite _ to show that he is a regular guy
despite a perceived surplus of gravitas _ which at least some
Americans seem to find intimidating, boring, or, as he himself
worries, just weird.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thinks America wants an intellectual for a
president, Gore said, ``I don't think book smarts are necessarily
the highest qualification to lead so much as good values, good
judgment, and a willingness to fight for the right thing. These
things are all cartoon images anyway _ Truman was extremely
well-read, for example. But if you give people the impression
you're a smarty pants, that's no good for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   He is keenly sensitive, though, to just such impressions, and he
really does not like to talk about some of his more obscure
preoccupations.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in a conversation about some of the ``big think''
questions that intrigue him, he began to moan, ``I can't say this,
it's going to sound so weird.'' He went on that way for a minute,
as if he were about to admit to something really twisted, before he
finally revealed the big secret: ``Oh OK! I find the ideas in the
fractals, both as a body of knowledge and as a metaphor, an
incredibly important way of looking at the world.'' (Fractal
geometry, as everyone knows, examines the irregular patterns that
repeat and are similar at all size scales. In nature, an example is
a mountain range.)
</P>
<P>
   His appreciation of science really exploded in his senior year,
when Gore also got to know Roger Revelle, the oceanographer who did
much of the pioneering work on the greenhouse effect and global
warming _ a major focus of Gore's 1992 environmental tome, ``Earth
in the Balance.'' When Revelle shared his ongoing research with the
students, Gore was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like such a privilege to be able to hear about the
readouts from some of those measurements in a group of no more than
a dozen undergraduates,'' Gore said. ``Here was this teacher
presenting something not years old but fresh out of the lab, with
profound implications for our future!''
</P>
<P>
   He also took ``The Human Life Cycle,'' a course on the stages of
human development taught by the psychologist Erik Erikson, who
coined the phrase ``identity crisis'' and believed that identity,
rather than being fixed in childhood, depends in part on how well a
person deals with each stage of his adult life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just as influential as any of the others, but more in
personal terms,'' Gore said. For the course, Gore prepared a
``psychobiography'' of his father and learned, for example, that
his dad's older brother Reginald, who had been disabled in World
War I, had been the one expected to succeed. ``I gained a sense of
perspective on him that I'd needed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he had already found an important friend in Marty Peretz,
who had him in a seminar his freshman year, ``Problems of
Post-Industrial Society.'' Along with an introduction to Marx and
Freud, Gore got a booster who later bought The New Republic and has
tirelessly plugged his former pupil's presidential prospects
through the years. They bonded his senior year, as well, at a time
when Peretz, like Gore, was increasingly disenchanted with the
tactics of the left.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore himself says that everything he learned in the
classroom at Harvard from his quartet of famous mentors was dwarfed
by the education he got from Tipper Aitcheson in those first years
after they met at his senior prom at St. Albans in Washington. A
year younger than Gore, she joined him in Boston his sophomore
year, studying at Garland Junior College and then Boston
University.
</P>
<P>
   When he speaks of his wife today, it is with awe, gratitude and
an explicit acknowledgment that even his parents had a less
formative influence on him: ``It's clearly the most important
relationship I've ever had with anyone, bar none,'' he said
recently. ``Even at a young age she helped me understand things I
NEVER would have been able to understand otherwise. She has a way
of understanding people and the world that I, well, I would be a
completely and totally different person in every way except for
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, an interviewer mentioned having met with her earlier
the same day, and he beamed with pride: ``Isn't she cool?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore says he knew almost right away, even at the age of 17, that
he wanted to spend the rest of his life with this woman. That was
one thing, at least, that he knew when he arrived freshman year and
was even more sure of on graduation day.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So much else, though, seemed up for grabs. In his junior year,
says Tyson, who roomed with Gore that year, ``came the
rev-o-lu-tion. The war came into our living room with the body bag
count every day. Every day, religiously, our gurus were Walter
Cronkite and Eric Sevareid.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, who is black, and quit the football team because he no
longer wanted to be a ``hired gladiator'' for white alumni, said he
and Gore talked themselves to sleep in their bunk beds many nights
that year, endlessly discussing race and the war. Gore read ``Soul
on Ice'' and ``The Autobiography of Malcolm X'' and they discussed
the books, too.
</P>
<P>
   Then Martin Luther King, Jr. was shot during their spring break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was driving with Tipper from Boston to Washington and it
happened when we were on the road,'' Gore remembered. ``It was
devastating. When we arrived, my mother was downtown at an auction
house and needed a ride home because the rioting had started. I
don't think I ever saw her scared, but as I drove up, stores on
either side were having glass fronts crushed in and there was
looting. She walked rather calmly but quickly as I drove up.''
</P>
<P>
   The first night the roommates were together again, Tyson said,
he and Gore both cried for their country and stayed up until 4 a.m.
talking. ``He was so upset because it had happened in Tennessee. I
just wanted to curse,'' Tyson said. ``It was very, very sad and we
were sick from watching our nation burn up. You didn't want to
believe what you were seeing and what had happened. How were we
going to stay together as a people?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very analytical and was saying in times of great cultural
change there is great chaos. But I also remember him saying,
`Jesus, we've got to understand who we are as a people and we
don't, and we haven't formed that e pluribus unum.' We both felt
that things had gotten so out of hand that his could happen in our
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spent some of that tense summer in Memphis, where the
shooting had occurred, while taking a course in Tennessee history
at Memphis State _ probably on some level in preparation for a
career in politics, though at the time he felt completely
disillusioned. Unsure what he wanted to do, he was thinking about
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   That summer, too, Gore helped his father write a short speech
for the 1968 Democratic Convention in Chicago, where he stayed with
his parents while other kids his age were fighting with police in
Grant Park. Inside the hall, both Gores shared the demonstrators'
bitterness over the war: ``Four years ago our party and the nominee
of our party promised the people that American boys would not be
sent to fight in a land war in Asia,'' Senator Gore told the
convention, to huge applause from supporters of Eugene McCarthy,
the anti-war candidate, who had been denied the nomination in favor
of Vice President Hubert Humphrey. ``They voted for our
distinguished leader, President Lyndon B. Johnson, but they got the
policies of Senator Goldwater.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, back at school in the fall, Gore and most of his friends
continued to shy away from various protest groups. ``We weren't
demonstrators,'' Tyson said. ``We distrusted these movements a lot
because a lot of this stuff was very emotional and not well thought
out. We were a pretty traditional bunch of guys, positive for civil
rights and women's rights but formal, transformed by the social
revolution to some extent but not buying into something we
considered detrimental to our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore himself recalls that while he agreed with their anti-war
sentiments, he found students who were protesting the presence of
ROTC on campus wrong-headed and even kind of juvenile. He thought
taking anger about the war out on the university was plain
illogical. ``It seemed silly to me to target the administration of
a private university,'' he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Though in a letter home he railed against the ``national
madness'' of anti-communism, he mostly disagreed with both the
tactics and rhetoric of the Students for a Democratic Society.
</P>
<P>
   And one thing he has in common with his opponent, Bush, who
experienced the '60s very differently, is that he was never
seriously tempted by anti-establishment politics. Both stuck close
to their father's view of the war, though those views were of
course quite different.
</P>
<P>
   Gore not only did not hate the establishment, but revered it. He
had been raised by a New Dealer who believed in nothing so much as
the power of government to change people's lives for the better,
and when the government disappointed him _ ``when America
uncharacteristically lost its way,'' as he puts it now _ he felt
deeply hurt, and declared that he wanted nothing to do with his
father's line of work.
</P>
<P>
   In his senior year, when police moved in and beat a number of
the students occupying University Hall, Jones remembers Gore's
reaction as ``the same reaction all Harvard people had, that
suddenly all this talk about the fascist threat was real. On that
day, we joined the ranks of paranoids who have people after them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody stayed away from the SDS'' entirely, Jones said. ``Jean
Paul Sartre's metaphor of words as bullets comes to mind, and
bullets were flying everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Cambridge in the late '60s, a refusal to fully join in
the revolution was itself a kind of rebellion. Peretz remembers
that Gore ``called attention to himself by the moderation of his
views. It took a kind of defiance to say, `Let's not get carried
away.'''
</P>
<P>
   Peretz's principal memory of his former student on June 12,
1969, the day Gore graduated, with honors, was that he seemed quite
embarrassed by his father's bragging about him. As part of a
planned protest, a number of Gore's classmates raised their fists
and walked out half-way through the ceremonies. Gore stayed in his
seat.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Gore did end up staging a one-man protest of sorts
when he showed up in his uniform in Harvard Yard a few months
later. That day, he was angry at the self-righteousness of kids who
thought all decisions about the war were easy. And finally, in
spite of himself, Al Gore was demonstrating after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
