<HEADER>
A9801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-ROYALTY-BIRTH     06-20 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ROYALTY-BIRTHDAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PRINCE WILLIAM, A REGAL BUT GUARDED COMING OF AGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Windsor Journal) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, England _ Five royal birthdays are to be feted at a
gala given by Queen Elizabeth II at Windsor Castle on Wednesday
night, but the celebrator who is the hope for continuing
generations of the beleaguered British monarchy will be marking his
18 years less ceremoniously.
</P>
<P>
   Final exam studies will keep Prince William in his Eton
dormitory room, a 10-minute walk from the largest joint royal
birthday party in memory. But his absence will hardly keep him and
his official passing into adulthood from being the center of
royal-watching attention.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when opinion surveys show enthusiasm for the reigning
Windsors at an all-time low, the handsome 6-foot-2-inch prince with
the shock of blond hair, cobalt blue eyes and downward-looking
smile so reminiscent of his mother, Diana, is coming onto the scene
as the family's best face forward.
</P>
<P>
   The black-tie event in the banquet hall beneath the crenelated
towers of the hilltop castle formally celebrates the birthdays of
the Queen Mother, 100 on Aug. 4; Princess Margaret, 70 on Aug. 21;
Princess Anne, 50 on Aug. 15; Prince Andrew, 40 last Feb. 19; and
William, 18 on Wednesday. The queen's 74th birthday also figured in
this festive week, since the sovereign's official birthday was
changed a century ago to a June date in hope of getting better
weather for the commemorative trooping of the color in Horse Guards
Parade in London _ with more than 1,200 marching soldiers in
scarlet tunics, the biggest ceremonial display on the royal
calendar. It took place Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But aware that all interest centers on the coming of age of the
winsome young prince destined to become king of England _ after his
father, Prince Charles _ and eager to ensure that his privacy not
be trespassed on, the press office of his father arranged the
release of 14 photos, a short television film and an anodyne
interview with Britain's domestic news agency, The Press
Association. Though he has long shied away from self-promotion,
William finds himself in the position of being the best marketing
opportunity now available to the family that calls itself The Firm.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio, shot over six weeks last winter and personally
approved by William, shows him dribbling a soccer ball on the
famous playing fields of Eton, strolling moodily through the
school's chapel cloisters, bobbing out of a pool in a water polo
match, adjusting the flame under a skillet in a cookery class,
surfing the Internet in a classmate's room, looking boy-band cute
in a black turtleneck sweater, and checking the attendance of an
arriving lower form boy as a member of the exclusive senior class
prefect society known as Pop.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, there are no pictures of him pursuing his interest in
hunting, shooting and military matters, no shots of him in the
uniform of the Combined Cadet Force, which he took part in for
years.
</P>
<P>
   The television film, shown over the weekend, contains the first
recorded utterance of the second-in-line for the British throne
when he is asked an offstage question about what he is cooking.
Historians note. The words are, ``Paella with chicken, rice, garlic
and beans.''
</P>
<P>
   In the question-and-answer interview, he discloses his
irritation with overweening show business agents who try to draw
attention to their clients by fantasizing romances with William.
``There's been a lot of nonsense put about by PR companies,'' he
says. ``I don't like being exploited in this way, but, as I get
older, it's increasingly hard to prevent.''
</P>
<P>
   William, a B-plus student with a busy extracurricular life, says
throughout the interview that he has liked his five years at Eton,
a marked departure from the experience of his father, who once
called Gordonstoun, his spartan Scottish school, ``Colditz in
kilts.''
</P>
<P>
   William intends to have his own party in 10 days at a local
bistro, but Charles had to limit his 18th birthday celebration to
inviting seven friends in for cakes and buns.
</P>
<P>
   On turning 18, William would normally be called His Royal
Highness, be addressed as sir and be greeted with bows and
curtsies, but the queen and his father have agreed to a request
from him that those practices be postponed until he is finished
with college.
</P>
<P>
   William is to take a traditional British ``gap year'' off for
as-yet-unannounced world travels before going to college, where he
intends to major in history of art. The schools that interest him
do not include Oxford or Cambridge, his father's alma mater. He is
expected to choose between two Scottish universities, Edinburgh and
St. Andrews, and three English ones, Bristol, Durham and East
Anglia.
</P>
<P>
   William's carefully managed emergence this week will be
short-lived. Prince Charles has asked the press to continue to
abide by the rules it adopted after the death of Diana in August
1997, under which William and his brother, Harry, 15, can be
photographed only at arranged occasions, usually with their father.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
