<P>
   BRITAIN-ROYALTY-BIRTHDAYS (Windsor, England) _ Five royal
birthdays are to be feted at a gala given by Queen Elizabeth II at
Windsor Castle on Wednesday night, but the celebrator who is the
hope for continuing generations of the beleaguered British monarchy
will be marking his 18 years less ceremoniously. Final exam studies
will keep Prince William in his Eton dormitory room, a 10-minute
walk from the largest joint royal birthday party in memory. But his
absence will hardly keep him and his official passing into
adulthood from being the center of royal-watching attention. A
journal by Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-U.N. (United Nations) _ Sudan wants to join a growing list
of pariah nations trying to create new international images for
themselves by engaging more positively with the world, the Sudanese
ambassador to the United Nations said Tuesday. Sudan's immediate
goals are ambitious. It is seeking African support for a regional
seat on the Security Council beginning next year. It is also lining
up international backing for a lifting of sanctions imposed four
years ago when Sudan was accused of harboring suspects in the
attempted assassination of President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt. Both
intentions present problems for the United States. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-CRIME (Rio de Janeiro, Brazil) _ Faced with growing
public alarm at a wave of crime, the Brazilian government decreed
an immediate ban today on the sale of firearms. The move came as as
part of a broader, $1.7 billion ``National Security Plan'' intended
to reduce urban violence and reform the police over the next three
years. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MASS-MOTHERS (Boston) _ At first, it seemed that it might be a
statistical blip. But no, public health officials said Tuesday, it
is a definite and striking trend: Massachusetts, they believe, has
become the first state where more babies are born to women over the
age of 30 than under it. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-CONDOS (Vail, Colo) _ The view from The Lodge at Lionshead
is to die for. Gore Creek babbles along noisily, just beyond
soaring pine trees that seem to reach halfway up the mountains in
the distance. ``You can even see the ski slopes,'' said Marilyn
Dyer, owner of Unit 1 and president of the Lodge homeowners
association, who splits the year between here and Denver. But not
all is as peaceful and serene as it appears outside the back
windows of Ms. Dyer's stylish 3-bedroom, 3-bath condominium. The
Lodge, which was built in 1978, is smack in the middle of a
proposed major development project that town officials argue is
critical for Vail's on-going economic stability. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
