   SAATCHI-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Six years after Maurice Saatchi
left Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, there's a new Maurice in charge, only this
time the name is pronounced the French way rather than the British.
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, the London agency company founded by Maurice
Saatchi and his brother, Charles, agreed Tuesday to be acquired by
a Paris-based rival, Publicis SA, for about $1.9 billion in stock.
Maurice Levy, the chairman and chief executive of Publicis, who is
proving to be almost as acquisitive as the Saatchis, will head a
merged entity, the Publicis Groupe, which will oversee the agencies
now under the Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi and Publicis banners. Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi, which has seesawed from successes to struggles and back
over almost three decades, will continue as an autonomous unit of
Publicis Groupe rather than as an independent company. By Stuart
Elliott.
