<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9811 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-FRAMINGHAM-     06-20 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FRAMINGHAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOSE HEART DATA? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 52 years, medicine has learned much of what it knows about
preventing heart disease and strokes from a long-term study of
10,000 Framingham residents and their descendants. More than 1,000
research works have been based on the examinations, food diaries,
X-rays, and blood samples that the study's participants contributed
for the good of science.
</P>
<P>
   Now, thanks to new techniques of analyzing data and identifying
errant genes, it is possible to take this wealth of information to
a new level with enormous potential benefits for the biotechnology
and pharmaceutical industries _ and for all of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   However, the National Heart, Blood, and Lung Institute, which
has responsibility for the Framingham Heart Study, should be very
cautious in establishing ground rules for use of the study's data
and tissue samples by profit-making firms. The subject is raised by
the proposal from a new company, Framingham Genomics Medicine,
which wants to digitize raw data and correlate the DNA makeup of
blood samples with the study's abundant clinical information. Its
plan is then to sell this enhanced data to biotech and
pharmaceutical firms.
</P>
<P>
   One big hitch is the conflict of interest issue raised by FGM's
parentage. It will be one-fifth owned by Boston University, which
for three decades has been supervising the heart study under
agreements with the National Heart, Blood, and Lung Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the institute, Dr. Claude Lenfant, has said he
wants assurances that no BU study workers would have any financial
interest in the new company. He has also said any arrangement with
the company would specify that it would not have exclusive access
to the study data or blood samples.
</P>
<P>
   But if, for instance, a rival of FGM stepped forward to do
similar work on heart study data, would it really have equal
access? And what if a university or nonprofit research institute
asked to do such work with the intention of making all its results
publicly available, thus undercutting FGM's business plan? Any
promises that all comers would face a level playing field have to
be weighed against the fact that outside researchers already
complain about restricted access to the data.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern of Lenfant is that, until now, outside
researchers who use the heart study's data have been expected to
contribute any new findings back to the study's body of
information. This is not likely to sit well with a company seeking
to sell its results to drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important issue may be the effect of FGM's plan on
the Framingham participants in the study. It would be a terrible
squandering of a medical resource if the new venture gets in the
way of recruiting third-generation family members into the study or
causes any long-term participants to quit. Decades ago,
participants consented to help out in a publicly funded
heart-disease project that did not even envision the use of
genotyping. Now, a company wants to make commercial use of the
deepest secrets of their genetic being, for purposes that could be
as trivial as exploring perfume allergies.
</P>
<P>
   Boston University officials say that just two study participants
have responded to a letter informing them of the new plans by
asking that their data not be included. But more needs to be done:
The company should contact all the living study participants and
relatives of the deceased for genuinely informed consent. The
inclusion of genetic information in the company's work also argues
for the most effective possible measures to maintain the anonymity
of all study participants.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, BU is already talking about setting aside some of
the new company's stock for a public-interest foundation in
Framingham to ensure that the community benefits from FGM's
profits. And BU promises the company would be willing to fund an
outside ethics advisory council to make sure all guidelines are
followed.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, the editors of The Merck Manual, a medical
reference book, compiled a list of the 10 top medical advances of
the 20th century and placed the Framingham Heart Study fourth,
behind infectious disease control, immunization, and vitamins but
ahead of molecular genetics and organ transplantation. It is the
gold standard of health studies of its kind. Nothing should be done
to jeopardize its continuing value in the understandable desire to
learn even more about diseases and their causes from the study's
rich resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9813 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OPEC-GAS-PRICES-NYT &LR;      06-20 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-GAS-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPECTED OPEC INCREASE IN PRODUCTION UNLIKELY TO AFFECT U.S.
PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OPEC ministers meeting Wednesday in Vienna are expected to agree
on a modest production increase, but the move is unlikely to bring
much relief to American gasoline consumers, who are paying more
than $2 a gallon in some regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If U.S. consumers are looking to the OPEC meeting as some kind
of salvation from gas prices this summer, they will be very
disappointed,'' said Raad Alkadiri, an analyst with the Petroleum
Finance Corp., a consulting group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Oil ministers arriving for their meeting in Vienna on Wednesday
said they were confident they would reach an agreement quickly, and
a consensus appears to have formed around an increase of 500,000
barrels a day, or about 2 percent of current output. Such an
increase has the support not only of Saudi Arabia, the most
influential OPEC member, but also the support of Iran, which
angrily rebelled at a production increase three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the ministers of Algeria and Qatar said in preparing for the
Vienna meeting that there was no shortage of oil in the world,
apparently suggesting that raising output by that much is not
necessary. Oil prices, which have surged in recent weeks, rose
further on the conflicting messages.
</P>
<P>
   In the oil supply-and-demand balance, most people have focused
on the supply side ever since crude prices began climbing last
year. Understandably so, because a decision by OPEC in early 1999
to cut supply led to a sharp rebound in oil prices, driving them to
more than $30 a barrel by this spring. In March, under heavy
pressure by the United States and other industrialized countries
that import petroleum, OPEC decided to increase production by 1.7
million barrels a day or about 7 percent, to about 24.7 million
barrels a day. Crude prices initially dipped, only to surpass the
$30 mark once again in the last few weeks, despite estimates by
many analysts that OPEC already is pumping about 500,000 barrels
more than it had agreed upon three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, average U.S. gasoline prices have risen
sharply, up nearly 13 percent since late April, according to the
Department of Energy. They show no sign of easing just as summer
driving season is starting.
</P>
<P>
   In the Great Lakes region, where gasoline costs more than $2 a
gallon, consumer anger has led to federal inquiries into possible
price gouging by area refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Even at such levels, gasoline prices adjusted for inflation are
still lower than they were for most of the century up to 1968,
according to a recent study by industry analysts Cambridge Energy
Research Associates. ``But this is a price that people very easily
get very angry about,'' said Daniel Yergin, chairman of Cambridge
Energy, ``partly because for the last couple of years it's been so
low.''
</P>
<P>
   OPEC leaders such as the Saudis have intimated that they, like
much of the rest of the world, are uncomfortable with current high
crude prices. If prices stayed above $30 for a long time, they
could hurt the economies of affluent oil consuming countries and
even lead to a recession, which would hurt OPEC as much as anyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   But any OPEC increase in output would deal only with the supply
side of the equation. Worldwide demand for oil, driven by the
robust American economy and strengthening recoveries in Asia and
Europe, continues only to grow and quickly absorbs OPEC supply
increases.
</P>
<P>
   For example, U.S. refineries that distill crude, the first step
to making gasoline, are operating at 94 percent of capacity, which
is considered high. And despite persistent complaints about
inflationary gasoline prices, Americans have yet to curtail their
driving, the American Automobile Association has reported.
</P>
<P>
   The relentless demand for petroleum in the United States may, in
fact, be one of the main reasons why crude prices have risen.
``There's this strange dynamic of U.S. gas prices affecting world
oil prices, when it usually was the other way around,'' Yergin
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago area, where gasoline has risen to $2.50 a gallon at
some stations in recent days, illustrates how prices and crude oil
production are not directly related.
</P>
<P>
   The stage for the run-up was set in late winter, when refineries
typically acquire crude to meet high gasoline demand over the
summer. A heating oil crisis compelled some U.S. refineries to keep
producing heating oil rather than shifting to gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   While crude was expensive at the time, prices in the market for
oil to be delivered in later months was decreasing. So rather than
replenishing their inventories at the higher prices, many
refineries bought crude for delivery later at the lower prices, in
something of a ``just-in-time'' basis. Consequently, inventories of
gasoline are now unusually low across the country, with stocks in
the week ending June 9 totaling 202.7 million gallons, compared
with 223.5 million last year, according to the American Petroleum
Institute, an industry group.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on lower-than-usual inventories, Great Lakes refineries
now must produce a new re-formulated gasoline that burns cleaner in
adherence with the latest Environmental Protection Agency
regulations. Because of how this gasoline is made, refineries
produce less of it than they do of conventional gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline supplies in the Great Lakes fell even lower when a
pipeline that feeds the region's refineries oil from the Gulf Coast
broke down in the spring. That pipeline is still operating at only
80 percent capacity, according to the American Petroleum Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA contends that its requirements for re-formulated
gasoline do not contribute to higher fuel prices. But American
Automobile Association has asked the EPA to suspend reformulated
gasoline requirements for certain parts of the country, including
the Midwest, for most of the summer because the cleaner-burning
fuel costs so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Re-formulated gasoline is a premium product and tighter
requirements mean it will be more expensive,'' said George Beranek,
an expert on refining at the Petroleum Finance Corp. ``You can't
mandate improvement and expect it to be free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1913EDT &QL; 
