<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9816 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OLDER-WORKERS-RETIRE-     06-20 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDER-WORKERS-RETIRE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVING AGE IS AN ASSET, NOT A LIABILITY
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mass., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT20-21 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GEOFFREY BREWER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Older employees don't work hard. They don't have the stamina of
their younger colleagues. They are overpaid and marking time before
they pack up for a life of golf or shuffleboard in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the misconceptions that vex people like Hank Merrill.
Two years ago, at age 58, Merrill lost his job as a sales manager
with Bank of America when the company was acquired by NationsBank.
Though he had more than enough money to retire, he wanted to keep
working. But he had no illusions about the job search that lay
ahead. ``I knew people are skeptical of hiring someone over 50,''
Merrill said. ``People assume you don't have drive and energy.''
One employer who rejected him essentially questioned his work
ethic, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one executive recruiter saw gold where other people
saw gray. Joel Harrison, a managing partner with the recruiting
firm DAK Associates in Conshohocken, Pa., said he was impressed
with Merrill's business connections and with his high energy. ``I
thought that this guy would outperform people 10 and 15 years
younger than him,'' Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Since DAK placed him as a West Coast regional vice
president at Nuveen Investments, the Chicago-based financial
services wholesaler, Merrill has become the company's top sales
representative in the country. And all his colleagues are at least
20 years younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hank has tons of credibility,'' said his boss, Michael Forstl,
38, a managing director at Nuveen headquarters. ``If you have been
in the business that long, you develop fantastic relationships in a
world that is very small.''
</P>
<P>
   The rejuvenation of Merrill's career holds a lesson for
employers in today's tight job market: Older folks can actually be
worth the extra money you have to pay them. They bring years of
experience and connections to the table, and they often surprise
their new bosses by showing nearly as much get-up-and-go as their
younger colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, they have demographics on their side. According to the
Census Bureau, the number of 20-to-34-year-olds in the United
States has declined by 6 million the last decade while the number
of people over 50 has increased by 12 million. In the next decade,
the census says, the number of people over 50 will increase by 21
million more by 2010, while the number of 20-to-34-year olds will
increase by only 4 million. ``There has simply been a shrinkage of
available young workers and an increase in older workers,'' said
Ken Dychtwald, a psychologist and author of ``Age Power: How the
21st Century Will Be Ruled by the New Old'' (Tarcher/Putnam, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, as Americans lead longer and healthier lives,
people are beginning to ask this fundamental question: ``What is
old?''
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number of companies are adjusting to the changing
dynamics of the job market by dipping deeper into the over-50 pool
of talent. DAK, a 10-person firm that specializes in recruiting
managers for financial services companies like New York Life,
Salomon Brothers Asset Management and J&AMP;W Seligman, says the
proportion of people it places who are in that age group has soared
to 20 percent today from just 5 percent a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a robust part of our business,'' said Daniel A.
Kreuter, the president and founder of DAK. ``It expands our
inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   Employer interest in older employees is particularly sharp in
the financial services industry because people over 50 control
two-thirds of the money invested in the stock market and like
dealing with people in their own age group, Dychtwald said. ``The
investment business will increasingly demand people who are
experienced and responsible and have a long track record,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but that does not mean that those same people won't
have to fight stereotypes, as even their advocates acknowledge.
``There's been a mindset that wholesaling is a young person's game,
that only 25-to-35-year-olds would want to sleep in hotels four
nights a week and work 75 hours a week,'' Kreuter said. ``Then when
they burn out at 40, you get the new crop in.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill seems determined to debunk the stereotypes. He travels
four or five days a week, meeting with up to five clients a day. He
routinely gets up at 5:30 a.m. and usually runs five miles before
work. He competes in triathlons, has run in marathons and rides his
mountain bike about 2,500 miles a year.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill's ``sheer stamina'' makes him effective, according to
Forstl. ``Success in this business comes from sweat, from getting
in front of as many brokers as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Older workers in other industries are thriving, too. Some, like
Hershel Sarbin, 75, have tried retirement and didn't like it. When
they seek to return to the world of work, they often find a welcome
mat waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Sarbin has actually retired twice, the first time in 1984 when
he was 59 and left his job as senior vice president of Ziff Corp.
in New York to dabble in teaching and consulting work. Alas, he
said: ``I felt instantly restless. I missed not being engaged in
critical business issues. I missed the phone calls. I missed the
action.''
</P>
<P>
   So, when a consulting client, Cowles Media, offered him the
position of chief executive in 1990, he grabbed it. At age 65,
Sarbin spearheaded a turnaround effort in which Cowles acquired or
started a host of magazines and newsletters and developed several
Internet properties. Within three years, the publishing company's
revenue had shot up by 300 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Sarbin tried retirement again. Again, he did some
consulting work; again, he felt a void in his life. So, in 1998, he
signed on as senior director with another consulting client, the
Peppers &AMP; Rogers Group, a marketing consulting firm in Stamford,
Conn. The firm was looking to develop online and print publishing
properties and saw Sarbin, who had more than 30 years of media
experience, as the right candidate. Sarbin now heads a 25-person
division that produces a print and online newsletter and a
magazine. Next month, he is scheduled to start an information
service that provides verbatim extracts online of marketing-related
books and articles.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and he gives up to 15 speeches a year on marketing topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not often that 75-year-old men are invited to sit down
and talk with 25-year-old dot-com experts and strategize about
where the market is going,'' Sarbin said. ``I don't have to seek
them out, they come to me. Why would I ever want to retire?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If he and others can refute the old-codger image with their
energy, they might find it harder to overcome potential employers'
reticence about paying them big salaries. Older wholesalers in the
financial services trade _ essentially, the people who sell
financial products to stockbrokers and financial advisers _ can
earn as much as $500,000 a year, while sellers under 30 may earn
less than $100,000. ``Wholesalers like me with a proven track
record are too expensive,'' said Robert Meitzer, 53, who was
recruited by DAK to work at Allmerica Financial Corp. in Worcester,
Mass., where he is now a senior vice president and a top seller.
</P>
<P>
   Like Merrill and Sarbin, Meitzer has more than 30 years of
experience in his industry. Like them, he could afford to retire
but loves working. And like them, he is a case study in the value
that old-timers can give to a company. Aside from the $340 million
in business he brought Allmerica last year, Meitzer acts as a
mentor to younger sellers, a contribution that can pay large, if
hard-to-measure, dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Oliver Tutt, 30, a fellow sales representative at
Allmerica who traveled frequently with Meitzer for three years and
eagerly soaked up the older man's insights. ``You face so much
rejection in this business, from brokers mistreating you to them
just forgetting about your appointments, that it's tough to keep
your sanity,'' Tutt said. ``Bob taught me to value myself and have
self-confidence and chalk bad meetings up to experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Meitzer believes the most important lesson he can teach the
younger generation _ many of whom have never gone through a
recession _ is to take the long view of markets. ``I remember the
bear market of 1971 to 1974, and learned that it's important to be
diversified across stocks,'' he said. ``I was able to see the
current market's volatility before it happened. I saw that the
bubble of the late 1990's was going to burst.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, some older people do fit the stereotypes associated
with them, and employers must evaluate job candidates carefully.
``There are certain things we look for,'' Kreuter of DAK said.
``People can get burnt out or cynical, and maybe not be open to new
strategies or ideas'' _ or to the latest Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   That goes for Merrill, the Nuveen employee who in most ways is a
star performer. He has had ``a hard time understanding our computer
system,'' said Forstl, his boss, and relies on his sales assistant
to gather information from the company's database.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill cheerfully acknowledges his shortcoming. ``We have a
system here that they like us to use, but I don't like it and don't
use it,'' he said. ``I have my own system.''
</P>
<P>
   But such drawbacks are relatively minor, Kreuter said. ``Good
people over 50 have wisdom and experience, and that's what matters
most,'' he said. ``Gray hair counts for something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
