<HEADER>
A9818 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BRITISH-COMIC-ALI-$AD     06-20 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-COMIC-ALI-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN LAUGHS, AND WONDERS AT WHOM IT'S REALLY LAUGHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday June 25)  
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Clad in his bright yellow athletic warm-up suit, Tommy
Hilfiger skull cap, sunglasses and dangling gold chains, the
British cult comic character Ali G conducted one of his trademark
hoax interviews on his hit late-night television program here with
Tony Benn, a longtime member of Parliament and ardent socialist,
completely straight-faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``These unemployed _ they just chillin' innit, man?'' he quizzed
a serious-looking Benn, who appeared thrown by his seemingly black
interviewer's unusual style of questioning and choice of clothing.
``Is goin' on strike jus' like 'avin' a sickie?''
</P>
<P>
   Without a hint of laughter, Ali G probed further. ``Does welfare
not just encourage young girls to go out and get jiggy with
Biggy?''
</P>
<P>
   Benn was clearly not in on the joke, in part because he was the
punch line, and in part because the comedian who plays Ali G is not
a black product of the inner city; he is a white, Jewish graduate
of Cambridge University.
</P>
<P>
   But Ali G's audience ate up the segment, repeating bits from the
interview at pubs around town for weeks, making `` Biggy'' a
momentary pop-culture reference among the 20-something generation.
</P>
<P>
   The politician acknowledged after the prank interview that he
never realized he was being duped.
</P>
<P>
   Benn has not been the only one to fall for the tongue-in-cheek
antics of Ali G, who has become the television icon of the moment
here. A long line of well-known politicians and academics have been
suckered. On a trip to the United States, Ali G asked an
unsuspecting Gen. Alexander M. Haig Jr., the former secretary of
state, ``Is it true that Reagan and Thatcher was doin' it?'' He
followed up with, ``Do you t'ink it's worth nukin' Russia now,
while it's weak?''
</P>
<P>
   Played by 28-year-old Sacha Baron Cohen from North London, the
Ali G character tries to mock young, white, middle-class suburban
men who presume to act stereotypically black, as well as the way in
which an older generation reacts to them. His language is a
potpourri of American gangsta rap and the Indian and Caribbean
accents of the British working class. Cohen even created a
fictitious gang, laughingly called Staines Massive after the London
suburb of Staines, which, of course, is led by Ali G.
</P>
<P>
   The Ali G character has become a lightning rod for praise and
controversy, stirring the English to applaud Ali G, who represents
a new form of comedy that speaks to a younger generation, and at
the same time to condemn the character as another example of racism
that has sadly been accepted by a broad and impressionable
audience.
</P>
<P>
   The character was created two years ago for several segments on
a late-night comedy program called ``The 11 O'Clock Show'' on
Channel 4. The Ali G character, who duped unsuspecting public
figures into interviews under the pretense that he was the host of
a public affairs program for teen-agers, became so popular that an
entire weekly television series was built around the character
called ``Da Ali G Show'' by the same network. A home video of the
original Ali G segments has become a top seller in Britain, and
another video may be on its way.
</P>
<P>
   His shtick has hit such a nerve that Cohen is set to appear in
Madonna's next music video as Ali G and is working on a script for
the movie production company Working Title, which made ``Four
Weddings and a Funeral'' and ``Notting Hill,'' about making a movie
based on the Ali G character.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear whether Cohen's brand of humor can attract a
broad audience beyond Britain and whether it would be accepted
without protest elsewhere. While there have been reports here that
Talkback Productions, which produces ``Da Ali G Show,'' may try to
take the program across the Atlantic, it will almost surely receive
an onslaught of criticism from a multitude of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   Here in England, the Ali G character has come under attack in
some circles. Cohen has received death threats and is regularly
condemned in the press. ``The fact that he has been a success
should not be treated as an excuse to quash discussion about the
propriety of the act,'' a commentator wrote recently in the daily
newspaper The Guardian. ``If the black and white minstrels weren't
funny, then why is Ali G?''
</P>
<P>
   But Ali G's defenders say the act is less about poking fun at
minority stereotypes than mocking ignorant whites. ``He is about a
white kid pretending to be black,'' said a spokesman for Channel 4.
``He is satirizing the way white kids try to copy the black street
culture and look ridiculous. If it's offensive to anyone, it's
offensive to white people.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Thompson, co-creator and producer of ``Da Ali G Show,''
believes the Ali G character just follows the model of a long list
of comedians who have successfully inspired laughs through a bit of
racism in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as Alf Garnett became a hero to bad-tempered racists in
the 1960s, and Loadsamoney inspired London football fans to wave
wads of cash at their northern counterparts in the 1980s, so Ali
has become a cultural magnet for inarticulate youth in the
2000's,'' Thompson wrote in The Sunday Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perverse but welcome accolade for one of the most
brilliant comic talents that I've ever encountered.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen refused to be interviewed for this article. In fact, his
agent and production company were so worried that Cohen would
become recognizable in the United States because of media coverage
_ and therefore unable to successfully pull pranks on future
interview subjects _ that they refused to provide ``production''
photos of Ali G in full garb regularly handed out to British media
organizations, or allow photographs to be taken of him as Ali G.
(The picture that accompanies this article was obtained from a
photo agency.)
</P>
<P>
   But Ali G's cover may not be blown after all. In one of the
better-known segments, he is dragged away from an environmental
protest by a policeman. ``Is it because I's black?'' he says.
Without even a second glance, the officer replies, ``Not at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
