<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES TO BOLSTER HATE CRIMES LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate approved landmark civil rights
legislation Tuesday that would add sexual orientation, gender and
disability to the list of federal hate crimes, sending it to the
House where it faces an uncertain fate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, which passed 57 to 42, the FBI or other federal
law enforcement officials could assist local authorities in
investigating such hate crimes, expanding the list from those
motivated by race, religion or national origin. Thirteen
Republicans joined 44 Democrats in support of the measure, with
Sen. Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia the only Democrat voting
against it.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time since Kennedy's legislation was introduced
in 1997 that it has not died in a committee and supporters were
optimistic that recent high-profile crimes and this year's election
would give it the momentum needed to become law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the Senate acting at its best with one voice,'' said
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., the main sponsor of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The vote added the hate crimes measure as an amendment to a
defense bill that is being used as a vehicle for other legislative
items, including a campaign financing bill sought by Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, acting in his constitutional role as
president of the Senate, stood by to cast a tie-breaking vote in
the event it was needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because hate crimes are an affront to all Americans, this vote
is a sign of hope for all Americans,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   While current federal law deals with hate crimes that interfere
with federally protected activities, such as serving on a jury,
trying to vote or enrolling in school, Kennedy's bill would require
the Justice Department to prove only that the crimes interfered
with interstate commerce _ a broad criterion.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Richard Armey, R-Texas, said he did not
expect the House to consider the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see that happening,'' Armey said. ``We're for strict
law enforcement and stiff penalties for vicious crimes irrespective
of the motive.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy was optimistic it will become law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to make Armey eat his words,'' Kennedy said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   During an emotional floor debate on the bill, Kennedy called
hate crimes ``a national disgrace'' that ``attack everything that
this country stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We as a United States Congress must take a clear and
unequivocal stand,'' Kennedy said. ``Equal protection of the laws
ought to apply to all Americans. ... Hate crimes are rooted in
hatred and bigotry and if America is going to be America, we should
root out hatred and bigotry.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., the main Republican supporter of the
bill, said the federal government must prosecute those ``who commit
the most malignant of crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a Mormon, said he used to have ``feelings of religious
reluctance'' to vote against broadening hate crimes legislation to
include homosexuals. But he said he changed his mind after the
death of Matthew Shepard, a 21-year-old University of Wyoming
student who was beaten to death in October 1998 because he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that year, James Byrd, a 49-year-old black man, was
dragged to his death behind a pickup truck in Jasper, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also cited the biblical story in which a woman was nearly
stoned to death for committing adultery until Jesus stopped the
attack. ``Put down the stone and cast a vote based on love,'' Smith
urged his colleagues. ``Cast a vote against hatred and vote for the
Kennedy-Smith amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   An alternative amendment by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, that would
authorize a study of hate crimes, also passed 50 to 49.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is precious little evidence showing there is a
widespread problem with authorities prosecuting crimes against gays
or blacks or women,'' Hatch said before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch has said he is concerned that the Kennedy measure
infringes on state and local powers of law enforcement. Although 40
states have some sort of hate crime statutes, many are limited to
race or religion.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said approval of the legislation
on hate crimes sends an important moral message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It raises the awareness of people,'' Boxer said. ``Just
because you have a certain disability or sexual orientation you
aren't any less as a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Birch, executive director of the Human Rights
Campaign, a Washington-based advocacy group for homosexuals and
lesbians, was hopeful the bill would become law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's amazing what the need to moderate can do in an
election year and I think the Republicans need to do just that,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Winnie Stachelberg, political director of the Human Rights
Campaign, called the vote historic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a recognition on the part of the Senate that gays and
lesbians ought to be treated the same way as all other Americans
are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
