<HEADLINE>
SUMMER SOLSTICE BRINGS JOY TO EARTH WORSHIPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, N.H. _ Midway between dawn and darkness, as a searing sun
burst through the towering oak and maple trees and the seasons
silently shifted from spring to summer, neo-pagans, Wiccans and
earth-worshipers of all varieties gathered in an ancient meadow
here Tuesday to celebrate the summer solstice.
</P>
<P>
   Chanting haunting melodies in Yoruba, in English, and in no
language at all; wearing shells and feathers and masks and robes;
invoking the elements of earth, air, fire and water and making
offerings to a stone, participants said they hoped to connect with
nature and with each other as they marked a turning point on the
calendar and, perhaps, in their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   The summer solstice, the day on which the sun is at its
northernmost point in the sky, is the longest day of the year and
has long been an occasion for worship by a variety of ancient
faiths.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, as some Americans have left traditional Western
religions and sought to reclaim or reinvent earth-based faiths,
they have turned to occasions such as the solstice as natural
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being in nature -- I feel connected to the earth and it
makes me feel peaceful and alive and it humbles me,'' said Keo
Opton, 40, a personal trainer and a witch. ``I feel a great
connection with the earth and with people. I don't feel that in a
church.''
</P>
<P>
   The rituals performed here, as in many neo-pagan and wiccan
celebrations around the country, are a mix of Native American and
pagan traditions and new forms of pageantry. The celebrants here
have been perfecting their ritual for six years, choosing to come
here to Mystery Hill because it is home to a collection of stone
walls and large shaped stones that has been called America's
Stonehenge by those who believe that the site was built by Native
Americans or early European migrants 4,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, believe it is the remains of a colonial farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a way of marking transitions in life -- we can see
parallels between what's happening in nature and what's happening
in our personal lives, and we can remember who we are as natural
beings,'' said Katja Esser, the organizer of Tuesday's ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Esser, dressed as a bear wearing imitation fur robes and a
Native American-style mask, led more than 100 celebrants on a
procession through the woods, past chambers and through passageways
and tunnels, re-emerging int the light as they beat on drums and
sang, ``Mother, I feel your heart beat. Ooh wah ooh wah ooh wah.
Mother, I feel you under my feet. Ooh wah ooh wah ooh wah.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Johnson wafted burning sage over the marchers, who waved
banners and flags as the ululated, skipped, strode, swayed and
stood in alternating moments of silence, song and shouting around
an altar of sticks and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Klein, 21, had a medicine wheel branded into one side of his
chest and had two Native American-style tattoos representing the
earth and healing herbs on his shoulder and on the other side of
his chest. He said he often makes personal changes around the time
of the solstice -- Wednesday, for example, he is scheduled to fly
to Germany to begin working for Greenpeace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do rituals all the time -- I'm tapped in to a lot of
different cultures,'' he said. ``Today is a matter of stepping into
the main part of my purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Several participants said they see no conflict between rituals
celebrating the earth and the Western monotheistic faiths.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Yardley, 77, who appeared to be the eldest participant
in the ritual, said she joined a coven ten years ago, but she also
considers herself an active Unitarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inspiring to know there are peole that are about
preserving and taking care of the earth,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A 50-year-old psychologist who would identify herself only as
``Silent Wolf'' because, she said, she is not ``out'' as a pagan,
said she was raised in Baptist churches and discovered pagan
rituals while in college in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never connected to traditional religion, but I did begin to
connect with nature, and I connect to the goddess,'' she said. ``I
believe the goddess is everywhere. That's where the energy is.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd included Michael Coyne, 35, a self-described
``spiritual state trooper'' who was attending his first such ritual
bearing an Inca-inspired drum he had just brought back from
Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   Solstice is celebrated in various ways around the world, and
some wicca activists in America have called for the day to become a
national holiday. This year, for the first time in 16 years,
British officials allowed Druids to worship at Stonehenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of neo-pagan movements consider themselves earth
religions, and the solstices and equinoxes form natural holidays,''
said Philip G. Davis, chairman of the department of religious
studies at the University of Prince Edward Island and author of
``Goddess Unmasked: The Rise of Neopagan Feminist Spirituality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical idea is that the forces of the divine are within
the universe, so a lot of people would consider these sort of
significant natural events, like the solstice, to be manifestations
of this divine force within nature, and as special moments in which
that force might be more accessible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
