u i BC-ISRAEL-REISGN-BOS &LR;      06-20 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-REISGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIGNATIONS THREATEN STABILITY OF BARAK GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHOSHANA LONDON SAPPIR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak's coalition government
moved toward the brink of collapse Tuesday when four Cabinet
ministers from Barak's largest partner in power submitted letters
of resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, Barak said he made the Orthodox Shas party a final
offer aimed at keeping the party from bolting.
</P>
<P>
   The resignations take effect Thursday. If Shas follows through
and quits the government, Barak could put together an alternative
coalition, but his ability to reach a peace agreement with the
Palestinians would be weakened.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian negotiators are working toward a
September target date for a framework agreement on the toughest
issues in their historic conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In a live broadcast on Israeli television, Barak reassured
Israelis he was still committed to peacemaking. ``In any case
Israel will have a government and it will take all the necessary
decisions on peace and society,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said he addressed Shas's main concern _ funding and
control of its education system. ``They know our offer and we are
waiting for their answer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Months of haggling over Shas's financial demands came to a head
two weeks ago when the 17-member bloc in Israel's 120-seat
parliament cast the decisive vote for a bill to call new elections.
The threat that the party would see the bill through until it
became a law, effectively dissolving parliament, was the start of
intense negotiations with Barak's One Israel party over funding for
Shas schools and the legalization of pirate radio stations the
party runs.
</P>
<P>
   Members of One Israel said agreement had been within close reach
when Shas tightened the screws by having its four cabinet ministers
resign.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Avraham Shohat, from Barak's party, said Shas
chose to quit beacause it did not wish to support Barak's peace
moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reached a solution for most of the problems,'' Shohat said.
``I conclude from that that apparently the resignation has other
reasons, which may be connected to Shas's desire not to be in the
government because of its expected political moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's political system is prone toward instability because of
separate voting for prime minister and for parliament. While Barak
was elected last year by an overwhelming majority, his party earned
only 26 seats. His ability to rule depends on coalitions with
several smaller parties that represent special interests. Shas
represents observant Jews of Middle Eastern origin. The party
excludes women as a matter of principle.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999 elections, its generally hardline voters supported
Barak's rival, then-Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Minister of Education Yossi Sarid leads the secular Meretz
party, which is the ideological opposite of Shas. The conflict
between Shas and Meretz is at the heart of the current coalition
crisis. Sarid refused to transfer the funds to Shas schools unless
they acceded to state supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Today Barak governs with a 68-52 majority. If Shass resignation
goes into effect, Barak is likely to invite the six-member,
anti-religious Shinui party to join the government. In that case he
will be ruling by a minority coalition that is likely to be
supported by the votes of seven members of Arab parties and three
members of the largely Communist Democratic Front for Peace and
Equality.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis came at a critical moment in Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is expected to
visit the Mideast next week for the second time this month, in
another attempt to nudge Barak and Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat toward an agreement. The parties are attempting to tackle
four key issues: the final borders between Israel and a Palestinian
entity, control of Jerusalem, the future of Palestinian refugees
and Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has said he would declare a Palestinian state in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip in September, whether or not a peace deal is
reached with Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1937EDT &QL; 
