<SLUG> BC-IBASIS-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBASIS CHINA DEAL HELPS STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (iBasis is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Mass. _ iBasis Inc., battling to lead the market for
international telephone calls routed over the Internet, is to
announce a pact Wednesday with China's third-largest phone carrier
that will help it cement its hold on Asia's lucrative
telecommunications market.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of iBasis have taken a pounding since February, losing
two-thirds of their peak value. But iBasis has been pouring out a
steady flow of announcements of new interconnection partnerships
with carriers around the world. They include this new deal with
Jitong Communications Co. Ltd. and Tuesday's pact with a top
Russian carrier.
</P>
<P>
   In Nasdaq trading, iBasis shares rose $3.75 to $32.50, but
they've gone into a nosedive from their $94 highs in February.
</P>
<P>
   Already, four-year-old iBasis has inbound and outbound
international calling deals with China Unicom and China Mobile, the
top wireless carrier.
</P>
<P>
   The new deal could help iBasis increase its share of outbound
international calls to 15 percent, president Ofer Gneezy said. Some
months, iBasis carries up to one of every 10 voice and fax calls
from the United States to China, which has 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   And iBasis already carries traffic for 11 of the 12 largest
US-based international carriers, 10 of the world's 20 largest
international carriers, and 70 international carriers in total.
</P>
<P>
   It undercuts conventional carriers' costs by routing calls from
phone to phone over the Internet, under strict monitoring,
reverting to the conventional phone network about 10 percent of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   However, deals such as the Jitong pact only open the door for
iBasis to carry some of these carriers' international calls, with
no guaranteed minimum. iBasis is in a dogfight with ITXC and other
start-ups for Internet phone-to-phone voice traffic, and with the
computer-to-phone carriers Net2Phone and Delta III.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to move on two fronts,'' Gneezy said. ``One is to get
more countries connected to our network. Another is to get more
traffic on those connections.''
</P>
<P>
   China is expected to have 160 million wireless subscribers
within five years, accounting for 1 of every 7 new cell phone
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Asia's telecommunications market represents $400
billion in sales this year, including domestic calls, according to
Australian analysts Paul Budde Communication. US researchers Frost
&AMP; Sullivan estimate Internet-based phone calls in Asia could grow
from $78 million now to $48 billion in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Chinese pacts, iBasis has carriage agreements with
Japan's NTT, the Thailand Communications Authority, Dacom in Korea,
and Telstra in Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9830 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BRITAIN-SUMMER-THEATE     06-20 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-SUMMER-THEATER-$ADV25-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE PLACE WHERE AMERICAN TALENT GETS RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday June 25)  
 By BENEDICT NIGHTINGALE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Americans still patriotically smarting at the number of
British prizewinners in this year's Tony Awards need only visit the
British capital itself to find a salve for sore pride. If the New
York theater sometimes looks a bit like Shaftesbury
Avenue-by-the-Hudson, there are parts of London this summer that
might be Broadway-on-the-Thames or even
Hollywood-Near-the-Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Revivals of David Mamet's ``Speed the Plow,'' Arthur Miller's
``All My Sons'' and Tennessee Williams' ``Orpheus Descending,'' the
British premiere of Miller's ``Peters' Connections,'' adaptations
of ``Singin' in the Rain'' and ``Baby Doll'': all are now or soon
to be found at addresses ranging from the Royal National Theater to
the Albery to the chic little Almeida. Moreover, Kathleen Turner's
Robinson is still doing a sedate striptease for her 20-ish lover in
a version of ``The Graduate'' that feels it can advertise itself as
``the hottest ticket in the country.'' And Turner is not the only
Hollywood star in London; Donald Sutherland has just moved his
lanky frame into the Savoy.
</P>
<P>
   Let me not overstate the case. As I'll be reporting in a moment,
the London theater is offering some striking non-American plays and
performances this summer. A gruff, tough Vanessa Redgrave is
aggressively pacing Shakespeare's Globe as the first female
Prospero any critic can recall. Alex Jennings is a tense, tormented
Albert Speer in an adaptation of Gitta Sereny's fine biography of
Hitler's favorite architect; Ralph Fiennes makes a chilling if
limited Coriolanus; and a pair of more or less unknown Irish actors
take 13 roles in a marvelous two-hander by a more or less unknown
Irish dramatist named Marie Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Yet an image that nicely exemplifies London's trans-Atlantic
drift embraces cascades of silver hair, an unnervingly loopy smile
and a marked North American accent. Whether he's firing a shotgun
at the journalist he has forgotten he's invited, or parading his
paranoia and narcissism in purely verbal ways, it's hard to resist
the quirky charisma that Donald Sutherland brings to the role of an
eccentric Nobel Prize winner in Eric-Emmanuel Schmitt's ``Enigmatic
Variations.'' The problem is the French author's play, a succession
of surprises that momentarily raise the eyebrows but are likely to
leave a disbelieving frown on the skin above them.
</P>
<P>
   John Rubinstein's earnestly self-effacing Erik Larsen has come
to interview Sutherland's Abel Znorko on his private island off the
Norwegian coast. At first, the great man deals condescendingly with
questions about whether his new epistolary novel is based on fact _
``I'm a writer, not a Xerox machine'' _ but then he abruptly and
none too explicably reverses himself. Actually, the book consists
of the myriad love letters he continued to exchange with a woman
with whom he had long ago had a rapturous affair: ``Lightning
struck, everything exploded, night became day, and we were asleep
in each others' arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that really the way Nobel laureates speak? When Sutherland's
Znorko proceeds to muse about the ``existential alienation of
closeness,'' to bemoan the ``single unifying spasm'' that takes
lovers ``back to solitude,'' and to claim that he ``imposed
separation so our love could be eternal,'' it's almost as if Sartre
were composing a bodice-ripper. But that's far from the last of the
evening's incongruities. I had better not reveal the twists of plot
that follow, if only because the play, which has already been seen
in Los Angeles and Toronto, could yet get a New York showing. They
did, however, leave my head feeling the way my body might if an
over-ambitious osteopath tried to convince me that my knees were
for sitting and my elbows for walking: twisted way out of true.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say that if Hamlet's letter to Horatio describing his
encounter with the pirates turned out to have been written by the
dead Ophelia, or if the correspondence between the sexual predators
in ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses'' had been penned by Cardinal
Richelieu and the Pope, it would be emotionally more revealing and
not vastly more preposterous. Still, those with the gift of
credulity will get their rewards. They won't find great depth or
density in Sutherland's performance, but they will see his
arrogantly upright Znorko become interestingly uncertain of
himself: a transition akin to the Tower of Babel turning into the
Leaning Tower of Pisa.
</P>
<P>
   That is just one of several startling mutations to be found on
the London stage right now. Indeed, if I had to pick out a best
performance for June, I would be hard put to choose between the 13
given by Sean Campion and Conleth Hill in the Belfast-born Jones'
``Stones in His Pockets'' at the New Ambassadors. Both are Irish
extras playing tattered Victorian peasants in a period romance
being filmed in scenic Kerry. But they have only to give a nudge to
their shoulders and their voice boxes _ and lo, we have the movie's
fluting American megastar, or a go-getting assistant director from
Dublin, or a troubled priest, or a Cockney rigger high on cocaine,
or the drunken old codger famous for having played an extra in
``The Quiet Man'' and been called ``wee Mickey'' by John Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   This is moviemaking entertainingly seen from the stance of those
crowd members whose job is to provide an anonymous background to
the glamorous doings of the hero and heroine. It is also, and more
seriously, pastoral Ireland observed by its losers. Campion's Jake
has just returned to his village after failing to make a fortune in
America, and Hill's Charlie is still reeling from the collapse of
his video business. They find it only too easy to obey the director
when he brusquely orders them to tug their forelocks or look
``dispossessed'' and ``defeated.'' But their feelings of defeat
don't match those of Campion's Sean Harkin, the poor, goofy extra
who is thrown out of his local pub on the orders of a spoiled
celebrity and, filling his pockets with stones, walks into the pond
once owned and then lost by his father.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' ant's-eye view of a Hollywood saga allows her to tackle
several subjects: rural deprivation, cultural exploitation, the gap
between the feted and the fated, and, perhaps above all, the lure
of dreams and the dream-industry. When Hill, as the priest, says
that ``imagination can be a damned curse in this country,'' he is
not only explaining a star-struck boy's suicide: he is also placing
``Stones in His Pockets'' in a tradition that extends from Synge's
``Playboy of the Western World'' through O'Casey's ``Juno and the
Paycock'' to Brian Friel's ``Translations.'' And though the reek of
self-pity sometimes rises from the stage's bare boards, Jones
banishes it in an ending that is unexpected, ironic and
refreshingly upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Talking of bravura transmogrification, what about Vanessa
Redgrave in ``The Tempest'' at Shakespeare's Globe? On she stalks
in a patched-up jacket and faded breeches, looking more like a
Balkan guerrilla than the gracious magus of theatrical tradition.
It is easier to believe that this tall, wizened, growling figure is
an exiled duke than it was to accept Mark Rylance as a frolicsome
Cleopatra at the same address last year. Equally, you have no doubt
that this Prospero has been hardened by 16 years spent warring with
the elements and his own resentment.
</P>
<P>
   Why such gender-bending in a replica of the Jacobean theater
where every role was played by a man or boy? Well, years ago Glenda
Jackson spoke for many aging actresses when she said, ``Why should
I stay in the theater to play the Nurse in `Romeo and Juliet?,'''
and became a Labor M.P. But you can't accuse Redgrave of redressing
the sexual imbalance in classic English plays just for politically
correct reasons. There are artistic gains. For instance, Redgrave
is the first Prospero I have seen who might have nurtured a
daughter from babyhood to adolescence. ``A cherubin thou wast that
did preserve me,'' she/he reassures Kananu Kirimi's worried
Miranda, and, for once, you sense the warmth and tenderness that
has sustained this unlikely duo.
</P>
<P>
   When she is cherishing Geraldine Alexander's ethereal Ariel,
too, you feel that Redgrave is bringing out what Jung would have
called the character's anima or feminine side. But this doesn't
lessen Prospero's flinty anger or Prospero's pain at renouncing
power. Only at the end does the performance soften. I really don't
think the duke's mercy should extend to doing a sort of high-five
with Jasper Britton's otherwise admirably anguished Caliban. But
this silly, sentimental touch must partly be blamed on the
director, Lenka Udovicki, who could have battled harder against one
of the Globe's built-in dangers: a tendency for actors to
ingratiate themselves with groundlings who are milling and
chortling just a few yards away.
</P>
<P>
   Fiennes, who is still playing a fretful, narcissistic Richard II
at the Gainsborough Studios in London's Shoreditch District,
changes and doesn't change for the ``Coriolanus'' that has just
joined the repertory the Almeida Theater Company is presenting in
the same big, bleak, ad-hoc playhouse. The eyes still have their
silvery glint. The classic profile is still in place. But something
has happened to the nose, which seems to have lifted an inch or
two, as if to put Coriolanus at a still greater distance from the
smelly mob.
</P>
<P>
   This built-in sneer, combined with an articulate disdain that
often rises to an eloquent contempt, certainly suits the unlovable
hero who is prepared to be exiled and join Rome's enemies rather
than compromise his conservative credo. The result is a bold,
charismatic Coriolanus but one who seems even more monochrome than
Shakespeare's original. After all, the mandarin monster dies
because his great foe, Linus Roache's Aufidius, calls him ``boy,''
unforgivably exposing his lifelong failure to stand up to his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Since you can imagine Barbara Jefford's majestically bellicose
Volumnia dismissing Boadicea as a bimbo and the Amazons as a bunch
of balky schoolgirls, there is every reason for Fiennes to stress
or at least suggest suppressed vulnerability. But not until he
yields to her pleas not to destroy Rome, grabbing her hand and
kneeling and sobbing, do you sense Coriolanus' inner child; and
it's insufficiently prepared for, depriving Jonathan Kent's mostly
admirable production of its one big chance of emotional complexity.
</P>
<P>
   David Edgar is a left-leaning dramatist who has made a specialty
of understanding right-wing minds, which is why his masterpiece is
probably ``Destiny,'' a 1976 play about the allure of British
nationalism. At three and a half hours, his ``Albert Speer'' makes
considerable demands on our rumps, minds and political
sensibilities, but, as Trevor Nunn directs the play in the National
Theater's Lyttelton auditorium, you will surely be impressed by its
size, gravity and willingness to ask difficult questions. How could
a man with the intelligence, sensitivity and, yes, decency that
Gitta Sereny's biography ascribes to Speer have reacted to Hitler's
Mephistopheles like some baby-faced Faust?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   A moment after we have met him, Alex Jennings' pale, grim Speer
sits brooding in Spandau, the only Nazi imprisoned there to feel
the need for repentance. And then come the flashbacks, explaining
how he rose from an obscure architect to the designer of the
grandiose capital of Greater Germania and then minister of
armaments. As Speer admits, he was ambitious, excited by power and
susceptible to flattery, especially when it came from the Teutonic
Charlemagne who had raised Germany from the ashes and treated him
like the kindly father he never had. In the 1930s, how many
impressionable young men would not have shrugged off occasional
rants about ``Jewish Bolsheviks'' or ``Slav subhumans'' from an
idealistic patriot who was also solving their Oedipal problems? How
many might not do so now?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question implicitly asked in the play's first half,
and it is the more challenging for Jennings' quiet intensity and
the excellent acting of Roger Allam as Hitler, a beguilingly
affable figure who gives his true nature away only when paranoia
surfaces or when setbacks in the war turn him into a babbling,
broken savage, demanding the demolition of Germany itself. The
second half, with Speer released from Spandau and restored to the
public-speaking circuit, raises a more particular worry. Was Speer
telling the truth when he denied any knowledge of the Holocaust?
Was his moral redemption a fake, his spiritual regeneration based
on a lie?
</P>
<P>
   The problem with plays like ``Albert Speer'' is that they are
circumscribed by the facts as they are known. Fiction may lack
historical authority but it brings freedom and freedom's rewards.
If Shakespeare had based, say, ``King Lear'' on some druid's
definitive biography, he could hardly have produced the fathomless
tragedy that imagination allowed. That is maybe why neither Edgar
nor Jennings can plunge too deeply into the darker side of Speer's
raveled, ravaged psyche, but must instead show him obsessively
denying that he was present when Himmler announced the Final
Solution and repeating his mantra: ``I should have known. I could
have known. I didn't know. I turned away.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this Speer is bright enough to realize that ignorance may
be willed and turning away can itself be a crime, perhaps more
heinous than acknowledging complicity and paying the penalty. And
at his play's end, Edgar does take a surely forgivable liberty,
bringing on Allam as the Hitler who still haunts his architect's
nightmares. And this Fuhrer is no paternal figure, but a sneering
fanatic who points out that he did indeed talk of the annihilation
of bolshevism and the destruction of the Jews, and asks, ``Why was
I cursed with never being taken literally?'' As Jennings' dying
Speer finally agrees, the phantom had a point _ and it's one that
implicates more people than himself.
</P>
<P>
   Whether New York will see ``Albert Speer'' or ``Stones in His
Pockets'' remains uncertain, but both Fiennes' ``Coriolanus'' and
his ``Richard II'' are headed for the Brooklyn Academy of Music in
the fall, and other British work will doubtless follow them to the
city. But then the coming months will see major revivals of
``Merrily We Roll Along'' and ``My Fair Lady'' in London, as well
as Cameron Mackintosh's mega-production of ``The Witches of
Eastwick,'' a musical, derived from John Updike's novel, by two
young Americans, John Dempsey and Dana P. Rowe. And who takes over
from Kathleen Turner in ``The Graduate'' at the beginning of
August? Why, Texas' very own Jerry Hall. No, the traffic across the
Atlantic is decidedly two-way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
