<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-RECOVERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ CONTINUES UPSWING, BREAKING 4000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A steady, monthlong rally in technology stocks pushed the Nasdaq
Composite index above the 4000 mark Tuesday for the first time
since early April.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq rose 23.54 points, an increase of less than 1
percentage point but enough to finish the day at 4013.37. Tech
stocks rallied for the fourth straight day, a signal, analysts
said, that high-quality companies will continue to benefit from the
country's conversion to an Internet economy, despite the rout in
many fragile dot-com companies.
</P>
<P>
   Since hitting its recent low of 3164.55 on May 23, Nasdaq has
rebounded nearly 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, with its blue-chip lineup of
old-economy names, is another story. After rallying between
mid-March and mid-April, the 30-stock Dow has followed a jagged
downward path that continued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, analysts said, seems vulnerable to the slowing that is
taking place in the overall economy and anticipated weakness in the
next round of earnings reports on the first quarter. The Dow
slumped 122.68 points, or 1.16 percent, to 10,435.16.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Engels, Tucker Anthony Inc. senior vice president and a
director of equity research, predicted the Nasdaq offers more hope
for investors in coming weeks or months than does the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tech is not dead,'' Engels said. ``We've really had a sifting
and sorting, where the less quality or early-stage companies that
were perhaps too early stage for the market have truly fallen to
the bottom. The names with staying power have moved and have
corrected quite a bit, and if the economy continues to grow and
tech continues to be major theme they will do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Driven by gains in such industry stalwarts as Intel Corp., the
world's biggest chip maker, the Nasdaq has staged an impressive
rally in recent weeks. Tuesday marks the first time it has
surpassed 4000 since April 11, when the market closed at 4055.90.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous tech stocks had stellar gains, including Intel, which
rose $1.8125 a share, to $138.3125, on expectations of higher
demand for its chips. National Semiconductor Corp. rose $5.25 a
share, to $72.25, after Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. analyst Joseph Osha
predicted the stock could reach $100 a share in 12 to 18 months
because of strong demand for its wireless and network products.
</P>
<P>
   But Philip Fine, who manages the Small-Cap and Aggressive Growth
funds for Loomis, Sayles &AMP; Co., said that while he expects the
Nasdaq to possibly return to about 4400, the index is not in the
midst of a major bull-market rally.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in Nasdaq stocks, he said, is being fueled by
speculative interest, though speculation is no longer focused on
dot-com companies and has shifted to other tech industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of money is flowing into relatively few stocks going
up,'' Fine said. ``It's basically a momentum move in the market and
it has not broadened out'' to non-tech stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates and evidence the economy's long-running
economic expansion may be slowing have dampened the Dow, which
historically has responded to economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Fine noted that financial-company stocks have been very weak
because of concerns about the quality of their loans. The New York
Stock Exchange's index of financial companies has lost about 7
percent since late May.
</P>
<P>
   Retail stocks also have slumped amid reports last week of steep
declines in sales to consumers. Retailers were hit after a Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co. analyst said June sales for stores open at least a year
were likely lower than expected for companies including May
Department Stores Co., Kmart Corp., J.C. Penney Co., and Federated
Department Stores Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only at Wal-Mart, among companies polled so far, are June
sales solidly on plan,'' Strachan wrote in a report to clients.
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell International Inc. accounted for almost a third of the
Dow's decline, after the company said earnings will fall short of
estimates. Honeywell, a pioneer in the computer industry, is now
considered an ``old economy'' stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``With anecdotal evidence the economy is slowing you have to
wonder if the problem is more widespread than Honeywell,'' said
Robert Streed, manager of the Northern Select Equity fund in
Chicago. ``Investors are skittish about the other industrial
names.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker Anthony's Engels attributed the Dow's slump to a range of
factors, from Honeywell to a weaker euro currency that is hurting
many US companies with international exposure. The upcoming
earnings announcements are another wild card for the Dow, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we can get through the earnings reporting season, the
Dow is probably going to be sluggish,'' Engels predicted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
