<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9834 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-FOLO21-COX     06-20 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-FOLO21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lakers celebrate, reflect on a season of excellence
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was the aftermath of another title celebration.
``We Are The Champions'' blared over the loudspeakers. Purple and
gold confetti cascaded from the rafters. Phil Jackson took it all
in with remarkable calm. Or maybe it was shock. Or both.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's placid demeanor amid the celebration Monday night at
the Staples Center was symbolic of the way he elevated the
once-underachieving Lakers to the summit. Rarely did he raise his
voice in the first year at the Lakers helm. But his players often
interpreted his calm as forceful statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Phil,'' guard Kobe Bryant said, ``he didn't have to say
anything from the beginning. When he walked in for the first time,
he had our attention because of his six championships (with the
Bulls). How can you ignore that?
</P>
<P>
   ``And during a game or practice, when he's not happy, he just
gives you a look, and you know you've messed up. And you get it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the same Lakers who yawned when former coaches Del
Harris and Kurt Rambis sought their attention, listened and
followed Jackson _ all the way to the NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   Their 116-111 Game 6 victory over the Indiana Pacers in the
Staples Center Monday night was a summation of a season of
remarkable achievement for Jackson. It might have been his best
coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson did not score a point, but he did score points with
Shaquille O'Neal and Bryant by the way he challenged them to become
complete players.
</P>
<P>
   In his first words after becoming a champion, O'Neal said:
``First of all, I want to thank the real coach of the year, Phil
Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Jackson, O'Neal won the all-star game MVP, the league
regular-season MVP and the NBA Finals MVP.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal punctuated his season with 41 points, 12 rebounds and
four blocks in the clincher. He scored 13 in the fourth quarter,
when the Lakers finally took the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry and Rick Fox made key contribuitons in the fourth
quarter, but it was O'Neal who led the way to the title. l ``I
think we needed Phil to do it,'' said O'Neal, who cried after the
game. ``We always won 50, 60 games. When we got into certain
situations in the playoffs, we could never get over the hump. But
Phil was able to keep us poised.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's ability to understand his role was critical to the
team's development. Jackson made it clear to the talented
21-year-old that the Lakers are Shaq's team. And knowing Bryant's
desire to have the kind of impact Michael Jordan did, Jackson told
Bryant to work harder as a defender.
</P>
<P>
   Although he breached the team concept at times, Bryant's game
grew considerably. And he became a first-team all defensive player.
</P>
<P>
   ``All young players should play under Phil,'' Bryant said. ``I'm
very fortunate. He breaks the game down for you, helps you
understand the game, where to attack, how to attack. I feel I have
an advantage over other young players because I play under him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson avoided labeling his success with this team, although as
recently as Friday he questioned whether it had the character to be
champions. But he sounded proud when he talked about the way the
team had started under him. In October, he had stopped the first
practice because he sensed that he was not receiving a committed
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `You guys can't play with the kind of energy I demand
as a coach, and you have to lift that up,' `` Jackson said. ``They
found a way to do that. That was the key to whether we could win or
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they could play with the kind of intensity
defensively that it takes to be a championship team,'' he said.
``From that standpoint, I'm very pleased they were able to bring
that level up to a maximum effort this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Buss said about Jackson's coaching, ``At least in my
mind, I doubt that anyone else could have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
