A9837 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-UGA-STADIUM21-COX     06-20 0238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-STADIUM21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Landscaping crews begin laying turf in Sanford Stadium
 &HT;    By Plott Brice
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ University of Georgia fans can stop worrying. The
jokes can cease about the foul-smelling liquid that seeped up
through the Sanford Stadium turf.
</P>
<P>
   About six months and $750,000 later, the Bulldogs have their
football field back.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, landscaping crews laid the first of dozens of rolls
of a Bermuda-grass hybrid known as Tifway 4-19 on a bed of sand,
clay and gravel. The rebuilding project, the result of years-old
drainage problems underneath Sanford field, is expected to be
completed sometime today.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs' Sept. 2 home-opener against Georgia Southern is
just 10 weeks away and the state is in the throes of a record
drought. But Ray McEwen, the Georgia athletic association's
landscaping chief, said, ``I can guarantee you we will have a 100
percent playable field.''
</P>
<P>
   McEwen said the first seven days are critical as the sod takes
root. UGA is using a chemical in the sand beneath the sod that
congeals the water and holds the moisture. Once rooted, the grass
is semi-dormant and can protect itself from searing sun and heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the sod was down, we could play tomorrow,'' McEwen
said.
</P>
<P>
   To the Bulldog faithful, comforting words indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
