<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-IMMIG-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVER HELD, SURVIVORS QUESTIONED IN DEATHS OF 58 CHINESE
IMMIGRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British police officers investigating the deaths of 58
Chinese immigrants found crammed into the freight container of a
truck in Dover ordered the Dutch driver held on suspicion of
manslaughter Tuesday and began interviewing two men in a Canterbury
hospital who lived through the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two men are of enormous value to us simply because they
are the only survivors,'' said Detective Superintendent Dennis
McGookin, the head of the investigation. ``This is being treated as
a homicide; it is a major criminal investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The case has focused attention on the lucrative international
business of smuggling desperate refugees who the British police say
will pay crime syndicates up to $30,000 each to be brought here.
Prime Minister Tony Blair, in Portugal at a European meeting, said
the case had prompted a ``huge willingness'' on the part of
continental leaders to ``tackle this problem of trade in human
misery.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch police said they had arrested a man in Rotterdam in
connection with the grisly early Monday discovery in the English
channel port, but they gave no details. The 50-foot transport was
registered to a Rotterdam company that had been set up just five
days earlier, and the police were searching for Arie van der Spek,
24, an engineer who lived at the address listed for the company.
</P>
<P>
   McGookin, the investigator, said initial forensic findings
showed the 54 men and 4 women died of ``some form of respiratory
failure.'' The truck's refrigeration system had been turned off,
turning the space packed with the migrants and stacked high with
tomato crates into an airless oven.
</P>
<P>
   Without identifying their sources, British newspapers reported
that the two survivors said they were clawing at the inside of the
sealed back door and screaming at the driver. The moment that
customs officers opened the doors, they reportedly said, was ``as
if an angel had been sent from heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers pulled the vehicle over shortly after midnight Sunday
as it left the ferry, which had made the four-and-a-half-hour
crossing from Zeebrugge in Belgium. Belgian authorities alerted
British customs officials about their suspicions when they could
find no prior record of the company listed in the registry and when
they saw the driver pay for the journey in cash.
</P>
<P>
   McGookin said the victims were all in their 20s and came from
Fujian province in southern China. ``These people have died a
horrific death, and somewhere in China, but also maybe in this
country, are their relatives,'' he said. ``We would appeal to
anyone that knows the deceased to come forward at once''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the estimated 150,000 Chinese living in Britain come
from Fujian, but authorities worry that they will not come forward
for fear of exposing themselves to arrest and deportation as
illegal residents. The police set up a public emergency phone
number staffed by Chinese speakers.
</P>
<P>
   McGookin said he was receiving cooperation from the Chinese
Embassy and government to identify victims and track down the gang
leaders who managed to ferry the refugees such a distance. ``To
have 60 young people in the back of a truck, there would have to
have taken some organization to get these people over from China,''
he said. ``In liaising with the Chinese police, hopefully we will
know more on this soon.''
</P>
<P>
   A Home Office spokesman said that since spring about 600
immigrants have been detained in Dover each month, down from 2,000
a month from January to March.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman credited laws put into effect in April for the
reduction. Since then truck drivers have been liable to fines of
$3,000 for every stowaway found on their rigs.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said, ``This tragedy has brought home to people the sheer
scale of this problem, and it doesn't just affect Britain, it
affects every other country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
