<HEADER>
A9842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MAHER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     06-20 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAHER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRUE STORY': A COMIC WHO WRITES WHAT HE KNOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of
review.)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Maher, known to those who watch late-night television as
the creator and host of the program ``Politically Incorrect,''
doesn't waste any time introducing the main characters of ``True
Story,'' a novel he wrote a decade ago that is just now being
published in hardcover. In his first paragraph he introduces the
five comedians who inhabit the rest of the book, five men of the
early 1980s variously unsuited for any of the usual bourgeois
occupations, riding the Amtrak Minuteman from New York to gigs in
Wilmington and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Maher is finished about 300 pages later, the reader
has had a thorough experience of this raucously ill-starred band of
brothers whose lives are equally devoted to career and sex. Too
thorough, actually. Maher has written a novel with many funny
passages of a kind of sandpaper humor whose chief engine is the
relentlessly adolescent urgings of the five strenuously striving
comics. Maher himself is a man of considerable restless talent,
with a special gift for earthy dialogue, more politically incorrect
in its absence of euphemism and nicety than his television program
is.
</P>
<P>
   So one enjoys ``True Story'' for its bawdy energy, its
flamethrower wit, even if it has the enduring impact of yesterday's
potato chips. There is a limit to just how long one wants to be in
intensive contact with a group of guys who remind you of the
nervously aggressive jokesters in high school, the ones who were
always cracking about masturbation and hair growing in the palm.''
</P>
<P>
   `Yeah, yeah,' Buck sighed. `The penis. It's our bane and boon,
isn't it?''' Buck is one of Maher's single-minded comedians, and
while there are many better lines of dialogue than that in this
book, that stale observation is typical of many. Maher's five main
characters range from a relative old hand to a relative neophyte in
the stand-up comic game.
</P>
<P>
   They are in their 20s and 30s, all saturated in the comic
sensibility of the early 1980s, a sort of post-Lenny Bruce mockery
of bourgeois pretense, a stripping away of the veneer of civility.
One of the enjoyable elements of Maher's book is that as a stand-up
comedian himself, he is able to write some pretty funny material
for his characters, like these lines in which Buck wishes his
audience goodbye:
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to stay, but it would keep me from going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because this is certainly a night I will remember till I get
to my car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, you were execrable, good night!''
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, as Maher says about a different passage,
that isn't all that funny, and indeed, the humor in ``True Story''
is hit or miss, as humor often is. Maher is a .300 hitter in this
sense, which is pretty good, especially when sustained over an
entire novel. Some passages are hilarious, but even so, there is
the general problem that jokes designed for a live club do not have
the same effect on the printed page. The same is true of the
constant repartee that takes place among the characters, a repartee
that varies between the stiletto and the sledgehammer forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the X factor in comedy,'' Maher writes at one point
about why jokes work sometimes and other times don't. ``One can
hone material, rehearse delivery, bone up on all the tangibles, but
in the end it comes down to something very much like what makes a
man and a woman have enduring passion _ something that no one can
ever know, because such knowledge, like that coveted by Adam and
Eve, would itself be the agent of destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, when ``True Story'' works, it works because of
Maher's energetic intelligence and his creation of characters whose
prolonged sophomorism has distinct qualities.
</P>
<P>
   The five comedians grow and change during the year or so of
``True Story's'' span, and Maher certainly captures their world as
they deal with comedy club managers, chase women, take drugs, worry
about ``zits'' and engage heroically in the risky effort to make
other people laugh on demand. They are not deep or refined
characters, and the wit is not subtle or dry, but they all have
charm, even if it comes from a rueful acknowledgment of their
fecklessness and their failings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good. I don't know if it's the drugs,'' one of the guys
tells Buck after they take LSD in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I paid good money for them, and I'd hate to think we
could be feeling good for free.''
</P>
<P>
   Maher lives comfortably within the cramped spiritual dimensions
of his characters, never trying to get out of them anything more
than they would feasibly produce. When Fat, in the interests of
seducing the young woman of his desires, goes on a diet, it lasts
for two meals. When Buck falls for a certain Vera, he finds her
frequent use of the word like, ``which he formerly had excoriated
as an unpardonable lapse of verbal facility and harbinger of the
collapse of Western civilization,'' charming.
</P>
<P>
   Dick, who is the champion seducer of the group, ends up with a
woman named Jill who is so sealed into the chamber of her own
selfishness that she cannot see the wreckage she causes around her.
She is recognizable as a post-'60s type, liberated to a fault but
devoid of any sense of rebellious idealism. Also recognizable is
Dick's ability to see through to her selfish core and yet to remain
trapped within her orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``True Story,'' in other words, often has a satirical ring of
truth to it. You might like it, though you'll have to have a fairly
large appetite for post-``Leave It to Beaver'' artifacts if you do.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TRUE STORY, A Novel'
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Maher
</P>
<P>
   302 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
