<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-BROADCAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES BILL EASING REGULATION OF PUBLIC BROADCASTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a move that would allow religious groups a
greater role in public television, the US House voted Tuesday to
abolish requirements that public broadcasters air a certain amount
of educational programming.
</P>
<P>
   The religious broadcasting bill, backed by the Christian
Coalition, touched off a wave of protest among many House Democrats
and public broadcasters who fear it would fundamentally alter the
nature of taxpayer-funded TV.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Edward J. Markey, a Massachusetts Democrat,
warned that the legislation would lead to ``the single, most
significant change in public television in history,'' blurring the
line between church and state.
</P>
<P>
   But House Republicans saw the legislation, which passed 264-159,
as a triumph for free speech. The bill would forbid the Federal
Communications Commission from trying to regulate the content of
public radio and TV stations. It also would broaden the scope of
who qualifies for a free TV license, making religious programming
an acceptable format for public TV license applicants.
</P>
<P>
   A similar version of the bill is pending in the Senate, where
its chances are uncertain. President Clinton is expected to veto
the legislation if it reaches the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Coming the day after a Supreme Court decision banning school
prayer at high school sports events, the vote was received warmly
among House Republican leaders, many of whom have long sought to
reduce funding for public broadcasting overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court may have banned prayer yet again, but the House has
defended religion on the airwaves,'' said Representative J.C.
Watts, Republican of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, non-profit groups qualify for a public broadcasting
license if they promise their programs will be mostly one of three
things: educational, instructional, or cultural.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would add a fourth category: religious.
</P>
<P>
   The debate grew out of a controversial case last year in
Pittsburgh, in which a religious group tried to obtain a
non-commercial broadcasting license. The FCC, responding to public
outrage, issued a directive clarifying existing broadcasting rules.
Instead of just promising to have ``primarily'' educational
programming _ a vague requirement that is rarely regulated _ the
FCC said licensees had to prove they were devoting half their
programming to educational, instructional or cultural shows.
</P>
<P>
   That directive prompted outrage among conservatives and
religious broadcasters, who argued that church services and Bible
study discussions should be deemed educational. The FCC withdrew
the order. But congressional Republicans, fearful that the FCC
might act on religious broadcasting again in the future, moved
ahead with the legislation that passed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not have government intervention'' in religious
broadcasting, said Representative Chip Pickering, Republican of
Mississippi, who sponsored the bill. ``We will find a value for the
religious voice in the public square.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From now on, the (Federal Communications) Commission will not
try to dictate the content of religious broadcasting,'' said
Representative Billy Tauzin, Republican of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, there are 181 non-commercial public television
licenses. Of those public TV broadcasters, approximately 15 have a
religious theme, or are part of a larger organization with a
religious affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, most religious broadcasters hold commercial licenses,
which, although they are not free, allow the licensee to play
advertisements and raise money. There are approximately 245
religious TV broadcasters in the United States, according to the
FCC.
</P>
<P>
   And according to Markey, the fact that religious broadcasters
are able to buy commercial licenses is proof that their free speech
is not being stifled. When it comes to public television licenses,
however, he argued that all broadcasters should be held to a
certain standard. Other critics of the bill said that in rural
communities with limited TV access, granting a religious group the
sole public TV license could be offensive to some.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those television stations are meant to serve the
non-commercial educational needs for the entire community,'' Markey
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
