A9845 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ELIAN21-COX     06-20 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawyers for Elian's dad seek end to legal delays
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The federal appeals court in Atlanta should reject an
appeal seeking to extend the ``excrutiating delays'' of Elian
Gonzalez's return to Cuba, lawyers for the boy's father said in
court motions filed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, also asked the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals to dissolve an injunction keeping Elian in
the United States while his case continues.
</P>
<P>
   In his motion, Gonzalez accused Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro, and
other Miami relatives of abusing the litigation process to delay
Elian's return to his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we urge the court to see through Lazaro's charade, stop
the excrutiating delays and allow this family to go home,'' said
the brief, signed by Washington lawyer Gregory Craig.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, of course, is another day of interference with Juan
Miguel's ability to raise his child as he sees fit,'' Craig added.
</P>
<P>
   Elian, his father, his stepmother and his half-brother have been
staying in the Washington area since late April.
</P>
<P>
   Craig and U.S. Justice Department lawyers separately filed
motions, asking the 11th Circuit to reject the Miami relatives'
request that the full 12-judge court reconsider a decision issued
earlier this month by a three-judge panel.
</P>
<P>
   In that decision, the panel said the Immigration and
Naturalization Service acted correctly in deciding only Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, and not Elian's Miami relatives, could apply for asylum
on the 6-year-old boy's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was the deadline for the parties to respond to the Miami
relatives' motion for reconsideration.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the relatives said the panel's decision was wrong
and in conflict with U.S. Supreme Court precedent.
</P>
<P>
   They also claimed the panel ignored the federal law allowing
``any alien'' _ including a child acting against his parent's
wishes _ to appeal for asylum.
</P>
<P>
   But the Justice Department replied that the panel was correct in
deferring to Attorney General Janet Reno's decision, who upheld an
INS ruling rejecting Elian's asylum application. ``That is the
paradigmatic kind of administrative decision to which deference is
owed,'' the Justice Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, in his brief, added, ``The decision of the INS
transcended levels of administrative deference _ reuniting Elian
with his sole surviving parent was simply the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   While the 11th Circuit has promised to consider Elian's case in
an expedited manner, there is no timetable for when the court must
decide whether it will rehear the issue. If the full court decides
to reconsider, it must schedule another hearing. If it rejects the
motion from Elian's Miami relatives, the relatives can then appeal
that decision to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
