<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-VOTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH, GORE AD CAMPAIGNS TARGET HISPANICS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GARY MARTIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bruising battle for Hispanic voters heats up as
Democrats launch a national advertising campaign featuring Vice
President Al Gore speaking Spanish and Texas Gov. George W. Bush
touts his outreach efforts to reach Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   The presumptive presidential nominees for the Republican and
Democratic parties are scheduled to address Hispanics at several
national conventions over the next two weeks to outline their
proposals on education, health care, taxes and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hispanic community has emerged as a powerful voting bloc
in this year's presidential campaign and our political influence is
expected to play a decisive role in key battleground states,'' said
Rick Dovalina, national president of the League of United Latin
American Citizens (LULAC).
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore are scheduled to speak during LULAC's 71st annual
National Convention next week.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates also will speak to the annual conference of the
National Council of La Raza, in San Diego, over the July 4th
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made dramatic inroads into traditional Democratic
voting constituencies to post a slim lead over Gore in several
national public opinion polls. The Republican governor remains
popular among Hispanics in his home state, as well as with
GOP-leaning Cuban-Americans in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is making an unprecedented effort to reach out
to Hispanics throughout America,'' said Sonia Colin, a Bush
spokeswoman. ``His compassionate conservative message ... is
resonating with the Hispanic community.''
</P>
<P>
   Individual members of the executive board of LULAC-Florida
endorsed Bush this past weekend. Bush's brother Jeb is the
Republican governor of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Wilkes, LULAC executive director in Washington, clarified
that while individual members may issue support, the national group
does not endorse candidates for any elective office and will not
officially support Bush or Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never endorsed a candidate,'' Wilkes said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, remains the overwhelming favorite among
Hispanic voters in California, a key state for a Democratic
presidential victory this fall and a state where he leads Bush by
double-digit margins in most public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also is rebounding among Latino voters
nationally, recovering from a 9 percentage-point deficit to a 12
percentage-point lead over Bush, according to a bipartisan
Voter.com-Battleground 2000 survey released in May.
</P>
<P>
   A Zogby International poll earlier this month showed Bush with a
slim lead nationally, but with Gore doing well with minority voters
and independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore has made gains among independent voters and women and he
is improving among black and Hispanic voters despite the fact that
Bush has enjoyed a few very good weeks on the campaign trail,''
pollster John Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   To capitalize, the Democratic National Convention launched issue
ads in Spanish, touting the party and Gore's proposals to raise
educational standards, expand children's health care, enhance
Social Security and secure Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll fight to protect Social Security and Medicare,'' Gore
says in Spanish in one of the ads.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is featured prominently in the 30-second issue ads, that
begin with a narrator who says: ``Al Gore and the Democrats, we can
count on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads began running Tuesday on television in Tampa, Orlando,
Milwaukee, Chicago and Albuquerque. The ads will run for an
indefinite period of time, said Dagoberto Vega, a DNC spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign ran Spanish-language ads before the California
primary and has recruited campaign help from prominent Hispanics in
key states to win the White House in November.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has run Spanish-language ads, produced by Lionel Sosa
of San Antonio. The Republican National Committee has cut its own
commercials produced by Frank Guerra, also of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   To drive the diversity point further, George P. Bush, the nephew
of the candidate and son of Jeb Bush and his Mexican-born wife
Columba, has hit the campaign trial in support of his uncle.
</P>
<P>
   The Rice University graduate appears in several bilingual
television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics make up 13 percent of the population, but will account
for 20 percent of the population in 2025, according to Census
Bureau projections.
</P>
<P>
   Latinos living in the United States are concentrated in nine
states: California, Texas, New York, Illinois, New Jersey, Arizona,
New Mexico and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Dovalina said LULAC members will be listening to the candidates'
vision for the future next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be listening intently to learn how they propose to
help Hispanic Americans enjoy the fullest possible range of
economic wealth, political empowerment and civil rights in our
increasingly diverse society,'' Dovalina said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
