<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9866 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-COURT-BOS &LR;      06-20 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-COURT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT JUDGE ASKS HIGH COURT TO TAKE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The massive federal antitrust lawsuit against Microsoft Corp. is
heading directly to the US Supreme Court, if US District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson has his way.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson asked the high court Tuesday to take up the case
directly, rather than allow it to wend its way through the federal
appeals process. Early this month, Jackson ordered that Microsoft
be broken up into two separate companies to halt predatory business
practices based on Microsoft's monopoly in desktop operating system
software; Microsoft plans to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the judge may be bad news for Microsoft, which
previously won a major victory over Jackson at the appeals level.
But Jackson also gave Microsoft a break by delaying a set of
interim sanctions against the company that were supposed to go into
effect prior to the breakup. As a result, Microsoft can continue
doing business as usual until the case is finally resolved. And
there's no guarantee the Supreme Court will accede to Jackson's
request and take up the case.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Mark Murray praised Jackson's decision to
hold off on sanctions. ``It will allow the appeal to go forward
promptly,'' Murray said, ``but it'll prevent unnecessary disruption
to consumers and the industry and Microsoft while the appeal goes
forward.'' Murray shrugged off Jackson's expedited appeal, saying
that the move was expected.
</P>
<P>
   The US Justice Department, which along with 19 state attorneys
general filed the antitrust suit against Microsoft, issued a
statement praising Jackson's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision affirms the Department's position that a quick
and effective remedy is necessary to resolve this significant
case...'' the statement said. ``The sooner a meaningful remedy is
in place, the better it will be for consumers and the marketplace
by providing increased innovation, more choices and better
products.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Justice Department added that Jackson's decision to
stay his interim sanctions against Microsoft further demonstrated
the need to resolve the case as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson invoked the 1974 Antitrust Expediting Act, a law that
permits the appeal of certain cases from the district court level
to the Supreme Court if they involve issues of national importance.
The law has only been used twice before, and both instances
involved the long-runninc case that resulted in the 1984 breakup of
the AT&AMP;T telephone monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Black, president of the Computer and Communications Industry
Association, which favors a breakup of Microsoft, said it was
impossible to predict whether the Supreme Court would agree to hear
the case. But he said that the court might be impressed by the
importance of the matter, and by the fact that the Expediting Act
is so rarely invoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They use it sparingly, and the court is inclined to give some
weight to the fact that it's only done occasionally,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Rule, who headed the US Justice Department's
antitrust division in the 1980s and works as a Microsoft
consultant, said the high court might be put off by the complexity
of the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Literally every substantive antitrust issue that the court
addressed in its conclusions of law will be challenged,'' said
Rule. And given the thousands of pages of testimony and exhibits
involved, the Supreme Court might prefer to let the appeals court
do the heavy lifting, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials have said they expect to win the case on
appeal, and their confidence has some basis in history. In June
1998, the DC Court of Appeals overturned an injunction from Jackson
that barred Microsoft from including an Internet browser in every
copy of its Windows 95 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson had concluded that the inclusion of the browser was a
tactic intended to crush rival browser maker Netscape
Communications Corp., which has since been acquired by America
Online Inc. But the appeals court held that Microsoft had a right
to add new features to its software, even if the company harmed a
rival in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is hoping it will get an equally sympathetic response
from the appeals court this time. But company spokesman Mark Murray
said the company expects to win no matter where the appeal is
heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said throughout this case that we're confident that
the facts and the law are on our side,'' he said, ``regardless of
whether the case is heard in the appeals court or the Supreme Court
or both.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
