<P>
   (NYT23) BERKELEY, Calif. -- June 20, 2000 -- OLDER-WORKERS-2 --
An increasing number of companies are adjusting to the changing
dynamics of the job market by dipping deeper into the over-50 pool
of talent. Older folks bring years of experience and connections to
the table, and they often surprise their new bosses by showing
nearly as much get-up-and-go as their younger colleagues. Hank
Merrill is seen bicycling in the Berkeley, Calif. (Dan Krauss/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) STAMFORD, CT. -- June 20, 2000 -- OLDER-WORKERS-1 -- An
increasing number of companies are adjusting to the changing
dynamics of the job market by dipping deeper into the over-50 pool
of talent. Older folks bring years of experience and connections to
the table, and they often surprise their new bosses by showing
nearly as much get-up-and-go as their younger colleagues. Hershel
Sarbin in his office Stamford, CT. (Thomas McDonald/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- June 20, 2000 -- INTERNET-PARENTS-2 -- Marc
Bell, center, chairman and chief executive officer of Globix, the
Global Internet Exchange, with his parents Ruth and Robert Bell,
who work for him. In the world of Internet startups, where a
typical chief executive is 30 and a labor shortage continues even
as some dot-coms fail, dot-commers in more than a few cases are
recruiting their own parents. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SAN MATEO, Calif. -- June 20, 2000 -- INTERNET-PARENTS-1
-- At age 67, Lucille Lee is working for her son, Prescott, left,
who is 38 and head of the Internet company ECircles. Lee's
situation is not that unusual. In the world of Internet startups,
where a typical chief executive is 30 and a labor shortage
continues even as some dot-coms fail, dot-commers in more than a
few cases are recruiting their own parents. (Thor Swift/The New
York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) EL PASO, Texas -- June 20, 2000 -- TEXAS-PARDON-BOARD-2
-- The Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles is the state's death
penalty system's final safeguard against wrongful executions. The
board is a largely obscure state agency whose 18 members, scattered
in seven offices round the state, have only once voted for a
commutation in a death case and who have not held a public hearing
on a capital case since 1992. Charles Shipman, a board member,
reviewing a case in February. (Tom Lankes/Austin-American
Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) AUSTIN, Texas -- June 20, 2000 -- TEXAS-PARDON-BOARD --
The Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles is the state's death penalty
system's final safeguard against wrongful executions. The board is
a largely obscure state agency whose 18 members, scattered in seven
offices round the state, have only once voted for a commutation in
a death case and who have not held a public hearing on a capital
case since 1992. Rissie Owens, a member of the board, interviewing
Dwayne Rhodes, serving time for robbery, who has gone blind while
in prison and is requesting parole. (Tom Lankes/Austin-American
Statesman) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- June 20, 2000 -- GORE-COLLEGE-5 --
Much of what Al Gore had in mind when he signed up for the Harvard
that John F. Kennedy went to was on the way out by Gore's freshman
year. The impressions left on Gore during the heated years of the
Vietnam War at the school explain a few things about Al Gore today,
more then 30 years after he left the university. Gore in Vietnam in
1971. (Courtesy of Vice President Al Gore/The New York Times)
</P>
