<P>
   (NYT9) WOODS HOLE, Mass. -- June 20, 2000 -- SCI-SQUID-BOS
--They come to the shores of Cape Cod every year for a summer
mating festival, and they make biologists very, very happy. The
slim, translucent squid give scientists insight into everything
from the roots of Alzheimer's disease to the mechanics of vision,
and they're ripe for the picking in the waters around Woods Hole.
At the Marine Biological Laboratory in Woods Hole, scientist Roger
Hanlon keeps his eyes on a squid tank. (Bill Greene/The Boston
Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- June 20, 2000 --
BKN--MARBURY-ROBBED -- New Jersey Nets guard Stephon Marbury was
robbed early Tuesday when two men reached into his car at a red
light and grabbed a diamond necklace he said was worth $150,000.
Police said the men approached Marbury's Bentley in the Chelsea
section of Manhattan at about 3:45 a.m. Marbury, who had just left
a Manhattan club, was not hurt. The two suspects fled. Marbury
during a game against Miami Heat in February. (G. Paul Burnett/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- June 20, 2000 -- LAMA-VISIT -- The Dalai
Lama, the exiled spiritual and political leader of Tibet, center,
greets supporters before a meeting with Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
right, chairman of the Senate Foriegn Relations Committee, Tuesday
on Capitol Hill. At left is Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass. The Dalai Lama
is meeting with members of Congress for continuing discussions on
the future of Tibet. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 20, 2000 -- NY-POLICE-AUTHORS --Lucas
Miller, a New York City police detective and former narcotics
undercover officer, writes a column for an Internet publication,
Slate magazine. The column is yet another example of the allure of
New York police stories, a mystique primed by television shows from
``Kojak'' to ``Law and Order'' and countless movies and books.
These days, the genre is thriving. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WORCESTER, England -- June 20, 2000 -- BRITAIN
WORCESTERSHIRE 4 -- The sun has set on the British Empire, but not
on a handful of products that followed the Union Jack overseas like
Lea &AMP; Perrins Worcestershire Sauce. Factory manager Dave Clements
inspects the sauce in blending tanks in Worcestershire where the
sauce has been made since 1897. (Carlos Lopez-Barillas/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WORCESTER, England -- June 20, 2000 --
BRITAIN-WORCESTERSHIRE-3 -- The sun has set on the British Empire,
but not on a handful of products that followed the Union Jack
overseas like Lea &AMP; Perrins Worcestershire Sauce. Antique Lea &AMP;
