<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      06-20 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVE ON MOSCOW TV: QUIZ A TYCOON ABOUT HIS ARREST
</HEADLINE>
  By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The owner of Russia's largest independent media
conglomerate appeared on his NTV network today in a live call-in
show and charged that he was arrested and jailed last week at the
behest of President Vladimir V. Putin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure that Putin knew,'' said the media owner, Vladimir
Gusinsky. ``Moreover, the decision was taken personally by Mr.
President.''
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky was detained last week on charges of embezzling state
property and was thrown into a Moscow jail. Following complaints
from Russian tycoons, journalists and American officials that the
arrest was politically motivated, he was released after three days
and restricted to Moscow, pending trial.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has insisted he had no advance knowledge of the arrest, an
assertion few political experts seem to accept. And Tuesday night
Gusinsky used his television program for two hours as a prime-time
forum on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Leading pundits and politicians, including those who support
Putin and the chief ideologist for the Communist Party, joined the
fray. Viewers called in with their questions, not all of them
friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Some wanted to know how Gusinsky had made his fortune and
suggested that the media tycoon, a Jew who holds Israeli as well as
Russian citizenship, managed to get out of prison only because of
the clout of the Jewish lobby. But there was also a female caller
from Minsk, the capital of autocratic Belarus, who cast Gusinsky's
case as part of a broader struggle for civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't give in, and keep up the struggle,'' she said before
abruptly hanging up.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky quipped that the call lasted less than 30 seconds and
thus was hard for security forces to track.
</P>
<P>
   As the owner of the nation's only independent television network
and several publications, Gusinsky has often been in the spotlight,
but never as starkly as he was Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   A 47-year-old former theatrical director, he is one of a small
group of tycoons who have acquired enormous influence since the
collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky acknowledged tonight that he had deviated from the
principle of journalistic objectivity and used his company, Media
Most, to help re-elect President Boris Yeltsin in 1996. He said he
now regretted that role, which he said had led to a
quasi-autocratic government of aides intent on preserving their own
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We committed a serious error in 1996,'' Gusinsky said. ``In
1996, we gave birth to a small monster which has since grown into
the present system.''
</P>
<P>
   The injustice of the current system, he insisted, was driven
home to him during his brief stay in the Butyrskaya jail, where he
encountered inmates who had spent months in jail on the flimsy
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky was held in preventative detention for several days
before he was charged, and sought to challenge the legality of his
arrest today in court. But a Moscow court threw out his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   While his view of Putin's role is widely shared in the media,
the tycoon did not say how he had determined that the president was
behind his arrest. He also said he was convinced that Alexander
Voloshin, the Kremlin chief of staff, did not have advance
knowledge of his detention.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that does not relieve him of his responsibility,''
Gusinsky added.
</P>
<P>
   Many questions seemed to have more to do with Gusinsky than with
Putin. Viewers wanted to know, for instance, whether it was
possible to be both rich and honest in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The network's own anchor, Yevgeny Kiselyov, asked Gusinsky to
explain why he held Israeli citizenship, why his family lived
abroad and why he paid personal income tax in Gibraltar, questions
which appeared to be intended to give the media tycoon an
opportunity to explain his life to the Russian public.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the power elite feared that Gusinsky's arrest
might signal a broader crackdown, Putin continues to be popular
with much of the public, which likes his vision of a strong state.
</P>
<P>
   One journalist, Alexander Minkin, said much of the country
seemed to perceive the case differently than Moscow-based
opinion-makers did. That seemed to be underscored by a questioner
who suggested that the media tycoon was part of a system of corrupt
insider deals.
</P>
<P>
   In reply, Gusinsky noted the gains Russia has made in free
speech and press freedom _ a development this media empire has
contributed to substantially.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not asking for sympathy,'' he said. ``But the fact that
you could ask that question without ending up on the prison bunks
where I was indicates that things have improved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
