<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-INC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INC. MAGAZINE, WEB SITE MAY BE NEAR $200M SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Another Boston-based institution is close to being sold
as New York-based executives from Bertelsmann AG's Gruner &AMP; Jahr
publishing unit hammer out final details on the purchase of Inc.
magazine and its Web site for a reported $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Inc. founder Bernard Goldhirsh had put the business magazine and
other assets on the block earlier this year, after 20 years of
publishing a successful journal for small business owners and
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's circulation is about 660,000, though in recent
years Inc. has battled to maintain advertising as competitors
jumped in to copy the model and to narrow the targeted audience to
Internet entrepreneurs. The conferences and Web site side of the
business also has been on a plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Gruner &AMP; Jahr publishes McCall's, Family Circle, Parents,
Fitness, and YM, a teen title. The acquisition of Inc., and its
advertising possibilities in the technology and business sector,
will widen the magazine unit's horizons considerably. It would be
the first acquisition under Daniel Brewster, formerly head of
American Express publishing, who became chief executive of Gruner &AMP;
Jahr earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Other contenders were believed to be the investing arm of New
York investment bank Veronis, Suhler &AMP; Associates of New York, home
to Joel Novak, formerly the number two man at the Goldhirsh Group,
owner of Inc.; and Time Warner's Time Inc. publishing unit,
publisher of Fortune, Fortune Small Business and most recently
eCompany Now. Goldman, Sachs Group Inc. was hired to handle the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Goldhirsh, who reportedly became interested in selling Inc.
after his wife died and his own health started to fail, is well
regarded in business and publishing circles and known for founding
Sail magazine, which contained more how-to information than the
rival Yachting. Similarly, at its debut two decades ago, Inc.
provided more practical information for small business owners and
entrepreneurs than Fortune, Forbes and Business Week.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine and Web site business is based in Boston's
Charlestown section, near the waterfront.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
