<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9877 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SINGSING-EXHIBIT-2TAK     06-20 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGSING-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTIMATE VIEW OF THE DEATH HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUDSON, N.Y. _ ``Our children are the apple of our eye, our
pride and most precious fortune, love them with all your heart and
always protect them,'' Julius Rosenberg, convicted of espionage and
condemned to death, wrote in a letter to one of his lawyers from
Sing Sing on June 19, 1953, just hours before his execution. The
handwriting is shaky with frantic crossings out.
</P>
<P>
   He also paid tribute to his wife, Ethel, who was to be executed
along with him. ``Words fail me when I attempt to tell of the
nobility and grandeur of my life's companion, my sweet and devoted
wife. Ours is a great love and wonderful relationship, it has made
my life full and rich.''
</P>
<P>
   A photograph of Rosenberg's letter is on view in ``Condemned,''
an unusually intimate and powerful exhibition about Sing Sing's
death row that recently opened at Time and Space Limited, an arts
center in Hudson, in Columbia County about 75 miles north of the
prison site at Ossining.
</P>
<P>
   There is an inventory of Ethel's possessions at the time of her
death: dainty, feminine things; deodorant; stockings; a shoebox of
letters from her children. There is her last letter to the
children: ``Dearest Sweethearts, my most precious children,'' she
writes. ``We press you close and kiss you with all our strength,
lovingly Daddy and Mommy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lining the stark white walls of the exhibition at Time and Space
are mug shots of some 130 people who were executed at Sing Sing
Correctional Facility, photocopies of their final letters to loved
ones, autopsy reports, the menu for a last meal, and other
memorabilia. Between 1891 and 1963, the year of the last legal
execution in New York State, more people _ 614 _ were executed at
Sing Sing than at any other prison. For years hence there were no
executions because of legal challenges and the opposition of two
governors, Hugh L. Carey and Mario M. Cuomo. In 1995, Gov. George
E. Pataki signed legislation reinstating capital punishment, but no
one has yet been executed under that law.
</P>
<P>
   Sing Sing has long held an almost mythological place in American
culture. Many books have been written about the prison and many
movies have been set there, including ``20,000 Years in Sing Sing''
and ``Each Dawn I Die.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the notorious people who met death there were Louis
(Lepke) Buchalter, the boss of the Brooklyn gang Murder Inc., which
was believed to be responsible for more than 20 murders. He was
convicted of ordering the shooting of a garment trucker.
</P>
<P>
   Also executed there were Martha Beck and Raymond Fernandez, the
so-called Lonely Hearts Killers. Fernandez met Beck, a nurse,
through a pen pal club for the lovelorn, the exhibition notes.
During the 1940s and '50s, the pair made headlines for swindling
lonely women, and they were eventually condemned for murdering a
woman with a hammer. Beck told prison officials when she arrived at
Sing Sing that crime was ``something I got into. I had no
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the crimes are particularly gruesome. Arthur Johnson,
21, was convicted of strangling and raping a 15-year-old girl.
Edward Haight was convicted of murdering two girls, 6 and 8. It is
recounted under his mug shot that he told prison officials, ``I
don't know why I did it.'' Frederick Wood, a salesman, was accused
of killing one man with a bottle, another with a shovel. A prison
official noted, the exhibition label relates, that Wood said ``he
hates homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   During sentencing procedures, the relatives of crime victims are
often given an opportunity to describe their loss to the court in
emotionally gripping ways. But this exhibition focuses on the
private emotions of some who were sent to the chair at Sing Sing
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition was organized by Scott Christianson, former
deputy director of parole operations for New York State, who
resigned from his job in 1995 in opposition to reinstitution of the
death penalty. He is now director of the New York Death Penalty
Documentation Project, an effort to gather the official record
regarding the state's administration of capital punishment. In
assembling the show, Christian drew on research for his book
``Condemned,'' published in March by New York University Press.
</P>
<P>
   The records on which the exhibition is based were stored at Sing
Sing and inaccessible to outsiders until 1977, when they went to
the New York State Archives in Albany. After being catalogued, they
were made available to Christianson in 1997 under the state's
Freedom of Information law. Now that the death penalty is legal
again in New York, Christianson said, ``I thought it was even more
important for people to have an opportunity to view this reality
they've ignored or not gotten access to.''
</P>
<P>
   Many letters in the exhibition are intimate, almost naked in
their emotion. ``There is no definition in the law as to what
constitutes an unwarranted invasion of privacy,'' said James D.
Folts, supervisor of reference services for the New York State
Archives, in explaining why the records were released to
Christianson.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition includes details about executions written by
prison officials in a matter-of-fact style.
</P>
<P>
   After the Rosenbergs went to the electric chair, the executioner
penciled in the time and the duration of the event on an index
card, a photograph of which is also in the exhibit: ``Julius
Rosenberg, SSP (NU)110-649. Time in: 8:04, Time Out: 8:06}. Amps
8.'' A record of Ethel's death: `` Time In: 8:11{, Time Out 8:16.''
Ethel required 6{ amps. But it took several doses of electricity to
kill her.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition continues through July 16.
</P>
<P>
   The records cover roughly 20 percent of the executions at Sing
Sing. ``I would hope the state could provide detailed records that
could be a basis for a challenge in the Supreme Court, if it is
shown that the death penalty was administered in an arbitrary or
capricious or racist way,'' Christianson said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped that the documents could be used to challenge
the death penalty in court by substantiating the argument that a
disproportionate number of blacks are executed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
