<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ME-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF SOCIETY'S DYING, AT LEAST IT'LL DIE LAUGHING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Carrey and the Farrelly brothers achieve something like
perfect baroque crudity with ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' their latest
comedy about all things that the human body can drip, ooze or
secrete.
</P>
<P>
   Moreso than in the comparatively restrained ``Dumb &AMP; Dumber,''
the zany comic dynamo and the writing-directing siblings prove that
their sickest sensiblities were made for one another. In
``Irene,''In ``Irene,'' they have crafted a densely packed circus
of scattershot insults, dirty jokes and bruising slapstick that is
often infernally hilarious _ and, yes, well out in front,
imagination- and daring-wise, of most competitors in the offensive
comedy sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   But even though it's a pleasure to report that Carrey's return
to full- throttled wackiness is among his best performances ever,
``Irene'' falls short of the giddy heights the Farrellys hit in
their last directing effort, ``There's Something About Mary.'' That
film did the impossible _ or at least, so far, unrepeatable _ for
this subgenre. It actually populated its outlandish gagscapes with
people you really believed could exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irene'' is not designed to pull off anything that difficult.
It's more purely a farce, with a knockabout road movie structure
that lends itself more to incident than character development. And
with Carrey playing two outsized caricatures in this one, there
ain't much room _ nor need _ for subtle behavioral niceties.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Carrey fits some remarkably understated effects in
the margins of all the foaming lunacy. As you're probably aware, he
pays a Rhode Island state trooper with a split personality
disorder. The cop's usual persona, kind but wimpy Charlie
Baileygates, keeps losing control to a vengeful Id monster that
calls himself Hank, hisses like Clint Eastwood at his most
intimdating and gets into all kinds of psychic and physical
trouble. Hank's nasty jags are vintage, inspired Carrey, but some
of the actor's Jekyll-to-Hyde transitions, as well as a scene or
two when he's operating through several layers of deception, have a
quiet canniness that's as complex and accomplished as anything he's
ever done.
</P>
<P>
   Hank and Charlie both fall in love with Renee Zellweger's Irene,
whom the entity escorts to answer an outstanding warrant in upstate
New York. The film's nonplot, which the Farrellys co-wrote with
childhood pal Mike Cerrone, has something to do with crooked cops
and land developers. But it's really just an excuse for Carrey and
the Farrellys to pull outrageous stunts against deceptively bucolic
backdrops.
</P>
<P>
   Terrible things are done to a cow, a chicken, a new mother,
innocent members of the law enforcement industry, young children
and a resilient albino fellow named, tastefully, Whitey (played by
droll newcomer Michael Bowman). Everybody is made merciless fun of,
including the game Zellweger's hard-pressed straightwoman, but no
one is mortified more frequently or severely than Carrey's
characters. Taking the sadomasochistic element that's always been
part of his comedy to the limit, Carrey violates and subjects
himself to every conceivable humiliation _ and a few most of us
mere mortals have thankfully never thought of.
</P>
<P>
   I keep coming back to Carrey's performance because it is that
unforgettably extreme. But even with all the effort he puts in, he
almost loses the film's comedy spotlight to three latter day
Stooges. Anthony Anderson, Mongo Brownlee and Jerod Mixon play _
are you ready for this? _ the three genius triplets Charlie's
runaway wife had with an African- American dwarf, whom he's
selflessly raised as his own. Somehow, though, the three hefty sons
talk trashier than Tupac; you've never heard atomic theory debated
quite the way they do.
</P>
<P>
   It's all utterly inexcusable. And uproarious. These guys have
such exuberant energy and fluid group timing that their foulmouthed
antics rise to the level of verbal ballet. Of course, it's also
disgusting, demented and evidence, if you want it to be, that civil
society is greatly endangered if not already dead and buried.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what all of ``Me, Myself and Irene'' is like. You can
hold your nose or laugh about it . . . but really, there's only one
viable option.
</P>
<P>
   ____ &QL; 
The film: ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' (R; language, violence, racism,
really dirty jokes) &QL; 
The stars: Jim Carrey, Renee Zellweger, Chris Cooper, Anthony
Anderson, Mongo Brownlee, Jerod Mixon, Michael Bowman &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Peter and Bobby Farrelly. Written by
the Farrellys and Mike Cerrone. Produced by Bradley Thomas.
Released by 20th Century Fox. &QL; 
Running time: 1 hour, 57 minutes &QL; 
Playing: Citywide
</P>
</TEXT>
