<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9879 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SINGSING-EXHIBIT-2NDT     06-20 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGSING-EXHIBIT-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
HUDSON, N.Y.: are executed.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sing Sing prison was built in 1825. The name comes from a Native
American tribe known as ``Sint Sinck,'' or ``stone upon stone,''
referring to the rocky terrain. An engraving from Harper's magazine
from the 1870s shows an idealized view of the prison as a
self-contained universe, with a hospital and sanitation facilities,
a nursery and a women's prison. There is a photograph of the ornate
warden's office with its wood paneling and coffered ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Another photograph shows a ``torture chair,'' as some convicts
referred to it, with a blindfolded and shackled prisoner. Sitting
upon it, the inmate was doused with water. Some drowned or died
from exposure, Christianson said. By the 1830s whippings were so
common at the prison that Sing Sing became known as a
``catocracy,'' after the cat o' nine tails.
</P>
<P>
   The first electric chair was built around 1889 and was designed
in the laboratory of Thomas Edison. Edison, an advocate of direct
current, was competing with George Westinghouse, who favored
alternating current. Edison suggested using Westinghouse's
alternating current for the electric chair to dramatize how
dangerous his rival's method could be for everyday use.
</P>
<P>
   The first execution by electric chair at Sing Sing took place in
1891. From 1920 to 1941, the prison's warden was Lewis E. Lawes,
who was an opponent of capital punishment. But he presided over 303
executions. The exhibition the well-known photograph of the
execution of Ruth Snyder in 1928, taken by a Daily News reporter
with a hidden camera, in which her body seems to shake with a
tremendous force.
</P>
<P>
   Death was not always instantaneous, Christianson pointed out,
and it sometimes required repeated administrations of electricity.
Sometimes the condemned person caught fire. There was debate about
whether death was caused by the electricity or by the autopsy that
quickly followed.
</P>
<P>
   One autopsy report from 1951 in the exhibition notes: ``The
cerebellum seen from the posterior surfaces is opaque and grayish
in color. It has a boiled appearance. The whole brain is
uncomfortably warm to the touch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my contention that one of the reasons legal autopsies
were made a requirement was not only an attempt to determine the
nature of death, but also to insure death,'' Christianson said.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of escapes from death row, a new death house was
built in 1920. It was called by The New York Times ``the most
impregnable penal institution in the world,'' and it began
executions in 1922. The death house had cells, an execution
chamber, a hospital, and an office for the ``Lunacy Commission,''
where prisoners were examined to see if they were sane when they
committed their crime. Radiating out from the execution chamber
were six staging areas, known as ``the Dance Hall.'' Adjoining the
chamber was a room where the executioner was concealed.
</P>
<P>
   The mug shots at Time and Space were taken when the condemned
arrived at the prison. Many prisoners wear the suits and ties they
had on for their sentencing in court. There is a mix of expressions
on the faces: panic, defiance, bewilderment. Most are young, some
only 17, like Norman Roye, a smooth-faced black youth with a
sorrowful look. Under the photo is his date of birth and the crime
of which he was convicted, strangling an old woman. He claimed
innocence and was executed on Jan. 9, 1956.
</P>
<P>
   There are letters from prisoners begging for mercy. Helen
Fowler, 37 and a mother of five, convicted of murder, wrote a
rambling letter to Lt. Gov. Hanley: ``I have a little boy, 10; one,
5; a girl of 14; one, 18; one, 20; a grandchild.'' She could not
hear the testimony at her trial, she said, because she was partly
deaf. According to the prosecutor, someone else actually killed the
victim. Fowler was convicted because she helped dispose of the
body. She was executed in November 1944.
</P>
<P>
   In one case a man was executed despite the last-minute plea of
his co-defendant that he was innocent. Two Chinese men, Lew York
Hing and Yun Tieh Li, were accused of killing a woman during a
robbery. But in a letter to Chief Justice Lehman, Yun Tieh Li wrote
that Lew York Hing ``had nothing to do with this murder. The one
who Do the killing in this case is `me and Eddie,''' a reference to
an unknown third person. Still, both Yun Tieh Li and Lew York Hing
were executed in August 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Some prisoners were mentally disabled or illiterate. A
psychiatrist described Oliver Little, 19, a laborer, convicted of
stabbing a man to death, as ``mentally defective, borderline
level.'' Yet the execution was legal.
</P>
<P>
   As the hour of death approached, the prisoners were entitled to
choose their final meal. Prisoner No. 123-881, Henry Flakes, asked
for barbecued chicken and strawberry shortcake with whipped cream.
Many prisoners sat down to write a last letter. For some it
appeared to be a psychological imperative, a spiritual ritual that
had a cleansing effect. Frank Newman, convicted of murdering his
wife, had claimed temporary insanity and acute alcoholism. ``I do
not believe I could describe how much I despise myself for this
terrible thing,'' he wrote to his sons in August 1956, the day
before he died. ``I loved Mother. I pray to God to forgive me and
that my boys will try to soften the terrible hatred you have for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   In another letter, from Jan. 14, 1960, Ivory Mason, convicted of
shooting a woman, wrote to his mother: ``Just a few lines to let
you hear from me as this will be my last letter to you.'' When
Mason arrived at Sing Sing, he was illiterate but later learned to
read and write. ``I must tarry on to my maker from which I come.
But don't worry mother. I have made my peace with God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And mother since you did not come to see me,'' he continued,
``I forgive you. I understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason ended with a plea for forgiveness: ``Sorry if I cause you
any heart ache and pains if so please forgive me. So I will close
and until we meet beyond the river it is well remembered I were
your Son.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
