<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JITTERS OVER PROFIT REPORTS PUSH DOW SHARPLY LOWER 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks were mixed Tuesday as concerns about corporate
profit growth hurt old-line manufacturing concerns even as
enthusiasm about the earnings prospects for technology companies
continued to rise.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, composed of many old economy
names, fell 122.68 points, or 1.2 percent, to 10,435.16. The
decline, which was led by General Motors and Honeywell, wiped out
Monday's 108.54-point advance.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nasdaq composite index rose for a fourth consecutive
session. Fueled by gains in stocks like Intel, Yahoo and Apple
Computer, the index gained 23.53, or 0.6 percent, to 4,013.36. It
was the first time in more than two months that the Nasdaq has
closed above 4,000. The index remains far below its March 10 record
of 5,048.62. But with its recent recovery, the index is now down
just 1.4 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be impressed by the continued recovery of
technology stocks, both large and small cap, and the deterioration
of the old economy issues,'' said James Paulson, chief investment
officer at Wells Capital Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is still a sense we are caught in a box: either the
economy is slowing much faster than anyone expects, which is a
negative, or the Fed is not finished tightening because the economy
is still growing strongly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index slipped 10.05, or 0.7
percent, to 1,475.95, as weakness in stocks like Tyco International
and Cisco Systems more than offset gains in America Online, Time
Warner and Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   After the market closed, Oracle, the world's biggest maker of
database software, reported fourth-quarter earnings that beat Wall
Street's estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the results, the stock, which closed Tuesday at 86 3/64,
up 3/64, fell after hours to as low as 83.
</P>
<P>
   Bad earnings news hurt GM after the automaker said its North
American operations would miss profit margin goals because of
declining car prices. And Honeywell fell sharply for a second day
after saying earnings would fall short of estimates.
</P>
<P>
   GM slumped 2 13/16, to 62 1/16. Honeywell dropped 3~, to a
52-week low of 36 3/8. The last two trading sessions, Honeywell's
stock price has fallen more than 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement from GM pulled down the other automakers. Ford
Motor fell 1 7/8, to 43, and DaimlerChrysler lost 1 1/16, to 54
3/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earnings preannouncements have been holding the market back,''
said Bryan Piskorowski, a market analyst at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have not had a major technology bellwether preannounce
an earnings shortfall, and that has allowed the Nasdaq to resume
its leadership role. As we muddle our way through to earnings
season, there is room on the upside, even if the Federal Reserve
Board raises short-term interest rates by one-quarter of a
percentage point.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel and Micron Technology were among the technology stocks
that helped lead the group's advance. Intel, which soared on
Monday, gained an additional 1 13/16 Tuesday, to close at 138 5/16.
And Micron rose 9, to 89].
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage stocks did better on unexpected strength in
second-quarter earnings from Goldman Sachs, whose results beat Wall
Street expectations. After an early rally, its shares closed at 89,
down 2|. But the results helped push up Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter's stock 2[, to 86 9/16. And Merrill Lynch rose 3{, to 122.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
