u a BC-WACO-LAWSUIT-HNS &LR;      06-20 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS SPAR OVER CULPABILITY AT DAVIDIAN COMPOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DICK J. REAVIS  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Militant followers of David Koresh may have set
one of the three fires that are blamed in the deaths of 74
residents of the Branch Davidian compound in 1993, an attorney for
Davidian survivors told a packed courtroom Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Caddell, lead plaintiffs attorney in the wrongful death
suit being brought against the federal government, declared in his
opening remarks that, ``Once the building was on fire, it appears
that a few persons in the gymnasium area started a fire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They believed that it would protect them,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell did not elaborate on his theory about the blaze,
although his comments set him at odds with other plaintiffs
attorneys, who do not agree that Davidians set any of the fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government was responsible for everything that happened
here,'' former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark told the court.
Clark is representing a group of adult Davidians who have remained
loyal to the faith.
</P>
<P>
   During his opening argument for the defense, U.S. attorney
Michael Bradford of Beaumont, Texas, maintained that the Davidians
``didn't just start one of those fires, they started all of the
fires.''
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs and defense attorneys outlined contrasting scenarios
for the 1993 events during separate 55-minute presentations Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell began by showing jurors photos and a videotape of the 25
children who died during the 1993 standoff. He argued that during
the initial raid on Feb. 28, government agents fired
indiscriminately at the Davidian residence hall and worship center,
endangering unarmed women and children. Cadell also argued that
agents fired pyrotechnic tear-gas rounds into the building April
19, the day of the fire, and contributed to the blaze by attempting
to demolish the building.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents were also negligent, he charged, in failing to
develop a plan for combating any fire that might develop at the
Davidian compound near Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about truth and responsibility, truth about what
happened at (the compound) and responsibility for it,'' the
plaintiffs attorney told the jury of four women and three men.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford countered that on Feb. 28, during the initial raid,
federal agents deployed ``cover fire,'' instead of firing
indiscriminately, as Caddell alleged.
</P>
<P>
   The gunfire ``was in defense of their lives,'' Bradford said,
pointing out that four ATF agents were killed in the shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford denied that any devices capable of starting a blaze
were fired into the Davidian compound on April 19. He said that the
destruction of its gymnasium, shortly before flames were spotted,
was a byproduct of attempts to penetrate the building with tear
gas.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents, in charge of federal operations at the time, did not
develop a firefighting plan because ``it was too dangerous to send
firemen into that situation,'' Bradford argued.
</P>
<P>
   Opening arguments concluded in the case before noon, and
following a short break, Caddell began to build the plaintiffs'
case with witness testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston lawyer's strategy is to show that adult males from
both the Davidian and federal camps needlessly endangered women and
children at the cult compound, bringing about the deaths of some 50
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, he called three female witnesses, all of whom
testified that the windows to their rooms on the second floor _
where only women and children lived _ were shattered by gunshots
fired by ATF agents. All three witnesses exited the compound
several days before the April 19 fire. One of the witnesses,
Natalie Nobrega, now 18, told the court that during the shootout,
``All of my quilt coverings were just full of holes. If I had been
sleeping, I don't think that I'd be here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobrega was 11 at the time. Her mother, Theresa, 48, died during
the April 19 fire.
</P>
<P>
   All three witnesses denied they were armed during the ATF raid.
They also denied seeing any women with guns. For witness Jaunessa
Wendell, that denial contradicted earlier statements.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Feb. 28 events, Wendell, then 8 years old,
told a Texas Ranger that her mother, ``laid down, got a gun and
started firing.''
</P>
<P>
   She also told the Ranger that Tuesday's third female witness,
Rita Riddle, 42, had been armed.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon she repudiated much of what she had said
during her childhood interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very scared at the time,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Jaydean, 34, was killed during the Feb. 28 gunfight;
her father, Mark, 40, died during the April 19 conflagration.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Dick Reavis by e-mail at dreavis(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
