<HEADER>
A9892 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BALLETS-RUSSES-DANCE-     06-20 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLETS-RUSSES-DANCE-$ADV25-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HAPPY GATHERING OF THE BALLETS RUSSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday June 25)  
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Everyone kissed everyone else and the kisses were
wonderful to behold. People kissed on lecture platforms, in a hotel
lobby, at an art gallery, at receptions. There were delighted cries
of, ``My dear, I haven't seen you for 50 years!'' And the remark
was not hyperbole. Happy tears flowed like Champagne. Champagne
also flowed.
</P>
<P>
   All this happened at the Ballets Russes celebration, an
extraordinary event that took place here June 1-4. It honored the
three great companies with Ballets Russes in their names: Sergei
Diaghilev's pioneering Ballets Russes (1909-29) and the successor
troupes of Col. W. de Basil (1932-52) and Sergei Denham (1938-62).
Their achievements never fail to amaze. By producing works by
choreographers like Michel Fokine, Leonide Massine, Vaslav
Nijinsky, Bronislava Nijinska and George Balanchine and, later,
David Lichine, Frederick Ashton and Agnes de Mille, these
cosmopolitan companies of dancers of many nationalities
significantly altered our basic concepts of dance aesthetics. By
constantly touring the world, they also introduced thousands of
people to ballet. The first ballet company I ever saw was Denham's.
And I was hooked on dance.
</P>
<P>
   A Ballets Russes reunion committee had been planning a
get-together for almost three years without ever holding one.
Fortunately, the committee allied itself with two balletomanes:
Douglas Blair Turnbaugh, a New York-based representative of the
International Dance Council of Unesco, and Olga Guardia de Smoak,
president of the New Orleans International Ballet Conference. And,
miraculously, with the help of a band of devoted volunteers, the
celebration happened. It attracted students, dance fans and
scholars from North and South America, Europe, Australia and Japan,
and when dancers of the former Ballets Russes companies assembled
onstage, they numbered 65. Many of them also taught and lectured.
And all were voluble conversationalists.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement was evident from the beginning, with people
scurrying to check in at the Sheraton Hotel, which, along with the
New Orleans Center for the Creative Arts, was the site of most of
the events. There were little shrieks of delight that increased in
volume later that evening at the opening of an exhibition of
Ballets Russes memorabilia at the New Orleans Museum of Art. The
euphoria was infectious, and New Orleans residents who attended
events became as excited as the dancers.
</P>
<P>
   That did not surprise Adda Pourmel, a Ballets Russes dancer who
has settled here. ``All they need in this town is an excuse for a
party _ and the longer the better,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the marvelous presences at this party were the elegant
Irina Baronova, one of the legendary ``baby ballerinas'' of the
'30s (``Oh, how we all resented that name when we got older,'' she
recalled), and other ballerinas like Mia Slavenska, Nathalie
Krassovska, Tatiana Stepanova, Irina Borowska and Nina Novak.
Moscelyne Larkin, an American Indian ballerina from Oklahoma, was
there. So was Raven Wilkinson who, when she joined Denham's group
in 1956, became the first black dancer to perform with a company
that regularly toured America. The celebration also attracted Nini
Theilade, a Danish dancer of legendary radiance (she can be seen as
the lyrical first fairy in Max Reinhardt's 1935 film version of ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream''). Unusual at the time, she was a ballet
dancer who was also interested in modern dance. Her hair has
grayed, but her vitality has not dimmed even though she has just
celebrated her 85th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The men present included premier danseurs like George Zoritch
and Alan Howard, and there was Marc Platt, who went on from the
Ballets Russes to a Broadway and Hollywood career, Robert Barnett,
who became the director of the Atlanta Ballet, and Robert Lindgren,
who founded the dance department at the innovative North Carolina
School of the Arts. Of course, no Ballets Russes assembly would be
complete without Frederic Franklin, a human perpetual-motion
machine who, at 86, keeps busy staging ballets and advising
companies everywhere. But he arrived late, for first he had to
portray Friar Laurence in American Ballet Theater's ``Romeo and
Juliet'' in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone had stories to tell. There was the one about the Texas
tour when the dancers' train broke down and they were herded onto a
bus with a large hole in its floor, through which they could see
the road beneath them as they sped over it. Then there was the time
when the train was stuck for three days in a snowstorm in the
Canadian Rockies. On one bus tour, when the dancers felt a need to
limber up, the driver would stop at any flat field with a wire
fence around it. Holding onto the fence, the company would go
through its exercises before the eyes of inquisitive cows and
startled passing motorists.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   But this was also a serious and aesthetically provocative event.
There was a performance at which dancers from 12 companies
volunteered their services to perform excerpts from the Ballets
Russes repertories. Yet some of these items looked hastily staged.
Of greater interest was the intermission, during which backdrops
from several Ballets Russes productions were shown onstage.
Particularly stunning were Eugene Berman's handsome Italian
Renaissance square for Ashton's ``Devil's Holiday,'' Henri
Matisse's monumental arches for Massine's ``Rouge et Noir,''
Salvador Dali's desolate bone-strewn landscape for Massine's
``Bacchanal'' and the charming California mining community Raoul
Pene Du Bois designed for Platt's ``Ghost Town.''
</P>
<P>
   But the truly important events were the panel discussions and
lecture demonstrations. Theilade taught a fascinating modern-dance
class for ballet dancers that emphasized bending, stretching and
wavelike movements designed to promote freedom and fluidity in the
upper body. Larkin showed how certain fluttering movements Fokine
devised in ``Les Sylphides'' gain special vitality if one realizes
that he wished dancers to imagine that they were sprites gesturally
sending messages abroad on the winds. Tatiana Leskova bubbled as
she coached a young dancer in the giddy Frivolity solo from
Massine's ``Presages.''
</P>
<P>
   Dramatic sequences from ``Giselle'' were demonstrated by
Krassovska, in the title role, with Victor Moreno as Albrecht and
Miguel Terekhov as Hilarion, all over 70. What could have looked
merely odd became a lesson in expressiveness. Thus, in the mad
scene, it was fascinating to see Krassovska's shy Giselle steadily
slip from reality into a strange supernatural realm.
</P>
<P>
   Most thrilling of all was Baronova's interpretation of the mimed
passage in ``The Sleeping Beauty'' in which the Lilac Fairy defies
the evil fairy's curse. The ballerina's eloquent hands and fingers
made every gesture meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   So much of what the Ballets Russes companies represented is
being lost. Panelist after panelist lamented how today's emphasis
upon speedy feet has led to a neglect of nuanced movements for the
upper body. And the erosion of repertory is appalling. The Ballets
Russes danced major works that are now almost totally forgotten:
among them, masterpieces by the unusually versatile and often
daring Massine. Although Balanchine's ballets are being carefully
preserved, no one drew up plans to save Massine's.
</P>
<P>
   But, provided one acts now, some may be salvageable. Dancers
with sharp memories who know and love them came to New Orleans.
Enterprising companies should call upon them now. By preserving the
best of the Ballets Russes style and repertory, troupes today can
make the celebration continue artistically for years to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
