u e BC-FLORENCE-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      06-20 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORENCE-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM MAY TO JUNE SOMETHING FOR THE EARS IN FLORENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORENCE, Italy _ In a city where you spend the day living
through your eyes, the annual music festival provides compensatory
evenings for the ears. It is one of the oldest such festivals _ the
present is the 63rd _ and it long ago outgrew its name of Maggio
Musicale (Musical May): events start in the middle of April and go
on until the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Performances are rather spread out over this period, and there
is not too much focus. Zubin Mehta is the principal director, and
he was around earlier to conduct the opening presentation of ``La
Traviata'' and a couple of concerts. Other musicians to appear this
year have included Maurizio Pollini and Radu Lupu.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the Maggio makes a point of contemporary music. Last
month there was a program of orchestral works by Azio Corghi and a
new opera by Giorgio Battistelli, who seems to come up with an
opera almost every other year. This time his surprising subject was
Raymond Roussel's novel ``Impressions of Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   In the city where opera was born, Monteverdi's ``Coronation of
Poppaea'' was an appropriate choice a month back. Now the festival
is presenting Tchaikovsky's ``Eugene Onegin,'' still something of a
rarity in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The musical preparation was in the hands of Semyon Bychkov, one
of the Maggio's favorite conductors, though Monday night the baton
was taken over by Kirill Petrenko, a younger Russian beginning to
make a mark in Austrian and German opera houses. He proved very
capable. The Maggio Musicale's orchestra is unpolished, but
Petrenko kept it smartly on track and was sensitive to his singers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cast, Galina Gorchakova compensated for vocal problems
_ trouble pitching high notes and a diminishment of rapture _ with
a noble bearing. In the last scene, the passion of her acting
seemed to bring back some of the old glory in her voice.
</P>
<P>
   The other principals were non-Russian, and, in some cases, not
too familiar with the style. Ramon Vargas, as Lensky, sang sweetly
and freely in the first act but became overwrought in the second.
Ferruccio Furlanetto looked appropriately grave and proud as Gremin
but grossly sentimentalized his aria by singing it as if close to
tears.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Frontali, though, was excellent in the title role. His
singing was always perfectly turned out: neatly phrased, secure,
elegant. Then in the final scene, where Onegin at last loses his
destructive self-possession, Frontali did not drop those qualities
but, far more effectively, heightened and emphasized them. He is a
fine, intelligent singer, and his Russian was convincing.
</P>
<P>
   The musical performance was also distinguished by Irini
Karaianni as Olga and by vigorous singing from the Maggio chorus,
rehearsed by Jose Luis Basso.
</P>
<P>
   On the visual side, the greatest impression was made by the
Pushkin-period costumes, designed by Joachim Herzog and beautifully
made. Christoph Sehl's sets featured wide spaces and tall birch
trunks, often surrounding and sometimes invading the interior
scenes. There were oddities of a similar kind, neither striking nor
meaningful, in Alexander Schulin's production. Having Onegin and
Olga dance in slow motion during the second-act ball, for instance,
made no sense when the music was up to speed, and just looked
clumsy.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, to end the festival, David Robertson conducts a
Stravinsky concert _ the Symphony of Psalms and ``Le Sacre du
Printemps'' _ out in the Piazza della Signoria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
