<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9898 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN--BIRD-HNS &LR;      06-20 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--BIRD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Bird leaves Pacers, but not exactly on his terms
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LOS ANGELES _ After eight years in the NBA, Shaquille O'Neal
finally won his championship Monday night, and he no longer could
control his emotions, each tear seeming to represent one of the
many criticisms that have dogged him since he entered the league.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird, too, looked as if he wanted to cry as he watched his
Pacers trudge off the court after the Lakers' 116-11 Game 6
victory.
</P>
<P>
   But Bird, who came so close to leading the underdog Pacers to a
championship, stood firm, his stone face chiseled into unemotional
hardness. There would be no emotion for the cameras to gobble up.
No tearful farewells. Just a quick: ``Nice knowing ya. See y'all
later.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bird almost did it.
</P>
<P>
   He almost pulled off his three-year plan with the Indiana
Pacers. But unfortunately, that time frame happened to coincide
with Phil Jackson's one-year plan with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   True to his word, Bird took the Pacers to their first NBA Finals
appearance just three years after taking over the perennially
disappointing (or underachieving) team, only to get rolled by the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   For the Lakers, the newly minted title is the franchise's
seventh since moving to Los Angeles in 1960 and 12th overall,
counting the five won by the Minneapolis Lakers in the 1940s and
'50s.
</P>
<P>
   The latest title came just one year and three days after Jackson
was named coach and was the franchise's first since Magic Johnson
and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar led the ``Lake Show'' to the 1988
championship, the last of five NBA crowns in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, who won three championships in the defunct American
Basketball Association, are left to ponder what could have been. Or
what will be.
</P>
<P>
   Now, again true to his word, Bird is stepping down as coach of
the Pacers, despite his wildly successful tenure with his
home-state team. And despite that success, Bird said leaving the
game on a losing note will eat at him for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably won't be happy again,'' Bird said. ``I'll probably
be miserable the rest of my life, to tell you the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to walk away from a team that is still fully
capable of contending for a championship is confusing to many. But
the players who have spent the past three years learning to forget
about Bird the Hall of Fame player and accept him as coach respect
his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I really can't (explain it),'' said point guard Mark
Jackson. ``I don't think anybody can. I respect the fact that he
made a decision from day one and then stuck to it when a lot of
people probably wouldn't have _ especially when they get a taste of
what has been accomplished this year. So I respect that. But, you
know, he's a different breed.''
</P>
<P>
   Which might go a long way toward explaining the decision.
</P>
<P>
   He compiled a 147-67 regular-season record in his three years,
winning Coach of the Year honors after a 58-24 season his first
year with the Pacers. And his team went at least as far as the
Eastern Conference finals all three years (34-19 record), losing to
Michael Jordan's Bulls in 1998 and the Knicks in 1999 before
breaking through this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Bird cannot tolerate being second-best, and the man who
drove the Boston Celtics to NBA championships can't accept losing,
even if it is in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that there's only one winner, and I've always felt that
way,'' Bird said. ``Whoever they crown champion is the only winner
that's going to be there. So it's not that I'm real disappointed in
what we've accomplished, because we've had some great games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played our hearts out, (but) there's only one champion. I'm
disappointed in the fact that we didn't get an opportunity to play
in the seventh game.''
</P>
<P>
   What he means is they didn't get a chance to win, which must irk
Bird, because many think the Pacers blew a couple of Finals games
because of inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was their first time here,'' said NBC's Isiah Thomas,
perhaps getting a head start on the critical analysis of what might
be his team next season. ``They weren't ready for it at the
beginning. They gave the first two games away. They didn't start
playing until Game 3 in Indiana (a 100-91 Pacers victory). That was
too late.''
</P>
<P>
   So now the focus shifts to his replacement. The early favorite
seems to be Thomas, who owns the Continental Basketball
Association. If that's true, Thomas is letting no one in on the
secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what people are saying, but it's too early to tell,''
said Thomas of the speculation he will take over as Pacers coach.
``It depends on what (Pacers president Donnie Walsh) decides. I
should know in the next couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the organization continue to hope Bird changes his mind
and comes back to coach the Pacers. After all, the team intends to
make every effort to bring back free agents Reggie Miller, Jalen
Rose and Rik Smits for another run.
</P>
<P>
   But they are now left to savor the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a larger-than-life figure in this state, in this
city and in basketball,'' said Pacers general manager David Kahn.
``Sometimes I looked down the bench and I found myself saying,
`Wait a minute _ that's Larry Bird coaching our team.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think time will tell, but I think it will be three of
the finest seasons the franchise will ever have seen. I'm not
conceding anything yet (as far as Bird's retirement), but I don't
think people will understand it until later what his presence has
meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a huge aftershock somewhere down the line and
you'll say, `You know what? Larry Bird coached us for three years.'
That was pretty incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Incredible and over.
</P>
<P>
   Bye, bye Birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's been a great experience,'' Bird said.
``Unfortunately, it's over, but it's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
