</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIFFERING VIEWS OFFERED FOR FACTS IN WACO SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ A lawsuit filed against the government by
survivors and relatives of those killed in the 1993 fire at the
Branch Davidian compound began Tuesday with the two sides giving
different interpretations of the same basic facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about truth and responsibility,'' said Michael A.
Caddell, the lead attorney for the plaintiffs. ``We'll hear the
truth about what happened at Mount Carmel and who bears the
responsibility for what happened, including the death of 25
children.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Michael Bradford, the U.S. attorney in Texas, told the
federal judge and seven-member advisory jury hearing the case that
responsibility was also the theme of his defense. ``The
responsibility for this tragedy is with David Koresh and the Branch
Davidians,'' Bradford said.
</P>
<P>
   The case grew out of a botched raid in which 10 people died,
including 4 Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms agents who were
trying to arrest the religious leader, Koresh, for weapons
violations. After a 51-day standoff, Koresh and more than 75 of his
followers died when fire broke out as federal agents used armored
vehicles to pump tear gas into the sect's ramshackle Mount Carmel
compound.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said the Branch Davidians had ambushed the 80 officers
involved in the first raid on Feb. 28, 1993. He said Koresh had
trained them to use weapons in anticipation of just such a
confrontation, and quoted him as telling his followers, `If you
can't kill for God, you can't die for God.'''
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs are asking for $695 million in damages from the
government, accusing federal agents of contributing to the deaths
of the Branch Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   Other allegations made by the plaintiffs, that agents fired into
the compound, preventing the Branch Davidians from fleeing, will be
heard later, according to an order by the judge, Walter S. Smith
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Saying his lawsuit revolves around four issues, Caddell ticked
them off: Did federal agents direct indiscriminate gunfire at the
compound during the initial raid? Did the FBI deviate from their
approved operational plan? Did unauthorized FBI action cause or
contribute to the fire? And did the FBI violate Attorney General
Janet Reno's orders by not having firefighting equipment available
on April 19, 1993?
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of this case rests on what happened on April 19,'' he
said, laying much of blame for the events of that day on the FBI's
field commanders for the Mount Carmel operation, the special agents
Jeffrey Jamar and Rick Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake, The men driving the tanks that day were only
following orders,'' Caddell said. ``The men responsible were Jamar
and Rogers.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell moved quickly to separate his clients from those Branch
Davidians involved with weapons or violence during the raid,
admitting that hundreds of firearms were found in the burned-out
compound.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not in dispute here,'' he said. ``Eight people were
convicted for those crimes and sent to prison. None of them are
involved in this lawsuit. I am not here to defend David Koresh.''
</P>
<P>
   He also conceded that some Branch Davidians may have set at
least one of three fires that government investigators say started
the April 19, 1993, conflagration.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bradford tried to deflect charges of
indiscriminate firing by government agents by describing the
chaotic conditions during the raid. ``They did not expect to
receive gunfire,'' he said. ``The agents were in a situation where
they were pinned down and fighting for their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Branch Davidians injured during the raid, he said, were
killed by their own companions. ``The BATF tried to get them out
for medical treatment, but instead of giving them medical
attention, they were shot,'' Bradford said.
</P>
<P>
   He also scoffed at Caddell's theory of the origin of the fires:
``They didn't start just one of the fires, they started all of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that jurors will have to sift through mountains of
documents and physical evidence, both sides tried to personalize
the anguish their clients have gone through over the events of
seven and a half years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford continually referred to the agents of the ATF and FBI
as victims of Koresh's bloodlust against the government. ``They
were simply trying to carry out their duties and responsibilities,
and they met a dangerous man named David Koresh,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, at one point in his presentation, Caddell displayed
photographs of 15 children killed, saying ``Let me introduce my
clients.''
</P>
<P>
   As the children's images appeared on a screen in the courtroom,
Caddell repeated a similar litany about each: ``She never owed a
gun. She never held a gun. She never fired a gun. She never hurt
anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
