u a BC-COLO-CONDOS-NYT &LR;      06-20 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-CONDOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN VAIL, PROPOSING A CHANGE OF VIEW IN THE NAME OF PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ The view from The Lodge at Lionshead is to die
for.
</P>
<P>
   Gore Creek babbles along noisily, just beyond soaring pine trees
that seem to reach halfway up the mountains in the distance. ``You
can even see the ski slopes,'' said Marilyn Dyer, owner of Unit 1
and president of the Lodge homeowners association, who splits the
year between here and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   But not all is as peaceful and serene as it appears outside the
back windows of Dyer's stylish three-bedroom, three-bath
condominium, which she has owned for 14 years. The Lodge, which was
built in 1978, is smack in the middle of a proposed major
development project that town officials argue is critical for
Vail's continued economic stability. To complete the most ambitious
of several options, town officials want to tear down the four-level
building and move all the residents, Dyer and 11 other unit owners,
to a nearby site, where the town would construct a new building for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a scale of 1 to 10, this would be close to a 10,'' Mayor
Ludwig Kurtz said, reflecting the town's urgent need to gain access
to the Lodge site. ``Specifically because of the competition we are
facing within the state and outside the state, not only in the ski
business but also in the leisure and lifestyle business, we need to
look at some pretty bold strokes.''
</P>
<P>
   For Vail and many other mountain resort towns in the West, these
are challenging times because of a booming national economy that
keeps them busy year round, with skiers in winter and hikers in
summer. To attract the growing number of families with vacation
money to burn, they are now engaged in a mighty competition, in
which amenities often mean the difference between winning and
losing billions in leisure dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Vail opened its ski resort in the early 1960s, making it one of
the first Colorado areas to win acclaim as a world-class resort.
But others, like Aspen, Telluride and Winter Park caught up fast.
With unusually warm winters in recent years shortening prime the
ski season, the competition has only intensified. This season,
skier visits to Colorado's 26 resorts dropped 4.5 percent, making
it the second consecutive season in which fewer lift tickets were
sold than the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Vail was a rare exception, with a 2.5 percent increase over the
1998-1999 ski season. But that was hardly enough for town officials
to abandon the ``Vail Renaissance,'' a master plan to re-energize
the resort, part of which includes building a second indoor skating
rink, a cultural center, a conference center, office and retail
space _ all of it wrapped around a small lake and open
European-style plaza that would serve as a community gathering
place.
</P>
<P>
   And so a band of architects set out to fulfill the town's
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was, for Dyer and her 11 neighbors, the most lavish
option meant tearing down the Lodge at Lionshead and moving them,
at no cost to the residents, elsewhere, a proposal that has not set
well with them. Adding insult to injury, the town council had
considered using a local law that would have allowed it to take
control of the lodge by declaring it ``blighted,'' a tactic Kurtz
now says is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Dyer said, she feels as if the homeowners have been
strong-armed by the town, and by extension, Vail Resorts, the
company that operates the ski slopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``How would you feel?'' she asked, with a sweep of her arm
taking in the vista beyond. ``This is why I chose this place. The
pool, the trees, the privacy. We even have a waterfall over there,
and we're so close to the creek.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell W. Forrest, director of community development for Vail,
said the town would do everything possible to replicate what the
Lodge owners now have, in effect, units of 1,600 to 2,200 square
feet that sell for as much as $1.5 million. By one design, a new
building could be constructed at its current site, only turned from
its current east-west axis to north-south, a change that would
deprive most owners of the views they have now. Another option is
to build across the proposed lake, a site still near the creek but
away from the tall pines.
</P>
<P>
   Or, the residents could decline both offers, forcing town
planners to embrace a less dramatic vision of the future, with
fewer amenities and a more modest-sized plaza. Dyer said she has no
idea what the homeowners association might decide.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz and other officials involved with the redevelopment plans
say that whatever the homeowners decide is fine and that the town
will plan accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be a small level of disappointment that we might
not be able to do as well as we could,'' Kurtz said, contemplating
the possibility that the homeowners would refuse to move. If so, he
promised, they would not be stigmatized as obstructionists.
</P>
<P>
   It was less clear if they were in any danger of having their
lift tickets pulled if they chose to remain. ``You know, I never
thought of that,'' Porter Wharton, senior vice president of public
affairs for Vail Resorts, said with a mischievous grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only kidding,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
