<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-HEALTH-CARE-N     06-20 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HEALTH-CARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, IN REVERSAL, PROPOSES INCREASES IN MEDICARE PAYMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Tuesday proposed increasing
Medicare payments to hospitals, nursing homes and other health care
providers Tuesday, as evidence grew that cuts made in 1997 had
harmed the quality of care around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked Congress to increase payments to providers by $21
billion in the next five years and by $40 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals represent an abrupt reversal by the
administration. In his budget request just five months ago, Clinton
asked Congress to cut payments to providers by $30 billion over the
next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The original cuts were made with bipartisan support, in the
Balanced Budget Act of 1997. Lawmakers wanted to slow the growth of
Medicare, but the savings have far exceeded expectations. Medicare
spending declined last year, by nearly 1 percent, to $209 billion.
It was the first decline since creation of Medicare in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Tuesday asked Congress to increase Medicare payments
to hospitals, home health agencies and nursing homes, and he
proposed a small increase for health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The first three sectors welcomed the proposals. But HMO
executives said they were disappointed, and they said the proposed
increases would not be enough to prevent HMOs from pulling out of
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration seems not to be addressing the crisis
facing Medicare beneficiaries in HMOs,'' said Karen M. Ignagni,
president of the American Association of Health Plans.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Kenneth E. Raske, president of the Greater
New York Hospital Association, hailed the proposal. Hospitals in
the New York area have laid off workers because of financial
problems that they trace to the 1997 law.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, the Democratic candidate for the U.S.
Senate in New York, has expressed concern about the adequacy of
Medicare payments to teaching hospitals. But Chris Jennings, the
health policy coordinator at the White House, said, ``She did not
develop, design, approve or review'' the proposals announced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is, in effect, getting out in front of a
parade that has already begun to form on Capitol Hill, where
lawmakers are scrambling to help health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   Home health care has been hit harder than any other service in
the last two years. Medicare spending on home care dropped 45
percent, to $9.7 billion in 1999 from $17.5 billion in 1997. Under
current law, payments will be cut by 15 percent in October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The president said Tuesday that Congress should delay that cut
for one year. But Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, said: ``The White
House plan is not enough. The 15 percent cut in home health
payments should be eliminated altogether.'' Many lawmakers share
that view.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, lobbyists for the elderly, seeking new prescription
drug benefits, had seen themselves as competing with health care
providers for scarce federal dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But with estimates of the federal budget surplus soaring, and
with the Medicare trust fund solvent until 2025, the president said
Tuesday, ``I believe we can do both'' _ enhance payments to
providers and add drug benefits to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   It is not at all certain that Congress will do both this year.
Politically, it is easy to increase payments to providers, by
changing just a few words in Medicare reimbursement formulas. But
lawmakers have had immense difficulty agreeing on Medicare drug
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton explained in detail how he wanted to spend half of the
money he proposed to give health care providers. Use of the other
half would be decided with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   These are the highlights of the president's plan:
</P>
<P>
   _ Hospitals would receive $5 billion over five years and $10
billion over 10 years. They would receive a full allowance for
inflation, increasing their Medicare payments about 3 percent,
rather than the 2 percent expected under current law. Medicare
would increase special payments to teaching hospitals and to
hospitals that serve large numbers of poor people.
</P>
<P>
   _ Home health agencies would receive $2 billion over five years
and $3 billion over 10 years. Home care agencies would get a 3.4
percent increase for inflation, rather than the 2.3 percent
expected under current law.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nursing homes would receive $1 billion over five years and $2
billion over 10 years. Restrictions on physical, occupational and
speech therapy would be delayed a year.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare officials had minimized complaints from health care
providers. But the White House changed its tune Tuesday, saying
that Medicare cuts appeared to ``undermine access to quality health
care services,'' as ``hospitals' financial status has deteriorated
significantly since 1997.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
