<SLUG> BC-LAKERS-VIOLENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. REJECTS DEMOCRATS' REQUEST FOR $6 MILLION IN CONVENTION
SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A day after the Los Angeles Lakers brought this
often jaded city to its feet by storming to the National Basketball
Association championship, the mayor and other embarrassed city
officials were grilled over a spasm of post-game violence that left
some police cruisers torched and four officers injured.
</P>
<P>
   Roving mobs that grew to several thousand people outside the
Staples Center, in downtown Los Angeles, where the Lakers won the
championship, burned and destroyed the two police cruisers, plus
one other automobile, and they made bonfires of souvenir T-shirts
and posters. They vandalized businesses, and battered and nearly
up-ended a television broadcast van before police on foot and on
horseback brought them under control, finally allowing the roughly
20,000 fans inside the arena to exit. There were 11 arrests, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan said the police did a good job of
containing the violence to the vicinity of Staples Center. But what
made the issue particularly sensitive, and led to the questions
from City Council members at Tuesday's meeting, is the growing
nervousness here over security for the Democratic convention, less
than two months away.
</P>
<P>
   The council Tuesday refused to vote for a Democratic Party
request for $6 million in city support of the convention, scheduled
to begin on Aug. 14. Council members agreed to provide $2 million
in bus service and other support, but refused to hand over $4
million in cash, insisting on more information before granting the
funds.
</P>
<P>
   But Riordan and other officials, including the police chief,
Bernard Parks, played down the violence and the threat to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night, we all witnessed pride and shame, winners and
losers,'' the mayor said at a news conference. But he called the
police response ``outstanding,'' and commented, ``I think the
police acted very responsibly, with restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks added, ``I think that what we saw yesterday was a very
disciplined effort by the police department. Certainly that
property damage can be replaced. We certainly feel as though the
end result was the best that we could do under those
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   But some council members said that the destruction of so much
property, and particularly the open hostility some of those in the
melee showed toward the police, was not a small matter, and added
to concerns about what sort of violence might accompany the
Democratic convention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
