<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9905 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-HATE-CRIMES-     06-20 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HATE-CRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES TO MAKE ATTACKS ON GAYS A CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With strong bipartisan support, the Senate voted on
Tuesday to make hate attacks on homosexuals a federal crime.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on Tuesday was an unexpectedly wide 57-42 tally and was
also the first time either house of Congress backed protection of
gays in a roll-call vote that could have political consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed a similar measure last year, quietly and by
unanimous consent, only to see it killed in a House-Senate
conference, and Republican leaders said they planned to do so again
this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Vice President Al Gore, who flew back from a campaign event
to preside and cast a tie-breaking vote if necessary, said that if
the House did not pass the measure on its own, the administration
would insist that it be included in wrap-up legislation before
Congress could adjourn.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who was calling senators on Tuesday and on
Monday asking for their votes, has repeatedly used that tactic in
recent years, and Republicans have often given in to avoid being
accused of shutting down the government.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed on Tuesday would expand federal jurisdiction for
crimes based on race, religion and national origin, and would also
add gender and handicapped status to the categories covered, as
well as sexual orientation. But while the issue never came up
openly in debate, senators on both sides agreed that the sexual
orientation issue was the question that made the bill a close call.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., who co-sponsored the bill with Sen.
Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., appealed to those who he said had told him
they did not want to vote for the bill and thereby seem to be
approving homosexuality. ``No matter how we pray, nor how we sin,
we can stand up for each other,'' he said. ``We can stand up
against hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy told the Senate, ``Hate crimes are rooted in hatred and
bigotry, and if America is ever going to be America, we should root
out hatred and bigotry.'' After the vote he said: ``This was a
bipartisan effort. It was the Senate acting at its best, with one
voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-four Democrats and 13 Republicans voted for the bill.
Forty-one Republicans and one Democrat, Sen. Robert Byrd of West
Virginia, voted no.
</P>
<P>
   But the only senator who spoke against the bill was Orrin Hatch,
the Utah Republican who heads the Judiciary Committee. He contended
the measure was unnecessary, because hate crimes were already being
adequately prosecuted by states and localities, and
unconstitutional because it invaded state authority.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed a narrower bill, one that would require a study of
whether states were ignoring hate crimes. ``I don't think it is
true,'' he said. But if it was, he added, he might support a
measure like the Kennedy-Smith bill. ``Hate crimes are abysmal,''
he said. ``They are horrible. We should all be against them.''
Hatch's proposal for a study was also adopted, 50-49.
</P>
<P>
   But if Hatch was the only vocal critic, others who voted no made
it clear that the protections based on sexual orientation had
turned them against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy-Smith bill, like Hatch's proposal, would authorize
federal grants and other assistance to state and local law
enforcement officials to prosecute hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   It would make a federal offense of crimes involving bodily
injury motivated by a victim's actual or perceived race, color,
religion, national origin, gender, sexual orientation or
disability. Federal law now prohibits crimes based on race,
national origin or religion, but only when the victim was seeking
to exercise a federally protected right, like voting, registering
for school or using a restaurant. But the bill passed on Tuesday
would also make a federal crime of random hate crimes, like the
murders of James Byrd Jr. in Texas and Matthew Shepard in Wyoming
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But to reach the Shepard case, and also hate crimes against the
handicapped or based on gender, the prosecution would have to
establish a direct connection to interstate commerce, though the
connection could be no more than that a gun used in a hate crime
had been bought in interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   And before a federal indictment could be obtained, the Justice
Department would have to certify that it had consulted with the
local authorities, who either had no jurisdiction or intention to
act, or that the state had requested or at least did not object to
federal action, or that the state had completed prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the fate of the legislation, Tuesday's vote propelled
the issue into the political campaign. At the presidential level,
Gore's enthusiasm contrasted to the attitude of Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, the likely Republican nominee. Last year, Bush said he
opposed including sexual orientation in a hate crimes bill the
Texas Legislature was considering. When that bill died without a
vote, supporters of it blamed him and said his lack of support was
dictated by presidential campaign considerations.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night Gore, the likely Democratic nominee, embraced
the bill eagerly. He said, ``Because hate crimes are an affront to
all Americans, this vote is a sign of hope for all Americans.'' He
said the next task was to get the House to vote on the measure. But
he was asked about the reluctance of Republican leaders, like Rep.
Dick Armey of Texas, the majority leader, who said, ``I don't see
that happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said House Republicans, like their Senate counterparts,
might learn that Americans wanted the bill passed into law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9906 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TEXAS-PARDON-BOARD-AR     06-20 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PARDON-BOARD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENDING EXECUTION IN TEXAS SPOTLIGHTS A SECRETIVE BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT18-19 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SARA RIMER with JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Some are active Republicans, their offices
decorated with stuffed elephants or pictures of Gov. George W.
Bush. Many have some sort of experience in law enforcement. These
include a former Secret Service agent, a former prosecutor and
several former parole workers. But there is also a psychologist, a
rancher and a former schoolteacher.
</P>
<P>
   These men and women are members of the Texas Board of Pardons
and Paroles, the obscure state agency whose job is to review the
clemency petitions of inmates in what is by far the nation's
busiest death row. When Bush is asked about the fairness of the
death penalty in Texas, he often says that the power to grant
clemency to death row inmates rests not with him, but with this
18-member board. Under state law he can only commute a death
penalty if they recommend it.
</P>
<P>
   But while Bush has made a point of distancing himself from the
board's decisions in capital cases, as governor he has appointed
al of its members to their six-year terms. He has also selected
the chairman and designated the six board members who set policy
and guidelines, all subject to approval by the state senate.
</P>
<P>
   Now the board is faced with its latest high-profile decision.
Unless it intervenes, Gary Graham, a convicted murderer whose case
has drawn national attention largely because of accounts of poor
work by his lawyer, will be executed at 6 p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, the chairman of the board has postponed the
deadline for the vote until noon Thursday, six hours before the
scheduled execution. If history is any measure, Graham's lawyers
face an uphill struggle. Since 1995, 68 death row inmates have
asked for clemency, and only once has the board granted it. They
have not held a public hearing on a capital case since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the board has been criticized for working in secret,
seldom explaining its life-or-death decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Adele Shank, an Ohio lawyer specializing in capital defense who
argued a landmark clemency case before the U.S. Supreme Court in
1997, said the Texas board is out of step with the decades-long
trend toward greater openness in handling capital clemency
decisions. Many state boards require public hearings if requested
in capital cases, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas board has also been accused by defense lawyers of not
giving a thorough review to the death row cases it is responsible
for evaluating.
</P>
<P>
   A majority vote is required for any form of clemency. Once the
board's votes are all in _ they generally send them in to the main
office in Austin by fax _ the decision is immediately relayed to
the governor. Board members are not required to meet publicly on
capital cases, or even to hold telephone conference calls _ and the
apparent lack of such discussion on any sort of systematic basis
has prompted criticism from defense lawyers as well as judges.
</P>
<P>
   But with Graham's lawyers trying to make a powerful case for his
innocence in the 1981 robbery murder for which he was sentenced to
death, there has been an unusual amount of conferring among members
about his case, said one board official who asked not to be quoted
by name. ``There's an awful lot of talking going on,'' said the
official. ``They're concerned about him being possibly innocent.
And they're concerned about the lack of an adequate defense.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Michael Jones, a spokesman for the
governor's office, said Bush does not personally interview any of
the candidates for the Paroles Board, noting that the governor
controls 3,000 appointments. He said candidates usually apply to
the governor's appointment office, which asks a variety of
questions, probing a person's views on crime and punishment and on
methods of treatment. But Jones said none of the candidates are
asked their views about the death penalty, nor are they asked their
political party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not one of the questions they ask people,'' Jones said of
the death penalty. He added, ``Capital murder cases are a very
small percentage of the caseload. The goal is to select people who
are balanced, fair, thorough and who make decisions based on facts
and who have no agenda except to protect the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said one goal in choosing members ``is to get a diverse
perspective,'' and the board is diverse in ethnicity and geographic
representation. But none of the members are criminal defense
lawyers, for example. In fact, at least five of the members once
worked for the Texas Department of Criminal Justice, the same
department charged with carrying out executions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume those are all folks strongly interested in improving
the criminal justice system,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with present and former officials indicate that most,
if not all, of the board members seem to support the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   One member who left in the last year, Bennie Elmore, abstained
in all capital cases, though he declined to say why. Some board
members said they believed it was for religious reasons, but
Elmore, in an interview in April, denied that, although he declined
to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Kent A. Schaffer, immediate past president of the Texas Criminal
Defense Lawyers Association, said all Texas governors carefully
select board members who can serve as a firewall when a
particularly sensitive case arises.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are predisposed to protect the governor,'' said Schaffer.
``The governor makes appointments to the board with people he knows
can take the heat. He's in the enviable position of saying, `I can
only do what they allow me to do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the board acts independently, but some lawyers here
believe that governors have ways of making their feelings known to
members who are beholden to them for their $80,000 a year jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be sure there are ways of communicating with the board
and letting them know what the governor wants,'' said Neil McCabe,
a law professor at South Texas College of Law. McCabe and others
pointed to the case of Henry Lee Lucas, the only person to be
granted clemency by the board. Ten days before the vote, Bush
publicly spoke of how he and the board would have to give careful
consideration to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Five board members interviewed in April said they regarded
themselves as independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no communication between us and Governor Bush on how
to vote,'' said Linda Garcia, a former prosecutor who works out of
the board's Angleton office, outside Houston. ``There just flat
isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said that when he reviews scheduled executions, he
considers two questions: whether the inmate may have been innocent,
and whether the inmate received full access to the courts. While
there are no clear guidelines on how the board's clemency decisions
in capital cases are made, several board members who discussed
their review of capital cases during interviews with the Times in
April said they also focus on those questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of innocence and guilt is something that I've always
looked at very closely,'' said Cynthia Tauss, who has studied
criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   Another board member, Tom Moss, a retired federal parole
officer, said he asks these questions: ``Have they had their day in
court? Is there anything in front of me to lead a rational person
to believe that this person might be innocent?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, two death row inmates filed a federal lawsuit against
the pardons board, criticizing its secrecy and failure to explain
its reasons for denying clemencies, in most cases.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Sam Sparks, of U.S. District Court in Austin, found that
while the Texas clemency system met ``the minimal procedural
safeguards'' required by the U.S. Supreme Court, he still suggested
that the board could easily offer reasons for its decisions and
hold public hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Administratively, the goal is more to protect the secrecy and
autonomy of the system rather than carrying out an efficient,
legally sound system,'' Sparks wrote in his opinion. ``The board
would not have to sacrifice its conservative ideology to carry out
its duties in a more fair and accurate fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time the inmates' lawsuit was pending, legislation had
been introduced in Texas that would require the board to consider
clemency appeals in public meetings. Bush resisted the changes. He
said public deliberations might create ``a chance for people to
rant and rail, a chance for people to emotionalize the process
beyond the questions that need to be asked.'' The bill died in the
legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   In capital clemency cases, both the prosecution and the defense
are free to submit documents, letters, videotapes and affidavits.
Board members said they also regularly receive letters from
relatives of both the victims and the inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The material in the Graham case is voluminous and fills several
notebooks, according to the board's general counsel, Laura McElroy.
In the clemency petition they submitted to the board three weeks
ago, Graham's defense lawyers, Jack B. Zimmermann and Richard H.
Burr, contend that Graham is innocent of the murder for which he
was convicted in 1981. The lawyers also presented videotapes of two
eyewitnesses who say they saw the killer, and that he was not
Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday Zimmermann and Burr met with the board chairman,
Gerald Garrett, and presented additional information, including
affidavits from two jurors who viewed videotapes of the witnesses
and said if they had heard their testimony during the original
trial, they would have voted to acquit Graham, Zimmermann said.
</P>
<P>
   The defense also included in its new submission a seven-minute
videotape of Jennifer Thompson, a North Carolina woman who
misidentified the man who raped her, and thus sent the wrong man to
prison. (He was released after 11 years because of DNA evidence
that showed he did not rape Thompson.)
</P>
<P>
   A jury sentenced Graham to death based on the testimony of a
single eyewitness, who said she saw him through the windshield of
her car, from 30 to 40 feet away at night, and fleetingly. That
witness has stuck to her account.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chairman assured us they will look at it, and get it out
right away to the members,'' Zimmermann said, referring to the new
material.
</P>
<P>
   The board members who were interviewed by the Times said they
review cases scrupulously, pouring over volumes of evidence. ``We
are their last chance,'' said Daniel Lang, a lawyer and board
member who works out of the Angleton office. ''It's somebody's
life. I think they're entitled to my full concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is their rulings in capital cases that have thrust the
board into the spotlight, they spend most of their time making
about 1,000 decisions a month on parole for state inmates,
decisions that mostly involve robberies and drug possession.
</P>
<P>
   Paddy Lann Burwell, the rancher on the board, says he spends 50
hours a week on the job, eating lunch at his desk, and taking cases
home to give them further consideration at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst nightmare would be to execute an innocent person,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
