u f BC-RUSSIA-INVEST-NYT &LR;      06-20 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS OPPOSE BREAKUP OF RUSSIA'S ELECTRIC MONOPOLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By SABRINA TAVERNISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of foreign investors in Russia's electricity monopoly,
Unified Energy Systems, has asked President Vladimir Putin to stop
a corporate restructuring they say is moving too fast and would
destroy the value of their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The group of 18 investors, representing more than 15 percent of
Unified Energy's stock, sent a letter to Putin stating that the
restructuring proposal would reduce future investment levels by
robbing the company of its principal assets at extremely low
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Their letter elevates what has been a simmering dispute between
foreign investors and the management of Unified Energy, which runs
the world's biggest power grid and is the most actively traded
Russian stock.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring proposal, designed by Anatoly Chubais, Unified
Energy's chief executive, would break the monopoly into hundreds of
smaller companies and sell stakes in them to raise $30 billion in
badly needed investment over 10 years. The company said Monday it
had reworked the proposal and planned to submit the revisions to
the government on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring proposal has attracted widespread attention in
Russia and abroad as a test case of restructuring the country's
investment-starved energy sector. Chubais, the architect of
Russia's state asset sales program, has championed free market
reforms and foreign investments in Russia. As recently as last
year, Chubais was a favorite of foreign investors, who voted to
make it more difficult to oust him from the post. But now they have
banded together against him, saying they fear a repeat of his asset
sales program, in which prize companies were sold at bargain
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complete mess,'' said Alexander Branis, associate
director at Prosperity Capital Management, with $140 million under
management, a quarter of which is in power companies. ``I doubt
that the proposal has changed much. For us it's disturbing that
Chubais has admitted that some of our concerns were legitimate but
is still pressing ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Unified Energy currently holds majority stakes in most of the
country's more than 80 regional power companies. Investors say
breaking regional companies up into distributors, sellers and
generators would create companies too small to actually attract
buyers. Unified Energy should merge groups of regional companies,
and sell stakes in the larger companies, they say. They also argue
that Russia must allow electricity prices to rise before Unified
Energy's assets will be attractive to serious buyers. Tariffs are
still well below production costs, while unpaid electricity bills
cripple the finances of the regional companies. Russians pay about
1.5 cents per kilowatt hour for their electricity, while Western
Europeans pay about 7 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Still, everyone from shareholders to company management agree
that a restructuring is needed. They argue that aging regional
power stations need new equipment, and that companies need the
ability to charge market prices for electricity and terminate
service to nonpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Unified Energy has said the country will suffer major gaps in
power supplies without major new investment within the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Not all investors oppose the breakup of the company. Some say
its dominant position is part of the problem. Charles Frank, acting
president of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development,
which invests in post-Soviet Russia companies, said last week in
St. Petersburg that while some of of the criticism of Unified
Energy's restructuring is valid, some is driven by a desire to
preserve the company's dominance. The Unified Energy monopoly, he
said, ``must be broken soon, without waiting for the perfect
regulatory regime or 100 percent tariff collection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MASS-OLDER-MOTHERS-NY     06-20 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-OLDER-MOTHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS SET APART IN RATIO OF OLDER MOTHERS
</HEADLINE>
  By CAREY GOLDBERG 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At first, it seemed that it might be a statistical
blip. But no, public health officials said Tuesday, it is a
definite and striking trend: Massachusetts, they believe, has
become the first state where more babies are born to women over the
age of 30 than under it.
</P>
<P>
   State figures made public this week showed that among
Massachusetts women who gave birth in 1998, about 43,000 were 30 or
over, and about 39,000 were under 30. That contrasted sharply with
state figures as recent as those from 1990, when only about 37,000
women 30 and over gave birth, compared with 55,000 under 30. In
1980, the number of new mothers under 30 was nearly triple the new
mothers 30 and over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a trend, this is happening,'' said Deborah Klein
Walker, the Massachusetts associate commissioner of public health.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1996 that the over-30 mothers first slightly exceeded
the under-30 mothers here, Walker said, and the increase in their
dominance has been steady ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in older mothers may be mainly of sociological rather
than medical interest, because there is no sharp change in
fertility or healthy births at the age or 30 or thereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   But in Massachusetts, at least, it does bring one medical
corollary: a slight rise in cases of low birth weight. That
condition usually occurs in premature babies, and they are more at
risk for problems like breathing difficulties and brain disorders.
</P>
<P>
   The link, said Dr. Fredric Frigoletto, chief of obstetrics at
Massachusetts General Hospital, is that ``older women might have
slightly more difficulty getting pregnant.'' These women,
Frigoletto added, often ``resort to artificial reproduction
techniques, which are associated with multiple births, and multiple
births are associated with prematurity.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Massachusetts, where insurance companies are required to
cover infertility treatments, has the highest number of multiple
births in the United States, and multiple births are strongly
associated with low birth weights, those less than 5.5 pounds.
According to the state statistics just released, in 1998 less than
5 percent of single babies were born at low birth weights, but 50
percent of twins and 92 percent of triplets weighed in low.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in multiple births means a change for health workers
gauging and fighting low birth weights. Historically, low birth
weights have occurred largely among poor young minority women, and
have tended to be a sign of faulty nutrition and prenatal care. But
now, with so many older mothers using high-technology help to have
babies, the low weights are occurring more often among white, more
affluent and more educated women as well.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to draw that distinction, state health officials
say, because the numbers might seem to indicate that efforts at
helping poor mothers were bringing little result; in fact, they
say, they are making progress, but the low birth weight numbers are
skewed by the pool of multiple births to older mothers.
</P>
<P>
   As for why Massachusetts has such a preponderance of older
mothers, many attribute it to the large number of educated women in
the state and their tendency to delay having children.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said she was virtually sure that Massachusetts was the
only state to reach the point where more babies were born to women
over 30 than under it. Federal reports on pregnancy rates and
births do not break the numbers down by state, and officials at the
National Center for Health Statistics said Tuesday that such
figures were not readily available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
