<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKAKEL-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKAKEL SHAKEN BY TESTIMONY AT HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ The long-frustrated effort to find and punish
the killer of teenager Martha Moxley exploded onto the public stage
Tuesday when two former classmates testified in court that Michael
Skakel confessed more than 20 years ago to murder.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel's classmates at a Maine treatment center for troubled
youths said that Ethel Kennedy's nephew, alternating between
anguish and arrogance, told them separately in 1978 that he had
killed a young woman.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel boasted: ``I'm going to get away with murder. I'm a
Kennedy,'' testified Gregory Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Another ex-classmate, John Higgins, said that during a tearful,
rambling, soul-purging on a porch at the Elan School in Poland
Spring, Maine, Skakel also confessed to him.
</P>
<P>
   As Higgins testified Tuesday morning, according to court artist
Christine Cornell, Skakel mouthed an obscenity at his former
confidant.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful testimony occurred during the opening day of a
single-judge hearing to determine whether ``reasonable cause''
exists to try Skakel for murder, and whether the case should be
transferred to Superior Court. In January, a grand jury indicted
Skakel, 39, for the 1975 murder of his next-door neighbor in a
gated neighborhood in Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel and Moxley were both 15-year-old juveniles when she was
bludgeoned and stabbed by a golf club traced to the Skakel family.
Moxley was found the day after she failed to return home from a
gathering at the Skakels' house, her body hidden under a pine tree
on her family's estate.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's testimony marked the first time that Skakel has
publicly heard the evidence collected against him during the grand
jury proceedings. And after the morning session ended with Higgins'
testimony of a confession, Skakel left the courtroom shaken and
heaving with sobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think those were tears of joy,'' said John Moxley,
Martha's brother. ``He now knows this is real.''
</P>
<P>
   The ex-classmates insisted under cross-examination that Skakel
confessed to murder. Coleman told State's Attorney Jonathan
Benedict that Skakel ``made a comment that he was trying to make
advances to this girl, and this girl was not complying with those
advances, and then drove her skull in.''
</P>
<P>
   Skakel also admitted the slaying during ``primal scream''
sessions, Coleman said, in which students were told to yell
apologies in an effort to confront their guilt. Joe Ricci, the
owner and operator of the Elan School, told The Boston Globe in
March that he is convinced Michael Skakel did not kill Moxley and
that his former students who claim he confessed to the murder are
lying.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, who is serving a one-year sentence in New York state
for criminal trespass, testified Tuesday that Skakel told him he
had returned to the body and masturbated over it.
</P>
<P>
   Michael ``Mickey'' Sherman, Skakel's attorney, had only begun to
question Coleman when he asked for an adjournment until this
morning. Earlier in the day, he called Higgins' testimony
``garbage'' after subjecting the Illinois man to a ferocious
cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   Both Higgins and Coleman said they did not speak with
authorities about the alleged confessions until several years ago,
after they had contacted television news and crime shows that had
focused on the unsolved case.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins admitted to Sherman that he had lied when he told
investigators as recently as three years ago that Skakel never
confessed to him.
</P>
<P>
   However, Higgins said, he lied only because he did not want to
become involved in the case. But he said that as his conscience
began to weigh more heavily on him, he called Dorothy Moxley, the
victim's mother, and asked her whether she wanted him to testify.
When she said yes, Higgins said, he decided to come forward and
tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that your final answer,'' asked Sherman, in one of many
sarcastic questions designed to damage Higgins' credibility before
Judge Maureen Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very amusing,'' Higgins replied.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman pressed the issue: ``Are you telling the truth today?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' answered Higgins, his arms spread wide in exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we know?'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins fired back, a finger pointed at Skakel: ``The one person
who knows is sitting right there, and that's the only one who
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll buy that,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins testified that Skakel confessed during a late-night
conversation while the pair acted as staff-appointed ``police'' to
monitor the activities of other students at Elan, which Higgins
described as ``a place to hide your kids if they bothered you.''
</P>
<P>
   While he listened in silence that night, Higgins said, Skakel
recounted taking a golf club from a bag in his home's garage,
running through pine woods, and then blacking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he didn't know whether he (killed Moxley). He couldn't
remember if he did it,'' Higgins said. ``He eventually said that he
did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman asked: ``Did Michael Skakel tell you he committed this
crime?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, he did,'' Higgins replied.
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses at Tuesday's hearing included former Greenwich
police chief Thomas Keegan, who conceded that the Skakels
reportedly left golf clubs lying on their grounds. However, he
scoffed at the theory that a transient committed the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you are in Belle Haven, a gated community, with lots of
cops around,'' Keegan said. ``It just doesn't seem probable that
someone wanders into Belle Haven, finds a golf club, and kills
Martha. ... It defies logic.''
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of Moxley's battered corpse were shown to Sheila
McGuire, a friend who was the first to discover the body, which she
initially believed to be an egg crate.
</P>
<P>
   The horrible discovery still haunts her, McGuire testified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
