<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-O'NEAL-LAKERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' O'NEAL CLIMBS TO TOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal was one of the most dominating
forces in the history of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Rik Smits.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal turned the 7-foot-4 Pacers center into the incredible
shrinking man by averaging 38 points and 16.7 rebounds during the
six-game series. O'Neal climaxed his terrific series Monday night
with 41 points and 12 rebounds as the Lakers survived Indiana in
Game 6, 116-111, to win the NBA title and the best-of-seven series,
4-2.
</P>
<P>
   For O'Neal, it was the sweetest of moments. O'Neal, 7-foot-1,]
had been belittled by critics in the past because his teams had a
penchant for ending their postseasons on the wrong end of a sweep.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 1999-2000 season, O'Neal did the sweeping. He joined
Willis Reed and Michael Jordan as the only players to win Most
Valuable Player honors in the All-Star Game, the regular season and
the NBA Finals in one season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the league for eight years, and this is what I
wanted to come to the NBA for,'' O'Neal said of his first NBA
title. ``Growing up, I used to see Larry \RBird\S and Magic
\RJohnson\S celebrate. Mike \RJordan\S.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the Finals in '95 \Rwith Orlando\S. I saw Hakeem
\ROlajuwon\S and Robert Horry celebrate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, O'Neal can celebrate in style after dismantling the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was huge,'' Lakers forward Rick Fox said. ``People don't
realize until they play with him how much he makes you better. How
much easier the game is when he is on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson, who completed his first season coaching the
Lakers, questioned whether O'Neal was in really good basketball
shape the past two seasons. O'Neal, in turn, said there's no way
the Lakers would have won it all without Jackson barking the
commands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of his resume, guys believed in him,'' O'Neal said.
``When he came in from the first day of training camp, it was no
nonsense. Being here in previous years before, coaches talking,
guys messing around.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Phil came in and said what he had to say, because of his
resume _ and we all know his resume _ we knew it was no nonsense.
He said, `If you don't do what I say, you're not going to be here.
If you don't like the way I handle it, let me know and we'll get
you out of here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of discipline I was used to with my father,
from LSU with Dale Brown. It was nice to go back to that
discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Lakers guard Kobe Bryant said it was nice that O'Neal could stay
healthy the entire season. O'Neal missed more than 50 games in his
first three seasons with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq had a hole in his abdomen last year,'' Bryant said.
``That's a tough thing to play with.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this year, Shaq was completely healthy and he just
attacked from the beginning of the season, and he's been great for
us all year long.''
</P>
<P>
   With O'Neal, 28, and Bryant, who turns 22 on Aug. 23, there's
talk of a Lakers dynasty. Pacers coach Larry Bird said as long as
O'Neal is patrolling the middle, beating the Lakers in a playoff
series will be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most dominating player in our league,'' Bird said.
``He's powerful, strong, able to get the ball in the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's improved immensely, starting to make shots farther from
the basket. He's just so dominating that they have an opportunity
here to do something great for a number of years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers tried double- and triple-teaming O'Neal. They tried
Hack-a-Shaq. But no X's and O's have been able to contain the
self-proclaimed ``Big Aristotle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With Shaquille O'Neal in the middle, he's very dominating,''
Bird said. ``He was phenomenal throughout the series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
