<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NEAL-WRESTLING-TRIALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERDOG STATUS BOTHERS OLYMPIC WRESTLING HOPEFUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEIDI PEDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Stephen Neal thought his days in the underdog role were
over.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5, 265-pound Neal had captured amateur wrestling
titles at will for the past three years. The triumphs included
perfect 1998 and 1999 NCAA seasons at California State-Bakersfield,
then freestyle crowns at the 1999 U.S. nationals, Pan American
Games and World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   All this, before age 24. In October, little seemed to stand
between Stephen Neal and the 2000 Olympic Games super-heavyweight
title.
</P>
<P>
   But eight months later, Neal finds himself in a struggle for a
berth on the U.S. Olympic team. His nemesis, Kerry McCoy, defeated
him in the final at the 2000 U.S. nationals in April. The two are
expected to meet again Saturday in the final at the U.S. Olympic
team trials, which start tomorrow at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd believed no one could stop my shots. But they've been
stopping them this year,'' said Neal, a four-time NCAA All-American
who continues to train at Cal State-Bakersfield. ``But when someone
beats me I always try to find why.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me put in a lot more hard work, and I think I'm in the
best shape of my life right now. I guess we'll see in Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   Since winning the Worlds in October, the California native has
had to face more than being the prime target of opponents. A torn
right-shoulder muscle suffered at a training camp in July was
repaired through arthroscopic surgery two weeks after the Worlds,
and recovery took longer than Neal expected.
</P>
<P>
   After the surgery, Neal said he stayed off the mat for three
months, and did little of his usual conditioning before January. He
said he gained about 10 pounds during the layoff, up from his usual
260.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably let myself get a little farther out of shape than I
should have,'' he said. ``I let my body fat percentage get up a
little too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Neal, who possesses unusual quickness for a heavyweight, had
become known for his ability to attack with force for an entire
match. The longer he sat out of training, the more he lost
conditioning, one of the primary advantages he had had on
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McCoy, a Penn State graduate who had defeated Neal in
the 1997 NCAA final and in one bout at the '99 World Trials, won
the 2000 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Neal's layoff showed when he returned to competition in March.
In his first tournament since the World Championships, he lost his
first match, 5-4, in Bulgaria to David Musulbes of Russia. Neal
went on to dominate two Bulgarians and place fifth, but he said his
performance was a sign that he needed to get back to work,
regardless of the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Though Neal started training full time again, his coach, T.J.
Kerr of Cal State-Bakersfield, said Neal wasn't in prime condition
at nationals. There, he defeated three opponents before he fell
behind in the final and lost to McCoy, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr said he thinks the loss upset Neal more than the wrestler
would admit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't really talk about it, but when you \Rwin\S
everything possible and then you lose the national championships,
that's got to really bother him,'' Kerr said. ``Now he's got some
things to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the loss, Neal's training program was redesigned.
In addition to intensifying his mat time and running, he began
following weightlifting and nutrition programs designed by a
bodybuilder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's leaner and stronger now. We think we've gotten him better
than he's ever been,'' Kerr said. ``We think that with Steve in the
best possible shape, with his mind ready to compete, things will
take care of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory at nationals earned McCoy an automatic berth in the
finals at the Olympic trials. Neal will have to win the
mini-tournament, which takes place tomorrow and Friday, to earn the
right to face McCoy in the finals. The wrestler who wins two out of
three matches Saturday wins the Olympic berth.
</P>
<P>
   Neal said thoughts of the Olympics are all the motivation he
needs to do his best.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you train for. I think Kerry and I pretty much
are wrestling for a gold medal,'' he said. ``It's hard to wait
around another four years. For me, it's right now.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
