<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9917 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-570&AMP;A     06-20 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS TO DELAY FINAL MISSILE DECISION UNTIL NEXT
ADMINISTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN LEE MYERS and ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration is quietly maneuvering
to sidestep a contentious decision over whether to build a national
missile defense system, playing down the significance of the
Pentagon's next test of the system and leaving final decisions on
deployment to the next administration, officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to avert a diplomatic and political crisis over breaking
the Antiballistic Missile Treaty of 1972, administration and
military officials have begun emphasizing that President Clinton
faces a decision this fall only on whether a defense shield is
feasible to counter missile threats.
</P>
<P>
   More binding decisions on building a radar site on Shemya Island
in Alaska and deploying the first of 100 interceptor missiles do
not have to be made until 2001 and 2003, well after Clinton leaves
office, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing the president has to decide this year is
whether to put out'' a request for bids to begin work at Shemya
Island, a senior Pentagon official said. ``And even then, the
contract will be written so the next administration can change it.
The name of the game now is not foreclosing any options.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has expressed support for building a national
missile defense, something long advocated by Republicans, the
administration's goals have shifted markedly in the past few months
as the Russians have balked at revising the ABM Treaty to allow the
deployment of an American system.
</P>
<P>
   Administration lawyers have already drafted legal arguments for
Clinton that would allow him to give a preliminary approval to move
ahead with construction of the first phase of the system on Shemya
Island, without having to announce a withdrawal from the treaty.
Several officials said Clinton did not want to make breaking the
treaty his lasting legacy in arms control.
</P>
<P>
   The administration imposed the deadlines that it is now having
trouble meeting. The timetable was designed by the Pentagon to meet
possible missile threats to American territory, specifically those
posed by North Korea, which has an active ballistic missile
program.
</P>
<P>
   Under the timetable, Clinton was faced with making a crucial
decision on whether to move ahead with the system and announce a
withdrawal from the treaty. That decision had been timed to the
Pentagon's tests of prototypes of its highly complex system of
radars and interceptor missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers' recommendations have now taken considerable
pressure off the next test, which the Pentagon announced Tuesday
would held on July 7.
</P>
<P>
   For months, officials have portrayed the test, which has already
been delayed by three months, as a make-or-break milestone in the
program's development. But now they say that because Clinton's
decision does not have to be a final, binding one, the test's
success or failure is not as crucial to the Pentagon's plans.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at the Pentagon on Tuesday, the
undersecretary of defense for acquisition and technology, Jacques
S. Gansler, suggested that the Pentagon could recommend moving
ahead with the initial stages of development even if the next test
is not a complete success. Because more tests are planned and the
president must simply approve preliminary steps toward
construction, the test need only to indicate the program is
feasible, not actually ready to deploy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE; OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the past few months, the debate over national missile
defenses has become more complicated, particularly in light of the
Russian refusal to renegotiate the treaty and what the
administration describes as the surprising depth of opposition from
allies wary that a defensive shield could spark an arms race.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a growing, bipartisan chorus from lawmakers on
Capitol Hill urging postponement of a final decision on deployment
to the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   The two presumptive presidential candidates, Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas and Vice President Al Gore, have both expressed support
for a system and not put pressure on Clinton to make any binding
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Administration and defense officials said the next missile test
remains important but has become less significant as the
administration tries to find a course somewhere between stirring a
diplomatic crisis by moving ahead with the system and a potential
political crisis for Gore by deciding not to.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to plan next month, an aging Minuteman II
missile will be launched from Vandenberg Air Force Base in
California toward the South Pacific. An interceptor missile will be
fired from Kwajalein Atoll in the Marshall Islands about 20 minutes
later and, after receiving communications from a complex array of
radars and command centers, home in on its target.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen said in a statement that the
test would be ``our most demanding yet,'' but the statement went on
to say that ``at least 16 more intercept tests'' were planned
before the system is to be fielded in 2005, including eight before
the decision in 2003 to actually buy interceptor missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The officials appeared to play down the test, in part because
they fear it will fail. One senior officer rated the chances of
success as no better than 50-50.
</P>
<P>
   The two previous tests of interceptor missiles had mixed
results. One in October succeeded in striking its target, but the
most recent one, in January, failed. The Pentagon has said it would
need to have two successful intercepts before moving ahead, but, as
Gansler suggested, officials appear increasingly confident that the
system is at least technologically feasible.
</P>
<P>
   An independent review of the Pentagon's program, led by a
retired Air Force general, Larry D. Welch, concluded in a report
released Tuesday that the ``technical capability to develop and
field the limited system'' against a relatively unsophisticated
threat like North Korea's ``is available.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
