<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CUBA-SANCTIONS-NYT &LR;      06-20 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-SANCTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE KILLS PLAN FOR PANEL TO REVIEW CUBAN EMBARGO 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate voted Tuesday to defeat an effort to
create a special commission to study the effectiveness of the U.S.
economic embargo against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment was struck from the defense authorization bill by
a vote of 59 to 41, after Republicans and a few Democrats rallied
against it, calling the measure ill-timed, ill-advised and a
backhanded attempt to change Cuba policy.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would have created a commission in which
Republicans, who tend to support the Cuban embargo, would have been
outnumbered by Democrats, who tend to want to end it.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat came as no surprise. Even Sen. Christopher J. Dodd,
the Connecticut Democrat who was one of the measure's sponsors, and
who has long worked to end sanctions against Cuba, did not expect
the amendment to survive. But it served a larger purpose for
critics of the Castro government: to keep the debate over Cuba
policy alive on Capitol Hill at a time when the Clinton
administration is softening on sanctions against other defiant
nations. On Monday, Clinton announced he would lift sanctions
against North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who voted to remove the amendment was Sen. John W.
Warner, the Virginia Republican. Warner, the chairman of the Armed
Services Committee, originally cosponsored the measure, an
indication of just how sensitive the issue of American's foreign
policy toward Cuba remains.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of a commission said that American policy toward Cuba
was outdated. ``Castro is in no position to export revolution, none
whatsoever,'' said Sen. Max Baucus, a Montana Democrat, referring
to the country's financial crisis. ``According to the Pentagon,
Castro represents no real threat to national security. So times
have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have in place a policy that has not worked in 40 years. It
was a different world in the 1960s.''
</P>
<P>
   But the measure's opponents argued that nothing has changed, so
Cuba should not be rewarded by a commission likely to recommend
ending the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the same regime that sent its troops to Africa to
further the cause of Communism,'' said Sen. John McCain, the
Arizona Republican, who said he supported lifting sanctions against
the communist government of Vietnam but only after it carried out
new policies. ``It's the same regime that continues to repress and
oppress its people.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether the United States should alter its
foreign policy toward Cuba, specifically on trade, took on new life
this year, when a powerful coalition that included agribusiness
giants increased pressure on lawmakers from farming states to open
new markets. Human rights organizations and major business groups,
including the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, have also lobbied
extensively on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Two Senate and House delegations sympathetic to the call for
weakening or lifting sanctions recently visited Cuba to see
conditions there for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders continue to grapple over how to proceed
on a measure, which some of them oppose, that would permit the
export of food and medicine to Cuba under certain restrictions. The
measure, sponsored by Rep. George Nethercutt, a Washington
Republican, has delayed consideration of the huge agriculture
spending bill. A similar provision has already passed the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, including Cuban-American lawmakers, say they are
ready to fight back. And Nethercutt is up against a formidable
opponent, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the majority whip, who has tried
once already to strip the provision from the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the Democratic leader, has also
come out in opposition to the provision.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, the Cuban American National Foundation, the
anti-Castro lobbying group, began running television ads reminding
voters that Cuba is run by a communist regime.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Cuban-American lawmakers want to ensure that
Cuba will be denied private and public financing to purchase food
and medicine. The Nethercutt measure excludes public financing and
is silent on other forms, House Republican aides say.
</P>
<P>
   ``American farmers are being told, if only you can sell some
crops to Cuba, your crisis will be relieved,'' said Sen. Robert G.
Torricelli, the New Jersey Democrat. ``Cuba has no money.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republican leaders face a quandary over how to handle
Nethercutt in this election year. He is a Republican who faces a
tough re-election effort in a one-time Democratic district. And
Nethercutt maintains he has enough votes to win on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli said he and the two Florida senators met with Warner
to try to persuade him to set aside the measure, arguing that the
best time to create a commission is after a new president is
elected. ``It makes more sense for a new president to consider the
idea,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
