<HEADER>
A9920 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DNC-CONVENTION-BAILOU     06-20 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-CONVENTION-BAILOUT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. CITY COUNCIL DELAYS VOTE ON MONEY FOR DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; A besieged Los Angeles City Council has put off a
decision on a $4 million payment to stage the Democratic National
Convention, citing concerns over how the money will be used and if
it should be in the form of a direct payment or a loan.
</P>
<P>
   Council members asked on Tuesday that more details be provided,
possibly as early as Friday, on the impact on the city's finances
and whether other ways - such as a temporary hike in the hotel bed
tax - could be used to repay part of the money. Officials
immediately expressed doubt about the legality of a bed tax hike
unless it is put to a public vote.
</P>
<P>
   The request from the convention's Host Committee for the money -
because its private fund raising has fallen short - has stirred a
controversy among city officials and the public, with radio talk
shows and the Daily News giving out the council office telephone
numbers to urge officials not to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   Council offices reported receiving hundreds of calls and
e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   And, the more-than-hourlong debate pitted council member
frustration with the convention's Host Committee as well as
competing political agendas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say I resent being put into this position,''
Councilwoman Jackie Goldberg said. ``Frankly, there's been no
outreach from the Host Committee to my office. I haven't been asked
for any input ... or any actual involvement. Now, my involvement is
sincerely requested when you're $4 million short. To say I don't
resent it would be a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Noelia Rodriguez, head of the Host Committee, acknowledged the
problems the committee has had in raising the money and said she
was ``humbly'' requesting the city help.
</P>
<P>
   The problem faced by the committee is that it needs the money by
July 1 to pay contractors for work to be done at Staples Center for
the convention, Rodriguez said, adding her group would prefer a
direct payment from the city rather than a loan.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez pointed to the $32.5 million that has been raised
privately, more than any other host committee, and said she was
looking to expand the group's partnership with the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great investment for the taxpayers of Los Angeles,''
Rodriguez said. ``The Democratic Convention is expected to generate
about $135 million in direct economic benefit for Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   She also cited the amounts invested by other jurisdictions in
their hosting of other political conventions. In Philadelphia, some
$17 million in direct cash payments from government were received
for this year's Republican National Convention, and in 1996, the
Chicago Host Committee received $14 million in public funds.
</P>
<P>
   But Councilman Joel Wachs questioned the need for city funds now
and raised the credibility problems it created.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you really have here is a few of the richest men in Los
Angeles asking the city to bail them out of their financial
obligations,'' Wachs said. ``That redefines what chutzpah is all
about. It is a slap in the face of every citizen who expects this
government to spend money in their interests and not the affluent
of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a deal and said we would provide all the services we
would provide any convention. We are honoring that deal. It is time
for those who put in writing that they would raise all the money
that they live up to their end of the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But other council members argued the Host Committee and its
principal backers - billionaires Eli Broad and Ron Burkle - had
done well and it was the city that would be embarrassed if the
convention did not go off well.
</P>
<P>
   ``However uncomfortable we may be with this, I don't think we
have a whole lot of choices,'' Councilwoman Ruth Galanter said.
``The fact of the matter is, it is the city that will hosting all
these people. They're not going to turn around and say the Host
Committee didn't do this or didn't do that. They're going to say it
was the city of Los Angeles that didn't do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Galanter and others noted the convention provided an opportunity
for the city to redeem itself from the dismal millennium New Year's
Eve party.
</P>
<P>
   It was Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas who asked for the delay on
the vote to get more information from city staffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have confidence that our own staff knows where this
money is going and that it is needed,'' Ridley-Thomas said. ``I do
not recall a time when we have allocated money without knowing how
it will be used.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Hal Bernson came up with the proposal to have the
city lend the money to the Host Committee as well as the temporary
increase in the bed tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want them to put on a good show but we also don't want to
use tax dollars,'' Bernson said. ``If we loan them the money, then
we will get some assurances it will be paid back as they continue
their fund raising.''
</P>
<P>
   While some skepticism was voiced over the proposal on how the
Host Committee could guarantee any repayment, other officials said
they believed it was worth studying.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, the council did agree to make a $2
million payment to the Los Angeles Visitors and Convention Bureau
to contract for shuttle buses during the convention.
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
