<SLUG> BC-HATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES EXPANSION 
OF FEDERAL HATE CRIME LAWS 

</HEADLINE>
 CRIMES-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate approved legislation Tuesday that would
broaden federal hate crime laws to include protections for gays and
the disabled following an aggressive lobbying effort by the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, approved 57-42, was prompted in part by the public
outrage over two brutal 1998 murders, one involving the dragging
death in Texas of James Byrd Jr., a 49-year-old black man, and the
beating death in Wyoming of Matthew Shepard, a 21-year-old gay
college student.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore interrupted his campaign for the
presidency to preside over the Senate in case his support was
needed to break a tie vote. But 13 Republicans joined with 44
Democrats to help pass the measure by a wide margin, leaving Gore
with no other job in the proceedings than to announce the final
tally.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton applauded the Senate action. ``This amendment
recognizes that hate crimes are different from other crimes,'' he
said in a statement. ``These crimes affect entire communities and
strike at the heart of our American system of values.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, co-sponsored by Sens. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., and Gordon Smith, R-Ore., would expand 1968 federal hate
crime statute involving religion, national origin and race to
include new categories specifically related to offenses motivated
by sexual orientation, disability or gender. It would also make it
easier for prosecutors to prove hatred as a criminal motive, and
give them more freedom to decide whether to step in if local
authorities decline to pursue a case.
</P>
<P>
   Although the measure drew more Republican support than expected,
its future is unclear because the Senate also approved a competing
hate crimes amendment offered by Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The Hatch measure, which passed 50-49 shortly before the
Kennedy-Smith bill was brought up, calls for a federal study of
hate-crimes prosecutions by state and local authorities and adds $5
million more to the Justice Department budget for the prosecution
of hate crimes. But Hatch stopped short of adding any new
categories to the federal laws, saying he believes that local
governments are doing well enough on their own dealing with crimes
of hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Both amendments will now be attached to a larger defense
spending bill, which has been bogged down in the Senate for weeks
because it is being used as a vehicle for hundreds of unrelated
measures that senators on both sides of the aisle would like to see
passed.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said Tuesday there
may be as many 100 more amendments to the bill to consider, and he
suggested that the entire measure might have to be set aside
indefinitely unless members can come to some agreement on detaching
unrelated amendments from the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Lott opposed the administration-supported bill, saying it would
``federalize'' many violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``State laws are working and doing a fine job,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Hatch and the Kennedy-Smith amendments were identical
to two competing measures that were approved by the Senate last
year by unanimous consent. But the House voted down a hate crimes
bill of its own last spring, and the Senate measures never survived
a conference with the House.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he hopes the legislation's fate will be different
this year, given the outrage many Americans feel in the aftermath
of the Byrd and Sheppard cases. He urged the House to take up the
issue again this year to ensure that a final bill gets to the
president for his signature.
</P>
<P>
   Republican House leaders have said they have no plans to
schedule a vote this year on hate crimes legislation. But Gore
suggested that the administration may use the threat of a veto on
other legislation to help force action by the House. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
