A9929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LEONE-U.N.-NYT &LR;      06-20 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEONE-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA LEONE ASKS UNITED NATIONS FOR ROLE IN WAR COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Sierra Leone has asked the United Nations to
set up a war crimes tribunal to try rebel leaders whose troops
maimed and killed Sierra Leoneans and abducted 500 international
peacekeepers, plunging the country into a new round of violence in
May.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed court, as outlined in a letter to
Secretary-General Kofi Annan from Sierra Leone's president, Ahmad
Tejan Kabbah, would be a far cry from an international tribunal of
the sort established in the 1990s for the Balkans and Rwanda.
Instead, it would be closer to the one now being created for
Cambodia's Khmer Rouge, with considerable power in the hands of the
national government. Prosecutors and judges would be a mix of
Sierra Leoneans and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The hybrid court envisioned by Sierra Leone would be based there
and limited to hearing cases against only one faction, the
Revolutionary United Front of Foday Sankoh. This spring, Sankoh
broke a year-old peace agreement that had given him a role in
government and turned his troops on both President Kabbah's army
and U.N. peacekeepers. He is now in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, which sent troops to Sierra Leone last month, helped
Sierra Leone draft its proposal for a tribunal, diplomats said
Tuesday. The court would be established under one of possibly three
Security Council resolutions on Sierra Leone to be debated in
coming weeks. The other two would impose an embargo on arms sales
and diamond exports and enlarge the U.N. peacekeeping force and
strengthen its powers.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats say the United States originally appeared to want a
more international tribunal, but now seemed to be closer to
supporting the British-assisted plan outlined by Kabbah. An
American official said that the United States was still far from a
decision on the shape of the court.
</P>
<P>
   At a Security Council meeting Tuesday, the American Ambassador
Richard Holbrooke said that he was against creating an entirely new
tribunal for Sierra Leone but that ``some form of extension of the
international war crime umbrella to cover these odious people must
be undertaken.''
</P>
<P>
   A copy of Kabbah's letter and its detailed annex, sent a week
ago, was made available to The New York Times by experts outside
the United Nations. Officials in the organization would not discuss
the plan, saying it is still being studied.
</P>
<P>
   The limitations on the proposed court's reach and the large role
reserved for the weak government and justice system of Sierra Leone
raise fears among some international human rights experts, who say
that numerous factions have been involved in abuses in Sierra
Leone, in a war marked by the hacking off of civilians' limbs and
the destruction of countless communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two main concerns that we have,'' said Peter
Bouckaert of Human Rights Watch, who recently returned from Sierra
Leone. ``One is that it deals only with the RUF. We think for a
tribunal to have any kind of international credibility, it would
have to address the criminal responsibility of all sides in the
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Revolutionary United Front, he said, there
are the Armed Forces Revolutionary Council; one of its most violent
factions, known as the West Side Boys; and bands of former
government soldiers who joined the rebels to attack Freetown, the
country's capital, in January 1999 after Sankoh broke an earlier
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A second concern cited by Bouckaert was ``the dominant role that
Sierra Leone would play in this proposed hybrid court, considering
the politicization that would take place and also the limited
capacity that the Sierra Leone judiciary has at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Kabbah said in his letter and annex that a court created by the
Security Council would have ``the advantage of strong enforcement
powers that will call for cooperation from states in
investigations, arrest, extradition and the enforcement of
sentence.'' He also asked that it be paid for through an
international trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the working of the court, Kabbah called for a
``narrow'' list of those to be charged from the Revolutionary
United Front, possibly in the dozens. He said this would allow the
court to be ``quick and efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Kabbah asked for a blend of Sierra Leone and international law
to be applied in order to include crimes against humanity and
crimes against peacekeepers, which are not in the national code. He
expected the court to sit in Sierra Leone unless security made it
necessary to move elsewhere. It would have West African and
possibly other judges. For appeals, the tribunal could make use of
an appeals panel in The Hague, which hears cases from the Balkans
and Rwanda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
