<HEADER>
A9930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GAS-PRICES-NYT &LR;      06-20 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL AND STATE OFFICIALS SUSPECT GASOLINE PRICE GOUGING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Midwest)   By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With gasoline prices in the Midwest surging past $2
a gallon, Gov. Frank L. O'Bannon of Indiana on Tuesday suspended
the state's gas tax for two months and warned that he may seek an
inquiry into possible price gouging by the oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   O'Bannon, who said the tax break would reduce the price of
gasoline in his state by as much as 10 cents a gallon, demanded to
know why gas stations in Indiana are charging record prices,
exceeding the national average by as much as 50 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The move came as the Federal Trade Commission opened an
investigation into the price increases in the Midwest, which have
drivers in Chicago paying an average of $2.13 a gallon, a 55
percent increase since January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoosiers can't afford to wait on federal and state
investigators to tell us why the Midwest is being hit so hard,''
O'Bannon said.
</P>
<P>
   If prices do not fall soon, he said, he will ask the state's
attorney general to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore said in Lexington, Ky., Tuesday that
profit reported by oil companies earlier this year suggested that
``big oil is gouging American consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee for president, said he
is seeking to arrange a meeting with the governors of states most
affected, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson and Carol Browner, the
administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The governors and the administration officials should work
together to determine whether the oil companies are fixing prices
or otherwise colluding against consumers, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Oil industry experts have attributed the rising prices to
limited supplies, the disruption of a pipeline in Michigan and a
new federal environmental requirement that regions with significant
air pollution sell cleaner-burning fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA last week said it would consider a request by Gov.
George Ryan of Illinois to waive rules that would have required
dealers to sell gasoline with less-polluting additives such as
ethanol beginning this month.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan had accused the environmental agency of failing to consider
the impact the new requirement would have.
</P>
<P>
   But federal officials said there were few indications that the
anti-pollution requirement was to blame for the price increases,
especially since the stock of reformulated gasoline is sufficient
and oil companies have had five years to prepare for the change.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jan Schakowsky, D-Ill., accused the oil companies of
gouging consumers in Chicago and Milwaukee in retaliation for the
new rules on additives.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pitofsky, the chairman of the Federal Trade Commission,
told members of the Illinois congressional delegation Tuesday that
price surges in some Midwestern cities raised enough questions to
warrant the inquiry, congressional officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC will issue subpoenas for testimony from oil company
executives beginning next week, the officials said. The
investigation, which could take as long as six weeks, will be
conducted by the FTC's Bureau of Competition, which has already
been looking into whether higher prices in California resulted from
collusion between gasoline refiners or distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard J. Durbin, D-Ill., told The Associated Press that
the investigation in the Midwest would send ``a clear signal to the
oil companies to bring down prices immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
