<HEADER>
A9932 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-BASEBALL-RESEARCH     06-20 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-RESEARCH21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball fanatics gather to pay homage to sport
 &HT;    By Joe Capozzi
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Skip Smith, a trial lawyer for Florida's
largest law firm, Holland &AMP; Knight, is supposed to be taking
depositions this week for a class-action lawsuit against a medical
management company.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 57-year-old litigator will stand at a podium in the
Sheraton West Palm Beach Hotel and argue a subject passionate to
his heart:
</P>
<P>
   Has Major League Baseball lost its pennant fever?
</P>
<P>
   Smith will be followed by a computer science professor from the
University of South Carolina, who will offer a debate on this
thought: Do intentional walks save runs?
</P>
<P>
   Retired newspaperman Eddie Gold will recite six poems, including
``Kerry Wood is Pitching Today.'' Rob Edelman from Albany, N.Y.,
will devote his 30-minute session to William Frawley, the actor
best known as Fred Mertz on ``I Love Lucy,'' who hung out with Joe
DiMaggio and had a clause in his contract that gave him time off
the set to attend the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   And for the most diehard fans, there's the slide show ``Where
They Lie: A Tour of Baseball Gravesites,'' offered by Stew
Thornley, who says he has visited the graves of more than 100
Baseball Hall of Famers.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the 30th annual convention of the Society For
American Baseball Research, a grass-roots following of 6,800
members from Cooperstown, N.Y., to Tahiti devoted to everything
balls, strikes and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The Star Trekkies of the baseball world, about 400 Saberites are
expected to converge on the Sheraton for four days of lectures,
numbers-crunching and general baseball breeze-shooting. Some will
clutch binders thick with stat sheets; others will stroll the lobby
dressed head-to-toe in uniforms of not-forgotten teams such as the
St. Louis Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, I thought I was a baseball expert,'' said
Smith, a lawyer for 33 years who joined SABR (pronounced
``say-ber'') in 1997. ``These people are total baseball geeks. They
make me look like an amateur.''
</P>
<P>
   Registration begins today, but the action starts Thursday with a
welcoming luncheon speech by SABR member and Florida Marlins
General Manager Dave Dombrowski. After two hours of committee
meetings, the research presentations begin with talks about Italian
baseball and Tom ``Lefty'' Sunkel, a minor-league pitcher who
pitched a no-hitter in 1946 despite being blind in one eye.
</P>
<P>
   In between discussions on ``The Evolution of the Relief
Pitcher'' and ``111 Years of Major League Ejections,'' the
Saberites will gather for the keynote speech by 89-year-old Elden
Auker, a submarine-style pitcher for the Detroit Tigers who once
struck out Babe Ruth and faced Dizzy Dean in Game7 of the 1934
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the highlight will be the annual Trivia Challenge,
described by veteran whizzes as a thorough and often ``vicious''
competition in which the top prize is bragging rights for being the
Mark McGwire of SABR know-it-alls.
</P>
<P>
   At last year's convention in Phoenix, one member recalled, ``I
was sitting at the hotel bar and there were guys talking about how
they could lure this other guy away from a team.''
</P>
<P>
   While it all sounds far out even to casual baseball fans, to the
Saberites, knowing who replaced Tony Kubek after he was struck in
the throat by Bill Virdon's grounder in Game7 of the 1960 World
Series (Joe DeMaestri) is serious stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone has a question about baseball, if we can't answer
it, chances are no one can,'' SABR President Jim Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   From Hall of Famer Ted Williams to Wellington High School
teacher Dale Hains, members pay annual dues of $50 and receive four
meticulously researched publications. Like articles in the New
England Journal of Medicine reporting the latest medical
breakthroughs, SABR's Baseball Research Journal has published
studies that have helped correct dozens of errors in baseball's
record books.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't as noble as fighting cancer,'' said West Palm Beach
attorney Jim Watt, the local organizer of the convention. ``It's
just all people who love baseball and love to research it.''
</P>
<P>
   Do they ever. One member, retired Western Union employee Joe
Donner, has looked up the box score of every major-league game
since 1871. ``I went to one presentation last year,'' Watt
recalled, ``and this one guy studied 17,000 intentional walks. I'm
sitting there thinking, `Get a life, guy!'''
</P>
<P>
   SABR geeks such as convention lecturer Mark Pankin, whose vanity
car plate reads ``NO DH,'' will argue that they have a life. It's
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always intersted in baseball. Lou Gehrig was my favorite
player,'' said Bob Davids. A retired U.S. Department of Energy
employee, Davids began publishing a newsletter called Baseball
Briefs around 1971 when he put out a call for people like him
intersted in forming a group.
</P>
<P>
   The first gathering of about 16 members took place in
Cooperstown, N.Y. Today, the society is recognized by Major League
Baseball for its work. It has helped spawn a new wave of baseball
research, which includes the basis for the Total Baseball
encyclopedia and for Bill James' thought-provoking revisionist
philosophy known as Sabermetrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very respected. They've definitely made a
contribution,'' said Jerome Holtzman, official historian for Major
League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Log on to SABR's daily e-mail digest, and discussions will range
from players who appeared on baseball cards without ever making it
into a game to the pronounciation of names (''It's 'Hah-nus'
Wagner, not ``Hoe-nis,'' a Saberite wrote last week).
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very, very deep,'' Dombrowksi said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, some members say, SABR is divided into two camps, bonded
by baseball but ``often at war with each other'': folks interested
in general history and the folks the longtime member referred to as
``the statistical freaks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't bother me,'' said stat expert Bob McConnell, one
of the original 16 charter members who acknowledges the ``freak''
label. ``I guess I'm a little bit odd. I like to play with numbers.
Other people have hobbies and I think they're odd. But I don't say
anything because I know mine is odd.''
</P>
<P>
   The history buffs have been labeled as odd, too. At the SABR
convention in Pittsburgh a few years ago, one tour went to a house
just off the University of Pittsburgh campus where Babe Ruth's
final home run is said to have landed on the front porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple college kids living there were looking out the window
at us, wondering why 20 guys in Pirate caps were standing in their
front yard,'' recalled Dennis Repp.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Watt says he won't be surprised if small crowds are
seen milling about in the Kravis Center parking garage looking for
the home-plate marker from old Connie Mack Field.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Watt admits he was impressed enough after attending a
recent convention that he and his pal Skip Smith lobbied hard to
persuade SABR to hold this year's gathering in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it certainly didn't hurt when Watt did some
name-dropping about a secretary in the law firm where he works,
Steel Hector &AMP; Davis. Judy Wilkinson is the daughter of the late
Bob Cain, the White Sox left-hander who walked Eddie Gaedel in the
midget's famous pinch-hitting apperance for the St. Louis Browns in
1951.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
