A9933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-TRADE-NYT &LR;      06-20 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND SENATORS MANEUVER TO EXPEDITE VOTE ON CHINA TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four weeks after the House approved a decisive bill
on trade with China, President Clinton summoned a bipartisan group
of senators to the White House on Tuesday night to talk strategy on
pressing Republican leaders to set a date for bringing up the bill
in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike supporters in the House, who had to hustle votes up to
the last minute, Senate backers of granting China permanent normal
trading status say they have more than 70 votes in favor. That is
enough to defeat a filibuster and win handily.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters want to pass a clean version of the House bill,
free of amendments that would force the measure back to the House
for a potentially treacherous second vote. And that is proving to
be tricky.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader and a supporter of the
bill, has said the Senate does not have time to defuse all possible
amendments and to vote on the measure before the weeklong July 4
recess. That leaves a three-week window in July before the long
August recess.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican leadership has given priority to approving
several must-pass spending bills this summer before considering the
trade measure, which would end Congress' annual review of China's
trade status.
</P>
<P>
   Some top Senate Republican aides suggested that the twists and
turns of the spending bills could put off a vote on the China
legislation until September, which supporters angrily said could
imperil the bill, as it might get caught up in election-year
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go into September, our chances for passage drop
precipitously,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the
Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House early on Tuesday evening, Clinton met with 17
Republicans and Democrats who support the bill. They included the
top Republican and Democrat on the Finance Committee, William V.
Roth Jr. of Delaware and Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York. It
was Clinton's second strategy session with senators since the House
passed the measure, 237-197, on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is undoubtedly one of the most important votes any of
these senators will ever take,'' the White House spokesman, Joe
Lockhart, said on Tuesday. ``And it's certainly our hope we can get
this done quickly and without the long arm of partisan politics
entering the fray.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans who support the bill say they were watching
the Senate machinations and consulting with Lott's staff. ``We're
monitoring it and we're not worried _ yet,'' said one House aide.
</P>
<P>
   Lott and Daschle are talking with several senators who have
expressed interest in offering amendments. Sen. Jesse Helms, a
North Carolina Republican who heads the Foreign Relations
Committee, has promised a ``robust debate'' and ``uncomfortable
votes'' on issues ranging from China's use of prison labor to its
crackdown on political dissent. Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., said
on Tuesday that he would offer amendments on human rights and labor
conditions in China.
</P>
<P>
   But the most immediate problem for Lott and the administration
is an amendment sponsored by Sens. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and
Robert Torricelli, D-N.J. The amendment would provide for an annual
review of China's record in trafficking nuclear, chemical and
biological warfare and missile technology. The measure would also
require the administration to impose sanctions on individuals,
groups or companies that the United States identifies as weapons
proliferators.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the national security adviser, Sandy Berger, met
with Senate Republicans to discuss Thompson's proposal and other
national security issues. On Friday, the White House chief of
staff, John D. Podesta, also met with Thompson about his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Lott is trying to negotiate with Democrats to allow for debate
and a separate vote on Thompson's measure _ the price for his
agreeing not to amend what is likely to be a popular provision to
the China trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said on Tuesday he would insist on a vote on his
measure before the Senate considers the trade bill. But the
administration opposes it, saying it is unnecessary and overly
broad and has thresholds for imposing sanctions that are too low.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2134EDT &QL; 
