<SLUG> BC-MADDEN-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATED SHOE DESIGNER STEVEN MADDEN FACES STOCK MANIPULATION
CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., a word in double parentheses ((thus)) should be set in
brackets.) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Steven Madden, a designer who is chairman and chief
executive of a popular women's shoe company, was arrested Tuesday
on charges of securities fraud, including the initial public
offering of his own company.
</P>
<P>
   In separate indictments, federal prosecutors in Brooklyn and
Manhattan charged Madden with securities fraud, conspiracy and
money laundering, saying that he participated in more than 20
fraudulent initial offerings of stock dating back to 1993, when
Steven Madden Ltd. went public.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Securities and Exchange Commission said in a
civil lawsuit arising from Madden's trading activities that the
stock frauds generated about $7 million in profits for Madden and
others who participated in the conspiracy. The commission is
seeking to bar Madden from serving as an officer or director of any
publicly traded company, said Wayne Carlin, SEC associate regional
director.
</P>
<P>
   Madden, 43, is a celebrated shoe designer whose trendy platform
styles are available in 3,000 department stores and 60 Steven
Madden Ltd. stores. The company had sales of $163 million in its
1999 year, nearly double the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   But Madden's arrest Tuesday cast a cloud over his fast-growing
company.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Marotta, an analyst who follows the company for
Wasserstein Perella Securities, called Madden pivotal to the
company and downgraded the stock from a ``buy'' to
``underperform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the key visionary,'' Marotta said. ``He has a team of
designers who execute his order, but he is the key guy. It is
difficult to understate his importance.''
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement released Tuesday, the company said its
``business remains strong and it plans to continue to execute its
long-term strategies.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Madden denied the charges Tuesday afternoon, and
said that their client was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in Brooklyn said Madden was involved in a
fraudulent scheme to manipulate the the stock of Steven Madden Ltd.
when it went from being a small regional company with limited
assets to a public company in December 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The offering was underwritten by the now-defunct brokerage firm
Stratton Oakmont. The National Association of Securities Dealers
had refused to allow Stratton Oakmont to underwrite the sale if any
of the brokerage firm's principals owned more than 4.9 percent of
the company's stock. To deceive regulators, prosecutors charged,
Madden falsely said that Stratton Oakmont's principals had sold
shares to a separate company controlled by Madden. Prosecutors said
that the sale was a sham and that Madden, in fact, had promised the
Stratton Oakmont principals that they would continue to control the
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that in 1997 a principal in Stratton Oakmont
demanded that Madden sell the stock and provide him with the
proceeds. Madden refused, the prosecutors said, because he did not
want to flood the market and depress the company's stock price.
After a lawsuit was filed in state court, prosecutors said, Madden
agreed to pay $4.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments in both Brooklyn and Manhattan charge that
Madden allegedly participated in a series of illicit stock
transactions during next several years involving Stratton Oakmont
and another brokerage firm, Monroe Parker, which is also now
defunct.
</P>
<P>
   In those deals, prosecutors charged, Madden agreed to buy stock
from from companies before their public offerings and then sell it
back to the brokerage firms once public trading began. The
prosecutors said that Madden was allowed to keep a portion of the
proceeds amounting to the difference between what he paid for the
stock and the price at which he sold it. They said the arrangement
allowed the firms to illegally manipulate the market price for
those stocks. In some examples, prosecutors said, the firms were
able to resell the stocks at inflated prices.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the principals of both brokerage firms have
already pleaded guilty to fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Madden's lawyers said their client had engaged in stock
transactions with the defunct brokerage firms, but that he was
innocent of acting illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``These indictments contain charges based on the words of
convicted felons who wreaked havoc on Wall Street, based on
campaigns of deception, fraud and lies,'' said Corey Winograd, one
of Madden's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody disputes ((Madden)) had transactions of stock,''
Winograd said. But he said that accusations of kickbacks and
fraudulent trades were unsubstantiated. ``There were transactions,
transactions that were documented, transactions that were lawful
and proper.''
</P>
<P>
   Madden was released on bond of $750,000, backed by three pieces
of property, including his home in East Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Madden is being charged with manipulating the stock
of Steve Madden Ltd., stock analysts say the company itself is in
sound financial shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two cast of characters we are dealing with here,''
Marotta said. ``One is the group that handled the IPO and is
involved with what happened with Steve's personal financials, and
the other are the people he hired for the company, and these groups
don't intersect.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Marotta says the company has a healthy balance
sheet, investors may lose confidence in the company in the short
run and the brand could ``get off track'' in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Madden owns 1.2 million shares, nearly 10 percent, of the
company, according to recent securities filings, and has options
that would bring his stake to 18 percent. While the prosecutors
were closing in on him, he sold 100,000 shares at $16 on May 31.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which peaked at $22 7/16 in April, fell $1.94 Tuesday
to $11.125 before trading was halted late in the morning. The
company went public at $4 a share in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
