<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LAKERS RULE. SOME DAY, THE BULLS. 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the morning after the pro basketball marathon finally ended,
Jerry Krause looked out the window of his office at the Chicago
Bulls' practice facility and there was the co-rookie of the year,
Elton Brand, working on his footwork for next season,
four-and-a-half-months away and counting.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of the Bulls' other young players, Ron Artest and
Michael Ruffin, were also in the building, energizing Krause as he
planned for the college draft and free-agent season, the time of
year when general managers become franchise players.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Jerry West is responsible for what happened in Los
Angeles last night,'' Krause said Tuesday. ``He's the one who
maneuvered to get that team under the cap so they could sign
Shaquille O'Neal. He's the one who made the Kobe Bryant deal
happen. But he's getting far less credit than he should. Instead
you hear, well, other things.''
</P>
<P>
   You hear about Phil Jackson winning in his first coaching try
out of Chicago, without Michael Jordan, for whom he has always had
the ultimate respect, and without Krause, for whom he has had,
well, other things.
</P>
<P>
   Intramural pettiness aside, Jackson deserves a round of applause
for being able to take his high-profile act elsewhere and
immediately succeed. Ditto West, who restored the Lakers to
prominence 12 years after they last won the title and nine years
after their last trip to the National Basketball Association
finals.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like a long time, consider when Boston and
Detroit, those erstwhile Lakers combatants in championship series
past, might next play in June.
</P>
<P>
   Krause spoke with West last week, the Pacers still nipping at
Shaq's heels, and West admitting that he was sweating, as in the
old days. ``He was saying that you go along for years trying to put
your team back into position where it has a realistic chance to
win, and then the pressure of feeling like you have to win hits
you,'' Krause said. ``At the end of our run here in Chicago, we
were playing not to lose. You get a little excited when you start
to think that soon, we could be playing to win.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no guarantees that the stripped-to-the-Brand Bulls
will soon be very good, or any good. Yet just as Jackson's
achievements should not pass without a proper salute, nor can the
work Krause has done steering his team into quality rebuilding
position. Less than two years after critics foolishly blamed him
for the deconstruction that had to occur the moment Elvis left the
building, he is taking two first-round selections, Nos. 4 and 7,
and six picks in all into next week's draft. For a class of
talented and potentially dominant free agents who are in various
stages of home-team disaffection, the Bulls are armed and ready,
$19 million under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Again, there are no sure things, but considering the altitude
from which the Bulls fell, Krause has a chance to author one of the
fastest and greatest retooling jobs in the history of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   As a mass-appeal phenomenon, the NBA suffered a descent that has
been, at least by measure of public perception, parallel to the
Bulls'. Television ratings fell precipitously, no shock considering
how invested in one player the league and its synergistic partners
were. Golf may be the current ratings rage, but if Tiger Woods left
Earth tomorrow to defy the gravitational odds elsewhere, golf would
revert to the modest, elitist draw it was.
</P>
<P>
   David Stern was right when he called this season a
``transitional year where the fans are getting to know our new
players.'' The commissioner's marketing machine tried too hard with
Vince Carter, but the league does have a solid nucleus of young
stars, and, as we've seen with Kobe, the kind who really want to
validate themselves with championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what these people are talking about when they say
it was a bad season,'' said Krause, the lifer who was thrilled by
the finals and the sight of games again featuring the art of
scoring the ball.
</P>
<P>
   His team won 17 games, but to measure the Bulls' standing by
number of victories distorts the context of how one can best cope
with prosperity's end. While a phenomenon such as Jordan bloats
interest, fan bases don't disappear overnight. Krause has noticed
that the White Sox fans, thought to be an endangered species in
Chicago, are returning in droves to Comiskey Park. Those 23,000
Bulls fans at the United Center won't stay forever, but, as Krause
said, with any luck, they'll have a competitive team again soon.
</P>
<P>
   For team and league, two years is a snap of the finger, a blink
of an eye, a chance to work on footwork and take small steps
forward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
