<SLUG> BC-NY-HARLEM-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER PREVENTION AND TREATMENT CENTER PLANNED FOR HARLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In one of the most expansive collaborations between a
major medical center and a New York community hospital, Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center will help establish a cancer
prevention and treatment center at the North General Hospital in
Harlem, executives at both centers said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The center will be known as the Ralph Lauren Center for Cancer
Prevention and Care, reflecting a $5 million gift from the fashion
designer's company. The creation of the center, which is expected
to be announced Wednesday, springs in part from years of research
demonstrating large disparities between blacks and whites in cancer
detection and survival rates, as well as Lauren's longstanding
interest in breast cancer philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   The center also reflects a subtle but significant shift in the
role that Sloan-Kettering, now under the leadership of Dr. Harold
Varmus, plays in areas where most people lack access to basic care,
let alone the cutting-edge research and high-profile doctors for
which Sloan-Kettering is internationally known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to feel we are serving the city,'' said Varmus, former
director of the National Institutes of Health who took the helm of
Sloan-Kettering this year. ``We are not doing as much as we can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The center is also an outgrowth of the relationship between
Sloan-Kettering and Dr. Harold P. Freeman, now president of North
General. Freeman was a founder and medical director of
Sloan-Kettering's Breast Examination Center of Harlem, which was
set up 20 years ago with the New York State Department of Health to
try to lower the rates of late-stage breast cancer among black
women.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman and Varmus decided that the hospital could reach more
people in Harlem with a center that could diagnose other forms of
cancer and with one that offered on-site treatment, rather than
referring patients elsewhere, which often leads to people's
stopping care. The Ralph Lauren center, which is to open late this
year, will provide screening and diagnostic tests for breast,
prostate, colon and cervical cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Sloan-Kettering's most prominent doctors will help
oversee the development of the center, and patients whose cancers
are diagnosed there may be referred to Sloan-Kettering for drug
trials or other treatments, something that many Harlem patients can
ill afford and know little about. The move may reflect Varmus'
interest in applying more of the hospital's research toward
clinical care for a broader swath of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Easy access to good care is crucial to early diagnoses of
cancer, both doctors said. Late detection is the No. 1 reason that
people die from treatable forms of cancer, and studies have shown
that many forms of cancer are detected later in blacks than in
whites. .
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in a 20-year study of more than 700 women in
Harlem that ended in 1986, only 30 percent had survived breast
cancer five years after diagnosis, compared with national rates
closer to 65 percent, Freeman said. Looked at another way, the
study found that only 6 percent of the women had early-stage, or
the most treatable, cancers. Since the center's inception, that
rate has risen to 40 percent, Freeman said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a study reported last year in the New England Journal of
Medicine found that blacks were less likely than whites to have
surgery for early-stage lung cancer and were thus more likely to
die from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this community, 41 percent of the people are poor,''
Freeman said. ``And poverty causes a set of complex human
circumstances that lead to late diagnoses. But there are things we
can do to confront those conditions by creating easy access to care
and smooth systems without barriers to treatment. We have found
that when you offer certain conditions to people, they tend to be
compliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauren was an early financial supporter of programs for breast
cancer. In 1989, he donated $100,000 to begin the Nina Hyde Center
for Breast Cancer Research at Georgetown University, named for his
friend, a fashion writer for The Washington Post who died the
following year.
</P>
<P>
   He also started a campaign called ``Fashion Targets Breast
Cancer'' and was recently introduced to Freeman. ``I wanted to do
more,'' Lauren said in an interview. ``Dr. Freeman really impressed
me. He made me aware of a lot of things I was not aware of in
Harlem.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauren said that recent reports of a mammogram center in the
Bronx where the state said hundreds of faulty tests were performed
had furthered his interest. ``That was really scary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what attracted Lauren to the project was that the center
will educate patients about their treatment. Lauren, who battled
with a benign brain tumor 12 years ago, said, ``I knew what it was
like not to know which doctor to go to, and I was well known.''
</P>
</TEXT>
