<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge Delays Restrictions in Microsoft Antitrust Case
</P>
<P>
   The trial judge in the Microsoft antitrust case unexpectedly
issued an order delaying the sweeping conduct restrictions he had
imposed until a higher court affirms them. Until the order by the
judge, Thomas Penfield Jackson, the Supreme Court would have been
called on to rule quickly on Microsoft's request to stay the remedy
order _ or to decide that the case should be sent to the appeals
court. Now the Supreme Court, or the appeals court, can review the
entire appeal, and rule on it, before deciding whether to impose
the judge's remedy, modify it or cancel it. The process could take
a year or longer.
</P>
<P>
   Publicis Reaches a Deal for Saatchi
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, the London agency company, agreed to be
acquired by Publicis for about $1.9 billion in stock. Maurice Levy,
the chairman and chief executive of Publicis, will head a merged
entity, the Publicis Groupe, which will oversee the agencies now
under the Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi and Publicis banners. Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
will continue as an autonomous unit. The American depository
receipts of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi fell $1.5625, to $31.50, after
increasing by 30.3 percent on Monday. Publicis dropped almost 12
percent. Stuart Elliott: Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle Posts 76% Gain in Earnings
</P>
<P>
   Propelled by strong sales of software applications for doing
business over the Internet, Oracle posted a 76 percent gain in
fourth-quarter earnings, beating analysts' estimates. But sales of
Oracle's core database product slightly trailed estimates, and
Oracle shares dropped in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Hits 4,000, but Dow Falls
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were mixed as the Dow Jones industrial average fell
122.68 points, or 1.2 percent, to 10,435.16, and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index slipped 10.05 points, or 0.7 percent, to
1,475.95. But the Nasdaq composite index gained 23.53 points, or
0.6 percent, to 4,013.36, closing above 4,000 for the first time in
more than two months. The index is now down just 1.4 percent this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Island Stock Jumps 31 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Digital Island soared 31 percent after the company
said that it was working with Compaq Computer, Intel and Microsoft
to create a network for delivering real-time audio and video on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs Profit Rises 21%
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming big paper losses on some of its investments, Goldman
Sachs rode its best performance in investment banking to a 21
percent increase in second-quarter profit, beating forecasts.
Despite the solid results, shares of Goldman fell $2.625, to $89.
</P>
<P>
   Breakup of Russian Utility Opposed
</P>
<P>
   A group of foreign investors in Russia's electricity monopoly,
Unified Energy Systems, has asked President Vladimir V. Putin to
stop a corporate breakup that the investors say is moving too fast
and would destroy the value of their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   I Was a Teen-age Phenomenon
</P>
<P>
   David Nelms, president and chief operating officer at Discover
Financial Services, a unit of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, was quite
the industrious teen-ager. He ran a lawn service and made more per
hour than his mother. He narrowly missed winning a $10,000
scholarship in a Junior Achievement competition. And he bought
several rental properties, managing and maintaining more than 50
units as an 18-year-old landlord. All that before college, marriage
and a Harvard MBA.
</P>
<P>
   Trade Deficit Narrowed in April
</P>
<P>
   The nation's trade deficit narrowed to $30.44 billion in April
from a record $30.6 billion in March as a decline in oil prices
offset record demand for foreign-made autos, computers and consumer
goods, government figures showed. The deficit is on track to reach
$350 billion this year, compared with last year's record of $265
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
