<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN SACHS REPORTS 21 PERCENT RISE IN QUARTERLY EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Overcoming big paper losses on some of its investments, the
Goldman Sachs Group rode its best performance in investment banking
to a 21 percent increase in net income in its fiscal second quarter
from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said Tuesday that it had earned $755 million, or $1.48 a
diluted share. The profits were as good as analysts had expected
before cautious talk from Goldman caused analysts to lower their
estimates last month. On May 25, a day before Goldman's quarter
ended, the analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial
estimated that the firm would earn $1.47 a diluted share, but by
Tuesday that projection had dropped to $1.37.
</P>
<P>
   The results compared favorably with the pro forma earnings of
$1.30 a share Goldman reported last May _ adjusted for the costs of
its initial public offering _ but they were 16 percent below the
record earnings of $887 million, or $1.76 a diluted share, it
recorded in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unexpectedly strong earnings, Goldman's share price
fell $2.625, to $89 on the New York Stock Exchange, while stocks of
some of other securities firms, including Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and
Lehman Brothers Holdings, rose 2.5 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the second time that Goldman has reported strong
numbers and other firms have rallied,'' said Henry McVey, a Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter analyst. McVey said investors appeared to be
hunting for less expensive stocks that would benefit from the same
factors that drove Goldman's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are also worried that the firm's employees and former
partners will flood the market with new shares that they can sell
for the first time this week, analysts said. Only about 15 percent
of the firm's outstanding shares have been available to trade,
McVey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are worried that what gave the stock a huge lift on the
way up _ an imbalance of demand and supply _ will start to work
against it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's balance sheet received its biggest boost from
underwriting stocks and advising companies on mergers in the United
States and, increasingly, in Europe. Its investment banking revenue
of $1.59 billion was 29 percent higher than in the first quarter,
which was Goldman's most profitable since it became a public
company a year ago, and 59 percent higher than in the second
quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman reaped hefty fees for underwriting huge stock offerings
for AT&AMP;T Wireless and PetroChina and for advising on acquisitions
like British Petroleum's purchase of Arco and Royal Bank of
Scotland's purchase of National Westminster Bank. Goldman ranked
first during the quarter as an underwriter of stocks, both global
and in the United States, David Viniar, the firm's chief financial
officer, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really dominated that sector completely in the quarter,''
Viniar said.
</P>
<P>
   The gains from banking and trading more than offset a sharp drop
in the value of Goldman's investments in private companies and
companies that have recently gone public. With the sell-off in
technology stocks that began in April, the value of those
investments fell $321 million in the quarter. Viniar estimated
those markdowns would result in a loss of about 19 cents a share
after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that loss represents a markdown on paper of unrealized
gains that had inflated Goldman's earnings in previous quarters,
Viniar said. Goldman recorded increases in the value of its
principal investments of more than $600 million in the previous two
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Viniar called that reversal a ``give-back of some of the froth
that was in the market.'' Still, he said, Goldman is looking at
``excellent'' returns on all of the investments that it had to mark
down last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's trading desks were living in two different worlds:
Revenue in stock trading rose 76 percent, while revenue from
trading bonds, currencies and commodities sank 30 percent from the
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The bond markets ``were really just slow,'' Viniar said, but
they have picked up in the last few weeks. ``When we look at the
business environment, we think the long-term prospects for our
business are as good as they have ever been,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
