<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE SHIFTS ON U.S. FUNDING FOR SUIT AGAINST TOBACCO INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Whirling around 180 degrees, the House on Tuesday
voted to allow the Department of Veterans Affairs to transfer $4
million to the Justice Department to help in its wide-ranging
lawsuit against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary about-face took place on a voice vote and
occurred less than 24 hours after the lawmakers had specifically
voted to ban such a transfer, arguing that the Justice Department
was taking away medical benefits from veterans to pay for its
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The measure defeated on Monday, an amendment by Rep. Henry A.
Waxman, D-Calif., would have permitted the transfer through
revisions of a $76.3 billion spending bill for the veterans agency
and the Department of House and Urban Affairs. It was defeated
207-197.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats crowed about the reversal Tuesday, asserting that it
showed that when forced into a public fight in defense of tobacco
companies, Republicans will ultimately back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to let them stop a lawsuit without people
noticing it,'' Waxman said. ``We believe that when people do notice
it, they can't sustain their position.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert scoffed at
suggestions that the reversal was an embarrassment to his party's
leadership by showing that it was unable to maintain a unified
front on the tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a decision that we had a good fight about taking
money from veterans health care and giving it to trial lawyers,''
said Hastert's spokesman, John Feehery.
</P>
<P>
   The battle is not yet over, Feehery said, and there will be
other opportunities to prevent the transfer of money to the Justice
Department for use in the lawsuit, which is seeking billions of
dollars from the tobacco companies to cover federal health-care
expenses related to tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican amendment in an upcoming spending bill to fund the
Commerce, Justice and State departments prohibits the Justice
Department from receiving any money for the lawsuit from other
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bipartisan victory should be a model for Congress,''
President Clinton said Tuesday in a statement praising the House
vote. ``The legal responsibility of the tobacco companies should be
decided in the courts by the judicial process.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the first vote on Monday, Attorney General Janet Reno had
pressed lawmakers to defeat of the measure blocking the transfer.
If the Justice Department cannot get financial help from other
agencies, Reno said, it might have to drop the lawsuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
