<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CONVENTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON ABC, BALLGAMES TOP POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the television battle between the Republicans and the
Democrats this summer, the winner is: the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Well, one of the winners, anyway. In a further downshifting of
convention coverage in prime time, ABC News announced Tuesday that
it would not pre-empt two preseason football games scheduled for
the opening nights of the Republican and Democratic national
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   But the network will not completely abandon politics in prime
time when the Republicans convene in Philadelphia on Monday, July
31, and the Democrats in Los Angeles on Monday, Aug. 14. David
Westin, the president of ABC News, said the network will provide
coverage during halftime of the games, one on July 31, when the
49ers play the New England Patriots, and the other on Aug. 14, when
the St. Louis Rams face the Tennessee Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Westin said that ABC News was planning an hour of coverage on
the second and third nights and two hours on the final night of
both conventions, with additional exposure on ``Nightline'' with
Ted Koppel. ABC officials said that was slightly less than the
network provided four years ago, when football did not intrude.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ABC News may as yet provide more prime-time coverage than
either of its rivals. CBS News and NBC News have yet to announce
their plans, but the two networks are considering scaling back.
(Neither party has announced its lineup of convention speakers.)
NBC News, however, will have a presence each night through its
all-news cable station, MSNBC, which will offer gavel-to-gavel
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for maintaining a strong prime-time presence by the
networks were disappointed by ABC News' announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidential campaign merits a halftime report in an NFL
preseason game,'' said Paul Taylor, executive director the Alliance
for Better Campaigns, which monitors network coverage of politics.
``What has broadcast television come to in terms of commitment?''
</P>
<P>
   Network officials say the lack of a contest for the nominations,
and the parties' desire to turn the gatherings into tightly
managed, four-day-long advertisements has diminished their value as
news events.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, a former political reporter, said the parties' decision
to present the conventions as feel-good commercials contributes to
the receding coverage on the networks, which still draw vastly
larger audiences than cable. But he added, ``By any modicum of news
judgment, it's an important occasion, even if it's a frustrating
occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Westin said ABC News had also invited Vice President Al Gore and
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas to face each other some time after the
conventions in an hourlong televised discussion, without a
moderator, and that the initial reaction from the campaigns had
been positive. He added that the network also wanted to produce
hourlong biographical specials of the two. The project's fate was
uncertain, he said, because the network might be required under the
fairness doctrine to also devote that amount to third-party
candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
