<HEADER>
A9944 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-UNIVERSAL-VIVENDI-LAD     06-20 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSAL-VIVENDI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA GIANT TO SHED ASSETS FOR EUROPEAN-STYLE SYNERGY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The new Vivendi Universal will quickly morph into
a global media company with a decidedly European accent, but don't
expect American theme park and studio operations to be bit players.
</P>
<P>
   The $34 billion buyout by Vivendi, the world's largest water
treatment company, of Seagram Co. Ltd., one of the world's biggest
spirits purveyors, will necessitate some asset shedding, the new
conglomerate's top two executives, Jean-Marie Messier and Edgar
Bronfman Jr., said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Look for Southern California-based studio and theme park
operations to be spared pain, at least in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theme parks will remain with the group. They are not going
to be (sold) off as a noncore asset,'' Bronfman, Seagram's
president and chief executive officer, said during a conference
call.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's key media and entertainment executives have
long-term contracts, so layoffs at this level are not likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be remaining in place, not because they have
long-term contracts but simply because they are good at what they
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other parts of the Seagram empire are not so secure. Seagram's
beverage business and such noble brands as Chivas Regal, Absolut
Vodka and Crown Royal will be divested as will Vivendi's
environmental enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   But both Messier, Vivendi's chairman and head of the new
company, and his second-in-command Bronfman stressed that Universal
Studios Inc., which includes the theme parks, will be critical to
the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Lescure, chief executive officer of Paris-based
entertainment company Canal Plus, in which Vivendi is half-owner,
will be responsible for all filmed entertainment assets, including
Universal Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Messier said he considers the parks and studio to be core
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi Universal will be able to offer consumers movies,
television programming, sports, music, games, and educational and
professional information via digital and analog formats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first company to combine premier global and local
content with next-generation digital distribution,'' Messier said.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi Universal will be the world's second-largest music
company after the Warner Music/EMI combination; have big studio
operations in the U.S. and Europe; control the second-largest film
library; and be an international leader in PC-based software game
publishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business and geographic mix of the two companies' media
properties is highly complementary,'' said Bank of America
securities analyst Stewart A. Halpern. ``The addition of Seagram's
content will create a compelling consumer proposition by offering a
comprehensive suite of service with seamless integration across all
distribution platforms, including the Internet, wireless and ...
television.''
</P>
<P>
   However, both executives, who jetted between news conferences in
Paris and New York on the supersonic Concorde, focused more on what
the combination means in Europe than the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   That's because there's where the synergies of the deal first
come into play.
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman, Vivendi Universal vice chairman, will be responsible
for Universal Music and all Internet activities. The music
operations were especially attractive to Vivendi, which has a new
50 percent stake in Internet portal Vizzavi.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the default portal for 80 million mobile and
interactive TV subscribers in Europe and a valuable new
distribution outlet for Universal's music content.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet Age is no longer a PC environment. It's
all-device, all the time, in all the places,'' Bronfman said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a cell phone user in Europe could be sent phone
mail message announcing the release date of a favorite artist's new
album, along with a sample cut.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers could also be alerted to concert dates, then order and
pay for tickets via the cell connection.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans may be familiar with this concept, but it is still
foreign to many in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to educate everyone on the power of the
distribution platform in Europe,'' Bronfman said. ``Clearly, we
have a lot on our plate. We don't have as powerful a footprint in
the U.S. as we do in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the one puzzling aspect to some analysts. At present,
the deal is more geared more toward the European market than the
U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a head scratcher. I think the synergies here in North
America are quite a bit lacking. I would have to think that there
are further shoes to drop,'' said Newcrest Capital Inc. analyst
Glynn Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this deal is an interim step. This is not the end
game.''
</P>
<P>
   One player that could emerge is Rupert Murdoch's News Corp.,
which also owns the Los Angeles Dodgers. Messier on Tuesday said he
would like to discuss the Seagram deal with Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch's office declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
