<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSAL-REAX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF MERGER CAUSES RIPPLE AT THEME PARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. _ &UR;  &LR; The music still blared, the fountains
still splashed and the crowds still came.
</P>
<P>
   It was business as usual Tuesday at the recently renovated
Universal CityWalk following the announcement of parent company
Seagram's merger with French communications giant Vivendi.
</P>
<P>
   Several groups of tourists visiting the Southern California
studio/theme park/shopping destination said they had no knowledge
of the merger, but the workers who spend each day in the shadow of
Universal Studios knew.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, an undercurrent of worry could be found. Some
employees said they were unsure about the future of their jobs, a
natural concern when one's employer is the subject of a merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there will be any impact in the short run,''
said Universal employee Bud Wisinski, who conducts tours of the
studios. ``But in the long term, who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi said it plans to shed noncore businesses in its effort
to build a corporate giant controlling the creation and
distribution of entertainment content. Seagram's liquor business
appears a likely spin-off target, but Wisinski wonders whether the
studios' tourism aspect might be another.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees on the fringes of Universal's empire were
completely unaware of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know about it until now,'' said Isabel Hernandez, a
sales clerk at The Prop Cart, a gift kiosk at the entry to
Universal Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Managers did not explain the implications of the sale to the
employees, Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Decatur, a limousine driver, said the merger is not likely
to have a significant effect on his business. Tourists will
continue to come to Universal Studios, one of Los Angeles' primary
tourism destinations, he said as he waited outside the studio for
his clients, who are visiting from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't even know it has happened,'' Decatur
said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the merger probably won't have an effect on the
souvenir businesses located at the CityWalk, said Alex Alcala, a
sales associate at the Hollywood T-shirt kiosk.
</P>
<P>
   But Alcala said he worries for some of his friends, who work in
the studio's food service and are union members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might affect them more than it will affect us,'' he said.
``I don't know if this company is pro-union or what.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9946 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SEAGRAM-VIVENDI-NYT &LR;      06-20 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAGRAM-VIVENDI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELDING CULTURES THE NEXT STEP IN SEAGRAM-VIVENDI DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (With SEAGRAM-VIVENDI-INTERNET) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Sitting on a stool next to Jean-Marie Messier, the
chairman of the newly minted Vivendi Universal, Edgar Bronfman Jr.
looked a little uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   But it soon become clear that Bronfman was not anxious because
he announced the sale of Seagram Co., his family's business, for
about $34 billion in stock to Vivendi SA, the French water utility
turned telecommunications and entertainment conglomerate. It was a
much more practical problem: He could not understand his new boss'
presentation, because, as one journalist whispered quite loudly,
``He doesn't speak French.''
</P>
<P>
   The moment offered a glimpse into the enormous challenge facing
the new company as both sides try to merge their vastly different
businesses and cultures _ and, of course, languages _ into a global
force that combines European business sensibility with American
popular culture. Vivendi Universal to become the second largest
media company after Time Warner-America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Investors worried Tuesday about the two companies' ability to
create a seamless worldwide telecommunications and entertainment
giant managed by a French company, pummeling Vivendi's shares down
8.35 euros, or 8.7 percent, to 88.10 euros, or $84.55. Shares of
Seagram fell about 9 percent _ $5.6875, to $58.625.
</P>
<P>
   Messier blamed the market's reaction to ``classical arbitrage''
and said it was a great time to buy Vivendi's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Vivendi will issue stock valued at
$77.35 for each share of Seagram. Seagram shareholders will get 0.8
shares of Vivendi stock if Vivendi's share price is less than
$96.69. If Vivendi's stock rises to more than $124.30 a share, the
ratio is fixed at 0.622 shares. With about 440 million shares
outstanding, that brings the value of the acquisition to about $34
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi also plans to buy the 51 percent of Canal Plus, the pay
television group, that it does not already own for about $10.6
billion. Canal Plus shareholders will receive 2 Vivendi shares for
each Canal Plus share. Shares of Canal Plus fell 12 percent
Tuesday, to 178.6 euros.
</P>
<P>
   However one trader said he doubted the decline was entirely
because of due to arbitrage. He speculated that there may be some
concern among Vivendi shareholders about the strategic value of the
deal, but said it was still likely to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi has agreed to pay Seagram $800 million as a break-up
fee, if the deal falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   Though Salomon Smith Barney analyst Jill Krutick described the
deal as a ``home run'' Tuesday, she nevertheless downgraded her
recommendation on Seagram from buy to neutral, contending that
trading in the stock reflected a frenzy, but not the fundamentals.
First Union's Scott Davis also came out with a neutral
recommendation after having been bullish.
</P>
<P>
   The union of Vivendi and Seagram puts Universal Studios and
Polygram records under the same roof as Canal Plus, as well as
Vizzavi, an Internet portal that will allow access across Europe
through wireless devices and personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are hoping to leverage Seagram's stable of
entertainment content over Vivendi's many distribution channels,
especially in the potential market for downloading digital media
over the Internet and wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   Messier said he was also enthusiastic about his new relationship
with USA Networks, of which Seagram owns 42 percent, with the right
to increase its investment. However, he acknowledged that he had
not yet met with the USA chairman, Barry Diller, though he had
spoken to him by phone and planned a meeting in the next several
days in New York.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether Diller would have one of the five seats that
Seagram will control on the 18-member board, Bronfman said that had
yet to be decided. Three of the seats go to Bronfman Jr., his
father, Edgar, and his uncle Charles.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bronfman said Tuesday that his family was completely
behind the deal, he added that they do have the right to sell their
stock 90 days after the deal's completion, which is expected to
happen next January or February, Vivendi officials said.
</P>
<P>
   If Bronfman was unhappy about giving up control of the company
his family had run for decades, he handled it smoothly Tuesday,
saying that if his mission had been to keep control, he would not
have sold. But he said, his goal had been to enhance shareholder
value.
</P>
<P>
   The combined companies will have revenue of $65 billion, of
which $28 billion will represent entertainment and media
operations. There will be roughly 1.2 billion shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The French press had tempered praise for the deal Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be applauded, but with some reserve,'' said an
editorial in the Le Monde, the French daily newspaper. ``This bet
is founded on a certain number of risks.''
</P>
<P>
   The editorial went on to warn: ```All foreign companies burned
their wings in Hollywood,''` referring to Japan's Matsushita
Electric Industrial Co.'s troubled ownership of MCA before it was
sold to Seagram, and Sony's somewhat difficult ownership of
Columbia Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Vivendi will be putting a Frenchman, Pierre Lescure,
Canal Plus' chairman, in charge of the combined company's film
operations, including Universal Studios. Lescure will manage the
unit from here rather than from Hollywood. Messier went to great
pains to explain that the U.S. film business would still be managed
on a day-to-day basis by Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The cultural differences between Messier and Bronfman were also
made apparent Tuesday, despite both executives' efforts to point
out their similarities. Telling the audience about his first
meeting with Bronfman at his house on Oct. 12, Messier ribbed him
for showing up ``without a tie and in short sleeves.'' (Bronfman
was on vacation.)
</P>
<P>
   For Messier, a former investment banker, the meeting was an
opportunity to discuss his vision to create what is now called
Vizzavi and was then code-named MAP, for a multi-access Internet
portal, prior to its development by Vivendi and Vodafone AirTouch,
the wireless telephone company. Both executives believed in the
idea of delivering content over the Internet and believed that was
the key to striking a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, said executives close to the talks, Bronfman
continued to shop the company around, particularly to Sony and the
News Corp. While both companies expressed initial interest, talks
with neither company went anywhere. Over the next eight months,
Bronfman met with Messier nine more times before reaching a deal
about 10 days ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
