<HEADER>
A9947 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-20 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SADLY, A BURNING MEMORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ You want to remember Monday night for the right
reasons. But it won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime after midnight, our stories on the Lakers' title-
clinching victory finished and filed, a Daily News colleague and I
walked up Staples Center's 11th Street driveway ramp, out of an
arena scented with celebration and into darkness tinged with
combustion.
</P>
<P>
   I had parked in a lot across the street. He had parked blocks
away in a lot at the corner of 9th and Figueroa. We had been
watching the rioting on television in the press room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, can you drive me to my car?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh . . . sure,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers and straggling fans milled about. The worst of
the vandalism immediately outside Staples Center was over. These
things always look wider-spread on TV. We had to wait, though, for
a fire truck to pass before we could walk across 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Sportswriters might be coldhearted cynics, but we get excited
about an historic moment and share in the hometown pride about Los
Angeles' first professional championship since 1988. I asked, as we
turned out of the parking lot onto Georgia Street, ``Where will
this rank among your sports memories?'' He answered, ``This was one
of the better ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Then we came to Olympic Boulevard and were stopped by a police
officer on foot. Squad cars were parked in the crosswalks. We
wanted to turn right and head east but were told we'd have to drive
straight ahead. I eased off the brake _ and immediately stomped on
it again.
</P>
<P>
   From our right, a black-and-white, lights flashing and siren
blaring, made a hard left in front of us. Then here came another
police car, and another and another. A dozen or more police cars in
single file, racing south.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly will remember !ital!this,'' my colleague said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the shame of what happened after the Lakers finished off
the Indiana Pacers Monday night in the sixth game of the NBA
Finals. At least for now, what we'll remember most vividly about
the feats of the extraordinary young men in purple and gold is the
lunacy of the idiots in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The TV news shows recycled scenes of burning automobiles when
they could have been replaying Shaquille O'Neal hugging his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ABC Radio news made the Lakers championship its lead story at 1
a.m. _ for half a sentence, before diving into a from-the-scene
report on the violence.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the nation saw and heard Los Angeles at what should
have been one of our finest hours.
</P>
<P>
   Don't call them fans. Don't call it celebration. Fans don't
celebrate their team's accomplishments by burning its posters and
T-shirts, by looting its city.
</P>
<P>
   Call them criminals, a mob looking for an excuse to misbehave.
</P>
<P>
   I'll leave the whys to others.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know whether Lakers and Staples Center officials are to
blame for drawing a crowd of thousands to the streets outside the
arena by showing the game on a huge television screen.
</P>
<P>
   (Although inviting have-nots to press their noses against the
window as ticket-holders party inside the building would seem to
encourage the us-against-the-establishment passion that would lead
to the burning of police cars and TV news vans and the smashing of
store windows.)
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if the police are to blame for responding slowly
and weakly.
</P>
<P>
   (Although they should have remembered what has happened
following championships in other cities and seen it coming _ when
that throbbing outdoor crowd was shown on the video screen inside
Staples Center following Rick Fox's 3-pointer with 8:21 left in the
game, I turned to the writers next to me and said, ``We'll be in
here for a long time if the Lakers win.'')
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what makes people do these things.
</P>
<P>
   I do know a relative few were involved in the rioting, and that
they weren't as bad as the soccer hooligans who bust heads, not
headlights.
</P>
<P>
   I do know that Monday night's hooligans are no more
representative of the citizens of Los Angeles than Shaq is. We are
not a city of mental midgets any more than we're a city of giants.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope the rest of the world realizes that, too.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, I'm not sure what I'll remember best, the
victory parade on Figueroa this morning or the police-car parade on
Olympic Monday night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
