<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORACLE SAYS EARNINGS UP, DRIVEN BY SALES OF INTERNET SOFTWARE
APPLICATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Propelled by strong sales of software
applications for doing business over the Internet, Oracle Corp. on
Tuesday reported fourth-quarter earnings well in excess of
analysts' estimates. But sales of Oracle's core database product
slightly trailed estimates, and Oracle shares dropped in
after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding investment gains, Oracle reported earnings of $926
million, or 31 cents a diluted share, up 76 percent from similarly
adjusted earnings of $527 million, or 18 cents a share, in the
period a year earlier. Revenue rose 17 percent, to $3.37 billion
from $2.94 billion, in the fourth quarter of fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Oracle to earn 26 cents in the quarter,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Total earnings for the quarter ended May 31 were $4.91 billion,
or $1.63 a diluted share. Total earnings included a $6.5 billion
one-time gain from the sale of shares of 12 percent of Oracle's
holdings in Oracle Japan; Oracle now owns 74 percent of the
operation. This equity reduction was necessary for Oracle Japan to
comply with the listing requirements of the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle shares closed Tuesday at $86.04, up 0.04 cents, in Nasdaq
trading, but dropped by $5 in after hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had one chink in their armor, which is that database
growth wasn't as strong as it should have been,'' said Robert
Austrian, an analyst with Banc of America Securities. ``But that's
balanced by the five gold stars they get in other areas. Their
e-business applications really are taking off and that of course is
the future of the new economy. Operating margins are on fire, and
it's really a case of leading by example.''
</P>
<P>
   Oracle said a year ago that it would cut $1 billion from
expenses, and company executives say that goal has been
accomplished by using their own Internet-based applications for
processes like sales force management and human resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now shooting for $2 billion,'' Geoff Henley, Oracle's
chief financial officer, said in a telephone interview. ``Of course
the second billion will be harder. It will have to come from higher
revenue growth, but we're confident we can do that,'' he said. ``A
billion dollars in annual savings translates to a 10-point
improvement in our margins. In Q4, our operating margin improved
13.7 points from 27.4 percent to 41.1 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley said the greatest contributor to the quarter's sales was
the strong growth in applications, and he added that he sees this
performance continuing in the first quarter. Oracle said
applications software sales increased 61 percent to $447 million in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty-one percent growth is just a stunning number, and the
pipeline is absolutely awesome. I would expect to see higher
license growth in Q1 than in Q4,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent slowdown in database license growth reflects a
shift in Oracle's sales model, not a longterm demand trend, Henley
said. ``It is strictly a comparison issue,'' he said. ``We had a
few really big deals close in Q4 1999, and we didn't do that this
year, by choice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in applications was led by customer relationship
management, or CRM, programs, sales of which grew at a 161 percent
rate. Companies use CRM programs to manage sales and service
operations. Database software sales increased 12 percent to $1.2
billion. Consulting, education and support revenues increased 7
percent to $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Ellison, Oracle's chairman and chief executive, said that
during the last quarter Oracle sold more application software than
SAP, the large European software company, ``$447 million vs. $352
million.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our applications business has been accelerating while there
has been flat. We think we have a chance of rolling up the
enterprise applications space,'' he said in a conference call with
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, adjusted net income increased 61 percent to $2.1
billion, or 69 cents a diluted share, compared with $1.3 billion,
or 43 cents a share, in fiscal 1999. Revenue grew 15 percent to
$10.13 billion from $8.83 billion in the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
