<SLUG> BC-ALLIANCE-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: ALLIANCE CAPITAL TO ACQUIRE SANFORD C. BERNSTEIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alliance Capital Management, the giant New York money
management firm, has agreed to acquire the privately held money
management and research firm Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co. for $3.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which was announced after trading closed Tuesday,
would create a company with $475 billion in assets under
management, 4,000 employees and 5.8 million mutual fund
shareholders. In trading after hours, Alliance, which is controlled
by the French financial services holding company AXA Group, fell
2.9 percent, to $48.50.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance is publicly traded, but structured as a limited
partnership. The deal consists of about $1.5 billion in cash and
40.8 million newly issued limited partnership shares of Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   After the death last year of Zalman C. Bernstein, the founder of
Sanford C. Bernstein who changed his name after converting to
Orthodox Judaism, executives have considered selling the company,
including a public offering. After the stock offering in Goldman
Sachs last year, Bernstein was left as one of the last prominent
privately held securities firms in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The combination is another in a string of recent mergers and
acquisitions among money management firms. Last week, the
Boston-based money manager Nvest agreed to be acquired by the
French money manager CDC Asset Management, in a deal valued at $700
million. On Monday, Old Mutual, a South African money manager,
agreed to buy United Asset Management Corp. for $1.46 billion. And
last month, UniCredito Italiano Group agreed to acquire the Boston
mutual fund company Pioneer Group for $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is becoming very commoditized, and it's become
very hard to differentiate yourself,'' said Christopher J. Brown,
an analyst with Financial Research, a mutual fund industry
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of Alliance and Bernstein, however, is larger
than the three previous deals combined, and the new company will
manage billions of dollars in retail and institutional accounts,
including equities and fixed-income investments. It also brings
together two firms known for different styles of investing.
According to Alliance executives, the potential for more
diversified offerings is part of the deal's attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alliance Capital is a recognized leader in the growth style of
investing; Bernstein in the value style,'' said Bruce W. Calvert,
chief executive of Alliance. Bernstein is also one of the largest
managers of private portfolios for wealthy clients, a coveted field
in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be able to compete effectively for institutional
investment management assignments in any of the world's major
markets,'' Calvert said.
</P>
<P>
   The divergent investment styles have led to divergent fortunes
of late for the firms. Investors, who have been impatient with
value-oriented investing during the technology-fueled bull market,
have withdrawn $1.6 billion from Bernstein mutual funds this year,
through April, making the firm's mutual fund division the
industry's third-worst seller, according to Financial Research.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance funds, meanwhile, have had $3.5 billion in inflows over
the corresponding period.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bernstein's struggles, the addition of a value-oriented
firm is considered critical to AXA's plans to broaden Alliance's
investment offerings and be ``sort of an international Citigroup,''
according to Clare Nickson, an analyst at UBS Warburg.
</P>
<P>
   In North America, AXA also controls Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
and AXA Financial, formerly the Equitable Companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-TYSON-NYT &LR;      06-20 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH OF A FRIEND PUTS TYSON IN A SOMBER MOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Being Mike Tyson means never having to say anything.
But his very presence induces an inimitable maelstrom of tumult and
disorder, even in London _ the home, incidentally, of the reigning
heavyweight champion, Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The play of England's national soccer team in the 2000 European
championships may be the top sports story here this week, but Tyson
has managed to find his niche in the sports soap opera category.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, he made news by canceling the only London news
conference he had scheduled for Saturday's fight in a Scottish
soccer stadium against Lou Saverese.
</P>
<P>
   Refusing to meet with reporters is not significant for Tyson,
but since he has already postponed the Saverese fight twice _ and
delayed his trip to London by four days because of the death of a
friend _ it fueled new suspicions that he may still pull out of
this fight.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Tommy Brooks, Tyson's co-trainer, who said of his
fighter, ``He's mentally distressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks acknowledged that Tyson was disturbed enough by the June
9 murder of a longtime friend, Darryl Baum, that he considered
postponing the fight last week. But then, there was the matter of
his contract with Showtime. Brooks said of Tyson, ``He's trying to
honor the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson did take a walk along Park Lane, across from Hyde Park,
followed by a huge contingent of reporters and photographers.
Wearing a soccer jersey and matching shorts, he stopped to pose for
a few photos and shook hands with some well-wishers.
</P>
<P>
   He has become a familiar public figure here. He took to the
streets of London on Sunday as well, visiting a tailor on Bond
Street by day and two wine bars in the Brixton neighborhood by
night. English newspapers ran accounts of Tyson being mobbed at the
wine bars. They quoted a female photographer who said she was
rescued by Tyson when the crush of people rushing at the boxer
knocked her over and pinned her against a railing. The photographer
said Tyson interceded and saved her from injury.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, British television crews were camped outside
Tyson's hotel astride Hyde Park hoping to catch his next absorbing
foray.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more Tyson does, whether it's good or bad, the more they
want to see him,'' Saverese said Tuesday, a wily smile beneath a
boxer's askew nose. It's like going to a car race to see a wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Tyson does not appear to be is woefully out of shape.
It had been rumored that his weight had ballooned to 270 pounds,
but walking past reporters on his way to a brief workout, he looked
trim. And calm.
</P>
<P>
   He also responded quietly to a question or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to fight,'' said Tyson, whose appearance in London
has also been opposed by leaders of women's groups, who did not
want him, as a convicted rapist, granted entry to England. ``That's
what I do. I'm a professional fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   This being the stealthy, shady world of boxing, where the
referee's last command is always ``protect yourself at all times,''
there are some who believe Tyson did not meet with reporters or
open his workout as planned because he is hiding something from
Saverese.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to play along, Brooks said: ``We have a nice little
surprise set up for Saverese. We've been working on some things.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson had been expected to arrive in London last Wednesday, but
instead he flew from Phoenix, where he had been training, to New
York to attend Baum's funeral on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's handlers said Baum and Tyson had been friends since
grade school. Brooks said Baum was like a brother to Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They treated each other like family,'' the trainer said.
</P>
<P>
   Baum had been with Tyson in Phoenix until June 8. Because he was
not part of the group coming to England for the fight, Baum flew
home to New York. He was shot on a street corner the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Mike's hurting,'' Jay Bright, Tyson's other trainer,
said. ``But he's very focused about these things. I never heard
anything about the fight being postponed.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but when Tyson flew to London on Sunday, Saverese _
already training in Glasgow _ made sure he got the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard he had landed over here,'' said Saverese, who
flew to London Tuesday to conduct his scheduled news conference,
``I was doing back flips in Glasgow.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Tyson plans a last London workout. He may even
entertain questions from reporters. Or he may not.
</P>
<P>
   Later that evening, Tyson is set to fly to Scotland. He is
expected to be met at the airport by protesters opposed to his
presence. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
