<SLUG> BC-CAFE-NICHOLSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICHOLSON GETS CURIOUSER AND CURIOUSER 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With all its quirks and aberrations, Manhattan is
often thought of as America's Oz. But there lurks, right in the
heart of the city, a smaller, even weirder Oz _ a Mini-Me of
strangeness. It is Nicholson, and nearly everything about it seems
designed to neutralize all known standards of restaurant criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The place has a history. For nearly half a century, it was Cafe
Nicholson, named after its creator, Johnny Nicholson, a window
dresser, antiques dealer and bohemian with a taste for high
society. In 1949, almost on a whim, he decided to open a cafe,
enlisting Edna Lewis as his chef. Within a couple of years, the
restaurant moved into its present location, a former artist's
studio, and a legend was born. Cafe Nicholson became the haunt of
society folk, writers, artists, actors and theater people. In a New
York restaurant scene defined by cozy neighborhood joints and
imposing temples of haute cuisine, Cafe Nicholson stood alone and
apart, a theme restaurant whose only theme was its owner's
idiosyncratic style.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson sold the restaurant last year, and it would have
seemed a safe bet that, with his disappearance from the scene, the
air would rush out of the souffle. Not so. A meal at Nicholson (the
restaurant has dropped ``Cafe'' from its name) may still be the
oddest legal experience available in New York.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, Nicholson occupies a peculiar spot, perched at
the edge of the entrance to the upper roadway of the Queensboro
Bridge. It looks like a guardhouse, and it's not much larger. You
enter through a narrow, open-air passageway, walk down five steps,
and enter what feels like a private home. Past a tiny bar and a
lounge, the dining room awaits.
</P>
<P>
   It is a very distinctive room. Nicholson's decor was once
described as Spanish-Portuguese belle epoque, and under the new
owner and chef, Patrick Woodside, working with the architect
Alexander Gorlin, things have become only more complex. The
cane-work settees with their silk throw pillows remain. So do the
brightly colored Spanish wall tiles with a satyr motif, the pastel
panels filled with cupids, and the stenciled ceiling border
depicting lily pads and lizards. The skylight, however, has been
replaced with a recessed panel covered in gold leaf, and the room
is now dominated by a large central table supporting multiple
exotic floral arrangements. Up front, the intimate lounge with a
small bar is also new.
</P>
<P>
   An erratic Modernist streak now runs through the design. Plates
look like heavyweight 1950s ashtrays. Water is poured from a white
ceramic cone, and bread is served in a cylindrical stone container
carved to resemble a curled strip of birch bark. Diners who reach
for the bread must then place it on a bread plate that looks like a
surfboard designed by Russel Wright. The sugar container is a Pyrex
custard cup.
</P>
<P>
   The streamlined dishes seem like antonyms, given the florid,
flamboyant style of cooking at Nicholson, which finds its natural
reflection in the dining room's Versailles-style gilt mirrors. One
evening, I ordered one of the house drinks, a Champagne cocktail
flavored with Cointreau, Chambord, gin, orange muscat and lavender.
It arrived in a shallow coupe, wide enough for a mouse to swim laps
in. A plump strawberry sat precariously on the rim. As a prelude to
the meal, the drink was the perfect symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Woodside, who also owns CamaJeBistro and Lounge in Greenwich
Village, has an opulent sensibility and a jeweler's sense of
design. Diners who might quail at the longer fixed-price menus need
have no fear. The leisurely pace of the service, and the
appetizer-size portions, make even the eight-course extravaganza an
ultra-fancy snack.
</P>
<P>
   Like the decor, the food at Nicholson swings wildly between
extremes. It can be romantic and elegant, or almost insanely
misjudged. The eight-course tasting menu, on one visit, began with
a wonderful amuse-bouche, a lump of sweetbread arranged in a
mille-feuille with cream and truffle essence.
</P>
<P>
   The road ahead was bumpy. A miniature assemblage of seared
scallops in a syrupy balsamic reduction was straightforward enough,
but the scallops lacked flavor. Three grape tomatoes, huddled
together in the center of a discus-size plate, made a bright second
act, tartly sweet in a vibrant basil vinaigrette. Lamb carpaccio,
glazed with mint and basil, had just enough thickness to support a
well-judged spicing of cumin and chili. It is hard to find a New
York menu without carpaccio. It has become a cliche. But
Nicholson's ranks among the best that I've come across.
</P>
<P>
   Truffle cream, truffles, caviar and mushrooms loom large in
Woodside's cooking vocabulary. They are the fins on his 1958
Cadillac. One evening, some combination of the four showed up on
every dish except the chocolate souffle. So it was no surprise, in
my eight-course excursion, to see truffle cream surrounding my
croustillant of shrimp and langoustine. What was surprising was the
espresso-chicory sabayon, looking unfortunately like beach foam,
that came with a lovely shell-pink pave of salmon. If the
combination sounds strange, I can testify that it tastes even
stranger.
</P>
<P>
   Woodside regained firmer ground with a pan-roasted pork
tenderloin in a red-wine reduction flavored with oxtail. It was one
of two entree choices. The alternative was a lobster treated
Souvaroff-style, a 19th-century overload preparation here involving
morels, chanterelles, spring onions and, surprise! _ truffle cream.
</P>
<P>
   After the grand tour, it's a short, sweet trip at dessert time.
Nicholson limits itself to a few classic souffles, led by a superb
but breathtakingly alcoholic apple-Calvados souffle, and
old-fashioned pleasers like a poached peach with Champagne sabayon.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere at Nicholson is almost indescribable. Stillness
reigns, interrupted only by the gentle creak of the parquet floor,
signaling the approach of a waiter, who, in truth, seems less like
an employee than a faithful family retainer, just as the restaurant
feels a bit like a room in the far west wing of Crotchet Castle.
The clientele seems to break down into two groups: neighborhood
residents of advanced years (it's been a long time since I've heard
an animated conversation about Perle Mesta) and young couples
seemingly on their way to a cotillion, if such things exist
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   I have to say, I left Nicholson on each visit with a look of
stupefied wonder on my face, and a feeling of regret. It is the one
restaurant guaranteed to make the world outside its doors, the mad,
mad circus of Manhattan, seem like an absolute bore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
