<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9983 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-GILBERTO-LATIN-MUSIC-     06-20 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILBERTO-LATIN-MUSIC-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMPLICITY VIA UNHEARD COMPLICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 25)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of a music so sure of its power that it need not raise its
voice above mezzo piano. Think of graceful arcs of phrase
reminiscent of Bellini. The harmonic and rhythmic language is
received, not invented, yet its predictabilities are paradoxically
filled with surprise. Wonder as well at how such extremes of
civility emanate from a region seemingly condemned to political
turmoil and chronic violence. What Latin America struggles to
achieve in its civic life it produces effortlessly in its musical
art.
</P>
<P>
   That art is carried to its delicate conclusion in the music of
Joao Gilberto, the Brazilian composer, singer and guitarist, who
offered an uninterrupted hour and a half of songs and instrumentals
recently at Carnegie Hall. Facing a JVC Jazz Festival audience left
restless and unnerved by an hour's delay, Gilberto (whose hotel, by
the way, was only a few doors down 57th Street) finally arrived,
excused himself lamely and tamed his listeners in five minutes. The
precision of the music evidently does not extend to private life.
</P>
<P>
   Avuncular and almost frail in his late 60s, though with
astonishing mastery of complex guitar patterns, Gilberto croaked
tonelessly in his bottom notes and barely whispered in his middle
range but sent out little ribbons of treble notes so pure and so
loaded with emotion as to set the nerve ends to tingling. We know
the stepwise chord patterns from years of listening to them yet
await them eagerly. Gilberto toys with expectations by revoicing
his chords, the highest notes suddenly made prominent in parallel
harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpected, too, are the disparities between sung text and
musical line, where the words of phrases often speed to an end
before the music beneath them has run its course. The compression
extends to meter, Gilberto omitting beats at the end of an orderly
pattern and throwing completed phrases in our laps before the ear
is ready to receive them.
</P>
<P>
   Given the frequent crowding of words into single lines, the
equilibrium is extraordinary. Describe it as utter simplicity
achieved by means of unnoticed complication. One admires these
feats of music with a joy and serenity that the vast majority of
new music coming out of the concert hall and the opera stage is at
a loss to replicate.
</P>
<P>
   More forward and perhaps rougher at the edges are other Latin
American musical cultures. There is the Argentine tango, in the
hands of performers like Astor Piazzolla. Here, too, the patterns
of harmony and movement are predictable, but we never tire of them.
Cuban music has been much in the news with the film and recordings
of the Buena Vista Social Club. Again, straightforward messages
arrive by way of thoughtfully layered rhythmic elements. They keep
the ear busy and the heart full.
</P>
<P>
   Even at their loudest and most agitated, and even with the
ornately lugubrious poetry that often surrounds them, the tango and
the Cuban love song are unfettered efforts to communicate. The
message, whether pleasant or not, is offered in welcoming terms.
The music works to be understood.
</P>
<P>
   This is how Mozart composed, even though so much 20th-century
classical music of the highest quality evidently felt otherwise.
The horrors of the times needed accurate reportage, so music had no
responsibility to be beautiful. I sense a real public stirring for
the music of Messiaen. The average listener doesn't take the
theoretical bases seriously and is only mildly amused by the
attempts to replicate birdcalls. The ``Turangalila Symphony'' and
the ``Quartet for the End of Time'' radiate a communicable spirit
that new-music audiences have rarely found anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The songs of Gilberto and his compatriots Caetano Veloso and
Antonio Carlos Jobim represent the art of Bellini outfitted with
microphone and loudspeaker. Arias like ``Casta diva'' declaim
because they happen inside a theater and must reach back to its
farthest rows. At Carnegie Hall, Gilberto's intimate musical
conversations maintained the illusion of a small room even as they
were being projected to 2,800 people. I confess to little interest
in sound technology, but the admirable electronic devices at work
here managed to shrink the hall rather than inflate the music.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, one finds echoes of a trend familiar to Europe: the
tendency of cultures with negligible folk and popular music to
produce great classical composers. Germany (the village brass band
versus Beethoven) and Austria (Schubert versus Schrammelmusik) are
examples. Mexico has given us Revueltas, Chavez and some very
interesting formal composers. It has also given us the mariachi
band, whose charm quotient _ for me, at least _ runs to about four
minutes. (I have always suspected the existence of courses at
Mexican conservatories devoted to training mariachi trumpeters how
to play out of tune.)
</P>
<P>
   So many Eastern European cultures have made their folk music a
rallying point for political identity. Breaking free of such
loyalties is not easy. Russian and Italian composers have done
better jobs of assimilation, yet Spain's classical music, which I
adore, still seems in thrall to its flamenco and folk-music roots.
</P>
<P>
   When postwar jazz reached into free form and extended-chord
harmonies, it seemed to arrive at a limit and snap. In an instant,
there were Elvis Presley and his four-chord accompaniments. The art
of Gilberto is simple only in its effect, but a classical music
that finds itself at the outer boundaries of esoterica may find a
similar rescue somewhat to the south.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
