<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9993 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-SYRIA-POWER-STRUGGLE-     06-20 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-POWER-STRUGGLE-INDEPENDENT-FISK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFIGHTING RAGES AS SYRIA'S BAATH PARTY CONFIRMS BASHAR  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This pithy 850-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   DAMASCUS _ He sat mute before the cameras, long legs and tall
body, black-tied, head erect, flashlights playing like lightning
over the narrow face and pale blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bashar Assad _ or Lieutenant General Dr. Bashar al-Assad as
we are now enjoined by the Damascus press to call the new
commander-in-chief of the Syrian army _ was on his way to becoming
President Lieutenant General Dr. Bashar al-Assad. Courtesy of the
Syrian Arab Socialist Baath party.
</P>
<P>
   The 950 delegates, silent as sheep in the massive auditorium of
the Ebla Sham Hotel _ an institution that comes complete with grey
marble halls and spurting fountains _ could all see the back of Dr.
Bashar's head at the front of the hall as he watched the 11 members
of the Progressive Front (only one of them from Bashar's own
Alawite community) take turns to praise his father's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``A genius on all fronts...an architect...unique in the
world...a man of destiny...Our former secretary general is absent
today, but he is present in his values.'' And that was just the
contribution of Abdullah Ahmar, assistant secretary general of the
Baath.
</P>
<P>
   The new secretary general, of course, is going to be Lieutenant
General Dr. Bashar.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the identity of the new party leader that's
important _ it goes without saying that Hafez Assad has handed on
his rule, caliph-like, to his son _ but the party's new ``regional
command'' of 21 members who will decide the nature of the new
regime, its ruthlessness and its loyalty to Bashar.
</P>
<P>
   There were eight vacancies to fill. One was that of the late
President Assad. Another that of his disgraced brother Rifaat,
still shrieking from his Spanish villa that Bashar's succession is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the seat left by an ex-prime minister, Mahoud
Zoghbi, who shot himself while awaiting a corruption trial. And yet
another vacancy caused by the hurried exile abroad of General
Hikmat Shehabi, the Syrian army chief-of-staff from 1974 to 1998
who fled yet more corruption charges and now resides _ wait for it
_ with his son in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   And Monday, Bashar's supporters and friends filled the eight
seats. Joining the regional command was Manaf Tlass _ son of
Assad's avuncular and poetic defense minister Mustafa (himself a
personal friend of Bashar), prime minister Mustafa Mero, foreign
minister Farouk el-Sharaa, minister of higher education Dr. Zuheir
Richa (a Christian from the largely Alawi city of Lattakia), Naji
Atari, the vice president for the economy, Adnan Omran, the former
ambassador to London and now information minister. And, of course,
Bashar himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strong team to take into a party leadership which _ in
theory _ governs Syria. There are other friends around Bashar, of
course. Take Assif Chawkat, his own brother-in-law who has assumed
Shehabi's importance as head of security. And even Taher Mikati,
the Lebanese brother of Lebanese minister Najib Mikati, a
techno-wizard who put Bashar online and just might _ we're talking
about Najib _ be Lebanon's next prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   But these are mere loyalists compared to the comrades of the
party.
</P>
<P>
   There's a little question, however, that needs answering, a
question that was raised rather pointedly by the Lebanese ``As
Safir'' newspaper last week when it said of the Baath that ``the
party is a corpse.''
</P>
<P>
   If the president takes all the decisions of state _ which he
does in Syria _ what is the Baath Party other than an obedient
acolyte, 950 attendant lords and ladies whose formal role is to
raise their hands, spontaneously and unanimously together, as they
did Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   There are those even in Syria who uncharitably suspect that the
Baath Party _ both in its original Michel Aflaq-inspired form and
in the version that Assad handed down _ is a form of theatre, that
it has been dead for a long time, only to be disinterred when a
future president must be given formal legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there at the coffee break on Saturday was former
minister of information Mohamed Salman, now on corruption charges _
``at the gate of the prison'' as they say in Syria _ receiving,
frozen-faced with anxiety, the careful greetings of old party
comrades who dared to be seen approaching him.
</P>
<P>
   No one should doubt the harshness of Syrian politics. After
reporters were politely asked to leave the congress on Saturday,
there were, perhaps, some more caustic remarks, some real debate.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Lebanese journalist Selim el-Lowzi reported
disputes within the party in the seventies, he was found dead near
Beirut airport, his right arm _ his writing arm _ burned down to
the bone with acid.
</P>
<P>
   And it was President Assad _ whose words were splashed across a
black banner in the auditorium _ who said that ``all party
congresses are important because they discuss the mistakes of the
past and work on avoiding them in the future...''
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure that Rifaat was a mistake. And Zohbi. And Shehabi. And
we'll hear of others. But most of all we'll hear of the wisdom of
electing Lieutenant General Dr. Bashar al-Assad to be secretary
general of the Syrian Arab Socialist Baath Party. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 850-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
