u f BC-SEAGRAM-VIVENDI-INTER     06-20 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAGRAM-VIVENDI-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: VIVENDI NOW MEDIA GIANT, BUT INTERNET CONTENT PLANS STILL
DISTANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related SEAGRAM-VIVENDI) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judging by the public pronouncements, one might think the
acquisition of Seagram by Vivendi will create a global
telecommunications powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``World's Largest Wireless Footprint,'' read one of the
bullet-points at the top of the news release announcing the
agreement. ``Vizzavi Will Be the Default Home Page for 80 million
Potential Mobile and Interactive TV Customers,'' read another,
referring to one of Vivendi's Internet initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some facts. The total of the telecommunications assets
to be owned by the new Vivendi Universal: 52 percent of Cegetel,
which is the No. 2 long-distance provider in France and also owns
80 percent of France's No. 2 cellular phone carrier. Vivendi
Universal would also own Canal Plus, a European pay television
company with 14 million subscribers, 25 percent of a British
satellite television operation, and 50 percent of the Vizzavi
European Internet portal, which began its first operation, in
France, Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Vizzavi took center stage Tuesday. At their Paris news
conference, Jean-Marie Messier, Vivendi's chairman, and Edgar
Bronfman Jr., Seagram's chief executive, repeatedly held out
Vizzavi as one of the cornerstones of their deal, as perhaps the
main engine for Vivendi Universal's growth. They heralded Vizzavi
as a tool for delivering music, and potentially video, to millions
of people using hand-held wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be able to get connected to your own personal music
library,'' Bronfman said at the news conference. ``I'm a great
believer in the future of wireless opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can supply Internet content way beyond Europe,'' Bronfman
added at the news conference. When someone suggested afterward that
it might take years for the technology to arrive to deliver mobile
wireless music, he said, ``Years? Months! We will be able to
distribute wireless music within months.'' Met with skepticism, he
said, ``I didn't say we'd be able to do it to 80 million people,
did I?''
</P>
<P>
   Vizzavi is meant to be an Internet portal with three legs:
wireless devices, personal computers and interactive televisions.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some more facts: Vizzavi hardly exists. Vivendi, not to
mention Seagram, has essentially zero business providing Internet
access to computers in any country. Even Vivendi does not expect to
be able to deliver Internet access to televisions in Europe until
next year at the earliest. It will, in fact, be a year or two until
any company, in Europe or the United States, is able to deliver
digital music to mobile wireless devices on any meaningful scale.
</P>
<P>
   It will take at least two years after that until anyone is able
to deliver decent-quality video on the same scale. Vivendi
Universal has no realistic chance of becoming a player in the U.S.
wireless Internet market any time soon. And the upshot is that is
it not at all clear just how acquiring Seagram helps Vivendi with
all of the hard work it faces in building Vizzavi on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't necessarily look at this deal as one where the whole
is worth more than the sum of its parts,'' said one media analyst
in the United States Tuesday, requesting his name not be used. ``I
happen to think the Bronfmans are cashing out.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, the general concept behind Vizzavi is clearly solid.
The buzz word that was electronic commerce two years ago and
business-to-business last year, is definitely mobile Internet
access this year. While many electronic commerce companies and
business-to-business electronic commerce companies have struggled
recently, no one can deny that they are serious industries. Mobile
Internet access will be serious as well, but Vivendi Universal does
not appear to be a company tailor-made to exploit it.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Vivendi Universal has to work through another
company to gain access to mobile wireless users outside France.
That company is Vodafone AirTouch PLC of Britain, the world's No. 1
wireless telephone provider. (That is how Vivendi and Seagram came
up with that first bullet point.)
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Vodafone and Vivendi agreed to create Vizzavi
as a 50-50 joint venture. Vodafone has 58 million wireless
subscribers in Europe, but has only minority investments in some of
the carriers that serve those customers. (The 80 million figure in
the second bullet point came from adding those 58 million users to
Vivendi's pay television roster and the total number of Cegetel
customers.) Vodafone wants Vizzavi to be the preferred Internet
portal for all of its European networks, but cannot necessarily
deliver all of them (though it will probably deliver most).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Vodafone is talking to other companies about their
wireless Internet portals. Though no deal appears imminent,
Vodafone has at least met with America Online Inc., for instance,
about carrying that service in Europe, according to people close to
those discussions.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the United States. Or, in reality, then there
is not the United States.
</P>
<P>
   There was some talk Tuesday about Vizzavi expanding to the
United States, but that is not going to happen in a meaningful way
soon. First of all, most of the big U.S.-based wireless providers
are building portals of their own, sometimes in partnership with
U.S.-based Internet companies like Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Vodafone is a partner in the new Verizon wireless
carrier, which also includes Bell Atlantic's wireless operation and
will soon include GTE's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an agreement with Vodafone, and as part of that we
have an agreement to be considered as a premier provider of content
in the U.S. as we have in Vizzavi,'' Philippe Germond, a senior
executive vice president of Vivendi, said in a telephone interview
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But it appears that that consideration is over, at least for
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Verizon will launch it's own wireless Internet portal in the
next couple of weeks,'' Jim Gerace, a Verizon spokesman, said in a
telephone interview Tuesday. ``It's separate and apart, though
compatible with what Vodafone is doing overseas. Our customers will
be able to go to it if they choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Verizon model, however, customers will be able to go
just about anywhere else on the Internet, as well, which means that
that compatibility is fairly close to meaningless. That is not a
word that applies to Vizzavi just now, but in Vizzavi's current
state, it might come close.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
