u e BC-TV-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-20 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: `BLUES CLUES' CREATOR; `SPORTS NIGHTS'; `LATE LATE SHOW'
PRODUCER 
</HEADLINE>
   C.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Blue's' Creator Wouldn't Stay
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if David E. Kelley were leaving ``Ally McBeal''; that
would surely make news.
</P>
<P>
   But the creator and producer of another television phenomenon
decided to leave his hit show a few months ago, and it happened
with no fanfare at all, no announcement from the network, no word
from anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the creator, Todd Kessler, is not quite as well known
as his show, and ``Blue's Clues'' may not make the cover of Vanity
Fair or even TV Guide.
</P>
<P>
   But the show is just as important to its network, Nickelodeon,
as anything just about any program producer has supplied to any
other network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue's Clues'' has defined Nick Jr., the preschool component
of the children's cable network, and established itself in just
four years as a classic rivaling ``Sesame Street.'' ``Blue's
Clues'' is seen by 14 million children a week.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more important, it has spawned a merchandising
empire, , from stuffed toys to lunchboxes to books.
</P>
<P>
   So why did Kessler's departure go unobserved?
</P>
<P>
   He said he simply had decided that ``it was time to move on.''
For him that meant creating a production company to develop and
produce movies and television shows for grown-ups. Kessler said he
was leaving with no hard feelings and was confident that his two
production partners, Angela Santomero and Traci Paige Johnson,
would maintain the show's standards.
</P>
<P>
   Brown Johnson (no relation to Traci Johnson), the Nickelodeon
executive in charge of Nick Jr., echoed Kessler's outlook on the
show's future. ``Angie and Traci really have a lot of great ideas
about what they want to do with the show,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked whether any conflict with Kessler had led to his
departure, Johnson said, ``I'm not comfortable talking about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   She declined to elaborate, and Kessler gave no indication that
any dispute with Nickelodeon influenced his decision to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler is certainly not leaving the show empty-handed. He said
he was guaranteed that he would be listed as executive producer on
the show as long as it lasts. ``I'll also have that credit on any
spinoffs they do as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon has already committed itself to producing two more
years of new episodes of ``Blue's Clues,'' which runs twice each
weekday on Nickelodeon, in the morning and afternoon. Soon the show
will have additional exposure when it becomes the centerpiece of
CBS's children's programming on Saturday and Sunday mornings.
</P>
<P>
   That schedule, which will start in September, is an early
example of the cooperation between the television holdings of
Viacom, which now owns both Nickelodeon and CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler was the first creator involved with ``Blue's Clues.'' He
said he had hit on the idea of a show combining live action and
animation after being asked by Nickelodeon executives to come up
with a program concept for preschoolers.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler then met Santomero, who had expertise in child
development and education. They brought in Johnson, who was an
artistic designer, and formed their partnership. All three have
been listed as creators and executive producers of the show.
</P>
<P>
   One breakthrough concept that Johnson attributed to Kessler was
creating all of the animation on a conventional desktop Apple
computer. ``I've always believed in spending more on creative
people than high-priced equipment,'' Kessler said.
</P>
<P>
   The show's other novel idea was to give young children the exact
same show five days a week to make it easier for them to learn by
repetition.
</P>
<P>
   Now Kessler is off buying short stories and novels to develop as
theatrical movies. ``This is something I always wanted to do _
start my own company and make movies,'' he said. The company is
called No Hands Productions. Kessler said he already had a deal
with Miramax Pictures to develop a film based on a short story he
had bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did 75 episodes of `Blue's Clues,''' he said. ``That's a
lot. I feel I've had so much impact with it, it's time to strike
out on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Striking Out?
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year ABC canceled ``Sports Night.'' Now Walt Disney
Co., the network's parent, is trying to sell it to another
television outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Aaron Sorkin for the Touchstone Television production
studio _ which, like ABC, is owned by Disney, the show centered on
a television sports news program much like ESPN's ``Sportscenter.''
TV Guide once called it ``the best show you're not watching.''
Despite critical praise, it did not draw very high ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Although it looked as if ``Sports Night'' might live on on HBO,
negotiations between Disney and the cable company are said to be
nearly dead. And one executive said that efforts to sell it to the
TNT or Showtime cable channels did not seem to be working out.
</P>
<P>
   Though there is still hope at Disney that ``Sports Night'' will
find a home, an executive who spoke on the condition of anonymity
expressed some doubt. The program is very expensive to produce, he
said, and thus very expensive to buy.
</P>
<P>
   This must come as a disappointment to Sorkin. But then, the
glass is still half-full for him. NBC has picked up his other show,
``West Wing,'' for another season.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
<P>
   Late of `Late Late'
</P>
<P>
   When Craig Kilborn left Comedy Central's ``Daily Show'' for
CBS's ``Late Late Show'' in mid-1999, he was teamed with a new
producer, Billy Kimball, who was also a veteran of Comedy Central
as the producer of ``Indecision '92,'' a farcical take on that
year's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Friday will be Kimball's last day on the show. He is leaving,
citing creative differences with the program's star, Kilborn. He
will be replaced by Mary Connelly, a onetime segment producer for
David Letterman, whose production company, World Wide Pants, owns
``Late Late Show.'' Most recently, she was a producer on ABC's
``Whose Line Is It Anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   Executives involved with the show said that Kilborn and Kimball
had decided that they no longer had chemistry. A spokesman for
Worldwide Pants said they ``had different ideas about how to take
the show forward,'' but would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Late Show,'' which featured Tom Snyder as the host before
Kilborn arrived, is doing better in the ratings than it did last
year. During the May sweeps, it was up 7 percent, with 1.45 million
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Kimball said he was not sure what he would do next. ``My idea
had been to star as Macbeth on Broadway,'' he said, jokingly
referring to the ill-fated Broadway foray by the television actor
Kelsey Grammer. ``But a few people have called me to say that is
not a good idea.'' _ By JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2225EDT &QL; 
