<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0017 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-NYT     06-20 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS HAVE A RING AND A LOT OF UPSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal stepped up to the dais Monday
night just as Jerry Buss, the owner of the Los Angeles Lakers,
finished telling the tale of how the supernova center, the new age
coaching sage and the young, bright shooting guard came together to
lead the franchise to its first championship in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Buss smiled at the sight of the 7-foot-1, 330-pound behemoth
pretending to clear his throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extension,'' O'Neal said through a mock cough. ``Extension.''
</P>
<P>
   Buss finally gave in. ``Whatever you want, baby,'' he told
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   What do you give the center who has everything? Or maybe a
better question: at what price a dynasty?
</P>
<P>
   After the cigar smoke had finished wafting through the Staples
Center _ and the Indiana Pacers had been dispensed in six mostly
pulsating games _ the Lakers toasted one another with Champagne,
waited for the rowdy streets outside the building to clear, and
then went their separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   The parade is scheduled for Wednesday, at which point O'Neal
will reiterate what he said after the clinching 116-111 Game 6
victory over the Pacers on Monday night in the National Basketball
Association finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get one next year, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Phil Jackson. Some triangle, no? The
triumph of the Lakers' trinity makes you wonder about the
possibilities, whether the NBA has another dynasty on its hands.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan won six titles in the 1990s with the same coach
who guided Kobe and Shaq to their first this season. The way Bryant
broke down defenses and O'Neal unleashed indefensible weapons the
past few months brought back shades of Magic Johnson and Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar, that Hall of Fame guard-center combination that led
the Lakers to five championships in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal averaged 38 points and 16.7 rebounds in the finals. He
became only the third player in league history to close out a
season with the scoring title, the most valuable player award and a
championship ring, and the third player to be named MVP of the
regular season, the All-Star Game and the NBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   At 28, O'Neal will only get better. Asked if the potential is
there for the Lakers to win multiple titles, Larry Bird, who won
three with the Boston Celtics and came close to another during his
three seasons as coach of the Pacers, replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it is with Shaquille O'Neal. He's the most dominating
player in our league. He's powerful, strong, able to get the ball
in the hole. He's just so dominating that they have an opportunity
to do something great for a number of years.''
</P>
<P>
   If O'Neal is the most dominant player in the league, Bryant has
quickly become the most dangerous perimeter player in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Named to the league's all-defensive team, he elevated his
stature in overtime of Game 4 by scoring 8 points after O'Neal
fouled out in the 120-118 victory at Conseco Fieldhouse. Bryant is
only 21.
</P>
<P>
   They both joined the Lakers in the summer of 1996, Bryant in a
draft-day trade with Charlotte and O'Neal, who had played with
Orlando, through free agency. They have never been the best of
friends, coexisting despite a feud that has turned ugly at times.
But on the court, they are undeniably the best inside-outside
combination in pro basketball.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal can extend his seven-year, $120 million contract this
summer _ a given, Buss said. Bryant appears to be a Laker for life.
If neither petty jealousy nor growing tired of seeing each other
every day gets in the way, few things can undermine their
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have definitely made their mark as one of the best
combinations ever to play this game,'' the Lakers reserve guard
Derek Fisher said Monday night. ''They carried us, and the rest of
us stepped it up when we needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Falling short for four seasons, they crossed the precipice in
Game 7 of the Western Conference finals against Portland, rallying
from 15 points down in the final 10 minutes to shock, and
eliminate, the Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   By barely escaping losing a three-games-to-one lead in the
conference finals and by staving off Indiana, the Lakers avoided
the indignity of becoming only the second 67-victory team not to
win a title.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of several signs revealing their vulnerability, signs
that should give 28 other teams a glimmer of hope _ including those
free-spending Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with a Game 3 debacle against Sacramento in the first
round, the Lakers went 4-6 in elimination games. The game before
they claimed their first title of the post-Magic era, the Lakers
suffered their worst loss of the season, a 33-point rout in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   They did not wield the hammer until Monday night, needing the
final minutes to wear down the game-but-defensively challenged
Pacers. Through it all, Jackson looked on like a ski instructor who
expected his students to fall off the chair lift now and then.
</P>
<P>
   He molded the egos and talent together flawlessly, siphoning
every ounce of energy from O'Neal to make sure the often-injured
center kept himself in prime physical condition. He did not have
qualms about singling Bryant out in front of his teammates, telling
him often and bluntly, ``Trust the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   When they finally raised the Larry O'Brien trophy and the purple
and gold confetti rained down from the rafters, it was plain to
see: All three sides of the triangle fit perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference has been Phil Jackson,'' said Bill Walton, the
NBC analyst and Hall of Fame center. ``What he did in terms of
challenging Shaq and Kobe to refocus their priorities, to become
defensive players, to become rebounders, to become passers, to get
in good shape, to become so focused in on the team, well, that has
made them champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see nothing that's going to keep these guys from staying at
the top _ unless they stop listening to the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   There are but a few questions. Glen Rice? He is not expected
back. Ron Harper may retire. A.C. Green won't start at power
forward much longer. But then, as long as Jerry West is in charge
of personnel, there are no worries.
</P>
<P>
   Only two-fifths of the starting lineup is guaranteed to return.
Those players just happen to be the only two the Lakers cannot
lose. Supporting casts don't collect banners as much as stars do.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq and Kobe have one _ and counting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
