<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0024 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-SOCIAL-     06-20 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-SOCIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE IS PURSUING HIS CASE FOR RETIREMENT SAVINGS PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. _ Vice President Al Gore set his case Tuesday for
government-subsidized savings accounts, saying his plan would help
families build wealth for retirement and other uses without putting
their guaranteed Social Security benefits at risk in the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to contrast his approach to Gov. George W. Bush's
proposal to create personal investment accounts within the Social
Security system, Gore said his plan would encourage lower- and
middle-income people to save by adding a program to supplement
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech, the tone of which could have been heard either as
robust populism or class warfare, Gore said his plan was intended
not just for people ``who think comfortably about their savings
over Scotch in the club looking out at the golf links, but also the
ones who carefully try to make it all add up to the dream over a
pressured half-hour break on the factory floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The appearance before a group of Democrats here was the latest
in his effort to focus the presidential race on the strong economy
and how best to apportion the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   In political terms, it gave Gore an opportunity to present a
positive alternative to Bush's proposal to allow workers to invest
a portion of their Social Security payroll taxes in the stock
market. And in economic terms it addressed one of the nation's
biggest weaknesses, the low rate of personal savings.
</P>
<P>
   Gore changed plans immediately after the speech, postponing
until Wednesday a trip to Des Moines and instead flying to
Washington in case his vote was needed in the Senate to break a tie
over hate crimes legislation backed by the Clinton administration.
In the end, Gore's vote was not needed.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's savings plan is built around providing matching funds,
through tax credits, for people who put money away in a type of
savings account that would be modeled after an Individual
Retirement Account. The plan, which would become effective
gradually over 10 years, would give more substantial credits to
people at the low end of the income spectrum, and would phase out
for people at higher income levels.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions to the accounts would be tax deductible, and
investment earnings would build tax free. The money would be taxed
on withdrawal. While the accounts would be intended for retirement
savings, the money could also be used to pay for college tuition, a
first home or catastrophic medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign said the plan would cost about $200 billion
over 10 years, making it one of the largest single initiatives
proposed by the vice president this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign said Gore's proposal followed Bush's lead in
acknowledging the attractiveness of allowing workers to invest for
retirement, but was otherwise flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Low-income workers living paycheck to paycheck cannot afford
it, and it doesn't stop Social Security from going broke,'' said
Ari Fleischer, Bush's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Gore continued his attack on Bush's investment-based approach,
saying it could drive the budget back into deficit, undermine the
nation's prosperity and penalize ``the elderly people who happen to
be on the losing end of a roll of the dice.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of the vice president's speech Tuesday sought to
portray his plan as a gateway to wealth, security and opportunity
for people who have historically had trouble putting aside any
substantial amounts of money in savings. He cast the issue in terms
of what happened to his childhood friends from two different
places.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones I went to school with in Washington, D.C., came
mostly from well-to-do families wth enough money to send them to
college and stake them to a good start,'' he said. ``And most of
them have done well in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones I spent my summers with in Carthage, Tenn., were at
least as smart, but their families weren't nearly as well off,'' he
said. ``And I saw the opportunity gap open, and widen, and there
were times when it broke my heart. They deserve more than they got.
And I'll be damned if I'm going to let that injustice continue.''
</P>
<P>
   In emphasizing his proposal's appeal to lower- and middle-income
residents, Gore drew an implicit comparison to Bush's plan. Bush's
approach is built around a large tax cut whose benefits would go
largely to people who pay the most taxes, the wealthy, and his
Social Security plan, which seeks to appeal to what Republicans see
as a large new investor class that encompasses many middle-income
people.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan has its roots in a proposal first offered by
President Clinton two years ago. Under the Clinton plan, low- and
moderate-income savers would not only have received matching funds
from the government, but they would have received an upfront
payment to get their savings accounts going.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore plan, which would be voluntary, would not offer any
upfront payment, and it is unclear how much new savings the program
would stimulate, especially among low-income households.
</P>
<P>
   It would offer matching funds for deposits made into the
accounts, with amount of the match dependent on income. A couple
making as much as $30,000 a year, for example, could each receive a
$3 for $1 match of deposits up to $500 a year; for their $500, each
person would receive another $1,500 through a tax credit, giving
the account a total value at the end of the year of $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   A couple making up to $60,000 would receive a $1 for $1 match of
their deposits up to $1,000 each. A couple earning as much as
$100,000 a year could contribute up to $1,500, and receive a match
of $1 for every $3 they deposit.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts would be administered by banks, brokerage firms and
other financial institutions, and would be limited to offering
mutual funds and other broad-based investments rather than
individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is expected to announce on Wednesday his support for modest
reductions in the federal estate tax to help farmers and small
business owners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
