<HEADER>
A0032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-BASEBALL-TESTS-NY     06-20 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-TESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HIGH, IT'S FAR, BUT THE BALL ISN'T LIVELIER
</HEADLINE>
  By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Testing the baseballs being used this season, Major
League Baseball was unable to squeeze any more juice out of them
than they found in balls from the previous two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   That was the report issued Tuesday by Sandy Alderson, executive
vice president of baseball operations, following a meeting with the
people who tested the balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no difference between the balls this year and the
balls from 1999 and _ to the extent we could test balls from '98 _
'98 as well,'' Alderson said. ``We're satisfied that nothing has
taken place in the last two or three years to change the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   An increase in home runs and runs this season fueled speculation
that the ball was livelier. Some pitchers have said the cover of
the ball is slicker than in the past, making it more difficult to
throw certain pitches. Other observers have explained the increase
in the growing strength of the hitters, the shrinking talent of the
pitchers and the smaller sizes of the new parks.
</P>
<P>
   Rawlings, which manufactures major league baseballs in Haiti,
has long said the balls have not changed, neither in the materials
used nor in the manufacturing process. Baseball assigned its
testing to Jim Sherwood, a professor at the University of
Massachusetts at Lowell, and Larry Fallon, who has a laboratory in
Cambridge, Mass. Under baseball rules, the key to the acceptability
of the balls is whether they fall within a range of specifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within this range of specifications that are acceptable, we
can have balls at both ends of the spectrum and they will perform
differently,'' Alderson said. ``But based on what we've seen so
far, we don't see balls at either end of the spectrum. They are
tightly bunched at sort of the high end of coefficient of
restitution specifications, but they have been for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to take balls at the low end of the spectrum,'' he
added, ``you'd have a ball like the Cubans have, which is
essentially dead. We haven't had that for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson said his study of the balls will continue. ``We want to
learn more about the process and see what continuity there has
been,'' he said. ``We want to see what the pattern has been over a
longer period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, the problem presented by the testing of older
baseballs is that the aging process can affect them.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Tuesday night's games, home runs were up over last
season from 2.31 a game to 2.56 and runs were up from 10.29 a game
to 10.49 a game.
</P>
<P>
   A flurry of high-scoring, lopsided games in the previous two
days prompted speculation that scoring was soaring out of control.
Research by Elias Sports Bureau, however, found a decline in the
number of games decided by 10 or more runs. Last season produced
exactly 100 such games. So far this season there have been 35 of
those games. That number projects to 84 for the entire season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0035 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-GRAHAM-HNS &LR;      06-20 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC OPINION TRIAL OF GRAHAM 
TAKES ANOTHER TWIST 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SALATHEIA BRYANT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The public opinion trial of convicted killer Gary
Graham took another twist Tuesday as Harris County District
Attorney John B. Holmes Jr. released an affidavit from a bailiff
 &UR;  &LR; who reported hearing Graham say as he was condemned: ``Next time
I'm not going to leave any witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days before Graham's execution date, he received a death-row
visit from the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who is trying to persuade
officials to grant Graham a new trial in which new evidence would
be heard.
</P>
<P>
   An expected decision by the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles
on whether Graham will be killed Thursday will likely not come down
until that day.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County Sheriff's Deputy Larry Pollinger, who is now
retired, spoke with prosecutors in Houston on Tuesday. He confirmed
the story and signed an affidavit. Assistant District Attorney Carl
Hobbs, who prosecuted the Graham case in 1981, signed another
affidavit Monday stating that Pollinger told him about the
statement minutes after a jury voted to sentence Graham to death
for capital murder
</P>
<P>
   ``At the conclusion of the trial, while preparing to return Mr.
Graham to the jail, he stated to me: `Next time I'm not going to
leave any witnesses,' '' Pollinger's affidavit said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes said he was inspired to release the affidavit, even
though it is inadmissible as evidence, in light of the tactics
being used by Graham supporters. Both supporters and those who
believe the execution is just have waged an escalating public
opinion war as Thursday's execution date draws closer.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who visited Graham in the morning at the Terrell Unit
in Livingston, and Bianca Jagger of Amnesty International USA came
to Houston to plead for a new trial for Graham. Noting other
witnesses who were available and questionable defense, Jackson said
Graham hadn't received a fair trial in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said if he cannot stop the execution he plans to witness
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``His spirits are being buoyed by support around the world. He's
winning in that (public opinion) court,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only asking Texas for a fair trial for Mr. Graham. We
offer our prayers but we seek a fair trail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson made a biblical reference to Gov. George W. Bush being
in the same position as Pontius Pilate, who was faced with freeing
either Jesus or a murderer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pontius Pilate had the power to set an innocent man free. He
didn't have the courage. He went with the crowd,'' Jackson said.
``We're saying to Governor Bush, don't let this man die. In this
case silence is not golden, it is betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes said he released the dramatic affidavit from the bailiff
in response to such emotional appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just rhetoric, made after the verdict and not a basis
for discussion in appeal,'' said Holmes. ``But I have no objection
to using it now. I'd hate to see the emotion of the moment cause
something wrong to happen in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bringing this up now for obvious reasons,'' he said,
meaning to counteract the publicity generated by Graham's backers.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General John Cornyn also mentioned the bailiff's
statement Monday on ABC's ``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for Graham questioned Holmes' decision to make it
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``No where in the litigation of this case has the district
attorney or attorney general's office ever alleged it,'' Richard
Burr, Graham's lead counsel, said. ``It's never been relied on in
opposing our pleadings in this case. You can't believe everything
that is said.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Jack Zimmermann added: ``There has been repeated briefs
filed in this case and that has never been mentioned. There's no
proof that was ever said.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham was convicted of the May 1981 robbery- murder of Bobby
Grant Lambert in a Houston supermarket parking lot. Bernadine
Skillern, who was sitting in her car at the time of the shooting,
was the only witness to positively identify Graham during his
trial. She still maintains her certitude.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Graham's new lawyers have petitioned state and
federal court to hear what they consider exculpatory evidence. Each
court, most recently, the U.S. Supreme Court, has refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is guilty and it has been confirmed over and over again by
every court,'' said Roe Wilson, an appellate specialist in Holmes'
office.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles is expected to rule
Thursday _ hours before his execution time _ on a Graham petition
for a reprieve so that a hearing can be held, a conditional pardon
granted or his death-sentence commuted.
</P>
<P>
   Graham supporters have rallied around the question of mistaken
identity and incompetent legal representation in their call for a
new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Burr said Tuesday they are considering filing another appeal
with the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technically, we'll have no chance at all,'' Burr admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Burr and Zimmermann touted affidavits from three jurors in the
Graham case, who say if they had heard witnesses Sherian Etuk and
Ronald Hubbard testify at trial, they would not have voted to
convict. The affidavits were sent to board members.
</P>
<P>
   Although both witnesses were named in the original 1981 police
report, they were not called as witnesses by Graham's trial lawyer,
Ron Mock, to challenge Skillern's testimony. Neither witness saw
the actual shooting. Both say however, they saw a man wearing a
white jacket and dark pants (the same description Skillern gave
police) before the shooting and he was four to seven inches shorter
than Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Burr said the witnesses were not mentioned in Graham's appeal
filed in 1987. No defense lawyer tracked them down until after he
became involved with the case in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But Cornyn says judges have deemed neither witness credible. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
