<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0036 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WORKLPLACE-COLUMN-NYT     06-20 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKLPLACE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING HOOKY, WORKING HOOKY
</HEADLINE>
  By LISA BELKIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm thinking of turning off my computer, silencing my cell phone
and going to the movies. I have no idea what film I'll see, but
that isn't the point. What matters is that the theater will be dark
and cool and virtually empty _ because it will be the middle of the
day, when I should really be at work.
</P>
<P>
   I never once played hooky as a child. I'm somewhat embarrassed
to admit that I never even thought of it. Maybe I am compensating
for that as an adult (or maybe this comes up on days when I don't
necessarily want to be an adult), but I get the periodic urge to
sneak out once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   I don't do it often. Maybe once or twice a year, if that _
usually when the weather turns warm. And I am very specific about
what I define as ``hooky.'' It does not include time off to visit
the accountant or take the car to the insurance adjuster or even to
attend the kindergarten year-end picnic. To count, it has to be a
minirebellion, a few delicious hours at a place where I know I
really am not supposed to be. The movies are a particular favorite.
When I emerge after the final credits, blinking in the afternoon
glare, I usually go home and concentrate more completely than I
could have done before.
</P>
<P>
   The restorative power of forbidden fruit has not been lost on
enlightened employers. Some companies go further still.
Morningstar, the financial services company in Chicago, gives
workers unlimited time off, no questions asked. (So far,
Morningstar says, no one has abused this privilege.) Strategy
Associates, a Silicon Valley consulting firm, has an employee-run
``Culture Club'' that schedules monthly hooky sessions for
activities like bowling, ice skating, ultimate Frisbee and, yes, an
afternoon at the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Posner, the president and chief executive of COMM2 Inc., a
seven-person advertising agency in Chicago, never takes time off.
``The sun and the moon will not rise and set if I stop working,''
she says. Yet, she insists that her employees play occasional
hooky. Every so often she hands out coupons that can be traded for
rewards as free-form as a day off or as specific as an afternoon at
a ballgame. The most cherished coupon, she says, is the one that
reads, ``Today it is too cold to go to work and I can't face
getting out of bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Just about the only thing her staff may not do, she says, is lie
about why they are not at work. ``I warn them: `If you lie, you're
gonna get caught and I'm never going to trust you,''' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Fass, who runs a five-person public-relations firm in
Manhattan, agrees. ``I would be unhappy, and would even feel I was
an unsuccessful, insensitive boss, if people sneaked out,'' she
says. ``I would resent that a good deal. It's a terrific perk to
let them take a `mental health day.' Sneaking out _ I think you
have trouble on your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Fass and Posner say they are trying to pre-empt employees like
Kerry Spreckman, who became so good at lying that she wrote and
published herself ``The Hooky Book,'' which lists 200 excuses to
tell a gullible boss. Among her favorites are ``My garage door
won't go up, so I can't get my car out,'' ``My key broke off in the
front door, and I have to wait for the locksmith'' and, she says,
``anything disgusting and medical because your boss just doesn't
want to hear about it.'' When all else fails, she suggests watching
the Weather Channel for natural disasters and then calling (from
home) and saying: ``I'm in Kansas; I came for the weekend to see my
cousin, and I'm sure you've heard about that tornado.''
</P>
<P>
   The grown-up part of me certainly understands why a boss values
trust, but the not- quite-grown-up part, the part that wants to
play hooky in the first place, thinks lying is such a harsh word.
Half the point of this, maybe even more than half, is that you
aren't supposed to be doing it. Having the boss' permission takes
that frisson of naughtiness away.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth McRae Smith understands all that. She is head of the
McRae Agency, which specializes in publicity for Internet
start-ups, and she has made it policy to play hooky with her office
staffs in San Diego and San Francisco. On a whim, she will close
business for the afternoon and take everyone antique shopping or
clothes shopping or on a drive along the coast for margaritas.
``It's probably a little less exciting because it's not
forbidden,'' she says, but to offset that she often ``contributes''
$100 or so to her employees' purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the boss is buying,'' she says, ``no one seems to mind that
the boss knows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
