<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-20 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSH TOPS $90 MILLION MARK
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush's presidential campaign continues to shatter
fund-raising records, topping the $90 million mark when receipts
for May are included. But most of the money has already been spent
and the Texas governor continues to beat the bushes for more.
Campaign officials announced Tuesday that Bush raised $6 million in
May and spent $4.9 million, leaving him with $7.1 million in the
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore reported that he had raised only $587,802
in May, and had spent $1.3 million. He was left with $8.2 million,
out of $37 million raised over all during the campaign. Gore
expects to qualify for $15 million in federal matching funds,
bringing his total pre-convention fund to the $40.5 million
spending cap placed on candidates who accept federal money. Bush,
who is not accepting federal money, expects to spend nearly twice
as much before the Republican National Convention, which starts on
July 31.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR ZEROS IN ON BUSH
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO has issued a warning to Gov. George W. Bush: ``The
Texas Truth Squad is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth squad, composed of workers from Texas, will appear at
labor-sponsored meetings around the country and will try to sully
Bush's reputation by talking about problems in Texas that include
education, health care and the treatment of farm workers. The union
leaflet says the truth squad will note that Texas ranks the lowest
among all states in the percentage of people who have health
insurance and near the bottom in College Board scores.
</P>
<P>
   John J. Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, will be the master of
ceremonies at the first truth squad event, to be held in
Philadelphia on June 29. Union officials say similar events will be
held in Albuquerque, Chicago, Cincinnati, Cleveland, Los Angeles,
Louisville, Ky., and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO has endorsed Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   PHYSICIST CHALLENGES BUCHANAN
</P>
<P>
   John Hagelin, the quantum physicist who founded the Natural Law
Party, on Tuesday challenged Pat Buchanan for the Reform Party's
presidential nomination and the right to spend the party's $12.6
million in federal campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to running as the nominee of the Natural Law Party,
whose platform emphasizes ``harnessing the managing intelligence of
nature'' Hagelin said he had qualified to have his name placed on
the mail ballot that Reform Party members will use to pick a
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that he would get more mail votes than Buchanan,
widely regarded as the favorite in the contest. If that happens, he
said, Buchanan's only hope to become the nominee would be to pull
off a coup at the party's national convention in Long Beach,
Calif., this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Buchanan left the Republican Party last year he has
been taking over the Reform Party, winning the biggest share of
convention delegates chosen at state party meetings. Party rules
say a two-thirds majority at the national convention can overturn
the result of mail-in balloting.
</P>
<P>
   AD CAMPAIGN AIMS AT MINORITIES
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party officials announced Tuesday the start of a
radio and television advertising campaign intended to appeal
specifically to African-American and Hispanic voters. Vice
President Al Gore's health care proposals, including a patients'
bill of rights plan, are the focus of advertisements intended for
African-Americans. The commercials for Hispanic voters, which are
in Spanish, touch on education and preserving Social Security. The
African-American advertisements will be broadcast in 17 states,
while the advertisements for Hispanics will shown only in Florida,
Illinois, New Mexico and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Los Angeles and Houston
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ Des Moines, Minneapolis and St. Paul
</P>
</TEXT>
