<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATIONS STALL AS THE UMPIRES' NEW UNION FACES FAMILIAR
OBSTACLES 
</HEADLINE>
  By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Major league umpires have a new union, but their new
leaders have discovered, much to their dismay, that they are
involved in the same old negotiations. After months of silence and
hope for a quick labor agreement, John Hirschbeck, the president of
the new union, said Tuesday that he was ``very disappointed in
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   So disappointed, discouraged and disenchanted, Hirschbeck said,
that umpires had discussed among themselves the possibility of a
strike.
</P>
<P>
   He did not discuss the possibility of taking a strike vote, but
he said: ``We started this new union with the hope of creating a
less confrontational relationship with management than had been in
the past with Richie Phillips and the old union. We weren't looking
for controversy. We were trying to show good faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he added: ``Their feeling of us is almost to take
advantage of a new union. Rather than work with us, it's like they
want to take advantage of us. Our cooperation shouldn't be taken
for weakness or lack of resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck talked by telephone from Boston, where he worked the
Red Sox-Yankees series. The interview was his first on the
negotiations since they began, and the disappointment he spoke of
was clear in his voice. Phillips, who has maintained a low profile
since his ouster, did not return a telephone call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Under an interim agreement, neither side can take any action
against the other until July 15, and then only after it has given
two weeks' notice, which cannot be done before July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, Major League Baseball's executive vice president
for baseball operations, said the commissioner's office would be
prepared to deal with any action the umpires might take.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get this thing negotiated,'' he said, ``but it has
to be done on reasonable terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson said a lockout of the umpires ``is not something we've
contemplated or would contemplate any time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   In talks conducted out of the glare of public scrutiny, the two
sides had reached agreement in principle on other elements of the
contract, but then negotiations stalled over four issues, and they
have not met for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck identified the thorny issues as control and
discipline, free speech, salaries and jobs for the 22 umpires whose
resignations were accepted last year following Phillips' failed
mass resignation strategy. That strategy prompted Hirschbeck, Joe
Brinkman and other umpires, mostly from the American League, to
form a new union.
</P>
<P>
   The insurgents won approval of a majority of the umpires in a
vote conducted by the National Labor Relations Board, but now, as
leaders, they have found a new collective bargaining agreement no
easier to attain than Phillips ever did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped it could have been done a long time ago,''
Hirschbeck said. ``The big changes they're trying to implement are
things we could never be satisfied with or tolerate in a
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck also said that Ralph Nelson, the executive in the
commissioner's office who is in charge of the umpires, has become a
focal point of distrust among the umpires. He said the relationship
with Nelson has become ``very strained,'' saying, ``Many umpires
have told me one thing was said to them and another was done; they
are not happy.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hirschbeck said, umpires have been fined for
reasons they previously did not face. He said six umpires have been
fined this season and believed that only one fine was ``somewhat
justified.'' Some of the fines, he said, were levied after umpires
allegedly did not run into the outfield to get closer to a fly
ball.
</P>
<P>
   He said one umpire was fined $250 on that basis, another $500.
``He had no idea that anything about his on-field performance was
wrong in what he was doing,'' Hirschbeck said of the latter umpire.
``It was about fly balls and coverage. All of a sudden he receives
a $500 fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson defended Nelson. He said Nelson did not do anything he
did not know about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy changing a management style when management to a
large extent has abdicated its role over a period of time,''
Alderson said. ``We've never hidden our intentions here. We
intended to exercise more control over the umpires. We are doing
that and we expect to do it going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck said the control issues, such as the fines, provided
an example of why umpires want somebody like an arbitrator to hear
appeals of disciplinary action against them. Management has held
firm against the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want total control over the umpires where they can walk
up to an umpire and say you're done,'' Hirschbeck said. ``I'm not
saying an umpire has to be like a Supreme Court judge and stay for
life, but it's only fair to have some type of system in place where
if an umpire does something wrong or needs to improve, he can go to
someone who is impartial.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have discussed the possibility of having five-man
umpiring crews, giving each umpire one week's vacation every fifth
week. That plan could lead to the rehiring of some of the 22
umpires who lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck said the two sides seemed to be moving toward a
resolution on the 22, but ``where we had gotten seemed to dissolve
at the last meeting.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
