</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PROPOSES $2.3 BILLION MORE FOR EDUCATION, COLLEGE AID FOR
TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUPERTINO, Calif. _ Visiting the cradle of the digital
revolution, Gov. George W. Bush warned Tuesday that school children
were not being adequately prepared for jobs in technology, and
proposed spending an additional $2.3 billion over five years to
improve math and science education in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we can do better,'' Bush told educators at De Anza
College, here in the heart of the Silicon Valley. The Texas
governor frequently cited tests of children in 21 countries,
including the United States, as yardsticks of just how much room
for improvement there was.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is America,'' Bush said. ``There's no reason for us to be
next to last in math. There's no reason for us to be last in
physics. We're the greatest country in the world. We ought to be
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond those exhortations to greatness, however, Bush talked
little about the proposals he was making, which were spelled out
instead in documents distributed by his aides. These plans were the
latest in a series of education initiatives that Bush has proposed
during the last three months, and they reflected his focus on
education as an issue with which he can appeal to moderate voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, called
for the federal government to spend an additional $1 billion over
five years on the establishment of a math and science partnership
fund to encourage universities and colleges to interact with public
schools in ways that enhanced math and science instruction for
children in kindergarten through the 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
   Bush proposed an additional $1 billion over five years to
increase the amount available in federal Pell grants that are given
to low-income students to help pay for college education. Under the
governor's plan, young people who have taken college-level math or
science courses in high school can qualify for a grant that would
be worth an additional $1,000. The average Pell grant, Bush's aides
said, is worth about $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Bush called for an additional $345 million over five
years to encourage college graduates who majored in science or math
to spend at least five years teaching in public schools in
under-served areas. Under current federal programs, graduates who
do this can have $5,000 of their student loans forgiven or paid by
the federal government. Bush would expand this amount to $17,500.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor was not merely articulating new policy Tuesday;
Bush was spending time in a state _ an electoral heavyweight _ that
has tilted heavily Democratic in the last few years, but one he
does not want to cede to Vice President Al Gore in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   California has 54 electoral votes, more than any other state,
and Bush's trip here this week, which began on Monday and is
scheduled to end on Wednesday, was his fourth swing through the
state since the primary here on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   A statewide poll conducted by the Field organization and made
public Tuesday showed Bush trailing Gore by 11 points, 46 percent
to 35 percent, though several previous polls have portrayed a
tighter race. Several times this week, Bush insisted that he could
compete successfully in California by appealing to Hispanic voters,
promoting his education plans and convincing people in the Silicon
Valley that his economic and trade policies would benefit them.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has described himself as a fiscal conservative, he
has proposed spending billions of dollars in federal money for
education since the campaign began. Gore has proposed spending even
more, and one of the educators with whom Bush met here Tuesday
seemed to suggest that Bush could be more generous.
</P>
<P>
   In a decidedly unscripted moment, Barbara Illowsky, a math
professor at De Anza College, told Bush that it would be terrific
if he ``were able to raise as much money for education'' as he had
for his presidential campaign and the Republican Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
