<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0066 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLAN     06-20 1944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS COULD BECOME A DYNASTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Long after Kobe Bryant's free throws sealed the
victory, long after Shaquille O'Neal's joyful tears splashed off
the golden ball, long after the Staples Center celebration ended
late Monday night, the Los Angeles Lakers' championship party raged
on, right into Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   It might not end for another decade.
</P>
<P>
   Although changes are inevitable in the coming months, the
Lakers' greatness is at their core, and it is an awesome
foundation: Shaq and Kobe. The 28-year-old center, the best at his
position, and the 21-year-old guard, perhaps the best at his.
</P>
<P>
   Together, under contract for the foreseeable future, and
improving along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Better chill another few cases of champagne and reserve another
round of stogies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you what,'' said teammate Glen Rice, ``that's the best
duo that I've seen in a long time. And they're going to be together
forever. . . . I've been able to sit back and watch those guys do
their thing and it's an unbelievable duo.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the Lakers' offices, no one was projecting a dynasty yet.
Instead, they were just enjoying the first step in the wake of the
championship-clinching victory over the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers executive Jerry West, who found it too painful to watch
the Game 6 finale on Monday, wore a satisfied look Tuesday in his
El Segundo office.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after the organization gambled to acquire Bryant in
trade and O'Neal with then the NBA's most lucrative contract, the
Lakers brought the championship home.
</P>
<P>
   West said he was happy for owner Jerry Buss, for the fans, who
``have been wonderful''; for first-year coach Phil Jackson, who
exceeded short-range expectations; but mostly for O'Neal, whose
greatness can no longer be questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other person I feel great for is Shaquille O'Neal,'' West
said. ``He's a very proud man who is the best player in basketball.
And no one knew until this year. And I'm so happy for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our coaching staff feels great. To go from Chicago to
here. . . . and there was always a question of, `Can you win
without Michael Jordan?' Well, he did. So I'm delighted for him and
his staff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Buss, you have to feel good for him,'' West said. ``He's
let us do some things around here that maybe some other people
wouldn't have, wouldn't be a big enough risk-taker. . . . We took
the ultimate risk and we came up with two players in one year that
I think anyone in the league would like to have these two guys on
their team. And they'd probably sacrifice their whole team for
those two guys. So that makes us feel real good. Jerry deserves
credit for allowing us to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the transactions that brought Bryant and O'Neal to
L.A. also took a tremendous toll on West, leading to annual
speculation that he will retire. The latest report surfaced Monday,
in the column of a cable talk-show host.
</P>
<P>
   West dismissed the report but at times sounded ready to hang it
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's had me retiring for the last four years, I think
that's what people want me to do,'' West quipped. ``A lot of it is
how you feel about yourself. You have to determine that. . . . This
has been an important part of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But is he still as driven in his work? ``I don't know that. I
don't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   So does that mean he's contemplating retirement? ``I don't know
that. You guys will be the first to know.''
</P>
<P>
   There might not be changes at the top. But there will certainly
be changes in the locker room. Among the free agents are starters
Rice, A.C. Green and Ron Harper. The team holds an option on Green
while Harper holds his own option. Key reserve Brian Shaw also is a
free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers aren't ready to say who'll be back and who won't.
Even Rice, unhappy with his role at times, has said he would
return, and the Lakers for now say they want him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what, I'm hopeful that everyone comes back,'' West
said. ``It's hard to break up teams. I have a wonderful
relationship with Glen Rice. We'll see what happens. He's a free
agent, he can go wherever he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   With Rice joining O'Neal and Bryant, the Lakers had a potent
offensive lineup, and with players such as Harper, Rick Fox and
Robert Horry, they also became one of the best defensive teams in
the league under Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most in the organization hoped for a 60-win season, nothing
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to win 55 or 60 games regardless of who coached
this team,'' West said, ``but that's not enough here. It's just not
enough. And (Jackson) molded these people into believers. He molded
them into a team instead of a collection of individuals. He brought
a confidence to this team that I hadn't seen in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   And pushed them to 67 regular-season wins, then a title. So much
for taking time to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're overachievers here,'' general manager Mitch Kupchak
said. ``People aren't going to believe that if you write it, but I
don't think anybody had expectations of us winning a championship
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all believed we'd have a good year and we could win
a championship, but I don't think anybody expected it. And
certainly no one expected us to have the regular-season record we
had. . . . But it's still a young, immature team to a degree. A
team that I think grew each series Sacramento, Phoenix, Portland in
particular and then Indiana. So maybe there's some character and
some maturity that's been able to last six or seven weeks and will
help us next year.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, a superstar tandem that is young and under
contract for a few years will help, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Kupchak said, ``is nice to know.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
COACH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PHIL JACKSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
__Season in review: This is the year he became more than just
Michael Jordan's coach. Jackson brought the best out of Shaquille
O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, instilled a discipline and a system that
maximized the Lakers' role players and produced the second-best
regular-season record (67-15) in franchise history. He shot for 60
wins; he got his seventh championship in nine years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __Outlook: Under contract for four more years, to the delight of
both management and players. When's the last time you could say
that? He'll have new challenges next season with a retooled
roster. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STARTERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SHAQUILLE O'NEAL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
__Season in review: This is the season everyone awaited, the year
Shaq grew up and led his team to the championship. He improved his
defense and rebounding, dominated the regular season, won the
scoring title (career-high 29.7 points per game) and the MVP award,
then gave the greatest postseason performance by a center in more
than a decade, adding the Finals MVP award to his collection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __Outlook: Signed through 2002-03, eligible for extension
through 2005-06. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A.C. GREEN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
__Season in review: Provided some gutty defense and rebounding but
at age 36 played limited minutes even while extending his ironman
streak to an NBA-record 1,110 games. His veteran leadership and
symbolic tie to past Lakers championships were just as
significant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __Outlook: Team holds one-year option for next season, but as
always, they need an upgrade at the position, and he's a candidate
to retire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GLEN RICE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
__Season in review: He struggled with his role as the third option
and never adapted well to the triangle offense, finishing with a
career-low shooting percentage (.430) and modest 15.9 points per
game. But the sacrifice got him his first NBA championship at age
33. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __Outlook: A free agent, Rice says he wants to return but seems
likely to find a better fit, and more money, elsewhere. Lakers
could use him in a sign-and-trade deal to acquire help at forward
and/or guard. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
KOBE BRYANT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
__Season in review: This is the year Bryant lived up to the hype
and became perhaps the best shooting guard in the league. He became
a much better team player and an All-Defensive first-team selection
while posting career highs in points (22.5), rebounds (6.3) and
assists (4.9). His clutch play in the championship run only
certified Bryant as a bona fide superstar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __Outlook: Signed through 2004-05. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RON HARPER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
__Season in review: Lured, gimpy knees and all, out of
semiretirement by Phil Jackson to help teach Bryant the triangle
offense and help the Lakers adapt to the new system. His
championship experience with the Bulls and calming presence were
major assets, and when the playoffs came, he actually became a
scorer again as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __Outlook: Holds option for one-year contract and says he'll
return if Jackson wants him but at age 35 is considering
retirement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
KEY RESERVES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ROBERT HORRY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
__Season in review: Began season as trade bait and in Jackson's
doghouse but became a player Jackson called the ``key to the
team,'' providing active defense, rebounding and 3-point shooting.
Played behind A.C. Green but got majority of minutes, proving once
again he could be effective as an undersized power forward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __Outlook: Signed through 2003-04 and could return in same role
next season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RICK FOX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
__Season in review: Not his best season statistically (6.5 points,
2.5 rebounds), but his gritty defense was irreplaceable, especially
during key stretches of the Finals, when he was sent in to stop
Indiana's Jalen Rose. Fox is a needed on-court enforcer, a tough
guy willing to do anything to win. Jackson often played Fox in the
fourth quarter of tight games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __Outlook: Signed through 2005, could become starter again if
Rice leaves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DEREK FISHER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
__Season in review: Started first month of season while Bryant was
injured, then returned to bench and struggled with his shot (.346
from field). Finished with career-high 6.3 points per game and
provided scrappy defense, used as primary defender on opponents'
shorter guards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __Outlook: Signed through 2006 but could be used as trade bait
since Jackson prefers taller guards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BRIAN SHAW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
__Season in review: Only became a Laker because Bryant broke his
hand in October but quickly became valuable reserve and a fan
favorite, igniting crowds with his lobs to Shaq, his former Orlando
teammate. Provided clutch 3-point shooting in Game 7 victory over
Portland. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __Outlook: A free agent and 36 years old, he could come back for
one more run if he doesn't retire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
OTHERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TRAVIS KNIGHT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Has body to play forward and center but didn't impress Jackson
enough to warrant many minutes. He has no clear role here but is
young (25) and under contract through 2003-04. Lakers will trade
him if they can. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JOHN SALLEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Lakers' other backup center also didn't play much after coming out
of a three-year retirement. But he was a good on-court tutor for
Shaq and a light-hearted presence in the locker room. He's a free
agent and Lakers might need his roster slot for a younger big man. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DEVEAN GEORGE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Rookie swingman impressed coaching staff but didn't get much
opportunity to play. Signed through 2001-02 (team option in 2003)
and could join rotation next season, although Jackson favors
veterans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JOHN CELESTAND &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Rookie point guard spent most of season on injured list, is a free
agent and will probably will sign elsewhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TYRONN LUE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Second-year point guard had some nice moments in November before
injuring his knee. He's also shorter (6-0) than Jackson prefers but
is under contract through 2000-01 (team option in 2002).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
