<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0068 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HITECH-RR-XINGS21-COX     06-20 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITECH-RR-XINGS21-COX1stled </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: 1stled fixes byline
 &HT;    Researchers exploring high-tech solution to rail crossing
collisions
 &HT;    By Joey Ledford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLUE RIDGE, Ga. _ As the brown Honda approached the unguarded
railroad crossing Tuesday, the radar detector hanging from its
windshield erupted with a constant stream of beeps.
</P>
<P>
   It's not what you think. Otto Rausch's detector hadn't picked up
a trooper trying to write him a ticket. It had detected the big red
and white Georgia Northeastern Railroad Co. locomotive sitting 164
feet down the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``See how it's beeping now?'' asked Rausch, a senior research
scientist at Georgia Tech. ``We're getting good signal strength.
</P>
<P>
   Rausch, Gene Greneker, another Georgia Tech researcher, and
Danny Diaz, a Georgia Tech senior, were working on the railroad on
this hot steamy day, testing a technology that could someday soon
be saving lives.
</P>
<P>
   On March 29, only about 30 miles from this spot just north of
Blue Ridge, a CSX train piled into a school bus, ripping it into
two pieces. Three children died and two others were critically
injured. The Tennessee Highway Patrol, which was called to the
crash just across the state line, later said an onboard video
camera indicated the Murray County school bus driver never stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had this receiver been sitting there (on the bus) beeping _
it's pretty raucous _ it would have been a wake-up call,'' said
Greneker.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists from the Georgia Tech Research Institute have
been working on the safety warning system since 1996, getting a
grant the next year from the Federal Highway Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could put one of these on every school bus in the
country,'' said Greneker, who said the system had performed
flawlessly during two days of tests. ``Next year, we'll probably go
to a rural county and put a receiver on every school bus and a
transmitter on every train going through the county.''
</P>
<P>
   After a year of such tests, the safety warning system could be
ready for use anywhere. Greneker said he's confident enough in the
system that it could be used already.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this system holds a lot of promise,'' said Dick
Hillman, safety manager for the Georgia Northeastern Railroad, who
volunteered a stretch of the railroad's popular Blue Ridge Scenic
Railway for the tests.
</P>
<P>
   Greneker said the transmitter aboard locomotives would be about
the size of a brick and is capable of transmitting a nine-digit
alphanumeric code as well as a voice message to specially designed
radar detectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Locomotive approaching crossing,'' the transmitted voice would
say, alerting the driver.
</P>
<P>
   Greneker said it is conceivable the system might be cheaper than
installing electric signals and gates on all unguarded rural grade
crossings. Those can run up to $100,000 per crossing.
</P>
<P>
   The safety warning system would cost much less _ about $600 for
each receiver on each locomotive, less than $100 per radar detector
receiver and about $25 for reflectors at each grade crossing. The
reflectors, a one-square-foot metal plate, are used to reflect the
line of sight signal from the locomotive up either side of the
highway, alerting equipped motorists approaching the crossing.
</P>
<P>
   The reflectors, which would sit on a pole, could be painted with
a small railroad crossbucks symbol and hopefully protected from
vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed something that would degrade gracefully on a country
crossing where people might shoot it up,'' said Greneker. A
reflector might even be able to take a shot or two and still send
the radar warning up and down the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Transmitters could even be installed on crossing gates and be
programmed to beam the signals when the gates are closing. But
Hillman noted that about half of all train-vehicle collisions occur
after motorists see crossing gates _ but ignore them _ driving
around the gate in an attempt to beat the train.
</P>
<P>
   The signal can transmit up to a mile away, but the reflectors
reduce the range to the point that motorists won't be distracted by
too-frequent alarms of possible hazards too far away, said
Greneker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to warn people,'' he said, ``but not too long before
they see what they're looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
