<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0210 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SAATCHI-AD-COLUMN-NYT     06-20 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAATCHI-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: $1.9 BILLION SAATCHI DEAL VAULTS PUBLICIS TO TOP
TIER 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six years after Maurice Saatchi left Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, there's
a new Maurice in charge, only this time the name is pronounced the
French way rather than the British.
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, the London agency company founded by Saatchi
and his brother, Charles, agreed Tuesday to be acquired by a
Paris-based rival, Publicis SA, for about $1.9 billion in stock.
Maurice Levy, the chairman and chief executive of Publicis, who is
proving to be almost as acquisitive as the Saatchis have been, will
head a merged entity, the Publicis Groupe, which will oversee the
agencies now under the Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi and Publicis banners.
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi will continue as an autonomous unit of the
Publicis Groupe rather than operate independently. That is
emblematic of the dwindling ranks of agencies not owned by giant
holding companies amid a whirlwind of deals like the pending
takeovers of Young &AMP; Rubicamby the WPP Group and Snyder
Communications by Havas Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WPP deal is a confirmation consolidation is happening, and
we had to make some decisions,'' Levy said in a telephone interview
Tuesday after a news conference in Paris. Discussions began in
December, he added, and turned serious in March, before he
unsuccessfully offered Publicis as an alternate buyer for Y&AMP;R.
</P>
<P>
   Word began leaking out Monday as Levy made plans for his news
conference to disclose the deal, the most recent in a spate that
has included familiar names like Fallon, Frankel and Hal Riney &AMP;
Partners. The deal, which is expected to be completed by
mid-September, would catapult the combination of Publicis and
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi into the top tier of mega-firms.
</P>
<P>
   The Publicis Groupe will rank fifth in billings, at $17.8
billion, and revenue, at $2.2 billion, behind Havas, Interpublic
Group of Cos., Omnicom Group and WPP.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a powerful new force in worldwide advertising, vaulting
to No. 5 overnight,'' said Bob Seelert, the chairman of Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi, who joined Levy for the telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing business in a consolidating world,'' said Seelert,
who will retain his title when Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi becomes a unit of
the Publicis Groupe. ``And this puts us up in the premier league.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was worried about Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi losing its
identity with its independence, Seelert replied: ``Quite the
contrary. Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi is a brand name to be cultivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Seelert, all of the top advertising executives at
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi have agreed to stay, he and Levy said, including
Kevin Roberts, its chief executive. Seelert will join the
supervisory board of the new Publicis Groupe and Roberts will join
the management board.
</P>
<P>
   By maintaining Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi as an autonomous agency
separate from those Publicis now owns, Levy and Seelert said, they
had assuaged the fears of clients concerned about potential
conflicts that could have scuttled the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin has talked to Procter &AMP; Gamble and Toyota,'' Levy said,
naming two principal clients of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi that compete
against Publicis clients like L'Oreal and Renault, which controls a
Toyota rival, Nissan Motor.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I have spoken personally to the CEOs of L'Oreal and
Renault,'' Levy said, adding that they were ``very supportive and
very enthusiastic and have no problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Less enthusiastic were investors in Paris, who pummeled Publicis
shares almost 12 percent, to 418 euros, or $401. Some advertising
industry analysts said they considered the deal overpriced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I would have preferred to pay a lower price, but I
will never overpay,'' Levy said. ``The price is fair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The price is approximately three times Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
revenue for 2000, which is in line with what Havas paid for Snyder
and what WPP is paying for Y&AMP; R,'' he added. ``And the deal will be
accretive to earnings in the first full year.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicis will pay the equivalent of 500 pence, or $7.56, for
each share of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, a premium of 51 percent to the
closing price on Friday on the London Stock Exchange. After rising
27 percent on Monday as word of the deal circulated among investors
and the advertising industry, shares of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi fell 1.5
pence Tuesday, to 419.5 pence, or $6.30.
</P>
<P>
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, the American
depository receipts of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi fell $1.5625, to $31.50,
after increasing 30 percent on Monday in anticipation of the deal.
In the negotiations, Publicis was advised by Lazard LLC, and
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi was advised by UBS Warburg Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The fine print of the deal is almost as long as that found at
the bottom of an ad promoting a bargain lease on a Renault or
Toyota. Approvals must be obtained from shareholders of Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi and Publicis at two special meetings in August and from a
British court to change corporate rules. Shareholders of Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi are to own 30 percent of the Publicis Groupe, with
shareholders of Publicis getting the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Shares and American depository receipts of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
will cease trading in London and New York and will be replaced by
shares and A.D.R.'s of the Publicis Groupe traded in Paris and New
York. And there will be changes in the direct and indirect
ownership rights to Publicis, controlled by the family of Marcel
Bleustein-Blanchet, the mentor of Levy who founded the agency in
1926, with the creation of 3.4 million to 4.5 million shares of
what will be the Publicis Groupe.
</P>
<P>
   In a twist worthy of an episode of ``Bewitched,'' in which
Samantha's mother plays tricks on her son-in-law's advertising
agency, Levy's relationship with Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi will come in
addition to his relationship with M &AMP; C Saatchi, the London agency
founded by the Saatchi brothers after they stormed out of Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi in 1994 in the wake of a bitter dispute with American
investors and the board there.
</P>
<P>
   When M &AMP; C Saatchi wrested the plum British Airways account from
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, Levy volunteered to handle the assignment in
countries outside of Europe and North America where the Saatchis'
shop had no offices. That alliance will continue between the
Publicis unit of the new Publicis Groupe and M &AMP; C Saatchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called him this morning to share the news,'' Levy said of
Maurice Saatchi, ``and he told me he is very happy to see the
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi name is in a safe home.'' There has been
speculation that Maurice Saatchi has toyed from time to time with
making a bid for Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never met Maurice Saatchi,'' said Seelert, who joined
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi after the brothers departed, ``but I think we've
got radically different people, a Maurice,'' which he pronounced
the French way, MORE-reese, ``as opposed to a Maurice,'' which he
pronounced the British way, MORR-iss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
