<HEADER>
A0195 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f BC-MICROSOFT-SPI &LR;      06-20 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SENDS MICROSOFT CASE TO SUPREME COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In a victory for Microsoft, the federal judge who
ordered Microsoft split apart and subjected to stringent controls
Tuesday halted all sanctions against the company pending appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson also handed a
win to the Justice Department, asking the Supreme Court to hear
Microsoft's antitrust appeal as the government had requested.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said immediate consideration by the Supreme Court is
warranted because two-year-old case's quick resolution ``is of
general public importance in the administration of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, nine days from the end of its term, on
Tuesday afternoon had not decided whether to accept the case or
remand it to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit, which
has eagerly agreed to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   While attorneys said Tuesday's actions increase the odds the
high court will hear the case _ an outcome Microsoft vigorously
opposes _ they also agreed the case has now entered unknown
territory.
</P>
<P>
   No case like this _ where one party is resisting Supreme Court
review, and ``the case'' up for review is actually a combination of
federal and state cases _ has ever arisen before under the
Expediting Act, the obscure law invoked by the government to
justify hastened Supreme Court review.
</P>
<P>
   So no one knows, for example, whether the parties will get a
chance to urge the Supreme Court to take or reject the case,
whether those arguments will be written or oral, when they may take
place, or how many justices must vote to accept the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no established rules on what will happen next.
People are writing on a blank slate,'' said an attorney familiar
with the case who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to Jackson's stay order Tuesday, which halts pending
appeal the judge's June 7 order in the trial, Microsoft legal
consultant Paul Rothstein said the company is ``cautiously
gleeful.''
</P>
<P>
   Slated to go into effect in about 11 weeks unless stayed, ``the
remedies were very onerous,'' Rothstein said. ``They would have
required Microsoft to start drawing up plans for its own
dissolution even while arguing against it.''
</P>
<P>
   They would also have required the disclosure of source code to
competitors and the alteration of contractual relationships with
computer makers and other partners.
</P>
<P>
   The dissolution itself is stayed pending appeal by the order's
own terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big win for Microsoft,'' said Rich Gray, an
intellectual property attorney with Outside General Counsel Silicon
Valley of Menlo Park, Calif. ``Jackson stayed the final order
completely. There was always the chance that whatever court heard
the stay motion could have left some or all of the remedies in
place. You can never predict.''
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust expert Bill Kovacic said Tuesday's stay order ``wins
Microsoft a measure of business freedom I'm sure they're glad to
have, to implement whatever business plans they have in the
pipeline'' pending the stay's expiration.
</P>
<P>
   By its terms, the stay will end when all appeals have been
exhausted, which could be years away, or when it is vacated by an
appellate court. If Microsoft wins, the provisions will never take
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft asked Jackson to stay his order on June 8, the day
after he issued it. But the government urged him not to do so, and
he complied with that urging until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackson desperately wants this case in the Supreme Court, and
staying his order now is his way of putting his thumb on the
scale,'' Gray said. ``This removes an irritant to the Supreme Court
and increases the odds it will keep the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has pushed to have the case heard in the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia, which ruled for the software
maker in an earlier case. The government has steadfastly resisted
that venue.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Jackson's action will let the government argue
the high court's immediate review is essential so Microsoft doesn't
escape sanctions first during appellate court proceedings and then
again during Supreme Court review, Kovacic said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government portrays itself standing on the sidelines
with empty pockets and no remedy after having won a two-year court
battle, it will make the Supreme Court think twice'' about refusing
the case, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's certification of the case to the Supreme Court, done
at the behest of the government, raises numerous questions about
how it should be conducted from this point on.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the two cases certified to the Supreme Court during
the Expediting Act's 26 years, no party opposed the certification,
Rule said. So it's not known how many of the Court's nine justices
must vote to hear a case arising under that law.
</P>
<P>
   The votes of four justices are required to obtain Supreme Court
jurisdiction under an alternative method called certiorari. A
majority vote is required to decide most cases, including those
that arrive ``as of right'' at the Supreme Court _ yet another type
of jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   But ``where the court is skipping a whole level of procedure, it
might require five justices'' to accept a case, suggested Microsoft
consultant Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   Though uncertainties abound, some attorneys said the court will
probably permit briefs by both sides, but not oral arguments. A
source close to Microsoft said the first brief will probably be
filed within 60 days and the response to that within 30 more days.
But, the source asked, ``Who will go first? Traditionally,
appellants lead, but here, the appellant is the one resisting
Supreme Court jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovacic speculated the court could ask for briefs by this fall _
or by as soon as June 30, when it leaves for its three-month summer
recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be highly unconventional, but there have been a lot
of surprises in this case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported Tuesday, without attribution, that
unless the justices expedite their handling of the case _ an action
government lawyers may seek _ Microsoft will have until Aug. 14 to
file an appeal from Jackson's ruling. That appeal would ask the
justices to decline hearing the case. The government then would
have 30 days to respond and explain why they think the case should
be decided directly by the Supreme Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
