<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NJ-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-NY     06-20 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIET TOWN EXPECTS ITS SENATE NOMINEES TO RUN WITH DIGNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  By IVER PETERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUMMIT, N.J. _ The Rev. Charles Rush had his flock gathered
around the communion table recently when he noticed them: Bob
Franks, the Republican nominee for the U.S. Senate, standing only a
few shoulder-widths away from Jon Corzine, the Democratic nominee,
both of them waiting patiently for the bread and wine to be passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just struck me how appropriate that this should happen in a
church,'' said Rush, the pastor of Christ Church here. ``We are all
different, but we are brought together in God's grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether by grace or by happenstance, the two contenders for the
seat being vacated by Sen. Frank Lautenberg are practically
neighbors here on the crest of the Watchung Mountains in central
New Jersey, and both are regarded as local boys. Corzine, the
multimillionaire bond trader and liberal Democrat, lives in the
rich North Side, while Franks, the journeyman moderate who founded
the Summit High School Young Republicans while he was in school,
grew up here and now has a home in a kind of suburb of a suburb at
Berkeley Heights, the next town over.
</P>
<P>
   Their proximity is both a source of local pride and a lesson in
the evolving politics of New Jersey, a state that grows more
suburban by the year and whose politics seem to be following the
people out of old urban traditions into something new.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was the two suburbanites, Corzine and Franks, who
beat the Camden political brawler and former governor, Jim Florio,
and the iron-jawed former Marine, William Gormley, whose campaign
was backed by Atlantic City casinos. And they did it, in part, by
maintaining the kind of amiability that is prized in places like
this, where you don't raise your voice too often.
</P>
<P>
   Summit is a hilltop city of about 20,000 with a high average
family income and level of education. (For every resident with only
a high school diploma, there are three with college or graduate
degrees.)
</P>
<P>
   It is a relatively new place, founded around the turn of the
century as a summer colony for sweltering New Yorkers, and it grew
into a year-round community after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   For all their suburban diffidence and taste, the residents are
too pleased to be neighbors of both candidates to hide their pride.
The Christ Church Web site announces the two contenders' membership
in the church (and describes the congregation as
interdenominational), while neighborliness triumphed over party
loyalty when several local Republicans, including the mayor, Walter
Long, were in the audience when Corzine announced his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local Republicans went completely nuts when they saw I was
there,'' Long said. ``But he's my friend, and I wanted to hear what
he had to say.'' These days, the worst that a Democrat running for
town council says of the Republicans who run the town is that they
lack business sense.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are equally polite. ``I've lived here for 12 years,
and I call it the Disneyland of New Jersey,'' said Dr. Eric Munoz,
a physician and Republican member of the town council. ``It has a
lot of diversity, a lot of different characteristics, urban and
suburban, but it all works together very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The regard for dignified moderation that money and comfortable
living encourage is assumed to be shared by the two candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``In politics, we don't hear a lot about people we can look up
to,'' Rush said. ``We live in the age of the antihero, where
everybody is compromised. And yet here we have Jon and Bob, who
have real integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   As do others here, Rush believes that the boys of Summit are
going to teach the rest of the state some lessons in manners.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to take the high road in this campaign,'' he
said. ``They just aren't negative people. Bob's usual disposition
is to have this huge smile on his face, and Jon's natural
disposition is to reach out and hug someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Corzine played some hardball in his primary battle
with Florio, and political campaigners may not be as fond of
gentlemanly conduct as Rush is.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the harshest Franks has been with his opponent has
been to say that Corzine, who spent approximately $35 million of
his own money in the primary, will also be open-handed with the
taxpayers' money. Corzine is on vacation and has said little in
reply, which may account for Long's easy summer confidence that the
race will be a boon to the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having two men from Summit, N.J., step up to the plate and run
for the U.S. Senate, that can only be good for this town,'' Long
said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's decision to take on the role of politician after a
successful career on Wall Street has also been good for the
Democrats here. As anyone will tell you, Summit is a
business-oriented town, full of bankers and brokers who hop the New
Jersey Transit Midtown Direct to Manhattan on weekday mornings, so
it is a place that respects Corzine's business success. To have one
of its richest and most successful citizens turn out to be a New
Deal Democrat has done wonders for his party here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic Party is blossoming with lots of new people and
new meetings, and it's all because of Jon,'' said Michel Bitritto,
a chemist in private industry. ``We've had meet-and-greets with
Jon, we've made telephone calls. My husband and my daughter and I
stood on the corner to get people to sign his ballot petitions.
He's had a wonderful effect.''
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Bitritto will take a step no Democrat has done in
Summit since the mid-1980s: She will run for town council on the
Democratic line, with Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz is the chairman of the local Republican committee, and he
was politely noncommittal in his assessment of Bitritto's chances
of election. But he conceded that Corzine has helped revive
Democratic fortunes here, and pointed to the results of the June 6
party primary, in which Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas were on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually the Republicans outvote the Democrats by 3 or 4 to
1,'' said Munoz, an assistant dean at the University for Medicine
and Dentistry of New Jersey in Newark. ``But in this primary, it
was Bush 1,255 votes, Gore 1,235. For a city like Summit, with far
more Republicans than Democrats, to have basically as many voters
going for Gore as for Bush really says a lot about Corzine's local
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in the hazy summer, with some schools already closed and
doctors and dentists closing early on Fridays, people like Rush and
Long may believe that the good feelings they have for each
candidate will continue into a quiet, uplifting, issues-oriented
race.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz is not so sure. He said that there is going to be too much
money flying around for tempers to stay calm for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a tradition of very polite politics here,'' Munoz
said, ``but when real contests start, we're not sure how polite we
are anymore. So I'll bet you a dollar that when push comes to shove
and November is getting closer, there are going to be some things
said that are not going to be so nice, not as nice as everything is
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
