<SLUG> BC-EXP-COLO-CONDOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN VAIL, PROPOSING A CHANGE OF VIEW IN THE NAME OF PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ The view from The Lodge at Lionshead is to die
for.
</P>
<P>
   Gore Creek babbles along noisily, just beyond soaring pine trees
that seem to reach halfway up the mountains in the distance. ``You
can even see the ski slopes,'' said Marilyn Dyer, owner of Unit 1
and president of the Lodge homeowners association, who splits the
year between here and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   But not all is as peaceful and serene as it appears outside the
back windows of Dyer's stylish three-bedroom condominium. The
Lodge, which was built in 1978, is smack in the middle of a
proposed major development project that town officials argue is
critical for Vail's continued economic stability. To complete the
most ambitious of several options, town officials want to tear down
the four-level building and move its 12 residents to a nearby site,
where the town would construct a new building for them.
</P>
<P>
   For Vail and many other mountain resort towns in the West, these
are challenging times because of a booming national economy that
keeps them busy year round, with skiers in winter and hikers in
summer. To attract the growing number of families with vacation
money to burn, they are now engaged in a mighty competition, in
which amenities often mean the difference between winning and
losing billions in leisure dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the ``Vail Renaissance,'' an ambitious master plan from
town officials to re-energize the resort, part of which includes
building a second indoor skating rink, a cultural center, a
conference center, office and retail space _ all of it wrapped
around a small lake and open European-style plaza that would serve
as a community gathering place.
</P>
<P>
   And so a band of architects set out to fulfill the town's
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The most lavish option meant tearing down the Lodge at Lionshead
and moving its residents, at no cost to them, elsewhere, a proposal
that has not set well with them.
</P>
<P>
   The residents could force town planners to embrace a less
dramatic vision of the future, with fewer amenities and a more
modest-sized plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Ludwig Kurtz and other officials involved with the
redevelopment plans say that whatever the homeowners decide is fine
and that the town will plan accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be a small level of disappointment that we might
not be able to do as well as we could,'' Kurtz said, contemplating
the possibility that the homeowners would refuse to move. If so, he
promised, they would not be stigmatized as obstructionists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
