<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKAKEL-TRAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESSES AT TRIAL IN '75 MURDER TELL OF SUSPECT'S STATEMENT AT
SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Conn., Maine)  By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ On the first day of public testimony about the
1975 killing of 15-year-old Martha Moxley in Greenwich, two
witnesses told a judge here Tuesday that Michael C. Skakel, a
nephew of Ethel Kennedy, confessed to the killing in the late 1970s
while he was attending a school for troubled youths in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The witnesses were both former classmates of Skakel's at the
Elan School in Poland Spring, Maine. One of them, John D. Higgins,
described a confused and tearful admission in which Skakel said he
had only fragmented memories of the crime. The other witness,
Gregory Coleman, said Skakel brazenly told him: ``I am going to get
away with murder. I am a Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Skakel, now 39, is charged with murder as a juvenile because he
was 15 at the time Moxley, his next-door neighbor, was found
bludgeoned to death under a pine tree in her family's yard.
Tuesday's testimony came on the first day of a ``reasonable cause''
hearing in which Judge Maureen Dennis will decide whether Skakel
should face a jury trial as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a crucial determination. If convicted in state
Superior Court as an adult, Skakel would face a sentence of 25
years to life in prison. If convicted as a juvenile, he could spend
little or no time in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The stress of the day showed. As Skakel left the courtroom for
the lunch recess, he broke down in sobs, his eyes streaked red as a
bodyguard led him to his car waiting outside.
</P>
<P>
   The tears were surprising, considering that just before the
recess, Skakel's lawyer, Michael Sherman, had skillfully set about
undermining the credibility of Higgins, the first witness to say he
had heard Skakel confess. Under cross-examination, Higgins admitted
that he had repeatedly lied to investigators and that his interest
in the Moxley case had been renewed only after he learned of a
large reward for information in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a trial, Tuesday's proceeding lacked the dramatic opening
statements from opposing lawyers eager to persuade a jury. Instead,
the prosecutor, Jonathan C. Benedict, simply called his first
witness, Sheila Maguire, a neighbor and friend of Moxley's who
discovered her body on Oct. 31, 1975. Then he introduced a
Greenwich map as the first exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was the sense of a momentous event. After a
quarter-century, the details of this sensational case, chronicled
in numerous best-selling books of varied credibility, were finally
being disclosed under oath in a court. Dorthy Moxley, Martha's
mother, sat in the front row of the packed, tiny courtroom. Dozens
of television crews lined the street outside.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict's second witness was Thomas G. Keegan, the former chief
of the Greenwich Police Department, who described how investigators
found three pieces of a golf club on the Moxley property that they
determined to be the murder weapon. The club, a 6-iron, was later
found to belong to a set owned by Rushton Skakel, the father of the
defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, the former chief was quickly asked by
Sherman about criticism of his department for ``botching'' the
Moxley case. Keegan testified that golf clubs, according to reports
of witnesses, were routinely left in the Skakel yard, but he
immediately rejected the implication that someone had come along,
picked up a club and killed the girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theory was that some transient came through the yard and
bludgeoned the girl,'' he said. ``That doesn't hold water.'' The
former chief testified that the handle portion of the golf club,
which had the name Skakel on it, was never found. ``My conclusion
is that the person who killed Martha was aware that name was on the
club,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sherman seemed to win a final point. ``In the course of your
investigation, did you find any evidence that Michael Skakel killed
Martha Moxley?'' he demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir,'' the former chief replied.
</P>
<P>
   And though the prosecution introduced into evidence the
eight-page autopsy report and called another former Greenwich
detective to the stand, the bulk of the day's testimony focused on
the two former classmates from the Elan School who told the judge
that they had heard the defendant confess.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins said that he and Skakel had been working as ``night
owls,'' making sure other students did not run away, and were
sitting on the porch of a dormitory building when Skakel described
his role in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He related to me that he had been involved in the murder of
someone or thought that he had been,'' Higgins testified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
