<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PARK-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 MEN INDICTED FOR CENTRAL PARK ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Manhattan grand jury Tuesday indicted five young
men on charges of rioting and sexually assaulting women in the June
11 melee in Central Park after the National Puerto Rican Day
Parade.
</P>
<P>
   None have posted bail, and remain in police custody.
</P>
<P>
   But a sixth man who was arrested last week, John Taylor, 24, was
not indicted, and the judge waived his $30,000 bail. Taylor was
released, pending further investigation by the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The men appeared in Manhattan Criminal Court in wrinkled
T-shirts and baggy jeans, and all but one seemed largely subdued
after a week spent in the eye of a public storm. They had been
arrested after police offered rewards and released their
photographs, taken from amateur videotapes of the incident. So far,
53 women have reported being attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Vargas, 18, who the police have said was an instigator
and was identified by at least five of the victims as having
participated in the attacks, grinned as he entered the courtroom of
Judge Cynthia Kern and thrust his fist in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The assistant district attorney, Maxine Rosenthal, announced
that the grand jury had indicted Vargas, Stephen Burt, 31, Emanuel
Nunez, 18, Roberto Camacho, 16, and Jensen Soto, 16. Soto did not
appear in court.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal said another man arrested in the attack and still in
custody, Isaias Lozano, 20, of Queens, was not indicted Tuesday but
would remain in jail pending further investigation by the grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor, who runs a barber shop near Rockaway Beach in
Queens, was released.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who has said he was involved in a water fight after the
parade but not in any of the attacks on women, told reporters that
one of the worst moments for him was when his picture was released.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about all the kids who saw it on TV and all the kids
in the community,'' he said. ``I want to clear my name, that's
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday morning, another suspect, Dellon Evans, 17, was
arraigned in Manhattan Criminal Court. The police, who said Evans
corralled women into the hands of their attackers, charged him with
rioting and sexual abuse. Judge Carol Edmead admonished him for
``encouraging an outrageous act against women,'' and set bail at
$50,000. His case will now go before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, Evans' lawyer, Mitchell Schuman,
denounced the amount of the bail, saying it was ``a human sacrifice
at the altar of public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the police also announced two more arrests bringing
the total to 20. Prosecutors said they expected the others in
custody to be indicted within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they had 22 other suspects _ based on witness
accounts and the videotapes _ who had not yet been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday night, Alexander Eraide, 23, of 123-48 135th Street
in Queens, surrendered at the 13th Precinct in Manhattan and was
charged with sexual abuse and rioting, police said, after he was
identified from a photograph. The police said that Eraide, along
with four men who have not yet been identified, touched a victim on
the buttocks.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-year-old boy, whose name and address have been withheld
because he is a juvenile, surrendered with his lawyer and was
charged with sexual abuse and rioting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no picture or video of him,'' said detective George
Nagy, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Police Commissioner Howard Safir said that the
police were searching for 22 other men.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said the suspects generally did not know each other. ``It
is a very diverse group. They are from every borough, from other
states.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, a Police Department spokeswoman, said the police
had obtained a new videotape of the assaults, were extracting
photographs from it and expected to release four more pictures
Wednesday, hoping the public will help to identify the men.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
