<HEADER>
A0228 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-SOC-KOROL-BURN-TEX     06-20 1780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-KOROL-BURN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS BURN PLAYER FINDS A NEW LIFE IN MLS 
HEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the 14-year-old Ukrainian boy sat in New York's Kennedy
International Airport, waiting for his new life to begin, his
dreams seemed like a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Aleksey Korol sat alone in the bustling airport, the
incomprehensible buzz of English all around him, about to board a
plane to live with strangers in a strange land.
</P>
<P>
   His head was filled with thoughts of the family he left
thousands of miles behind _ his father, who works odd jobs to help
make ends meet, and his mother who earns the equivalent of $250 a
month working as a secretary for a sports organization. Both suffer
from cancer and other effects that linger from the nuclear reactor
accident at Chernobyl, about 120 miles from Korol's hometown of
Belaya Tserkov in Ukraine. He couldn't escape those thoughts, of
his mother taking pills to keep leukemia in check, of his father's
treatments for stomach cancer.
</P>
<P>
   His mind also wandered to his friends, with whom he once played
soccer, some of whom have abandoned their hopes of playing
professionally and now live on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Korol would board a plane in New York to live with virtual
strangers in a strange land, leaving behind the unrest of life in
the former Soviet Union for the chance of a brighter future in the
United States. For Korol, soccer was his escape.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years later, Korol's dream is reality. He graduated from
high school in the United States and attended Indiana University,
where he was a three-time All-Big Ten selection. Korol was the
fifth pick in the MLS Draft last year. The Burn wanted him enough
to trade popular forward Dante Washington to get him. Korol, also a
forward, has scored two goals and added two assists in his only two
starts with the Burn.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly halfway through his first season in MLS, Korol fits right
into the friendly banter of the Burn's locker room. He chats
effortlessly with reporters, signs autographs with a smile and
looks every part a professional soccer player at 22 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Not many of his teammates are aware of what it took for him to
get there.
Life left behind As a rookie, Korol's professional career is
waiting to unfold, with goals to be scored, assists to be recorded,
playoffs to be reached. But in life, he is an established veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Korol can't remember his life without soccer. His father, Yuri,
played professionally before a knee injury cut short his career.
But Yuri had visions of his son following in his footsteps, said
Aleksey's mother, Tatiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aleksey was born ... to carry the torch for his father,''
Tatiana said through a translator. ``Before he was born, \RYuri\S
was very excited about that because then there was somebody to
continue his path.''
</P>
<P>
   Yuri got his wish. His son began training at age 6 and later
attended the prestigious Dynamo Kiev soccer institution, which
prepares athletes for the Olympics and professional careers, when
he was 12. He lived at the institution, which was about 70 miles
from his hometown on the outskirts of Kiev. Belaya Tserkov means
``white church,'' for the only building left standing after a fire
swept through the town, destroying everything but the church.
</P>
<P>
   As was the norm for amateur athletes in the Soviet Union,
Korol's chances of a solid financial future rested on goals, not
grades, at Dynamo's institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just didn't concentrate on being a student,'' Korol said.
``You were a soccer player first. At times, you had to go to
training and miss two or three weeks of school. And then you'd go
back and talk to the teacher, and they would just take care of it
for you. As long as you were doing OK as a soccer player, that was
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Korol lived at the academy and traveled home about every other
weekend, playing with Dynamo in tournaments around the world. In
1991, Korol visited the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The trip itself _ Dynamo Kiev played several exhibition and
friendly matches in Rochester, N.Y. _ was nothing out of the
ordinary. It was the return home that marked an overhaul of Korol's
life.
</P>
<P>
   Korol and his teammates returned to find their native country in
upheaval. During their stay in America, the political foundation of
the Soviet Union had begun to crumble, leaving the country in
widespread chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came back, everything had changed,'' Korol said.
``There was so much corruption, and violence and destruction. My
American family wanted me to come and stay with them and experience
this life.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family thought it would be the best thing for me to come
here and get an education, and experience a normal life. There, it
was only soccer. Here I have a chance to play soccer and have an
education.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Korol returned to Rochester, after an invitation from his
American host family, the Chiricos. Korol's stay with the Chiricos
during a tournament was short, only three weeks. But it was enough
time for him to taste a better life.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RWe\S thought it would change for the better, but we realized
it would take a long time, and it would maybe take a whole
generation \Rfor things to change in the Ukraine\S, and the safest
thing was for me to take this opportunity and make a new life for
myself,'' Korol said.
Time to adjust The new life Korol envisioned didn't come right
away. He points to that long layover in Kennedy International as
one of the bleakest moments since his return to America in 1993.
The devastating homesickness lingered for several months, broken up
by occasional phone calls back home that flooded Korol with
reflection and, sometimes, regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I talked to my parents, I was thinking that I
wanted to go back,'' he said. ``But for some reason, I knew in the
long run that it was going to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Korol first had to adjust to the American lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   In Ukraine, clothes shopping meant buying one or two new shirts
every two or three years. Food for meals came from the market and
from the Korols' land, which yielded plenty of potatoes, apples and
strawberries to freeze for the winter. He traveled to and from the
soccer institution alone, and rarely played in front of his family.
</P>
<P>
   With the Chiricos, Korol lived in a four-bedroom house with
three soccer-playing boys near his age. Back home Korol lived in a
two-bedroom apartment with six others, and a worn-down car was
shared between four adults. The Chiricos had four cars, meaning
there was always an available ride _ not on a train or a bus _ to
and from soccer practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiricos' day-to-day routine _ going to soccer practice,
picking up groceries, shopping _ was in stark contrast to the life
Korol knew back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grocery store was a big thing for him just because they
don't have the selection,'' Nancy Chirico said.
</P>
<P>
   High school was also a big adjustment. Korol was expected to
graduate with his classmates in four years at Livonia High School _
even though he didn't know how to form a sentence in English when
he arrived as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Individual lessons with an English teacher began to pay off.
Korol said he rediscovered himself through the language. Instead of
smiling and laughing in response to words he didn't understand, he
could reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I started learning English, my life changed,''
Korol said. ``I could communicate and be my own person. For the
first few months, nobody knew who I was. I was just a face and a
smile, but nobody knew who I was until I opened my mouth. And now
it's hard to shut it sometimes.''
Bridging gaps As Korol was forging bonds with the new people in his
life, the Chiricos and Korols were beginning to form a powerful
bond through him.
</P>
<P>
   Surrendering her son to a family she had never met, thousands of
miles away, to live indefinitely was the hardest decision, Tatiana
said, she has ever made. Her first trip to the United States in the
summer of 1995 helped allay some of her fears.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Tatiana was overwhelmed by the American middle-class
lifestyle, which is lavish by Ukrainian standards. She cried upon
seeing the rows and rows of food in the supermarket. She was also
overwhelmed with relief upon meeting the Chiricos and seeing how
her son was welcomed into their household.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I came to the United States, all my worries
disappeared,'' said Tatiana, whose husband hasn't visited the
United States. ``Once I saw the attitude of Nancy and the boys, and
how they treated him, all my worries were gone. When I came back
over the second time, I was going with the feeling that I was
visiting relatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy said she felt the same way. On Tatiana's second trip, in
1998, Nancy arranged for her to see a doctor on a volunteer visit,
to make sure the initial diagnosis of her leukemia by doctors in
Ukraine was correct. Since then, Tatiana has made another trip to
the United States for treatment _ something that wouldn't have
happened if not for her son. Tatiana and Nancy correspond on a
regular basis, conversing through one of Nancy's friends who is
from Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling of family goes back to the first time Aleksey walked
through the Chiricos' door, Nancy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the kids are concerned, there are four children in
this family,'' she said. ``Each of them will say they have three
brothers. When we made the decision to bring Aleksey here, we said
he can't come as a guest. He can't just stay. He has to be a part
of this family, and he has to be a son to us as much as we have to
be parents to him. I don't think anybody in this family has ever
regretted it, and I don't think Aleksey has either.''
</P>
<P>
   Korol has returned home to Ukraine twice. The most recent trip
was last summer, when he and his girlfriend, Erin Heimann, visited
for three weeks. Now that he's making his own money, Korol talks to
his family on the phone every several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Korol doesn't know when, or if, he'll apply for American
citizenship. For now, he's satisfied with a work visa through MLS,
where he has begun what appears to be a bright career. He has
scored two goals in his two starts with the Burn, who play tonight
at first-place Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   His responsibilities as a professional player take up plenty of
time, but Korol continues to reflect often about his family. He
dreams of saving enough money to bring his mother and father to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Korol still has soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my wildest dreams I had no idea he would ever be living in
the United States,'' Tatiana said. ``I wish him the most out of it.
I'm very eased that he is living the dream we can only dream
about.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
