<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON CALLS FOR MEASURES TO GUARD PRIVACY OF PERSONAL
RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE GEORGE, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton asserted Tuesday that
businesses and medical institutions were threatening personal
privacy by routinely collecting financial and medical records, and
she urged Congress to give consumers control over how such
information is used.
</P>
<P>
   And in a speech on privacy to broadcast executives, Clinton, the
Democratic candidate for U.S. Senate, scolded some New York City
television stations for broadcasting videotapes of groups of men
sexually assaulting women in Central Park nine days ago without
obscuring the women's faces. Some television stations, as well as
most newspapers that reproduced still photographs from the videos,
obscured the faces of the victims, as is customary in most sexual
crime cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could not be a more dramatic example of the importance
of privacy than those images,'' the first lady told the New York
State Broadcasters Association. ``I believe it was wrong to show
the faces of the women being assaulted without getting their
permission. You can report the news without adding to the trauma of
those already victimized.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, noting First Amendment restrictions on regulating the
press, said she was not proposing legal measures to prevent the
media from showing the faces of victims in such cases.
</P>
<P>
   She did call on Congress, however, to enact legislation that
would give consumers and patients control over health care and
financial records, which she argued are becoming increasingly
available because of computer databases and transmission of
information through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individuals should have the right to choose whether and to
whom their personal financial and medical information is
disclosed,'' Clinton said. ``They should have the right to know
how, when and how much of that information is being used. And they
should have the right to see it for themselves to know if it is
accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   With her remarks Tuesday, Clinton introduced in her race against
Rep. Rick Lazio, a Republican from Long Island, an issue that has
gained increasing notice in campaigns across the nation this year.
Clinton's assistants asserted Tuesday that personal privacy had
long been a concern of the first lady, and Clinton said she would
make ``the protection of citizen privacy in the information age a
top priority'' if she were elected to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, through a spokesman, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Clinton offered her support for a variety of
measures proposed in Congress, which has shown increasing interest
in this issue.
</P>
<P>
   On medical records, Clinton urged Congress to adopt legislation
that would require the consent of patients before records could be
released by employers, health care institutions or insurers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to restore trust in the health care system, all
Americans need to have confidence that their medical tests will be
used to heal them, not deny them privacy, jobs or health
coverage,'' Clinton said. ``What good are the best genetic tests
and treatments in the world if people are too scared to use them?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said businesses should be barred from distributing
or selling information about the credit history, payment schedule,
account balances and personal spending habits of consumers without
obtaining their specific permission in advance.
</P>
<P>
   In making her argument, Clinton made fleeting reference to her
own adjustment to public life. ``Now I know when you enter public
life you give up a lot of your privacy. Believe me, I know that all
too well,'' she said. ``But you shouldn't give up your privacy when
you visit your doctor, take a trip to the video store, or buy a
book on the Internet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
