<SLUG> BC-BLUECROSS-RULING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE CROSS DOES HAVE RESPONSIBILITY TO THE PUBLIC, APPEALS COURT
RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas City is
a public benefit corporation and cannot engage in activities that
jeopardize that status, the Missouri Court of Appeals in Kansas
City ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After examining the purpose for which Blue Cross and Blue
Shield of Kansas City was originally organized, we determined that
it has a public purpose,'' the court said in its opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is the latest development in a years-long series of
court and legislative battles over the nature of Blue Cross plans
in a rapidly changing health insurance landscape.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1997 lawsuit against Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon,
Blue Cross asked the Cole County Circuit Court in Jefferson City to
declare Blue Cross a nonprofit mutual benefit corporation that was
formed to serve the interests of its members, not the public at
large.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross, the largest health insurer in the Kansas City area,
filed its lawsuit after Missouri questioned the legality of a
failed attempt to merge with Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas,
which is based in Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1998, Cole County Circuit Judge Thomas Brown ruled
that Blue Cross was a public benefit corporation and must act
accordingly. In essence, the judge ruled that Blue Cross could not
do anything _ a merger or whatever _ that would prevent it from
fulfilling its mission to serve the public good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed in the court's decision,'' Blue Cross
spokeswoman Jean Peat said Tuesday. ``However, we have not yet had
the chance to review the decision in detail. We will want to
carefully assess our options as we move forward, and this issue is
only one of a number of factors Blue Cross and Blue Shield of
Kansas City considers in its overall strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Peat said it was ``important to note that this decision in no
way affects Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas City's ability to
serve our current and future members.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said in a release that the appeals court ruling ``affirms
the law that prevents nonprofit assets that belong to the public
from being converted to for-profit uses not benefiting the general
public. The courts again have clearly stated that charitable
nonprofits must fulfill their obligation to use their assets to
benefit the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Farr Fitch, chairwoman of the St. Louis-based Missouri
Consumer Health Care Watch Coalition, said she was pleased with
Tuesday's ruling. ``These types of decisions benefit all
consumers,'' Fitch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
