r f BC-HEALTHCARE-INDICT-KAN     06-20 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-INDICT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR FIRMS, 11 INDIVIDUALS INDICTED IN HEALTH-CARE FRAUD CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES and JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Continuing its crackdown on fraud in Medicare
and Medicaid programs, the U.S. attorney's office in Kansas City
reported Tuesday that a federal grand jury in Springfield had
indicted four southern Missouri health-care companies and 11
individuals on kickback and false-claims charges.
</P>
<P>
   The individuals include Robert C. LaHue, 59, who was convicted
by a federal jury in April 1999 of soliciting and receiving
kickbacks in exchange for referring patients to Baptist Medical
Center and other hospitals. LaHue, an osteopathic physician who
owned the now-defunct Blue Valley Medical Group, was sentenced to
70 months in prison but is free while he appeals his conviction.
</P>
<P>
   LaHue declined to comment Tuesday, as did his attorney, Bruce
Houdek.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment, which represents a formal accusation by the
government, comes amid a years-long government crusade against
health-care fraud. The General Accounting Office estimates that
dollars lost to such fraud amount to 3 percent to 10 percent of
total health care expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that estimate, between $6.2 billion and $20.8 billion
was lost to Medicare fraud in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quantifying how much money is lost to fraud is difficult
because of the very nature of fraud itself,'' said Alwyn Cassil, a
spokeswoman with the inspector general's office of the U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services. ``You don't know about it
unless you detect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many hospital and physician groups counter that honest mistakes,
resulting from the maze of Medicare and Medicaid regulations, are
often criminalized by prosecutors. Medicare is the federal health
program for the elderly and disabled; Medicaid is the federal-state
health program for the indigent.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-count indictment was returned under seal on June 15 and
unsealed Tuesday at the initial court appearance of one of the
defendants. Except for LaHue, who lives in Stilwell in Johnson
County, Kan., none of the individual defendants lives in the
metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment alleges that the owners and operators of
residential care facilities in Lamar and Joplin directed patients
from the facilities to LaHue and three other doctors. The doctors
then allegedly falsely certified that the patients were homebound
and in need of home health services.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say the arrangement enabled the doctors to bill
Medicare and Medicaid for patient visits and enabled the
residential facilities to bill Medicare and Medicaid for home
health services. Altogether, the allegedly false claims resulted in
overpayments of more than $1 million, according to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also charges that the owners and managers of the
facilities offered discounts and other incentives to local
residential care homes in return for access to their patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The allegation is that the residential care operators steered
patients to the doctors so they would make fraudulent
certifications that they were homebound, which made them eligible
for Medicare and Medicaid,'' said Chris Whitley, a spokesman for
the U.S. attorney's office in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Named in the indictment are Sterling Home Health Care Inc. in
Lamar, doing business as Regal Home Health Care, which is charged
with four counts of conspiracy to defraud the government and two
counts of paying illegal kickbacks; La-Du's Home Health Care Inc.
in Joplin, which is charged with two counts of conspiracy to
defraud the government and two counts of paying illegal kickbacks;
Sandhill Inc. in Lamar, which is charged with four counts of
conspiracy to defraud the government; and A to Z Billing Services
Inc. in Joplin, which is charged with one count of conspiracy to
defraud the government.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling, La-Du's, Sandhill and A to Z were variously owned or
controlled by Robert Joseph Dupont Jr. of Oronogo and Karl Otis
Householder of Milo, according to the indictment. Dupont, 55, and
Householder, 62, are charged with conspiracy, making false
applications for Medicaid benefits, filing false Medicare cost
reports, failing to file Medicare cost reports and paying illegal
kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Besides LaHue, the indictment names physicians Jan Dierks
Garwood, 51, of Nixa; David Ray Trobaugh, 52, of Carthage; and
Rafael Augusto Calabria, 60, of Mooresboro, N.C. Other defendants
include two registered nurses, one licensed practical nurse and
Dupont's daughter, Kelley Anne Liveoak, 37, of Webb City.
</P>
<P>
   Through health-care anti-fraud actions, the federal government
collected $490 million last year in civil, criminal and
administrative penalties, according to Cassil of the Department of
Health and Human Services. That contrasts with 1997, when about
$1.1 billion was collected, and 1998, when about $300 million was
collected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ebbs and flows,'' Cassil said. ``A lot of it depends on
when the case is actually settled.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest health-care fraud settlement ever was reached in
January, when a Boston-based kidney dialysis provider paid $486
million to settle civil and criminal allegations of health-care
fraud, Cassil said.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, HCA, formerly known as Columbia//HCA Healthcare
Corp., reached a $745 million tentative settlement with the U.S.
Justice Department over fraud allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000620.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0235 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-STROKE-CARE-KAN &LR;      06-20 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STROKE-CARE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY HOSPITALS REPORTEDLY FAIL TO PROVIDE STROKE PATIENTS PROPER
CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ On Memorial Day morning three years ago, Earl
Munger was jogging through his Gladstone neighborhood when he was
felled by a stroke. He lay by the road, paralyzed on his right side
and unable to speak.
</P>
<P>
   But Munger, 65, counts himself as lucky.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor found him and immediately called an ambulance. Munger
was taken to North Kansas City Hospital, where doctors gave him the
clot-busting drug tPA.
</P>
<P>
   Within a couple of hours, Munger could speak and his paralysis
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was virtually back to normal,'' Munger said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of state-of-the-art care all stroke patients
should receive, but many patients don't, a national group of
medical organizations called the Brain Attack Coalition said
Tuesday at a news teleconference in Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The failure by hospitals to provide that care leaves thousands
of stroke patients needlessly disabled and costs millions of
dollars for their rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition, which includes the American Heart Association,
the American Academy of Neurology and other health and professional
groups, called for specially staffed and equipped stroke centers at
hospitals across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The stroke centers would operate the way trauma centers do now
to provide rapid, expert attention for a medical emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Stroke centers should be open 24 hours, be able to begin
evaluating stroke patients within five minutes of their arrival,
conduct brain scans to determine the type of stroke and provide tPA
if appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   One study found that stroke centers reduced the odds of death or
serious disability by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the coalition's proposal were published today
(Wednesday) in the Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a long way from the ideal,'' said Marc Mayberg of the
Cleveland Clinic Foundation and a co-author of the article.
``Patients aren't getting to the emergency room in time. When they
do...they're not getting optimal care.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons range from limited hospital staffing that makes it
difficult to assess patients to physician concerns about
complications from tPA, which stands for tissue-type plasminogen
activator.
</P>
<P>
   About 600,000 people in the United States suffer strokes every
year. Stroke is the third-greatest killer in the United States and
one of the leading causes of disability.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent survey of hospitals found that 66 percent lacked
standard treatment plans for stroke and 82 percent did not rapidly
identify patients who were experiencing strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Another study found that only 2 to 3 percent of stroke patients
received tPA.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors now call strokes ``brain attacks'' to highlight their
similarity to heart attacks. In both cases, the blood supply is
disrupted, causing tissue damage.
</P>
<P>
   Some strokes are caused by burst blood vessels in the brain. But
most are due to blood clots that block vessels.
</P>
<P>
   If given intravenously within three hours of a stroke caused by
a blood clot, tPA can in many cases dissolve the clot and minimize
injury to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of stroke care the Brain Attack Coalition envisions is
available at a relatively small number of hospitals nationwide,
mostly those associated with medical schools, said Mark Alberts, a
Duke University physician and lead author of the journal article.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to move to the next step to include community,
urban and rural hospitals. The number could be increased to at
least several hundred and maybe even a thousand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City area has a number of hospitals that are
well-equipped to handle stroke, doctors say. But good stroke care
remains ``very spotty'' from hospital to hospital, said Marilyn
Rymer, a neurologist and director of the stroke center at St.
Luke's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where you land can determine the whole outcome, whether or not
you end up disabled,'' she said. ``That's the case locally and
nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Rymer is co-chairwoman of a stroke task force of the Greater
Kansas City Division of the American Heart Association that is
working to educate hospitals, health care professionals and the
public about the need to recognize stroke symptoms and seek prompt
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Local ambulance services are doing a good job getting stroke
patients to hospitals quickly, Rymer said, and patients appear to
be more knowledgeable about stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City is certainly as sophisticated as any place in the
country as far as the early recognition and treatment of stroke
victims,'' said Joseph Waeckerle, co-chairman of the Heart
Association task force and director of emergency medicine for three
Health Midwest hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Rymer recommended that people concerned about getting good
stroke care ask their doctors which hospitals they would recommend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do your homework. Know your hospitals,'' she said. ``Find out
ahead of time who is going to be able to treat you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
