<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0238 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DEBBIE-DISAPPEARANCE-     06-20 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBBIE-DISAPPEARANCE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDHOOD FRIENDSHIP DISAPPEARED IN CASE OF MISSING WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FULLERTON, Calif. _ Between her thumb and fingers Suzanne
Lawrence absent-mindedly rubs a tear-drop-shaped crystal _ Debbie
Faith's good luck charm.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne has kept it wrapped in a black velvet bag for the last
seven years, except for once when her little sister, Sarah, took it
to show-and-tell. Sarah dropped it, and now a corner is chipped.
But it still shimmers in the light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debbie gave this to me so she'd have a reason to come back,''
said Suzanne. She sighed and pushed back a wisp of blond hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't work, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Faith and her mother, Sheila, disappeared six years ago. Last
week, authorities linked the Faiths with John E. Robinson Sr., an
Olathe, Kan., man who is charged in five deaths and being
questioned in the disappearance of six other persons.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie's story, it might seem, is a tragic one, because her life
could be viewed as one long list of misfortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosed with cerebral palsy, she needed a motorized-wheelchair
to move her body. Her dad died before she reached her teens. The
family needed food stamps. Her mom became lonely and began using
personal ads to meet men, usually the wrong men, friends
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   But Debbie shunned victimhood. She owned a free-wheeling giggle
that would make others laugh. She made deep friendships. She had
hopes for the future, even dreamed of walking.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, her mother began moving, drawn first from Orange County
in Southern California to Northern California, then to Colorado by
her own hopes _ of romance. The next year, Debbie called to alert
Suzanne of another move, this time to Kansas. Sheila had connected
with a nice man named ``John,'' who even promised to help Debbie
ride one of his horses, Suzanne said.
</P>
<P>
   And for six years, Suzanne has prayed and cried and wondered,
hoping she'd see Debbie again.
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, she saw her friend's smiling face once more _
when it flashed across the TV news.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne's family, gathered in their living room, told stories
about Debbie.
</P>
<P>
   ``So funny...She was always so polite to adults...You forgot she
was in a wheelchair because she was so outgoing...Do you remember
when she started those water fights at the park?...''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne chimed in with her own ``remember when'' stories,
spilling them out like disconnected dots on a bingo board. She
grinned as she talked; she likes remembering Debbie. She's glad
that other people care to know, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was more like my sister, than just a girl friend,'' she
said, then her face fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``...We talked all the time. Something terrible, horrible has
happened to her. I know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne first met Debbie Faith in choir practice at the Nicolas
Junior High School choir in Fullerton in 1991. That summer, Debbie
and Sheila buried John Faith's ashes under a pier on Huntington
Beach. Debbie cried then. She used to love the beach, she told her
mom. No more. Now the beach would forever make her sad.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie had spent most of her life in a wheelchair. On both her
arms were braces. She could move one hand just enough to push the
buttons on her wheelchair. She needed a catheter. She was too heavy
for Sheila, who used a hoist to move Debbie into bed at night.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie, then 12, also sang. She loved Neil Diamond songs. She
was a soprano. Not a very good one, according to her choir teacher,
but she loved trying.
</P>
<P>
   On that autumn day that they met in choir practice, Suzanne,
then 11, was assigned to be Debbie's singing helper. By the end of
the hour, the seventh-grade girls became best buddies.
</P>
<P>
   For the next two years they were inseparable: walking and
wheeling the few blocks from their homes to the mall after school;
eating strawberry ice cream in root beer floats; telling stories
during sleep-overs in Debbie's apartment, or just picking up bread
at the grocery. Sometimes the bread was squished, said Suzanne,
smiling again. ``We'd eat it before Sheila found out, to destroy
the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie liked to be silly, to make Suzanne _ or ``Sissy'' as she
called her _ laugh. If Debbie saw an elderly man at the mall or
someone else in a wheelchair, she raced them, giggling and zipping
away with her electric motor whining at top speed.
</P>
<P>
   As teens, Suzanne and Debbie talked about crushes on their choir
teacher, wrote fan letters to soap opera stars, called psychic hot
lines to foretell their futures. One psychic told Debbie she would
walk.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie wanted to go on to become a counselor to the deaf and
blind. Suzanne wanted to be a physical education teacher for the
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1993,... MORE
</P>
<P>
   FULLERTON, Calif. _ ...teacher for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1993, two weeks after graduation from junior high,
Debbie and her mother, Sheila, moved away to Santa Cruz in Northern
California. Two boyfriends were in her mother's life, but both were
married. Debbie didn't like that at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we really didn't like the one man named Jim Fox,''
recalled Suzanne. ``He came over once a week to their apartment,
sometimes twice a week.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sheila knew Fox was going to visit, she'd give the girls
money and hurry them out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a nice man to young girls,'' she told Suzanne when
she asked why. Once, Jim Fox arrived unannounced. He took a look at
Suzanne and told her she had nice legs and a nice rear end, using
adult words. That night she told her mother, Debbie Lawrence, about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't worried because I knew that Sheila was watching out
for both girls,'' said Debbie Lawrence. ``Sheila seemed like an
excellent mother to me. I trusted her.''
</P>
<P>
   Months later, Suzanne's parents read a story in the newspaper
about an investigation on Fox, a foster parent accused of molesting
teen-age girls. He died before police completed their
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheila Faith's new boyfriend in Santa Cruz turned out to be
a loser, too, says Suzanne. ``Debbie told me he was crazy and that
they were going to move to Colorado because they had some friends
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The friends were the Guerreros, whom they met in California.
Melissa Guerrero, who also uses a wheelchair, had known Debbie
since the second grade.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Guerrero drove the Faiths from Santa Cruz to Colorado in
their 1978 Chevrolet white van. The van quit three times before it
made it to Pueblo.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of living was better in Colorado, but there was one
more reason for the move. Sheila had answered another ad for a
boyfriend prospect in Pueblo.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the distance, Debbie and Suzanne were determined
to stay friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was my sister, and I was hers,'' said Suzanne.
</P>
<P>
   The Lawrence family tightened their budget to allow for
Suzanne's large phone bills. The Faiths, who lived on Debbie's
disability checks, couldn't afford them.
</P>
<P>
   The girls' favorite time to talk was during ``American
Gladiator.'' They could watch it together, teasing each other about
the body of each others' favorite sports warrior. Suzanne liked
``Turbo.'' Debbie liked ``Tower.''
</P>
<P>
   And once, after writing a zillion fan letters, said Suzanne, a
star from ``All My Children'' called her friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debbie was almost hysterical. I had to hold the phone away
from my ear she was so loud,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another time Debbie called to say that doctors in Colorado told
her she didn't have cerebral palsy after all, but spina bifida. And
they told her that maybe, just maybe, she'd walk again, with lots
of physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The phone calls continued. They spent New Year's Eve talking to
each other and counting down the seconds despite the time zone
difference. She remembers even more clearly the talk they had a few
days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving to Kansas,'' Debbie announced to Suzanne. ``Mom
met a guy named John from the newspaper. He has a farm in Kansas
and horses and he said he was going to help me get on one and he
said you could come and visit us whenever you wanted too. Isn't
that great?''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne was silent.
</P>
<P>
   Her stomach had flopped, thinking about her friend moving even
farther away. And the news of yet another boyfriend for Debbie's
mother just didn't feel right, she said now. It wasn't fair that
Debbie would have to move again and start over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have to go?'' Suzanne finally asked Debbie. ``I mean,
you're so happy in Colorado, why move?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Sissy, Mom's so lonely. If this will make her happy,
we're gonna go for it,'' Suzanne recalled her friend saying.
``Besides, Mom talked with John a long time. He's really nice. I'll
call you when we get there. Don't worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie never made that call. She and her mother dropped out of
sight immediately after leaving Pueblo.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of a commercial mail center in Olathe reported that a
man matching the description of Robinson and using one of his
aliases was picking up the Faith checks, forwarded from Pueblo for
years. Robinson has not been charged in connection with the Faiths.
</P>
<P>
   Best friends know things in their heart of hearts about each
other. Suzanne keeps a ray of optimism. Just like light through a
chipped crystal.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne will be 21 next month. She only has one wish for her
birthday:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know what happened to my friend. My wish is to find
Sheila and Debbie alive.''
</P>
<P>
   And she wrapped the black velvet around the teardrop of glass
and put it away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
