<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LESSON IN GOVERNMENT INEFFICIENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSION, Kan. _ If you want to observe a good working argument
for why many government activities should be turned over to the
private sector, visit the Johnson County motor vehicle office in
Mission.
</P>
<P>
   My nightmare occurred last week because the usual easy-as-pie,
do-everything-by-mail routine was superseded by the need to get a
lien removed from the family flivver's title. This is usually a
happy time, because it signals the beginning of a wonderful life
without car-loan payments.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the price paid in aggravation to get to this
state of bliss was high. The task of renewing tags, paying property
taxes and clearing titles took more than an hour. It was the sort
of ordeal that gives government inefficiency a bad name.
</P>
<P>
   The good news was that my frightful experience wasn't nearly as
awful as that of many others gathered there trying to register new
cars.
</P>
<P>
   The first challenge was finding the right line, because of the
dearth of instruction signs. After five minutes in the first line
encountered, a nearby fellow sufferer noticed my paperwork and
tipped me to the fact that I was in the wrong line. Go over there
to the renewal line, and consider yourself lucky, she said. She had
been there for nearly three hours and was the next number to be
called for whatever it was she needed done.
</P>
<P>
   The most amazing part of the experience was how well all those
horribly abused taxpayers were handling their plight. There was a
lot of grousing, of course, but it was mostly good-natured stuff
peppered with jokes about government and tax dollars in action.
</P>
<P>
   Another enlightening moment came Monday afternoon listening to
Jerry Fogel's show on ``compelling KPHN'' during drive time. Fogel,
it seems, had a simple question, called the motor vehicle office
but was never able to make contact with a live human. The miffed
talkmeister was then inspired to ask his listeners whether his was
an isolated incident or whether Johnson Countians did indeed have a
problem worthy of serious attention by their elected leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Fogel's response was a litany of ghastly tales of endless waits
both at the facility and on telephones trying to get answers to
simple questions.
</P>
<P>
   Given the shortage of employees available to help customers, is
the area's tight labor market the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Not entirely, said Johnson County Treasurer Bill O'Brien. It's
more a matter of not enough money being budgeted to sustain
adequate staffing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to hire some people,'' O'Brien said, ``and we've got
to allow some room in the budget to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Demands on the operation have intensified as the strong economy
has fueled more new car sales. Although demand has mounted for
new-car registrations, which take longer than renewals, there
hasn't been enough money to match staffing levels with the growing
workload.
</P>
<P>
   This operation's deteriorating situation would seem to be
sending a message to the powers that be: Either fund it adequately
or contract it out to a private company.
</P>
<P>
   Given that this fiasco involves such an awesome revenue machine,
it seems penny wise and pound foolish to be overly close with its
budget. Moreover, beyond financial considerations, the damage being
done to county government's credibility among its taxpaying voters
is incalculable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
