A0241 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT     06-20 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVES TO RESTRICT CELL PHONES REFLECT REACTION AGAINST VOCAL
MINORITY 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Business Travel appears each Wednesday. Joe Sharkey's e-mail
address is jsharkey(AT)nytimes.com.) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to a lucky One-Pass upgrade, I was sitting in first class
on a Continental Airlines flight to Florida one sunny morning last
week waiting for takeoff. The flight attendant was passing out
those steaming face towels and taking drink orders. What a swell
flight so far, I thought. But then that dreaded telltale chirp
sounded from the row behind me.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, a cell phone idiot began braying into the morning's
serenity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on the plane,'' he declared in a voice as loud as a cattle
auctioneer's. ``We're going to take off in a couple of minutes.
Listen, did you put on the air conditioner? What? What? Nah, you
got to hit the reset button. What? Hit the reset! It's on the left!
What? Listen .''
</P>
<P>
   It went on like this for several long minutes. Then he barked
goodbye and snapped the phone lid shut. But before a sigh of relief
had time to form, he made another call. In the seat beside me, a
woman who looked like a very nice person muttered a single word,
softly, but with feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Die,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   We've come a long way in the cell phone culture since last
summer. Then, after years of resistance, several airlines decided
to relax strict prohibitions against using cell phones. Motivated
both by public demand and by a realization that passengers ducking
away to make last-minute phone calls at the gate were delaying
boarding and affecting on-time performance, most airlines began
allowing passengers to use cell phones until the pilot started
taxiing. The development was generally applauded by passengers.
</P>
<P>
   In the year since this change, however, there has been a
remarkable shift in general attitude toward cell phone use in
public, thanks to a minority of users who make the rest of us
cringe whenever we see them cracking that cell phone. And while the
airlines and federal regulators still insist that in-flight cell
phone use is a safety hazard that can interfere with complex
cockpit communications and navigation technology, some experts and
cell phone industry officials have been publicly arguing that the
science supporting the ban is questionable. After all, they say,
cell phone use is routine on board private corporate aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that the obvious market potential causes the safety
problems to be adequately addressed, will we be arriving at a point
where passengers gabbing incessantly into cell phones might be a
steady part of the airline experience, just as they are on other
public conveyances such as trains and buses?
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, there doesn't seem to be any discernible rush to
forge ahead into that particular segment of the brave new
technological world. Many experts point to rapid technological
innovations and believe that live Internet and e-mail service will
be available on some airplanes within a year. But no one is
predicting a cell phone breakout in the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think in the foreseeable future you'll be able to use
them, because the testing has just not been done to prove that they
are not harmful,'' said Kathryn Creedy, a spokeswoman for the
Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``So at this point, the syllogism still exists,'' Creedy said.
``We require that testing be done by the airlines or the industry
in order to prove that it is not harmful. And since that testing
has not been done, therefore they are banned.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Creedy declined to speculate on whether, given the
general level of annoyance that many people now show toward being
subjected to someone else's cell phone conversation, the airline
industry might now be willing to maintain the status quo. After
all, airlines make money when passengers place expensive calls on
existing on-board phones.
</P>
<P>
   But several academic authorities in telephone communications
agree that perhaps the public is now ready to weigh the cultural,
rather than just the scientific, argument against encouraging cell
phones in the skies _ especially on long, crowded flights where
people are already tense and often uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Growing moves across the country to restrict annoying cell
phones on other forms of pubic transportation reflect a swelling
reaction against a vocal minority of cell phone users, said Thomas
I. White, a professor of business ethics at Loyola Marymount
University in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who get on everyone's nerves, they're coming from a
sense that no one else matters. They're totally self-absorbed, and
they seem to think that the impact of their actions on other people
are absolutely inconsequential,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plays itself out in two ways. One, it is seen as an
eroding of civility or a disruption of civil discourse. This is
what we are seeing in San Francisco where cell phones are being
banned from many restaurants. And two, the self-absorption can also
be seen as a safety issue, such as in Los Angeles, where there are
moves to restrict cell phone use in cars.''
</P>
<P>
   White said he wouldn't be surprised to see the move to restrict
public use of cell phones grow, especially if it became apparent
that they might be allowed on airplane flights.
</P>
<P>
   Creedy conceded that passengers might well welcome the
``respite'' from cell phone annoyances that is provided by the
continuing ban, but stressed that safety is the FAA's only concern
in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   White, meanwhile, said: ``I'm assuming the only way the airlines
can get away with continuing to ban cell hones is because they say,
that's going to mess up the radar or the communications. And the
only reason people respect the ban is we're all scared to pull out
our cell phones and make a call because it might make the plane go
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, whatever works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-00 2357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
